<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEAL-SCOOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOOP ON AN OWNER'S DEAL RAISES ISSUE OF FAVORITISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The featured article in the first issue of The Daily Deal,
American Lawyer Media Inc.'s new journal for the world of mergers
and acquisitions, broke the news that Voicestream Wireless Corp.
was ``in the midst of negotiating a new acquisition.'' It added
that ``Analysts agree that Aerial Communications is the likeliest
candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   What the piece did not say was that American Lawyer Media is
owned by Bruce Wasserstein's investment banking firm, Wasserstein
Perella &AMP; Co., and that the investment banker for a group of
Aerial's independent directors was the same Wasserstein Perella &AMP;
Co. The bankers advising Voicestream were Goldman, Sachs and those
for Aerial's management were Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette.
</P>
<P>
   The issues involved in news organizations' covering their
corporate bosses or corporate cousins are hardly new since the rise
of media giants like Time Warner Inc., with its stable of news
magazines, and Walt Disney Co., which owns ABC News. But the
VoiceStream-Aerial article raised a slightly different issue: What
happens when a corporate boss is in a position to leak information
about an upcoming deal to its news subsidiary?
</P>
<P>
   Both Wasserstein and Robert Teitelman, the editor in chief of
The Daily Deal, strenuously deny that happened in this case, which
was mentioned Tuesday in The Financial Times. And it was unclear if
Wasserstein knew either about the news article or the merger talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has any reason to worry. Never did, never has, never
will,'' Wasserstein said Tuesday, pointing out that the firm's
American Lawyer Media had plenty of other publications, and that
this issue has not been raised in those cases. Wasserstein Perella
has owned American Lawyer Media for two years through its
subsidiary, U.S. Equity Partners LP.
</P>
<P>
   One banker, who spoke on condition that he not be named, said it
would be foolish to risk the trust of a company's banking clients,
or otherwise hurt its business, for the sake of a few scoops in a
newspaper subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Teitelman said in an interview, ``I know who the source is and
it was not from Wasserstein.''
</P>
<P>
   But outside observers, like the securities law professor Alan
Bromberg of Southern Methodist University, were troubled by the
overlapping interests involved. ``One tends to wonder, since he was
involved in the publication, was favoritism exercised?'' Bromberg
said. ``Confidentiality is always important in negotiating a
deal.'' Leaks, he said, can affect ``not only if you'll make the
deal but when you'll make the deal and at what price you'll make a
deal. There are a lot of examples where leaks killed a deal because
the market began to run up and that priced the deal out of the
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Teitelman said that the issue had not occurred to him in the
helter-skelter rush to publication of his newspaper. Nor, he said,
would it have made much difference. ``You create your Chinese
walls. You say you have your Chinese walls. The only thing that
matters at the end of the day is what you do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
