<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-BYE-WEEK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS COACH HAS POSITIVE FEELINGS ON BYE WEEK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Chan Gailey has no worries about the upcoming
bye week possibly serving as a momentum-killer to the Cowboys' 2-0
start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you lose momentum by having an off-week,'' the
Cowboys' coach said yesterday. ``I think you lose momentum by
losing games.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead to the Cowboys' next game Oct. 3 against Arizona,
this much is known:
</P>
<P>
   For the month of September, only the NFL schedule maker will be
able to lay claim to having stopped the Cowboys, who sit alone atop
the NFC East and share the NFC's best record with Detroit, also
2-0. St. Louis is 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know me, it's all positive,'' said Gailey, pointing to
injuries _ both old and new _ that will be helped by getting the
extra week to heal. ``There's no better time than now to have a
break ... whatever the reason, pick one. That's my story and I'm
sticking to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are coming off a 24-7 Monday Night Football victory
over Atlanta. By the Arizona game 11 days from now, cornerbacks
Deion Sanders and Kevin Smith could be back, along with rookie
backup tight end Mike Lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey expects Smith, who had a bulging disk diagnosed in his
back during training camp and received a series of three injections
to control the inflammation, to be back practicing with the team
``if not this week then next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said Smith, who hasn't been on the field since the Hall
of Fame exhibition game Aug. 9 in Canton, Ohio, is ``closer to one
week than six weeks'' in being ready to play again. Gailey would
not comment specifically when asked about Smith's chances of
playing against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   There are two new injuries along the offensive line that need
mending time. If there was a game this week, said Gailey, right
tackle Erik Williams (strained quadriceps) and right guard Everett
McIver (strained hamstring) would be listed as ``doubtful.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is no game this week, which is another reason for the
Cowboys to welcome the bye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everett is a little more doubtful than Erik right now,''
Gailey said. Replacements Tony Hutson and Ben Fricke did a suitable
job of filling in ``but weren't as crisp as the first group, and
they shouldn't be because they don't take as many reps,'' Gailey
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hutson, who can play either guard or tackle, played the whole
game in Williams' place at right tackle. Gailey described Williams'
injury as ``a bizarre thing.'' He experienced pain simply jogging
onto the field after pregame warmups.
</P>
<P>
   Fricke, a first-year free agent who was out of football when the
Cowboys called him early in camp during a rash of injuries to
offensive linemen, came in at the two-minute warning of the first
half and finished the game.
</P>
<P>
   What Gailey has seen from the Cowboys after two games into his
second season can be measured more in heart than in statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've shown we're capable of winning through adversity,''
Gailey said of the Cowboys' 41-35 overtime victory at Washington
and the 24-7 win over Atlanta. ``The first week, we overcame \Ra
21-point deficit\S and a \R504 yards allowed\S performance that was
not up to the standards of our defense. This week, we overcame
injuries to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've shown we can fight through adversity, and I think that
will help us win down the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey was especially impressed with the stoicism shown by
receiver Raghib ``Rocket'' Ismail, who was forced to leave the game
late in the first quarter when he landed hard on the same left
shoulder that he slightly separated in early August. Ismail
returned to play the entire second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was painful \Rfor Ismail\S, but there was no structural
damage,'' said Gailey. ``He came back and went to war for us. I was
very impressed in what he did for our football team.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, there isn't much Gailey will object to these days,
not even an idle week on the schedule when his team is hot.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
