<HEADER>
A1005 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-PAC10-LADN     09-22 2009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PAC10-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACIFIC-10 CAPSULES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A closer look at the Pac-10 schools (apart from
USC and UCLA): &QL; 
ARIZONA WILDCATS &QL; 
__ Record: 2-2, 0-1.
</P>
<P>
   __ Are they good? A long time ago, they were supposed to be.
After losses to Penn State and Stanford, and a narrow win over TCU,
however, the Wildcats are no longer feared by the rest of the
conference. They might be lucky to go to the Aloha Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   __ Players who matter: Linebacker DaShon Polk of Taft leads what
was supposedly a dominating defense _ except against Penn State,
TCU and Stanford. Wide receiver Dennis Northcutt is the Wildcats'
best big-game performer. Running back Trung Canidate takes pressure
off the quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   __ QB status: Maybe the only team in the nation that wanted a
two-quarterback system. Keith Smith and Ortege Jenkins seem to
complement each other wonderfully, but Jenkins has begun to assert
himself.
</P>
<P>
   __ Coach's status: Dick Tomey went 12-1 last season and secured
his job for some time, but in a Tomey tradition, the Wildcats are
bombing when there are high preseason expectations.
</P>
<P>
   __ How they'll win: The Wildcats can confuse teams with the 1-2
punch of Smith and Jenkins, and their home-field advantage usually
wins games by itself. Usually.
</P>
<P>
   __ How they'll lose: Arizona's biggest weakness is the absence
of Chris McAlister, who singlehandedly kept one side of the field
off-limits to opposing offenses. The defense is extremely suspect,
forcing the offense to carry the burden.
</P>
<P>
   __ The key game: The Wildcats host USC on Oct. 9. They are
expected to win, so if they lose, the season is over. Oh wait, the
season is over.
</P>
<P>
   __ End result: Arizona wanted to compete for national title. Now
they won't even get a Pac-10 title. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
ARIZONA STATE SUN DEVILS &QL; 
__ Record: 1-1, 0-0.
</P>
<P>
   __ Are they good? After a disastrous 5-6 season, the Sun Devils
could be the dark horse to win the Pac-10 title, as long as they
don't play New Mexico State anymore.
</P>
<P>
   __ Players who matter: Quarterback Ryan Kealy must return from
minor knee surgery or the Sun Devils will be finished. Tailback
J.R. Redmond is a legitimate Heisman Trophy candidate. Cornerback
Courtney Jackson has been a mainstay for three years.
</P>
<P>
   __ Coach's status: Snyder is coming off a losing season but has
plenty of goodwill left from the '96 Rose Bowl season. He'll be
here as long as he wants.
</P>
<P>
   __ How they'll win: The Sun Devils' offense is nicely balanced
with Kealy's passing and Redmond's running. The defense, peppered
with JC transfers, is better despite the New Mexico State
performance.
</P>
<P>
   __ How they'll lose: Kealy needs to recover from his
season-opening knee injury. The defense has holes and has to put
more pressure on quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   __ The key game: Oct. 2 against UCLA. The Sun Devils believe
they are a better team, but to avert last season's early collapse
and build confidence, they need a quality victory.
</P>
<P>
   __ End result: With everyone obsessed over Arizona, UCLA and
USC, the Sun Devils can quietly go about their business and contend
for conference title, provided the New Mexico State game was a
fluke. &QL; 
CALIFORNIA &QL; 
__ Record: 1-1, 0-0.
</P>
<P>
   __ Are they good? They could be, although history suggests
otherwise. The Golden Bears have one of the best defenses in the
conference, so if the offense is merely adequate, a bowl trip is
conceivable.
</P>
<P>
   __ Players who matter: Linebacker Sekou Sanyika is ready for a
breakout season. His position-mate, Matt Beck, is just as good.
Defensive linemen Jerry DeLoach and Andre Carter are among the
conference's best.
</P>
<P>
   __ QB status: Sophomore Samuel Clemons is filling time until
freshman Kyle Boller is ready to start.
</P>
<P>
   __ Coach's status: Tom Holmoe dumped offensive coordinator Doug
Cosbie and offensive line coach Monte Clark last year and is not
popular in Berkeley. A big recruiting year bought some time, but
the Bears need to start winning.
</P>
<P>
   __ How they'll win: Defense. Defense. Defense. The offense will
sputter, but if Holmoe has the guts to play CB Deltha O'Neal 20-25
plays on offense, the Bears could cause problems. Already, 12 of
Cal's 19 freshmen have played.
</P>
<P>
   __ How they'll lose: Clemons proves inept and Boller has to play
too much too soon. The defense suffers any injuries at linebacker
or along the line.
</P>
<P>
   __ The key game: Saturday against Arizona State. The Bears are
reeling from their loss to Nebraska and got a week off to recover.
But things could go downhill fast if they don't beat ASU in
Strawberry Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   __ End result: If Boller survived the Nebraska experience, Cal
could pull off a six-win season. &QL; 
OREGON &QL; 
__ Record: 2-1, 0-0.
</P>
<P>
   __ Are they good? Perhaps. The Ducks no longer have Akili Smith,
but A.J. Feeley has been impressive in three starts. The key will
be whether tailback Reuben Droughns can regain form after suffering
a broken leg.
</P>
<P>
   __ Players who matter: Besides Droughns, wide receiver Tony
Hartley is always dangerous. But you win with defense, and
linebacker Peter Sirmon and cornerback Brandon McLemore are going
to have to have career seasons.
</P>
<P>
   __ QB status: Feeley has locked up the job, after beating out
sophomore Joey Harrington in training camp.
</P>
<P>
   __ Coach's status: Mike Bellotti just signed a long-term
contract, and has made people forget they cared when Rich Brooks
left for the St. Louis Rams.
</P>
<P>
   __ How they'll win: Feeley should have the passing game going
full speed now. The defense has more talent than people think.
</P>
<P>
   __ How they'll lose: The Ducks can be overpowered by physical
teams, as Michigan State demonstrated, and the running game
sputters when Droughns isn't 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   __ The key game: Oct. 2 at Washington. The Ducks dislike no team
more in the conference, and Bellotti can't stand new Huskies coach
Rick Neuheisel. Should be interesting.
</P>
<P>
   __ End result: The Ducks will take their lumps in the conference
but should be able to squeeze a trip to the Aloha Bowl out of this
season. &QL; 
OREGON STATE &QL; 
__ Record: 3-0, 0-0.
</P>
<P>
   __ Are they good? No, but they might not be bad. The Beavers
have a new coach (Dennis Erickson) and are more confident than ever
after Mike Riley turned the program around.
</P>
<P>
   __ Players who matter: Quarterback Jonathan Smith leads the
Pac-10 in passing amd tailback Ken Simonton is averaging 188.5
yards per game. Linebacker Jonathan Jackson anchors a defense that
is trying to replace six starters.
</P>
<P>
   __ QB status: Smith is the man, especially with senior Terrance
Bryant suspended at the outset of the season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Coach's status: Erickson is being treated like a king. He has
so much authority that he canceled plans to install grass and will
keep AstroTurf at Parker Stadium, which he thinks will suit a
pass-happy offense.
</P>
<P>
   __ How they'll win: By scheduling bad teams. Oregon State has
the Pac-10's longest winning streak (four games), partly by playing
the likes of Nevada, Fresno State and Georgia Southern in the
pre-league games.
</P>
<P>
   __ How they'll lose: By playing Pac-10 teams. The Beavers are
actually not pushovers anymore, but neither Smith nor Simonton can
have an off day, because the defense can't shut anyone down.
</P>
<P>
   __ The key game: Oct. 16 at Stanford. The Beavers hunger for a
winning season and this is one of those games that makes a
difference. A win makes a bowl a real possibility and a loss means
Oregon State needs to pull a major upset somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   __ End result: If the Beavers can shake off the adjustment of
having their third coach in four years, they will likely pull off a
winning season. &QL; 
STANFORD &QL; 
__ Record: 2-1, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   __ Are they good? Who knows? The Cardinal has been reeling for
two years and its morale wasn't helped by the 69-17 shellacking
Texas gave it. But wins over Washington State and Arizona forced a
total re-evaluation of its potential.
</P>
<P>
   __ Players who matter: Remember when Todd Husak was viewed as a
stopgap measure? Now he's indispensable. Flanker Troy Walters is
the most underappreciated player in the Pac-10. Freshman running
back Kerry Carter from Canada is already a pleasant surprise.
</P>
<P>
   __ QB status: Husak is starting, with Camarillo's Joe Borchard
the backup. How many recruiting analysts goofed by calling Randy
Fasani one of the nation's best backs in '96?
</P>
<P>
   __ Coach's status: The alumni were foaming at the mouth to
replace Tyrone Willingham, but athletic director Ted Leland has
brushed off any notion for a coaching change and the heat is off
right now. Willingham is 17-17 vs. the Pac-10 _ and half of those
wins have come against Cal and Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   __ How they'll win: Stanford needs to outscore teams, with
Walters and Collins providing the points. And the defense can't
allow 69 points a game again. Right?
</P>
<P>
   __ How they'll lose: Many different ways. The defense can be
porous, as Texas showed, and Husak can be inconsistent. The overall
sick feeling surrounding the program would also be worth a couple
of losses, unless the Arizona game cured that problem.
</P>
<P>
   __ The key game: Saturday against UCLA. OK, the Cardinal routed
Arizona and pummeled Washington State. Now it's time to see if this
season will be different. Don't bet any money on that yet.
</P>
<P>
   __ End result: The good news is Stanford is in first place in
the Pac-10. The bad news is seven teams haven't started conference
play. &QL; 
WASHINGTON &QL; 
__ Record: 0-2, 0-0.
</P>
<P>
   __ Are they good? The Huskies have too much talent to go through
too much pain in Rick Neuheisel's first year.
</P>
<P>
   __ Players who matter: Linebacker Lester Towns might be the
Pac-10's best. Defensive ends Jabari Issa and Mac Tuiaea won't back
down from anyone, and quarterback Marques Tuiasosopo is emerging as
a bonafide star.
</P>
<P>
   __ QB status: No more Huards left for Huskies fans to boo?
That's good news for Neuheisel, because Tuiasosopo will cause more
headaches than any other quarterback, with his ability to scramble
and throw on the run.
</P>
<P>
   __ Coach's status: Neuheisel is the highest-paid coach in the
conference (about $1 million per season), and he'll have at least a
two-year grace period while he rebuilds from what Jim Lambright
left.
</P>
<P>
   __ How they'll win: The defensive line is strong, and Towns is
an eraser at linebacker. The offense keeps opponents off-balance as
long as Tuiasosopo is healthy.
</P>
<P>
   __ How they'll lose: The secondary is full of holes, as Brigham
Young proved, and the running game is inconsistent with sophomore
Willie Hurst and freshman Paul Arnold at tailback.
</P>
<P>
   __ The key game: Oct. 16 against Arizona State. The Huskies
could still have delusions about making a run in the conference. If
they're serious, they need to derail the Sun Devils in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   __ End result: If Neuheisel keeps Huskies off probation, let's
pencil this in as a six-win season. &QL; 
WASHINGTON STATE &QL; 
__ Record: 0-3, 0-1.
</P>
<P>
   __ Are they good? Next question.
</P>
<P>
   __ Players who matter: Tailback Kevin Brown, before being kicked
off team for burglary and transferring to UNLV, and cornerback
Chris Martin, who was declared academically ineligible.
</P>
<P>
   __ QB status: Senior Steve Birnbaum has started the first three
games with limited success, and freshman Jason Gesser continues to
push his way into the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   __ Coach's status: Mike Price might not survive this season, but
hey, this is Washington State. He took them to the Rose Bowl two
years ago, so it's his job for life.
</P>
<P>
   __ How they'll win: A major snowstorm will blow through Pullman
for every home game, rendering opponents helpless.
</P>
<P>
   __ How they'll lose: There's too many reasons to list here, but
it doesn't help that 17 players the Cougars figured would be on
this year's roster are not, mostly for academic or
off-field-behavior reasons.
</P>
<P>
   __ The key game: Oct. 9 against SW Louisiana. Hey, you take a
win wherever you can get it around the Palouse these days.
</P>
<P>
   __ End result: A long time ago, in a season far, far away, the
Cougars went to the Rose Bowl. They might call the Chargers about
taking Ryan Leaf back.
</P>
</TEXT>
