A1006 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-JONES-NYT &LR;      09-22 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-JONES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO HOME RUNS ADD TO SOLID CASE FOR MVP
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   News usually travels quickly in baseball. If somebody's
assistant general manager is interviewed for someone else's general
manager's job, the word goes hurtling through the game's unofficial
network of officials and scouts. If a young phenom is suddenly
found to have trouble hitting breaking balls, he might as well head
for the minors yesterday because the scouts record it in their
notebooks and instantly spread the word on the network.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets must have had their connection to the network wired
into the telephone switching station in Rochelle Park, N.J., that
was flooded out by Hurricane Floyd because they apparently never
got the word: Chipper Jones is hitting home runs right-handed these
days.
</P>
<P>
   Jones hit a home run left-handed against right-handed Rick Reed
in the first inning last night, then hit one right-handed against
the left-handed Dennis Cook in the eighth inning. The result: the
Atlanta Braves took the first part of their six-part test against
the Mets, winning, 2-1, and doubling their division lead over the
Mets to two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there are MVPs on the Mets and around the league,''
Bobby Cox, the Braves' manager, had said before the game, ``but to
me, because of our situation. ...''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't finish the sentence, but Cox was nominating his third
baseman for National League most valuable player. Jones, he
explained, did not have Andres Galarraga and Javier Lopez hitting
behind him. Galarraga has been out all season, Lopez for the second
half. Their absence has made his job tougher, but he has been
outdoing even himself.
</P>
<P>
   A switch-hitter, Jones has been an immensely improved hitter
from the right side of the plate. Before this year, in four
seasons, Jones hit 96 home runs left-handed, 12 right-handed. Last
season only two of his 34 home runs were hit as a right-handed
batter.
</P>
<P>
   His game-winning blow Tuesday night was his 14th home run this
season as a right-handed hitter, one third of his total of 42. He
has batted three times as often left-handed as right-handed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year,'' Cox said, ``he had a good year right-handed, but
he didn't have the power.'' He didn't have Don Baylor as his
hitting coach either.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's more aggressive right-handed,'' Pat Corrales, the Braves'
dugout coach, said. ``He doesn't feel for the ball. He's swinging
the same from both sides. I think Donny got that out of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga, a Baylor disciple since their year in St. Louis
together (1992), has no doubt that Baylor is the one responsible
for Jones' improvement. ''For me, he's the best,'' Galarraga said
of Baylor. ``One year with him and I was the batting champion. He
knows what he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   In Jones, Baylor has a new believer. Calling his transformation
a ``change in philosophy,'' Jones explained his previous
philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going up there concerned with being a .300 hitter and
driving in the runs when they were out there,'' Jones said, ``not
thinking about the home run, not really trying to hit the home run.
When I got to spring training, Don Baylor didn't like that approach
too much. He said I hit third for one of the best teams in the game
and when they turned me around, I have to make them pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A little more swinging from the heels than in years past has
made the difference,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really has helped,'' he said. ``But that's not all. It's
the mental approach. I had a little fundamental flaw in my swing
from that side and we fixed that. All of a sudden balls started
jumping off the bat a little harder and going a little farther.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones acknowledged that he was skeptical at first about Baylor's
views.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the strikeouts would go up,'' he said, ``but they're
pretty much on par with where they've always been.''
</P>
<P>
   When Cook came in to pitch for the Mets Tuesday night, Jones had
managed only one hit in seven career at-bats against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look for a fastball you can get extension on and hopefully
you won't miss it because he's got some good breaking stuff to go
along with it,'' Jones said of Cook. ``With the count 1 and 1, he
hadn't thrown me a fastball yet. Then he threw me one I could get
extension on.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones extended all the way to the left-center field seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won the game for us the other day hitting a home run
right-handed,'' Cox had noted earlier. Jones hit a 10th-inning home
run against left-handed Steve Kline of Montreal last Friday. His
blow against Cook broke a 1-1 tie and kept the Mets from tying the
Braves for first place. ``That first punch is important,'' Jones
said, borrowing from another sport in discussing the first of six
games the teams will play in 10 days ``It's important to establish
some momentum. But by no means are they going to give in. A lot can
happen in the last two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   And no matter what happens between the teams in these last two
weeks, he said, ``We could see each other again in the playoffs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
