<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-JOURNALIST-DEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUTCH JOURNALIST KILLED IN EAST TIMOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (With TIMOR-RDP, TIMOR-INDONESIA) 
(mk) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, East Timor _ A Dutch journalist working for the Christian
Science Monitor and The Financial Times was killed here on Tuesday,
apparently by armed men who pursued his motorbike from a rogue
checkpoint, witnesses said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The journalist, Sander Thoenes, had arrived here only hours
before, hiring a motorbike to tour the city. The motorbike driver
said Thoenes had fallen when the motorbike was hit by bullets.
Reporters who visited the area Wednesday morning found his body.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. Peter Cosgrove, who heads the international
peacekeeping force here, told journalists Wednesday, ``It's been
quite a dangerous 24 hours. There are some signs of the militia's
being agitated by a return into Dili of previously displaced
population.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the armed men ``have attempted to step up actions as a
show that all is not yet secure,'' adding: ``I would agree with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it is obviously a reaction to our presence,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The general declined to confirm the killing of Thoenes. But he
did confirm another incident on Tuesday in the same eastern portion
of the city, Becora, in which a British journalist and an American
photographer were attacked by armed men.
</P>
<P>
   He said they hid, used mobile telephones to call for help and
were rescued by Australian troops.
</P>
<P>
   The motorbike driver, Florindo da Consiecao Araujo, said he and
Thoenes tried to flee when they spotted the checkpoint manned by
six men wearing dark green Indonesian military uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the journalist to hang on tight and I tried to turn
around and they started shooting, pa-pa-pa-pa, 10 or 20 times,''
the driver said. ``The bullets cruised past. He didn't say
anything. He just hung on to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The motorbike was hit and the two men fell, Araujo said. The
driver ran, pursued by some of the armed men. ``I saw the
journalist looking like he was asleep on the ground,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The reporters said they found Thoenes' body behind a burned-out
house, where it had apparently been dragged. A notebook and a pen
lay beside it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
