<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1010 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-CAR-MONTOYA-HNS &LR;      09-22 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MONTOYA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
A few weeks ago, it became clear Juan Montoya was a lock to be CART
Rookie of the Year this season. By that time, Montoya also knew he
had a chance to accomplish a bigger goal.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Rookie of the Year would be nice,'' he said. ``But I didn't
come here for that. I came here to win championships.''
</P>
<P>
   The young Colombian comes to town this week with a chance to
clinch the 1999 FedEx championship Sunday in the Texaco/Havoline
Grand Prix of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``This season has been much more than I, or anyone on the team,
could have expected,'' said Montoya, who turned 24 Monday. ``We now
realize we have a chance to make history, so the team is committed
to earning as many points as we can in each race to see if we can
make that dream a reality.''
</P>
<P>
   With a rookie record of seven victories this season, including
three in the last four races, Montoya has a 28-point lead over
Dario Franchitti with three events remaining in the battle for the
PPG Cup.
</P>
<P>
   If Montoya leaves Houston with a 45-point advantage or more, he
will have clinched the championship and become the second rookie in
history to win the title. Nigel Mansell won the PPG Cup as a rookie
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   For Montoya to clinch the championship here, he likely will need
to win the race in the No. 4 Target Honda/Reynard and have
Franchitti, the defending champion in Houston, finish 10th or
worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the race, I'm not going to be thinking about how many
points I need or where Dario is on the track,'' Montoya said. ``I'm
just going to concentrate on driving hard. If it ends up that I
clinch, I'll be extremely excited. I'm not expecting it, so if it
happens, it may take awhile to sink in.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, it won't be easy to clinch the championship Sunday,
but Montoya is assured of leaving Houston with the points lead
regardless of what happens in the downtown street race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember at what point I actually started thinking
about winning the PPG Cup, but I try my best not to think about
it,'' he said. ``My goal from the beginning has been to score as
many points as possible each race, and that's how I'm approaching
Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   If Montoya holds on to win the title, it will be the fourth
consecutive championship for the Target team of Chip Ganassi.
Italy's Alex Zanardi, whom Montoya replaced, won the crown in 1997
and 1998, and Jimmy Vasser won the championship for the team in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an exciting time of year for us,'' Vasser said. ``Our
team knows what it's like to be in this position where so much is
riding on each race. And I've learned over the course of the season
that Juan is as tough mentally as he is physically, so he's up to
the task. He's in good position, and he knows I'm here if he's
looking for advice.''
</P>
<P>
   Montoya hasn't needed much advice along the way, but he knows
people have wondered whether he's really this good or if he was
lucky enough to inherit the best car on the best team in CART.
</P>
<P>
   From 1996 through 1998, Ganassi's two-car team won 23 CART races
while all the other drivers on the circuit amassed 29 victories.
Zanardi, who left to drive in Formula One this season, won seven of
19 races last year and clinched the title with four events
remaining, the earliest of any CART champion. Vasser finished
second.
</P>
<P>
   So Montoya couldn't have asked for a better situation to begin
his CART career, and everybody knew it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The car's a title contender,'' Michael Andretti said when
asked earlier this year if Montoya could contend for the
championship. ``That team will give him the experience to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Montoya admits he has a talented team behind him, but he also
thinks it takes a great driver to bring the team to the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chip has given me a great opportunity here, and the
Honda-Firestone combination is the best,'' Montoya said. ``But I
don't think I'm out of the equation.''
</P>
<P>
   Mo Nunn, the top engineer for the Target team, was the man who
persuaded Ganassi to sign the little-known Montoya after they went
to Spain last fall to watch him test a McLaren Formula One car.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't take any genius to know this kid was something
special,'' Nunn said. ``When I got back, I told the guys on our
team that the kid was going to win right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Montoya has earned six of his victories in streaks. He won three
in a row early in the year at Long Beach, Calif.; Nazareth, Pa.;
and Rio de Janeiro. He won at Cleveland on June 27, then added
another three-victory streak at Lexington, Ohio; Chicago; and
Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   He has put himself in position to clinch the points
championship, something he said he learned how to do last year when
he won the Formula 3000 title in Europe. Montoya felt he should
have won the Formula 3000 championship in 1997, but he was too
aggressive at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I saw a chance to win, I went for it,'' he said.
``Sometimes I shouldn't have. In 1997, I threw away points _ enough
points to win the championship _ in three or four races by making
mistakes. Last year I won the championship because I was smarter
and didn't try to win when I didn't have the best car.''
</P>
<P>
   Those early lessons seem to be paying off now and have helped
Montoya get the most out of a quality car and an experienced team.
He is closing in on his first major championship, which can be a
nerve-racking time for a young driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having too much fun to feel nervous about it,'' Montoya
said. ``No one expected me to be doing this well so soon, so I
don't feel any pressure. I'm still a rookie, so I feel like I have
nothing to lose.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
