u a BC-CT-ENCEPHALITIS-NYT &LR;      09-22 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-ENCEPHALITIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 ENCEPHALITIS DETECTED IN MOSQUITOES IN CONNECTICUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-ENCEPHALITIS) 
(mk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENWICH, Conn. _ State scientists said Tuesday night that they
had found the potentially deadly St. Louis encephalitis in
mosquitoes trapped at a country club here and in a crow from a back
yard in Westport. Greenwich officials immediately said they planned
to restrict outdoor activities from 5 p.m. to dawn, including youth
football and soccer practices.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwich's restrictions, contained in a directive that
officials expected to issue Wednesday morning, reflected the
concern that has mounted throughout the region in the three weeks
since the mosquito-borne disease was discovered in New York City.
Three people have died in the city, and nine other cases have been
confirmed. On Monday, Westchester County officials announced that
two people there had contracted the disease. A third case was
confirmed in Westchester County Tuesday in an 80-year-old Yonkers
man. County officials declined to identify the man, but said he was
in stable condition at a hospital in Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   No one in Connecticut has been found to have the disease. But
Tuesday's discoveries of the virus led officials of the state
Department of Environmental Protection to prepare for widespread
aerial spraying of insecticide in Fairfield County next week. As a
first step, street-by-street spraying from trucks is to begin at
sunset Thursday in the Old Greenwich area.
</P>
<P>
   The insecticide, called Scourge, is a synthetic version of an
agent found in chrysanthemums. Officials recommended that people
stay inside, close their doors and windows, and bring children's
toys inside during the spraying. The insecticide breaks down after
about three hours of sunlight, diminishing potential exposure to
people or pets, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwich officials said they would ask day care services and
homes for the elderly to allow their charges outside only from 8
a.m. to 5 p.m. Caroline Baisley, the town's director of health,
said the measures would remain in effect ``until we get a handle on
this.''
</P>
<P>
   The order extends to golf, a leading activity here. ``When you
tee off, you're going to be told, `Be back by five,''' Dr. Baisley
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Greenwich first selectman, Tom Ragland, who has the
functions of mayor, said that although the possibility of any given
person contracting the disease was remote, the ban on what he
called ``absolutely all outside activities'' was a reasonable
precaution. For instance, he said, youth sports practices would not
be allowed on town fields, where most are held. He acknowledged he
could not stop private gatherings like backyard barbecues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously this will be difficult to enforce, but it's in their
best interest,'' he said. ``How can you overreact to a disease that
is a lethal disease? They're going to be thankful that we are
minding the store.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials had a calmer tone as they announced their
findings. Dr. Theodore Andreadis, the chief medical entomologist at
the Connecticut Agricultural Experimental Station, in New Haven,
called the two confirmations ``a very significant finding,'' but
sought to allay public fear. ``Less than 1 percent of people who
are bitten by an infected mosquito will exhibit any disease,'' he
said. ``And of that 1 percent, only roughly 5 to 15 percent will
die. Unfortunately, the elderly are most at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   The virus was found in a pool of adult mosquitoes collected
Sept. 14 in a trap at the Innis Arden Golf Club, on the
Greenwich-Stamford line. The crow was submitted to state officials
on Sept. 13 after it was found dead in a back yard on Riverside
Drive in Westport by a homeowner who was concerned about a rash of
dead birds. The bird died of the disease, Andreadis said. State
officials said that although the bird could not be expected to give
the disease to humans, the discovery was very troubling because
birds travel in a wide range and can pass on the disease when
bitten by mosquitoes, which then transmit it to people.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. John Rowland said the most important preventive steps
people can take are to cover up when outside after sunset, and to
dump out stagnant water in clogged gutters, old tires and wading
pools. ``We don't want to alarm anyone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the announcement was greeted with alarm in
Greenwich. Many children walk to school in the area where the virus
was found, and several nursery schools are nearby. Paula Corrado,
58, who lives about two miles from the country club where the virus
was found, said the announcement evoked the Alfred Hitchcock film
``The Birds'' and said she expected her neighbors to react with
``controlled panic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
