<HEADLINE>
SUMMER OF '99 WAS MEMORABLE FOR HUMIDITY THAT WOULDN'T QUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHAWNA A. HAMEL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ This summer may not have been one of the
hottest to blanket the Kansas City area before the millennium, but
it was one of the most humid.
</P>
<P>
   With the last full day of summer upon Kansas Citians today,
things have simmered down. Area residents are enjoying brisk
mornings for the first time in months, awaiting autumn's debut at
6:31 a.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But the summer of '99 made its presence felt. Although it won't
go into the record books for its high temperatures, it did generate
heat indexes that surged well above 100 for several periods _
including the unbearable 114 degrees reached July 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a really, really humid summer with some very high
heat indexes,'' said Chad Pettera, meteorologist for Wichita-based
WeatherData Inc. ``The weather pattern of the summer never really
changed a lot _ it got real warm, and it stayed real long. And if
anything would make a summer seem hot, that would.''
</P>
<P>
   At least 19 persons in the area died this summer of heat-related
illnesses. Most of the victims were elderly people who lived alone
or those who lived in the inner city and suffered health problems
like asthma or diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the month of July, there were days when the
Metropolitan Ambulance Services Trust and the Kansas City Fire
Department ran heat-related calls back to back with rarely a break
in between, MAST spokesman Don Pickard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty hot every July, but there was something about this
July, because we ran a ton of calls,'' Pickard said. ``As far as we
know, it was the busiest month in the history of the system for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   In the week from July 23 to July 30, the area suffered through
its highest temperatures, where the high readings hit 98 and stayed
at or above that level, including 103 degrees for two days at the
end of month.
</P>
<P>
   During that period, the heat took its greatest toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first couple of days of high temperatures are fairly slow
for us,'' Pickard said, ``but once you get into the fourth or fifth
day of a heat wave _ or especially the first or second weeks _
we've got this surge in calls. Heat has a cumulative effect,
because the longer it lasts, the bigger toll it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   For at least a week, Kansas City Power &AMP; Light asked its
customers to conserve energy _ a request it rarely makes,
spokeswoman Pam Levetzow said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was just an incredibly important thing we asked because
this summer was so unique,'' she said. ``The heat wave had hit
every region of the country at the same time. Luckily, we didn't
have a problem, but the potential was there to put the energy
system in serious jeopardy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
