<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-REFORMERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: REFORMERS PARTY ON 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, Sept. 22:
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is the sober nature of the upcoming presidential race
that allows the Reform Party to suddenly seem less about reform and
more about party. The dean of Reformers wears a boa to his
wrestling gig. One possible candidate wonders in print why
Americans fought Hitler, another made a name for himself building
casinos designed to rival the Taj Mahal, and then there is the
glamorous Hollywood movie star who seems oddly somber in
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   If political parties like to boast of having a big tent, this
one is beginning to feel a little like a circus. Minnesota's
governor, Jesse Ventura, the party's top elected official, believes
in free trade. Pat Buchanan, a conservative Republican considering
defection, favors protectionism and extreme isolationism. Donald
Trump, Ventura's favorite, believes he is living the workingman's
fantasy and would undoubtedly campaign from his nearest penthouse
suite. Warren Beatty, a liberal who wants to talk about campaign
finance reform, has been eyeing the Reform Party as a way to
pressure his own Democratic Party. To borrow a phrase from those
younger voters the Reformers are trying so desperately to attract:
Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   To clear some of the befuddlement about the Reformers, Lawrence
Goodwyn, Duke University's expert on the populist movement in
America, offers a reminder that this party is not an invention of
the people, not an institution created by some political
groundswell over issues not being addressed by the establishment
parties. The Reform Party is a very hierarchical political machine
crafted for one purpose: the promotion of the self-anointed
presidential candidate Ross Perot. Perot appears to have talked his
way out of favor, winning almost 20 million votes in 1992 and
barely 8 million by 1996. With such a trend line, the former
presidential candidate has allegedly promised to stay in the
background, allowing others to take over the complicated process of
getting on state ballots and staging a national primary.
</P>
<P>
   With their chaperone missing, however, the Reform Party appears
to be going a little crazy. One resolution could be the crowning of
Perot's successor, whose benefits would include the kind of intense
media spotlight that seeks out this kind of wackiness. Moreover,
there is $12 million in the kitty from federal matching funds and a
chance to participate in the presidential debates. Thus, the
strange political vacuum at the top of this party is an invitation
for any candidate who wants to make plenty of noise and not a
little mischief, a conservative helping elect the Democratic
presidential candidate or a liberal helping elect the Republican.
What becomes surprising, given such power, is not that there are so
many possible applicants for the Reform Party nomination, but so
few.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 0047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
