<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1021 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-MCCAIN-KAN-KAN &LR;      09-22 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-KAN-KAN </SLUG>
  
 McCain demonstrates his no-nonsense approach  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ Just minutes before Sen. John McCain
stepped into the packed auditorium of the Johnson County Central
Resource Library Tuesday, an aide took the senator aside.
</P>
<P>
   A little hair spray was needed, a quick comb to smooth the
Arizona Republican's solidly gray hair.
</P>
<P>
   Just another perk for a high-powered Washington insider who's
vying to be the GOP nominee for president?
</P>
<P>
   Hardly. McCain, who was repeatedly tortured during his 5 years
as a prisoner of war in North Vietnam, cannot raise his arms high
enough to do the job himself.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's time in Vietnam is one of the chief topics of his new
book, ``Faith of My Fathers,'' a memoir that covers his life as the
son and grandson of four-star Navy admirals.
</P>
<P>
   His account of brutal treatment _ the Vietnamese left McCain
hanging for hours by his arms, which were broken after he ejected
from his downed jet _ is one reason the book is No. 3 on The New
York Times best-seller list. Its success brought the senator to the
Kansas City area Tuesday as part of a national book tour.
</P>
<P>
   But asked if he ever goes a day without remembering that painful
time in the infamous ``Hanoi Hilton'' prison, McCain offered an
unexpected response.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, months. Because I was able to put it behind me,'' the
63-year-old, three-term senator told interviewer Mike Shanin of
KPHN Radio.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain said he regularly received telephone calls, letters
or e-mails from his comrades. Then he delivered a trademark line:
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, the great privilege of my life was to serve in the
company of heroes, to have the privilege to observe a thousand acts
of courage, compassion and love. Their friendship will be what I
always treasure.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator insists he was no hero himself, even though he
turned down an opportunity to be freed early after the Vietnamese
learned that McCain's father was a top-ranked commander. Being
released before other prisoners who had served longer would have
violated the code of conduct, McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his stop at the library before about 150 people, the
Republican attended a fund-raiser at the Kansas City Club in Kansas
City, Mo., and spoke to about 1,600 people Tuesday night at the
Village Presbyterian Church in Prairie Village, Kan. Vivien
Jennings of Rainy Day Books, who organized the event, said McCain
drew as many people as some other well-known authors she brings to
town.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been in the media a lot lately, and I think he's really
captured their interest,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, McCain is riding a wave these days. His book is a big
success. He has moved into the solid double digits in polls in New
Hampshire, the nation's first primary state, although he is still
far behind the front-runner, Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Wolfe of La Cygne, Kan., said it would be nice to vote for
a hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``He spits it out and tells it like it is,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Reynolds of Liberty said she liked the fact that McCain
did not adhere to the GOP line and was a bit of a maverick.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a sense of honor about himself,'' Reynolds said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he could catch Bush, McCain pointed to former Texas
Gov. John Connally, who in 1980 was far ahead at a similar point in
a presidential campaign and then collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still early,'' McCain said. ``Governor Bush is a good
man. But I think I'm more qualified.''
</P>
<P>
   About Pat Buchanan, the Republican hopeful considering a move to
the Reform Party, McCain was blunt. He said Buchanan was not making
progress in New Hampshire where the state's booming economy is
drowning out Buchanan's protectionist message.
</P>
<P>
   And McCain suggested the Reform Party may not be a good fit for
Buchanan, who has emphasized social issues such as abortion. The
Reform Party focuses more on economic issues.
</P>
<P>
   Next to his book, McCain's claim to fame is his authorship of
one of the major campaign-finance bills now before Congress. McCain
and his Democratic colleague, Sen. Russ Feingold of Wisconsin,
recently pared down the measure, but its chief target is still the
large, unregulated amounts of ``soft'' money that can be
contributed to political parties.
</P>
<P>
   On the subject of money and politics, McCain is clearly
impatient, even angry, although his stand has proved unpopular with
some other senators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soft money corrupts the legislative process,'' McCain said
earlier Tuesday on KCUR's ``Walt Bodine Show.'' ``We are now
involved in a vast influence-peddling scheme that keeps us all in
office.''
</P>
<P>
   The money-drenched political system is turning off younger
Americans in droves, McCain said. And it's discouraging Americans
of all stripes who see well-heeled interests receiving special
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder that the tax code is 44,000 pages long, McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's full of deals good for special interests,'' he said.
``It's just wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 0049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
