<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NJ-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFRONTING POLICE MISCONDUCT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, Sept. 22:
</P>
<P>
   Correcting the long history of racial discrimination in the New
Jersey State Police will take more than the appointment of a new
superintendent. But Gov. Christie Whitman has made a positive move
by nominating Carson Dunbar, an administrator in the FBI's New York
office, to lead the troubled department.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar, who was a New Jersey trooper in the 1970s, will become
the first person of African-American ancestry to head the
2,700-member force. He faces the daunting task of changing a police
culture that has tolerated racial harassment against minority
troopers and allowed the use of racial profiling _ the illegal
practice of targeting motorists by skin color _ to flourish for
years. But the crisis will not end with Dunbar's arrival. The
Justice Department is investigating discrimination complaints and
may appoint a federal monitor to oversee the police. Numerous
lawsuits alleging bias by the agency have also been filed by
current and former troopers.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few months Whitman has ordered an overhaul of
hiring and promotion practices and appointed a monitor within the
state attorney general's office to oversee the police. But leaders
in minority communities remain skeptical. Change will depend on
whether she makes police reform a priority in her remaining years
in office _ and on whether Dunbar is strong enough to root out
those who have tolerated racist practices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 0050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1024 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-PIRATES-HN     09-22 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-PIRATES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
PITTSBURGH _ Prior to Tuesday, Astros manager Larry Dierker had
gotten more innings out of his bullpen than he had from his
starting rotation on the current road trip, which pretty much tells
you why they lost three of the first four games.
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the sake of the arm-weary bullpen, the Astros were in
desperate need of a quality start Tuesday, and Scott Elarton rose
to the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Elarton, who has pitched with tendinitis in his right shoulder
for most of the season, threw a career-high 131 pitches and worked
6 strong innings to lead the Astros to a 6-3 victory over the
Pittsburgh Pirates. It was the Astros' first win at Three Rivers
Stadium this season.
</P>
<P>
   The only downer of the evening came during the eighth inning
when closer Billy Wagner felt a twinge in his left elbow. Wagner
didn't think it was anything to be alarmed about, but to be on the
safe side Dierker used veteran righthander Doug Henry to pitch the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy wanted to go back out there,'' Dierker said. ``But the
trainers didn't think he should go back, (pitching coach) Vern
(Ruhle) didn't think he should go back and I didn't think he should
go back. About the only person who thought he should go back was
Billy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We practically had to tackle him to keep him from going out
there. I didn't see any reason to take chances. With a three-run
lead, I thought Henry could do the job. Being a pitcher and having
problems with my arm, it scares the heck out of me to think of them
feeling anything in their arms.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry allowed two baserunners in the ninth but kept the Pirates
from scoring to earn his second save. His was one of the few fresh
arms in a bullpen that has worked far too many innings over the
past five days. That's what made Elarton's workmanlike effort so
timely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elarton really gave us everything he had,'' Dierker said. ``It
was a great effort. Our bullpen got beat up in St. Louis, and it
got beat up here last night. We didn't have many guys down there
with fresh arms.''
</P>
<P>
   Elarton (9-4) engaged in a pitchers' duel of young guns with
Pirates righthander Kris Benson, who pitched seven innings. Both
took shutouts into the seventh inning, with Benson (11-14) losing
his to a four-run outburst by the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, Elarton was gone after allowing three of the
first four batters he faced to reach base in the bottom of the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little surprised,'' Elarton said of his high pitch
count. ``After I had runners at first and second in the seventh
inning, I didn't have a lot left. Because of my shoulder, I don't
think I have quite the stamina I'd like to have. It really takes a
lot to get it loose in the late innings.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates put runners in scoring position against Elarton in
each of the first three innings but never broke through. After the
Pirates squandered their best scoring chances, Elarton retired 10
of 11 batters before running out of gas in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Astros were faring no better against Benson, who
retired 17 of the first 19 batters he faced, including 13 in a row.
The Astros advanced one runner into scoring position prior to their
prosperous seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Benson has always been pretty good,'' said Astros left fielder
Daryle Ward, who faced Benson during his minor-league career. ``He
goes right at you with his best stuff. He's not scared to challenge
you, and that's a sign that a pitcher's going to be good.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward's one-out single broke a scoreless tie in the seventh, and
the Astros scored three runs on Paul Bako's two-run double and a
throwing error by Pirates first baseman Kevin Young, who was trying
to nail Bako at third after Ricky Gutierrez had grounded out.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Cabrera inherited Elarton's seventh-inning jam and pitched
admirably despite allowing two of Elarton's runners to score on
Mike Benjamin's fielder's choice grounder and a single by Brian
Giles, who is 6-for-9 with three RBIs in the first two games of the
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's seems like Giles and (Kevin) Young are coming up every
inning,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Barker's two-run single in the eighth made it a four-run
lead, but Brant Brown's solo homer off Cabrera gave the Pirates
hope in the bottom of the inning. Wagner squelched that rally, and
Henry handled the ninth to pull the Astros to within a game of .500
on what has been a trying road trip.
</P>
<P>
   It's not often the Astros win two of five games and none of the
wins is credited to Mike Hampton, Jose Lima or Shane Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened to those guys in their last starts is not going
to happen very often,'' Elarton said. ``They just had a bad day.
It's good to know that (Chris Holt) and I can give us some strong
innings, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
