<HEADER>
A1025 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-TENNIS-KC-KAN &LR;      09-22 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TENNIS-KC-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMASH HITS EVENT A HIT WITH TENNIS, MUSIC FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MECHELLE VOEPEL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ You know how it is. Athletes want to be rock
stars, rock stars want to be athletes, and ordinary folks just want
to be around either one.
</P>
<P>
   So at All-Star Smash Hits on Tuesday at Municipal Auditorium, a
lot of people got what they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   The DuPont World TeamTennis event, in which musician Elton
John's team won 21-17 over the team captained by tennis legend
Billie Jean King, raised money for AIDS awareness and prevention,
and provided quite a few laughs for the 5,793 in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   From the tennis standpoint, four-time U.S. Open and three-time
Wimbledon champion John McEnroe said, ``It's about 80-90 percent
fun. But you want to show you can still swat a few balls around.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as Martina Navratilova, who won a record 167 singles titles
during her pro career, said, ``We're all very nice to each other
until near the end. Then the blood starts to flow.''
</P>
<P>
   The tennis just wasn't the old-timer stuff, though. The No. 1
men's player, Andre Agassi, and No. 6 women's player, Mary Pierce,
also were part of the event. So was Alexandra Stevenson, an
18-year-old player who made it to the Wimbledon semifinals in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have here is three generations of tennis,'' King said
during a news conference with her team of Agassi, Stevenson, Bob
Bryan and Mariaan de Swardt, who plays for the World TeamTennis'
Kansas City Explorers. ``Young, middle-aged and...mature.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, 29, piped up, ``Which am I?''
</P>
<P>
   King responded, ``You're middle-aged.''
</P>
<P>
   In tennis years, that's right. In real life, the middle-ager is
the 55-year-old King, with beat-up knees but boundless energy. She
and John met in 1973, just before her ``Battle of the Sexes''
victory over Bobby Riggs, and have been friends ever since.
</P>
<P>
   King founded World TeamTennis, and John wrote the hit song
``Philadelphia Freedom'' in honor of the Philly team King played
for in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like little kids together,'' King said. ``We've always
just connected like that.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the seventh Smash Hits event they've conducted, the
first in Kansas City. None of the participants was paid. All
proceeds go to the Elton John AIDS Foundation and two local groups,
the Heart of America Community AIDS Partnership and Design
Industries Foundation Fighting AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The previous Smash Hits events have raised about $1.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Preceeding the tennis was an auction, at which the top bid was
Nancy Kauffman's $25,000 for four tickets to John's post-Oscars
party in Beverly Hills, Calif., next March. The auction raised
$128,875, approximately 50 percent of which stays with the local
charities.
</P>
<P>
   The best auctioneer proved to be Agassi, who got $10,500 for the
racket he used to win the U.S. Open title a week and half ago.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest fun for those at the auction, though, was just
seeing so many superstars live and in person, a dream come true for
some. Meanwhile, John was asked whether a dream of his would be to
switch places with a pro tennis player.
</P>
<P>
   Before he could answer, McEnroe tried his hand at singing,
warbling the opening of ``Rocket Man'': ``She packed my bags last
night...''
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't everybody want to be a rock star? Or an athlete?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
