<SLUG> BC-CHARTER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
55 CHARTER SCHOOLS IN HOT WATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA BIGGS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phoenix officials said Tuesday that they will shut down as many
as 55 charter schools unless the institutions confirm that they
have met legal occupancy requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said the 55 schools lack certificates of
occupancy, documents that show the institutions meet health, safety
and other conditions required by law.
</P>
<P>
   Potential problems at the schools could range from such minor
areas as landscaping to serious matters like health and safety
issues, said Alan Olson, Phoenix assistant director of development
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to shut anybody down for minor, inconsequential
issues,'' Olson said. ``But if we find major safety issues . . . we
have no choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson said that the city sent out notification letters Monday to
27 of the schools, and that about a dozen responded Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The other 28 letters will be sent out next week. The schools
have 10 days to respond or be found in non-compliance.
</P>
<P>
   Calls late Tuesday to several of the first 27 schools went
unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Graham Keegan, state superintendent of public instruction,
said Tuesday that she believes the city's concern is a legitimate
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been unhappy with what I think was some loose record
keeping,'' Keegan said. ``That does not mean we've got 55 schools
out there that are unsafe.''
</P>
<P>
   But Keegan called the city's action ``a good opportunity to go
back and check that everyone's got their things in order.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about charter schools were raised earlier this month
when a downtown Phoenix institution was found to be in violation of
fire-safety regulations. Sterling Academy of Mathematics and
Sciences, chartered by the Peach Springs Unified School District in
far northwestern Arizona, remains closed.
</P>
<P>
   The Sterling case evoked a statement of concern from Gov. Jane
Hull and prompted the state fire marshal to order inspections of
every Arizona charter school within the next month.
</P>
<P>
   Gretchen Wolfe, a charter-school consultant who serves on the
board of EduPreneurship Student Center, said some charters located
in churches had received a mixed message regarding certificates of
occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a gray area not long ago where the schools were
being told if the church had a certificate of occupancy that
included the classrooms, that was good enough,'' she said. ``That's
why I think a bunch of these are getting caught.''
</P>
<P>
   EduPreneurship's Phoenix campus is one of the 27 schools
receiving notice from the city. However, many of the other schools
on the list are not operating in churches.
</P>
<P>
   Keegan agreed that some schools might be operating under the
mistaken notion that their building's former certificate of
occupancy remains valid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like buying a car and not changing the name on the
title,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She emphasized that the state has 380 charter schools and that
only a handful has exhibited problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's growing pains,'' Keegan said. ``The most important thing
is, Number 1, are the kids safe? Is it academically sound and is
the money being followed well?'' &QL; 
Patricia Biggs can be reached at (602) 444-2473 or at
patricia.biggs(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
