<HEADER>
A1029 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     09-22 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREER'S INJURY A SCARY SITUATION FOR THE STRETCH DRIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ They were cruising along with the greatest of
first-place ease.
</P>
<P>
   The manager and general manager had new contracts. The catcher
was batting .331. The magic number was seven, and counting.
</P>
<P>
   On a clear evening such as last night, the Rangers could see
October.
</P>
<P>
   Except, alas, for left fielder Rusty Greer, who had enough
trouble seeing Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the top of the fifth inning against the Baltimore Orioles,
Roberto Kelly took Greer's place in left field. The terse
announcement in the press box said only that Greer was removed from
the game after ``experiencing discomfort in his left eye.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the same left eye, of course, that served as a catcher's
mitt for a ball thrown by teammate Rick Helling nine days ago. The
same left eye that Greer said ``couldn't see anything'' in the
minutes after the accident. The same left eye that doctors had
checked, rechecked and finally diagnosed as being back to 20-20.
</P>
<P>
   The only left eye that Rusty Greer has ever had.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was made that Greer will be checked today by
both an opthamologist and a retina specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Call me old-fashioned, but for lack of a better word, this is
scary news. We're talking about an eyeball here, not a pulled groin
or a sore elbow. We're talking about a vital chord in the lineup's
nine-piece harmony. We're talking about a career here, not just a
pennant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it's scary,'' Greer admitted after the game. ``It's
scary because more than anything, you don't know when it's going to
get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Call me squeamish, but talk of eyeballs sends chills up my
spine. A broken foot _ no problem. A fastball off the top of the
noggin' _ no big deal.
</P>
<P>
   But start talking about poking eyeballs, and I get weak in the
knees. In grammar school, a kid in my class used to be able to turn
his eyelids inside out. Every time he did it at recess, which was
almost daily, I would feel like throwing up.
</P>
<P>
   While working out in the outfield before a game last week in
Kansas City, Greer walked smack into a long-toss pitch thrown by
Helling. It made a sound, Rusty says, that he'll never forget.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the Rangers don't need this. Greer is batting .302 and
was poised for his first 20-home run, 100-runs-batted-in season. He
bats third in the order and, as his 102 runs scored attest, he is a
vital piece in the Rangers' vision of a bright postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Greer said he felt no pain, but reported experiencing blurred
vision during his second at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was blurry from the outfield, not so much at shorter
distances,'' Greer said, as a post-game media crowd gathered around
him. ``I just felt uncomfortable out there and didn't want to cost
the ballclub. That's when I went to Johnny and asked to come out.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a thing, of course, that I don't normally do.''
</P>
<P>
   Except when he runs into walls, Greer almost always plays. But
in 1996, he ran into the wall at Cleveland and fractured a rib in
his right side. Greer missed 15 critical games from Sept. 6-20, and
the Rangers went 6-9, disappearing from the pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, including last night's 4-2 defeat, the team is
4-3 since Greer's eye injury. Not exactly a late-season collapse,
but . . . it's an eyeball we're talking about here. Didn't that
have something to do with Kirby Puckett's retirement?
</P>
<P>
   At his locker, Rusty offered one possible explanation. Though he
had worked out in recent days, he had not performed under game
conditions. He also had taken batting practice, but had neither hit
nor tried to catch fly balls under the lights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's just the fact that I got whacked in the eye and
it's only been eight days,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After his initial examination, doctors assured Greer that the
eye would get better.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when?'' Rusty wondered last night. ``Does that happen
tomorrow? Two weeks from now? Two months?''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball, we are reminded at times like this, isn't called
hardball for nothing. The mind races and thinks about Don Slaught,
Dickie Thon _ both of them one-time Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize,'' Greer said, soberly, ``it's not only life, but
career and everything else we're talking about here.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of losing Rusty Greer at this point should scare all
Rangers fans sily.
</P>
<P>
   It's an eyeball we're talking about. And suddenly, October
doesn't seem all that clear.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
