<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1038 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-DEADKIDS-AZR &LR;      09-22 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEADKIDS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
5 YEARS LATER, TRIAL AP PROACHES FOR MOM, BEAU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL SOWERS AND VICTORIA   
 Harker  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five years after a convicted prostitute and her mentally
retarded boyfriend were charged with killing her two small
children, neither has gone to trial and they have lived in a
Maricopa County jail longer than anyone else awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Greer, 32, and Brent Linner, 29, were charged in
December 1994 with first-degree murder and child abuse in the
deaths of Henry, 5, and Odessa, 3, who police say were beaten with
tennis rackets, drowned in a bathtub, wrapped in garbage bags and
pushed 10 &UR; feet down a sewer line under a manhole cover.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago this week, the children were discovered. They had
been murdered up to four months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The grisly tale of the Greer children of Phoenix dominated the
news in late 1994 and raised questions once again about child
welfare in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after 30 postponements, Greer, who has a history of mental
illness and drug addiction, is expected to be tried on Nov. 15, and
Linner, diagnosed as severely retarded, is slated for trial Dec. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, homicide defendants go to court in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of pages of court records in the case document delays
typical of a court system that has been grappling with ways to move
criminal cases more rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   The postponements were caused, in part, by a tangle of
scheduling conflicts between prosecutors and defense attorneys who
were juggling multiple cases. There were also changes in judges
scheduled to hear the case.
</P>
<P>
   One woman, Paula Davey, who had herself appointed the victim
advocate for the dead children, is outraged over the delays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want these children to be forgotten,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Court records show that Loretta Greer has been the architect of
many of the delays. In some instances, she has refused to go to
court. She has dismissed two court-appointed attorneys, and she has
delayed her trial for two years by apparently faking symptoms of
mental illness, according to court records.
</P>
<P>
   From 1994 to 1996, Greer tried to convince court officials that
she was mentally incapable of assisting in her defense and should
not go to trial.
</P>
<P>
   But in September 1996, Commissioner Carey Hyatt declared her
competent to stand trial because she said Greer was ``intentionally
producing general or exaggerated psychological symptoms.''
</P>
<P>
   Linner was declared fit to stand trial within a year after he
was charged with murder. Greer's demands also delayed Linner's
trial as they were originally to be tried together. The decision to
try them separately was made only recently.
</P>
<P>
   Greer's bizarre behavior is a legend in the courthouse. In some
appearances, she has yelled or hummed. Once, she had to be tied
into a wheelchair with a blanket.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very manipulative,'' said Luis Calvo, one of her fired
attorneys. ``She tries to take charge in court.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Greer is confined to a special section of the jail reserved for
the most troublesome inmates and has a single cell.
</P>
<P>
   Linner and Greer were charged in December 1994, but she had been
in jail since September, and he since November on unrelated
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Greer's care alone has cost county taxpayers $66,950, based on
the typical $35 daily cost of keeping an inmate.
</P>
<P>
   Since she has been in custody, Greer has also sent the jail into
turmoil, filing 719 grievances in 1998 alone, including claims that
her food is poisoned, that other inmates call her ``baby killer''
and that slamming cell doors keep her awake at night. &QL; 
READY FOR TRIALS
</P>
<P>
   Maricopa County Attorney Rick Romley does not fault judges for
the delays, saying they have to be sure that Greer and Linner can
assist in their defenses. If those issues were ignored, he said,
convictions could be reversed on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, he says, ``We continue to argue that we are ready
to go to trial but, ultimately, the decision is up to the court.
There is no way to intervene at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer is to be tried by Judge Bernard Dougherty; Linner by Judge
Paul Katz.
</P>
<P>
   Court rules prohibit judges from discussing active cases.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors are asking for the death penalty for Greer. But in
July, they said they would not seek Linner's execution, in part
because of his mental retardation. &QL; 
DEATH DESCRIPTIONS
</P>
<P>
   In a March jailhouse interview requested by ``The Arizona
Republic,'' Greer blamed Linner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voices told him to kill right around the time of the murder,''
Greer said, saying she can't recall what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was strayed from the here and now,'' she said. ``All I know
is that what I was going through was very scary. Demons were trying
to take me away.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews with police in 1994, Linner told them that Greer
beat the children with the tennis racket, then drowned them. Greer
wove a different story, telling police that they died three weeks
apart. She doesn't specify dates.
</P>
<P>
   Henry died first, she said, after he fell and hit his head, then
drowned. ``Brent said he would get rid of the body,'' she told
police, but didn't elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   She admitted hitting Henry with a tennis racket four times the
day he died. And she said she struck Odessa with a 16-inch-long rod
about two weeks before she &UR; found her dead in a closet.
</P>
<P>
   The day she died, Odessa had been left in the closet for 18
hours, Greer told police. She said she and Linner decided to put
the 3-year-old in the sewer.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear when the children died. Court records say it was
sometime between May and July 1994. Their decomposed bodies were
found only after Linner led police to a manhole cover near their
36th Avenue and Osborn Road apartment on Sept. 20, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Linner took police to the bodies because he said he was angry
with Greer for hitting him over the head with a pot.
</P>
<P>
   From jail, Greer, who has two other children in foster care,
insists that ``there is no mother who loves her babies more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a monster like that,'' she said. &QL; 
Carol Sowers can be reached at (602) 444-7482 or at
carol.sowers(at)pni.com. Victoria Harker can be reached at (602)
444-8058 or at victoria.harker(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
