<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1041 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-LAPD-PROBE-2TAKES-LAD     09-22 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAPD-PROBE-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECIAL BOARD TO STUDY LAPD OPERATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Staff Writer Troy Anderson contributed to this story 
BY RICK ORLOV AND PHILLIP W. BROWNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Fighting to restore the LAPD's credibility,
Police Chief Bernard C. Parks announced that he has launched an
unprecedented Board of Inquiry investigation of the entire
department in the wake of the Rampart Division corruption scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The board _ 60 command staffers above the rank of captain with a
six-week deadline _ will examine whether the LAPD is plagued by the
same failed procedures and policies that allowed Officer Rafael
Perez to steal eight pounds of cocaine from an evidence locker and
frame a 22-year-old illegal immigrant.
</P>
<P>
   Parks said a criminal probe will continue on a parallel track,
focusing on Perez and 11 other officers who have been suspended in
the wake of Perez's conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a good likelihood more officers will be identified as
the investigation continues,'' Parks said after testifying before
the Police Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue running down every lead. We may end up with a
lot of information we can't prove.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a citywide agency, and we will look throughout the
department for problems. When we go to someone's house at 2 in the
morning, we have to have the public's confidence to let us in.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks' announcement came amid the following developments in the
deepening LAPD corruption scandal:
</P>
<P>
   Police Commission Inspector General Jeff Eglash said he will
monitor the investigations, and Parks and the City Council assured
him he will receive access to all documents and resources.
</P>
<P>
   An injunction against the 18th Street gang that was based on
former Officer Perez's testimony was suspended by a judge partly
because of inaccuracies in his statements.
</P>
<P>
   City and county officials urged the re-establishment of the
district attorney's team to investigate officer-involved shootings
independently of the police. It was disbanded in 1996 for lack of
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a backstop. It's insurance against a breakdown in the
integrity of the system,'' said county Supervisor Zev Yaroslavsky.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Tom Hayden, D-Los Angeles, urged the Police
Commission to investigate the ``de facto custody'' of Javier
Francisco Ovando, the 22-year-old illegal immigrant allegedly
framed by Perez and his partner, Officer Nino Durden, in an October
1996 assault that left Ovando paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commission President Gerald Chaleff said it was too early
to determine whether a commission investigation is warranted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my understanding that Mr. Ovando's wishes are being
respected. But if facts come to light that require us looking into
the matter, we most certainly will.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks said Ovando is not in police custody.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been free to come or go, to call whoever he wishes,''
Parks said. ``We are providing security, but he is not in any form
of custody.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys who have accused the LAPD of holding Ovando against
his will have other motives, Parks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The motives of the attorneys who say otherwise had no concern
for Ovando until they realized they had an opportunity to sue the
city.''
</P>
<P>
   Ovando said in an interview that he has requested police
protection because of the media attention and uncertainties he
faces now that he's out of prison.
</P>
<P>
   He said he thanks God that he is alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never imagined that all this was going to happen. But as you
see, I came out free,'' Ovando, speaking in Spanish from inside a
police facility to KABC-TV (Channel 7).
</P>
<P>
   Parks said Perez believes he will need five more days to divulge
all he knows about the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the nature of an investigation,'' Parks said. ``We have
to document everything he says, and we want more clarification on
everything he has raised. That's the way it goes. You start with A
and go to Z. You don't start at Z and work backwards. We will go
wherever this takes us.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks said he is stepping up training of officers to end the
``code of silence'' in which officers refuse to inform superiors of
any misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   The chief said the department is preparing a guide for officers
on false and misleading statements.
</P>
<P>
   Parks said the scandal has severely affected morale throughout
the department.
</P>
<P>
   ``It affects everyone, us, the community, the City Council,''
Parks said. ``Officers are the most visual part of city government
and the only legacy officers have is their word, their credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``When something like this happens it takes that credibility
away and has a major impact on the city.''
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: impact on the city.''
</P>
<P>
   City Attorney James Hahn said prosecutors will go to court today
to seek a suspension on the MacArthur Park gang injunction,
following a Superior Court judge's suspension for one month of an
injunction against the 18th Street gang in the Pico-Union area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to review this and hope we can come back to court to
get these reinstated,'' Hahn said. ``We worked very hard on it, but
the bottom line is that if we don't have confidence in the
declarations given to us (in support of a judicial order), we can't
ask the court to continue enforcement of the injunction.''
</P>
<P>
   The injunctions are in jeopardy because of testimony concerning
Ovando. Perez told investigators it was Durden who shot Ovando.
</P>
<P>
   Hahn said his office is in the process of working with the
District Attorney's Office in reviewing every case in which Perez
was a witness and he also voiced concern of the potential liability
facing the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have big payouts in jury trials, it's because the
jury is mad.''
</P>
<P>
   The LAPD Board of Inquiry _ the largest ever assembled _ will
include a fresh look at the Rampart Division anti-gang unit in
which Perez worked and whether it had enough supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Because of space problems at Rampart, the unit was provided with
its own space in offices away from the station.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that might have caused some of the problem,'' said an
official familiar with the inquiry. ``They were basically on their
own, with no one watching them. Not a watch commander. Not a
captain.''
</P>
<P>
   During the Police Commission meeting, Chaleff emphasized that
Eglash will have ``complete access'' to all documents and every
step taken in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will be able to look at every sensitive document, go to
every meeting, every interview that is conducted. He will have
absolute, complete access.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
