<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1043 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN     09-22 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LOS ANGELES _ Some years ago, the owner of another NFL team helped
broker the purchase of the San Francisco 49ers by the Eddie
DeBartolo clan, father and son.
</P>
<P>
   The Morabito brothers were the sellers, meaning that on both
sides the deal was all in the family. At the closing, one of the
Morabitos announced there had been unexpected expenses and the
price had gone up a million.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie DeBartolo Sr. leaped from his seat and growled, ``I won't
pay it. I don't do business that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The attendant owner was beside him, and also beside himself. He
tugged at the elder DeBartolo's sleeve and whispered, ``Eddie, let
me to talk to you.''
</P>
<P>
   They moved to an adjoining room, and the middleman went straight
to the bottom line: ``Pay the million. Get the deal done. It's
still a sweeter deal than you can imagine.'' While Senior was
thinking it over, the kid was jumping up and down, telling him,
``Listen to him, Dad. He knows what he's talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was done. A few weeks later, the NFL announced that the
new contract for television rights had tripled over the previous
payment. Suddenly, the million-dollar bump seemed like
popcorn-and-candy money.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers became the team of the '80s with Eddie Jr. running the
show and spending freely until he was sacked by legal woes and
forced to yield his control of the franchise. The NFL giveth, and
the NFL taketh away.
</P>
<P>
   Which bring us to the latest turn on the yellow brick road that
may or may not lead to an expansion franchise, the league's 32nd
and last as far into the future as your eyes can see.
</P>
<P>
   It appears Los Angeles is down to its final bidder, Marvin
Davis, a poor but humble billionaire who up to now has led a
sheltered life as a movie mogul and oilman. Davis is said to have
told the NFL he will not quibble over the franchise, rumored to
cost above $500 million, and is prepared to pay for a stadium on
land he has optioned at Hollywood Park. At 74, he wants his two
sons, Gregg and John, to manage the investment.
</P>
<P>
   A new element to the deal is the expressed interest of John
Elway as a shareholder and potential team president. The inclusion
of Elway on his side adds depth to the Davis bid, although it isn't
clear he would bring cash to the table, even though he sold his
shares in a national car chain for $85 million. Also, it has
occurred to many fans that John is not finished doing God's work in
the huddle of the Denver Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Davis has been mentioned as a possible buyer of the
Dodgers, Cowboys, Broncos and Oakland A's. But no deals were
struck, proving this may be a shrewd horse trader or merely someone
whose name is easily dropped.
</P>
<P>
   If Davis is indeed willing and able to shell out nearly a
billion for the franchise fee and sports complex, sources say the
NFL might drop its demand for a significant amount of tax dollars.
Up to now, this policy has been depicted as a test of community
sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the speculation spins and buzzes here, the league's
expansion committee is reported to be talking with Bob McNair,
trying to negotiate the final price of a franchise in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   As of the moment, we can hold these truths to be self-evident:
The owners have been impressed with McNair's persistence, his hard
work, his net worth, his willingness to meet their conditions. Even
those who don't like anybody seem to like McNair.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, an owner who lavishes praise on McNair offers
nary an encouraging word. ``He's a great guy,'' this owner says,
``but they are going to shaft him. He doesn't know it, but they are
going to shaft him.''
</P>
<P>
   No one who has followed his effort can doubt that McNair
deserves a franchise _ if you think owning an NFL team is a good
thing to have happen to you.
</P>
<P>
   Several owners are still on the fence about expanding at all,
preferring to go with none of the above for the time being. The
pressure to admit Los Angeles is being brought by the networks, to
which the owners often respond in unison, ``Yes, boss.''
</P>
<P>
   The league's television contract is heavily back-loaded, up to
2003, and there is strong sentiment not to expand the lodge until
after that date.
</P>
<P>
   There is still skepticism that Marvin Davis will prove to be the
man, or Los Angeles the city. But on the drive into town Tuesday,
the gentleman behind the wheel said, ``You hear that there is a lot
of apathy in this town, but that isn't what I hear. The other day
the Los Angeles Daily News ran a poll, and 79 percent of the voters
said they would take back Al Davis and the Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that surprised me. I bet it even surprised Al Davis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
