<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1047 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-PRICELINE-GROCERIES-N     09-22 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRICELINE-GROCERIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROCERIES JOIN BIG ITEMS ON A NAME-YOUR-PRICE WEB SITE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.J., Conn.)  (mk) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Priceline.com Inc., an online bidding site for
big-ticket purchases like airline tickets and automobiles, plans to
begin offering consumers in the New York area cut-rate prices on
groceries like applesauce and cereal.
</P>
<P>
   In a deal announced Tuesday, Priceline will license its
trademark and software to Priceline.com Webhouse Club Inc., a new
venture through which consumers can set the prices they are willing
to pay for grocery store staples ranging from disposable razors to
peanut butter. If participating supermarkets accept the prices, the
purchases can be picked up at the stores with a shopping list
reflecting the discounts. Consumers will print out the discount
lists from their computers.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Nov. 1, 600 supermarkets in New York, New Jersey and
Connecticut, including Food Emporium, A&AMP;P and D'Agostino, will
begin taking part in the operation.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, shoppers looking to shave costs from their grocery
bills can log on to the Webhouse Club at Priceline.com and name
their preferred price on a particular item. If the bid is accepted,
the price is locked in and the cost of the item is charged to the
customer's credit card. Members print out their private price lists
and go to the store.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a whole new way to save money,'' said Walter D'Agostino,
of D'Agostino supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but shoppers would be well advised not to count on
buying a case of Coke for a buck or lobster tails for $1.99.
Customers will receive up to 40 percent off regular store prices
and half off on some goods.
</P>
<P>
   By offering a new way to save, Webhouse and its retail partners
are taking aim at buy-in-bulk price clubs and a growing number of
online supermarket operators.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Otto, Webhouse's president and chief executive, said,
``Unlike product-ordering Web sites, with their fixed prices,
shipping fees and delayed delivery, we view America's neighborhood
stores as a powerful and unmatched asset.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial analysts who follow the grocery business said the
Webhouse model might appeal to coupon clippers and online shopping
aficionados but would not likely change the way most people shop
for milk and bread. For one, they said they doubted that harried
shoppers would take the time to point-and-click to bid on an entire
shopping list to save 15 cents on a can of soup or a stick of
deodorant. What is more, many low-income consumers, who would
benefit most from discount pricing, will be virtually excluded from
the savings because getting the discounts requires a computer, an
Internet account and a credit card. After 90 days, users will be
charged $3 per month for the service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not overly excited about it,'' said Ray Dirks, an analyst
with Security Capital Trading. ``I really think the larger-price
items are much more appropriate for something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   But Priceline sees the expansion of its ``name-your-price''
concept to everyday, small-ticket items as a way to expand its
Web-based business.
</P>
<P>
   ``By initially allowing consumers to name their price for
products in more than 140 frequently purchased grocery categories,
and eventually expanding to a much wider variety of retail
categories, the increased traffic to Priceline.com as a whole will
help accelerate the growth of Priceline.com's airline, hotel and
other businesses,'' said Jay Walker, founder and vice chairman of
Priceline, which plans to expand the service nationally by next
year. Priceline, which is based in Stamford, Conn., will also
eventually receive fee-for-referral payments from the participating
supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, said Rakesh Sood, an analyst who follows the company
for Goldman Sachs, is for consumers to become so familiar with
clicking onto Priceline that they eventually turn to the site for
competitive prices on an extended range of goods and services like
rental cars and credit card deals. Retailers hope the concept will
lure more bargain hunters.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Webhouse Club, each of our customers can
electronically tell us what they want to buy and the price they
want to pay,'' said Christian Haub, A&AMP;P's chief executive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
