<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINES ANNOUNCE `VOLUNTARY' PLEDGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because concern about Hurricane Floyd crowded out much other
news last week, few people appear to have noticed that the nation's
airlines filed with the Department of Transportation their pledges
to improve customer service.
</P>
<P>
   The ``voluntary'' pledges, which were actually adopted under
congressional threats to come up with improvements or else, are an
outgrowth of growing customer dissatisfaction with the overall
flight experience, dissatisfaction that boiled over after Detroit
passengers were kept aboard planes for hours last January during a
killer snowstorm hit the city.
</P>
<P>
   Now the airlines have agreed to tell passengers the lowest fare
available for each flight, to notify customers of cancellations,
delays and diversions, to ensure that all written complaints are
responded to within 60 days and to make every reasonable effort to
provide food, water and restroom facilities for on-board passengers
who are on the ground for an extended period.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have said that some of the proposals, all of which are
required to go into effect by Dec. 15, are already required by law
or by custom. But some airlines have gone beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   Delta, for example, will telephone customers to notify them of
flight cancellations when they are known at least two hours before
departure. (The new pledges provide that airlines notify customers
at the airport or aboard an affected airplane.) Northwest promised
not to hold passengers on-board an aircraft for more than one hour
in the event of an in-bound flight delay. US Airways plans a
consumer advisory board to provide advice on the airline's
performance.
</P>
<P>
   United will deploy 600 high-tech baggage scanners at its busiest
airports, and its web site will list fares from other airlines. In
case of a delay or overbooked flight, Alaska Airlines will offer,
among other things, a kit containing a phone card, snack
certificate and a choice of frequent flier miles or discount off
future travel.
</P>
<P>
   Still, none of the pledges addressed a big complaint of economy
class passengers: Since airlines continue to jam passengers into
every available inch of space (in fareness, probably because
passengers want rock-bottom fares that just about mandate packing
passengers like sardines), why isn't at least one airline bold
enough or prescient enough to adjust its seats to keep them from
reclining more than an inch or two, instead of into the lap of the
person directly behind.
</P>
<P>
   Air France is offering bargain fares to more than 80 European
cities, including roundtrip fares to Paris for $328 from New York,
Newark and Boston; $388 from Washington; $408 from Atlanta and
Chicago; $478 from San Francisco and $528 from Los Angeles. Good
for departures from Nov. 1 through March 31, 2000, tickets must be
bought no later than Oct. 5. Restrictions apply.
</P>
<P>
   Through midnight this Friday, British Airways has discount fares
available for travel to London from Oct. 1 through Dec. 8.
Examples: From nine East Coast gateways, including Boston, Newark
and New York's Kennedy Airport, $198 for departure on Wednesday,
$300 for departure on Saturday. The corresponding fares for
Chicago, Detroit, Houston, Dallas and Miami are $248 and $350, and
from Denver, Phoenix, Seattle, San Francisco, Los Angeles and San
Diego, $298 to $400. Restrictions apply.
</P>
<P>
   Delta cut fares yesterday for travel in much of the United
States and to some European destinations, for travel between Oct. 5
and Dec. 15. Fares are said to be as much as 35 percent less than
21-day advance purchase tickets, with even bigger discounts for
booking online. American and Continental matched the discounts.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 2, Japan Airlines will begin flying between New York and
Sao Paulo, Brazil, four times a week Through Jan. 31. 2000, members
of the airline's frequent flier program will receive double miles,
while first class and business class passengers who buy their
tickets in the United States will also receive door-to-door
limousine service.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 5, Northwest Airlines will add two additional nonstops a
week between its Minneapolis/St. Paul hub and Tokyo's Narita
airport. The new flights, one on Friday and one on Saturday (the
peak departure days for business travel to Asia), are in addition
to the existing daily nonstops over the same route.
</P>
<P>
   Austrian Airlines made it official Tuesday that it is joining
the Star Alliance, effective next summer. The new member will give
the alliance a formidable presence in Central and Eastern Europe,
to complement its presence throughout much of the rest of the
world. The alliance's other members are United Airlines, Air
Canada, Ansett of Australia, Air New Zealand, Lufthansa of Germany,
Scandinavian Airlines Systems, Thai Airways and Varig of Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran will take delivery Friday of its first Boeing 717, the
new fuel-efficient jet with 117 seats (including 12 in business
class), 100 percent fresh air and increased overhead storage space.
The airline will add seven more B-717s this year and 42 others
through 2002.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 0136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
