<HEADLINE>
`WEST WING' SOARS, `GET REAL' FAKES IT 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roswell is this television season's most lovable mutt. &QL; 
Part X-Files, part (fill in the Buf fy/Dawson/Felicity teen show of
your choosing here), the show, which premieres Oct. 6, makes
excellent use of the one true thing everybody feels in high school:
I'm different from everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Only these kids really are. It's not acne, bad hair or a secret
desire to wear leggings underneath their pants and dance on
Broadway that sets them apart. It's their . . . lineage.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the big spaceship crash in 1947 that the government
keeps covering up? (If you know your X-Files, you do.) Imagine it
really happened. While you're at it, imagine that not all the
aliens were killed _ and that not all were adults. And that just
before the millennium, a network made a show about the survivors.
As a bonus, imagine that they look like refugees from the cover of
Teen People.
</P>
<P>
   Which would make the teens in Roswell more than 50 years old,
but that's people years. Let's not quib ble. Alien years must be
different.
</P>
<P>
   The show takes place in pres ent-day Roswell, N.M., where Liz _
a human, played by Shiri Appleby _ works as a waitress in the
Crashdown Cafe. (Roswell gets bonus cool points for offhandedly
giving entrees out-of-this-world names like the Sigourney Weaver _
you know, she was in the Alien movies. Get it?)
</P>
<P>
   A drunken argument ends with Liz accidentally shot in the chest.
Happily for her, Max (Jason Behr) is on hand _ literally. He heals
her as discreetly as he can. But this being TV, and their being
teens, there's more to the story.
</P>
<P>
   Although she dates the sheriff's lunkheaded son, Liz has her eye
on Max. Having your life saved by your secret crush offers you a
good excuse to talk to him, and soon it's clear that Max has a
thing for Liz, too. But this being TV, and their being teens . . .
well, you know.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff totes around some alien baggage of his own, so he's
suspicious. The lunkheaded boy friend doesn't like his girlfriend
hanging out with another guy.
</P>
<P>
   But most important, it's impera tive to Max, his sister and
their friend that no one discover where they're from (``Up north?''
Liz asks innocently when Max points sky ward).
</P>
<P>
   If all this sounds like a 3rd Rock From the Sun that's actually
worth watching, don't believe it _ Ros well's way better than that.
</P>
<P>
   Its creators, naturally, say there's more to it than alien
shenanigans, and they're right.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a love story, and all this other stuff is part of telling
that love story,'' Jason Katims said this sum mer. ``The thing with
the aliens is really interesting, but it's (only) an aspect of the
show.''
</P>
<P>
   Other aspects include good writ ing, likable characters and
enough quirkiness to remind you you're not watching Felicity on
Mars.
</P>
<P>
   Look for the bad-joke police to make an arrest any minute now,
but it must be said: Roswell is, uh, out of this world. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Other new Wednesday night shows:
</P>
<P>
   The West Wing  &UR; _ The terrible thing about television: With all
the garbage out there, why should we have to choose between this
and Roswell? Aren't there any other time slots available? Aaron
Sorkin, the brains behind Sports Night (and not coincidentally the
writer of the feature film The American Presi dent), takes a stab
at the White House and draws comic blood. It's witty, if, like
Sports Night, a little talky at times. Well worth watching. Just
like Roswell. Ugh.
</P>
<P>
   Get Real  &UR; _ The great thing about television: With two good
shows vying for your time at this hour already, you can skip this
family comedy/drama with Fox atti tude. (Which is to say that when
the moronic son's mom catches a girl spending the night with him,
after worrying a little, she invites her to stay for breakfast.
Kids _ they're so cute at that age.)
</P>
<P>
   Work With Me &UR; _ The worst chemistry since Dr. Jekyll was cooking
up experiments in his lab. Kevin Pollack is no Mr. Hyde _ usually
he's quite likable _ but he and Nancy Travis (usually likable, too)
just don't click as married lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Oh Grow Up _ One roommate just found out he's gay (his wife was
as surprised as he was). Another is a womanizer who discovers he
has a teenage daughter. The third is a Struggling Artist. Oh, and
the dog talks (via subtitles). So why didn't I hate it? Because
somehow the characters are likable, especially Alan Basche as the
artist. Oddly enough, this might grow on you. &QL; 
Reach Bill Goodykoontz at (602) 444-8974 or at bill.goody
koontz &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
