A1060 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     09-22 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOKIE WILLIAMS SAYS G'DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If the high-profile Los Angeles Dodgers starters
pitched this way in April and May, maybe the rookies would never
have had the September proving ground they stand upon now.
</P>
<P>
   Anyhow, Australian lefty Jeff Williams was the third Dodgers
rookie to make his first career start in the past month. And
following the same pattern as Mike Judd and Eric Gagne, Williams
was impressive.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed two hits and an unearned run in five innings to win
his first major-league start, 9-4 against the San Francisco Giants
at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 27, struck out one and walked three. The Giants' only
run scored when left fielder Gary Sheffield apparently lost Barry
Bonds' liner in the lights.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, with two innings of major-league experience, could
have melted there. Instead he didn't allow a runner past second
base after that. He retired seven straight at one point and 11 of
the last 13 batters he faced to defeat Giants' left-hander Kirk
Rueter (14-9).
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros gave the Dodgers a 3-1 lead in the first with his
33rd homer. Raul Mondesi added an RBI single in the third and then
smacked his career-high 31st homer in the seventh to give the
Dodgers a 9-4 lead. In each of the last two seasons, Mondesi hit 30
homers.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield also atoned for his miscue with his 28th homer of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   All things considered, Dodgers manager Davey Johnson would
rather be getting Chan Ho Park, Ismael Valdes and Kevin Brown set
for the playoffs, not figuring out where Williams, Gagne or Judd
fit into the future. But he does have a certain fondness for
watching the inexperienced compete in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this time of year, giving young players an opportunity
to play,'' Johnson said. ``It's an exciting time for the young
players, to bring them up. It's also kind of an ice-breaking for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Judd allowed four earned runs in 61/3 innings in his first
major-league start, a win against the Montreal Expos on Aug. 12.
Judd made three more starts.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne's outing was the most dominant, though he wasn't involved
in the decision against the Florida Marlins. He did, however,
strike out eight and allow two hits in six shutout innings. Gagne's
third start came in Monday's extra-inning victory.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Williams gets another start could depend on the health
of right-hander Darren Dreifort, who's status won't be determined
until Thursday. He's bothered by tightness in his pitching
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing the trio of Williams, Gagne and Judd has done is
give the Dodgers some measure of comfort if they decide to trade
one of their front-line starters in the offseason. Johnson said
either Judd or Gagne could be a fifth starter for the club next
season. Williams may find his name on that list after this start.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, signed as a nondrafted free agent out of Southeastern
Louisiana in 1996, piqued the Dodgers' interest during spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was searching for left-handed help in the bullpen. Chris
Haney and Greg Cadaret were doing very little and Pedro Borbon and
rookie Onan Masaoka had yet to establish themselves. So they took a
look at Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he's been in the Dodgers' plans, though it's
debatable whether he'll project out to a starter or reliever. After
spending his first two years in the organization as a starter,
Williams began this year in the bullpen for Triple-A Albuquerque
before moving to the starting rotation in midseason.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was 5-3 as a reliever with the Dukes and 4-4 as a
starter.
</P>
<P>
   One thing the Dodgers like about Gagne is his ability to toughen
up in adverse situations and battle out of innings. Williams showed
that in the minor leagues by limiting the two-out, run-scoring
hits. Opponents batted .217 with runners on base and two outs
against him.
</P>
</TEXT>
