<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORTIZ REGAINS HIS FORM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Ramon Ortiz has been experiencing his share of
growing pains, the Anaheim Angels' pitching phenom enduring his
knocks in his previous four starts entering Tuesday's game against
the Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   But Ortiz, a hard-throwing right-hander from the Dominican
Republic, on Tuesday regained some of the flash that made the
Angels so optimistic about his future.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz, though, also showed some of the inconsistency that is
common for a 23-year-old rookie who began the season in Double-A.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz went five-plus innings, allowing three runs and four hits
while striking out five and walking four as the Angels won a 7-5
decision before 16,486 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz began the game by throwing seven consecutive pitches out
of the strike zone. Devil Rays leadoff hitter Miguel Cairo walked,
went to second on a wild pitch and scored on Dave Martinez's RBI
single.
</P>
<P>
   But Ortiz responded by retiring the next 13 consecutive hitters.
With one out in the fifth, Jose Guillen broke the string with a
single, but Ortiz struck out Bubba Trammell for the second out of
the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz, though, then walked Tony Graffanino and Cairo to load the
bases before giving up a two-run single to Martinez. Ortiz escaped
further damage by striking out Jose Canseco.
</P>
<P>
   ``More consistency within the strike zone and utilization of all
his pitches. Those are the two main things,'' Angels interim
manager Joe Maddon said before the game, when asked what he's
looking for from Ortiz. ``He's been out of the zone with has
fastball, and his breaking ball has not been as good as we'd like
to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz got some help early from the Angels offense, which was a
change. The Angels had scored only one run in his previous two
starts combined, which includes the no-hitter by the Twins' Eric
Milton.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the Angels got a two-out, two-run single by Andy Sheets
in the second inning, and run-scoring hits by Tim Salmon (single)
and Troy Glaus (double) in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz took a 4-3 lead into the sixth, but gave up a leadoff
double to Fred McGriff, then walked John Flaherty and was yanked.
</P>
<P>
   Gary DiSarcina's two-run homer in the sixth inning _ his first
homer since June 24, 1998, off the Dodgers' Darren Dreifort _ gave
the Angels a 6-3 lead, but the Devil Rays got the two runs back in
the seventh on McGriff's two-run single.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
