<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-THIE-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BOULDER, RICK-BASHING HITS ITS STRIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOULDER, Colo. _ Bent and pointing as he coaches on the Colorado
sidelines, Rick Neuheisel is screaming toward the field in the
5-foot-high black-and-white photo that is mounted next to a huge TV
screen above the back bar in one of this burg's largest sports
bistros, the Lazy Dog.
</P>
<P>
   But the photo has been modified with a hand-crafted cartoon
bubble emerging from his mouth. The four sentences say:
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no loyalty!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't coach!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can be bought!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a loser!''
</P>
<P>
   Which is about as tidy a summary as one will find of the
feelings held by many Buffalo fans here toward their former coach,
who in January took the money and ran to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, if those same words were pasted on a photo of Gary
Barnett and hung in a Chicago sports bar, many Northwestern fans
would hoist a glass in a sarcastic toast to the sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   Barnett is in Colorado now, succeeding Neuheisel. So he is now
officially ordained a hero. At least, until he takes the money and
runs. Or gets fired.
</P>
<P>
   In another part of town, the Pearl Street nightlife strip, Jim
Cunningham is nursing a beer and a resentment toward Neuheisel, who
in four years here won a highly respectable 33 games but apparently
fewer fans. Cunningham is an engineer with a master's degree from
CU and knowledgeable about the seamier aspects of big-time sports.
But talk of Neuheisel short-cuts his brain and gets him in the gut.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be watching that game Saturday with drool coming out of
our mouths,'' he said of the Colorado-Washington match at Husky
Stadium. ``That cheesy little blond -------.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how it often is with Neuheisel, among the most
provocative figures in college football. His same actions, or
inactions, done by another coach would draw scant notice. But
because he is so well-rewarded so young, and is so unlike the
traditional portrait of a college football coach, the condemnations
for his deviations are endless and visceral.
</P>
<P>
   Before Colorado's game with Kansas last week, Barnett showed up
to a team meeting in combat fatigues armed with a clip from the
movie ``Patton'' and a bunch of sophomoric rhetoric about war.
(Personal aside: If elected King of the Sports World, my first act
will be to line up in long rows every jock, coach and fan who uses
war analogies in sports and slap these folks, Three Stooges-style,
until they are too swollen to speak.)
</P>
<P>
   If Neuheisel had pulled that stunt, here or at Washington, he
would have been hooted into resignation. But Barnett drew only
chuckles.
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel probably will be stuck with a bull's eye until he gets
fat and bald, wears sansabelt slacks and uses ``dad-gummit''
instead of complete sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Which isn't to say that Neuheisel is an innocent victim of
superficial judgments. His game-coaching mistakes, along with his
friendlier treatment of players and glib Eddie Haskell-ish style,
have compromised him, burning up credibility with some fans more
quickly than a conventional coach.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the tavern, Cunningham was explaining that the bar of
professional standards is a little different for a football coach.
He accepts Neuheisel's defense that most any worker in any job
would have leapt at the kind of pay and prestige improvements
Neuheisel was offered at Washington. Still ...
</P>
<P>
   ``You like to think that there are some people in the world who
feel some things are bigger than money, even if you don't,'' he
said. ``When you see Rick on the street, he's very approachable,
the kind of regular guy you can go up to and say, `How's it going?'
Then when he goes for the money, after saying he was staying here,
you wonder what to believe; you wonder what example he's setting
for his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we don't expect college coaches to go for the lowest
common denominator.''
</P>
<P>
   There may be no greater repository of naivete than the fans of
big-time college sports.
</P>
<P>
   Over at the Lazy Dog, the bar crowd was full of the usual
Rick-bashing, but one customer offered a similar theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he made the move, it said he cared more about himself
than CU,'' said David, a liquor store manager. ``I would have gone
for the money, too, but you want a leader to be better than you.
That football coach is in charge of a lot of young people, and you
hope he shows them something more important.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people here by now have accepted what happened. But
they don't have to like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone feels so alienated. A popular Pearl Street
restaurant called Pasta Jay's is a hangout for Colorado coaches and
players. The owner, Jay Elowsky, is a big Buffs booster who is a
game-day sideline volunteer and occasionally runs spaghetti to
coaches working late in the video room.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my circle, I hear people say how much they miss him; I know
I do,'' said Elowsky, who is flying to Seattle today for the game
and a little vacation. ``I don't feel betrayed. I think people need
to understand that as long as Rick was here, he was under the
shadow of Bill McCartney (Neuheisel's predecessor who won the 1990
national title). Besides the money at Washington, Rick saw a good
opportunity to put his own print on a program. That's a big
challenge, but very seductive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned the restaurant business from my uncle, working eight
years for him. When I left to start this place 11 years ago, my
uncle felt betrayed. But he knew that I had to go on my own,
because doing it yourself is very alluring.''
</P>
<P>
   The analogy isn't perfect _ the football coaching business gets
customers a little more worked up than the restaurant business.
Fans take their teams, and the rejection of their teams, much more
personally.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, most college fans don't recognize their passion is
just another business. They vainly believe the college game is
something more and better.
</P>
<P>
   What happened at Washington and Colorado last winter, and the
schools' coincidental convergence on the field this Saturday, helps
put a little honest light on remarks from any coach who says he
bleeds purple and gold, or black and gold.
</P>
<P>
   There is one color, green, and as long as everyone understands
that, the Lazy Dog can fill its space above the back bar with a
photo of Barnett dressed in combat fatigues.
</P>
<P>
   Darts, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
