<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1064 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG     09-22 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VETERAN SAYS NHL IS ONLY OPTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Len Barrie, a 30-year-old journeyman center
who spent the past 1{ seasons playing in Germany, isn't down to his
last chance in the NHL, according to Kings coach Andy Murray.
Barrie, however, begs to differ.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't make it and be successful this year, it would be
difficult to go back to Europe,'' said Barrie, who signed a
free-agent contract with the Kings in July. ``You either go over
there and get fat and finish up your career or you get in shape,
come back here and resume your career.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrie, who once scored 116 points in the IHL, is getting some
long looks with his strong play during training camp, and the knee
injury that is expected to sideline another offensive-minded
center, Jason Blake, for at least another three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Barrie scored an unassisted goal Monday against the Ducks, his
second in three games, and he'll again center the second line with
Donald Audette and Glen Murray when the Kings play San Jose in an
exhibition game tonight in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   __ Norstrom, Taylor meet: In an effort to come to terms with
unsigned All-Star defenseman Mattias Norstrom, a restricted free
agent, Kings Senior Vice President/General Manager Dave Taylor had
lunch Monday with Norstrom in an effort to assure him that he's a
large part of the Kings plans.
</P>
<P>
   Norstrom, who earned $950,000 last season, wondered earlier this
week if the Kings respected his ability after his offer of a
one-year, $1.3 million deal down from his initial asking price of
three years, $1.7 million each was rejected by the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   He was seeking a three-year package at $1.7 million each. The
Kings are reportedly offering a three-year deal that averages just
over $1.2 million per year or a one-year, $1.045 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read (Norstrom's comments) and the first thing I told him
was we absolutely respect him as a player,'' Taylor said. ``We
value him as an important part of our club and view him as a second
defenseman.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are waiting to hear if rookie Finnish defenseman Jere
Karalahti, who was once arrested for heroin possession, will be
granted a visa.
</P>
<P>
   __ Last licks? The Kings were quick to brush aside Monday's
messy third-period free-for-alls, which left Anaheim's Teemu
Selanne and the Kings' Jason Podollan with stitches. Murray and
Mighty Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg also nearly came to blows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be different in the season because we won't be
able to take cheap penalties,'' Ian Laperriere said. ``We won't be
able to go crazy like we did.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who think otherwise, the teams play again Dec. 3 at
the Pond.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
