<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1065 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MRSBRADLEY-PROFILE-AR     09-22 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSBRADLEY-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE BRADLEY BANDWAGON, THE DOCTOR IS IN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ernestine Schlant grew up in the Bavarian city of
Passau, where the Jews had all disappeared by the time she was 7
and one did not speak of the forced labor camp down the road. Her
father was in the Luftwaffe _ although not, she says, in the Nazi
party _ at the same time that she was bringing tea to the wounded
German soldiers whose hospital had taken over her school.
</P>
<P>
   Now, like an angry retort half a century later, Dr. Schlant has
published ``The Language of Silence,'' a criticism of liberal
German writers like Guenter Grass and Heinrich Boell for what she
sees as their failure to come to terms with the Holocaust. It is,
of course, a personal text, too: ``I would not say that I feel
guilty,'' Dr. Schlant said Tuesday over coffee in midtown, ``but I
would say that I feel there is a legacy that is, well, a great
burden. This is my document, my attempt to really work it
through.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this is striking enough. But Dr. Schlant is also Mrs.
Bill Bradley, wife of the former senator and Knicks star who is
running for president. Even in the era of Hillary Rodham Clinton,
Dr. Schlant is an unusual political spouse. Probably she beat the
first lady at not baking cookies. But unlike Mrs. Clinton, Dr.
Schlant is unknown in political circles, and never moved to
Washington while Bradley was in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, The New Republic gave Dr. Schlant's book a
4,000-word review, calling it a ``vigorous, comprehensive and
troubling'' challenge to the conventional wisdom, without ever
mentioning who her husband is.
</P>
<P>
   But all that is changing. For the first time in her career as a
professor of German and comparative literature at Montclair State
University, Dr. Schlant has taken a leave to campaign full time for
her husband. ``The awesomeness of the office is such,'' she said,
``that I couldn't possibly say, `Well, that's for you, Bill, I have
other things to do.' I couldn't see how I could possibly live with
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly it is the right moment for her. At 64, she has written
five books, raised two daughters (one is from an earlier marriage)
and survived breast cancer and a 1992 mastectomy. She has the
spirit of someone who is living on extra time. ``Whenever I speak
with breast cancer survivors, we all agree that life after cancer
is better than it was before,'' she said. ``We know more where our
values are. It's much more streamlined.''
</P>
<P>
   So here she is, on a sodden Tuesday morning, parked in the lobby
of the Millennium Hotel in midtown Manhattan, en route to Fox News
and then to Boston, not at all unhappy. ``Let me tell you, it's
fun, it's really fun,'' Dr. Schlant said, of the campaign. ``It's
great. Maybe it's a little like teaching. I can speak on a subject
I know, and I can speak to my heart's content. The subject being
Bill, it's not a chore at all.''
</P>
<P>
   At this fresh date, Dr. Schlant is still a compelling
combination of intellectual sophistication and seeming
guilelessness, eager to talk about why she feels Grass falls short
of ``really doing justice to the Holocaust'' in ``The Tin Drum,''
then just as eager to answer questions about how she met Bradley.
(It's a good story: She was assigned by the New York film company
she was working for in 1970 to line up the Knicks star to interview
poet and sports fan Marianne Moore. She had never heard of him, or
the Knicks, even though she lived in Bradley's building, but
immediately found him ``adorable.'')
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, meanwhile, fell for a woman who, as she puts it,
-``hadn't been lassoed into the myth of Bill Bradley,'' and also
one, to judge from pictures at the time, who looked like a cerebral
Audrey Hepburn.
</P>
<P>
   Schlant first came to America in 1957, as a stewardess with Pan
Am, then went to Emory University in Atlanta, where her
undergraduate adviser, Walter Strauss, was the first of many Jews
she met who opened her eyes to what had really happened in Germany.
``He was like a midwife to my realization of the enormity of the
Holocaust,'' Dr. Schlant said. ``So I came to this tremendously
upsetting reality of the Holocaust, almost being held and comforted
by Jews here.''
</P>
<P>
   The subject would come up, ``almost like the second or third
sentence in a conversation,'' she said, as soon as a Jewish
acquaintance learned she had grown up in Germany. (She is now an
American citizen.) ``It would be almost like a bond,'' Dr. Schlant
said. ``Although we would be on totally different sides of the
fence, we would know immediately what we were speaking about.'' Dr.
Schlant added that she likes to think she would have written her
book if she had remained in Germany, ``but of course I don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Today she sees herself as just another supporter working for her
husband _ ``My value to the campaign, and my self-image, is that
I'm not trying to be a political wife'' _ who happens to know him
better than anyone else. Her cancer, she added, ``made both of us
discover depths in our relationship that we never knew were
there.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``We had a wonderful marriage before, but it was not
put through the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Schlant, who uses Ernestine Bradley on the campaign trail,
was about to say that her husband had always supported her career
and other such niceties. There was a time, for example, when
Bradley raised their daughter, then 10, in Washington, and Dr.
Schlant flew down for long weekends. But she was able to rescue
herself from political spouse-speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to use the word `support,''' she said, ``because
it's condescending.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
