<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNTRYWIDE-EARNINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTRYWIDE EXCEEDS ANALYSTS' HOPES AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY CHRIS SIEROTY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALABASAS _ Countrywide Credit Industries Inc., which has
enjoyed almost four years of record earnings, announced that second
quarter earnings once again exceeded Wall Street expectations,
leading one analyst to describe the company's results as ``pretty
impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Countrywide's better-than-expected earnings sent the company's
share price up $1.25, or 4.15 percent, Tuesday to $31.5625 per
share. However, the company's stock price remains nearly 40 percent
lower than its 52-week high of $51.4375 set in January.
</P>
<P>
   The residential finance company based in Calabasas, 28 miles
northwest of Los Angeles, reported unaudited net earnings for the
second quarter ended Aug. 31 were $106.5 million, a 12 percent
increase over earnings of $95.1 million for the same quarter in
1998. Diluted earnings per share for the second quarter were 91
cents, up from 81 cents for the second quarter of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected earnings of 88 cents a share, said Gary
Gordon, a managing director with Paine Webber in New York. Gordon
said he was impressed with the company's second quarter results,
but cautioned that increased price competition within the home loan
industry would make the next two quarters ``very challenging'' for
Countrywide.
</P>
<P>
   Angelo R. Mozilo, Countrywide's chairman and chief executive
officer, said in a statement that the company has produced record
results despite rising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Servicing earnings growth more than offset the decline in
production earnings which resulted from lower volume,'' Mozilo said
in the statement.
</P>
<P>
   The company said its loan service portfolio grew to $236 billion
with a weighted average coupon of 7.4 percent at Aug. 31 from $195
billion with a weighted average coupon of 7.7 percent at the end of
the second quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
