<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIGHTY DUCKS NOTEBOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The day after the Los Angeles Kings and
Anaheim Mighty Ducks combined for 149 penalty minutes in a 8-1 Los
Angeles victory, the Ducks admitted they were embarrassed and
hopefully a little wiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we (learned a lesson), said Anaheim coach Craig
Hartsburg after Tuesday's practice. ``You just had to look up at
the scoreboard ... we know we were embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a good thing (getting routed), but once in a while it
brings what's important back into focus.
</P>
<P>
   Aki Berg's check on Teemu Selanne seemed to get the bad bood
flowing, but Selanne, who picked up four stitches when his visor
cut his lip, said it appeared worse than it was and that ``I think
it was an accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Selanne, who said the play began when fell down after stepping
on a stick, even joked that Berg, as a fellow Finn, ``would be
scared to touch me.''
</P>
<P>
   But the way the Ducks played was no joke to Selanne, who said
the Anaheim players held a players-only meeting after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the worst we've skated all year, he said. ``They (the
Kings) were excited, it being the last game at the Forum, and we
were a step behind all night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was obviously embarrassing. We got frustrated and that's
why all the fights started.''
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Kariya out: &UR; !off! &LR;  Paul Kariya did not practice with the
team and said he remains on a day-to-day basis with his left-quad
injury.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim captain continues to work on strengthing his leg in
off-ice workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have gone on the ice before I had proper strength and when I
make a quick move I blow it out again,'' said Kariya. ``I just have
to get the strength back. The last couple of days it's a lot
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Kariya took part in several practices last week but said while
he could get away with practicing at less than full speed he was
not ready for game conditions.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!To AHL: &UR; !off! &LR;  In somewhat of a surprising move, the
Ducks assigned second-year forward Johan Davidsson to Cincinnati of
the Amrican Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   Davidsson was a regular much of last season, scoring 3 goals and
8 points in 64 games while filling mostly a checking role for
Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Winger Mike Leclerc's strong traing camp showing and the ability
of Pascal Trepanier to play both forward and defense might have
made Davidsson expendable for now.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks are carrying 28 players and will likely reduce their
roster to 22 or 23 by opening night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
