<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARCIA WINS 16TH AS GRIFFEY, RODRIGUEZ LEAD HR BARRAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It was Royals against royalty, Kansas City against the
crown prince of Caracas. The electoral process won.
</P>
<P>
   Stumping hard for AL Rookie of the Year honors, Freddy Garcia
swung a few more votes his way Tuesday night, the Mariners'
first-year pitcher turning in another persuasive performance. The
right-hander went five innings and posted his 16th victory in 24
decisions as the Mariners took a 13-3 decision before 34,179 fans
at Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have a rookie who comes around very often and wins
16 games,'' Mariners catcher Tom Lampkin said. ``He's putting his
two cents in.''
</P>
<P>
   While Garcia was busy adding to his season-long list of first
impressions, teammates Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex Rodriguez _ proven
superstars yet neither one a rookie of the year selectee _
continued to chase ancient history.
</P>
<P>
   Giving his club a 2-0 lead in the first, Griffey socked his 47th
homer, and 397th of his career. That left him alone at 32nd on the
all-time long-ball ladder, breaking a tie with Joe Carter. Griffey
also had a run-scoring single in the fourth, raising his RBI total
to 130.
</P>
<P>
   His slump a thing of the past, Rodriguez launched his 40th and
41st homers, making him the first AL shortstop to top the 40 mark
twice, and only the second big league shortstop to do so. Ernie
Banks pulled this feat five times for the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very proud of that accomplishment, particularly after
missing six weeks,'' Rodriguez said. ``It's special, no doubt about
it. But I wish I was doing it for a team in a pennant race.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Blowers and Lampkin also homered, while Edgar Martinez
collected four hits, the latter a season high and raising his
average to .346.
</P>
<P>
   The beneficiary of all this offense was Garcia, who wasn't his
usual efficient self against Kansas City. But that's what was
impressive _ he still got the job done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad we hit good tonight,'' Garcia said. ``I tried to make
good pitches, but my balls had no movement. I try to be too fine.
(I'll) take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Lampkin, ``There's times when Freddy pitched well and
hadn't gotten the win or the decision, so this was good for him.''
</P>
<P>
   With 16 victories, Garcia became the winningest Venezuelan
pitcher in the big leagues, surpassing countrymen Wilson Alvarez
and Omar Daal, both registering 15.
</P>
<P>
   With possibly two starts left, the Mariners' first-year player
has a chance to break the club record for rookie pitching victories
_ 17, now shared by Mark Langston (1984) and Dave Fleming (1992).
</P>
<P>
   Garcia had to gut this one out. He was working on just four days
rest, and it showed. He threw three wild pitches to tie a club
record. He walked four batters. He had no changeup. Yet he made the
big pitch whenever he needed it, escaping jams in the third, fourth
and fifth innings.
</P>
<P>
   He even needed four outs to get out of the first inning,
striking out his third batter, Carlos Beltran, but putting him on
with his first wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Larboring, Garcia finally gave way to reliever Frankie Rodriguez
after throwing 107 pitches through his five frames. Garcia
permitted seven hits, one to Beltran, probably his strongest
competition for the AL rookie honor.
</P>
<P>
   When asked for his input on the award, Mariners manager Lou
Piniella seemed torn between his pitcher and Beltran, a Royals
center fielder who went 3-for-5, 1-for-3 against Garcia, to raise
his average to .295.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid in Kansas City, how can you not look his way? He's a
heckuva outfielder,'' the Mariners manager said, listing Beltran's
stats, which include 22 homers and 104 RBIs. ``But you look
(Garcia's) way, too. Sixteen wins should make him rookie pitcher of
the year (sic). When you look at the young talent that's surfaced
around the league, it's as good as it's been in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Lampkin, ``Carlos Beltran is definitely showing why he has
a shot to be rookie of the year. But you don't have a rookie very
often who comes around and wins 16.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia said if he doesn't receive the award, his Kansas City
counterpart will.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beltran, he's so good,'' the pitcher said. ``He can do
everything. He's one of the superstars. We'll see what happens
after the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad campaign strategy for Garcia. Take the humble
approach. Set up the hitter. Praise the opponent. Then steal the
award from him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
