<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUSAK-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSAK OFF TO FAST START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ The three-game totals that Todd Husak has
put together this season fit nicely into the profile of a Stanford
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   He's completed 53 passes in 108 attempts for 784 yards with five
touchdowns and one interception. But, before you talk about the
individual passing numbers, Husak wants to discuss some other
reasons the Cardinal has generated 104 points in the past two
games.
</P>
<P>
   He would first like to talk about an offensive line that is
doing a better job of keeping his uniform clean and a running
attack that has been stimulated by the emergence of running back
Kerry Carter, a freshman from Canada, whose senior season never got
underway because of a teacher's strike. Or he'll tell you about a
defense which, at least in the last two games, has created
wonderful field position for the Stanford offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is working for us,'' said Husak, a 6-foot-3,
210-pound senior, who is a native of Long Beach and St. John Bosco
High graduate. ``When everything works, putting up 50 is a
possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   And when everything doesn't, then 69-17 becomes all too
possible. It was by that 69-17 margin that Stanford lost its opener
on a sweltering Sept. 4 at Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly cannot explain what happened,'' said Husak of the
miserable outing against the Longhorns. ``Going in, we were
confident. We thought we would give those guys a game and maybe
walk out with a victory.''
</P>
<P>
   After 30 minutes, the Longhorns led, 48-10, and after 60 minutes
the Stanford players were trying to figure out what went wrong in
the school's most lopsided defeat since dropping a 67-0 decision to
Cal in 1918.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a team, we decided `Hey this season is not like last
season','' Husak said of the 3-8 squad in 1998. ``This team is a
lot different than last year's team. Nothing against those
(seniors), but this year's seniors are playing with a sense of
urgency.''
</P>
<P>
   The urgency turned into two big games for Husak in a 54-17
victory over Washington State and a 50-22 triumph at Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Todd has really sharpened up game and taken it to the next
level,'' Cardinal coach Tyrone Willingham said. `` He's been
excellent at the physical job of throwing the football and also the
mental demands of getting the team in the right offense at the
right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Doing that against Washington State does little to change public
opinion of the Cardinal, but decisively beating an Arizona that
began the season ranked in the national top five should open some
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some people will just think Arizona was overated,''
said Husak, who was 21 of 35 for 364 yards against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Another chance to prove they are a good team will come Saturday
when the Cardinal welcomes defending Pac-10 champion UCLA to Palo
Alto.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Husak threw for 419 yards and a touchdown in a 28-24
loss to the Bruins at the Rose Bowl. It was the third best passing
yardage total in Stanford history, but Husak and his teammates will
remember the day for the disappointment of seeing receiver Jeff
Allen being stripped by UCLA defensive back Marques Anderson a yard
short of what could have been the winning touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Close doesn't count,'' said Husak, who holds the school's top
single-game with his 450 compiled in a loss to Oregon State. ``You
can pick a couple of (tough losses) last year. Arizona State was a
heartbreaker. UCLA was a heartbreaker. But, yeah, maybe (the story
of) last season can be wrapped up in one play.''
</P>
<P>
   Husak hopes it will be nine games which would include a bowl
game to wrap up a Stanford career that began in relative anonymity.
His only year as a full-time starter at St. John Bosco was as a
senior and Stanford was pretty much his lone option.
</P>
<P>
   Which probably made it easier to step into a Stanford
quarterback tradition which includes All-Americans John Elway,
Frankie Albert, Guy Benjamin, Mike Boryla, John Brodie and 1970
Heisman Trophy winner Jim Plunkett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel any pressure from it because nobody expected
much from me,'' Husak said. ``It was more like `You're no John
Elway'.''
</P>
<P>
   When he's done, though, Husak's name will be prominent in the
school's record book.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's clearly a guy that as you watch him, he just gets better
and better,'' Arizona coach Dick Tomey said.
</P>
<P>
   Husak is currently seventh on the Stanford career passing yards
list and is eighth in total offense. The 3,092 he compiled last
year on 233 completions in 447 attempts marked only the third time
in school history that a quarterback has eclipsed the 3,000-yard
mark.
</P>
<P>
   But those numbers aren't the ones that are important right now.
He wants to do what Chad Hutchinson did in 1996, which is lead the
team to a bowl game.
</P>
<P>
   And, there something about the last two games that has Husak
believing the Cardinal are going to be busy for the holidays for
the first time since beating Michigan State, 38-0, in the 1996 Sun
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we are real similiar mentally to my freshman year
when we started 2-5 and won our last five games,'' Husak said.
``Those guys just believed we were going to win and we did. I think
that's how this team is handling themselves now. We just need to
keep that going.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
