<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IBSEN IN CONTROL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif.  &UR; _ &LR;  Zak Ibsen has gone from the low man on the
depth chart to a fixture in the Los Angeles Galaxy's starting
lineup. All it took was for Ibsen to gain control of himself.
</P>
<P>
   Ibsen, 27, has played in 21 of 27 games this season and had
started five straight before a recent case of the flu forced him
back to the bench. He returned to action last week against Colorado
in a substitute role.
</P>
<P>
   Ibsen has learned to appreciate his time in the starting lineup,
and he hopes to see more action when the Galaxy plays host to rival
Washington D.C. United Saturday at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Reared as a soccer prodigy, Ibsen received wide acclaim as a
youngster, playing for several U.S. national youth teams. But he
nearly self-destructed before his career really began.
</P>
<P>
   Ibsen left Dallas after the 1996 inaugural Major League Soccer
season to play beach soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dallas wanted us to get in an off-season program, but I
thought I could make more money playing beach soccer,'' he said.
``That was a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Ibsen missed the entire 1997 season and had to convince Chicago
coach Bob Bradley his commitment was genuine again. Bradley
acquired Ibsen from Dallas, figuring he had nothing to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Ibsen made the most of his opportunity as a substitute, helping
the Fire defeat the Galaxy in the MLS playoffs before capturing the
MLS Cup and U.S. Cup titles in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ibsen wasn't happy with his surroundings. He wanted to
return to Southern California with his wife and finish his degree
at UCLA, where from 1990-94 he spent time both as one of coach Sigi
Schmid's favorite and least favorite players.
</P>
<P>
   In the offseason, Ibsen was traded to the Galaxy for nothing
more than a second-round college draft pick in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm forever in debt to Bob Bradley for trading me to L.A. for
such a low value,'' said Ibsen. ``I know I wasn't a need for
Octavio (Zambrano, former Galaxy coach). I came to Octavio and said
`I want to be here,' and he gave up as little as he could to get
me.''
</P>
<P>
   When Zambrano was fired in favor of Schmid, Ibsen wasn't sure
what to expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sigi and I definitely butted heads when I was at UCLA,'' said
Ibsen. ``It took a long time for us to sort of understand each
other, but we finally arrived at that point.''
</P>
<P>
   Ibsen blames himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it was me being 18,'' he said. ``I was on the
National team and thought I was pretty hot stuff. But Sigi's a
great coach. All you have to do is see how many great players came
through UCLA during his tenure.''
</P>
<P>
   Ibsen has started in place of Ezra Hendrickson at right back and
Roy Myers on occasions. He has made the most his opportunities.
Ibsen scored two goals in a 4-2 win over New York/New Jersey and
has helped the defense remain solid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat quietly and patiently waiting my turn,'' said Ibsen.
``It seemed like (Schmid) went through just about everybody on the
team before he came to me. Everyone has their own motivation
factor. For me, I've accepted a lesser role than I thought I was
capable of for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat the bench the whole year in Chicago and most of this
season. Personally, I felt sitting on the bench and having a
back-seat role wasn't going to help this team win. I don't need to
start every game, but there's no reason judging by how I've played
that I can't help this team win. I'm all about winning
championships and will do whatever it takes. If we don't win, then
I will complain.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmid has not been disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zak is an experienced player and he's been part of a
championship team,'' said Schmid. ``I felt confident that when it
was his time to come in he would do well. With Zak, I'm not sure if
he'll start or keep coming off the bench, but he's proven to me how
valuable he is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
