r a BC-FORBES-CALIFORNIA-SFC     09-22 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBES-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP HOPEFUL FORBES TOUTS HIMSELF AS CONSERVATIVES' ALTERNATIVE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     and LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Striving to establish himself as the genuine GOP
conservative in the 2000 presidential race, Steve Forbes said
Tuesday that he has formally challenged GOP front-runner George W.
Bush to a series of debates but that Bush has failed to respond to
the invitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm talking about several hours each. (I'll debate) anywhere
he wants,'' said Forbes on board his high-tech Victory Express I
bus to Sacramento at the start of a weeklong California tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``That way, not only can voters see what you stand for, but get
a feel for whether you have the backbone, the compass, the
determination to make positive things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Forbes campaign, sensing opportunity with the possible
defection of Pat Buchanan from the GOP, has become increasingly
vocal in its suggestions that the Texas governor has failed to
outline his policy on key issues like abortion, taxes and
immigration.
</P>
<P>
   Bush ``needs to get out and debate the issues, and let the
members of the party see where he stands,'' said John Herrington,
the former Secretary of Energy under Ronald Reagan and now state
chair of the Forbes campaign. ``He can't keep campaigning from an
ivory tower.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's campaign was quick to respond to those charges
Tuesday _ and the suggestion that the Texas governor is running
away from issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush looks forward to debating about all the issues
next year, when people are paying attention,'' said the governor's
spokeswoman, Mindy Tucker, noting that Bush has agreed to attend a
January 15 debate in Iowa. She said that Forbes ``can continue to
watch as the governor lays out his policy initiatives this fall.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, she said, he will outline his plans ``to make sure
we have a strong national defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, Forbes _ facing Bush's strong lead in the polls
and his prodigious fund-raising strength _ is taking off the
gloves. He appeared feisty and relaxed Tuesday as he swung his way
across the Bay Area toward the Central Valley.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke in Modesto, Calif., last night at a barbecue attended
by more 1,000 supporters. He will continue on to Fresno Wednesday
and Southern California tomorrow. Forbes will also deliver the
keynote address this weekend at the state Republican convention in
Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Asked in a Chronicle interview how his policies relate to those
of Bush, Forbes said, ``Just compare: I put a tax proposal on the
table. ... I put a real Social Security proposal on the table ...
not some vague, throwaway line (in speeches).''
</P>
<P>
   ``On education: He wants a bigger role for the federal
government,'' said Forbes. ``Mine is rooted in parents and
communities and schools. I trust parents, not politicians, on
education.''
</P>
<P>
   With six months to go before the March 2000 primary and still in
single digits in the polls, Forbes is convinced that conservative
Republicans uncomfortable with Bush's juggernaut _ and dismayed by
Buchanan's possible defection from the GOP _ will find a home with
him.
</P>
<P>
   The Forbes campaign notes that there have already been some
high-profile defections from other campaigns recently.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Charles Jarvis resigned his post as national campaign
chair for GOP conservative presidential hopeful Gary Bauer, calling
Forbes the best chance for conservatives to elect a president in
the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, two key South Carolina Buchanan supporters jumped to
Forbes' ship.
</P>
<P>
   And California GOP Assemblyman Thomas ``Rico'' Oller of San
Andreas announced he was ``the crack in the wall'' _ the first
state legislator the back Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve is emerging as the responsible conservative alternative
to George Bush,'' said Steve Merksamer, a veteran GOP strategist
and Forbes campaign adviser. ``He's developing a lot of momentum in
the early primary states and here in California. He's a serious
candidate for serious conservatives.'`
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's possible move to the Reform Party ``underscores the
need for this party to have an inspired, principled, genuine
message,'' Forbes said. ``We had one in the '80s, and we won. The
last two elections we didn't, and we lost. No message, no
victory.''
</P>
<P>
   But Forbes, a millionaire businessman, also has the luxury of
money for his latest California push. That was evident Tuesday at
the crack of dawn when his convoy, two super-equipped high-tech
buses dubbed Victory Express I and II, took off from Oakland to the
blaring sounds of Willie Nelson's ``On the Road Again.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also ample evidence of Forbes' tech-savvy interest in
the politics of the Internet. In what may be the most
technologically advanced presidential campaign on the road, a
campaign staff photographer documents each stop and immediately
downloads photos onto the candidate's Web site,
 &UR; www.forbes2000.com.  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 0307EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
