<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 03:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1096 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     09-22 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 IS `SANDWICH GANG' FULL OF BOLOGNA?  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco's No. 1 problem is the homeless,
according to a Chronicle poll. And if you think it's a problem to
you, imagine what a bummer it is to the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   If you polled them, the three top problems would probably be
homelessness, foodlessness and hopelessness. Muni would be well
down the list.
</P>
<P>
   The homeful, meanwhile, are sharply divided among those who
believe we're not helping the homeless enough and those who believe
we're helping too much.
</P>
<P>
   I know this after a recent column about a group of Marin County
high school students who come to the city every Saturday and hand
out 500 sandwiches to the homeless. The SFPD shut down the
operation two Saturdays ago. After much media attention, the P.D.
helped the kids get back into business.
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief Fred Lau helped speed the students through the
permits jungle, because while it's technically not a crime to feed
the homeless, it does require more permits than opening a brothel
theme park.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people supported the students. If you've ever been a
parent and you caught your son or daughter handing out sandwiches
to poor people, your first thought was probably not:
 &UR; Oh, Lord, where have I gone wrong?  &LR; But a lot of readers said to
tell those bleeding-heart rich kids to take a ferry-boatload of the
S.F. homeless back to Marin County.
</P>
<P>
   Many folks said the sandwich gang was making the homeless
problem worse by making the city more attractive to the
down-and-out. And that's a debate-worthy point: that the better you
treat homeless people, the more of them there will be.
</P>
<P>
   There's no easy answer, but here's a note sent by Travis Brooks,
a former San Franciscan who now lives in New Hampshire:
</P>
<P>
   ``I was mugged in San Francisco. Eleven plates and 44 screws
later, I found myself with little sense of who I was or what I
could do. I lived in a hotel in the Tenderloin for I guess four
months, having to check my driver's license to tell someone my
name. ...
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of OSTLER22 (66341 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``What I remember most about being lost, when I couldn't even
remember my own name, are two things: One, the absolute fear of not
knowing who I was. Two, the beauty of the kindness of strangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Picture not knowing who you are or what you are worth, not
knowing if you are something at all, and being handed a couple of
sandwiches by someone who thinks you mean something.''
</P>
<P>
   TO BE HONEST with you, Doug Wilkins might be on to a new trend.
Which is a lot better than being on to an old trend.
</P>
<P>
   He noticed it first on sports radio station KNBR. The
announcers, Doug says, tend to begin any given statement with ``To
be honest with you,'' or ``I'll be honest with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug asks, ``Does this reflect an exciting new trend to sporadic
honesty in sports gab?''
</P>
<P>
   I hope not, but Doug also noticed the honesty lead-in popping up
in other media, and in real life.
</P>
<P>
   To be honest with you, Doug, I think radio guys and others
simply got sick of the previous trend _ starting every statement
with ``I mean.''
</P>
<P>
   I mean, like, y'know?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (I hear you. _ Editor) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HIS CALCULATOR working overtime, Jim Corrigan came up with a
stat. The SFFD released its biannual overtime report to the Board
of Supes two weeks ago, and the report listed $10,076,000 in
overtime for fiscal year 1998-99. Jim did the math and says each
hour in San Francisco, city firefighters earn $1,153 in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ADD SANDWICHES: The cop crackdown on the Marin Sandwich Gang,
several readers point out, was merely to protect the homeless
people from the germy kids.
</P>
<P>
   Health standards in food-handling should protect the homeless
too, they point out. Joseph F. Melanson notes, ``San Francisco has
one of the best health departments of any major city.''
</P>
<P>
   And one of the slowest. It took 'em seven years to crack down on
this particular health menace.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, why isn't the Health Dept. putting padlocks on
Dumpsters?
</P>
<P>
   CUTE COMMERCIAL on TV for AT&AMP;T directory assistance: A woman
phones 00 and tells the perky operator she's looking for a cab
driver named ``Pizzaria.''
</P>
<P>
   The operator checks her computer and deduces that the cabbie is
probably Pete Zorria.
</P>
<P>
   This disturbs alert reader Cary Hammer, because as the perky
operator locates Pete Zorria in her computer, there is a quick shot
of the operator's computer screen, which seems to contain an
extensive intelligence dossier on old Pete, including a large
photo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is one supposed to assume,'' Hammer wonders, ``that this is to
aid operators faced with calls such as, `I met a girl at a party
last night and I was too drunk to remember her name, but she was
real pretty with dark hair kind of up in a bun. Can you find her,
please?'
</P>
<P>
   ``When I had my phone installed, I don't remember a photo shoot,
but perhaps there is a camera in the phone itself. Does the Freedom
of Information Act allow me to get my AT&AMP;T file and see what the
phone company thinks of me?''
</P>
<P>
   I'll save you the time, Cary. They don't like you anymore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
