<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 03:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1098 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-TEARS-FOR-RAISA-425&AMP;a     09-22 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEARS-FOR-RAISA-425&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY RUSSIANS WILL SHED TEARS OVER RAISA GORBACHEV  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This poignant ``separate buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS TIMELY
ARTICLE OFFERS A 125-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 425. TOTAL UNCUT IS 900
WORDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By HELEN WOMACK  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russians would be the first to admit their strange
national propensity for envying others their success, yet pitying
them in misfortune. That was how they treated Raisa Gorbachev, who
died of leukemia in a German hospital Monday.
</P>
<P>
   When she was the first Soviet President's glittering First Lady,
they detested her. When she fell ill, Russians gave her their
hearts.
</P>
<P>
   The news that she had succumbed to an infection before she could
receive a transplant of bone marrow from her sister was the first
item on the television news here Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raisa Maximovna suffered very much in the past few weeks but
her death was peaceful,'' NTV's correspondent in Germany assured
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Mikhail Gorbachev, who helped to end the Cold War with his
policies of perestroika (restructuring) and glasnost (openness),
would bring his wife home to be buried in Moscow's Novodevichy
cemetery, he said. President Boris Yeltsin had sent his condolences
and promised a charter plane to fly the body to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Raisa Gorbachev's last weeks, not only did her
husband keep a vigil at the Muenster Clinic that tried to save her
but also the whole of Russia followed her saga, as if she were a
soap opera star.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of ordinary Russians sent letters, recipes for herbal
medicines and even offers of money to the couple they once reviled.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just the way we are,'' said Olga Podolskaya, a
secretary. ``We used to find Raisa extremely irritating. But at the
end, we felt sorry for her and even more sorry for him, the loyal
and loving husband, constantly at her bedside.''
</P>
<P>
   Raisa Gorbachev herself knew how the Russian public felt about
her. In an interview for the TV show ``Hero With His Tie Off,''
recorded when she was well, she recounted how hard it had been to
be the first ever First Lady in a society that hid its political
wives.
</P>
<P>
   Russians almost never saw Viktoria, wife of the late Communist
leader, Leonid Brezhnev, and as for one of his successor's, Yuri
Andropov, they were not sure whether he had a wife at all.
</P>
<P>
   Raisa broke a taboo by appearing in public with her husband. For
him, admitting that he had a partner and that she played an
important role in his life was a personal act of glasnost, an
extension of his policy of openness.
</P>
<P>
   Like all pioneers, the Gorbachevs paid for being ahead of their
time. Raisa was a clever, educated woman, a species that many
Russians still have trouble in accepting. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (125-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 425) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She was born Raisa Maximovna Titorenko in the Siberian region of
Altai in 1932. Her father, Maxim Titorenko, had gone out to Siberia
to help build the railways. The young Raisa was bright enough to go
all the way from this provincial backwater to Moscow State
University (MGU), where she studied philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   There she met Mikhail, a promising law student, whom she married
in 1953. When he returned to his native Stavropol district in
southern Russia to become a local Communist Party boss, she joined
him and took up a career in teaching.
</P>
<P>
   When he was promoted to a party job in Moscow, in charge of
Soviet agriculture, she did research at her old philosophy faculty
at MGU. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Her public appearances began soon after her husband became
Kremlin leader in 1985. Not only did she take on the chairmanship
of the Soviet Culture Fund but she also joined Gorbachev on his
domestic outings to meet the people and his numerous trips to
foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   She always wore an elegant dress or suit and a tasteful amount
of jewelry. That was her mistake. Russians were green with envy
because she had a measure of sophistication.
</P>
<P>
   And not only Russians. It was said that Nancy Reagan could not
abide her either because on one occasion she showed her knowledge
of art while guiding the American First Lady around Moscow's famous
Tretyakov Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Russians would have preferred Raisa Gorbachev to be
more homely. Naina Yeltsina, wife of President Yeltsin, has
cultivated an image of the little woman in the kitchen, probably
because of all the bile directed at Raisa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must admit I hated her too,'' said Ms. Podolskaya. ``I
remember once seeing her following Gorbachev on some agricultural
or industrial visit. She was trotting along behind him in
high-heeled shoes and I thought `why doesn't she just stay at
home?'
</P>
<P>
   ``In retrospect, I realize that I was jealous because she had
more dresses than the average Russian woman. She was trying to be a
real First Lady. But I think she was badly advised. Someone should
have told her to wear the same outfit more than once.''
</P>
<P>
   Once her husband was out of power, Raisa avoided the limelight.
In 1996, she sold the extensive wardrobe that had attracted so much
criticism.
</P>
<P>
   She devoted her time to fund-raising for cancer care and
research. Before she knew she had leukemia herself, she was helping
other victims.
</P>
<P>
   That was why Russians came to love her and why many will shed
tears when Raisa flies home for the last time. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this timely, introspective article from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please
call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
