<HEADLINE>
A CAPSULATED HISTORY OF EAST TIMOR  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This brief 275-word ``separate buy'' backgrounder is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By RICHARD LLOYD PARRY  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why is there a little bit of East Timor surrounded by West
Timor?
</P>
<P>
   The small triangle of land, folded into the north coast of
Indonesian West Timor, is the enclave of Oecussi, and its continued
existence as part of East Timor is the result of a historical
accident.
</P>
<P>
   When Portuguese and Dutch traders first visited the island of
Timor in the early sixteenth century, they had separate spheres of
influence. The situation became even more complicated with the rise
of the Topasses, a class of mixed blood Portuguese-Timorese who
seized control of much of the island, often at the expense of the
Portuguese themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In 1701, a governor newly arrived from Lisbon was forced by the
Topasses to relocate his capital to the port of Lifau, which later
became known as Oecussi. When the two European power formally
partitioned the island between them in the 19th century, it
remained part of the Portuguese colony.
</P>
<P>
   Oecussi has always been the part of East Timor most susceptible
to the influence of the West.
</P>
<P>
   During the period of Indonesian infiltration leading up to the
invasion of 1975, it quickly came under the control of Jakarta.
Throughout the 24-year war, the guerrilla army Falintil had
virtually no presence there.
</P>
<P>
   Many suspect that the recent violence and ethnic cleansing
inflicted on Timor is an attempt to justify the partitioning off of
some of the East's provinces. If this turns out to be the case,
then Oecussi _ surrounded by Indonesia and with no independent land
route to Dili will be especially vulnerable. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this helpful 275-word article from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please
call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
