<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1303 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA23-COX     09-22 1377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LIFE IN AMERICA: High school football is community
 &HT;    (Eds: This another story in a series of reports on life in
small-town America _ the values, the stories and the characters _
at the end of the millennium. Photos and a sig/locator map are
available.)
 &HT;    By Paul Reines
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ David Eldridge never thought of high school
football as a healer.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanon High School football parent, however, had his eyes
opened last season when he said last year's state champions
transformed a town divided over a school levy and other matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It brought the community together. It gave us something to
rally around. People put their differences aside and the school is
better for it,'' Eldridge said. ``If the football team is down,
there's not that aura of cooperation amongst everybody.'' He said
football lets people cast aside prejudices rooted in educational or
financial differences. Respect becomes performance- and
effort-based.
</P>
<P>
   Ned Drees could have told Eldridge all about the power of high
school football.
</P>
<P>
   Drees figures he's watched more than 400 Covington Buccaneers
football games, home and away, since the team's inception in 1947.
Drees even schedules his annual departure for winter in Florida for
after the last regular-season game in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not an expert on football,'' said Drees, 84, a Covington
mayor in the 1950s. ``I just enjoy the excitement, the thrill of
watching the boys. I'd almost feel bad if I didn't go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right from the beginning,'' he said, noting the team became a
winner in its second season, ``that was the thing to do, to go to
the football game.''
</P>
<P>
   High school football is an institution with a devout following
in small towns such as Covington. It means more than wins and
losses.
</P>
<P>
   In many places, the game _ usually on a Friday night _ is a glue
that unites a community, allowing folks to catch up on each other's
lives and savor the emotional rush that comes with screaming lungs
out in a common cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friday nights, the town might as well roll up the streets
because everyone's at the football game,'' said Maggie Amburgey,
owner of the Country Lace store in Covington.
</P>
<P>
   With the likely exception of Dayton, where basketball generally
garners the most support, football has reigned as the No. 1 sport
in rural Ohio. Down periods don't last long for powerhouses such as
Troy, Piqua, Kettering Fairmont and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning has a lot to do with it,'' said Jim Siewe, an
insurance salesman and Kettering Fairmont booster. ``Unfortunately,
but it does.''
</P>
<P>
   Academics have studied the phenomenon of the loyalty to favorite
teams and discovered being a fan boosts people's self-esteem and
self-confidence, their sense of belonging and closeness to
neighbors, and overall happiness, said Charles Kimble, a University
of Dayton psychology professor.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Wann, a psychology professor at Murray State University
in Kentucky, said the placement of games on a select number of
Friday nights adds to people's excitement about high school
football. ``You've worked your way through the work week. You can
think about those people saying, 'It's Wednesday. Only two more
days.'''
</P>
<P>
   People also revel in ``euphoric stress,'' a term psychologists
use to describe a nervousness that people welcome _ for example, as
sports fans or roller-coaster riders, Wann said. ``It helps them
feel invigorated. They seek out that energy.'' Doug McIntosh,
president of Carlisle High School's boosters, said the stands are
packed _ largely with older adults who don't have a kid in the
school system _ every game, no matter the team's record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's just excited about football,'' he said. ``It
doesn't matter if we're 0-10 or 1-10 or 8-2. The turnout's still
there. Everybody still shows up.''
</P>
<P>
   Businesses chip in to help teams pay for their needs. Merchants
let parents display pictures of local players in their storefront
windows.
</P>
<P>
   Rituals abound: Residents paint their town's mascot in
driveways. There are bonfires and pep rallies. In some places on
Saturday mornings, regulars in coffee shops critique performances
of the evening before. ``Saturday-morning quarterbacking,'' Drees
called it.
</P>
<P>
   Walt McCutchan, a Lebanon parent, agreed. ``They'll talk about
it if you lose. They'll get you if you lose too.''
</P>
<P>
   Small towns most seem to demonstrate intimate involvement with
their teen athletes because parents typically know dozens if not
all of their kids' peers who are either in pads, cheerleading or in
band.
</P>
<P>
   Said Siewe, of the more densely populated Kettering, ``I
wouldn't say it's as rabid (here) as you might find in the smaller
towns, where everybody goes to the game, wouldn't think of doing
anything else on a Friday night.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps reinforcing that small-town fan base is the tendency of
former players to remain town residents after high school
graduation or to return shortly into manhood to live where they
grew up. Men, many of whom have gained a few pounds since their own
glory days between the hash marks, thrill in seeing a son or
grandson, in peak physical condition, let an opposing ballcarrier
have it.Football is also valued, some said, for what it teaches
kids: discipline, responsibility and cooperation. It's also about
extreme physical exertion _ both in training and in the contest _
just like the prevailing farming work ethic in a predominantly
rural county.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids do this because they love the game. It's not for money,''
said Ed Lowther, 60, a retired counselor who lives in West Milton.
``There are a lot of people who would rather watch the high school
team than watch the Cleveland Browns if they were playing 10 miles
away. It's real football. It's not professional football, where
people get paid millions of dollars and are whiners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real and it's local.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Troy High School senior Joanna Lepore, ``Football is
religion around here. As soon as football season comes, the whole
town goes wild.'' Troy's 10,000-seat stadium, extraordinarily large
for a city of 21,000, plays a big part in that, according to Mayor
Pete Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   The stands include everyone from rabid fans to locals barely
moved by a clutch interception or circus reception, as high school
football affords residents chances to see each other on a regular
basis. Five Friday nights each fall serve as unofficial high school
and other reunions. The predictability of who attends goes a step
further: fans tend to sit in the same place every game.
</P>
<P>
   Residents' gushing of praise for high school football is not
universal.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Moore, who lives in Troy but grew up and works in Piqua,
thinks the demand for victories in those two towns is a mixed
blessing. She laments that less-skilled players don't get in games
often. Some kids don't get rewarded for their participation, she
said. ``I'm not against sports,'' the 54-year-old woman said. ``I
know in Troy, they don't ever want to lose a game. I'm sure
academics suffers. I think sportsmanship suffers. The kids don't
know how to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Lepore, ``There's a whole attitude toward football players
that they're set apart'' out in the community. But at school, she
said, the players don't get special treatment from students and
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   In tiny Bradford, football is the essential source of civic
pride, some said. With some 300 students in the seventh- to
12th-grade school, residents are proud when their teams hold their
ground against the bigger schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you only have half the amount of kids going out for a team
as Covington, if they do decent, it's saying something,'' said Rod
Kimmel, 32, who played football for Covington now lives in
Bradford.
</P>
<P>
   Communities don't need a long-standing football tradition to
feel an affinity for the game, according to Erin Mitchell, 20, of
Pleasant Hill. Students in the Newton school district, lacking a
football program, head for West Milton on Friday nights, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you lose, they don't care. They just want to see
someone play football.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Reines writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 1056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1304 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA23-COX     09-22 1377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LIFE IN AMERICA: High school football is community
