</P>
<P>
   Small towns most seem to demonstrate intimate involvement with
their teen athletes because parents typically know dozens if not
all of their kids' peers who are either in pads, cheerleading or in
band.
</P>
<P>
   Said Siewe, of the more densely populated Kettering, ``I
wouldn't say it's as rabid (here) as you might find in the smaller
towns, where everybody goes to the game, wouldn't think of doing
anything else on a Friday night.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps reinforcing that small-town fan base is the tendency of
former players to remain town residents after high school
graduation or to return shortly into manhood to live where they
grew up. Men, many of whom have gained a few pounds since their own
glory days between the hash marks, thrill in seeing a son or
grandson, in peak physical condition, let an opposing ballcarrier
have it.Football is also valued, some said, for what it teaches
kids: discipline, responsibility and cooperation. It's also about
extreme physical exertion _ both in training and in the contest _
just like the prevailing farming work ethic in a predominantly
rural county.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids do this because they love the game. It's not for money,''
said Ed Lowther, 60, a retired counselor who lives in West Milton.
``There are a lot of people who would rather watch the high school
team than watch the Cleveland Browns if they were playing 10 miles
away. It's real football. It's not professional football, where
people get paid millions of dollars and are whiners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real and it's local.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Troy High School senior Joanna Lepore, ``Football is
religion around here. As soon as football season comes, the whole
town goes wild.'' Troy's 10,000-seat stadium, extraordinarily large
for a city of 21,000, plays a big part in that, according to Mayor
Pete Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   The stands include everyone from rabid fans to locals barely
moved by a clutch interception or circus reception, as high school
football affords residents chances to see each other on a regular
basis. Five Friday nights each fall serve as unofficial high school
and other reunions. The predictability of who attends goes a step
further: fans tend to sit in the same place every game.
</P>
<P>
   Residents' gushing of praise for high school football is not
universal.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Moore, who lives in Troy but grew up and works in Piqua,
thinks the demand for victories in those two towns is a mixed
blessing. She laments that less-skilled players don't get in games
often. Some kids don't get rewarded for their participation, she
said. ``I'm not against sports,'' the 54-year-old woman said. ``I
know in Troy, they don't ever want to lose a game. I'm sure
academics suffers. I think sportsmanship suffers. The kids don't
know how to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Lepore, ``There's a whole attitude toward football players
that they're set apart'' out in the community. But at school, she
said, the players don't get special treatment from students and
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   In tiny Bradford, football is the essential source of civic
pride, some said. With some 300 students in the seventh- to
12th-grade school, residents are proud when their teams hold their
ground against the bigger schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you only have half the amount of kids going out for a team
as Covington, if they do decent, it's saying something,'' said Rod
Kimmel, 32, who played football for Covington now lives in
Bradford.
</P>
<P>
   Communities don't need a long-standing football tradition to
feel an affinity for the game, according to Erin Mitchell, 20, of
Pleasant Hill. Students in the Newton school district, lacking a
football program, head for West Milton on Friday nights, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you lose, they don't care. They just want to see
someone play football.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Reines writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
