A1305 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-CERABINO-COLUMN23-COX     09-22 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CERABINO-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    There oughta be a law, but not for Max and Mollie
 &HT;    (EDS: CQ Richerd.)
 &HT;    By Frank Cerabino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When Max Gordon and his bride-to-be,
Mollie Levy, got their marriage license in Delray Beach last week,
things weren't as simple as they imagined.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clerk handed us a book to read,'' Mollie remembered.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, I said, 'What's the book about?' and she said,
'Parenting.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Parenting?'' Mollie said. ``We don't need to read the book, we
can write it.''
</P>
<P>
   Max Gordon is 90. Mollie Levy is 82. And between them they have
six children, 14 grandchildren and 17 great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   But in Florida, their union is just another potential bad
marriage, a marriage that needs safeguarding by the Marriage
Preparation and Preservation Act of 1998, a law spawned by a desire
to protect children from the effects of bad marriages.
</P>
<P>
   So, instead of being handed a license, Max and Mollie got a book
to read. They sat down with the Family Law Handbook to read about
the legal ramifications of marriage. Mollie had to read to Max
because of his cataracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just skimmed it,'' Mollie said. ``There was stuff about
child custody, and about how you should treat children if you have
them. The only reason I read it was because I thought we might get
tested on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then they got back in line for the clerk, and got their next
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   The license would cost them $88.50, unless they volunteered to
take a four-hour premarital course, which would give them a $32.50
discount on the cost of the license.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you picture us sitting there with a bunch of 19 and 20
years olds trying to learn about marriage?'' Mollie said.
</P>
<P>
   Max and Mollie, who both outlived their first spouses after long
marriages, opted to skip the course and pay for the more expensive
license.
</P>
<P>
   No senior citizen discount this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day he reminds me about that $88 license,'' Mollie said.
</P>
<P>
   But Max isn't complaining too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time I make an honest woman out of her,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Max and Mollie have been living together in her condominium in
suburban Delray Beach for the past year. They had met when they
both lived in an independent living facility, and Max used to walk
by her door, whistling, ``Molly and me, and baby makes three.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time he saw me in a dress he said, 'Why do wear
slacks when you have such great gams?''' she remembered.
</P>
<P>
   While hospitalized last month with an angina attack, Max floored
his 65-year-old son, Norton, by asking his permission to get
married again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, 'Whatever you do is fine with me,''' the son said.
``I'm glad my father's getting married _ I missed his first one.''
</P>
<P>
   When Mollie broke the news to her 48-year-old son, he was happy
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, 'Mom, you've got a better sex life than me,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Max, who was married for 62 years the first time, said he's
looking forward to his new marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take what comes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, it's too bad Max and Mollie aren't taking the
premarital training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had anybody over 50 years old,'' said Richerd
Whittemore, a licensed clinical social worker in West Palm Beach
who teaches the course. ``It's not such a bad thing to do. There's
a lot of problem solving and communications skills we talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   Another course instructor, Beth Cutler, a mental health
counselor from Boca Raton, said the older couple would be able to
both learn and help others in the class.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd have a blast with them,'' she said. ``They'd have an
insight on life that people who are 30 years old don't have.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Rossin (D-West Palm Beach), the state legislator who
sponsored the law creating the premarital classes, said he didn't
have newlyweds like Max and Mollie in mind when he sought to
protect young children from bad marriages.
</P>
<P>
   ``But anybody could learn from the class,'' Rossin said.
``They'd meet younger people, and they'd probably have a ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Max and Mollie said they've got enough excitement in their lives
right now. They just got a bigger dining room table to accommodate
feeding a suddenly larger extended family. There's an October
wedding to plan, and a honeymoon cruise a couple months later.
</P>
<P>
   And besides, they're not anticipating any marital problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have we had an argument yet?'' Mollie asked.
</P>
<P>
   Max, hard of hearing, sat in his recliner and smiled without
realizing his talkative fiancee was speaking to him.
</P>
<P>
   A perfect couple.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Cerabino writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
