<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1307 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-KELSO-COLUMN23-COX     09-22 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Let's get one thing straight about this flap over
what kind of woman gets to enter the Miss America Pageant.
</P>
<P>
   Guys don't care about what kind of woman gets to enter the Miss
America Pageant, because guys don't want to watch the Miss America
Pageant to start with.
</P>
<P>
   Guys would rather be watching football on the tube than watching
the Miss America pageant. Guys would rather be listening to John
Madden making grunting noises than watching the Miss America
Pageant.
</P>
<P>
   Whether previously pregnant or formerly married women are
allowed to enter the Miss America Pageant is not an issue with most
guys. How many times have you heard guys talking about that over by
the office coffee pot? None. Having to watch the Miss America
Pageant at all is the real issue with guys.
</P>
<P>
   Show me a guy who is watching the Miss America Pageant, and I'll
show you some poor schlep who is watching it because his old lady
wants to see what kind of makeup Miss New Jersey is wearing.
</P>
<P>
   Show me a guy watching the Miss America Pageant and I'll show
you a guy who is trying to find the remote so he can switch to
ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Show me a guy who is watching the Miss America Pageant at home
on TV, and I'll show you a father who has three girls, no boys _
and no vote.
</P>
<P>
   Beauty pageants are like $500,000 weddings. The only people who
enjoy them are females.
</P>
<P>
   So if all of the young women entered in the Miss America Pageant
aren't vestal virgins, most guys aren't going to lose a lot of
sleep over it. If, say, Miss Nebraska has been around the block a
few times, what difference does it make as long as she's had all of
her shots? Most guys are more concerned with the over and under on
the Denver game.
</P>
<P>
   So I find it highly amusing that Sheryl McCarthy, a columnist
for Newsday, is all worked up about the ``male sexual fantasy''
surrounding the Miss America Pageant.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, lady, get a grip. The male sexual fantasy ain't watching
some 18-year-old from Mississippi play ``Ode to Joy'' out of tune
on a French horn.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pageant is the embodiment of a male sexual fantasy that's
been embraced by millions of romance-seeking women whose real lives
don't fit the fantasy one bit,'' McCarthy writes.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy's column laments that the recent attempt to change the
rules of the Miss America Pageant to include women who have been
pregnant, and formerly married women, was unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the people who run the Miss America Pageant were honest,
they'd admit that their annual extravaganza could be accurately be
called The Miss Pretend To Be a Virgin Contest,'' McCarthy writes.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but so what? Guys don't care if Miss America is dating
the World Wrestling Federation, because guys don't want to be
watching Miss Arkansas yodel in D flat in the first place. Ladies,
do us a favor, call the whole thing off, and turn in your tiaras,
for gosh sakes. If I want to see somebody cry at the end, I can
watch the Jerry Lewis Telethon.
</P>
<P>
   If you ladies want to get your skirts in a knot about who gets
to enter the Miss America Pageant and who doesn't, don't drag us
guys into the argument.
</P>
<P>
   We just want to get our hands on the remote so we can watch the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: jkelso(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
