<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINOR-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eleven minutes that shouldn't happen to anyone
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The dispatcher stayed on the line for 11
minutes. Eleven long minutes. Through the thumping up the stairs.
Through his yells. Through her screams, shrill, eerie shrieks that
erupted from the depths of a frightened woman's soul.
</P>
<P>
   She stayed on through the gunshots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello,'' she kept saying. ``Hello. Hello. Hello.''
</P>
<P>
   She stayed on until the officer was there and the dead had been
counted. Two at the scene. One the next day at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only picture it,'' says West Palm Beach Police
Department spokeswoman Dena Peterson. ``I can't fathom it.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened last week in a townhouse off Village Boulevard _
one of those developments with the second-floor bedrooms and the
courtyard patio outside the front door _ is what Judge Cory Ciklin
works every day to prevent: A domestic shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Police say it happened like this. Arlister ``Joe'' Williams came
to his estranged wife's apartment to pick up some things. It was a
prearranged meeting, so his wife's sister let him in. Williams
stood at the foot of the stairs and talked to his wife. Then he
pulled out a .32-caliber pistol and started shooting. First, his
sister-in-law. Then her daughter. Both in the head. ``I don't
understand why the other deaths,'' says Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   Then Williams chased his wife, Bridgette Williams, up the
stairs, through the bedroom, down the stairs. The struggle was so
loud and so violent that, at one point, police think he pulled off
half her ear lobe, earring and all. The screaming and struggling on
the 911 tape is like something from a bad movie. He followed her
out the front door, through the courtyard, down the sidewalk. He
dragged her back and shot her in the head, just like the others. He
left her collapsed just outside the courtyard gate. Then he shot
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Williams, 28, died. His estranged wife, also 28, didn't. But
she was in critical condition Tuesday, and it was unclear if she
will recover. Joe Williams also killed Bridgette's sister and
16-year-old niece.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the shooting, after Ciklin read about the murders
and Williams' suicide in the newspaper, Ciklin had his assistant
look up all the names in the computer. He wanted to quiet his
biggest fear.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to know if the Williamses had been before him
recently. They hadn't. ``That's the first thing I always do,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Because there's no way Ciklin _ who has been the main judge for
the domestic violence court division in Palm Beach County since it
was started in May 1998 _ can remember the nearly 4,000 cases that
came into his courtroom last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's made me appreciative of having had what I now know was a
normal childhood,'' says Ciklin, who will leave the domestic court
bench this January.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was arguing in my family, but there was never any kind
of physical violence. But now I know that for thousands of
families, domestic violence is a way of life. It's an accepted way
of life.''
</P>
<P>
   He sees husbands and wives who are headed for divorce but come
to his courtroom first to fake abuse so they will have the
``strategic advantage'' in the upcoming proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   He sees first-timers, shocked and repentant. He sees stalkers
who swear they will stop. He sees husbands who beat their wives
again and again, and wives who fit all too tidily into the profile
of the abused woman. Right or wrong, explicable or downright
baffling, again and again, he watches women willing to ``take the
beatings so the children can be fed for another day.''
</P>
<P>
   But in his 18 months on the bench, Ciklin has also seen
something else.
</P>
<P>
   A little change. A little improvement.
</P>
<P>
   A little success.
</P>
<P>
   The woman who gets the nerve to leave. The children who are put
in a safe house. The man who goes through domestic abuse classes
and learns to deal with anger through words instead of fists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are success stories from the letters I've
received,'' Ciklin said. ``We don't get hundreds of them. But we do
get three or five every month. Of course, receiving just one a
month is good.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Judge Cory Ciklin knows.
</P>
<P>
   He knows how life can unravel in a mere 11 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Emily J. Minor writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
