<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: Take one of two takes.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him: q&AMP;a(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: I thought hurricane names were in alphabetical order, but
after Dennis came Floyd. Was there not one beginning with ``E''?
</P>
<P>
   A: There was a tropical storm named Emily, the fifth of the 1999
hurricane season, Aug. 24-28. You didn't hear much about it because
it was one of the smallest tropical storms on record, with winds
barely above 35 mph extending only 60 miles from its center.
</P>
<P>
   Emily was spotted Aug. 23 as a tiny swirl of clouds, showers and
thunderstorms by the National Hurricane Center. Almost immediately,
Emily was pulled northward as it fell under the control of the much
larger Hurricane Cindy. Emily weakened to a tropical depression on
Aug. 26. By Aug. 28, when Cindy had intensified to a Category 4
hurricane with 140 mph winds and a far-reaching structure, Emily
was ripped apart and absorbed into its circulation.
</P>
<P>
   Not every letter in the alphabet is used in storm names, by the
way. Q, U, X, Y and Z aren't included because of the scarcity of
names beginning with those letters.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Would you list the top five contestants in the Miss America
contest?
</P>
<P>
   A: The 4th runner-up was Miss Texas, Yanci Yarbrough, of
Childress; 3rd, Miss Maryland, Keri Schrader, of Rockville; 2nd,
Miss Pennsylvania, Susan Spafford, of Erie; 1st, Miss Illinois,
Jade Smalls, of Evanston. Miss Kentucky, Heather Renee French, of
Maysville, was crowned Miss America 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The media and public officials described the recent coastal
exodus in the face of Hurricane Floyd as ``the largest peacetime
evacuation in U.S. history.'' The implication is that there was a
bigger evacuation during wartime, but even those of us who lived
through World War II are aware of no such thing. Can you explain?
</P>
<P>
   A: This appears to be one of those sound bites that got out of
hand. According to the Federal Emergency Management Agency, records
indicate no evacuation in peacetime or otherwise in the United
States that was larger. It should have been described only as ``the
largest evacuation of this type,'' said FEMA spokeswoman Mary
Hudak, with no reference to ``peacetime.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, nearly 800,000 people were evacuated in preparation for
Hurricane Elena, she added, but that was well short of the
estimated 1.25 million evacuated from Florida alone for Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What has become of former New York Jets star ``Broadway'' Joe
Namath? I haven't seen any mention of him in years.
</P>
<P>
   A: The dashing former football hero _ a brilliant quarterback
first with the University of Alabama, then with the Jets (1965-76),
and finally with the Los Angeles Rams (one season) _ has talked
about coaching or returning to broadcasting, but has decided
against both. He was hobbled for years with knee problems,
undergoing five operations before retiring after the 1977 season.
</P>
<P>
   Namath's current interest, in addition to a passion for golf, is
a football camp he and ex-teammate John Dockery operate for boys
ages 8-18 on the campus of Nichols College in Dudley, Mass. Other
than that, he stays out of the news.
</P>
<P>
   Once the quintessential swinging bachelor, known for cruising
the hottest clubs and bars and squiring bombshells like Raquel
Welch, Namath settled down in 1984 when he married, ending the
playboy lifestyle that had fascinated the public for years. By
1998, the marriage crumbled and the couple filed for divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the difference between a typhoon and a hurricane?
</P>
<P>
   A: They're regional terms given to the same type of mature
tropical cyclones, depending on where they develop. The term
hurricane is used for those originating over the North Atlantic and
eastern North Pacific oceans; typhoon, western North Pacific;
cyclones, Arabian Sea, the Bay of Bengal and Indian Ocean, and
within the coastal waters of Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you know anything about a church in South Carolina that
sells the original colonial-era Carolina Gold rice?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's Holy Trinity Episcopal in Ridgeland, S.C. The rice is
grown at a Low Country plantation and some is donated to the church
to sell to the public. A limited amount is available now, priced at
$10 for a 1 1/2-pound bag plus $1.75 for shipping, the Rev. Johnnie
Davis told Q&AMP;A. The crop usually is harvested around the first of
December, he added, with milling starting soon thereafter. To check
on availability of the next crop, he suggested waiting until
December, then calling 843-726-3743. While he didn't speculate on
the kind of harvest expected, he said the crop last year was
``really good.'' Ridgeland didn't experience much rain or wind from
Hurricane Floyd, so that shouldn't be a factor.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina Gold is the variety that European nobility prized for
its sweet, nutty taste and whiter-than-white color after it was
washed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Could you list how all the states ranked on their Scholastic
Aptitude Test scores?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. But as the College Board warns: ``Comparing or ranking
states on the basis of SAT scores alone is invalid and strongly
discouraged by the College Board.'' And keep in mind the disparity
in the percentage of students taking the SAT, varying from 4
percent in Mississippi and South Dakota to 80 percent in
Connecticut and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   That said, here's the information you want, from highest to
lowest combined verbal and math scores for 1999:
</P>
<P>
   1100s: North Dakota (1199); Iowa (1192); Minnesota (1184);
Wisconsin (1179); South Dakota (1173); Illinois and Kansas (tie,
1154); Missouri (1144); Nebraska (1139); Utah (1138); Oklahoma
(1127); Michigan (1122); Louisiana and Arkansas (tie, 1119);
Alabama (1116); Tennessee (1112); Mississippi (1111); Ohio (1102).
</P>
<P>
   1000s: Wyoming (1097); Kentucky (1094); Montana and New Mexico
(tie, 1091); Idaho (1082); Colorado (1076); Washington (1051);
Oregon (1050); Arizona (1049); West Virginia (1039); New Hampshire
(1038); Alaska (1030); Nevada (1029); Massachusetts (1022); Vermont
(1020); Connecticut (1019); Maryland (1014); California (1011);
Maine (1010); New Jersey (1008); Virginia (1007); Rhode Island
(1003); Delaware (1000).
</P>
<P>
   900s: New York and Florida (tie, 997); Hawaii (995); Indiana
(994); Pennsylvania and Texas (tie, 993); North Carolina (986);
District of Columbia (972); Georgia (969); South Carolina (954).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you list all states, with the percentage of students in
each, taking the SAT in 1999?
</P>
<P>
   A: Alabama, 9 percent; Alaska, 50; Arizona, 34; Arkansas, 6;
California, 49; Colorado, 32; Connecticut, 80; Delaware, 67;
District of Columbia, 77; Florida, 53; Georgia, 63; Hawaii, 52;
Idaho, 16; Illinois, 12; Indiana, 60; Iowa, 5; Kansas, 9; Kentucky,
12; Louisiana, 8; Maine, 68; Maryland, 65; Massachusetts, 78;
Michigan, 11; Minnesota, 9; Mississippi, 4; Missouri, 8; Montana,
21; Nebraska, 8; Nevada, 34; New Hampshire, 72; New Jersey, 80; New
Mexico, 12; New York, 76; North Carolina, 61; North Dakota, 5;
Ohio, 25; Oklahoma, 8; Oregon, 53; Pennsylvania, 70; Rhode Island,
70; South Carolina, 61; South Dakota, 4; Tennessee, 13; Texas, 50;
Utah, 5; Vermont, 70; Virginia, 65; Washington, 52; West Virginia,
18; Wisconsin, 7; Wyoming, 10.
</P>
<P>
   Complete statistics can be found online at the College Board Web
site (www.collegeboard.org), clicking first on 1999 College Bound
Seniors, then on Tables and Related Items, and then on SAT Averages
by State for 1989 and 1996-1999.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've read that Habitat for Humanity International has built
and rehabilitated more than 80,000 houses. Where was the first
Habitat house built, and is it still there?
</P>
<P>
   A: Habitat for Humanity International evolved over a period of
time, developing from the seed of a small, interracial, Christian
farming community known as Koinonia Farm, in Sumter County, Ga.,
about 12 miles south of Americus. Koinonia was founded in 1942 by
farmer and biblical scholar Clarence Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Koinonia first laid out 42 half-acre sites, with 4 acres
reserved as a community park and recreational area, in 1968.
Millard and Linda Fuller, who founded Habitat for Humanity
International in 1976, first visited Koinonia in 1965, subsequently
developing the concept of ``partnership housing,'' where those in
need of adequate shelter would work side by side with volunteers to
build simple, decent houses.
</P>
<P>
   Habitat's first house, built in 1976, is at Koinonia. ``It's
still there, part of a thriving community,'' Habitat spokesman
Michael Crook told Q&AMP;A.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've noticed black ribbons worn on their uniforms by the San
Francisco Giants. What does that signify?
</P>
<P>
   A: The ribbons, actually purple, were worn at the game Sept. 12
_ for that one day only _ in honor of ``RSVP Day,'' said Giants
spokesman Stan Martinez. RSVP stands for Results Stop Violence
Program, he said, explaining that it's an initiative against youth
violence. The Giants have been supporting the program for several
years, Martinez added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My stepson has been called to interview for his American
citizenship. He needs to bring proof of his Selective Service
registration, which he has lost. Where can we get a replacement?
</P>
<P>
   A: Copies of proof of registration may be obtained by calling
Selective Service at 847-688-6888. You also may obtain a copy by
writing: Selective Service System, P.O. Box 94638, Palatine, IL
60094-4638. Make sure to provide your name, date of birth, Social
Security number and current mailing address. General information
about registration is available online at the Selective Service
System Web site: www.sss.gov/
</P>
<P>
   Q: What can you tell us about the hamlet of Chappaqua, N.Y.,
where the Clintons purchased a home? Is that the same place where
Sen.Ted Kennedy was involved in a car accident some years ago in
which a young woman died?
</P>
<P>
   A: Two different places. Two different states, even.
</P>
<P>
   Chappaqua, where President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton
will live in a $1.7 million, 11-room Dutch Colonial home, is in the
suburbs of Westchester County, north of New York City. The choice
of a home in New York allows Mrs. Clinton to be a resident of the
state in the likely event that she runs for the U.S. Senate. The
five-bedroom home was purchased after President Clinton's chief
fund-raiser, Terry McAuliffe, personally secured the loan by
putting up $1.35 million of his own money with Bankers Trust, which
holds the mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   Chappaquiddick is a small island just off the eastern tip of
Martha's Vineyard, itself an island off the coast of Massachusetts.
It became a household word on the night of July 18, 1969, when a
car driven by Sen. Edward Kennedy (D-Mass.) plunged off a small
wooden bridge into a pond. His 28-year-old companion, Mary Jo
Kopechne, was drowned.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Cardinal John O'Connor had a brain tumor removed recently.
Can you tell me what type tumor, and the prognosis?
</P>
<P>
   A: As previously reported, O'Connor, complaining of nausea and
weakness, was hospitalized in New York for tests Aug. 25. Doctors
at Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center removed the tumor, and he
was released Sept. 5, with radiation therapy expected to follow.
</P>
<P>
   An initial statement on the 79-year-old cardinal's condition
issued by Joseph Zwilling, spokesman for the Archdiocese of New
York, gave no details about the nature of the tumor or its precise
size and location, and Zwilling said he couldn't release any more
information. But it was reported in The New York Times that the
tumor was confined to the brain's surface.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor made his first public appearance after the surgery
Sept. 12. Speaking at New York's St. Patrick's Cathedral, he didn't
say whether the tumor was malignant, or what the prognosis might
be. Contacted at the archdiocese offices Sept. 16, Zwilling said
O'Connor ``is resuming his schedule gradually and is doing much
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
