r a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS23-TAKE     09-22 1602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS23-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: Take two of 2 takes.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: News reports mentioned that an elite force of Gurkha fighters
from Nepal were going to participate in the peacekeeping force that
is about to go to East Timor. Who are they, and what are they known
for?
</P>
<P>
   A: Gurkhas first came to Nepal in the 12th century, when they
were driven out of northern India by the Muslims. The Gurkhas claim
descent from the warlike Rajputs of northern India, in the present
state of Rajasthan.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting quality of Nepal's Gurkha solders, an ethnically
diverse military force created by Prithvi Narayan Shah, is
legendary. He led them in their 1769 conquest of the Nepal Valley,
which resulted in the consolidation of numerous petty
principalities and provided the foundation for the modern state of
Nepal. From the mid-1800s, the Gurkha troops were heavily recruited
by Britain and, since 1947 have been a significant minority within
the army of India.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A published list of the costliest U.S. hurricanes omitted
Opal, which swept northward from the Gulf of Mexico a couple of
years ago. How did it compare?
</P>
<P>
   A: Opal ranks 27th on the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration's list of the top 30 damaging U.S. hurricanes
between 1900 and 1998. The storm, rated Category 3, struck
northwest Florida and Alabama in 1995 and caused damage estimated
at $3.3 billion (normalized to 1998 dollars by inflation, wealth
increases, and coastal county population changes). The NOAA list,
by the way, ranks a Category 4 hurricane striking southeast Florida
and Alabama in 1926 as No. 1, causing $80.6 billion in damage.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read several months ago that Amy Carter was expecting a
baby, but I never saw a follow-up. Can you update me?
</P>
<P>
   A: The birth of Hugo James Wentzel was reported July 31. Amy
Carter, daughter of former President Jimmy Carter and Rosalynn
Carter, gave birth to her son July 29 at a metro Atlanta hospital.
He weighed 7 pounds, 13 ounces. Amy Carter is married to computer
specialist Jim Wentzel.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've seen several mentions of the Saffir-Simpson scale used
to measure the strength of hurricanes. Who were Saffir and Simpson?
</P>
<P>
   A: Herbert Saffir and Robert Simpson were the developers in 1973
of the damage-potential scale named for them. Simpson was director
of the National Hurricane Center and Saffir was a construction
engineer and wind specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Their scale separates mature hurricanes _ tropical cyclones with
winds of 74 mph or greater _ into five ascending classes or
categories.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I remember Bill Bradley being called ``Dollar Bill'' when he
played in the NBA. Can you find out what that meant?
</P>
<P>
   A: Some people say it comes from his austere tipping and
spending habits, while others accept the more likely explanation
that he hit the jackpot long before the NBA's megabuck explosion
when, in 1967, he signed a $500,000 contract with the New York
Knicks. Yet another explanation is that in ``street'' basketball,
when a player shoots and is confident the ball will go in, the
player shouts ``money,'' as in ``It's money in the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read a brief item about Casey Riggan, a Midland, Texas,
student who was punished for taking a photo of his married
principal's car outside a teacher's house. Could we have a little
more detail? Was the photo displayed?
</P>
<P>
   A: The picture was never taken to Midland High School, and it
wasn't taken on school property or during school time, said
Riggan's mother, Gail. ``They (school officials) have absolutely no
right under the law to say he can't photograph a car in front of a
house, something that anybody else in the nation can do,'' she
added.
</P>
<P>
   Casey, 18, a senior who was barred from graduation after word of
the picture got around town and rumors about the principal began to
circulate, said he just kept the picture in a closet at home. But
he and his friends talked about it. When Neil RIchmond, the
principal, asked him to write a formal apology, the teen refused,
precipitating his suspension. Richmond says Riggan was disciplined
for being disrespectful to an adult by fostering rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Riggan, meanwhile, claims that he didn't even take the picture.
He said he believes the student who did take it wasn't suspended
because he was a star on the school baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   The student has filed a federal lawsuit against the school
district for infringing on his right of free speech. U.S. District
Judge Royal Ferguson, who already has thrown out several motions
from Riggan's attorney, is expected to decide soon whether the
lawsuit warrants a trial.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How is Walter Payton doing? Back in the winter it was
reported that he had a rare liver disease, but I haven't seen any
mention of him since.
</P>
<P>
   A: There hasn't been much to report since the legendary former
member of the Chicago Bears _ one of the greatest all-around
running backs in football history _ tearfully delivered the news to
reporters that he's suffering from primary sclerosing cholangitis
and in need of a liver transplant. Soon after, Payton joined a list
of 12,000 people who share his blood type and are waiting for
transplants.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 13, it was reported that Payton's disease was
progressing faster than expected, and a few weeks later he began
wearing a beeper to notify him if a donated liver was available so
he could go immediately to the Mayo Clinic in Minnesota for the
transplant operation. Then on March 5 his wife, Connie, said he
wouldn't be able to attend the opening of Galyan's, a sporting
goods megastore in Chicago. ``Right now, in your prayers is the
best place for Walter,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   While he threw out the first pitch at the Cubs' home opener in
April, he then had to cancel a personal appearance the following
day because of fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   Fans can follow the latest reports on Payton's health online,
and send messages of support, at a site operated by the Chicago
Tribune: www.chicago.tribune.com/sports/bears/ (in the list of
continuing stories, click on Walter Payton's fight).
</P>
<P>
   Q: In terms of a weather-related evacuation order, what does
``mandatory'' mean, when some people seem to stay put anyway?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's no strict, universal definition of ``mandatory,''
meaning one that would apply to every area and in every case, said
Mary Hudak of the Federal Emergency Management Agency. Decisions on
evacuations are up to local authorities and can vary from county to
county, even from sheriff to sheriff. Part of what FEMA does is
provide ``the best information available'' to those local officials
so they can make the best decisions for the well-being of
residents, Hudak added.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, it's a free country and people cannot be forcibly
removed from their homes if they choose to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the difference between a tidal wave and a storm surge
associated with a hurricane?
</P>
<P>
   A: The effect on a coastline may be similar, since both can be
tremendously devastating, but they're not the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   A ``tidal wave'' _ which should be called a tsunami or seismic
sea wave, because it has no connection with the tides _ is a
catastrophic ocean wave usually caused by an underwater earthquake
with a magnitude greater than 6.5 on the Richter scale. Underwater
or coastal landslide or volcanic eruptions also may cause a
tsunami.
</P>
<P>
   A storm surge is an increase in the average water level _
possibly of 15 feet or more _ as the hurricane or other intense
storm moves close to the coast. The advancing storm surge combines
with the normal tide to create the hurricane storm tide. This
buildup of water level can cause severe flooding in coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Isn't Timor where Capt. William Bligh and some of his crewmen
landed after the mutiny on the HMS Bounty and their subsequent long
ordeal at sea?
</P>
<P>
   A: Right you are. In a remarkable feat of seamanship, Bligh
(captain of the Bounty, but with the rank of lieutenant in the
British navy) and the crew members who were loyal to him reached
Timor on June 14, 1789, after a voyage of about 3,600 miles in an
open longboat. They had been turned adrift after Fletcher Christian
and other mutineers seized
</P>
<P>
   Q: Serena Williams, who defeated Martina Hingis to win the U.S.
Open, was quoted as saying,``I'm so excited I had a chance to
accomplish that while she's still alive,'' referring to Althea
Gibson. What is Gibson's condition?
</P>
<P>
   A: The tennis legend _ in 1957, the first black player to win
the Wimbledon singles title and the first to win the U.S. national
title, among many other championships _ has developed various
ailments and has suffered two strokes that apparently left her
barely able to walk or talk. So she lives almost as a recluse in
East Orange, N.J., refusing interview requests and rarely venturing
out.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Clayton-Gray, executive director of the East
Orange-based Althea Gibson Foundation, told reporters earlier this
year that the former tennis star ``just basically wants to rest.''
Doctors say Gibson, 72, is severely depressed, but in essence
suffers from a broken spirit. She wasn't even able to attend the
dedication in May of the Althea Gibson Early Childhood Education
Academy in East Orange.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her reclusiveness, Gibson is said always to take an
annual birthday call from former New York Mayor David Dinkens. Both
were born in 1927, he in Trenton, N.J., and Gibson in Silver, S.C.
Dinkens' call always begins: ``Hey, champ.''
</P>
<P>
   (ENDIT)
</P>
