r d BC-FOOD-PEPPERS23-COX     09-22 0369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PEPPERS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Peppers reach their prime for preserving
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It's now or never. Unless you relish paying
winter prices of $2.99 when you need just one red bell pepper, this
is the week to pick a peck of peppers and put 'em up.
</P>
<P>
   We're not talking anything serious such as canning; nothing that
requires precise skills. This job can be as easy as cutting a
pepper into chunks, freezing the chunks on a cookie sheet and
bagging them up for a winter soup or stew.
</P>
<P>
   If you're willing to spend a little more time, an even better
way to enjoy these peppers later is to roast them. Char and blister
them on a grill, range or under the broiler. Once skinned and
seeded, they can be packed in oil. Roasted peppers can be stored
for a while in the refrigerator but last for months in the freezer.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that preserving peppers is one of those summer
projects worth putting off until the last moment. The bell peppers
started turning color in August, but the price still was high. But
now you can find red peppers as low as five for $1.
</P>
<P>
   At that price you can afford to be selective. This year it's
important to take a good look at what you buy. Some farmers without
irrigation have a skimpy harvest and less-than-ideal crop. But Mike
Brown, who is blessed with irrigation at his farm, has a field of
5,000 plants full of big, ripe peppers. If you're feeling
ambitious, he'll sell you a peck for $6.
</P>
<P>
   If you're roasting the peppers, take a few minutes to pick out
specimens that are reasonably straight-sided. Some peppers grow
into convoluted shapes that never evenly roast. Perfect peppers
command the highest price, two for $1. But if you're just cutting
them up to freeze, the twisted ones are acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid any peppers that are wrinkled or soft. Red bells tend to
soften on the stalk more quickly than green and are more perishable
once picked. And some farmers don't cull them out before they truck
them to market.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: annheller(AT)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
