<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1319 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-PEPPERS-PRESERVE     09-22 0345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PEPPERS-PRESERVE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Roast, freeze peppers to preserve
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's how to preserve those peppers:
</P>
<P>
   _ Freeze them: With a large knife, cut off the tops and bottom,
then cut the pepper in half vertically. Remove and discard seeds
and ribs. Cut the pepper halves into quarters, 1/2-inch slices or
large squares. Place in a single layer on a cookie sheet. Cover
with waxed paper and freeze until firm. Bag them in sturdy freezer
bags. If you thaw them before using, the peel easily pulls off. You
can also freeze whole peppers. Remove the stem and scoop out the
seeds and ribs from the top. Freeze and when solid, nestle them
together in batches of four. Wrap with plastic wrap and seal well
in freezer bags. They will keep their shape if you stuff the pepper
shells while still frozen before cooking them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Roast them: If you're doing just a few peppers, it's easy to
spear them with the tines of a fork and roast them over the gas
flame of the stove. When the skin is blistered and blackened _ but
not burned _ put them in a mixing bowl and cover with plastic wrap
to let the steam loosen the skin. After 10 or 15 minutes, use a
sharp knife to pull off the peel. Do this over the bowl to retain
any juices. Cut the peppers in half and remove the seeds, ribs and
stem. Layer them with oil, preferably olive oil, in a sterilized
glass jar or plastic freezer container. Freeze in amounts usable
for a single recipe. For more immediate use, place in containers
with a lid and cover with olive oil, making sure the peppers are
fully immersed. Cover and refrigerate. Resist the impulse to add
garlic, which can cause contamination.
</P>
<P>
   If you're roasting a peck of peppers, place them on a broiler
rack or over the medium coals of a grill. Turn until all sides are
blackened, then place in a bowl and cover until steam loosens the
skin.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
