<HEADER>
A1320 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-PEPPERS-RECIPES2     09-22 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PEPPERS-RECIPES23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Good pepper prices sweeten dishes
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   At $3 a pop for peppers in winter, the eight peppers needed for
this recipe would cost $24.
</P>
<P>
   Roast your own peppers using local two-for-$1 peppers and you
can cut that price to $4, an acceptable expenditure for an elegant
side dish.
</P>
<P>
   GRATIN OF RED PEPPERS
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   8 roasted red bell peppers
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons freshly grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   If using oil-packed peppers, drain them well. Cut the peppers
into strips.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 450 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange half the pepper strips in the bottom of a medium gratin
dish or glass casserole.
</P>
<P>
   Puree the remaining red peppers with the cream in a blender or
food processor. Season with salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Pour the pepper cream over the pepper strips, sprinkle with the
cheese and place briefly in the 450-degree oven to heat through.
Alternatively, place under a hot broiler until the mixture bubbles
and sizzles.
</P>
<P>
   Serve immediately with bread to soak up any extra pepper sauce.
</P>
<P>
   _ Recipe is from the new Peppers Peppers Peppers by Marlena
Spieler (Firefly, $19.95).
</P>
<P>
   Peperonata is a pepper mixture that can be served with grilled
bread as an appetizer or as a side dish. Because the pepper chunks
are cooked for a long time, there is little lost by using frozen
peppers. And using frozen chunks makes this a dish that can be
assembled in less than five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   PEPERONATA
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 cups
</P>
<P>
   6 bell peppers, cut into chunks
</P>
<P>
   6 cloves garlic, chopped
</P>
<P>
   5 to 6 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 tablespoons red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh chopped oregano, or 1 teaspoon dried
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 to 1/2 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh chopped parsley or 2 tablespoons fresh
chopped basil
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Place the peppers in a shallow baking pan. Toss them with the
garlic, oil, vinegar, oregano, salt and sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for about 30 minutes, stirring once or twice. Remove, taste
and adjust seasoning, adding more vinegar, salt and sugar if
necessary. Return to the oven for another 5 to 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from the oven and sprinkle with the parsley or basil. The
peppers can be served warm or at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   For a more substantial appetizer or lunch, top the peppers with
slices of goat cheese and return to the oven until lightly browned
and soft.
</P>
<P>
   If you've also frozen yellow peppers, include some for
contrasting color.
</P>
<P>
   _ Recipe from the new Peppers Peppers Peppers by Marlena Spieler
(Firefly, $19.95).
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
