<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1321 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-WINE-COLUMN23-COX     09-22 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WINE COLUMN: Some things are better left alone
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Basking in the artificial afterglow of a
health-label victory, some wine producers and marketers want to
take another big leap, this time seeking to sell souped-up wine as
a beneficial drug.
</P>
<P>
   Good grief. Talk about a slippery slope.
</P>
<P>
   The wine is called Le Vin du Coeur, a rose-style wine from the
Provence region of France. Its gimmick: It contains extra
polyphenols, the naturally occurring compounds from the skin and
seeds of grapes that some research suggests make red wine in
moderation good for the heart. The French pink wine has twice the
amount of polyphenols normally found in red wine, according to
publicity materials. (A quick check suggests the wine hasn't made
it yet to the local market.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The latest trend in the food world _ and one of the hottest
marketing segments of the industry _ is to enhance the naturally
occurring health benefits of particular foods,'' gushes the press
release. ```Functional foods,' `designer foods,' `nutraceuticals'
and `pharmafoods' are all buzzwords that are becoming more popular
with consumers, scientists, culinary historians and food and
beverage manufacturers.''
</P>
<P>
   Um, not this consumer, thanks. At least, not with my wine.
</P>
<P>
   The marketers of the new ``heart-healthy'' wine point out quite
correctly that fortified foods are nothing new. Salt has iodine.
Breakfast cereals are laced with vitamins. Maybe fortification of
wine with some of its most beneficial compounds is a natural
extension of that practice.
</P>
<P>
   But here's one key difference: Wine just happens to contain
alcohol, which a significant percentage of the population can't
tolerate safely and which can turn to poison if abused. Touting any
alcoholic beverage as beneficial medicine seems a bit, well,
tawdry.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason federal regulators have been so persnickety
about warning labels, only recently handing the wine industry a
half-a-loaf victory by approving two health-related labels
including, ``The proud people who made this wine encourage you to
consult your family doctor about the health effects of wine
consumption.'' The feds rejected suggested labels that referred to
``health benefits.'' I'll bet they were leery of those who would
seize upon the health angle to promote wines irresponsibly. Gosh,
that wouldn't happen, would it?
</P>
<P>
   I'm as excited as anybody about the recent research showing
health benefits of moderate wine consumption. But using that
information haphazardly will just threaten the wine industry's
common-sense efforts on wine labeling and will provide ammunition
to the anti-alcohol lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, why mess with a good thing?
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fisher writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: markfisher(AT)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
