 Wednesday, Sept. 22, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Thursday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6320.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-QUAKE-LESSONS (San Francisco) _ The Taiwanese quake may
have involved the same type of sinister fault that triggered the
Northridge earthquake in Southern California almost six years ago _
a ``blind thrust'' fault. These buried faults _ which cause
vertical ground motion _ lurk within the crust, unseen and
unpredictable. U.S. scientists hope to learn more about the
behavior of ``blind thrust'' faults by studying seismic data from
Taiwan. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-VULTURES (Merced, Calif.) _ Turkey vultures have
tightened their talons on a five-block stretch of one of the
busiest boulevards in this Central Valley town, generating a
neighborly conflict that could almost be described as agitated. By
MICHAEL DOUGAN.
</P>
<P>
   SF-MAYOR (San Francisco) _ With 14 candidates hoping to be San
Francisco's next mayor, it often takes something different,
ludicrous even, to get media coverage. Jim Reid rode a Muni bus
three days straight. Lucrecia Bermudez stormed a mayoral debate
with a bullhorn. Martin Eng, however, has decided to attack the
very organization he wants attention from. He has sued the San
Francisco Chronicle for ignoring him. By JULIE CHAO.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCE (``f'' categories)
</P>
<P>
   JOB-PROMOTIONS (San Francisco) _ When Hewlett-Packard recently
appointed Carleton ``Carly'' Fiorina as president and CEO, the move
symbolized two major trends in corporate America. Lost behind the
obvious one _ more women are gradually rising to the top _ is
another trend expected to have a huge impact over the next decade:
H-P directors weren't comfortable promoting one of their current
workers to CEO. They had to go outside the company. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   CAREERS-LONG-TERM (San Francisco) _ Getting bored in the job?
Look for things that inspire you and give you energy. They can help
you decide whether you're just temporarily out of breath or are so
wiped out that you should stop and run a different race. You can
draw energy from hobbies or spirituality or people you see every
day, like teachers and friends and family. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COSMETICS-ONLINE (San Francisco) _ Who ever heard of buying
cosmetics online? You can't touch them, smell them, try them. But
then, if you live in Helena, Mont., or somewhere in Guam, there
probably isn't a decent high-end cosmetics counter in sight to
purchase those delicious luxury goods that show up in Vogue, W and
Harper's Bazaar. What's a girl to do? Log on, of course. By CYNTHIA
ROBINS.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-SIMPSONS (Undated) _ ``The Simpsons,'' whose 11th season
premieres Sunday, may challenge the record of ``The Adventures of
Ozzie &AMP; Harriet'' as the longest-running sitcom ever, 14 years.
Creator Matt Groening said the comedy's durability can be traced
not only to the characters being well-drawn, but the fact they are
animation. ``In animation, at least the characters don't grow old.
Animation lends itself to novelty and surprise,'' he says. By MARK
McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   TV-GROW-UP (Undated) _ It may prove too much of a task to
defend, even trumpet (though not too loudly) a sitcom that has a
dog named Mom who talks in subtitles. Then again, the guy behind
``Oh Grow Up,'' Alan Ball, is the same guy behind the new movie
``American Beauty,'' which has had many raves. ``Oh Grow Up'' has
the semiprecious distinction of being the second-best sitcom this
fall _ behind ``Action'' _ and primarily because virtually all
others are horrible. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-MYSTERIES (Undated) _ For fans of mysteries and
thrillers, fall is a joyous season because so many of the genre's
best writers are published in September, October and November. By
BOBBIE HESS.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   APPLES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Proclaimed our national fruit by Ralph
Waldo Emerson, the 19th-century poet and essayist, apples are a
wonderful mirror for what is regarded as American. For starters,
they are far more diverse than most folks imagine; there are more
than 7,000 varieties, with more being developed all the time. By
DOUG BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS-KNEES (San Francisco) _ Maybe some genius will take a
break from the mounting dot-com dreck and figure out a way to make
and install artificial knee ligaments for the sport's
student-athletes. Think of it: super-strong, resilient knee
ligaments, made of some as-yet unknown material, capable of
withstanding the front bumper of a Lexus at 30 miles an hour,
attached to your favorite running back. By JOHN CRUMPACKER.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The Marin County Emergency
Operation Center recently held a Y2K drill. This was the New Year's
Eve disaster scenario, according to the Mill Valley Herald:
``Sharks are at Stinson, a riot's happening at the Mill Valley
Safeway, a tent has fallen on Huey Lewis, and foul-tasting oysters
at a millennium party have made hundreds of people deathly ill.''
By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   BROWNFIELDS (San Francisco) _ The Sierra Club took an unexpected
hit July 5, when it was called elitist in a full-page ad in the New
York Times. The Sierrans were predictably indignant. They claimed
to deserve better. It could have been worse. ``Racist'' and
``fascist'' also were kicked around by the militant young
copywriters at the Greenlining Institute, which bought the space
for the big-type screed. By SCOTT WINOKUR.
</P>
