<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 11:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1372 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CPT-WEB-COPYRIGHT-BOS     09-22 1439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-WEB-COPYRIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISSUE OF WEB COPYRIGHT HOTLY DEBATED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By ANNE E. KORNBLUT   
 c.1999 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Picture this: A scientist spends years compiling
the world's largest book of poison antidotes. Then, shortly after
it's published, he turns on his computer to find a competing
researcher has photocopied the book, posted it to a Web page and
splashed it across the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Legal? Yes, under current law.
</P>
<P>
   Preventable?
</P>
<P>
   That is the question perplexing Congress right now. The issue
extends far beyond the scientific community, affecting millions of
stockbrokers, librarians, real estate agents and publishers _
anyone who makes a living collecting information. Today, such
compilations, otherwise known as databases, go largely unprotected
by copyright laws that safeguard the interests of the authors and
publishers of creative works.
</P>
<P>
   Until lately, this had not seemed unfair: Databases, after all,
are generally gatherings of information created by someone else.
But the rise of the Internet has prompted heated debate over
whether those laws should change.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are tremendous within the $25 billion information
service industry: database owners fear they will lose huge profits
if outsiders can freely copy their information, while on-line
companies, such as Yahoo!, fear they could be run into the ground
if they can't easily trade in others' works.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prospect of restricting the availability of information in
the Information Age is a cause for concern to anyone interested in
the future of the Internet,'' said John Scheibel, a lobbyist for
Yahoo!, a portal site that allows Internet users to search the Web
_ and thrives off easily connecting users to databases around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have the most powerful computers, the most
sophisticated search engines and fully operative broadband systems,
but none of it will mean much without the information to flow over
those lines,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Broadly speaking, the debate is between people who collect raw
data and people who distribute it _ a dividing line that has grown
far deeper with the expansion of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate agents, for example, gather information about which
apartments are available. Their concern is that an on-line
publisher could see their listings in the window of an agency, copy
them down, and put them up on a Web site _ all perfectly legal
under current federal law.
</P>
<P>
   Lexis keeps vast collections of court decisions. They might be
faced with a competing on-line publisher who decides to use Lexis
data to launch a website of all court decisions from Massachusetts
_ also perfectly legal under copyright law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would anyone spend $2 million to create a database if it's
not going to be protected?'' said David Mirchin, of SilverPlatter
Information, a database publisher in Norton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The issue resonates in Massachusetts, where academic
institutions and technology firms have lined up against database
publishing companies on opposite sides of the debate. It has also
split members of the Massachusetts delegation, four of whom sit on
the two House committees sparring over what role the federal
government should play.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Edward J. Markey, the Democrat who is the ranking
Democrat on the House telecommunications subcommitee, has sided
largely with the 70 groups that are pushing for easy access to
databases _ among them corporations such as AT&AMP;T and universities
such as Brandeis. What they want is legislation that would not
restrict people from copying databases unless they plan to use the
information in a directly competitive way.
</P>
<P>
   Their concern: restricting access could stifle the economy.
On-line stockbrokers, for example, worry that if Congress goes for
more restrictive copyright language, the New York Stock Exchange
would claim its stock quotes are part of a protected database. That
would allowing the NYSE to charge exorbitant licensing fees for
each stock price, dampening the enthusiasm of companies such as
Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. or Bloomberg Financial Markets _ and,
opponents argue, giving the stock exchange a virtual monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Academic researchers worry they would be forced to pay for
information that is currently free or inexpensive _ such a listing
of chemicals or a database of the elements. And Internet service
providers want to keep access to databases as free as possible, as
part of their strategy to encourage people to do business on line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see this as part of e-commerce, as part of a network
economy,'' Markey said.
</P>
<P>
   But detractors say that the less restrictive version of the
copyright bill has too many loopholes, and could sap the incentive
of those whose work is collecting raw data into extensive
databases.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. William Delahunt is among those who sees database piracy as
a serious law-and-order matter. Congress' mission is to keep
companies from becoming ``victims of unscrupulous freeloaders who
can exploit their work with a click of a mouse,'' according to a
letter he co-wrote this month.
</P>
<P>
   That view is shared by virtually everyone on the House Judiciary
Committee. Along with Delahunt, fellow Democratic Massachusetts
Representatives Barney Frank and Martin T. Meehan also support the
stricter bill, which more closely resembles true copyright law.
People who copy information out of a database for commercial use
would have to clear it with the owner first _ just as people are
required to do now with newspaper articles or Broadway plays.
</P>
<P>
   Lifting whole sections out of, say, a consumer directory of
doctors' addresses to open a medical referral service would be
against the law. So would copying information to compete directly
with any owner of a database.
</P>
<P>
   The bill even raises the possibility of criminal sanctions
against database pirates.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the push for stricter copyright regulations are some
major corporate and other interests: Reed Elsevier, owner of Lexis
Nexis and of Cahners Publishing of Newton, Mass; the American
Medical Association; and the National Association of Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   All freely concede that their goal is to preserve their private
interests _ the profitability of the databases they collect. And
they see the potential threat as grave: Some advocates paint a
database doomsday scenario, in which whole databases are secretly
spirited away to the Internet, with no accountability for their
accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   A favorite example is Poisindex a database produced by
Micromedex, which does, in fact, list poison remedies for use in
emergency rooms. To date, the data has not been copied and posted
on the Internet. But if it were, ``there is nothing in the law that
would allow Poisindex to tell them to stop,'' according to Dan
Duncan, a lobbyist for the Software &AMP; Information Industry
Association. A parent browsing the Internet for poison remedies
would have no legal recourse if the pirated version of the index,
published without updates, revisions or accurate instructions, gave
outdated medical advice , he said.
</P>
<P>
   Already, advocates of strict regulations say there have been
tangible consequences to the lack of database piracy laws.
</P>
<P>
   One example is Warren Publishing, a Washington-based company
that printed a three-volume book of US cable systems. Another
company copied the book and reissued it on diskette. Warren
Publishing took their competitors to court and lost at the appeals
level; they have since become among the most outspoken advocates of
tougher rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were totally ripped off. It seemed to us an extremely
unfair decision. We invested hundreds of thousands of dollars each
year into producing this product, and the court basically
sanctioned'' its piracy, said Lynn Levine, assistant publisher for
research.
</P>
<P>
   Although Warren Publishing also reached a settlement with the
defendants, the case underscored database owners' worst fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is at stake here is that producers of factual
compilations of information enjoy no general law protecting them
from piracy in the United States,'' Duncan said. ``If this
legislation does not go through, there will be much less quality
database information for users.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank agreed: ``I'm strong believer in the First Amendment, but
the First Amendment doesn't mean you have the right to publish
other people's work. I think there is a value to society of people
compiling databases. But if you get zero protection, why would you
do it? Data compilation is not fun. It's not something people do
for the sheer creative joy of it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-20-99 1939EDT &QL;
</P>
