<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-RESEARCH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO GET THE LOWDOWN ON GOOD AND BAD COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By EDWARD IWATA   
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As the digital culture zaps its way into nearly
every facet of our lives, it's no secret that the Web has evolved
into an awesome weapon for millions of investors and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Financial information is power, and you can quickly nab those
factoids online for free or for a reasonable cost _ compared with
the millions of dollars that companies pay brokerages, investment
firms and research consultants for their services.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the average investor can't tap into the same powerful
databases and pricy financial services as money managers and equity
analysts. But some sharp Main Street investors _ armed with
personal computers, tenacious brainpower and a wealth of online
resources _ know nearly as much about companies and stocks as the
Wall Street pros do.
</P>
<P>
   If you're an investment newbie or an online rookie, you may feel
bowled over by the thousands of financial resources on the Web.
Where do you begin? What are the best ways to get the lowdown on
good and bad corporations? What online tools are quick, handy and
helpful? Your first stop: the U.S. Securities and Exchange
Commission, the agency that enforces federal securities law, and
its Web site (www.sec.gov).
</P>
<P>
   Publicly traded corporations _ companies whose shares are bought
and sold on the stock exchanges _ must file financial statements
throughout the year with the SEC. If you can survive the numbing
legal and financial jargon, the reports often are gold mines of
information.
</P>
<P>
   Need a quick profile or snapshot of a company? Check out the
annual report given to shareholders or the 10-K report, an annual
report to the SEC, both of which give an overview of a company's
financial assets, market outlook, products and other big picture
topics.
</P>
<P>
   Want to know how much top executives are making? Look up the
company's proxy statement for salaries, stock option packages and
other compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Digging for dirt on a merger, bankruptcy or other big event that
will affect a company's stock or earnings performance by 5 percent
or more? Pore through the 8-K report, which companies must file
after a ``materially important'' event occurs.
</P>
<P>
   Want to invest in an IPO, a company's initial public offering _
its first sale of shares on the stock market? The prospectus will
give you a good overview of a private company about to go public.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Internet, researchers would have to dig laboriously
through reams of SEC documents in government or business libraries.
Or they'd call a company's investor relations office and have the
papers snail-mailed to them.
</P>
<P>
   Now, you simply click to the SEC's Web site and find reports
rapid-fire on the EDGAR database. Ain't technology wonderful?
(EDGAR, by the way, stands for Electronic Data Gathering, Analysis
and Retrieval.) You also can check with several private firms _
including edgar- online.com, freeedgar.com and others _ that sell
SEC electronic filings for a fee. A company's complete SEC filings
and supplemental documents may not be on EDGAR, but the private
services will hunt it down for you.
</P>
<P>
   Next, get turned on to the best financial Web sites. If you
aren't addicted yet, get your fix fast _ the Internet and the stock
market aren't going away.
</P>
<P>
   The sites will help you probe a company's stock and financial
performance, call up business news stories and SEC documents, study
market sectors and the economy, set up your investment portfolio
and chat with other investors.
</P>
<P>
   Say you want the scoop on IPO investing. While investment firms
dominate the IPO market, a small but growing niche of individual
online investors are getting a piece of the IPO pie.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to do a story on the new trend. To get a quick read on
IPOs, I clicked into CBS MarketWatch's financial news Web site
(www.marketwatch.com) and CNET's technology news site
(www.news.com/investor) to skim dozens of archived articles and
breaking stories on new offerings and tech stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Then I did a broad Web search using various search engines,
punching in the key words ``IPOs,'' ``online'' and ``individuals.''
The search called up investment firms that specialize in IPOs for
online investors. I looked up their corporate profiles at
www.hoovers.com, the Web site of the venerable Hoover's corporate
directory, then zipped over to each firm's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   A few keystrokes later, I clicked Raging Bull
(www.ragingbull.com), a popular high-tech investment site for day
traders, and posted a request on message boards to interview online
IPO investors. Within the hour, three investors had e-mailed or
called me.
</P>
<P>
   As I chatted with one investor on the phone, I used the SEC's
Web site and an investment research firm, www.ipomonitor.com, to
call up up summaries of IPOs he liked. I also searched several
other Web sites that follow the IPO market.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, all of that paper research would have taken
several days. With high-powered online resources, it took me only a
few hours. It's like leaping from a single-engine plane to a jet
fighter.
</P>
<P>
   So get started. Top financial portals include CyberInvest
(www.cyberinvest.com), ETrade Group (www.etrade.com), Excite
(www.excite.com), Go2Net's Silicon Valley Investor
(www.siliconinvestor.com), Investorama (www.investorama.com),
Microsoft's MoneyCentral Investor (investor.msn.com), Motley Fool
(www.fool.com), Yahoo! Finance (quote.yahoo.com) and others.
</P>
<P>
   A sampling of superior news sites include ABCNews.com
(www.abcnews.go.com), Bloomberg (www.bloomberg.com), CBS
MarketWatch.com (www.marketwatch.com), CNN's CNNfn (www.cnnfn.com),
Dow Jones Interactive (www.djinteractive.com) and TheStreet.com
(www.thestreet.com) and the Wall Street Journal's (www.wsj.com).
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, check out some excellent books on corporate and online
research. It may cost you a few bucks and give you paper cuts, but
the books carry thousands of hands-on research techniques.
</P>
<P>
   For Internet research tips, look into ``Competitive
Intelligence, Competitive Advantage'' (Abacus) by Michelle DeWitt.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you're an online god, you're guaranteed to discover
dozens of new financial sites in this book.
</P>
<P>
   Another good study: ``The Irwin Guide to Using the Wall Street
Journal'' (McGraw-Hill) by Michael Lehmann, an economics professor
at the University of San Francisco. Not exactly light bedtime
reading but still a great guide to the Journal, the bible of
business journalism, whether the print or online edition.
</P>
<P>
   I'd also recommend ``The New Competitor Intelligence'' (John
Wiley &AMP; Sons) by Leonard Fuld, a business research consultant in
Cambridge, Mass., and ``Competitive Intelligence'' by Larry
Kahaner, a former BusinessWeek journalist.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-21-99 1209EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
