<HEADER>
A1378 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CPT-Y2K-DON'T-$ADV19-     09-22 0369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-Y2K-DON'T-$ADV19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT NOT TO DO WHEN THE MILLENNIUM NEARS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By MARILYN GEEWAX  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many Americans are checking off lists of things to do as they
prepare for possible Y2K problems. But a list of what not to do on
Jan. 1. is just as important.
</P>
<P>
   _ DON'T pick up the phone at 12:01 a.m. to wish loved ones a
happy new year. Phone companies say there's a limit to how many
receivers can get a dial tone at one time, regardless of
Y2K-related problems.
</P>
<P>
   _ DON'T run into the yard at 11:59 p.m. Dec. 31 to welcome 2000
by firing a gun. Every bullet that goes up must come down _
possibly into the skull of your neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   _ DON'T stockpile gasoline. Fill your car's gas tank several
days before the year's end _ period. Keeping big containers full of
gasoline in the garage is an invitation to disaster.
</P>
<P>
   _ DON'T wait until 8 p.m. on Dec. 31 to go to an automated
teller machine for cash. If everyone waits until the final hours of
1999 to stock up on cash for the long weekend, the machines will
run dry and stir fears of bank failures. And don't keep large
amounts of cash in your home, vulnerable to thieves.
</P>
<P>
   _ DON'T invite hordes over for a New Year's Eve dinner and then
wait until 3 p.m. on Dec. 31 to buy your food and beverages. If
huge crowds pack into grocery stores on the last day of the year,
tempers could flare in long checkout lines and contribute to a
panicky feeling that night.
</P>
<P>
   _ DON'T make elaborate travel plans for the first few days of
January. Though airlines promise to be safe, no one can guarantee
that airport computers won't mix up reservations or that traffic
lights surrounding airports won't malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   _ DON'T fall for Y2K scams. Con artists are using Y2K to cheat
people out of their money. For example, some crooks pretend to be
bank officials calling people for personal financial information
``to conduct Y2K tests.'' Other shady organizations are touting
overpriced goods and services that are ``Y2K guaranteed.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
