</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DIGITAL STORAGE LOCKER' FOR MUSIC DOWNLOADS  
 A NEW WEB SITE OFFERS TO FIX THINGS WITH THE JUDGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is an increasingly popular Internet activity: downloading,
storing and playing digital music files on a computer or a portable
player that can handle the MP3 digital music format.
</P>
<P>
   And it can be annoyingly difficult: Users often do not pay
attention to where downloads land on their hard drives _ and since
there is no industry-wide convention for naming music files, a song
might arrive as a file called eleanorrigby.mp3 or, more blindly,
977X021.mp3. As a result, finding the downloaded tunes can be a
scavenger hunt _ especially on Windows computers.
</P>
<P>
   Detecting a potential business opportunity, two executives with
Internet start-up experience and venture capital have set up a
Silicon Valley company called Myplay. Its Web-based service,
planned for a mid-October rollout, is meant to make it easier to
download and organize music files by song title _ with artist and
album also listed, if Myplay has the information in its database.
Each user's files would be kept in a personal ``digital storage
locker'' on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Other than offering a sample starter kit of some 100 licensed
songs from an eclectic repertoire that includes Elvis Costello and
George Gershwin, Myplay assumes that users will obtain their own
music files on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   A user would have access to the storage locker from any computer
connected to the Internet _ similarly to the way Microsoft's
Hotmail and other Web-based e-mail services enable a person to
check e-mail from any computer, rather than being tied to a single
desktop or laptop machine.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Camplejohn, the 34-year-old co-founder and chief executive
of Myplay, is a former Apple Computer marketing executive. His
cofounder, David Pakman, 30, is a former Apple colleague who was a
business development executive at the online music distributor N2K,
before it merged with CD Now earlier this year. The company, which
is based in Redwood City, Calif., and whose financial backers
include the Silicon Valley venture firms IVP and Interval Capital,
plans to offer each customer a free storage locker that could hold
250 megabytes _ some five to six hours _ of music.
</P>
<P>
   While Myplay may eventually sell monthly subscriptions for
additional storage space, the company's main revenue would come
from advertising and from marketing agreements with music companies
like Dreamworks Records, a unit of Dreamworks SKG, that has signed
on as a charter advertiser.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Somers, a marketing executive with Dreamworks Records, said
his company would offer individual tracks to Myplay customers,
including one from the band Powerman 5000. People who downloaded
the Powerman 5000 track might then receive promotional e-mails
about the band's albums, concerts and the like.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way of finding out what people are listening to,''
Somers said. ``It's another aspect of one-to-one marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   _ TIM RACE
</P>
<P>
   A New Web Site Offers to Fix Things With the Judge
</P>
<P>
   No, it is not called Misdemeanors.com, but it might well be.
</P>
<P>
   These days, with Web sites devoted to selling just about any
conceivable type of goods or services, it appears that the next
frontier for entrepreneurs is using the Internet to help people pay
their debts to society.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that is the theory behind Govworks.com, a New York
company that will let people pay fines for traffic tickets and
other petty violations by entering their credit-card numbers and
the summons information at its Web site. It will begin testing the
system next month in 10 cities, including Springfield, Mass., and
Stamford, Conn. By the end of the year, it plans to serve people
who have committed misdemeanors in the 3,000 largest cities in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``People spend more money on Class C misdemeanors than on
music,'' said Kaleil Izaza Tuzman, 27, the company's Colombian-born
founder, who came up with the idea while working as an arbitrage
trader at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Class C misdemeanors include parking and traffic violations and
other offenses like public indecency, although Govworks will not
handle fines for the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Govworks will charge a 5 percent transaction fee for each fine
paid.
</P>
<P>
   But wait, there's more! Violators who sign up for a magazine
subscription, apply for a credit card or get an auto insurance
quote at the site will pay no fee and will even get a $5 or $10
reduction on their ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Tuzman says the company will be much more than a time-saver for
scofflaws. The company hopes to automate other civic transactions
like tax payments, surplus-property auctions and
purchasing-contract requisitions. And it will list all manner of
information generated by local governments, from job listings to
video replays of city council meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The company has attracted $15 million in investments from
Silicon Valley's Mayfield Fund, the New York City Investment Fund,
Hearst New Media and Kohlberg Kravis Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Govworks does not need a city's cooperation to act as a fine
collector, because it can simply mail a check like any electronic
bill-payment service. But ultimately its founders hope that cities
will agree to accept electronic payments and to pay for various
additional services.
</P>
<P>
   Govworks says it has no plans to work with corrections
departments or their hard-core clientele. Any takers for
Felonies.com?
</P>
<P>
   _ SAUL HANSELL
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
