<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 12:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1387 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-ONLINE-OPTIONS-AR     09-22 1370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-ONLINE-OPTIONS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB SITES OFFER A NEW LURE FOR WRITERS: WEALTH ON PAPER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER and COREY KILGANNON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Casting about for ways to raise its profile, Nerve.com, a
little-known Web site billing its contents as ``literary smut,''
last week sent out come-ons to 60 of the country's best-known
writers, from Joyce Carol Oates to John Updike, offering them not
just $2 a word for their contributions, but a package of stock
options in the company.
</P>
<P>
   Options, the speculative scrip given mythic status by the
success of some Internet start-ups, are seeping into the literary
and journalistic world, as Nerve.com has taken its cue from Web
sites like Salon and TheStreet.com, both of which have used stock
options to lure or reward freelance talent.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Nerve.com is still romancing venture
capitalists, and a long way away from an initial public offering or
acquisition _ events that would eventually give the options
whatever bankable value they may have. Rufus Griscom, 28, who is
Nerve's editor in chief and chief executive, boasts that ``next
week we will have a Pulitzer Prize-winner'' committed to write for
the site.
</P>
<P>
   Griscom's effort to find a name-brand literary asset to call his
own _ and subvert the economics of the freelance writing business _
comes as name-brand writers are slowly turning up on the Web. David
Talbot, the editor of Salon, the San Francisco-based Webzine, has
Garrison Keillor and Camille Paglia as regular contributors. He
said that he had offered stock options to about 10 of Salon's
best-known freelance writers and illustrators _ but would not say
which.
</P>
<P>
   The options in Salon, which offered stock to the public in June
for an initial price of $10.50, allow recipients to purchase Salon
shares for $1 or less in most cases, said Todd Hagen, Salon's chief
financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have used options for consultants and contractors for
years,'' Hagen, who has handled the financial affairs of Web
companies and software companies, said. ``The concept of using
options isn't unique. What is unique is that we as a media company
are doing it with columnists and freelancers.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Moore, publisher of Slate.com, an online magazine owned by
the Microsoft Corp., said he had not heard of the practice of
offering stock options to freelancers. ``There are plenty of
fantasy stories of people hitting it rich off Internet stock option
payments,'' Moore added. ``But these offerings could be completely
worthless, too.'' For Slate, he said, it would make little sense _
the magazine is owned by Microsoft, making the currency of options
too valuable for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the writers who received the offer from Nerve also said
it made little sense to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't write for the Web,'' said Joyce Carol Oates.
``I'm not a Web person.'' Gay Talese said: ``I don't know why this
would have any appeal. It has no appeal to me.'' He said he thought
such a speculative deal ``would have a one in 10,000 chance of
working out.''
</P>
<P>
   John Updike said he had not yet received Nerve's offer, adding,
``I probably would not have responded anyway.'' He added, ``Young
writers may be willing to gamble writing for stock options, but at
my advanced age, I prefer to get paid in dreary old cash.''
</P>
<P>
   The approach of Nerve, Salon and TheStreet.com has its parallels
in other Web ventures. In May, Atomfilms.com, a privately owned
online film distribution company, which buys licensing rights for
independent short films, began offering artists stock packages
along with cash payment for licensing rights to their films, said
Heather Redman, senior vice president of business affairs for
Atomfilms.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shouldn't be the reason an artist chooses us,'' Ms. Redman
said. ``It's more like this is something to put in the back of your
underwear drawer and pull out if we make it big one day. There
really isn't any worth to it until we go public or we're
acquired.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Last March, Alanis Morissette, the rock singer, received a stock
package payment from MP3.com, an Internet company that posts
recordings for free downloading by users. Ms. Morissette agreed to
endorse MP3.com, allowing the site to post exclusive photographs
from her current tour. In return, MP3.com agreed to help sponsor
the singer's tour and to pay a total of 436,000 shares, roughly 2
percent of the company, to Ms. Morissette and Atlas/Third Rail, an
entertainment company in which hger, Scott Welch, is a
partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they couldn't pay us in the traditional sense,''
Welch said. ``So we took a handshake and the stock. We didn't know
what it would be worth, but it didn't hurt that the deal was in all
the papers with Alanis' picture next to it.''
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com went public on July 21 at $20, and its value soared,
closing the first day of trading above $63. Since then it has
retreated, closing last Friday at $32.625. But that still makes the
stake owned by Ms. Morissette and Welch worth a total of $14.2
million. Welch declined to discuss how soon the two are entitled to
sell some or all of those shares.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Stock-for-words deals are not entirely unprecedented. In 1953,
when Hugh Hefner was putting together the first issue of Playboy,
he persuaded more than half the contributing illustrators and
writers to accept stock in lieu of cash for their work.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1998 Playboy magazine article, Hefner quoted one early
Playboy writer, Burt Zollo, who accepted 100 shares of stock, as
saying, ``I sold it the first day it was traded and became a
millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Weber, the editor in chief of The Industry Standard, a
magazine focusing on Internet commerce and culture, said he
believed the phenomenon of options payments would not last. ``I
would be surprised if it were the beginning of a trend,'' he said.
``It's very much driven by the current hype about options.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who are not there when the options are passed out, he
added, may not be missing much. ``Most people who get stock options
do not get rich,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Kansas, editor of TheStreet.com _ in which the New York
Times Co. has a minority stake _ offered options to some key
freelance contributors earlier this year, before The Street.com
made its initial public offering in May. ``It's a good way to
reward important contributors and it's a good way to make sure they
stick with you over the longer term,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hagen, the chief financial officer at Salon, said that most of
the options offered its writers vest _ meaning that the freelancers
gain legal title to the options _ in stages over a four-year
period, beginning one year after the initial offering last June.
The stock is currently trading at $6.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lewis, a contributor to several magazines, including The
New York Times Magazine, has written about his decision to turn
down The Street.com's offer of a 2.5 percent stake a few years ago
in return for writing a weekly column.
</P>
<P>
   The illogical speculation in Internet stocks has created its own
logic, at least temporarily, Lewis said in an interview. ``For this
brief moment, perceptions are creating their own reality,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Griscom is only too happy to peddle his perceptions. ``Everyone
knows people are making a huge amount of money off these Internet
companies and they want to participate in that,'' he said. He
added, ``The only way we can make a more generous offer than a New
Yorker or a Vanity Fair is to offer fat stock options packages.''
</P>
<P>
   Will it all last? Lewis said he doubted it. ``There will be
astonishing aspects of capitalism in the near future,'' he said.
``But this particular astonishing aspect won't last. I don't think
it's sustainable for journalists to become millionaires, unless
they cease to be journalists. I don't think they are that valuable
economically. Culturally they're valuable, but not economically.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-19-99 1721EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 1200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
