<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECHNOBUDDY21-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
It's not difficult to check out a PC's Y2K readiness 
By Bill Husted  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Last week, I put the Y2K problem into perspective.
</P>
<P>
   I spent an entire week of vacation stripping wallpaper and
painting a bathroom, then _ in the process of moving a toilet so I
could paint behind it _ having water cascade through the floor into
the room below. After fixing all this, I decided that no matter how
bad Y2K problems get for the home PC user, they will never be as
severe as a leaky toilet.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I'll end up being wrong as far as how bad things will be
for business and government computer networks; after all, not even
the experts can agree on that. But I'm pretty sure that when it
comes to the home user, there isn't much to worry about. What few
problems there are can be fixed easily.
</P>
<P>
   We'll start with changing a setting in Windows that keeps your
computer from getting confused about the date when the year 2000
comes.
</P>
<P>
   Go to the Start button and select Settings. Then select Control
Panel and double-click to open the icon called Regional Settings.
Select the tab at the top that says Date. Change the setting for
Short Date Style (using the arrow at the right) so that it reads:
MM/dd/yyyy. That forces Windows to use four digits for the year (as
in 2001), compared with the two-digit style (which is the way
Windows normally handles year dates).
</P>
<P>
   The next thing to do is check to see how well your computer and
its software are prepared to handle other Year 2000 problems.
You'll hear a lot of dumb advice about how to do this, including
setting your computer's date ahead _ tricking it into thinking that
it is already the new century _ and then seeing what, if anything,
goes wrong. Don't do that.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, go to a Web site maintained by a company called NSTL
where you'll get some testing advice, including the statement that
``improper testing can be disastrous.'' At this site _ located at
www.nstl.com/html/nstly2k.htmlY(at)Kcheck _ you'll be able to
download software programs (at no cost) that will check your
computer without doing any harm. The NSTL is a good outfit and does
a lot of work for government and business testing software and
hardware, so you can trust it. Using the program is easy, by the
way: You simply download it, double-click to start it up and follow
the on-screen directions.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on what the test reveals, you are almost done. But
there are still a few other things to do. One of the biggest Y2K
problems facing the home user is caused by older software programs
that weren't created with the year 2000 in mind.
</P>
<P>
   You can usually narrow the list of programs to worry about to
those where knowing the correct year is important. For instance,
you certainly will want to make sure that your money management
software, spreadsheets, databases and even word processor are
Y2K-compliant.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to find out is to go to the Web site of the
manufacturer of each program. If you don't know the address of the
Web site or can't find it in the manual, just use a Web search
engine such as AltaVista or Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   Once you are at the Web site, you'll almost certainly find
information about which versions of the software have Y2K problems.
(You can usually find the version number of a program by checking
under the Help menu for that program and selecting the item called
``About.'')
</P>
<P>
   If you're lucky, the Web site will tell you how to fix any Y2K
problems, or it may even have a free ``bug fix'' program that you
can download to automate the process of updating your program. For
really old programs, you may have to buy a new version.
</P>
<P>
   Now you've done the reasonable and practical things to prepare
your PC for the year 2000. Sure, there's more that you could do,
but these steps should be plenty for the average home user. Now you
can spend your time worrying about important stuff like leaky
toilets.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
