 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Site satirizes Mississippi's mobile homes 
By Mark Clothier  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Every state has at least one whipping boy, a
neighboring state that serves as the butt of jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Regions, too, have similar setups: West Virginia, for example,
is the home state for the subject of several jokes told in the
Mid-Atlantic region.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps one state above all serves as the punch line for an
entire nation: Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Architecture, too, has its hierarchy. Mobile homes sit _ on
cinder blocks, no doubt _ near the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Mobile Homes of Mississippi, www.kelleys.org/mhomes/,
is the Web site where the twain shall meet.
</P>
<P>
   As the introduction states, ``When you think of Mississippi,
what comes to mind? Illiteracy? Sweltering heat? Bigotry? Velvet
Elvis? These are all valid responses. However, we must remember
what Mississippi gives to the world of architecture. The mobile
home is an icon in every Mississippi town with as much symbolism as
the second-place trophy (the Civil War memorial) adorning every
Mississippi town square.''
</P>
<P>
   The site includes, as one would imagine, irate letters from
offended readers. It also includes a gift shop and a group of
photos of trailers from one town, Columbus, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   The photos show potentially mobile homes, trash-strewn yards and
rusting cars on cinder blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Author Doug Kelley provides a bit of commentary under each
photo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important to have a mobile-home owner's association
when selecting a neighborhood (a k a trailer park). Otherwise you
can have neighbors like this one who park their cars on the
driveway rather than on the yard. Also, note the dual air
conditioning units. Getting a little uppity, aren't we???''
</P>
<P>
   Kelley, a former Mississippi resident now living in Washington,
insists the site is not a digital ax grind against poor people. In
the question-and-answer section of the site, he addresses one
question that was asked, ``How can you make fun of poor people?''
</P>
<P>
   Kelley's reply:
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor people!? ... I'm making fun of slobs.''
</P>
<P>
   A wide-ranging money site
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of money management sites on the Web, but the
folks at Microsoft have done such a good job of making co-founder
Bill Gates a multi-multibillionaire that moneycentral
</P>
<P>
   .msn.com is worth a look.
</P>
<P>
   The site includes columns on a range of issues, including family
finance, retirement and tuition planning, mutual funds, taxes and
investing.
</P>
<P>
   New features include links to financial advisers; news updates
from The Wall Street Journal, Reuters and MSNBC; the ability to pay
some bills online; 401(k) information; and college planning tools.
</P>
<P>
   The site also includes Microsoft Passport, a service designed to
let people reach several Web accounts through one password. The
feature is expected _ keep in mind this is Microsoft we're talking
about _ to be available this fall.
</P>
<P>
   A four-letter word meaning `aid'
</P>
<P>
   The line of communication for crossword puzzle help runs
something like this: Ask your spouse/parent/roommate or look it up
in a dictionary. Now you can check the Web.
</P>
<P>
   One site, www.oneacross.com, is an online version of a crossword
puzzle dictionary. To find an answer, type the clue or phrase and
the number of space blocks. The site provides possible answers.
</P>
<P>
   The site also includes links to almanacs, online crossword
puzzles and a crossword dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
