 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Sega Dreamcast in fast lane 
By James Cummings  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Joe Sampson, 17, deftly nudges a directional
control with his thumb, and the blond warrior goddess on the
television screen in front of him moves in on her barbarian
opponent with a high-pitched battle cry, swinging her magic sword
that separates into linked sections that snap like a whip.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has the coolest weapon in the game,'' says Sampson.
</P>
<P>
   The goddess dances around the barbarian delivering kicks and
sword blows, her breath coming in clouds of white smoke as she
grunts and gasps in the cold mountain air.
</P>
<P>
   Finally Sampson has his minion leap in and grab the barbarian
for a judo flip that sends him flailing off the edge of the battle
platform.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most of the people who rushed out and bought a Sega
Dreamcast when the next-generation game system went on sale Sept.
9, Sampson of Newberry Twp. imported a system from Japan and has
been playing since July. So he's had time to sharpen his skills at
several Dreamcast games.
</P>
<P>
   And this fan, who owns every game system Sega ever made, says
Dreamcast is clearly the best system available to home gamers _
ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's a lot smoother; the characters move more
realistically,'' Sampson said. ``The characters and the backgrounds
are more detailed and three-dimensional. And the games are fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Retailers said many customers shared Sampson's enthusiasm the
first few days Dreamcast was available, and sales of the $199
systems were brisk. By the end of the first week after release many
stores were unable to keep the game system in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Donna DeGroat, who works in the electronics section at the Toys
R Us store near the Dayton Mall, said 64 customers ordered
Dreamcast in advance at her store, and another 20 bought games off
the shelf in the first two days it was available.
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT DREAMCAST
</P>
<P>
   What it is...
</P>
<P>
   Sega Dreamcast plays games on discs that look like CDs, but the
discs hold more information than traditional CD-ROMs.
</P>
<P>
   The system has built-in expansion ports for future upgrades. It
starts with 24 megabytes of memory to handle complex interactive
games with rich, detailed backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   The game system is based on a 200 MHz Hitachi SH-4 central
processing unit and the NEC PowerVR 2DC 3D graphics chip, which
Sega says is the most powerful 3D technology ever developed for a
console system.
</P>
<P>
   The Hitachi SH-4 gives the Sega Dreamcast 15 times the power of
a Sony PlayStation, 10 times the power of a Nintendo 64 and four
times the graphics processing power of the fastest Pentium II
processor, the company claims.
</P>
<P>
   The game has ports for four controllers to allow four players at
once. The system comes with one controller, and additional units
can be bought for $29.99.
</P>
<P>
   Dreamcast has a built-in 56k modem for online play, but the
online system is still being developed. Keyboards are available for
$24.99 for Web browsing.
</P>
<P>
   The Visual Memory Unit accessory sells for about $25, and it
offers a liquid crystal display screen that lets users play
separate games with just the memory unit. The screen also allows
secret play calling in sports games, while other game systems may
require players to make their choices on the television screen
where their opponents can see them.
</P>
<P>
   The Jump Pack will add jolts and vibrations synchronized to
onscreen game action.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the wings is the Dreamcast Fishing Controller. The
Fishing Controller will offer realistic casting and reeling action
along with motion generators that mimic the feel of a fish taking
the bait. It should turn up in stores next month when the Sega Bass
Fishing game premieres.
</P>
<P>
   Sega promises 28 games by year's end, and most local retailers
currently carry 10 to 20. Some titles may be sold out by now in
most locations.
</P>
<P>
   Titles cross all the popular game genres including:
</P>
<P>
   _ Hydro Thunder, $49.99: A boat racing game where players can
choose any of 13 high-performance boats to race on 11
three-dimensional tracks. Based on a popular arcade game, Hydro
Thunder boat jump over ramps and do loops through twisting tracks
similar to bobsled runs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ready 2 Rumble Boxing, $49.99: Boxing announcer Michael
Buffer's voice screams ``Let's get ready to rumble!'' as 16 bizarre
fighters go head-to-head. Sega promises ``You can watch your
opponent's face contort with pain and swell with contusions.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Airforce Delta, $49.99: A combat flying game in which players
become airborne mercenaries. Do well in a mission and you earn
enough money to buy more than 30 different international aircraft
to get the job done.
</P>
<P>
   _ NFL Blitz 2000, $49.99: Another version of an arcade game.
Players _ four can play at once _ call plays and control realistic
players on the field. The players on the field have set
characteristics of speed, strength and agility, but individual
players can ``get hot'' and perform above their normal abilities.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-20-99 1104EDT &QL;
</P>
