 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Reviews mixed for upgrade of QuickTime multimedia player 
By Charles Haddad  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Apple recently released a major update of its popular
multimedia player QuickTime. The software, version 4.0, has
received mixed reviews from leading Mac sources such as magazines
MacWorld and MacAddict.
</P>
<P>
   Both applauded QuickTime's added functions but decried the look
of it. To quote the MacWorld reviewer, ``QuickTime Player is an
interface-design disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   QuickTime comes in two parts, one free and the other a $30
version that includes multimedia authoring features. The free
piece, called QuickTime Player, lets users play video and audio
clips.
</P>
<P>
   First, let's look at what reviewers like about QuickTime.
Everyone is raving about the ease with which you can download the
software from Apple's Web site. The minimal installation requires 2
megabytes. You can get additional features through an updating
utility that's part of the free software. But adding features
greatly increases QuickTime's size, which tops out at 7 megabytes.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewers also liked the addition of true streaming
capabilities. This is technology that lets you watch, say, a news
broadcast or hear a radio station in real time over the Internet.
Streaming is a feature that has been part of RealNetworks' and
Microsoft's Windows Media products for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there isn't much available to watch or listen to
yet with QuickTime 4.0. That should change over time, because
QuickTime is a prominent player in the multimedia market.
</P>
<P>
   QuickTime 4.0 also adds the ability to listen to MP3 files,
which have become the standard for storing and distributing popular
music across the Internet. But, unlike its competitors, QuickTime
doesn't include the ability to support playlists. Nor does it play
all types of MP3 files.
</P>
<P>
   QuickTime 4.0 does, however, include some new, needed controls.
There's a panel of buttons, accessible through the press of an
icon, to control bass and treble like a CD player.
</P>
<P>
   What reviewers didn't like was the brushed aluminum look of
QuickTime and its set of controls. They said the bright finish
makes small movies appear too dark. They said the new favorites
drawer, where you can store bookmarks of favorite streaming sites,
was poorly designed.
</P>
<P>
   You can see what all the fuss is about for yourself. QuickTime
is easily downloaded from Apple's home page. The address is
www.apple.com/quicktime/.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-20-99 1104EDT &QL;
</P>
