 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Looking at this century on Web 
By Frances Katz  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the late 1970s, the punk-rock group the Ramones had
a minor hit called ``End of the Century.''
</P>
<P>
   The song seemed a bit extreme then, about 20 years before
millennium madness would grip the world with a blend of panic and
nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us came into the century and millennium late in the
game. We missed a lot of history, people and events. While waiting
for the dawn of the new century, why not take a look at the last
hundred or thousand years courtesy of that time machine on your
desk _ a computer connected to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't got the time or the attention span to review
every significant historical blip over the last thousand years,
Britain's Guardian newspaper is a quick way to brush up in a hurry
without breaking a sweat. The Guardian is slicing its way through
the millennium in short order with a site called ``1,000 Years in
500 Days'' (www.newsunlimited.co.uk).
</P>
<P>
   The countdown has begun, so if you bookmark the site now, you'll
have missed 400 days or so, but it's still worth a visit. The focus
is on British history, with a nod to Europe and those upstart
Americans. But there are also links to popular fashions,
philosophers and politicians through the years.
</P>
<P>
   Another quick fix is provided by Time magazine, which has
compiled the Time 100. The project (www.pathfinder.com
</P>
<P>
   /time/time100/index.html) started in March 1998 and is divided
into easy-to-swallow sections such as Leaders and Revolutionaries,
Artists and Entertainers, Builders and Titans, Scientists and
Thinkers, and Heroes and Icons.
</P>
<P>
   Time will cap off the list by naming its Person of the Century
in December. It also invites readers to vote for the bests and
worsts _ something the print edition never does.
</P>
<P>
   Especially fun is the section that asks you to vote for the
worst ideas of the century. Oh my! So many choices! Everything from
``The Jerry Springer Show'' to the Titanic, New Coke and baseball's
designated hitter rule. This site is great fun, and you may learn a
little something, too. Vote early and often. It's your century,
too, you know.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times on the Web has always been known for
outstanding specials, and its six special editions focusing on the
millennium are both beautiful to look at and amazingly
comprehensive, with audio, video and interactive polls and chats.
</P>
<P>
   The first special, called simply ``The Best,'' includes articles
from literary luminaries such as Joyce Carol Oates, Wendy
Wasserstein, Scott Turow and Umberto Eco.
</P>
<P>
   The second installment focuses on contributions made by women in
the last thousand years. It's called ``Women: The Shadow Story of
the Millennium'' (www
</P>
<P>
   .nytimes.com/library
</P>
<P>
   /magazine/millennium/m2
</P>
<P>
   /index.html). There are articles on everything from the struggle
of China's women to Deborah Tannen on communication between the
sexes.
</P>
<P>
   The third installment focuses on centuries of exploration and
man's need to venture into the unknown. It's beautifully designed,
and the topics are well thought out and offbeat enough to hold the
attention of readers with almost no interest in world history but
who love any kind of well-told story. The Times plans several more
millennium specials, which should be worth waiting for.
</P>
<P>
   One good reason to download and install the RealAudio player is
to listen to, rather than read, some of this century's great
speeches _ from Winston Churchill to the Rev. Martin Luther King
Jr. to the infamous ``Wear Sunscreen'' essay written by a Chicago
Tribune writer that was splashed over the Internet as Kurt
Vonnegut's MIT commencement address several years ago (he wasn't
there and never gave it).
</P>
<P>
   Still, the speeches, brought to the Web by Elycia's Real Audio
and the Minnesota Law Network (www.chicago-law.net
</P>
<P>
   /speeches/speech.html) take advantage of the Web to bring a
little bit of history to life.
</P>
<P>
   As the phone company used to say, it's the next best thing to
being there.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-20-99 1104EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 1207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
