<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 12:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1453 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w BC-IMMIGRATION-CHILDREN-     09-22 1300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRATION-CHILDREN-$ADV26-CO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LAWYERS NOT PROVIDED FOR YOUNG ASYLUM-SEEKERS
 &HT;    670&AMP;add. For release Sunday, Sept. 26
 &HT;    By SUSAN E. SMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hundreds of children who illegally enter the United
States by themselves each year are deported without the benefit of
legal counsel, immigration officials and human rights groups say.
</P>
<P>
   American children in the judicial system have court-appointed
attorneys, but the Immigration and Naturalization Service is not
required to provide free legal representation to these
unaccompanied children.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the children, who come from nations as different as
Honduras and China, are returned to countries that are plagued by
violence and poverty.
</P>
<P>
   As more children become the victims of violence and regional
wars, human rights groups and lawyers are seeking to change the
law.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no other area of law where children are expected to
answer charges, appear before a judge and prosecutors and represent
themselves without the benefit of an appointed counsel,'' said
Steve Lang, coordinator and attorney for the South Texas Pro Bono
Asylum Representation Project, or ProBAR.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than 11 percent of adult detainees receive legal
representation during asylum proceedings, said Wendy Young, author
of a widely cited study on children and U.S. asylum practices. She
estimates that the figure is significantly less for unaccompanied
children.
</P>
<P>
   INS officials could not say how many of the unaccompanied
children receive legal representation or are eventually granted
asylum.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. law does not require that illegal immigrants receive free
legal representation. However, children are given a list of pro
bono attorneys when they are apprehended by the agency, said John
Pogash, national juvenile coordinator for the INS.
</P>
<P>
   To be granted asylum, a person must demonstrate political
persecution, which sounds simple but is as confounding as
navigating the tax code, immigration lawyers say. Federal law,
which mirrors the United Nations Convention on Refugees, states
that a person must prove persecution based on race, religion,
national origin, political belief or association with a group.
</P>
<P>
   With children, that's particularly difficult to prove because
they are too young to comprehend their circumstances, let alone
explain them to others, said Young, a staff attorney and Washington
liaison for the Women's Commission for Refugee Women and Children.
</P>
<P>
   Lang, whose office is in Harlingen, Texas, divides the children
who enter the country alone into three categories: those who want
to return home right away, those who have families in the United
States, and those who could seek asylum on their own. Pro bono
attorneys target the latter group.
</P>
<P>
   The push for legal counsel for young asylum seekers comes at a
time when Congress is preparing to debate new immigration bills. A
bill has yet to be introduced that requires legal counsel for
children who enter the United States illegally, but congressional
staffers say the issue is being discussed by some lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say U.S. tax dollars should not be used to help these
young illegal immigrants and that too little information exists
about the problem to start discussing solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``To ask taxpayers to be funding a blank check is a pretty
radical departure (from current immigration policy) and potentially
very expensive for something that may be helping organized criminal
activities,'' said Dan Stein, executive director of the Federation
for American Immigration Reform. Some of the children could be used
by adults as drug couriers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 5,300 children illegally entered the United States
last year, according to INS records. More than 1,300 of the
children were detained for an average of 32 days in shelters and
juvenile detention centers, a practice Young and others criticize.
A majority of those in custody, usually teenaged boys, entered the
country alone.
</P>
<P>
   Children in INS custody are placed either in shelters, foster
homes or juvenile correctional facilities, many of which are in
states along the Mexican border, until their cases are settled.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The Women's Commission for Refugee Women and Children helped the
INS develop new guidelines for the treatment of children seeking
asylum. The issue is increasingly important to immigration reform
groups at a time when children are the majority of the world's
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 United Nations study found that in the prior decade war
and upheavals had killed 2 million children, disabled 4 million to
5 million and rendered homeless 12 million.
</P>
<P>
   Many children like Oscar, a 15-year-old Honduran, come to the
United States to flee street life. Oscar, an orphan, was routinely
beat up by gangs and police officers, according to lawyers who
represented him in asylum hearings.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, whose full name was withheld to protect his identity,
repeatedly fled foster homes and shelters before the INS sent him
to juvenile detention centers in Liberty County, Texas, and San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   He recently received asylum and soon could be adopted by a Texas
family, ending his 18-month odyssey in the U.S. immigration system.
</P>
<P>
   His happy ending is the exception to the rule, say advocates.
Few children who enter this country alone are granted asylum, and
few are adopted, they say. Here, too, the numbers are unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 16,975 people who were granted asylum this year, 2,735
were children, according to the INS. The agency couldn't say how
many of the children who received the asylum entered the United
States alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legal representation (for asylum seekers) is a big growth
industry because of the people on the move,'' said Stein. ``It's
straining the (American Bar Association's) resources and
capacity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a move on the part of activists to expand the
(asylum) process, but we can't provide refugee status for everyone
who is fleeing random political violence,'' argued Stein, who said
he understands concerns about the children's well-being.
</P>
<P>
   When a child is denied asylum, the INS contacts his or her
embassy or consulate, which arranges to repatriate the child.
</P>
<P>
   Although most agree the larger issue is securing legal counsel
for the children, human rights groups also want the INS to stop
holding youth in juvenile detention centers. In many cases,
innocent children share facilities with American children who have
committed violent crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this kid has suffered in any way, then you are taking the
very victim of persecution and punishing them further by detaining
them with criminals,'' said Lang of ProBAR.
</P>
<P>
   The only children routinely placed in such facilities are those
who might flee or who exhibit behavioral problems, INS officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the children are placed in the juvenile facilities
when there is nowhere else for them to go, Pogash explained.
</P>
<P>
   The larger issue, say advocates for immigration reform, is the
need for asylum policies to incorporate new forms of persecution
aimed at children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those that inflict human rights abuse have realized that
inflicting abuses on children is an effective way to get at the
whole family,'' said Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making sure that legal counsel is in place is one way to
ensure our jurisprudence (in cases involving children) evolves
appropriately,'' said Young.
</P>
<P>
   But Stein said more information should be gathered on the
children before pushing for a change in the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The operations of the INS are deplorable, and we all know
it,'' he said. ``But it's not prudent to make policy based on the
scanty information we have.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
