<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 12:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1455 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS23-COX     09-22 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini audio reviews
 &HT;    By Eileen Drennen, Sonia Murray and Richard L. Eldredge
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Breakfast in New Orleans,
</P>
<P>
   Dinner in Timbuktu''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Cockburn. Rykodisc. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Like a wandering poet, Canadian singer-songwriter Bruce Cockburn
collects pictures, couching his sense of existential mystery in the
concrete. A ceiling fan becomes a mandala, hope a flame, and a
mango much more than mere fruit. Since the power of love colors
every guitar-ringing number, whether Middle Eastern acoustic or
Delta-fied electric, it makes sense to underpin these soul-stirring
songs with a woman's voice. Lucinda Williams' bluesy harmonies
enrich nearly half, her warm whispers a grounding for his coolest
abstractions. Though vocalists Margo Timmins and Jonell Mosser do
backup too, Cockburn's pairings with Williams, especially the
lovely rooftop still-life ``Look How Far the Light Came,'' are
best. His arpeggiated guitar sounds like the sun's waning rays,
streaming through a jewel-like glass of wine; gold and pink merging
the way their soaring voices do: pop music in the service of art.
</P>
<P>
   _Eileen M. Drennen
</P>
<P>
   RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``Crow's Nest''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Crow. Noontime/Sony. 15 tracks. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   It says a lot about race relations in the '90s when a group of
young Southern black men can call themselves Jim Crow. In short,
it's a signal that the Atlanta rap trio embraces its home in its
shiny and shameful entirety. For further explanation spend some
time in the ``Crow's Nest,'' a debut outstanding in its near
sample-free production and well-rounded in its storytelling. Be
warned, the cringe factor is as prominent as its melodic tales of
``frapping'' (sex) and ``baby mama drama'' are frequent. But so is
the sincerity when it takes all of that into consideration: ``I try
to tighten up,'' goes ``One of These Days, ``but dollar signs keep
lighting up in front of my face / And I can taste it / So I'm on
this paper chase / Wastin' my precious time / Trying to pace my
grind / Unaware of the finish line/ (Expletive) dying.''
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   JAZZ
</P>
<P>
   ``It's All About Love''
</P>
<P>
   Carla Cook. MaxJazz. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   If the listener is broad-minded enough, vocalist Carla Cook's
MaxJazz debut yields many riches. Finicky straight-ahead jazz
purists or folks expecting strictly a Dianne Reeves-inspired
jazz-infused brew of steaming R&AMP;B will likely be dismayed. As Cook
herself explains in the liner notes, ``I listen to the masters, and
that can mean Miles (Davis) or Chaka Khan.'' What makes ``It's All
About Love'' such a pleasant surprise is that like Davis and Khan,
Cook's exquisitely supple instrument can tackle either genre with
complete ease. At points, Cook's elasticity is reminiscent of Al
Jarreau. Accompanied only by bassist Darryl Hall on the first verse
of ``The Way You Look Tonight,'' Cook comes off as a shy
seductress. By the time the rest of the trio joins in, she's kicked
off her high heels vocally, dimmed the lights and cracked open the
champagne. The outing features fine support by pianist Cyrus
Chestnut, Hall and drummer Billy Kilson. As evidenced by the
life-affirming lyrics and groove of the title track, Cook can
write, too.
</P>
<P>
   _Richard L. Eldredge
</P>
<P>
   Eileen Drennen, Sonia Murray and Richard L. Eldredge write for
the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
