<HEADER>
A1457 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE23-COX     09-22 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Slow food: Take time to smell the pot roast
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twentieth century scientific and technological advancements have
made lots of things more accessible, faster and convenient for more
people, but there is a high price to pay. As we have come to expect
instant gratification and instant responses, any sort of delay sets
us on edge. We have become desensitized and impatient with the time
taken to accomplish some of the simple processes of life.
</P>
<P>
   Resisting this trend in a quiet, civilized way is a group called
Slow Food, an international movement that believes the first
defense against the dehumanizing frenzy of modern life begins by
rediscovering the convivial joy of the table.
</P>
<P>
   Begun in 1989 in Italy as a response to a fast food franchise
opening on an ancient piazza in Rome, the movement now has about
60,000 members in 35 countries. Local branches called Convivia
exist in 21 cities across the United States; the groups meet
regularly to prepare and immerse themselves in long, leisurely
meals.
</P>
<P>
   The microwave is anathema to the Slow Food philosophy, which
actively opposes the ``nuke it and eat it'' way of life. They
believe that the patient preparation of a meal _ the careful
chopping, the slow stirring, the mixing, the blending of
ingredients _ is a form of meditation that fosters concentration
and patience.
</P>
<P>
   But there is more to Slow Food than just preparing and enjoying
wonderful food. The group is concerned that the fast food culture
and multinational food conglomerates are eroding the world's
culinary and cultural heritage. Indeed, we have in our midst an
entire generation of young people whose palates respond only to Big
Macs and fries. Further, more and more indigenous foods have
disappeared and been replaced with often tasteless, scientifically
engineered varieties in the name of convenience and low cost.
</P>
<P>
   Slow Food is out to buck this trend by sponsoring a variety of
events designed to educate and enlighten people as to what is at
stake and inspire people to reclaim their culinary heritage.
</P>
<P>
   The organization vigorously supports farmers and food artisans
who grow and use heirloom foods despite the economic hardships
involved. They organize food tastings, cooking classes, trips, and,
yes, some memorable eating experiences. A recent event sponsored by
a New York convivia re-created the family dinner from Thomas Mann's
novel ``Buddenbrooks.''
</P>
<P>
   RELATED SITES
</P>
<P>
   If you are interested in finding out more about the effects of
fast food on our culture, the Internet has many insightful and
interesting sites.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For a sensible, balanced look at the nutritional aspects of
fast food see
www.ag.state.mn.us/home/consumer/health/fastfoodfacts.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you prefer, shall we say, a more activist approach with
regard to fast food and society, see www.mcspotlight.org/help.html.
With 21,000 files it bills itself as ``the biggest, loudest, most
read anti-McDonald's extravaganza the world has ever seen.'' They
also say, ``Don't get us wrong, though, we're not telling you to
give up your Big Macs. We just provide the info for you to judge
for yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For an overview of the legal battle between McDonald's and the
environmental group Greenpeace, see www.lbbs.org/zmag/articles
</P>
<P>
   /kovelsept97.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A more scholastic approach can be found at the Sociology
Corner, at www.sociology.net
</P>
<P>
   /mcdonald, which provides an overview of the book ``The
McDonaldization of Society'' by George Ritzer.
</P>
<P>
   SLOW FOOD SITES
</P>
<P>
   To find out more about Slow Food, visit its site at
www.slowfood.com. You can learn about how to set up a local
convivia. Find out about events, workshops and trips and subscribe
to the magazine ``Slow.'' You will also find some terrific recipes
and thought-provoking articles on this quiet revolution.
</P>
<P>
   For an idea of what the various convivia are doing, search out
``slow food'' and find many home pages of convivia around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to try to slow down your culinary pace at least part
of the time, here are some slow food sites to check:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The quintessential slow food meal is a roast. See ``A Toast to
the Roast'' at http://homearts.com
</P>
<P>
   /gh/food/c7roasf2.htm for mouthwatering recipes for a variety of
roasts, side dishes and suggested wines.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For lists and lists of home-style slow-cooked crockpot
recipes, see pages.ivillage.com/misc
</P>
<P>
   /momof3add/crockpot.html and southernfood
</P>
<P>
   .miningco.com/library/crock/blcpidx.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Cooking in Crocks, Pots and Clay'' is a good introduction to
various methods of slow cooking and includes recipes at
www.foodwine.com/food
</P>
<P>
   /egg/egg0396/earthfod.html.
</P>
<P>
   Bavarian Pot Roast
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings Preparation time: 10 minutes Cooking time: 8-12
hours
</P>
<P>
   Pot roast, the ultimate slow food, can simmer all day in a
crockpot. This one's subtle cloves, ginger and apple juice provide
a hint of Bavaria that's especially welcome on a fall day.
</P>
<P>
   3- to 4-pound beef arm or chuck pot roast
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   3 whole cloves
</P>
<P>
   4 medium apples, cored and quartered (leave skin on)
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup apple juice
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   Wipe roast well and trim off all excess fat. Lightly rub top of
meat with oil. Dust meat with salt, pepper and ginger. Insert
cloves into meat. Place apples and onions in bottom of crockpot.
Put roast on top of the apples and onions. Pour in the apple juice.
Cover and cook on a low setting for 8 to 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the roast and apples to a warm platter when fully cooked.
Pour the liquid out of the crockpot into a saucepan. Drain off as
much of the fat as you can. Make a smooth paste with the flour and
water and stir the paste into the liquid. Cook over medium heat
until thickened, 5 to 10 minutes. Serve gravy alongside the sliced
roast, apples and onions.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 491 calories, 36 grams protein, 31 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 57), 15 grams carbohydrates, 126
milligrams cholesterol, 522 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
