<HEADER>
A1458 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP23-COX     09-22 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A heavenly taste of the islands
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Shirley Barker of Morrow (Ga.) lost her recipe for a
favorite Hawaiian Banana Bread that was moist and is greatly
missed.
</P>
<P>
   Her request resulted in a handful of possibilities, including
the two tested here. The first is baked in a flat pan and includes
coconut, which Barker does not remember from her earlier recipe.
The second is baked in loaf pans and is denser and moister,
according to our tester, who liked both but preferred the loaf
version.
</P>
<P>
   Hawaiian Banana Bread
</P>
<P>
   Makes 20 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 12 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 40-45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly love it,'' Lee Merritt said of this banana bread
recipe, sent to her several years ago by her niece Julie Wilkes.
</P>
<P>
   1 3/4 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 (8-ounce) can crushed pineapple, drained
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup coconut flakes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup (about 3) mashed bananas
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Grease and flour a 9-by-13-inch pan
and set aside. In a large bowl, combine the flour, baking soda,
salt, sugar and pecans. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a large mixing bowl, combine the beaten eggs, oil, vanilla,
pineapple, coconut and bananas. Add the dry mixture and mix
together by hand until just incorporated. Pour into prepared pan
and bake 40 to 45 minutes or until lightly browned and tests done.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 287 calories, 3 grams protein, 16 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 51), 34 grams carbohydrates, 32
milligrams cholesterol, 170 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Hawaiian Banana Nut
</P>
<P>
   Bread
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 loaves, 16 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 50-55 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This version comes from Mary Beth Janda of Woodstock (Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   3 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped nuts
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cups mashed ripe bananas
</P>
<P>
   1 (8-ounce) can crushed pineapple, drained
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. In a large mixing bowl, combine
flour, sugar, baking soda, salt, cinnamon and nuts. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In another bowl, combine eggs, oil, bananas, pineapple and
vanilla. Add to dry ingredients and stir just until moistened.
Grease and flour two 9-by-5-by-3-inch loaf pans. Spoon batter
evenly into pans. Bake 50 to 55 minutes, or until done. Cool 10
minutes before removing from pans. Remove to wire racks to cool
completely.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 457 calories, 5 grams protein, 27 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 51), 52 grams carbohydrates, 224
milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Recipe requests
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Debbie Erdmanczyk asks by e-mail for a cake made with apricot
nectar and a cake mix. She remembers her grandmother making it when
she was a child.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting the column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests for this column should be sent to
</P>
<P>
   Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Include a daytime telephone
number.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
