<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 12:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1459 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN     09-22 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Searching for the best of the Octoberfest brews
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's no telling how many hogs and chickens have
donated their ribs and rumps, knuckles and drumsticks to the cause,
but Munich is merry with the spirit of Octoberfest, the 16-day,
end-of-summer festival that Americans must think is written into
the city charter.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, all of Bavaria is bursting with bonhomie. Fests of one
kind or another are in full swing, with some 5 million tourists and
locals filling beer halls and biergartens to eat, drink and be very
merry indeed. It's a historical footnote that Octoberfest was
conceived not as the world's largest beer party, but as a wedding
reception. In 1810, when Crown Prince Ludwig of Bavaria was married
to Queen Theresia, the groom's father invited the townsfolk to the
village green afterward for a big picnic, with food and beer on the
crown.
</P>
<P>
   The village green is now a fairgrounds, and on the first Sunday
of Octoberfest a parade makes its way there. The big brewers of
Munich _ classic names such as Paulaner, Spaten, Hacker-Pschorr,
Lowenbrau, Hofbrauhaus _ all take part, and over the next two weeks
their huge beer halls are packed.
</P>
<P>
   The beers of Octoberfest, deep bronze to amber in color and malt
accented, are twins to the Marzen beers brewed in March but enjoyed
in autumn. Munich restricts its party to the local breweries, but a
visitor can enjoy himself just as well by escaping to one of the
smaller towns nearby. One is Aying, where he could sup on dumplings
and sausages while sipping Octoberfest as brewed by one of the
world's great breweries, Ayinger.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that you pretty much have to be there _ in Munich
or the countryside _ to know the real taste of Octoberfest beer.
Even so, Octoberfests were showing up on shelves in Atlanta as
early as August, a domestic version from Samuel Adams leading the
way. The reasons have more to do with commerce than tradition.
</P>
<P>
   But these are beers _ lightly hopped, and complex in their malt
profile _ that don't travel well. We sampled six, five from Germany
plus the Sam Adams. Four of the five German Octoberfests were
oxidized to one degree or another. One of the imports, from Beck's,
was surprisingly fresh and produced an impressively creamy crown.
It just didn't have the malty character you expect of an
Octoberfest. But then, Beck's is brewed in the northwest German
city of Bremen and not in Bavaria.
</P>
<P>
   Impressions of the other five:
</P>
<P>
   Paulaner. Good, toasty malty flavor that hinted at what it must
taste like in Munich. Oxidized, but not so much that a glass
couldn't be enjoyed over German potato salad, bratwursts,
stone-ground mustard and pumpernickel. An entire six-pack (about
$7.98) would be an investment in disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Hacker-Pschorr ($6.98). Malt character slightly deeper than that
of the Paulaner, but also a step further along in oxidation.
</P>
<P>
   Beck's ($5.98). A little more body than either the Paulaner or
the Hacker-Pschorr, and clearly fresher. Beer to beer, Beck's is
not in a league with any of the Munich breweries, but its
Octoberfest this year is better than last year's. Whether it's in
the Marzen/Octoberfest style is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   Spaten Ur-Marzen ($6.98). A classic beer from the 14th-century
brewery whose name is associated with the development of lagering
methods and with the Marzen/Octoberfest style. A creamy white head,
with a firm body and rounded maltiness. But, sad to say, the
freshness was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Ayinger ($2.68 for 17-ounce bottle). Thick, rocky head over what
looks to be an unfiltered beer. A deeper malt profile and longer
finish than the Spaten. Drunk fresh, this might have been the best
of the lot.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Adams ($6.48). Not having spent time in the hold of a
ship, the Sam Adams was fresh and clean, and in many respects it
held its own. But the head receded quickly, and the malt character
seemed a bit thin.
</P>
<P>
   All of these beers are made to be enjoyed with the sweetness of
grilled meats, especially pork and chicken, the richness of
dumplings and German cheeses. Slightly spicy and mellow in the
mouth, they marry well with dishes that are in no way subtle but
are sumptuous as anything can be.
</P>
<P>
   PICK OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   In the countries of Northern Europe, a boy with white or very
blond hair is sometimes called a flaxhead. It is not a put-down. To
the contrary, a flaxhead is often a leader of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   But you see the word ``flax-head'' on the label of Vlaskop and
think something else _ at least I did. What do you know, I thought,
here's a beer with flax in the grist. Other brewers have added hemp
seeds, still others rye. A portion of oats gives some of the best
stouts their silky smoothness, and corn is a staple of many a
cheaply made lager, including Corona. The best-selling beer in the
world _ Budweiser _ uses rice.
</P>
<P>
   So why not flax?
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere someone's probably using a pinch, but Brewery Strubbe
of Belgium uses only barley, along with hops, yeast and water. By
``flaxhead,'' the Flanders brewers are referring to the beer's
color, a cloudy white-yellow that in certain light can even suggest
apple-green.
</P>
<P>
   Vlaskop is an unfiltered wheat-style ale without wheat, light in
body with almost a citrusy quality. It's hard to achieve such
lightness of body in a beer using only barley in the grist, but
Vlaskop would fool even an experienced beer judge. This is a summer
beer that doesn't call itself one, delightful year-round as an
aperitif, with salads or with white-meat fish.
</P>
<P>
   At $2.89 a bottle Vlaskop isn't cheap, but you don't judge
Belgian beers by six-pack prices any more than you judge them with
a six-pack palate.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
