<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-CORNELL23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In today's multi-genre music world, ex-Soundgarden singer Chris
Cornell proudly plays ...
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The word ``rock'' rarely stands alone anymore. In recent years,
the most revolutionary musical form of the 20th century has
shattered into a million subgenres, giving rise to such niche terms
as ``extreme rock'' (Korn, Limp Bizkit), ``jam-rock'' (Widespread
Panic, Dave Matthews), even ``post-rock'' (Tortoise, Gastr del
Sol).
</P>
<P>
   The first solo album by the ex-lead belter for deified grunge
group Soundgarden extols the virtues of that once-sufficient
monosyllabic label. ``Euphoria Morning'' defiantly treads rock's
vast, neglected middle ground between screechy noise merchants and
Top 40 pop jockeys.
</P>
<P>
   No hyphens need be used to describe its majestic guitar sound
and slowly building tempos or Cornell's magnificently arena-size
voice. Even the song titles speak to a simpler, more unified time _
would Limp Bizkit's Fred Durst ever sing a tune as dreamily
'70s-reverent as ``Moonchild''?
</P>
<P>
   The anthemic opener, ``Can't Change Me,'' builds on the
Beatles-inflected sonic boom of Soundgarden's own ``Black Hole
Sun.'' With more vocal economy than he ever exhibited with his
former band, Cornell sings about a man who refuses to give up his
old ways, no matter how limiting they may be.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have seen too many rock icons turn to techno, disco or
Top 40 R&AMP;B to salvage their careers will find Cornell's
stubbornness comforting. For keepers of rock's perilously
flickering flame, ``Euphoria Morning'' sounds like a new day
dawning.
</P>
<P>
   ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Euphoria Morning''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Cornell. A&AMP;M Records. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
