<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-COUNTRY23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McBride shows limited `Emotion'
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you get the feeling that country music is having an identity
crisis (i.e., crusty geezers Alabama singing with 'N Sync), this CD
from tiny powerhouse Martina McBride plops the genre down squarely
on the therapist's couch. Although her voice is one of the
strongest laying down tracks in any studio, McBride seems to have
set her sights on becoming Nashville's sunshine and lollipops gal
rather than a barroom queen. Although the Kansas songbird has shown
she can sing V-8 country (``Whatever You Say''), she's opted to hop
on Faith Hill's Top 40 joy ride with a set of tunes that are as
edgy as a VW Beetle.
</P>
<P>
   The breezy single ``I Love You'' is typical of the offerings
here, a slumber-party-perfect tune designed for little-girl
lip-sync (``Baybee, you're so cooool!''). One exception is the
Indigo Girlish ``Love's the Only House,'' a kind of out-of-place
'90s protest song about ghettos and guns laid over a Dylan
harmonica.
</P>
<P>
   While peers such as Jo Dee Messina and Lee Ann Womack prove that
there's still plenty of potential in earthy, dime-store country,
McBride is tossing out songs like samples at a Neiman Marcus
cosmetics counter. Maybe next time, she'll get back to basics.
</P>
<P>
   COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   ``Emotion''
</P>
<P>
   Martina McBride. RCA. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
