<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini views
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera, Steve Murray and Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Out-of-Towners'' (PG-13) _ It's a mess from the start.
The screenplay is based on the Neil Simon original 1970 film, but
it feels staler the second it starts to unreel. Henry (Steve
Martin) and Nancy Clark (Goldie Hawn) are a long-married couple
from Ohio trying to redefine their lives now that the children are
grown. They land in New York and high jinks ensue. The only time
the film hints at the madcap success it could be is when John
Cleese appears as the secretly cross-dressing hotel manager. Grade:
C+
</P>
<P>
   _Drew Jubera
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Ravenous'' (R) _ Robert Carlyle and Guy Pearce star in a
19th-century black comedy about cannibalism. Yep, you heard that
right. A strange mix of frontier humor and vampire tale, the movie
is energetically made and gleefully gross, but it outstays its
welcome. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Open Your Eyes'' (R) _ A jigsaw puzzle of a film blending
elements of paranoid thriller and romantic melodrama. Director and
co-writer Alejandro Amenabar wants to deliver a Hitchcockian
mystery in '90s clothes (there's even an explicit homage to a
famous scene in ``Vertigo''). For its first half, it's an
intriguing ride. But the movie starts to feel like a short story
that's been uncomfortably stretched to feature-length. In Spanish
with subtitles. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Joan of Arc'' (unrated) _ Leelee Sobieski glows. Even when
she's not being burned at the stake as Joan of Arc, even in the
midst of a battle scene bogged down in mud, the 16-year-old actress
(who strongly resembles a young Helen Hunt) is so radiant, so
utterly convinced and convincing, that you'll want to follow her
into battle
</P>
<P>
   just like legions of mud-spattered Frenchmen do repeatedly in
this made-for-TV miniseries. Priced to buy, $19.98. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Phil Kloer
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera, Steve Murray and Phil Kloer write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
