<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDOE-MATRIX23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Matrix' is technological thrill ride
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Matrix'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   A knockout sci-fi flick. Writer-directors Andy and Larry
Wachowski's surprise blockbuster turns out to be the year's best
blend of story, action and FX, easily beating out the noisy
kiddiefest called ``The Phantom Menace.'' The filmmaking brothers,
who first teamed for ``Bound,'' bring their sharp storytelling and
visual showmanship to an adventure starring Keanu Reeves that
should please both comic book fanatics and mainstream moviegoers _
at least those with attention spans resilient enough to follow the
twisty plot. Reeves plays a computer hacker nicknamed Neo who falls
in with a band of rebels in black leather (Laurence Fishburne and
Carrie-Anne Moss among them) who open his eyes to Balancing
intelligence. With stunning special effects and action, it's a
movie that earns its explosions, high kicks and cascades of spent
bullets. The VHS is priced for rental; DVD, $24.98. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
