<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT DID BILL BRADLEY THINK HE WAS ACCOMPLISHING?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom regarding the viability of Bill
Bradley's campaign for president seems to be changing by the day _
or maybe by the hour.
</P>
<P>
   When he first decided to challenge Vice President Al Gore for
the Democratic presidential nomination, Bradley's long-shot
campaign was widely derided as an exercise in futility. But as
Bradley quietly went about the business of raising money and
drumming up grassroots support, the perception that he was a
no-chance underdog began to change.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, the deep-thinkers were advising us to take Bradley
seriously, to consider the possibility that the former basketball
star might be tiptoeing toward a gigantic upset in this race that
so recently had been dismissed as no race at all.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for Bradley's success, some analysts said, was that
he was cleverly positioning himself slightly to the left of Gore in
hopes of appealing to liberal Democrats who are disenchanted with
what they see as the Clinton-Gore administration's pandering to the
center of the political spectrum. The trick for Bradley was to
energize liberals during the primary campaign without coming off as
a radical left-winger who would be unelectable in November.
</P>
<P>
   The plan seemed to be working perfectly until Bradley unveiled
two proposals: amending the 1964 Civil Rights Act to ban
discrimination against homosexuals, and changing military
regulations to allow gays to serve openly in the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   His plan to rewrite the Civil Rights Act moved Bradley so far
off the beaten path that he found himself out of step even with
ultra-liberals and gay-rights defenders such as Barney Frank, the
openly gay Massachusetts congressman. And Bradley's proposal on
overhauling the military's policy on homosexuals provoked
considerable criticism _ especially when he admitted that he hadn't
consulted with military leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Globe quoted Frank as saying that Bradley's plan to
add gay rights to the Civil Rights Act was ``well-intentioned but
very incorrect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I admire his instinct. ... But he is mistaken about the way to
do it. What Bill Bradley has proposed ignores the very careful
legislative work we've been doing. I wish he had checked with us,''
Frank said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Bradley's idea of doing away with ``don't ask, don't
tell'' and opening the military to gays, well, just ask Bill
Clinton what happens to politicians who make such promises without
checking with the generals. It was Clinton, in fact, who conjured
up ``don't ask, don't tell'' after his attempt to lift the
military's ban against gays was shot down by the brass.
</P>
<P>
   All this raises a question: What was Bradley trying to
accomplish with this pair of controversial and unachievable
proposals?
</P>
<P>
   Bradley had already set himself up as a leaning-to-the-left
alternative to Gore. There was no reason to risk branding himself
as a wild-eyed liberal bent on creating havoc with radical policies
that most voters would find unappealing if not thoroughly
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Bradley figured that he needed to shake things up, to
generate some interest in a race that so far has failed to capture
the public's attention. But it seems a little early for that sort
of desperation; the first primaries are still months away.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe Bradley's money machine has started to sputter and he
hoped to jingle the cash register with some contributions from
gay-rights activists. Wouldn't you think he'd have been better off
making some phone calls and sending out a few letters?
</P>
<P>
   In any case, there is some good news here _ for voters, if not
for Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Unless he radicalizes himself right out of the race, Bradley
still has a fighting chance to become the Democratic nominee. And
the more forthright he is about his liberalism, the easier it will
be for the voting public to distinguish his views from those of the
Republican nominee.
</P>
<P>
   The third-party crowd keeps complaining that Democrats and
Republicans are too much alike. If Bradley is the Democratic
candidate in 2000, that could change in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
