<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-LONG-TERM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK FOR INSPIRATION IN WORK AND BEYOND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the last couple of months, there is one
phrase that I find myself saying over and over again _ and it's not
``Don't we have any chocolate around here?'' Whether I'm sitting in
traffic or getting back from lunch or watching television, I'll
mutter to myself, ``God, I hate work.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong: As jobs go, mine's a good one, with generous
amounts of freedom and flexibility, decent pay and nice people to
work with. But that doesn't mean I can't develop an irrational
hatred of it every once in a while, even for a couple of months at
a time.
</P>
<P>
   Some career counselors would be aghast at all this, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Do what you love, they'd say. Follow your passion. Repeat
affirmations like ``My job is wonderful,'' ``I'm good at what I
do'' and ``Work gives my life purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Think of your career as running a marathon. It's challenging, it
demands a lot of energy and it can give you a terrific sense of
exhilaration and purpose, but it also seems to take forever, and
can leave you gasping for breath long before your 26 miles are up.
If you're not careful, it can even kill you.
</P>
<P>
   Career counselors are rarely marathon runners. They usually
start in one career, then decide after several years to become
counselors. Instead of running a 26-mile race, they choose two
13-mile races. That can be a terrific strategy, but it's not the
same thing as running a marathon.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose you're gasping for air at the 13-mile mark. You don't
hate your boss, your co-workers or your company, but that finish
line called retirement sure seems a long way away. Unless you see
another career out there that stirs your passion, how do you decide
whether to change to something else or keep running the marathon?
Look for a water station.
</P>
<P>
   Every few miles, most marathon runners grab a cup of water,
either for dousing or for drinking. It gives them strength to
continue the journey.
</P>
<P>
   When you're young and talented and in a decent company, your
career has plenty of water stations. A lot of things seem fresh and
interesting, your bosses offer encouragement and your pay raises
seem huge.
</P>
<P>
   But then the water stations start growing scarce. A lot of
things seem stale and boring, your bosses take you for granted and
your pay raises barely keep up with the cost of living _ if you're
lucky.
</P>
<P>
   It's tempting at this point to start jogging, moseying your way
toward the finish line. That's how people get laid off.
</P>
<P>
   Look instead for water stations from the rest of your life,
things that inspire you and give you energy. They can help you
decide whether you're just temporarily out of breath or are so
wiped out that you should stop and run a different race.
</P>
<P>
   You can draw energy from hobbies or spirituality or people you
see every day, like teachers and friends and family. Traveling
always inspires me, which is why I'm not too concerned about hating
work for the moment. When I know that a nice vacation is around the
corner, it keeps me from going around the bend.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the day-to-day stuff doesn't cut it, though, here are sources
of workplace inspiration:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Patch Adams.'' In the movie, based on a true story, Robin
Williams' character commits himself to a mental institution because
he's feeling suicidal. While he's there, he finds his purpose:
helping other patients.
</P>
<P>
   Adams goes on to become a doctor, making laughter a regular part
of his work. He doesn't buy the notion that doctors should maintain
a sense of detachment, or that medical insurance should set the
standard for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   He gets frustrated with the day-to-day garbage we all have to
put up with, but he never loses sight of the people he's helping _
and how the quality of his work can change their lives.
</P>
<P>
   _ The 1980 U.S. Olympic hockey team. Seeded seventh in an
eight-team field, back in the time of the Cold War and the Iranian
hostages, the team upset the powerful Soviet Union and went on to
win the gold medal. It may have been called the Miracle on Ice, but
it was the product of hard work and teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``For seven months they pushed each other on and pulled each
other along, from rung to rung, until for two weeks in February
they _ a bunch of unheralded amateurs _ became the best hockey team
in the world,'' E.M. Swift wrote when Sports Illustrated named the
team as Sportsmen of the Year. ``The best TEAM. The whole was
greater than the sum of its parts by a mile.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes teamwork shows you just how great you can be. For
those who don't have a long memory or a Y chromosome, the same sort
of thing happened on a smaller scale this year with the U.S.
Women's World Cup soccer team. They were an inspiration to us all.
</P>
<P>
   _ Richard Nelson Bolles. He is proof that sometimes the best
thing that can ever happen to you is to get laid off.
</P>
<P>
   Bolles had absolutely nothing to do with the career advice field
until he and some colleagues were getting laid off from church
jobs. He researched what they should do next and came up with
enough knowledge to write a book. ``What Color Is Your Parachute?''
has sold more than 6 million copies.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``A Chorus Line.'' The long-running Broadway musical had tons
of job-hunting inspiration, but two songs in particular stand out:
``Nothing'' and ``What I Did for Love.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing'' reminds us that even at a prestigious school, not
every teacher is a gem. The same thing is true at work: Even at a
Fortune 500 company, your boss can be a dolt.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have people at your company who inspire you? If the
answer is no, it means one of two things: You've lost interest in
your career or you've outgrown your company. Make sure you know
which it is before you abandon the marathon.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``What I Did for Love,'' sometimes the best thing you can
do is follow your heart _ in careers as well as romances. Sometimes
that also may mean stepping away from a career because it's doing
too much harm to your family or personal life. Don't discount the
power of emotion in deciding whether to stay or go.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fox Mulder from ``The X-Files.'' Sure, his theories may seem a
little alien to you, but sometimes faith is all you have to help
you overcome your failures and get past your adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   Before someone cures cancer, thousands will have tried and
failed, but that doesn't mean their efforts were wasted. Those who
are afraid to fail will never succeed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
