 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY -- No. 444 -- Sept. 22, 1999 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are offering the following articles for sale. Please contact
us for availability your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. 'JAKOB'S' LEADER : ROBIN WILLIAMS FINDS LAUGHTER IN HELL Last
year, Roberto Benigni's award-winning film ``Life Is Beautiful''
proved that there's no place so grim that laughter can't be found
there - not even a Nazi concentration camp. Now Robin Williams -
considered by many to be America's funniest man - is out to prove
that there's more where that came from. His new film, ``Jakob the
Liar'' is based on the tragi-comic novel by Polish-born Jurek
Becker, who spent much of his youth in the Lotz ghetto and wrote
his book while living in East Germany. ``I know people in the most
extraordinarily horrific situations will still have moments of
comedy,'' says Williams. ``It's that somehow-surviving vestige of
humanity that keeps you going in the face of atrocity. ... It's a
very intimate portrayal of life in the face of death.'' By Ivor
Davis. 1,500 words + photos. (N/A Great Britain and Australia.)
____________________________________________________________ 2.
MENA SUVARI : 'AMERICAN BEAUTY' ``What I liked about Angela,'' says
actress Mena Suvari about her character in the film ``American
Beauty,'' is that I could bring a lot of myself into the part.
She's very flamboyant and wild and funny and I enjoyed stressing
that playful aspect of her. Angela may appear angelic, but her
long, blond hair and sensuous lips conspire to suggest a teenage
femme fatale. Toying with her best friend's middle-aged father
(played by Kevin Spacey,) who's going through a severe mid-life
crisis, she happily contributes to the image of a sexually
experienced girl determined never to be ``ordinary.'' By Dan Yakir.
BPI. 800 words + photo.
____________________________________________________________ 3.
ROXANN DAWSON RIDES 'THE BARGE OF THE DEAD' Roxann Dawson has been
playing ``Star Trek : Voyager's'' B'Elanna Torres for six years. A
combination of makeup and prosthetic appliances convincingly
transforms her into half-human/half-Klingon (the makeup takes
two-and-a-half hours to apply, and nearly an hour to remove.) In
the episode ``Barge of the Dead,'' she is sent on a treacherous
trek through Klingon hell after a near-death experience. ``The sets
were phenomenal, the story is great and it's very exciting to get
an episode that is not only physically demanding but emotionally
demanding,'' says Torres. By Ian Spelling. 1,000 words + photo.
____________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   4. 'WEST WING' TAKES FLIGHT In Hollywood, some of the most
successful entertainment ideas have been born out of the
traditional high-powered lunch. That was the case when writer Aaron
Sorkin and executive producer John Wells met over a meal two years
ago and decided to attempt a television drama about the inner
workings of the White House. The result of that meeting, ``The West
Wing,'' is set to premiere. With Martin Sheen as the president and
Rob Lowe as deputy communications director, it is one of the most
highly anticipated new series of the autumn season. Sorkin
discourages any comparisons between ``West Wing'' and the Clinton
administration. It does not focus on political issues but on the
people who run the White House, their lives and conflicts. By
Tamara Conniff. BPI. 800 words + photo.
____________________________________________________________ 5.
RECIPE FOR A HIT SITCOM Every year, the TV networks offer dozens of
new comedies and dramas and every year 80 per cent of them are
labelled as failures. Most major hits - including 'MASH,''
``Cheers'' and ``Seinfeld'' - struggled for a full season or longer
to build a decent following. The question is, how do some shows
beat the odds? Is there a recipe for success? By Christopher
Loudon. TV Guide Canada. 1,300 words + photo.
____________________________________________________________ 6.
DAVE MATTHEWS, MAKING MUSIC THE OLD-FASHIONED WAY After nearly 16
months of touring, Dave Matthews wants to go home. He's not
complaining about his success. Matthews has earned a break, having
engineered one of the decade's most succssful rock careers since
forming his band in 1991. Each of the band's five albums has sold
platinum, or better. The Dave Matthews Band has built its success
through the old-fashioned route of hard touring and grassroots
marketing - with a few modern touches. It is a constantly evolving
institution, with a marked experimental streak that many bands
would be afraid to indulge. By Gary Graff. 1,500 words + photo.
