<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1527 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-22 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUTURE SCHLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Marin County Emergency Operation Center
recently held a Y2K drill. This was the New Year's Eve disaster
scenario, according to the Mill Valley Herald newspaper: ``Sharks
are at Stinson, a riot's happening at the Mill Valley Safeway, a
tent has fallen on Huey Lewis, and foul-tasting oysters at a
millennium party have made hundreds of people deathly ill.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad oysters and bad vibes, that's a Marin disaster, and what any
of it has to do with computer clocks is anybody's guess. A riot at
Safeway in Mill Valley? Whole Foods is more like it.
</P>
<P>
   While Marin was preparing for computers to crash, bringing down
Huey Lewis' tent, a real disaster was happening next door to the
Mill Valley Safeway. Mill Valley, the town where the original
``Invasion of the Body Snatchers'' was set, has had a storefront
snatched by Starbucks.
</P>
<P>
   The town has long fought Starbucks, and the Seattle chain
finally snuck one by the Mill Valley Planning Commission, putting a
Starbucks in a Jamba Juice that had permission to have a ``coffee
bar.''
</P>
<P>
   Starbucks isn't a coffee bar. It's a cultural/retail
infestation, the first sign that a town is going to look like every
other commercial strip in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Also coming soon in Mill Valley: a 6,000-square-foot office and
retail space in a former parking lot near downtown's former train
depot. Just what a nice Bay Area town needs _ less parking, more
cute expensive stuff no one needs.
</P>
<P>
   At least the world might end before the millennium arrives,
sparing us a lot of hype and bad oysters. The latest
end-of-the-world scenario was posed by abcnews.com technology
writer David Melville.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the dot in ``.com'' stands for the grain of salt you
have to take with Net columns.
</P>
<P>
   Melville writes that an ``eccentric'' (the giveaway) physicist
friend is worried because Brookhaven National Laboratory is using a
collider to try to create the conditions that prevailed
milliseconds before the Big Bang, which turned primordial
quark-gluon plasma into the universe.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. The scare theory is that this could create a black
hole that would eventually consume the entire Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Naah. Not as scary as ``The Blair Witch Project.''
</P>
<P>
   the real end of the world will come sometime in 2000 when we
realize that we're in the future and can't imagine anything beyond
it. We'll be like Wile E. Coyote running off a cliff and looking
down, and the stock market will fall with us.
</P>
<P>
   For example, UCLA economists just predicted that in 2020
California will have a population of 47.7 million. Who cares? No
one can imagine 2020. And aren't there 47.7 million people in
California now? And just on I-80.
</P>
<P>
   We're all getting an overdose of future schlock.
</P>
<P>
   Major retail controversy: The Sears holiday catalog features a
line of ``Heroes and Villains'' action figures that includes a doll
with a black trench coat, shotgun and rifle _ startlingly similar
to the teen-agers in the ``Trench Coat Mafia'' who shot up the high
school in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Sears halted sales of the trench coat gunman, but you have to
ask what's going on in America. In my day, the Sears catalog didn't
sell criminal dolls with guns. It just sold guns, and was as
all-American as can be.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The latest historical controversy is over Edmund Morris'
``Dutch,'' the forthcoming authorized biography of Ronald Reagan.
In the book, Morris invents a narrator, conveniently named Edmund
Morris, who follows Reagan like Sancho Panza throughout Reagan's
life _ from Reagan's small Illinois hometown to the White House and
the Reagan ranch.
</P>
<P>
   You have to admit, this is the perfect match of style and
subject matter. The alleged narrator meets the alleged president,
and has to listen to all those supposedly true war stories taken
from ``Hellcats of the Navy.''
</P>
<P>
   The fictional American people await the book with faked
interest.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
