<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1529 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-OMEARA-2TAK     09-22 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-OMEARA-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'MEARA MORTAL 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ It was a year later, almost to the week and
the day. Sunday night, same place, the Augusta National golf club.
One man, Jose Maria Olazabal, was accepting the green jacket, the
warm applause at the awards ceremony on the practice green reaching
out beyond Magnolia Lane, the 1999 Masters champion crowned.
</P>
<P>
   A year earlier, it had been Mark O'Meara slipping on the green
jacket, next heading down the hill to the media building and there
spinning a warm tale of how he had birdied the 17th and 18th holes
on the final round to win the Masters, a feat only Arnold Palmer
had ever accomplished in Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the relationship between athletes and the media in other
sports, the relations between the golf media and golfers is more
often warm than brittle, more often understanding than
confrontational. It is because golf is such a lonely battle at the
highest level, but even more it is because golf is so different.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball players and basketball players and football and hockey
players receive their millions as much for potential as for
results. It is not so in golf. The only guarantee in golf is that
the man with the fewest strokes wins; golfers are paid for what
they have done, not for what they will do. If Darwin chose to
examine sports, he would have chosen golf where only the strongest
survive. The weak struggle and fight and then fall away.
</P>
<P>
   So O'Meara told his tale of how _ so un-O'Meara-like _ he had
told himself as he approached the 17th tee that he was going to
birdie the final two holes. Then, ``for some reason,'' O'Meara went
on, ``I told my caddie, `I'm going to birdie the last two holes and
win this sucker.' And he kind of looked at me, not with a shocked
mind, but just said, `Yeah, let's go.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The golf media took all this in. The golf media took all this as
a most pleasant surprise because O'Meara was 41 and this likeable
man still had not won a major. Even more, perhaps, it was so
pleasant because O'Meara looks like Everyman, like any number of
men at a golf course on Saturday morning anywhere in America _
middle-aged, a bit of gray in his hair, maybe a pound or two too
heavy.
</P>
<P>
   So a year passed. O'Meara's caddie, the man who said, ``Yeah,
let's go,'' to O'Meara in 1998, again carried O'Meara's bag in the
Masters of 1999, and when Sunday's round was done, this time with a
78 and a tie for 31st place, Jerry Higginbotham put down O'Meara's
bag for the last time after five years of toting it.
</P>
<P>
   He had been fired.
</P>
<P>
   A decision made at Augusta. A year after O'Meara's greatest
triumph, a year in which O'Meara had won both the Masters and the
British Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah . . . yeah,'' said Higginbotham when asked if it still
hurts. ``But it was one of those things where we're trying to keep
it behind us because it's old news. He wanted to do something
different and, for whatever reason he had, it was up to him. He's
the boss.''
</P>
<P>
   The caddie paused. He was standing on the front lawn of The
Country Club in Brookline, just moments after he and O'Meara had
bumped into each other shortly after arriving for The Ryder Cup.
The two had chatted amiably for several minutes and appearances
were fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark and I had a great five years, and a marvelous last
year,'' said Higginbotham. ``It was a great run with Mark and, as
you just saw, I was talking to him and we were yukking it up.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the firing made sense. O'Meara had had his greatest year
ever and then his caddie was gone. Higginbotham had scratched and
searched and questioned and probed but the only reason he could
come up with was the answer of a true pragmatist.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how it goes out here between the caddies and the
players,'' he said. ``There's a lot of shuffling around. Sometimes
it happens at the top and sometimes it happens at the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes in the middle. Because much has changed for Mark
O'Meara in the last year. The toast of golf last year now is
struggling.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The European media already have reached for their easiest,
most-used and abused stereotype of Americans in describing Mark
O'Meara and his pals in the Stars 'n' Gripes Brigade _ David ``It's
only an exhibition'' Duval, Tiger Woods, and Phil Mickelson _ and
it always comes out in some variation of ``spoiled millionaires.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough, if the US Ryder Cup team fares poorly this weekend
at The Country Club, the European jibes will be mild compared to
what Americans will toss at the Brookline Four. Their countrymen
will be unsparing.
</P>
<P>
   Just as true, O'Meara heads into the Ryder Cup with the shakiest
game of any of the Brookline Four. He jokes that it's done him
little good lately to aim his drives down the fairways only to find
his golf balls in the rough. Maybe, O'Meara suggested as many a
15-handicapper has done, ``I should aim for the rough'' and then
the ball might find the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   Long ago, back when O'Meara, 42, was a teenager, he used to have
a dastardly hook off the tee and, as close pal Woods has said to
Golf Digest, ``Mark always has had a fear of the left ball. When
Mark is feeling a little uneasy, Mark tends to slow down his body.
And when he slows down his body, his hands outrace his body, and he
tends to hit the ball just a little left.''
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived at Brookline Monday, O'Meara assessed his game
as ``OK. It could be a little bit better, but it's OK. I'm playing
reasonably well. I'm not playing great by any means but I'm playing
all right. We'll see how the practice rounds go.''
</P>
<P>
   So will US captain Ben Crenshaw. Unlike two years ago at
Valderrama, when the pairing of O'Meara and Woods, his Florida
neighbor and all-around pal, seemed ideal (only to have the two
Americans go 1-2 when paired), O'Meara's status this time seems
less lofty. O'Meara even said he would not cause a ruckus if
Crenshaw decides to sit him out for a match or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully I'll play well when the time needs to be called,''
said O'Meara, who is on his fifth Ryder Cup team. ``I've been
feeling more confident lately. I'm starting to play a little bit
better.''
</P>
<P>
   The US team has several players who could utter the same
uninspiring words as O'Meara _ golf that is ``OK but not great'' _
so Crenshaw might take a very close look at O'Meara. O'Meara's best
finish since March has been an 11th place in the Greater Hartford
Open.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 1318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1531 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-OMEARA-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     09-22 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OMEARA-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BROOKLINE, Mass.: ... Hartford Open.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As O'Meara conceded, a key reason the Europeans have upset the
United States in the last two Ryder Cups ``is that the European
team has really combined well in the team events, alternate shot
and best ball. And also because they have outputted us and been
very good in their short games.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara even said he would not mind if Crenshaw does not pair
him with Woods, his closest friend. ``I've told the captain I'm
willing to play with any guy on the team,'' said O'Meara. ``I'll be
very flexible with that and I think he'll take a hard look at the
pairings. Whether I play with Tiger is hard to say right now.''
</P>
<P>
   For sure, though, O'Meara will be grouped with Woods, Duval and
Mickelson on the issue of US players being paid. Ironically, even
if Duval has taken the most heat since the issue erupted at the PGA
tournament last month, it was O'Meara who has been a longtime
advocate. Even though Crenshaw and others on the US team have taken
a strong stance on the opposite side, O'Meara said he believes the
team will be unified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't worried about it then (at the PGA) and I'm not
worried about it now,'' O'Meara said of a possible split on the
team. ``Everybody has a different opinion and there's nothing wrong
with that. That's just the way life is. But I still respect my
fellow teammates whether their opinion is the same as mine or not.
And when it comes time to teeing it up on Friday and trying to win,
I think we're all on the same page on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Too late to change the American image, say observers from across
the Atlantic. The American image has been reinforced _ ``spoiled
millionaires.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark O'Meara may be rich, but spoiled is another matter. As one
prominent woman golfer knows very well, O'Meara has come a long
way.
</P>
<P>
   It was the mid-1970s, and Billie Jean King had squished Bobby
Riggs in tennis, the women's rights movement was on the rise, and
Jane Blaylock found herself in California for golf's Challenge of
the the Sexes _ Blaylock against Hale Irwin. Only problem was that
Blaylock had no caddie.
</P>
<P>
   A local youth was found, a would-be golfer familiar with the
course ``and I remember seeing this really adorable guy with those
Irish eyes of his,'' recalled Blaylock. ``I was the envy of all the
players. I had the best-looking caddie of everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The caddie was Mark O'Meara, then 18, and the two were an ideal
pairing, said Blaylock. She would halve her match with Irwin, and
then Blaylock asked O'Meara to caddie for her in the Dinah Shore
Classic. ``I came in third and Mark got a nice check,'' said
Blaylock, the New Hampshire native who now lives in Boston. ``And I
remember how that check helped Mark out a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The two then agreed that O'Meara would caddy for Blaylock on the
LPGA Tour for the summer until O'Meara returned to school. ``But
his daddy wouldn't let him take the (family) truck for the summer,
and he couldn't get around (to the tournaments),'' said Blaylock.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the golfer-caddie relationship was broken, Blaylock kept
in touch with O'Meara and watched his first tentative steps toward
becoming a pro. ``It was like watching my own son,'' said Blaylock.
</P>
<P>
   Years passed and O'Meara would make money, but it was not until
he and Woods learned they were neighbors in the same exclusive
community near Orlando that O'Meara was able to take the final step
to the top. Woods lit a fire in O'Meara, who's nearly twice his
age, while O'Meara was a solidifying influence on Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark and Tiger help each other all the time,'' said
Higginbotham. ``They work together all the time. They know each
other's game like no one else does. They play practice rounds
together. Most of all, they're best friends and a lot of people
don't realize that, but they really are true, best friends.''
</P>
<P>
   It has speculated that O'Meara's slide this year after a
spectacular 1998 may be attributed to his . . . well, obsession
with money. At the NEC Invitational last month in Akron, Ohio, for
instance, O'Meara lodged in an $80-a-night Comfort Inn which,
although close to the Firestone Country Club site, was a far cry
from the plusher lodgings where the other golfers stayed. O'Meara
also went shopping for necessities at a K-Mart in a mall near the
Comfort Inn.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara has traveled hundreds of thousands of miles in the 17
months since winning the Masters, taking home lucrative appearance
money on foreign shores (PGA events in America do not give
appearance money), traveling from Dubai to Ireland, where O'Meara
earns 50,000 Irish pounds, for instance, from Bord Failte, the
Irish tourist board. He also has appeared at scores of corporate
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``After having the great year he had, it's been pretty much a
proven pattern as other golfers have found out,'' said
Higginbotham. ``You see it on the PGA Tour all the time; there's
always a letdown after a great year. It's happened to all the
greats of the game. But, to be honest with you, I don't think Mark
has had a bad year.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, O'Meara has yet to win in 1999. He and the others of the
Brookline Four have been pilloried. He got rid of his caddie of
five years, the last of those five years very good. And he comes to
The Country Club not sure of his golf game.
</P>
<P>
   But what happens this weekend in Brookline just might define all
of 1999 for O'Meara. His year very quickly could get much worse . .
. or much better. Money, or no money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
