<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1532 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-SHAUGHNESSY     09-22 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMON PERCEPTION: TEAMS THAT ARE WORLDS APART 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ The hats are the same as they were two years
ago in Valderrama. The American players wear caps that have their
last names stitched on the back (T. Woods, D. Duval), while the
backs of the European caps read, ``European Team.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryder Cup golf. The best of America vs. the best of Europe. Or,
as our friends across the sea like to think, (itals)individual
stars vs. team players.(unitals
</P>
<P>
   More than any international competition _ more than the
Olympics, the World Cup or the Davis Cup _ this is the event that
reinforces all the stereotypes that (itals)they,(unitals) the
Euros, have about (itals)us,(unitals) the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   It is a broad brush and Americans are painted as bloated,
uptight, overconfident, impatient, and totally lacking in team
spirit. Meanwhile, the Europeans are perceived as fun-loving,
hungry, self-made, and passionate about team play.
</P>
<P>
   The Euros are beer-swilling, chain-smoking frat boys who play
for the love of the game. The Americans are the 1978 Red Sox of 25
players, 25 cabs . . . ultra-privileged, overpaid, prone to choke,
and totally insulated from anything connected with real world and
everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   Who can forget two years ago, when an Italian cardboard box
maker, Costantino Rocca, kicked Tiger Woods's butt all the way to
the Mediterranean Sea on Super Sunday in Valderrama? You think the
Europeans didn't love that? It's classic, little-guy-beats-big-guy
stuff and the Euros love to throw it in our faces.
</P>
<P>
   Again this year, the Americans are making it tough on
themselves. In September's American Golf Digest, US player Payne
Steward said of the European team, ``On paper, they shouldn't be
caddying for us.'' Tuesday, Jeff Maggert said, ``Let's face it,
we've got the 12 best players in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The British tabloids no doubt are having a field day with that
one. It's the golf equivalent of Dick Williams saying his 1967 Game
7 plan was ``Lonborg and Champagne.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month's Mess in Medinah only fortified all of Europe's
disgust with the American team. Perhaps you remember the cat fight
at the PGA Championship when American ace David Duval complained
about no pay for the players and called the Ryder Cup an
``exhibition.'' Duval also said ``it would take players not
playing'' to forge a change in the compensation issue.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods, at that time, added that he would like to see
competitors paid anywhere from $200,000 to $500,000, and be able to
do whatever they saw fit with the money. He said he would donate it
to charity. Meanwhile, fellow American Phil Mickelson wanted to
know who negotiated the deal that paid millions to The Country
Club.
</P>
<P>
   After a meeting of all top Ryder candidates, US captain Ben
Crenshaw said he was ``personally disappointed in a couple of
people,'' then made it clear exactly who he was talking about. Mark
O'Meara was stunned that Crenshaw ratted him out.
</P>
<P>
   After the Medinah mess, Brit Nick Faldo, a veteran of Europe's
last two Ryder victories, shrugged his Harrison Ford shoulders and
said, ``And they wonder why they can't win this team event.''
European captain Mark James added, ``We're not going into the Ryder
Cup for money. Never have been . . . We're losing touch with
reality, some people, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   The Euros had only one pre-Cup controversy and it involved
whether the players' caddies would be allowed to fly to America
with the team on the Concorde. Lee Westwood was among those players
who fought for the caddies and said, ``Team spirit is the advantage
the Europeans always have over the Americans.'' Alas, Westwood and
pals lost the fight for the little people, but again, the contrast
with the selfish Americans could not be more clear.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody was backing away from the pay-for-play issue Tuesday,
but the wounds are still there and it's extra pressure for the
American lads.
</P>
<P>
   American Justin Leonard said, ``We're here to play the matches
and compensation is longer part of this with the players.''
Crenshaw said, ``All thoughts are playing together for the Cup and
it's been that way for a while. It dissipated very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, one couldn't help but notice that Woods, Duval, O'Meara,
and Mickelson _ the Medinah Four _ played a practice round together
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Woods and Duval weren't pressed on the compensation question,
but denied that the Europeans play this event with more passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of that stuff is made up,'' said the pulseless
Duval. ``We try just as hard as they do. That's a disservice to the
European team, to say that when they win. It's disrespectful to
their play.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe we are less passionate than they are,'' added
Woods. ``We try just as hard as they do.''
</P>
<P>
   The American stars were quite accomodating and Duval even poked
fun at himself a few times. But they have to know the pressure is
mounting. They have said the Euros shouldn't be caddying for them.
They have said they have the 12 best golfers in the world. They
have complained about compensation. And they wear hats that promote
themselves instead of their team.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
