<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-ROOTS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RYDER HAD FAITH IN HIS IDEA 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Golf? God bless us, golf?
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes, in a manner of speaking. Religion had played a part
in this whole unlikely evolution, just as it had reached into every
nook and cranny of his life, 68-year-old Samuel Ryder mused with a
chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   After all, if he hadn't been reluctantly persuaded to take up
the game by his parson, Rev. Frank Wheeler, in St. Albans almost 20
years ago, he most assuredly wouldn't be sitting here now, on the
veranda of the young Wentworth Golf Club, beneath the imposing
ramparts that dominated its concrete castle design. He wouldn't be
gazing out at the East Course, completed just a few months ago by
Harry Shapland Colt but already a gem in the affluent Surrey
countryside, awaiting the start of these informal team matches
between the finest American and British professional golfers prior
to the 1926 British Open.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal and Ancient Golf Club of St. Andrews had decreed that
for the first time, qualifying would be necessary for this Open,
and the Americans had fulfilled that obligation at Sunningdale,
just a couple of miles from Wentworth, and had some time to kill.
So the flamboyant, garrulous Walter Hagen, representing the United
States, and Wentworth pro George Duncan, along with Ryder's
personal instructor, Abe Mitchell, had arranged this competition.
Had arranged the particulars of it, that is, for the genesis of it
had come from Samuel Ryder. The London Daily Telegraph had reported
his grand intention of someday matching the best of the US and
Great Britain in a team competition back in 1925, and while the
opportunity hadn't presented itself then, this little gap in the
schedule had proved ideal.
</P>
<P>
   It had been announced in the Times of London two months ago that
Ryder would present a trophy to the winner of these international
matches June 4 and 5, and this morning's Times had trumpeted the
first day of competition under the headline ``Ryder Cup.'' Truth be
told, there was no cup _ just 5 pounds for each participant and 5
more to each member of the winning team. But there certainly was a
Ryder, and these matches were a tribute to him _ he had,
appropriately enough, sown the seeds for them _ though he didn't
see it that way. He considered them a tribute to God and to a
lifelong desire to help the less fortunate. Which, he had
discovered almost by accident, included the British touring pros.
That came years after he discovered golf. Under protest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The breakdown had been no surprise, really. Sam Ryder had
devoted many of his 50 years to the roles of businessman and
benefactor with compulsive zeal, so the collapse, the sheer
exhaustion that caused it, was perhaps inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   When his doctor ordered that he take up some form of exercise as
a diversion from his more serious pursuits, Ryder naturally had
settled upon cricket. He had played the sport while growing up near
Manchester in northern England, one of eight children of a
nurseryman of middling success, and he had loved it. But he hadn't
played it in years, and the strain at his age, his physician
informed him, might kill him before it cured him. What to do?
</P>
<P>
   How about golf? suggested Rev. Wheeler, an aficionado of the
game and Ryder's longtime friend. Preposterous, countered Ryder.
Golf? Why, it was nothing but orienteering with a stick. Such a
waste of time.
</P>
<P>
   But while he didn't consider his minister infallible in such
secular matters, he finally agreed, just to appease him. And,
wonder of wonders, he found himself captivated by the game. He
couldn't quite explain the attraction _ then again, who could truly
pinpoint the source of an obsession? _ but he became consumed by
it, just as he had his other endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he didn't go public, not right away. Instead, he had a
200-yard hole installed behind the magnificent Marlborough House,
which he had leased since 1905, and ordered a hedge planted as part
of it so he could practice his chipping. Then he brought in the
local pro from Verulam Golf Club, a fellow named Hill _ for the
life of him, he couldn't recall the poor man's first name _ to
tutor him. Hill soon left the scene, replaced by his successor at
Verulam, Charles Wallis, and Ryder continued his private education
until he felt ready to reveal himself as a true golfer.
</P>
<P>
   He had been that way in everything he did. The seed business,
for instance. He had begun his career with large companies in
Manchester and then London, even while retaining an interest in his
father's concern, and he had traveled Europe extensively. His tours
of the Continent had inspired a brainstorm _ why not sell seeds in
small packets, at a penny each, so that the common man could afford
a garden just as surely as the wealthy? His father had advised
against it, but Sam was not to be dissuaded. He left the family
business in Sale, Cheshire, and relocated to St. Albans, in the
county of Hertfordshire.
</P>
<P>
   He did not pick this spot by happenstance. He studied a map and
chose the town because of its strategic location on a direct
railway line that went from London all the way up to Scotland, thus
serving as a center of transport. He and his wife, Helen, moved
into a tiny house at 5 Folly Lane and, ignoring the mocking irony
of this address, went to work. They would package the seeds at
home, then carry them in a clothes basket to the post office each
Friday night so that they would be available to would-be customers
by Saturday afternoon _ the one half-day off each week the British
workingman received.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was pure genius. The business eventually grew into a
worldwide success, and along the way, Ryder moved into larger
quarters, first into a chapel that had opened in 1697 but now was
in disuse, then to 27 Holywell Hill, the site of an inn once
visited by Queen Elizabeth in 1577. Later he would branch out,
forming Heath and Heather Ltd., which sold herbs for medicinal use.
Among its products was a smoking mixture that was supposed to
facilitate sweet dreams, and when English Customs tried to curtail
it as a violation of regulations regarding the sale of tobacco
products, Ryder went to court. The case was a cause celebre, and
the media attention it generated guaranteed the success of the
product.
</P>
<P>
   But he was more than a financial wizard. He took pity on the
poor, though he once patronizingly referred to them as ``much
better people than we thought they were,'' and he was among the
first employers to grant vacation and health benefits. Skeptics
warned him that this was foolhardy, that the workers would take
advantage of him, but he said simply, ``Well, let them.'' In fact,
the opposite proved true _ most of his 350 employees developed an
intense loyalty to him, far more so than did the town fathers.
</P>
<P>
   St. Albans was built near the ruins of Verulainam, once the
third-largest city in the British portion of the Roman Empire, and
its centerpiece was an abbey originally constructed in 900. In a
town of such history and heritage, Ryder was an interloper,
regarded warily because of his occasional indulgences in northern
bluntness.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't prevent him from becoming one of the town's
leading citizens, grudgingly as that prominence may have come.
Eight years after his arrival in 1895, he was elected to the city
council, and in 1905, his fellow councilors selected him mayor. He
wasted no time expressing his contempt for the governing body that
had elevated him, saying in his acceptance speech that it was a
lifeless organization.
</P>
<P>
   But more often, he engaged in gentle sarcasm, though some
mistook it for abrasiveness. And he was at heart a kind man,
devoted to his family: Helen and their three daughters _ Marjorie,
Kay, and Joan, the youngest and, he had to admit, his favorite. He
often would play the piano during the evening while the girls
played cards. Finding that their bickering over the games sometimes
became intolerable, he had a trophy made up _ a glass vase with the
inscription ``No Grumbling'' _ and it would be awarded once a week
to whichever of the three was adjudged to have complained the
loudest.
</P>
<P>
   That was an example of his humor, and if people couldn't accept
it, that was their problem. But he was more given to acts of
benevolence. Upon arriving in St. Albans, he immediately became
Sunday school superintendent of the Spicer Street Chapel _a
Congregationalist church, for he followed a nonconformist doctrine,
no matter how it sat with the Church of England. He put his
business skills to work overseeing the expansion of the Spicer
Street facility and eventually funding the larger Trinity Church.
</P>
<P>
   Even an act of apparent self-importance was in fact the practice
of charity. During his term as mayor, Ryder followed the tradition
of the times and had a portrait of himself in his magisterial robes
commissioned. It was a huge oil painting in which he resembled a
head of church or state, a monument to pomposity, his critics said.
But it was actually vital employment for the artist, Francis
Saulsbury, who had fallen upon hard times since doing a portrait of
Ryder's daughters. Saulsbury's career was revived, and some of his
works eventually were displayed in the Royal Academy of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Ryder preached these tenets at home, and when one of his
daughters would complain about doing something, he would say,
``Never mind, child, it's part of the discipline of life.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 1322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
