<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1536 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-WORCESTER-B     09-22 1350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-WORCESTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORCESTER WAS THE PERFECT HOST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ There are pictures and framed letters to
remind guests that they have walked into a cherished home of
yesteryear. Clocks can be found, if you need to have the day's
time, but calendars are not required. At Worcester Country Club, it
can be any year your imagination desires, for a century's worth of
character, charm, and elegance is beneath every step taken on the
golf course and behind every door of the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Ross created this marvelous golf course, which has been
preserved by grateful guardians, and there are still some who may
have been there that September day in 1914 when President William
H. Taft struck the first drive. It was here, in 1925, that golf's
greatest legend, Robert Tyre Jones Jr., contributed the most
gracious act of sportsmanship the game has ever seen. Fourteen
years later, Byron Nelson won a Mass. Open over these hallowed
grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were those gentlemen who arrived in early June of
1927. A proud group of Brits, they had taken a ship, the Aquitania,
across the Atlantic, disembarking in Manhattan. A few days later,
following a look at Babe Ruth and the Yankees and some golf in
Westchester, the men found themselves in the rolling hills of
central Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   They had come to play golf for honor. They had come to play golf
for pride. They had come to play the first official Ryder Cup
matches.
</P>
<P>
   At Worcester Country Club? Why Worcester?
</P>
<P>
   It isn't documented, but the reason seems to be threefold.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely, the players agreed on Worcester CC since many of
them had taken part in the US Open there two years earlier. (That
was the Open in which Jones called a penalty stroke on himself and
was forced into a playoff, which he lost to Willie MacFarlane.)
</P>
<P>
   Logistically, Worcester made sense because the US Open would be
held two weeks later at Oakmont in Pennsylvania, and the Brits
could use the matches as a warm-up.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Worcester's head professional at the time was Willie
Ogg, a legendary figure. He was a Scotsman who was friendly with
many of the Brits, while also involved with the PGA of America. It
stands to reason that he had an influence on the decision to bring
this international golf match to Worcester.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever got them to Worcester serves as trivial backdrop to
the reality that indeed, on June 3-4, 1927, a golf competition was
born right here in Massachusetts. Eighteen professional golfers
with their fashionable knickers and ties, their mashies and
niblicks, their loose swings and combative spirits started
something that they could not recognize if they were with us today.
</P>
<P>
   None of them are, of course, not with the passing this spring of
Gene Sarazen at the age of 97. He had been the last remaining
player from that 1927 competition. ``A wonderful man,'' recalls
Fred Hill, who at 89 is one of the few who can remember that 1927
Ryder Cup. ``He was a little nervous, a bit cocky, but he was very
generous.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill caddied for Sarazen in 1927 and received $80. The money he
gave to his mother; the memories he still has.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There were local, national, and international events going on in
June of 1927 that commanded attention, so it would be a great
exaggeration to say the first Ryder Cup match dominated news. Not
with the country still trumpeting Charles Lindbergh's historic
flight while also monitoring the plight of Clarence Chamberlin,
lost in travel. There was also the death of the infamous Lizzie
Borden. Charlie Chaplin had himself in a messy marital mess, and
the Sacco-Venzetti case was a hot topic of conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, golf was a pleasant distraction and this Ryder Cup seemed
a curious thing. Certainly it was to a couple of Worcester CC
members, brothers Bill and Tom Kelleher.
</P>
<P>
   They are 91 and 84, respectively, but they were schoolboys 72
years ago and since their dad was a member at Worcester CC, it was
an easy decision to attend the matches. Bill was a golfer and
wanted to see the great players of the era _ Walter Hagen and
Johnny Farrell, Ted Ray and Aubrey Boomer. ``That was the main
reason I came out,'' he said, ``to watch them play and improve my
game. I wanted to copy those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Hagen, the US playing captain, was every bit the showman and
star attraction history makes him out to be, said the Kelleher
brothers. He arrived every day in a chauffeur-driven limo,
``accompanied by a pretty woman,'' they said, and was good to the
kids who shagged balls for him at the range.
</P>
<P>
   One of those shaggers was Frank Blanchard, who had hoped to
caddie in the event, though he settled on work at the range.
``Hagen gave me a dozen balls. I wish to hell I still had them.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Blanchard: ``I remember he drank a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean all he could,'' said Al McIntyre, now 84 but a mere
12 years old when he snuck a peak that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he was shrewd,'' said Bill Kelleher. ``When he'd hit a
ball in the rough he'd look at it, walk back and forth, and the
gallery would follow his every step. Back and forth. Back and
forth. This was before ropes so people got close. After a while,
when he'd get around to hitting his ball, the grass would be matted
down.''
</P>
<P>
   There were good crowds, the men recalled, and newspaper accounts
of the day put the figure at 2,000. Some reports had it at 4,000.
</P>
<P>
   What the event did lack was close competition. The Americans,
humbled terribly by a 13 1/2-1 1/2score in an informal match the
year before at Gleneagles in Scotland, won three of four foursomes
matches on Friday. The next day, despite the cool, damp, and windy
weather that seemed to make the Brits feel at home, the Homebreds _
as they had come to be called _ won six of eight singles matches,
halved another, and completed a 9 1/2-2 1/2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The play of the American golfers, once the ball had reached
the green, was a revelation,'' is how Boston reporters saw it. ``It
was here that the homebred product excelled and was really the
advantage that enabled the Americans to score such an impressive
victory.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, according to Ray: ``They putted in much better
form than we did.''
</P>
<P>
   The rout was set in motion early as Farrell and Joe Turnesa
dealt an 8 and 6 blow to what was supposedly Great Britain's best
duo _ George Duncan and Archie Compston. Sarazen and Al Waltrous
followed with a 3 and 2 win over Arthur Havers and Herbert Jolly,
which more than offset the only US loss _ Lei Diegel and Bill
Mehlhorn getting whipped, 7 and 5, by Boomer and Charles Whitcombe.
</P>
<P>
   McIntyre recalls watching Boomer walk shoeless from the
clubhouse to the first tee. ``He forgot his golf shoes and had to
run in quickly for them. He rushed to the first tee and didn't have
time for a practice swing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Worcester CC sits proudly amid rolling hills, pampered and cared
for by a membership that treasures its every square inch. It is
just a 40-minute ride from The Country Club in Brookline, where the
33d Ryder Cup matches will attract tens of thousands of people in a
multimillion dollar event that bares little resemblance to what
took place 72 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the Bancroft Hotel in Worcester, where the players stayed
and had their pre-match banquet in 1927, is now an office building.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Hill stopped playing the game two years ago ``because it's
no fun to play bogey golf when you used to be good,'' though he is
helping his daughter with the game. He walks with a cane but can,
at a moment's notice, go into his still-fluid golf swing with it.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Kelleher fell two years ago and had to quit playing, though
he vows to return to the tee. His brother Tom plays frequently,
quite often with Al as they trade off member-guests at their
respective clubs.
</P>
<P>
   And Frank Blanchard, who was witness to the 1927 Ryder Cup, died
at the age of 88, shortly after sharing his 1927 memories. ``You
should have seen Hagen,'' said Blanchard. ``He was something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
