<HEADLINE>
WINS NOT ENOUGH FOR NEW REALIST CARROLL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ As usual, Bruce Armstrong was on to
something Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably the keenest analyst of the Patriots' situation at any
given moment, the veteran left tackle assessed his team's
remarkable second-half comeback against the Indianapolis Colts from
the perspective of Pete Carroll, New England's beleaguered head
coach, and concluded, ``If you're going to blame him for the
losses, you have to give him credit for the victories.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong is quite right.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the 1999 NFL season is far from decided. As dead
as the Jets look at the moment and as alive as the Patriots seem
today, anything can happen in 14 weeks, and not all of it will be
good. If you go by the first two weeks, the Washington Redskins are
ready to become one of the most prolific scoring offenses in NFL
history. If you go by the first two weeks, the New York Giants
could give up triple-figure numbers to New England's offense Sunday
night. Neither is likely to be the case.
</P>
<P>
   The point is, the first two weeks can be a portent or a mirage,
and unlike past years, Carroll seemed to sense that Monday, 24
hours after his team rallied from a 28-7 deficit to a 31-28
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Gone was the cheerleader's empty-headed enthusiasm for all
things good and the fan's blind eye to all things negative. Within
four sentences, it was reality time for his players and the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 2-0, but we're not satisfied with the way we're
playing,'' Carroll said. ``We need a lot of improvement. We have to
show improvement if we're going to go anywhere. We can't continue
to hurt ourselves and count on coming out with miraculous wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Huh?
</P>
<P>
   Had Don Shula suddenly invaded Carroll's body? Had Bear Bryant _
whose team never had a chance of beating anybody, to hear him say
it _ somehow risen from the dead and come back in the shape of
Pistol-Packing, I'm-Feelin'-Dangerous Pete?
</P>
<P>
   Carroll has coached and approached things differently so far
this year than he did in his first two seasons. He is more the
father and less the understanding uncle. He is more the taskmaster
and less the overnight-camping-trip organizer.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll will never be a jut-jawed Shula. That is not his
personality. But he appears to have learned much the past two years
about command, and at least one lesson is the simplest of all but
the hardest for a coach to accept: that the players are his enemy.
</P>
<P>
   They don't mean to be. Seldom do they want to be. But players
are players, and by their very nature they put a coach at risk
because their agenda is not always his agenda. They play for a
living. The coach works for a living.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll finally seems to have figured that out, having pushed
his players harder this summer and being less willing to accept
whatever lame excuse they have for failure. Asked about the spate
of first-half penalties that helped put his team in a hole Sunday,
Carroll didn't do what he'd done so often in the past.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't defend the players. He didn't squawk about the
officials or split the hair of this or that ruling. Instead he
pointed out that many were aggressive penalties rather than merely
stupid ones but added, ``It's overaggressiveness. We'll have
officials on the field this week.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Carroll was not assuming the penalty problem
would go away just because boys will be boys and the fellas really
wanna do good and let's get after 'em and you'll see now.
</P>
<P>
   This time it was simply, ``We'll have officials on the field,''
meaning he would import some local high school and college
officials to work practice this week, throwing flags when players
cross the line to remind them of the consequences.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say he hasn't done similar things in the past.
The difference is, this year he's doing what the best coaches in
sports do. He's making his players accountable, and publicly so.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll and the Patriots are no strangers to fast starts. They
have opened at 4-1 each of his first two years, and they are 2-0
with the Giants and lowly Browns coming up in the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But those 4-1 teams went 2-8 in the seasons' next quarter,
having grown full of themselves in part from the blind praise
heaped upon them by their boss in the face of their obvious
deficiencies. It would appear that will not be the case this
season.
</P>
<P>
   In the NFL, it is not how you start that counts; it's where you
finish. Carroll seems to understand that more clearly. He is still
excited to win the way he did the past two weekends _ on late field
goals _ but he is mindful that games like that can just as easily
be lost. While it is traditional to talk about ``character'' (one
of the most overused words in sports) when a team wins with a
last-second field goal, no one wants to talk about a lack of
character when it doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Carroll avoided that word while talking about New
England's latest thrilling win. Instead he framed it the way it
needed to be framed _ draped as much in black as in red, white, and
blue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the two turnovers, we wouldn't have been able to
win,'' Carroll cautioned. ``We would have run out of time. I'd like
to tell you I knew it was going to happen, but I was surprised in
general we were able to turn the game around.''
</P>
<P>
   Those words, though not what the public was used to hearing from
Carroll, should be welcome ones because they were the truth, just
as he told his team the truth at halftime when he made it clear it
wasn't the coaches' plan that was the problem but the players'
execution of it.
</P>
<P>
   Success in coaching hinges on how well the players do what is
asked of them. The coach's job is to be sure they understand what
that is and to make sure they do it. Realizing this, Carroll
slightly adjusted the defense into a more basic attack and told the
players the rest was up to them.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the rest of the job is reminding them what reality
is. Pete Carroll did that Monday by looking at his team and its
stirring victory and its 2-0 start for what it really was _ a
dangerous route to keep taking if they want to keep winning.
</P>
<P>
   They may not have wanted to hear it, but them's the facts, and
it was reassuring to hear them coming from the boss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
