<HEADLINE>
HISTORY CALLS FOR CAUTION ON ALLEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you reach 30 years of age and make a living by running a
football, there are only so many carries left. The next could be
your last.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Allen is 31 and has been banged around as much as, if not
more than, any other running back in the league in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   He may be the only runner in the NFL with two completely
reconstructed knees. One total repair job can mean the end of the
line. Two almost always does. But not for Allen, who has made
important contributions to the Patriots in their heart-pounding,
last-gasp victories in the first two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Back in training camp, when Allen was being talked about as a
possibility with the Patriots, I checked with his previous
employers, the Washington Redskins, and was told the following:
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry could still do it for a limited number of carries and
not over an entire season. The last two years with us, he started
strong and then started to wear down and couldn't finish the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   A check of the records shows that Allen played just 10 games
each of the last two seasons. He surrendered his body too many
times and couldn't make it to the end.
</P>
<P>
   But so far Allen has been on top of his game. Maybe missing all
of training camp has rejuvenated him. In the opener against the
Jets, he had a clutch 22-yard touchdown burst in the second half on
a third-and-short situation, which was typical of what Allen can do
for a team.
</P>
<P>
   Allen is not a speed burner. Never has been. But he is a tough,
physical runner who hits the holes and linebackers with abandon, a
pinball runner, fighting for every inch. He also has excellent
vision, and from his vast experience he knows when, and where, to
cut.
</P>
<P>
   In two games, he has carried 30 times for 128 yards and caught
three passes, one for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   How about making Allen the ``closer''? Bring him in on
short-yardage and goal-line situations for three periods, then let
him finish in the fourth, when the opposition is wearing down. It
would seem to be a perfect role for him, one that could get him
through the season healthy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Giants coach Jim Fassel was not a happy camper Tuesday. ``We
just played a terrible game against Washington,'' said Fassel. ``I
didn't think we could play like that. That's the worst defensive
game we've had since I've been here. On both sides of the ball, it
looked like they were quick and fast, and we were in slow motion.
It was that way the whole game.'' The Giants were smacked by the
Redskins, 50-21, and come to Foxborough, Mass. to play the Patriots
Sunday night. ``We better step up our game higher than it has been
up there on Sunday night. They are playing very well. (Drew)
Bledsoe is playing in control and in rhythm. He's the best in the
league right now. I don't think anyone's playing better or with
more confidence. You can watch him on film and just see the
confidence. As a team, they've been making a lot of plays. The guys
around him have been getting open. Terry Glenn's been getting 100
yards, and when that happens, they usually win.'' The Giants won
their opener in Tampa Bay, but after a good showing on offense in
the exhibition season, they have been bogged down. ``All of last
year we were last in the league on converting third downs,'' said
Fassel. ``At the end of preseason, we were No. 1. Now we are having
a tough time again.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A big plus for the Giants this weekend will be the long-awaited
return of Jason Sehorn, a Pro Bowl cornerback in 1997. In 1998, he
talked the Giants into letting him return kickoffs (read this, Ty
Law), and on the very first one, in an exhibition game, he blew his
knee apart and missed all of last season. This year, after working
out hard and bulking up to 225 pounds, Sehorn pulled a hamstring in
camp and hasn't played. ``He wanted to play last week and could
have played last week,'' said Fassel. ``But I told him he has not
played in over a year, and I thought he would be better sitting out
one more week. If he had played all last year and missed a few
weeks of training camp, I would have played him Sunday. But I
thought this would be better.'' In the past, the Giants have moved
Sehorn around to match up with the other team's best receiver. ``It
could happen in this game,'' mused Fassel. ``Jason and Terry Glenn.
Now that would be pretty good.'' If that happens, Sehorn's
hamstring had better be 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
