<HEADLINE>
THE STRATEGY, FORMAT OF RYDER MATCH PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you are a casual golf fan and tune into the Ryder Cup
matches, you may be confused. Unlike the weekly tournament play you
may watch, whereby individuals have scores such as 4-under or
2-over, the Ryder Cup will be match play. A beginner's guide:
</P>
<P>
   MATCH PLAY _ The idea here is to win holes, regardless of total
score in relation to par. If European Colin Montgomerie makes a 4,
and American David Duval makes a 5, Montgomerie wins the hole. If
the players tie, the hole is ``halved.'' The match continues until
a player is ahead by more holes than there are left to play. For
example: If Montgomerie leads by three holes and there are just two
remaining, he wins by a score of 3 and 2. The same scoring format
holds true whether they are playing singles or team. There will be
three types of competition over the three days:
</P>
<P>
   Singles (12 matches, all on Sunday) _ Played as above.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Foursomes (8 matches total, 4 each on Friday and Saturday
mornings) _ More commonly called ``alternate shot,'' this format
pits two players from Europe in a match against two from the US,
with each team playing one ball. Let's say the match is Montgomerie
and Lee Westwood vs. Duval and Tiger Woods. The teams on their own
decide who hits first off the first tee. For the sake of arguemnt,
let's say Westwood hits first. Montgomerie would then hit the
second shot, Westwood the third, and so on until the hole is
finished. Same thing for the US _ Duval and Woods would alternate
until the hole is holed. Again, it would be low score on the hole
that wins. Each team alternates as to who shoots first on the hole,
regardless of who shot last on the previous hole.
</P>
<P>
   Four-ball (8 matches total, 4 each on Friday and Saturday
afternoons) _ More commonly called ``best ball,'' it again involves
two players against two players. In this format, however, all the
players play their own ball, with the low score counting for the
team. Thus, if Montgomerie makes 4 and Westwood a 5, Europe counts
the 4. If Duval makes 4 and Woods a 3, the US counts the 3 and wins
the hole.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHOOSING SIDES _ On Thursday evening, each captain will choose
four teams of two from among his 12 golfers to compete in Friday
morning's ``foursomes.'' He will secretly designate them to play
1st, 2d, 3d, 4th, and submit his list to officials, who then will
announce the pairings (Europe No. 1 vs. US No. 1, etc.). After the
Friday morning matches are played, captains will then select their
four two-man teams for the Friday afternoon ``four-ball'' and may
choose any player, whether they played in the morning or not. The
same selection process will hold true for Saturday's matches. The
pairings for the 12 Sunday singles matches will be submitted by the
captains late Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GLOSSARY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Common Ryder Cup-related golf terms you may hear throughout the
week and what they mean:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Match play _ This is the overall format of the event. Players
try and win holes by getting lower scores. The match is won by
whoever has the most holes, not the player with the lower score.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All square _ Means the match is even.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Up _ You will hear this a lot. It means you have won these many
more holes than your opponent. Davis Love and Mark O'Meara are ``2
up'' in their match with Paul Lawrie and Andrew Coltart.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 and 3 _ A score you may hear during match play. Darren Clarke
defeats Jeff Maggert by ``4 and 3'' means he was four holes up with
three holes to play, thus Maggert cannot overcome the deficit and
the match is over.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Win a hole _ Your score is lower than your opponents, thus you
``win'' a hole. Whether you are one, two or three strokes lower is
of no matter. It counts for one hole.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Halve _ A tie. Payne Stewart makes four on a hole and so does
his opponent. They ``halve'' the hole.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dormie _ It means you cannot do worse than a tie, that you lead
your oppponent by as many holes as there are left to play. Colin
Montgomerie is 3 up with three holes to play. Thus, Montgomerie is
dormie, for if he loses all three holes, the worst he would do is
halve the match.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Concede _ To acknowledge that you cannot beat your opponent on a
hole. Davis Love is 20 feet away, putting for a bogey, but Lee
Westwood is 10 feet away and has two putts for par. Love
acknowledges that Westwood will do no worse than 2-putt for a 4,
thus he concedes the hole.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Honors _ To hit first off the tee is to have honors. At the
first tee, this is determined by tournament officials, but on holes
thereafter the low score has honors. If the previous hole was a
halve, whomever had honors keeps them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
