u f BC-WEB-RIVALRIES-BOS &LR;      09-22 1297
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-RIVALRIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU, TOO INVENTED THE NET? GET IN LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A pack of engineers, venture capitalists, and officers of star
on-line companies such as Yahoo Inc. and Amazon.com are gathering
this week to celebrate three decades of the Internet _ or something
like that.
</P>
<P>
   The event is billed as the Internet's 30th birthday party and is
pegged to experiments that took place in the fall of 1969, when the
first bits of digitized text were sent between computer
laboratories in Los Angeles and Menlo Park, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   From that halting beginning, the new medium now reaches almost
200 million people worldwide. The party in Atherton, Calif., will
commemorate the explosion with speeches, investment announcements,
and a menu including coconut-beer shrimp and conch fritters.
</P>
<P>
   But the Internet's booming success has also prompted more
scrutiny of its origins _ and touched off some rather unfestive
bickering.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, it turns out not everyone regards 1969 as the
Internet's birth year. Historian Janet Abbate, whose ``Inventing
the Internet'' was just published by the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology Press, thinks October 1972 might be regarded as a better
boot-up period.
</P>
<P>
   That was when a military predecessor to the Internet called the
ARPANET was the subject of a conference in Washington. Unlike the
1969 experiments, the 1972 gathering sparked much public interest
in electronic communications, Abbate says. ``To my mind, that's
when it gets up and running.''
</P>
<P>
   About the upcoming Silicon Valley festival, she said, ``I feel
kind of like `whoop-de-do.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, debates over the history of cyberspace were
confined to narrow engineering circles. No longer: the massive
attention and cash directed to on-line projects have prompted a
rush by everyone from university deans to presidential candidate Al
Gore to talk up their early associations with the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sense that history's about to be written here and
they don't want to be left out,'' said Lyman Chapin, chief
technology officer for a GTE Corp. unit that is the successor to
Bolt, Beranek &AMP; Newman Inc., the Cambridge defense contractor that
built some of the first networking computers.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the chronology of events that created the network of
networks now known as the Internet isn't in dispute. But parcelling
out credit for these advances is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no squabbling over the facts, there's only squabbling
over branding,'' said Robert Kahn, who helped write the key
Internet protocol known as TCP/IP to enable computers to talk to
each other.
</P>
<P>
   Already competing claims have led to revisions. For instance,
MCI WorldCom Inc. for years had referred to its senior vice
president Vint Cerf as ``the father of the Internet.'' There was
some basis for the description: Cerf founded the Internet Society
in 1992 and shared a National Technology Medal with Kahn in 1997
for their work on TCP/IP in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   But some of Cerf's former colleagues complained Worldcom's
description excluded others. A few months ago WorldCom made an edit
to its site on the World Wide Web and now describes Cerf as being
``widely known as a `father of the Internet.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Cerf says he asked for the change in order to reflect the work
of others, including Kahn, who gets much less attention in his
current post as president of the nonprofit Corporation for National
Research Initiatives in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``This work was not done in a vacuum,'' Cerf wrote in a recent
e-mail message.
</P>
<P>
   That's still not good enough for some, including Leonard
Kleinrock, a computer science professor at the University of
California at Los Angeles. In academic papers in the early 1960s,
Kleinrock first described the technique known as
``packet-switching,'' chopping up messages into small digital
pieces to speed them over telecommunications networks.
</P>
<P>
   He also oversaw some of the first experiments in 1969, and, as a
result, Kleinrock calls himself the person ``most responsible'' for
the creation of the Internet, along with Larry Roberts, who
developed the ARPANET. Kahn and Cerf rank no better than third-most
and fourth-most influential, respectively, Kleinrock says, and
shouldn't be credited with paternity in any case.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to be the father you need to both help conceive and
be present at the birth,'' Kleinrock said. As far as the Internet
goes, he said, ``I was at both!''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's a faction of engineers who regard Cerf and
Kleinrock both as theoretical hangers-on. ``All they were really
saying was `maybe those things could work,' '' says Frank Heart, a
retired engineer from Bolt, Beranek.
</P>
<P>
   As Heart sees it, the translation of networking theory into
practice was done by Roberts' and Heart's own Bolt, Beranek group.
Beginning in 1969, they built what were called ``interface message
processors,'' small devices to connect bigger computers to
telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the difference between Einstein saying E(EQ)MC
squared and the people at Los Alamos who actually built the atom
bomb,'' Heart said.
</P>
<P>
   On the subject of atomic weapons, another debate relates to what
extent the Internet derives from Cold War military research to help
command-and-control systems survive a nuclear first strike. The
issue centers on the contributions made by Paul Baran, a Rand Corp.
employee who published a survivability study for the Pentagon in
1964.
</P>
<P>
   Baran's work and that of a British researcher later caught the
attention of Roberts when he was managing ARPANET and led him to
hire Baran as an adviser. But in later years, people trying to
build the Internet's commercial credibility became uncomfortable
with the Internet's association with nuclear-warfighting.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Roberts minimizes the influence of Baran's survivability
research. On a Web site describing Baran's 1964 paper, Roberts
writes ``It is from this paper that the rumor was started that the
Internet was created by the military to withstand nuclear war. This
is totally false.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Roberts said, ``Paul has somehow wound up as
being the inventor of packet-switching, and that's sort of
strange.''
</P>
<P>
   Baran says packet-switching did relate to survivability research
and calls it naive to expect the military would have funded the
ARPANET later on if it hadn't offered certain military benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that was done on the ARPANET was supposedly done in
the name of connecting civilian computers. There was more to it
that was downplayed for political reasons,'' Baran said. ``Remember
that in the late 1960s, anything that had to do with the military
was anathema to the universities.''
</P>
<P>
   Such debates put off some Bolt, Beranek alumni such as John
McQuillan, who helped design switching programs for digital
signals. Now a Concord-based venture capitalist, McQuillan worries
disputes about the various contributions of the Internet's pioneers
might appear ``unseemly.''
</P>
<P>
   In previous decades, he said, ``the whole point of the research
was getting it right and getting a paper in a peer-reviewed
journal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays the Internet is all about making money, getting
funding and patents,'' he said. ``That makes it much more important
whose idea was whose.''
</P>
<P>
   But what's a little hyperbole among friends? Bob Metcalfe, the
inventor of the networking technique known as ``Ethernet,'' helped
run the 1972 conference on the ARPANET but says he's not bothered
by the attention to events of 1969, either.
</P>
<P>
   Now he looks forward to the upcoming celebration in Silicon
Valley. ``There are many occasions to celebrate the birthday'' of
the Internet, Metcalfe said. ``It's any excuse for a party!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
