<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1548 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-COMMENT-ART-BOS &LR;      09-22 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-COMMENT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MVP CANDIDATE GARCIAPARRA SKIPS THE STUMP SPEECHES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Every time you see Pedro Martinez pitch these days,
your admiration for the man and his talents grows greater and
greater. More than Roger Clemens he excels. More than Luis Tiant he
radiates. More than any other star pitcher to come to Fenway Park
over the years, he puts something special on the table. Luckily,
we're all around to drink it in.
</P>
<P>
   As he left the field Tuesday night after another historic
performance, a chant of ``MVP, MVP'' began, as if his 3-0 shutout
and 300th strikeout were the only measures of his greatness. They
weren't, as we found out later. Martinez, pitching like a man
possessed, calmly and efficiently had gone to work knowing that his
favorite aunt, Maria, had died. He got the news just 15 minutes
before game time. There was little emotion as he went the distance
for his 22d victory of the season. But there was plenty of it
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to do what she'd want me to do,'' he would say.
``Which is to do well. That's what I tried to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to put it in the back of your mind the best you can.
Yes, we were close, very close. I can't tell you how close.''
</P>
<P>
   When the news trickled through the clubhouse after the game,
everybody knew what Martinez meant by that. There were still some
wanting to talk about the Most Valuable Player, which traditionally
goes to an everyday player, such as shortstop Nomar Garciaparra.
But Martinez's performance under the greatest kind of pressure a
player can feel won't go without notice.
</P>
<P>
   He is a great pitcher. But only a man with unbelievable courage
could have done what he did. Martinez did his job, which included
addressing a sympathetic media corps that would have left him alone
at the drop of a microphone. He stood his ground and answered all
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three hundred strikeouts,'' he said. ``It wasn't special at
all. I've done it before. It's nice to get 300 strikeouts in the
American League and a record. But our main concern is reaching the
playoffs and doing something about it. I didn't even know that I
broke a record until I looked at the scoreboard.''
</P>
<P>
   In becoming the second pitcher to record 300 strikeouts in each
league (after Randy Johnson), Martinez was certainly worth the
price of admission. Pitching coach Joe Kerrigan, who saw a young
Randy Johnson in Montreal, gave this technical assessment of
Martinez:
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he dominates is something. He does it with three
pitches. You might see a guy come along with a great
fastball-curveball-slider combination. But just to see three
dominant pitches is amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jimy Williams, who saw his share of great pitchers in
Atlanta, added, ``I really don't know if we understand how special
a pitcher we're seeing in 1999 and we really won't until time goes
by. Especially when you look at the ERAs across the board, the home
run totals, and teams scoring what they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty special just to have the opportunity to watch this
man pitch every game. I've seen guys win games but not with the
strikeouts. All kinds of different pitches. I've never seen
anything like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez knows things easily could have been worse. He missed
two weeks with a sore shoulder. Had he continued to throw instead
of going on the disabled list in July, it might have led to a
dreary end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's consistency,'' said Martinez. ``I've been healthy enough
to go out there and pitch well for the team. That's what I've been
doing. I'm focused to go out and pitch well and help this team get
to the playoffs and take them a little bit further than I did last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be debate about the MVP. Garciaparra, with a
league-leading .359 batting average, is making his bid. He is
closing in on 200 hits and will have 100 RBIs. A year ago, he
finished second in the balloting.
</P>
<P>
   But let's not forget Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the writers who choose the MVP are traditionalists and
don't like to pick players who go out there only every fifth day,''
said Kerrigan. ``But every now and then a pitcher comes along who
deserves their consideration. Pedro is one of those pitchers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
