<SLUG> BC-GENZYME-GOATS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENZYME'S GOLDEN GOATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLTON, Mass. _ Eight years ago Genzyme Corp. set about
building a $110 million cathedral-like bio-manufacturing plant in
Boston to make a single drug that sells for $170,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   If Genzyme's executives could have done it all over again,
they'd have skipped the sophisticated bio-reactors, lengthy
stainless steel plumbing, and high-priced architecture, and bought
a farm.
</P>
<P>
   There they might have produced the same drug, called Cerezyme,
at a fraction of the former cost, using some imported New Zealand
goats housed in spotless barns and tended by a 70-person staff,
including veterinarians with a molecular biology lab and a
hospital-style operating room at their disposal.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Genzyme did just that. Here, on 184 verdant acres, a
Genzyme subsidiary, Genzyme Transgenics Corp., maintains a herd of
1,600 goats whose lactating females are producing in their milk
nearly a dozen other proposed drugs _ developmental therapies that
hold promise for treating diseases including arthritis, malaria,
diabetes, AIDS, and psoriasis.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the only reason why Cerezyme, which is used to treat a
rare spleen disorder, is not being produced here is that when
Genzyme was building its showcase Boston factory it did not fully
understand the scientific potential of goats.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time we realized that we could produce Cerezyme using
goats, we were (already) very far along with building the Allston
plant and using more traditional bio-manufacturing,'' said Suzanne
Groet, vice president of business development for Framingham-based
Genzyme Transgenics, which runs the Charlton farm.
</P>
<P>
   Today the farm is a busy place, nearly five years old and with
capacity for up to 2,000 goats. It focuses on producing proposed
drugs for such major pharmaceutical makers as Eli Lilly &AMP; Co.,
Bristol Myers-Squibb, Centocor Corp., and BASF Corp.
</P>
<P>
   These companies are partnering with Genzyme Transgenics to test
whether some existing and new drugs can be produced less
expensively and with greater manufacturing flexibility, according
to Dr. Sandra Lehrman, president of Genzyme Transgenics.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the capital needed to make 100 kilograms per
year of a pharmaceutical the traditional way with bricks, mortar,
bio-reactors, and stainless steel, initial production will cost
between $20 million and $70 million,'' said Lehrman.
</P>
<P>
   ``With transgenic goats, the costs are between $2 million and $5
million to produce the same amount with probably 35 goats, each
producing 5 to 10 grams of the protein per liter of milk. It's a
great business.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the drugs that the goats now produce, antithrombin III,
is currently in pivotal trials in small groups of patients with
heart conditions, in Europe and the United States, to assess its
efficacy in regulating blood clotting.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to seek US Food and Drug Administration
approval for the drug next year, which would make Genzyme the first
US company to receive such clearance for a human drug produced in
an animal. That would put it ahead of two European companies,
Pharming Group of the Netherlands, which is working with rabbits,
and Pharmaceutial Proteins Ltd., the Scottish company best known
for its cloned sheep Dolly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see cloning as a research effort that could potentially
create efficiencies in production for us,'' said Lehrman. ``Our
focus is producing drugs for chronic diseases, like cancer,
diabetes, and arthritis, that require large amounts of medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Genzyme Transgenics said that even before it gains
FDA approval for ATIII's blood-clotting qualities, it hopes to
launch clinical trials for a variant, antiangiogenic antithrombin
III (or aaATIII) with potential for treating cancer.
</P>
<P>
   This proposed drug targets a cancerous tumor's blood supply with
the goal of shrinking it and preventing its regrowth. It was
developed at Children's Hospital in Boston in the laboratory led by
cancer researcher Dr. Judah Folkman.
</P>
<P>
   And while similar versions of the drug are being developed using
traditional biotechnology manufacturing practices by EntreMed Inc.,
of Rockville, Md., Genzyme officials privately say they have a
competitive edge because they can produce their version more
quickly and less expensively using goats.
</P>
<P>
   In the world of pharmaceutical factories, Genzyme, more than any
other US drug or biotech company, is devoted to creating a thriving
business in low-cost manufacturing of protein-based pharmaceuticals
using dairy animials.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the goat farm, which is the largest devoted to
pharmaceutical production, Genzyme is also working with the
Pharming Group to produce a drug in the milk of rabbits to treat
Pompe's disease, a rare genetic disorder that causes muscular
degeneration in infants.
</P>
<P>
   ``This technology is gaining a higher profile as a viable and
efficient option for production of therapeutic proteins,'' Mary Ann
Gray, a biotechnology analyst at Raymond James &AMP; Associates, a Wall
Street investment firm, said in a recent report. ``Goats are
attractive for this production process because they breed
rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   Genzyme has 40 goats available for its antithrombin III clinical
trials, but because the goats are so productive, only three will be
needed to make enough of the compound for the tests.
</P>
<P>
   With goats instead of complex bio-reactor equipment, said
Gregory Liposky, vice president of operations at the Genzyme
Transgenics farm, ``We can make large amounts of protein-based
drugs, such as for malaria and arthritis, that are just simply too
expensive to produce any other way.''
</P>
<P>
   The company recently purchased an additional 184 acres adjacent
to the current farm for future expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Just outside Liposky's office are photographs of Genzyme
executives, including chief executive Henri Termeer, that mimic the
current American Dairy Association milk mustache ads.
</P>
<P>
   Termeer's bears the tag line: ``We put more in the mustache.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
