<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1553 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d BC-FOOD-CHILD-PEPIN-2TAK     09-22 1436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHILD-PEPIN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMEONE'S IN THE KITCHEN WITH JULIA 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (Includes recipes)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ At the stove, they act like an old married
couple, except they don't finish each other's sentences. Jacques
Pepin asks Julia Child how she wants the tomatoes sliced and
whether she likes Dijon mustard in the dressing. He, the
professional chef and television veteran, defers to her. She, the
most beloved home cook in the nation, encourages him to be
chattier.
</P>
<P>
   In her kitchen, where hundreds of famous people have come
through and dozens of TV shows have been filmed, Child and Pepin
are making salade Nicoise together. It's probably their thousandth.
It's not quite the same salad that will appear on their new 22-part
TV series, ``Julia and Jacques Cooking at Home,'' nor is it exactly
like the one in the companion book, ``Julia and Jacques Cooking at
Home'' (Alfred A. Knopf). This is a new kind of cooking, announces
the French-born Pepin. ``Cuisine d'opportunity,'' he says,
pronouncing the English word ``dop-pear-tune-ee-tay'' so it sounds
convincingly French.
</P>
<P>
   They aren't quite cleaning out the fridge, but there are things
left from other meals. A crew from National Public Radio had been
there that morning, so remnants from their Caesar salad lesson are
on hand.
</P>
<P>
   The Nicoise ingredients seem common enough: lettuce, green
beans, tomatoes, potatoes, eggs, and canned tuna. Some come from
the supermarket (``Stah Mahket,'' says Child, in the breathy voice
so familiar it makes you smile). And none requires complicated
preparation.
</P>
<P>
   But a little magic takes place when Child and Pepin go at this
food. All sense of ordinariness disappears. She plops and plunks
and whooshes, all the while regaling the visitor with stories and
opinions. He's fascinating to watch just chopping an onion, or
flipping a skilletful of mushrooms so high in the air that it
reminds you that the French word ``saute'' means ``jump.''
</P>
<P>
   This is four-handed cooking that ends with all 20 fingers on the
platter.
</P>
<P>
   The Nicoise will get the outer leaves of romaine _ the hearts
went into NPR's Caesar. ``I'm probably one of the few people still
alive who had Caesar salad with the original Caesar,'' says Child,
who turned 87 in August. She was raised in Pasadena, Calif., and
when she was 9, her parents took her to Tijuana, Mexico, where
restaurateur Caesar Cardini made his salads tableside. ``Tijuana
was a cheapy, tumbledown border town,'' she says. ``They had one
nice hotel. The rest of it was cheapo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You go there,'' Pepin interjects, ``for a divorce'' _ he says
dee-vorce _ ``and a Caesar salad.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Caesar, says Child, ``people didn't eat salad. It was for
sissies.''
</P>
<P>
   The banter between the two is easy, built from a friendship that
goes back some 40 years. When they met, Pepin was new to this
country and Child was fairly new to cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Born to restaurateurs in Bourg-en-Bresse, near Lyon, Pepin had
been cooking professionally since his 13th birthday. As a very
young man, he was chef to French President Charles de Gaulle. When
Pepin came to New York, he met the late Helen McCully, then editor
of House Beautiful. ``She was Jacques's American mother,'' says
Child.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very influential,'' agrees Pepin. ``She was feisty and
a wonderful woman.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early years of Pepin and Child's friendship, whenever he
and his wife, Gloria, came to Boston, he would stop by to see Child
and her late husband, Paul. They'd all have dinner together in the
famous kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Now, when Pepin comes, he cooks. He's standing next to the old
Garland stove, chopping garlic for the wild mushrooms he picked the
day before. He's brought only some of the 15 pounds he collected
near his home in Connecticut, but the haul includes some prized
chicken-of-the-woods. These will accompany the Nicoise because,
during mushroom season, Pepin has been known to show up anywhere
there's a stove and start cooking his wild finds.
</P>
<P>
   Child goes to the refrigerator and finds green beans, all topped
and tailed and ready for blanching. ``I'll put them in the same pot
as the potatoes,'' says Pepin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do separate ones,'' suggests Child. ``I'll get some hot water
going.''
</P>
<P>
   The eggs, already hard-cooked, wait in a bowl of cold water.
Pepin has also brought bouquets of fresh greens and herbs _
purslane, sorrel, basil, tarragon _ which he adds to the romaine.
Child doesn't peel the tomatoes, although she might have in earlier
years, so there is only the simple task of cutting them into
quarters. She has Lazio tuna fish in olive oil, which she orders
from a company on the West Coast. ``There are only 3 more grams of
fat in oil than there is in water-packed tuna. People are so afraid
of fat. This fear of fat has ruined the tuna industry and ruined
the beef industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Child's Nicoise is the traditional salad served all over
Provence, dressed with lemon juice and olive oil. She remembers
ordering Nicoise as soon as she landed at the Nice airport (when it
had a good restaurant), en route to the Childs' house in the south
of France. Pepin likes to add fresh tuna to his Nicoise, and he
makes his vinaigrette in a jar.
</P>
<P>
   They're producing variations on a theme, as they have done since
their collaboration began, while Pepin was teaching classes at
Boston University's Seminars in the Culinary Arts and its cooking
certificate programs. Child joined him, and eventually they taped
``Cooking in Concert'' before a live audience. The response, by all
accounts, was overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   Pepin liked the idea of turning it into a series. He called KQED
in San Francisco, the public television station where he had filmed
``Jacques Pepin's Cooking Techniques'' and ``Today's Gourmet With
Jacques Pepin.''
</P>
<P>
   The station told Pepin it didn't know if it had the money. So he
went to Geoffrey Drummond, whose A La Carte Communications has
filmed _ in Child's kitchen _ ``In Julia's Kitchen With Master
Chefs,'' then ``Baking with Julia.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepin and Child heap praise on Drummond, who agreed to let them
do a series that was largely improvised. That meant holding
discussions before taping, of course, and having a backup kitchen
of cooks ready to produce anything. ``The way we did it was a bit
different,'' says Pepin. ``We didn't want to do a book that said,
`He said, she said.' We just cooked together. It's not
confrontational. It's just bantering.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We filmed two a day for a couple of weeks,'' says Child. ``It
was no sweat, very informal. We didn't do any recipes ahead. They
brought all the standard stuff. It was more difficult for the
cameraman and producer. They were a bit lost. But it turned out to
be more the way it is really done in the kitchen.''
</P>
<P>
   He cooked. She cooked. They chatted, got silly sometimes, and
improvised on French culinary traditions. ``It was cuisine
spontanee,'' says Pepin.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way they like it. Decide as they work. ``Shall we put
it on a platter?'' Child asks Pepin. ``I think it's nicer than in a
bowl. I hate having it nicely arranged and then tossed and
ruined.'' She pulls out a large round platter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have many beans,'' says Child, ``but enough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomatoes in wedges, Julia?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I like wedges. I don't bother to peel them. I have a
lemon here _ I did have a lemon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I used it in the Caesar.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I found the other half. Do we have enough elements?''
</P>
<P>
   Pepin surveys the counter. ``Yes, beans, potatoes, eggs. We have
the tuna. Do you want some mustard in the dressing?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a little dressing here. See how you like this.''
</P>
<P>
   She holds the dressing so he can dip his finger into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good. We have olives, we have dressing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more lemon if we need it.''
</P>
<P>
   He puts the dressed greens in the middle of the platter. She
halves the eggs and places them at the edges. With his hands, Pepin
picks up the whole round of tuna and breaks it apart into large
chunks. Child has found a can of anchovies (from the Caesar).
</P>
<P>
   ``One reason people don't like anchovies is that they have an
old can in the refrigerator,'' she says. Pepin breaks up the
anchovies with his fingers and scatters them around the salad.
</P>
<P>
   Child uses her hands to add the tomatoes to the platter, then he
adds the sliced potatoes in two mounds at the edges. Green beans go
between the tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
