<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1559 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d BC-FOOD-CHILD-PEPIN-2ND &LR;      09-22 1345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHILD-PEPIN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 CAMBRIDGE, Mass.: ... the tomatoes.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The salad is finished. All that's left on the kitchen table is a
small plate that once held tuna and now holds its oil, and an empty
can of anchovies with oil on the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Pepin picks up both. Tuna oil goes all over the greens and
vegetables. He pours the anchovy oil onto the potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Then quickly: plates, forks, napkins, wine, and wine glasses.
Everyone dives in.
</P>
<P>
   Spontanee.
</P>
<P>
   And awfully good.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
JULIA'S CAESAR SALAD
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   18 to 24 crisp, narrow leaves from hearts of 2 heads romaine
lettuce, or 1 package romaine hearts (about 1 pound)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup plain toasted croutons (recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   1 large garlic clove, peeled
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup or more excellent olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 whole lemon, halved and seeded
</P>
<P>
   Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons freshly grated imported Parmigiano- Reggiano
cheese
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Separate the leaves and wash them carefully to keep them whole.
Roll them loosely in clean towels and keep refrigerated until
serving time.
</P>
<P>
   To flavor the croutons, crush the garlic clove with the flat of
a chef's knife, sprinkle on 1/4 teaspoon of salt, and mince well.
Pour about 1 tablespoon of olive oil on the garlic and mash again
with the knife, rubbing and pressing to make a soft puree.
</P>
<P>
   Scrape the puree into the frying pan, add another tablespoon of
oil, and warm over low-medium heat. Add the croutons and toss for 1
or 2 minutes to infuse them with the garlic oil, then remove from
the heat.
</P>
<P>
   To coddle the egg, bring a small saucepan of water to a simmer.
Pierce the large end of the egg with a pushpin to prevent cracking,
then simmer it for exactly 1 minute.
</P>
<P>
   Have all ready the dressing ingredients and a salad fork and
spoon for tossing.
</P>
<P>
   Drizzle 2 tablespoons of olive oil over the romaine leaves and
toss to coat, lifting the leaves from the bottom and turning them
toward you, so they tumble over like a wave. Sprinkle with a
generous pinch of salt and several grinds of pepper, toss once or
twice, then add the lemon juice and several drops of
Worcestershire, and toss again. Taste for seasoning and add more,
if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Crack the egg and drop it right on the romaine leaves, then toss
to break it up and coat the leaves. Sprinkle on the cheese, toss
briefly, then add the croutons (and garlicky bits in the pan, if
you wish) and toss for the last time, just to mix them into the
salad.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange 6 or more leaves in a single layer on individual plates,
scatter the croutons all around, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2 to 3.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
PLAIN TOASTED CROUTONS
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees. Remove the crusts from 4 or
more thick slices of home-style white bread and slice the bread
into 1/2-inch strips, then cut the strips into 1/2-inch cubes.
Spread the cubes in a single layer on a cookie sheet and set in the
oven for about 10 minutes, turning once or twice, until lightly
toasted on all sides. Spread the cubes on a tray to cool before
using or freezing.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 cups.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
JULIA'S COMPOSED NEAR-NICOISE SALAD
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 large red onion, peeled, halved, and sliced into thin half
rounds
</P>
<P>
   1 large green bell pepper, peeled if you wish, quartered, and
sliced into long thin strips
</P>
<P>
   1 cup or more green and black olives
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 cups small tomatoes (combination of red cherry and yellow
pear types recommended)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound green beans (about 2 cups), trimmed, blanched, dried,
and chilled
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup or more Jacques's vinaigrette in a jar (recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   4 hard-boiled eggs, peeled and halved lengthwise
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup or so mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1 (2-ounce) can anchovies, packed in olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 (12-ounce) can tuna fish, best quality, packed in olive oil,
or 2 smaller cans
</P>
<P>
   Sprigs of basil, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Toss the onion to separate the slices and mound them all loosely
in the center of the platter. Then divide the pepper slices into 2
equal portions and arrange on opposite sides of the platter.
Similarly, arrange the olives and the tomatoes each in 2 piles, on
either side of the onion mound, creating a symmetrical design. In a
bowl, toss the green beans with 2 tablespoons of the vinaigrette to
coat evenly, then arrange them in the remaining opposite spaces of
the platter. Nestle each of the 8 egg halves in between the
vegetables, or arrange them around the outside of the platter,
spaced equally. Top each egg half with a teaspoon of mayonnaise,
drape an anchovy fillet over the mayo, and drizzle the anchovy oil
on top.
</P>
<P>
   Invert the open can of tuna directly over the onions, and shake
to release the fish (with all of its oil) in a round in the center
of the salad.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, drizzle 1/3 cup or more of the dressing over the entire
salad. Stand a large spray of basil leaves in the center of the
tuna and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
JACQUES'S NEAR-NICOISE SALAD
</P>
<P>
   WITH SAUTEED FRESH TUNA
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces fresh tuna, in a chunk
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup or so Jacques's vinaigrette in a jar (recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped scallions
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cooked waxy potatoes, such as fingerlings or small red
or white new potatoes, in 1/2-inch chunks
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons small black Nicoise olives
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup thinly sliced red onion
</P>
<P>
   5 or 6 fresh green basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 small ripe tomato, cut into wedges
</P>
<P>
   1 hard-boiled egg, quartered lengthwise into wedges
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Large handful of mesclun or other tender salad greens
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cut the raw tuna into 1/3-inch-thick slices (about 4 or 5) and
sprinkle with half the salt. Coat the bottom of a frying pan with 1
or 2 tablespoons of the vinaigrette and set over high heat. When
sizzling, quickly lay all the tuna pieces flat in the pan and cook
for about 20 seconds, until just opaque on the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Flip the slices over, cook another 10 seconds, then remove the
pan from the heat, allowing the tuna to finish cooking while you
assemble the salad.
</P>
<P>
   Place the scallions, potato chunks, olives, onion, basil leaves,
and the tomato and egg wedges in the mixing bowl. Drizzle on about
2 to 3 tablespoons of the vinaigrette, season with the rest of the
salt and the black pepper, and toss briefly to coat. Add the
mesclun to the bowl and toss again, gently.
</P>
<P>
   Turn the salad out onto a dinner plate, and arrange the chunky
vegetable and egg pieces _ if they are hidden by the mesclun leaves
_ so they are nicely displayed. Lay the tuna slices on top of the
mound of greens and drizzle the pan juices over the salad. Serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 1 or 2.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
JULIA'S LEMON-OIL DRESSING
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced shallots or scallions
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons Dijon-style prepared mustard
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons freshly squeezed lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   About 1/4 teaspoon salt or more to taste
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup excellent olive oil
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Put the shallots or scallions, mustard, lemon juice, salt, and
pepper in a small mixing bowl and whisk until well blended.
</P>
<P>
   Pour in the oil slowly, in droplets at first, and then in a thin
stream, whisking constantly until the oil has been completely
emulsified and the dressing has thickened. Taste and adjust the
seasoning. Use immediately. If the dressing seperates while
standing, whisk to blend.
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 2/3 cup.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
JACQUES'S VINAIGRETTE IN A JAR
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons chopped garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Dijon-style prepared mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup red or white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup extra-virgin olive oil or peanut oil, or mixture of both
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Put all of the ingredients in a jar, screw on the lid, and shake
very well. Taste and adjust the seasonings, adding more oil or
vinegar, as you like.
</P>
<P>
   Store in the refrigerator up to 2 weeks. Shake to blend before
using.
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 1 1/2 cups.
</P>
