<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1563 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-DEMOCRATS-JEFFORDS-BO     09-22 1434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATS-JEFFORDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME DEMOCRATS, JEFFORDS NOT SO MODERATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLEBURY, Vt. _ Until now, it would have been fair to call
Senator James M. Jeffords a favorite dance partner of the
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The Vermont Republican was the ``nice guy'' to his liberal
counterparts _ a softspoken Ivy Leaguer who talked about helping
families and educating kids. His record was Democrat-friendly, too,
voting for gun control, health care for the disabled, and funding
for the National Endowment for the Arts. When President Clinton was
impeached, Jeffords was the first Republican senator to say he
would vote to acquit.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent months, Jeffords has transformed into something
else in the minds of Democrats: a bull's eye. Democratic Party
officials say Jeffords has begun acting like a hardline
conservative, first voting in favor of a Republican managed
health-care plan, then, as they see it, caving in on a GOP tax cut
bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has very carefully created an image for himself up here in
Vermont as someone with a moderate to liberal voting record, and
the Democratic Party and our Democratic candidates are going to go
to great lengths to point out that's not necessarily the case,''
said Mark Michaud, executive director of the Vermont Democratic
Party. Beating Jeffords, he said, ``will be our highest priority in
terms of next year's campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The attack comes 14 months before Jeffords is up for reelection
_ and is seen as a clear sign Democrats are determinedly plotting
his demise. But with Jeffords' power as chairman of the Health,
Education, Labor, and Pensions Committee, and a voting record that
is nearly identical to some Democrats', the strategy may have its
drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Although Democrats will try to sell Jeffords as a conservative,
he has generally been in sync with the state's independent-minded
voters, aides to House and Senate Democrats said. Further, even
some Democrats concede Jeffords' defeat could reduce the party's
influence in the labor committee, by removing a mostly-reliable
ally.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Bernard Sanders, Vermont's only House member, has
not said whether he will run. But he is seriously considering it.
</P>
<P>
   If he runs, he would have the backing of the Democratic Party,
and if he wins, the chairman of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee, Robert Torricelli, has promised that Sanders would have
an equal shot at committee assignments, even though he is a
registered Independent. Other opponents are lining up as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim Jeffords has taken some positions and votes in leadership
roles that are terrifically bad politics in Vermont,'' said Jim
Jordan, political director of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee. ``He is, of course, naturally much less conservative
than most of them, but that's part of the deal when you're a
committee chairman. And nowhere was that evident than during the
HMO debate.''
</P>
<P>
   This summer, that debate resulted in the passage of a
GOP-sponsored bill that covers only the 48 million Americans who
belong to health-care plans exempt from state regulation. Senate
Democrats _ all of whom voted to reject the GOP bill _ lambasted it
as weak, because it excludes 113 million people. President Clinton
promised to veto it.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, who could pose the most serious threat to Jeffords,
opposes the Republican HMO plan. Another potential challenger,
Democratic Vermont state Senator Jan Backus, pounced on the vote:
``We're disappointed that at the federal level they don't seem able
to do patient protections we've already done,'' Backus said,
referring to Vermont laws that guarantee a woman's right to make
her obstetrician/gynecologist her primary care physician.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffords, however, stands by his vote in favor of the bill. The
Republican version is less expensive, according to the
Congressional Budget Office, which predicted a 6.1 percent rise in
insurance premiums if the Democratic plan were passed. Jeffords
said that could have led to the cancellation of some people's
health care plans altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Said his state director, Jolinda H. LaClair: ``I don't know that
the Democratic bill would have taken care of patients in the way
they need.'' What Jeffords did, she said, was ``try to look at
things that were realistic, that did not threaten patient care or
the quality of our drug supply.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether voters will see Jeffords' final vote as
irresponsible or see his ability to help establish any patient
protection in a Republican-controlled Senate as a victory.
</P>
<P>
   His vote to approve the $792 billion GOP tax cut package could
cut both ways, too. Although he finally voted in favor of the bill,
which Sanders attacked as ``the most irresponsible legislation . .
. in years,'' Jeffords also worked for compromises during the
debate, ensuring, for example, that certain low-income workers
would have their marriage penalty tax eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeffords' opponents may be hard-pressed to persuade voters
to judge the senator on a particular vote. He has defined himself
as having power in Washington; if Jeffords is part of a
conservative leadership in the Senate, allies said, he is one who
has brought federal dollars to the state in the form of grants for
education, transportation projects, and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   During a visit to a day-care center here this month, Jeffords
proudly announced a $409,810 Department of Education grant to the
Family Resource Partnership Project. Then he settled in to hear
employees' worries. No one seemed concerned about Jeffords' recent
votes; several were eager to talk about what they perceived as his
record overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't view Jim as either a Democrat or a Republican. We
view Jim as a child advocate,'' said Kathi J. Apgar, president of
the Vermont Association for the Education of Young Children. ``I
think it would be only misinformed people that would vote to
replace Jim's position of leadership in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   That is clearly the defense Jeffords hopes to use. ``For a small
state that has very little power outside of seniority, we are in
the best position to help Vermont right now,'' he said, referring
to his alliance with the senior Vermont senator, Democrat Patrick
J. Leahy. ``Voters are very aware that I vote independently. They
watch me closely, and they know I'm not tied down by any political
party.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders could prove to be a formidable opponent. Because Vermont
has one House seat, Sanders is a familiar name statewide. He is
also a beloved character _ a socialist who would offer a distinct
alternative to Jeffords. In a Democratic poll this March, Sanders
led Jeffords, 45 percent to 40 percent. Recently, he has made
headlines by attacking an IBM plan to change its pension plan in a
way that could adversely affect seniors _ embarrassing Jeffords by
being the first to tackle the issue in Vermont, where IBM is the
biggest employer.
</P>
<P>
   Even LaClair admits Sanders would create a ``tough race.'' But
the specter of a challenge has its advantages for Jeffords: he
already has more than $650,000 on hand, and fund-raising would be
greatly helped if donors felt he faced a real threat.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Jeffords has been an unpredictable ally to
Democrats. He voted against a minimum-wage increase in 1998. He
supported bills opposed by labor unions that let employers handle
workplace disputes.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Senate Democrats who could lose the most if Jeffords
departs, some Democratic aides said. He is still among the most
independent legislators in the GOP, and would likely be replaced by
a more conservative senator as Labor committee chairman if he lost
and Republicans maintained control.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he supported Clinton policies in 69 percent of his
votes. He is also one of a dwindling number of Northeast moderates
whom Democrats can rely on to help cobble a majority; another
moderate Republican senator, John Chafee of Rhode Island, is
retiring, which means that number could shrink further still.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffords is likely to use that argument in his campaign. And
Bill Mayers, an administrator at the Parent-Child Center in
Middlebury, said that if Sanders runs, ``a lot of people will be
torn.'' At the same time, he said Vermont ``has this image of being
rural and provincial, and in one sense, that's right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Being farmers, you don't look at what's happening this day.
You look at what's happening this season,'' he said. ``You look at
the big picture. And I think that's what will happen with
Jeffords.''
</P>
</TEXT>
