<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WEST WING' CLEANS UP THE WHITE HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE WEST WING 
Starring: Martin Sheen, Rob Lowe, Moira Kelly, John Spencer,
Allison Janney, Bradley Whitford 
On: NBC, Wednesday at 9 p.m. 
Rated: TV14 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The networks may indeed be infusing prime time with sex and
violence, as Steve Allen and his right brigade have complained. But
``The West Wing,'' NBC's slick new drama about the Oval Office, is
``Little House on the Prairie'' next to the ``Animal House'' of
recent White House news.
</P>
<P>
   The show is a smart, exhilarating, well-written hour that, if
anything, is a little naive about the folks who run our nation's
most important office. The men and women behind Martin Sheen's
liberal president seem to be loyal, principled employees whose
worst flaws may be workaholism and over-enthusiasm. Despite the
country's disillusionment with politics, ``The West Wing'' takes a
sweetly patriotic view of American government, especially when
Sheen shows up to spout his folksy, avuncular wisdom. His scenes
are almost Capraesque. Of course, that doesn't mean the show won't
attract protest, and advertiser dismay, beginning with a slight of
the religious right. ``The West Wing'' is definitely not ``The
Right Wing.''
</P>
<P>
   This ultimate workplace drama is the latest baby from Aaron
Sorkin, the writer who became a TV phenomenon last season with the
half-hour ``Sports Night.'' It's simlarly peopled with high-strung
employees hooked on verbal volleys, but the White House characters
are less painfully earnest and robot-sounding than those on
``Sports Night.'' They include John Spencer's brusque chief of
staff, Brad Whitford's fiery deputy chief of staff, Richard
Schiff's cynical communications director, and Allison Janney's
press secretary, who slyly encourages the press to ``by all means
enjoy yourselves'' as they buzz around big news of the president's
sprained ankle. With some shrewd development, they could evolve
into a dynamic ``ER''-like ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Lowe is a standout as the deputy communications director, a
pretty boy who sleeps with a woman he later learns is a high-priced
hooker. Whoops. Lowe couldn't have asked for a better vehicle, and
there is amusing subtext to be found in his performance when you
recall the former Brat Packer's videotaped dalliance at the 1988
Democratic Convention. Woops. The fiesty Moira Kelly also shines as
a political consultant to a senator who is planning to run against
Sheen's President Josiah Bartlet.
</P>
<P>
   Sorkin's emphasis in ``The West Wing,'' at least based on the
premiere, is on the staffers' lives and not on the political
situations that face the administration. True to the tenor of our
time, the show doesn't ask viewers to keep up with complex and
newsy plot turns, other than a few references to Cuban refugees and
abortion. The goal is to make the White House resemble other
white-collar workplaces, with their complicated power structures
and stress issues. Except, of course, that the eyes of the world
are trained on this particular office, a fact that is bound to
haunt Lowe's Sam Seaborn as the season progresses.
</P>
<P>
   The premiere is just about as polished as TV gets these days.
Watch the way the episode races along, a wonder of smooth camera
glides and careful choreography, trademarks of the show's two other
executive producers, John Wells of ``ER'' and Thomas Schlamme, the
noted TV director of shows like ``The Practice'' and ``Sports
Night.'' The characters are constantly in motion, usually striding
down hallways, and the camera is always with them, unless it stops
for a moment to catch a small ancillary moment. While this
technique feels claustrophobic on ``Sports Night,'' it enlivens
``The West Wing,'' which features an expansive White House set.
It's a reproduction, and it looks almost better than real.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
