<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1580 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-ROOTS-2ND &LR;  &UR;      09-22 1664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-ROOTS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BROOKLINE, Mass.: ... of life.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was with such diligence that he attacked golf, and only after
he became a fair player, getting his handicap down to 9 (out of a
maximum of 18), did he join Verulam, the course designed in 1905 by
former British Open champion James Braid.
</P>
<P>
   Here again, Ryder's influence was instantly felt. Verulam was a
parkland course, designed to accommodate limited space, and it
originally consisted of nine holes with a tin shed for a clubhouse
built on land reluctantly leased to the town by the Earl of
Verulam. In 1909, soon after Ryder joined the club, the earl
suddenly had a change of heart, insisting that he would extend the
lease at affordable terms only if the course were expanded to 18
holes, with nine more on the other side of Cottonmill Lane. Ryder's
handiwork was detected in the earl's surprise support, and in 1911,
he was elected captain of Verulam for the first of three terms.
During that time, he oversaw the construction of the rambling
Edwardian clubhouse that replaced the shack.
</P>
<P>
   His epiphany concerning the plight of the touring pro did not
come until years later.
</P>
<P>
   During the early 1920s, the Ryder family would spend summer
vacations in the southeastern seaside retreat of Weymouth in Dorset
County. Automobiles were alien at the time; most families on
holiday would travel by train. But the Ryders would debark from a
magnificent Bentley of which they were all vigorously, and
justifiably, proud. For Sam, these getaways included golfing
pilgrimages to the Weymouth course Came Down, staffed by the noted
pros Charles, Ernest, and Reginald Whitcombe.
</P>
<P>
   Ryder was not above frivolity, such as wearing a ridiculous
wooly pink hat during occasional rounds. Helen, never accused of
having a sense of humor, would berate him when he wore it at
Verulam, and he would respond, ``Don't worry, everybody here knows
me.'' When he'd don the hat at Came Down and receive a similar
rebuke from his wife, he would say, ``Don't worry, nobody here
knows me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Whitcombe brothers came to know him, and befriend him. Their
conversations included tales of woe about their livelihood. They
were at the members' beck and call, they lamented, and had to
arrange their tournament schedules accordingly. British pros were
not paid for their time away from the course. Tournaments always
were scheduled to end on Fridays so the competitors could be back
at their clubs to serve the membership on weekends. And they were
paid a pittance compared to their American counterparts,
particularly the likes of Hagen, whose grandeur was as impressive
as his game.
</P>
<P>
   Ryder regarded all this sympathetically, but true to his nature,
he paid it more than lip service. Rather than simply condemning the
working conditions, he set about trying to improve them. He began
underwriting challenge matches at Verulam and neighboring clubs _
most notably the Heath and Heather Tournament July 10, 1923. Events
such as this attracted the cream of British golf: former Open
champions Harry Vardon and Ted Ray and J.H. Taylor and Duncan and
Braid, plus the shy, self-effacing Mitchell, whose lamentable
epitaph was that he was the greatest British golfer never to win
the Open.
</P>
<P>
   Prize money could reach as much as 450 pounds, and more than
competition, the intent was to supplement the pros' meager wages.
It was after one of these matches in late 1925 that Ryder
stunningly announced he had hired Mitchell, then the professional
at North Foreland, as his private pro. Perhaps Ryder was charmed by
Mitchell's personality or the fact that, like himself, Mitchell
once had been a gardener. Whatever the reason, the princely annual
salary of 500 pounds plus 250 pounds expenses freed Mitchell to
pursue tournament golf.
</P>
<P>
   That was the idea behind the hiring, but Ryder felt he could do
more on a larger level.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now here he was at Wentworth, accompanied by Joan and surrounded
by the most elite professionals on both sides of the ocean, plus a
crowd estimated at 2,000-3,000. The imperial Hagen had declared
himself US captain, and his lineup included Tommy Armour, defending
Open champion Jim Barnes, Cyril Walker, Al Watrous, Bill Mehlhorn,
Joe Kirkwood, Emmet French, Fred McLeod, and Joe Stein. The
Britons, led by nonplaying captain Taylor, featured Duncan,
Mitchell, Ray, Arthur Havers, Ernest Whitcombe, Aubrey Boomer,
Archie Compston, George Gadd, Herbert Jolly, and Fred Robson.
</P>
<P>
   Ryder followed them as they set out on Colt's tight 6,315-yard
creation, highlighted by his signature 11th hole, a 462-yard, par-4
dogleg right that required a fade over a mountain of heather, then
a draw to the green. Bordered by stately, ancient houses on prime
Surrey real estate, the course, baked by the sun and sprouting
heath and heather in devilish places, posed a test to the British,
a hopeless mystery to the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   As a concession, the Americans had agreed that the first day
would consist of foursomes, a format they rarely played but the
English relished. They also dominated, winning all five 36-hole
contests. Ryder delightedly watched the beloved Mitchell and Duncan
rout Hagen and Barnes, 9 and 8, in the day's main event.
</P>
<P>
   In the singles the following day, it was more of the same. The
lone American winner was Mehlhorn, who beat Compston on the 36th
hole. Whitcombe and French halved their match; otherwise, it was
all England. Ryder was positively giddy as Mitchell whipped Barnes,
8 and 7, and Duncan destroyed Hagen, 6 and 5, capping the hosts' 13
1/2-1 1/2 landslide.
</P>
<P>
   But establishing superiority hadn't been the point. Fostering
international goodwill had been. And while he was out of earshot,
Ryder would have been heartened to hear Hagen say in the wake of
the whipping, ``The spirit is so pleasant. Let's do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, Hagen, and Armour discussed the matter further and
decided, ``We've really enjoyed this. Let's talk to Mr. Ryder.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryder was unaware of all this as he and the players adjourned to
the small, round tables in the clubhouse lounge, the Burma Bar, for
the postmatch banquet of champagne and chicken sandwiches the
sponsor had promised.
</P>
<P>
   Ryder preferred Johnnie Walker, though he seldom imbibed in
public. But he was feeling magnanimous nonetheless as he proposed a
toast and said, ``We really should do this again.''
</P>
<P>
   Seated next to him, Duncan pounced on the opening. ``You know,
Mr. Ryder,'' he said, ``it would be great if we could do this every
year. You should donate a trophy, and we could play for it.''
</P>
<P>
   What a splendid idea, thought Ryder. And as usual, he acted upon
it. After returning to St. Albans, he commissioned the noted
British jewelers Mappin and Webb to design a gold trophy for 450
pounds. It was to be awarded regularly to the winner of the Ryder
Cup, and it was topped by the lifelike figure of a golfer.
</P>
<P>
   Abe Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first official Ryder Cup Matches were held at Worcester
Country Club in 1927, following the drafting of the Ryder Cup Deed.
Before the British team sailed for the US, Helen Ryder presented
the trophy to Gadd, representing the PGA, on the veranda of Verulam
Golf Club. Overwhelmed by the reception they received on the other
side of the Atlantic, the British were trounced, 9-2, at Worcester.
Two years later, the deed of trust was amended to hold the matches
biennially and to mandate that all players must be natives of the
country for which they were participating. One reason the 1926
matches at Wentworth are considered unofficial was that several
members of the US team were not American natives; in fact, some,
such as Barnes, hailed from Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
   By 1977, the format was altered for a three-day event: five
foursomes on the first day, five four-balls on the second, and 10
singles on the third. In 1979, after years of US domination, the
eligibility was changed to include players from throughout Europe.
Since then, European success _ and Ryder Cup interest _ have
increased exponentially.
</P>
<P>
   The 33d Ryder Cup Matches, now a billion-dollar enterprise, will
be held this weekend at The Country Club in Brookline.
</P>
<P>
   Verulam Golf Club, which bills itself as ``The Home of the Ryder
Cup,'' never has hosted a Ryder Cup. But it is stuffed with Ryder
memorabilia, including the mayoral portrait that dominates the
Ryder Room and an oil painting of Mitchell that was donated last
fall by Samuel Ryder's only two male heirs, great grandsons Sam and
Tom Ryder-Smith. Sam, who works on Disney cruises, will be at this
year's matches as a guest of the British PGA.
</P>
<P>
   Wentworth Golf Club hosted one Ryder Cup _ the 1953 matches,
which the Americans won, 6 1/2-5 1/2. It now features three courses
_ the East, the West, and the Edinburgh. The East no longer is
considered the championship course. The West is, though its first
hole was the original launching point for the East.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Ryder attended two more Ryder Cup Matches _ British
victories at Moortown in 1929 and Southport in 1933. The '33
matches were highlighted by the attendance of the Duke of Windsor,
the future King Edward VIII, who mingled with the crowd of 15,000,
as did a proud Ryder.
</P>
<P>
   Having contracted pneumonia on an annual Christmas vacation to
London, Ryder died on Jan. 2, 1936, and was buried in St. Albans
Cemetery. His estate amounted to 28,000 pounds, a rather modest
tally for a man of such obvious wealth. Before his death, he
explained why: ``I have given most of my money to religion and golf
during my lifetime, for I thought it would do rather more good than
after my death.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Material from the monograph ``Samuel Ryder'' by William B.
Murgatroyd and Alan Booth; golf historian Peter Fry; Wentworth and
Verulam golf clubs; former Wentworth secretary and managing
director Richard Doyle-Davidson; Ryder's granddaughter Mary Moore
and grandson-in-law John Ryder-Smith; and the Times of London was
used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
