<HEADLINE>
THREE ATTRACTIONS FROM SPAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Sergio Garcia is electric, spontaneous,
theatrical, passionate, vibrant. That combination has made him the
singular sensation of world golf.
</P>
<P>
   And typical of Spanish golf.
</P>
<P>
   As enthralling an international presence as the 19-year-old has
become since he turned pro five whole months ago, he is merely
perpetuating a tradition in his homeland. True, golf doesn't just
take a back seat to soccer along the Mediterranean, it gets stowed
in the trunk. But in spite of the game's lack of cachet, golf
greatness has become a virtual Spanish cottage industry. That's why
the king and queen are here to whoop it up for three of their
subjects _ Garcia, Jose Maria Olazabal, and Miguel Angel Jimenez _
who form a quarter of the European team that will face the United
States at The Country Club this weekend in the 33d Ryder Cup
Matches.
</P>
<P>
   That's also why the Spanish influence has played a major role in
the competition since the original Great Britain-US format was
expanded to include all of the Continent in 1979. Since then, the
onetime ho-hum American biennial showcase has turned into a true
duel, with Europe capturing the Cup five times, including the last
two.
</P>
<P>
   The bloodlines of achievement course through Garcia. Seve
Ballesteros, the original firebrand, and Olazabal have served as
the mentors of history's youngest Ryder Cupper since his
adolescence. But they have had accomplices in Spain's emergence on
the course. Jose Maria Canizares and Manuel Pinero have made lesser
contributions to Europe's Ryder renaissance, and Jimenez is the
latest supporting player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think just seeing all those Spanish players playing in the
Ryder Cup, it's an honor to be here,'' said Garcia. ``It's an honor
to be following in their footsteps.''
</P>
<P>
   The trail was blazed by Ballesteros, who played on three Ryder
champions and captained the 1997 victors at Valderrama on his
native soil. He's never been a barrel of laughs, but he is a
competitive furnace, and that has rubbed off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Seve has been a big inspiration over the years,'' said
European captain Mark James, a reserved Englishman. ``There's no
question about that. He certainly brought a unique type of passion
to the Matches. He has a certain kind of charisma which has a
magnified effect during the week of the Ryder Cup. And now we have
Sergio Garcia, who has risen through to become _ we regard him as a
young Seve.''
</P>
<P>
   That Seve's game has deteriorated, which is why he's not here.
But Olazabal, the 1999 Masters champion, serves as a reminder of
Ballesteros in his prime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the inception of the European Ryder Cup team, it's been
Seve, hasn't it, that has dominated that,'' said another subdued
son of the Empire, Scotland's Colin Montgomerie. ``And with his
partnership with Olazabal, they're the most successful partnership
in Ryder Cup history.''
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal doesn't consider that a coincidence. Both he and
Ballesteros have been visceral forces, and he believes it's a
product of their heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way we are, most of us, anyway,'' he said. ``It's
very difficult to see a Spanish person which is very quiet and
doesn't react to certain situations. We are not as calm as some of
the British, that's for sure, or Germans or Swedish. And sometimes
it might play against us, but sometimes it plays in our favor. And
it's just a matter of driving that force in your benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest incarnation is Garcia, who has enchanted his
audiences even while bedazzling them. His spectacular success _
which included a third-place finish in the Byron Nelson Classic,
his second US pro tournament, and a victory in the European Tour's
Irish Open less than two months after his debut _ crested in the
PGA Championship at Medinah, Ill., last month. There Garcia
finished second by a stroke to America's designated prodigy, Tiger
Woods, in the standings but overtook him in the popularity polls.
Not only has the kid flourished, but he's looked as if he's having
a grand time doing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just like that,'' he said. ``I think most of the Spanish
persons are just like that. They are very open persons. They are
very funny. They're always trying to make friends. That's what I
always try to do.''
</P>
<P>
   That's partially what makes him a big deal around the world. And
just one of the guys at home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
