<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-BARNES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1975 _ BARNES GOES BEAR-HUNTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ It is an exaggeration to say that Brian
Barnes is bigger than life. There have been times in his golfing
career, however, when this massive man with the Popeye arms has at
least been able to look life eye-to-eye. Like the time when he
played his final round early and headed straight to the bar, at
about the same time the wind started howling and the rain started
pouring and the scores started soaring. Next thing anyone knew,
Barnes was tied for the lead.
</P>
<P>
   They retrieved him from the bar for the playoff, which he won,
of course. It may have been the time he marked his ball with a beer
can _ or that could have been another tournament. Doesn't much
matter, because there is always another tale to tell when the topic
is Brian Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   He was a drinker, wasn't he?
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus handicap,'' said Barnes, a recovering alcoholic.
</P>
<P>
   But he was also a tough competitor and at the 1975 Ryder Cup at
Laurel Valley Golf Club in Ligonier, Penn., Barnes stole the show.
</P>
<P>
   That competition was pretty much going the way they always did
in those days _ that is, an American rout. It was 4-0 after the
opening foursomes and through two days it was 12 1/2-3 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Fearful of putting the spectators to sleep _ if they even had
decided to stay _ US captain Arnold Palmer had to do something. ``I
have been told that it's a fact,'' said Barnes, ``that Arnie had
gone to Bernard Hunt, who was our captain, and asked him
specifically who he thought might give Jack (Nicklaus) a bit of a
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to have somebody who might possibly have the chance
of bringing him down a peg or two. And Bernard said, `The only guy
I have who hits the ball as far as Jack does, and is not a bad
match player, is Barnesy.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said he had played with Nicklaus before and though ``he
was my hero, always has been,'' the big Englishman was certainly
not in awe. His play showed it as Barnes, smoking his pipe all the
way, won, 4 and 2, in the morning singles competition.
</P>
<P>
   Now it was Nicklaus's turn to orchestrate things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack went to Arnold,'' said Barnes, ``and basically said, `To
keep the interest going and the spectators going, you've gotta give
me an opportunity to get my own back with Barnesy.' ''
</P>
<P>
   This was just a month after Nicklaus had won his fourth PGA
Championship, just five months removed from his fifth Masters
title. In other words, he was in his prime _ and his competitive
juices were now flowing.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus started birdie-birdie. ``But as luck would have it,''
said Barnes, ``he didn't continue on that vein and whatever
happened, I beat him. Made a birdie from 10 feet on the 17th to
win, 2 and 1.
</P>
<P>
   The US trounced Great Britain &AMP; Ireland, 21-11, At the closing
ceremonies, Palmer praised his team, but couldn't resist a playful
jab at Nicklaus. ``Even Jack, who lost twice today. But he doesn't
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Nicklaus, his ears burning at such a comment, snapped:
``Yes I do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
