   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GLF-RYDER-TCC (Brookline, Mass.) _ The Country Club has been
around for so long now (117 years) that fable has overtaken fact.
By John Powers. 1000 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   GLF-RYDER-GARCIA (Brookline, Mass.) _ Sergio Garcia is electric,
spontaneous, theatrical, passionate, vibrant. That's why he's the
sensation of world golf. And typical of Spanish golf. By Bob Duffy.
680 words.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-RYDER-ROOTS (Brookline, Mass.) _ Samuel Ryder, the English
seed merchant, is credited with starting the event, which got off
to a slow start. By Bob Duffy. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   GLF-RYDER-GLENEAGLES (Gleneagles, Scotland) _ Five years before
Samuel Ryder underwrote unofficial Ryder Cup matches, they held a
match at Gleneagles. By Bob Duffy. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-RYDER-WORCESTER (Worcester, Mass.) _ Worcester Country Club
hosted the first Ryder Cup, mainly because former Scottish pro
Willie Ogg was head pro there. By Jim McCabe. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-RYDER-1985 (Brookline, Mass.) _ The Europeans had been
pounded consistently when they finally broke through for their
first win since 1957. Like the America's Cup, this was a sporting
event that did not matter until the US lost. By Bob Duffy. 1900
words.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-RYDER-OMEARA (Brookline, Mass.) _ Mark O'Meara heads into
the Ryder Cup with the shakiest game of any of the Brookline Four.
He jokes that it's done him little good lately to aim his drives
down the fairways only to find his golf balls in the rough. By
Michael Madden. (2 takes) PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   GLF-RYDER-NICKLAUS (Brookline, Mass.) _ It could be argued that
two acts in which Jack nicklaus was directly associated helped make
the Ryder Cup a serious competition. By Jim McCabe. 750 words.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-RYDER-BARNES (Brookline, Mass.) _ Brian Barnes was a tough
competitor and at the 1975 Ryder Cup at Laurel Valley Golf Club in
Ligonier, Pa. he stole the show. By Jim McCabe. 675 words.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-RYDER-FORMATS (Brookline, Mass.) _ Captains may pair an
inexperienced player with an experienced one. The strategies of
Ryder Cup match play. By Jim McCabe. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-RYDER-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN (Brookline, Mass.) _ More than any
international competition, this is the event that reinforces the
stereotypes that the Euros have about the Americans. By Dan
Shaughnessy. PHOTO
</P>
