<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1592 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-TCC-ART-BOS     09-22 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-TCC-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCC HAS MADE AN ATTEMPT TO SHED CLOAK OF EXCLUSIVITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ The joke around the clubhouse is that there's
a ``no bow tie'' rule this week. And that goes for Ascots, too.
After all, isn't neckwear what comes to mind when one imagines the
primrose playground on Clyde Street? Bow ties and Brahmins and blue
blood?
</P>
<P>
   The Country Club has been around for so long now (117 years)
that fable has overtaken fact. The name itself evokes a
19th-century aura of Cabots and Lodges and Saltonstalls, of
plus-fours and mashie niblicks, of gin and tonics and watercress
sandwiches _ and insularity.
</P>
<P>
   Most stories written about the club during the past century draw
upon a list of adjectives ranging from stuffy to snooty. Not so,
its members insist. ``We're all humans here,'' testifies club
president Gerry Church. ``We get up in the  &UR; morning  &LR; and go to bed
at night. We're just like everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   The Country Club's 1,300 well-to-do members may not be quite
like everybody else, but they're more like everybody else than they
were a decade ago. Since the club hosted the 1988 US Open, women
have been allowed to become voting members, blacks have been
admitted, and the number of other non-WASPs has been slowly
growing. And TCC has made a point of reaching out beyond its gates
to the world outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``It still is an exclusive club, there's no getting around
that,'' says Richard Kelliher, Brookline's town administrator.
``But the leadership of the club has made a genuine attempt to
connect with the community.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, the club has allowed the high school's golf teams to
play matches there and has arranged annual outings for local
police, fire fighters, and other town employees. But this week's
Ryder Cup has been the catalyst for an historic partnership between
club and town that will extend into the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the $3 million that Brookline will reap from corporate
tents at the public Putterham Meadows course, plus free tickets to
practice and competition rounds, the club is putting up a
six-figure donation to endow a youth foundation and will host an
annual public tournament to keep the money flowing. TCC will also
donate a statue of golfing legend (and townsman) Francis Ouimet to
the town, provide Thanksgiving dinner for elderly Brookline
residents, help develop a mentoring program for young people, and
provide meeting space for town organizations during the winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've opened up a new era of good feeling,'' says John
Cornish, a longtime member who chairs the club's Ryder Cup
committee. ``I've always thought we had a good relationship with
the town, although some people felt otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the club's unprecedented linkage with the town, some
local critics have felt that TCC should broaden its WASPish
membership rolls to reflect Brookline's diversity. But The Country
Club is not the YMCA, defenders point out. It is a private
institution that pays taxes and has the right to choose its own
members. ``A club is a club is a club,'' says Kelliher.
</P>
<P>
   There were no other country clubs when TCC was founded in 1882.
J. Murray Forbes, a China trade merchant who lived in a
Commonwealth Avenue townhouse, wanted a suburban retreat where
cold-roast Boston families could dine, bowl, play lawn tennis, and
race horses. Golf, considered a nuisance by the horsemen, didn't
come until a decade later.
</P>
<P>
   Though TCC was a founding member of the US Golf Association, has
hosted three Opens, and has 27 holes scattered among its 250 acres,
its members have never considered it a golf club. ``I still think
of it as a social club with a great sport facility,'' says Church.
</P>
<P>
   Besides its ``nature-made'' golf layout, which perennially ranks
among the nation's top 50, The Country Club offers tennis courts, a
curling rink, a swimming pool, a skeet range, cross-country skiing
trails, and a skating pond, where Olympic champion Tenley Albright
practiced before the 1956 Games.
</P>
<P>
   Though the primrose-painted clubhouse is expansive and
comfortable, it is hardly ostentatious. That has never been The
Country Club's style. ``This is a very laid-back place,'' says
member Lionel Spiro. ``Look around the parking lot. The automobiles
are not very fancy cars. Most of the people like to lead very
understated lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Privacy is prized at TCC. ``Like a lot of clubs, there are
members here who don't crave public attention,'' says Cornish. So
when they're asked about their membership demographics and their
minority membership, club officials shrug. ``Our policy is that
race, color, creed, ethnicity, and sexual preference are not
considered,'' says Cornish. ``So we don't keep statistics like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Though it's a historical fact that no Jews were admitted until
the '70s, no women (as full members) until 1989, and no blacks
until 1994, there are more of all of them now, members say. ``The
club is more diverse than it was,'' says Spiro, who is Jewish,
``and there is a desire to have that continue.''
</P>
<P>
   There are practical barriers, though, to how quickly diversity
will come to The Country Club. There are already 900 active members
and a waiting list that exceeds five years, even for a plentiful
pool of legacies. ``The way it works is, members propose their
friends for membership,'' says Cornish.
</P>
<P>
   For generations, that meant Lodges were proposing Cabots. ``But
our generation and our children's generation have friends that are
more diverse than their grandfathers' were, so the membership is
becoming more diverse,'' says Cornish. ``This wasn't a decision
made on an institutional basis. It just happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The Country Club is evolving, its members say, as American
society is evolving, albeit more slowly. ``Like all private country
clubs, we lag the rest of the world,'' concedes Cornish. ``But I
think the perception of us isn't the complete reality.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been 11 years since the rest of the world was invited to
wander among the yellow-hued buildings and dodge the squirrels and
tromp across the greensward at Mr. Forbes's suburban retreat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's a fine place,'' says Church, ``and we're glad to
have the world come in and see what we're about. We've come a long
way since the 1988 Open. We've been getting ourselves ready for the
21st century.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
