<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-NICKLAUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICKLAUS WAS A EUROPEAN AMBASSADOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ For all his accomplishments as the game's
greatest player, Jack Nicklaus is sometimes overlooked as perhaps
the golf's ultimate sportsman.
</P>
<P>
   His involvment with the Ryder Cup is an example. In fact, it
could be argued that two acts in which he was directly associated
helped make the Ryder Cup the serious competition that it now is.
</P>
<P>
   The most important one came during the 1977 competition at Royal
Lytham and St. Annes in England. Nicklaus was a Ryder Cup member
for the fifth time (he would play just once more, in 1981) but
something was seriously wrong, he thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat down one night with Lord John Derby, the head of the PGA
of Great Britain. I said, `John, you know that for everyone on the
American team it's a great honor to make the team and it's a great
honor to play in these matches. But, frankly, whenthe matches
start, there isn't much competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Americans would win that year, making it 18 wins and
22 matches. This bothered Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We win every year,'' he told Derby. ``And I don't think that's
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus's suggestion? Extend the dimensions of the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `You've got a European Tour that you're part of,and I
think if you included the European players and made it Europe
versus the United States, I think you'd have some really great
matches that would really add to the Ryder Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Derby took Nicklaus's idea and ran with it. In 1979, the
Americans hosted a European Ryder Cup team that included the
charismatic Seve Ballesteros. That, too, was an American victory,
but it didn't take long for Nicklaus's vision to take hold. The
Europeans broke through in 1985 and the Ryder Cup has never been
the same.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly is a different competition than what took place in
1969, which is when Nicklaus made his Cup debut. And what a debut
it was.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was one of America's best in 1965 and 1967, Nicklaus
had been ineligible for Ryder Cup play because he had yet to be a
member of the PGA of America for five years (which was the rule
back then). His debut was put on hold until the second second set
of matches in the morning when Nicklaus and Dan Sikes earned a 1 up
foursomes victory over Bernard Hunt and Peter Butler.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus lost the next day in a four-ball match with Sikes, then
sat out the afternoon matches. He was beaten, 4 and 3, by Tony
Jacklin in the morning singles of the final day, and that afternoon
drew Jacklin again.
</P>
<P>
   As they played the 18th hole, Nicklaus and Jacklin were all
square, and the match, too, was tied. Nicklaus seemed to have the
edge on the hole, and when he made his 4-footer for par, the
pressure shifted to Jacklin. But only for a moment, because
Nicklaus, knowing the US had secured no worse than a tie (and
consequently had retained the Ryder Cup), bent down and picked up
Jacklin's mark.
</P>
<P>
   He had conceded the putt, much to the anger of his captain, Sam
Snead. Thirty years later, Snead still can't believe Nicklaus did
not force Jacklin to make the putt. ``All the boys were hotter than
hell,'' said Snead.
</P>
<P>
   If they were, they never let on to Nicklaus. Nor did Snead. ``He
never said a word to me,'' said Nicklaus. ``The only time I've ever
heard anything like that was from the media. But Snead never said a
word to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, I can't imagine Tony Jacklin ever missing a 2-foot putt
in that situation, nor would I ever give him the opportunity to.''
</P>
<P>
   Two feet? Jacklin howls with laughter. He hears about that putt
all the time and it's amazing how long it sometimes get. But no, he
said, he wouldn't have missed it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
