<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1604 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-1985-BOS &LR;      09-22 1836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-1985-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORRANCE TURNED THE PAGE IN 1985 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ It was the most unforgettable moment in Sam
Torrance's life, so indelible that it couldn't be vaporized by a
bout of self-inflicted amnesia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was drunk for four days solid,'' he recalls, somehow, 14
years after the fact. ``I drank all night Sunday. I drank eight
bottles of champagne for lunch Monday. I went to a friend's house
and drank all night there. I went to Spain. Finally, at 2 a.m.
Wednesday, I decided, `I can't get any more in me. ' ''
</P>
<P>
   The binge was fueled by a cocktail of euphoria, relief,
deliverance, and transformation. And while Torrance extended the
celebration to excess, in truth an entire continent's spirits were
overflowing. Because when Torrance sank a 30-foot birdie putt on
the 18th hole at The Belfry in Sutton Coldfield, England, on Sept.
15, 1985, he not only beat Andy North, 1 up, he produced the
climactic point in Europe's 16 1/2-11 1/2 victory over the United
States in the Ryder Cup. Thus ended a 26-year stranglehold of
American superiority in the biennial international team matches _
and thus began an era of true competition that has turned this
former foregone conclusion into the extravaganza that will descend
upon The Country Club in Brookline Friday through Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the biggest event in the world now,'' says Nick Faldo, a
member of the trailblazing '85 team. ``Ask someone about the 2001
Ryder Cup and they'll want to talk to you. Ask someone about the
2001 US Open and they'll go, `Huh?' ''
</P>
<P>
   If you asked someone about the Ryder Cups of 1958-83, they'd go,
``How much did the Americans win by?''
</P>
<P>
   The situation grew so embarrassingly hopeless for Great Britain,
the US opponent since Englishman Samuel Ryder inaugurated the
matches in 1927, that the perennial losers' lineup was expanded to
include the Continent in 1979, reflecting both the growing
influence of the European Tour and the ineptitude of the founding
nation.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate impact: two more American slaughters, in '79 and
'81, reinforcing the notion that the matches would forever be
reduced to a formality, an afterthought on the golf calendar, as
reflected by the 21-3-1 US domination.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1983, the Europeans made a far more significant move than
increasing the eligibility pool. They named Briton Tony Jacklin,
the former British and US Open champion, as nonplaying captain. And
with him came a new concept.
</P>
<P>
   Teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   Jacklin took note that the Europeans were treated like
second-class citizens and played like second-rate golfers. He
suspected there might be a correlation. ``We'd travel in the back
of the bus,'' he says. ``The Americans would come over on the
Concorde.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacklin got his men reservations on the big plane. He dressed
them all in cashmere jackets, a welcome fashion departure from the
ragtag ensembles of the past. But his most important innovation was
the Team Room. He had been appalled by the fact that in the past,
the European Cuppers had acted like a group of strangers without
allegiance, that after their matches, the players would head off
with their wives to the shopping malls or restaurants, as if their
individual day's work was all that mattered, and never mind the
fate of the whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was vital that the players spend time together,''
he says. ``They needed a place they could gather, talk, console
each other after a hard day.''
</P>
<P>
   To satisfy all tastes, the menu was catered with a cross section
of cuisines _ ``pasta, meat, fish, you name it,'' says Jacklin _
with a heaping helping of harmony.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all designed to make them feel good about themselves,''
says Jacklin. ``I figured if these things made them feel better,
they'd have nothing else to do but play to their optimum.''
</P>
<P>
   They almost pulled off a coup in the '83 matches at Palm Beach
Gardens, Fla., but Lanny Wadkins overtook Jose Maria Canizares on
the final two holes of the deciding singles duel as the Americans
eked out a 14 1/2-13 1/2 triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was sort of a steppingstone,'' says Jacklin. ``Only
those of us who were there that last afternoon knew how close it
was. We were convinced we were going to nip through.''
</P>
<P>
   When they got nipped instead, the Europeans were disconsolate in
the immediate aftermath. But Seve Ballesteros, the 26-year-old
Spanish swashbuckler, would have none of it. ``This was a
victory,'' he told his teammates. ``We only lost by a point.''
</P>
<P>
   Technicalities aside, Jacklin noticed on the plane _ the
Concorde _ home that ``it was a confidence builder. We thought, `If
we can come that close over there, we can beat them on our own
turf.' ''
</P>
<P>
   So there was a true sense of possibility when the Continent's
constellation of stars _ Ballesteros, Canizares, Manuel Pinero, and
Jose Rivero from Spain; Bernhard Langer from West Germany; and
Torrance, Faldo, Sandy Lyle, Ian Woosnam, Howard Clark, Ken Brown,
and Paul Way of Great Britain _ gathered at The Belfry near
Birmingham the second weekend in September of '85. Still, as they
looked across at the American arsenal _ North, Wadkins, Ray Floyd,
Hal Sutton, Hubert Green, Tom Kite, Mark O'Meara, Calvin Peete,
Craig Stadler, Peter Jacobsen, Curtis Strange, and Fuzzy Zoeller _
they wondered if their self-assurance was misplaced bravado.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American thing was always very strong,'' says Ballesteros.
``It was hard to be very confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacklin set the stage for combat by engaging his counterpart, US
captain Lee Trevino, in some gamesmanship.
</P>
<P>
   At dinner on the eve of the competition, Trevino introduced his
squad as if he were emptying a cash register. ``He's going, `This
guy has won $628,242.18,' and so on,'' says Faldo. ``He winds up
with, `That's a total of $13 million' or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacklin offered a simple rebuttal. ``He said, `I'd like to
introduce my team alphabetically,' '' recalls Faldo. `` `Seve
Ballesteros.' And the crowd went nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   During the opening ceremonies the following day, the chastened
Trevino opted for the humble alphabetical routine. ``Then Tony got
up,'' says Faldo, ``and he says, `Here's so-and-so, winner of 17
tournaments, and Ken Brown, winner of five events . . . ' And we're
going, `What? Ken Brown hasn't won five events.' But Tony got the
crowd going again. It was wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Things didn't look so grand after the first day when the
Americans took a 4 1/2-3 1/2 lead through the foursomes _
traditionally a British stronghold _ and four-ball play.
</P>
<P>
   But the tide began to change the following morning. In the final
four-ball, Stadler needed to sink a putt of less than 2 feet _ ``a
gimme,'' recalls Torrance, spreading his hands barely apart _ on
the 18th hole to give him and Strange a victory over Lyle and
Langer and keep the momentum in red, white, and blue.
</P>
<P>
   He missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the turning point,'' says Torrance. ``It showed us,
`These guys are feeling it like us. Let's get out and do it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   They did, to the tune of a 5 1/2-2 1/2 second-day tally for a
9-7 lead entering the finale, which consisted of 12 singles
matches.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans needed only 5 1/2 points to end the misery, but
Jacklin was leaving nothing to chance. ``Tony was brilliant
tactically,'' says Faldo. ``He said, `They're expecting us to save
our strongest players for last. Let's get after them early.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, one of his choices was virtually made for him. The
fearless Pinero begged the captain to let him play first, and when
he discovered his opponent would be the European-killer of two
years before, Wadkins, ``he literally leaped 3 feet in the air,''
recalls Jacklin. ``He was over the moon. He said, `I'll put out
Wadkins.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And he did, 3 and 1.
</P>
<P>
   That triggered a surge of five European victories in the first
six matches. Which meant that Torrance-North loomed as the
clincher. And Jacklin made sure his 32-year-old veteran knew it.
The captain had been scrambling all over the course, trying to be
available for the start and finish of each match, but the stakes in
this one required his constant attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came up to me and said, `Come on, we only need 1 more
point; you can do it,' '' recalls Torrance.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, his prospects were looking grim. ``I was three down
after 10,'' says Torrance. ``Then I made three or four birdies
coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was still 1 down at the 17th when he stood over a 6-foot
birdie putt that could square the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toughest putt I've ever had to make,'' says Torrance.
``Everything was shaking.''
</P>
<P>
   But not his stroke, which proved straight and true and left
things even as he and North arrived at the 18th tee on the
7,176-yard, par-72 Brabazon course.
</P>
<P>
   Torrance boomed his drive, leaving himself a 9-iron to the
green. North skied his drive, leaving himself in the water. The
match _ and the curse _ effectively were over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had everything I could do to control my emotions,'' says
Torrance. ``I had tears in my eyes coming off the tee.''
</P>
<P>
   As a schoolboy in Largs, Scotland, Torrance had dreamed of
someday sinking the putt to win the Ryder Cup. Now here it was,
even if it wasn't as dramatic as his fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I basically had three putts from 30 feet to win,'' says
Torrance.
</P>
<P>
   He nailed the first, and unleashed a torrent of exultation among
30,000 fans, the third straight Ryder Cup record attendance in as
many days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Belfry was a good course,'' says Faldo. ``You could hear
the crowds on the other holes. It was nice to hear the cheers and
know they were for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Torrance in particular. He's won 21 European Tour events, but he
says, ``This was 50 million times greater.''
</P>
<P>
   Was he a hero?
</P>
<P>
   ``Still am,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   His first act in this newfound role was to leap into Jacklin's
arms, and after the final points had been tallied, the winners
repaired to the roof of The Belfry, where they sprayed the crowd
with champagne. Not all of it, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boys drank in the bar in the Team Room,'' says Jacklin,
who savored the win in private contemplation, sipping a whiskey in
his hotel room. ``They raised a few roofs that night.''
</P>
<P>
   Some raised more than others, as Torrance can attest. And there
were even more reasons for toasts two years later when Jacklin led
the Europeans to a 15-13 decision at Muirfield Village in Dublin,
Ohio, their first win ever on American soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the most satisfying days of my life,'' says
Jacklin. ``There's only one first time, isn't there?''
</P>
<P>
   But there's no sign of a last time anymore. Starting with the
breakthrough at The Belfry, the Europeans have won four of the past
seven Ryders, including the last two. And when they come to
Brookline, needing only a tie to retain the Cup, their assistant
captain will be 46-year-old Sam Torrance.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's a sobering thought.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material from wire services was used to prepare this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
