<HEADLINE>
GLENEAGLES MATCH IN 1921 SET THE PRECEDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENEAGLES, Scotland _ It was the precursor to the precursor.
</P>
<P>
   Five years before British seed merchant Samuel Ryder underwrote
unofficial matches between US and English pros _ and six years
before he donated the cup that bears his name and has become
emblematic of world team golf supremacy _ an informal international
competition was held at Gleneagles, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   The genesis, like so many of the specifics concerning the
evolution of the Ryder Cup, is buried in the sand traps of time.
Some sources say the Gleneagles matches were the inspiration of
Sylvanus P. Jermain, the first president of the Inverness Club in
Toledo, Ohio. Others credit the brainstorm to Golf Illustrated
magazine circulation manager James Harnett.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever was the originator, Michael Hobbs reports in his book
``The Ryder Cup: The Illustrated History'' that during a meeting of
the US PGA on Dec. 15, 1920, a motion was passed to fund a trip by
a group of American pros who would receive expenses plus $1,000
each to meet their British counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of Gleneagles, a jewel in the making in the lush
farmland of central Scotland, was obvious. It was the site of the
Glasgow Herald 1,000 Guineas Tournament, the richest in the world
at the time, with a 740-pound purse and 200 pounds to the winner
awarded by the sponsoring newspaper. With top American pros, led by
the flashy Walter Hagen, on hand for the Glasgow tournament and the
British Open two weeks later at St. Andrews, the team event was
considered a natural prelude.
</P>
<P>
   When they arrived for the matches, held June 6, 1921, the
Americans found a hotel sprouting from the heather that was not
only palatial but partial. Only three of the four floors had been
completed, and there was no roof, so the players stayed in sleeper
cars at nearby Gleneagles Station, according to Hobbs. The resort
was the brainchild of Donald Mathieson, board chairman of
London-based Caledonian Railways, who wanted to capitalize
commercially on the sporting pursuits _ golfing, hunting, fishing _
that flourished in the Scottish midlands.
</P>
<P>
   While the hotel remained a work in progress, the golf facilities
were another matter. Legendary British player and course architect
James Braid had carved the King's Course from the glacial valley,
building on a surface of sand and gravel, which allowed natural
year-round draining, to create a seeming oxymoron _ an inland links
layout, nine holes going out and nine coming in.
</P>
<P>
   The course, which offered a panoramic view of the surrounding
Ochils Hills, climbed 175 feet from the first to the 12th hole,
then began its descent to the 18th and the rudimentary clubhouse,
the Dormy Shop. Each hole was self-contained in its own
amphitheater, and each boasted a distinct feature. For instance,
the 13th, called ``Braid's Brawest'' (Scottish for ``Best''), was
guarded by two sinister bunkers, ``Auld Nick'' (``Devil'') and
``Young Nick.'' The 14th contained seven bunkers, one for each day
of the week, arranged in diagonal torture.
</P>
<P>
   ``God created the landscape,'' said Braid. ``I was commissioned
to find the golf holes.''
</P>
<P>
   The holes he sculpted were considered British Open-caliber,
though Hobbs writes that the American pros complained about the
disheveled fairways and bunkers, proving that they were no
different than their descendants of today.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, they played five foursomes matches in the morning
and 10 singles in the afternoon under brilliant sunshine amid a
tricky breeze. As would be the case five years later at Wentworth,
England, in Ryder's first clambake, the British romped, 10 1/2-4
1/2. The hosts _ composed of Braid, George Duncan, Abe Mitchell,
Harry Vardon, Ted Ray, J.H. and Josh Taylor, Arthur Havers, James
Ockenden, and James Sherlock _ enjoyed a 3-1 advantage in the
morning matches, winning three and halving two, and went 6 1/2-3
1/2 in the singles against the US contingent: Hagen, Jock
Hutchison, Emmet French, Fred McLeod, Tom Kerrigan, Clarence
Hackney, Wilfrid Reid, George McLean, Charles Hoffner, and Bill
Mehlhorn.
</P>
<P>
   In the headline foursomes, Duncan canned a putt on the 18th that
enabled him and Mitchell to halve their match with Hagen and
Hutchison. The British duos dominated the other matches,
highlighted by Vardon and Ray's 5-and-4 rout of French and
Kerrigan.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan set the tone in the afternoon by edging Hutchison _ one
of three Scottish natives on the American team _ 2 and 1. Hagen
halved his duel with Mitchell, but otherwise, Brittania ruled.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the contestants repaired to the Dormy House for
refreshments and postmortems. Each received a gold commemorative
medal _ later in the week, Mitchell would earn a much grander prize
by capturing the Glasgow Herald tourney _ but there were no calls
for a regular renewal of the event.
</P>
<P>
   International competition was dormant for five years until the
St. Albans seed merchant took over. And that's why the US and
European pros at The Country Club in Brookline this weekend will be
competing for the Ryder Cup, not the Gleneagles Grail.
</P>
</TEXT>
