<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBURBIA: NOT SO BAD, BUT WE HATE IT ANYWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   O suburbia! Are you the home address of the American Dream, or
are you the place where that dream goes to die?
</P>
<P>
   Even after spending most of my life in the suburbs, I'm still
not sure. Neither is P.J. O'Rourke, but being P.J. means never
having to say you're ambivalent. You simply go looking for laughs
in all the politically incorrect places.
</P>
<P>
   O'Rourke gets himself all cranked up for a good tirade against
suburbia in Rolling Stone, but statistics keep debunking his
arguments and interfering with his grumpy mood, making him even
grumpier. His research reveals that the 'burbs aren't as expensive
as they're cracked up to be, that the alleged hassle of commuting
is largely self-inflicted, that the issue of suburban sprawl is
exaggerated, that suburban kids are better-educated and less
TV-addicted than city kids, and, in his opinion, that designated
punching bag Al Gore's ``livability'' agenda will only screw up
suburbia.
</P>
<P>
   Still, O'Rourke hates suburbia on metaphysical grounds, a hatred
expressed in that sui P.J. way. ``How'd we wind up here?'' he
cries, giving voice to a generational lament. ``We were going to
live in Barcelona, Maui, on a mountaintop in Nepal. We were going
to be a novelist, a painter, a Mother Teresa, a Malcolm X, a Jim
Morrison but with more girls, more drugs and a thirtieth birthday.
. . . Oh, how did life turn out so dull?''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Baker, as earnest as O'Rourke is uproarious, also has a
bone to pick with suburbia in the Utne Reader.
</P>
<P>
   Baker builds a case that the trend toward suburban mega-houses _
a ``McMansion mania'' creating ``ostentatious symbols of America's
class divide'' _ has contributed to the erosion of the nation's
supply of affordable housing while also encouraging ``auto-based
sprawl'' and the ``decimation of green space.'' Beyond that, she
argues, the proliferation of these supersized homes is corroding
the very idea of neighborhood and of a shared public space, and
insists: ``The megahouse is a fortress standing guard in a
wasteland.'' Baker and O'Rourke wouldn't likely agree on much, but
they agree on the wasteland part.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One penalty for excessive media hype can be a public backlash of
the sort that sank ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' the Kubrick/Cruise/Kidman
opus billed as an erotic thriller that proved to be neither erotic
nor thrilling.
</P>
<P>
   Another is to be dissected in Brill's Content, where Katherine
Rosman takes the media to task for allowing themselves to be played
like violins in the movie's skillfully orchestrated publicity
campaign. ``The treatment of `Eyes Wide Shut' marks a low point in
the morphing of journalism into marketing,'' Rosman asserts, then
goes on to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Even though every TV show and magazine but Time was denied an
advance viewing of the movie or any details about it from the
stars, and thus could not know that they were being manipulated
into hyping a bomb, that didn't stop many programs and publications
from leaping at the chance to showcase Tom and Nicole.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because the bottom line is the bottom line: With newsstand
sales vital, magazines are desperate to get some sexual sizzle on
their covers, at whatever cost to their credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pure entertainment and pure sex. Those are the things that
push magazines off the newsstands,'' Rosman quotes Esquire editor
David Granger as saying. ``It's almost a risk to put anything else
on the cover, a commercial risk.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It probably goes without saying that ``Eyes Wide Shut'' is not
represented in Entertainment Weekly's list of ``The 100 Greatest
Moments in Movies 1950-2000.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1950 cutoff seems like cheating, and as with all lists there
are choices to quarrel with here (``The Poseidon Adventure''? And
what's with all the Charlton Heston movies?). But in general,
nobody does this sort of thing better than the pop-culture-savvy
folks at EW, who interviewed stars to dig up piquant anecdotes and
details about well-known films.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, for instance, that Meryl Streep was the second choice
for ``Kramer vs. Kramer'' _ behind Kate Jackson of ``Charlie's
Angels.'' Robert DeNiro's famous ``You talkin' to me?'' ad-lib in
``Taxi Driver'' was inspired by a comedian he'd seen in a New York
deli. Marlon Brando had one condition, according to James Caan, for
performing a flashback scene in ``Godfather II'': ``Fire the head
of the studio!'' (They shot the scene without him.). And my
favorite ancedote: At the 1970 Oscars, with counterculture favorite
``Midnight Cowboy'' up against John Wayne's ``True Grit,'' Dennis
Hopper sat directly in front of Wayne during the ceremony wearing a
large Stetson.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sneering at Norman Rockwell has long been a favorite parlor game
among art snobs who couldn't forgive Rockwell for creating
illustrations that emphasized our common humanity rather than our
intractable alienation, and that were actually comprehensible by
ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
   So it is all the more surprising that the Guggenheim Museum, an
outpost of modern art, agreed to host the traveling Rockwell
retrospective. In ARTnews, Edgar Allen Beem talks to critics and
curators and finds a growing respect for Rockwell, even among the
intelligentsia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety-eight percent of the artists he was presumed to be
worse than are unheard of today,'' notes critic Dave Hickey.
``Rockwell is a canonical artist whether museums say so or not.''
New Yorker art critic Peter Schjeldahl adds: ``Rockwell is
terrific. It's become too tedious to pretend he isn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 1351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1620 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-22 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CONTRARIAN BACKPEDALS ON THOREAU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is as many of you have suspected _ I suffer from a
degenerative mental disease. It is called Incipient Thoreauvianism.
</P>
<P>
   Heaven knows my Thoreau-bashing credentials are very much in
order. In 1991, I observed the 50th anniversary of the Thoreau
Society with a contrarian assessment of the writer who made the
world safe for Cliff's Notes: ``Concord's most eminent sociopath .
. . a misanthrope, a slob, and a loser . . . a tree-hugging
pyromaniac (Thoreau accidentally set fire to a Concord forest).'' I
suggested Thoreau was a victim of Columnist's Disease: ``He
pontificated endlessly on subjects he knew nothing about.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, rock 'n' roll god Don Henley of the Eagles
denounced me for suggesting that his championing of the Walden
Woods cause had more to do with salvaging his career than with
honoring Thoreau. At the time, Henley was shaking down concertgoers
for $97 a seat, purporting to direct some of the proceeds to
``save'' Walden. ``Look at it this way,'' I wrote. ``For $97, you
can feed a village in Rwanda or Don Henley's ego, whichever you
choose.''
</P>
<P>
   Is it too late to switch sides? Thoreau himself says no: ``It is
never too late to give up our prejudices.''
</P>
<P>
   The further the world moves away from Thoreau, the more his
message appeals to me. I converted this summer when I spent two
nights on the Presidential Range ridgeline in the Appalachian
Mountain Club huts in New Hampshire. When I arrived atop Mt.
Madison in a driving rain, I asked the crew chief to direct me to
the fireplace so I could dry off. There is no fireplace here, he
replied. No hot water either, and fairly rustic plumbing. No cell
phones. No fax. Just a bunch of happy, smelly people.
</P>
<P>
   Sign me up! I've never joined a church, but I fired off my
membership application to the AMC posthaste. (How can you resist an
organization whose motto is ``Cotton kills''?) I knew I was in the
right club when I started perusing the personal ads in the Club's
Outdoors magazine: ``Daring non-traditional maverick with
traditional edge . . . Fit, dark blonde . . . Author, professor,
successful consultant . . . Advanced scuba diver. Loves independent
films . . . likes metaphor . . . Great legs.''
</P>
<P>
   But I digress.
</P>
<P>
   The other day I jotted down a list of directions in which the
world seemed to be headed, and in virtually every instance I seemed
to be going the other way. Statistics have a way of leaving me
behind. I drive more slowly than the norm, infuriating the muscle
cars behind me, and even my own family. Shouldn't I have been
married more times? Shouldn't I have switched jobs more often?
Shouldn't I be receiving more TV channels? How about fewer?
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't help but be amused by last week's explosion of
``journalism'' touting the new wonder product Visor. In theory,
Visor is the technological equivalent of the Holy Grail, an
``all-in-one'' pocket-size digital gizmo that is a combination
computer/Web surfer/digital music recorder-player/fax
modem/e-mailer and Hot Line to God for all I know. Gotta have it? I
don't think so. Thoreau understood how technologies can come to
rule their creators: ``We do not ride on the railroad,'' he wrote
in ``Walden.'' ``It rides upon us.''
</P>
<P>
   This month, Harper's magazine is republishing a 1939
appreciation of Thoreau by E.B. White, who offered this praise to
the steward of Walden Pond: ``As our common complexities increase,
any tale of individual simplicity . . . acquires a new fascination;
as our goods accumulate, but not our well-being, your report of an
existence without material adornment takes on a certain awkward
credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Thoreau is hard to love. The million-word Journal is
impenetrable. The travel writings meander here and there; when
Thoreau gets lost, you get lost with him. He may be best remembered
as an aphorist, which is no small thing. And credibility, awkward
or not, is valuable coin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 1353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
