<HEADER>
A1624 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-22 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARRITY'S DEATH REIGNITES WHITE DENIAL ABOUT SEGREGATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even with all the facts about white flight, it was not enough to
stem the unforgiving rage hurled last week toward the corpse of
Judge W. Arthur Garrity Jr. A predictable example from a proven
small mind came from Boston City Council President James Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said of Garrity's order to desegregate the Boston Public
Schools a quarter century ago, ``I don't know if it is possible to
calculate how many lives he destroyed, how many marriages broke up
because husbands and wives didn't have good jobs because of good
education. How many people turned to drugs and alcohol? . . . I
have no reason to be sad that he died.''
</P>
<P>
   A peculiar example came from a man who tried to prove his mindhad grown from his myopic South Boston roots, former mayor Ray
Flynn. Despite his worldly travels as ambassador to the Vatican,
Flynn had this to say about Garrity:
</P>
<P>
   ``I only wish that the decision he made about the Boston public
schools didn't disrupt the education of our children and the
stability of our city as it did. In my opinion, public schools in
Boston still haven't recovered from the decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Garrity may be dead, but the white denial surrounding his
attempt to engineer educational equality is as blind as ever. In
all the coverage of Garrity's death, nothing was volunteered from
these apologists for a resistance as virulent as that in 1950s
Little Rock as to how African-American children in the Boston of
the 1970s were going to get a quality education.
</P>
<P>
   Garrity ruled that Boston ran a ``dual school system'' that gave
white neighborhood schools far more resources than black schools.
When Flynn said he wished Garrity did not ``disrupt'' the education
of ``our'' children, he meant only white children. The education of
black children was in a permanent state of disruption that
destroyed employment and college opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   There is no evidence to support the notion that school busing by
itself destroyed white families or sparked white flight. Many white
families were running away as fast and as far away as they could
from black folks regardless of busing.
</P>
<P>
   In their 1996 book ``Dismantling Desgregation,'' Harvard
University professor Gary Orfield and co-author Susan Eaton found
that major cities that either had little or no busing or ended
busing by the early 1980s still had massive white flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``If white enrollment declines were caused by busing, then
cities with neighborhood schools would have stable enrollments, but
there are very big white enrollment losses there,'' Orfield and
Eaton wrote. They also said busing critics ignore the fact that
all-white suburbs are still being built while residential
segregation has expanded in cities, fueling drops in white urban
enrollment ``no matter what happens in the schools.''
</P>
<P>
   African-American students braved the rocks, the sight of
overturned police cars, effigies, slurs, and threats to get on the
buses. But the window where busing might have provided a better
education for African-American students was short lived. By the mid
1980s, Boston was gripped with conditions similar to most large
cities. The suburbs had expanded, the cities and their property tax
bases had shrunk, and the schools _ busing or no busing, Garrity or
no Garrity _ are once again dual systems.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's system is 75 percent African-American and Latino and 16
percent white, but it's most prestigious school, Boston Latin, is
51 percent white and 29 percent African-American and Latino.
</P>
<P>
   While white parents of privilege have destroyed affirmative
action at Latin and in busing in order to hoard scarce resources,
African-American parents fight to jump ahead of each other on the
massive waiting list for the METCO program that allows
African-American children in the Boston Public Schools to attend
suburban schools.
</P>
<P>
   Left behind are low income students, usually of color, in what
Orfield calls the ``resegregation of American schools.'' In a
report released in June, Massachusetts had the seventh-highest rate
of resegregation among the 28 states with substantial
African-American enrollments and the fourth-highest rate of
resegregation among the 12 states with large Latino populations.
</P>
<P>
   Orfield wrote, ``We are floating back toward an educational
pattern that has never in the nation's history produced equal and
successful schools. There is no good evidence it work now.''
</P>
<P>
   That is precisely the problem with the carping over Garrity's
corpse. The Flynns, the Kellys, the Kevin Whites, let alone the
rock throwers, criticized the judge knowing they were not about to
pour resources into black neighborhood schools. That stasis led
naturally to a large scale abandonment of the schools once they
inevitably became mostly black, brown, and of low income.
</P>
<P>
   Garrity did the best he could with the Little Rock he was
handed. Now he watches down from the big bench in the sky, no
longer to be reached by the hate mail and obscene phone calls that
called him a ``Nazi'' and ``nigger lover.'' He waits to see if the
politicians and citizens of today and tomorrow will fight for
resources or set low-income black and brown children adrift in the
new dual system, allowing them to be pulled away from opportunity
by the rip tide of separate and unequal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
