<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1628 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CAMPAIGN-BUSH-BOS &LR;      09-22 1792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BUSH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH BALANCES BETWEEN SCRIPT AND IMPROVISATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEDFORD, N.H. _ Texas Governor George W. Bush is burning. He
can't believe what Vice President Al Gore just did, showing up in
Texas to chide the governor for letting children be taught in
trailers.
</P>
<P>
   This, Bush says, is exactly the trouble with Gore. While Bush
braves controversy, calling for federal tax dollars for private
schools, Gore talks about building new schools, doubtless after
consulting with a pollster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure the polls said something about buildings,'' says
Bush, scrunched behind a kitchenette table in the campaign
Winnebago known as Minnie the Winnie. ``I talk about children and
he talks about buildings. Therein lies the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush scans a semicircle of aides, smiling now and clearly
satisfied. There is just one problem: On the very day Bush is
lashing out against Gore for ignoring children, the vice president
has unveiled a plan to provide health insurance for every child in
America.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has no child health plan _ not yet. An aide later says that
advisers are crafting one.
</P>
<P>
   It is a moment that says much about the way the Texas governor
is campaigning for president, scripted to the sentence when the
issue is familiar; improvising, sometimes awkwardly, when it is
not.
</P>
<P>
   At campaign stops in the key states of Iowa, New Hampshire and
Michigan, plus an unexpected detour to Texas to deal with the Fort
Worth church shooting, Bush emerges as a candidate almost forming
before your eyes, substance racing to catch up to the famous name
and front-runner status.
</P>
<P>
   He is a consummate campaigner, tending to the crowds on the
trail like a host at a barbecue, glad-handing every comer, grinning
at flashbulbs of a thousand cameras. He seems bemused by it all,
this cowboy-booted son of a former president, barely known
nationally until this year, and now treated like a political
incarnation of a country-and-western star.
</P>
<P>
   But as Bush travels through the key caucus and primary states,
the layers of complexity behind his incandescent smile are slowly
revealed. On the stump, he plays it safe and predictable, rarely
risking a new phrase. But in question-and-answer sessions that
follow, Bush sometimes seems stumped, struggling to answer
questions about federal repayment of immigration costs to states
and the use of US troops in East Timor. But he does it all with a
wink and a pleading smile that seems to say, ``Go easy on me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And mostly, the voters do.
</P>
<P>
   On one recent day, the bandwagon makes a hastily arranged stop
at a sunny plaza outside the Holy Redeemer Church in southwest
Detroit, a heavily Hispanic area that usually votes solidly
Democratic. Amid the mariachi music, an announcer's introduction
booms across the crowd assembled to celebrate Mexican Independence
Day: ``Senor George W. Bush!''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor strides on stage, speaking Spanish for a few
minutes, before bellowing, ``God Bless Mexico!'' to thunderous
applause. Beaming with delight, he sweeps his hand across the
audience and says, ``This is the American dream.'' The hundreds of
people, many of them waving Mexican flags freshly signed by Bush,
roar back their approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush, Bush!'' the chant begins. ``Viva Bush!''
</P>
<P>
   Among those in the crowd is Benjamin Leiva, 42, who has never
voted before, but plans to back Bush. When Bush approaches a booth
set up by the Jobs Corps, Ranada Reid, 29, excitedly comes out from
behind the counter and tells the governor she has seen people
criticize him on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ignore them and be a good president,'' Reid tells Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will, or my Mom's going to get down on me,'' Bush says,
grinning.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Reid says she has always supported Democrats but will
vote for Bush because ``he is a different kind of Republican. He
really cares about people.'' So what did Reid think about Bush's
father, former President Bush? Reid's face turned sour. ``President
Bush was plastic,'' she says. ``Governor Bush is different.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, when asked, speaks warmly about the bond of love and
gratitude between son and father. But the former president's
political legacy is not an unalloyed blessing, which may explain
this: At more than 20 campaign events observed by a reporter this
summer, Bush never brought up his father's name except when the two
met at the family compound in Kennebunkport.
</P>
<P>
   Bush leaves the Detroit event with a grin as wide as the festive
Mexican hats. His political strategy rests greatly on the theory
that he can win over Democrats and independents, by ``going where
Republicans usually don't go,'' as he puts it. If Bush wins the
Republican primary and becomes president, aides say, the key could
be groundwork laid in places like the sun-splashed courtyard of
Holy Redeemer Church.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The flip side of the Bush campaign sometimes is not so sunny. In
an ongoing Doonesbury cartoon strip, written by Bush's fellow Yale
alumnus Garry Trudeau, the governor is mercilessly portrayed as an
airhead who wears a cowboy hat, with frequent allusions to Bush's
refusal to say whether he used cocaine or other illegal drugs. It
is an issue rarely raised by voters at Bush's public events, but
often comes up in encounters with the news media.
</P>
<P>
   On one recent day in New Hampshire, after traveling the state in
his Winnebago, Bush is pumped, smiling, his eyes handsomely
crinkled at the corners, ready for any question. Until, that is, a
reporter asks: Has the governor ever broken the law himself?
</P>
<P>
   Just hours earlier, Bush had lectured an audience about his plan
for a ``new era of responsibility,'' deriding a decade when people
said, ``If it feels good, do it.'' Bush warned of the evils of drug
use and alcohol abuse, and suggested that he had a place for those
who break the law: ``In Texas, we call it jail.'' The crowd loved
it, hooting and hollering as a beaming Bush left the podium.
</P>
<P>
   But now, in the confines of ``Minnie the Winnie,'' the candidate
recoils, seeing the question as yet another way to pose the drug
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to talk about what I did.'' Bush says sternly,
looking like he might show his visitor the exit. Then, winking, he
smiles and says: ``Nice try!'' And a moment later, ``It was
clever!'' But then he is stern again, declaring: ``It was not
clever. I have answered the question all I am going to answer it.''
</P>
<P>
   And then it passes. If there is a contradiction between his
words and deeds, Bush won't acknowledge it. He is having too much
fun as the front-runner campaigning for president, and he knows the
fun might fade in the coming months. The son of a former president
has seen his father lose campaigns in 1964, 1970, and 1992 for the
House, Senate, and presidency, so one of his favorite lines is that
he is ``not afraid of failure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens on a campaign trail is you end up looking at the
unvarnished person.'' Bush says in a moment of introspection. ``I
get tired. It is a grueling experience.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Milford, N.H., a village-turned-suburb near the Massachusetts
border, the streets are blocked off and lined with security agents,
as if the president were about to arrive. Bush is swarmed as he
leaves the restaurant and takes a carefully choreographed walk to
the fire station.
</P>
<P>
   Such scenes raise the question: How did Bush soar so high so
fast in the polls. The answer is circular. He is high in the polls
because he has always been high in the polls, thanks to his name
recognition and the belief of many Republicans that he is most
likely to be elected.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ask Bush about the polls, and he displays nothing but
contempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to know principles,'' Bush says. ``People are
sickened by the politics of taking polls. I've never taken a poll
as governor to figure out what issue I should take a stand on.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same vein, Bush insists he is running a grass-roots
campaign, albeit with $50 million in the bank, including a huge
amount from the party establishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's fitting to launch a grass-roots campaign in a fire
station,'' Bush tells the crowd of 200 or so people inside the
sweltering fire station. The audience may not have grasped Bush's
logic, but most loved his message.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's speech rarely varies. He always starts by saying he loves
his wife, Laura _ ``the best decision I ever made'' _ and his twin
17-year-old daughters. He wants to restore ``dignity to the Oval
Office,'' an allusion to President Clinton's infidelity. Then he
urges the audience to reject ``the politics of personal
destruction'' _ the sort of politics that would force him to say
more of the ``young and irresponsible'' ways he says he has left
behind.
</P>
<P>
   His is a broad-band message, crafted to appeal to Republicans,
independents, and even Democrats. And where he seems to contradict
himself, it seems not to bother the candidate or most in his
audience. Bush, for example, says the government can cut taxes
largely by eliminating many programs, but he has implied he would
boost the defense budget by billions of dollars because the country
must have a ``sharpened sword.''
</P>
<P>
   But when encountering the unexpected, he seems to lose his edge.
After Bush's stump speech to the Greater Salem Chamber of Commerce
in Windham, N.H., a member of the audience rises to tell Bush about
his 25-year-old mentally retarded son. What will Bush do to help
the mentally retarded get jobs, asks Philip A. Pearson.
</P>
<P>
   Bush does not appear to have thought about the matter. When
Pearson seems unsatisfied with Bush's vague promise to discuss the
issue, Bush shrugs and curtly ends the question-and-answer session.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bush knows he must fill in the blanks. For one thing, voters,
even admirers, tell him as much.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Ryer, a recently relocated Texan who lives in Amherst,
N.H., greets the governor in Milford and says she is a big fan of
his. But she says that she has gone from definitely supporting Bush
to probably backing him, partly because she is intrigued by the
life story of Senator John McCain, the Arizona Republican and
former Vietnam prisoner of war. ``I do look forward to hearing more
about the issues,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Bush says he plans to fill in many of the blanks this fall with
a series of policy announcements, but he sees no reason to hurry,
or to shift his overall message or tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``People seem to like the message and if it is working, why
change?'' Bush says, then adds, as if in confidence: ``By the way,
in the '94 campaign (for governor) I pretty much said the same
thing the entire campaign there, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 1357EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1630 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-22 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG MAN ON CAMPUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fifty years ago a tall, beefy Irishman from Cambridge, Mass. got
himself elected speaker of the Massachusetts House.
</P>
<P>
   Tom to his wife and old friends, Tip to the rest of mankind, he
became US House Speaker Thomas P. O'Neill, blending the same yeasty
mixture of Irish stories, canny political judgments, and skillful
compromising at the national level as he had at home where he
discovered his own Newtonian theory of the civic universe: ``All
politics is local.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Depression he was one of the Boston Irish schoolboys who
took the streetcar to the end of the line at Chestnut Hill and
hiked up the slope to Boston College. When he enrolled only four
buildings were there to welcome the threadbare sons of immigrants
and turn them into Jesuit-educated men.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's back on campus. In spirit, at least, in photographs, in
video and audio, in the very furniture that was in his Washington
office, as well as in 500 linear feet of storage boxes where his
papers, books, and the accumulated possessions of a half-century in
government and politics is collected, collated, and searched by
scholar and student alike.
</P>
<P>
   In the airy and capacious library that bears his name, a
permanent exhibit opens Friday tracking the life of the man who'll
be remembered as the last popular speaker. All who've succeeded him
have been swallowed up by toxic vapors of partisanship and
diminished by rancor.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Wright and Newt Gingrich resigned under fire, diminished by
ethics investigations, isolated by partisan attacks. Tom Foley got
defeated in the '94 landslide that made Gingrich speaker; Newt's
designated successor, Bob Livingston, never even got the gavel,
resigning before taking formal control. And the present
post-impeachment speaker, Denny Hastert, an Illinois Republican,
blows an uncertain trumpet, presiding over a bare five-seat
majority whose members careen off in all directions.
</P>
<P>
   It was vastly different under O'Neill, before Gingrich's
right-wing posse poisoned the well of comity which had sustained
the House for the half-century since the Red Scare of the '50s.
</P>
<P>
   Politics was friendlier and the government ran better when there
was more friendship and less hate-mongering in Washington. The
Beltway has gone the way of Beirut, Belfast, and Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   You walk into the BC exhibit and there's a lifesize photo of
O'Neill at the door; you feel like shaking hands. From speakers and
video stations his throaty baritone dispenses quips and comments,
wit and wisdom. ``There are some things about politics that never
change: Giving your word and keeping it is still the bedrock. Vote
your conscience, your country, your district, the leadership, in
that order.''
</P>
<P>
   On one panel is a photo of Leo Diehl, O'Neill's closest
associate over a half-century of slugging it out in the political
trenches. There's the house on Russell Street in Cambridge, the
tribute to Sister Agatha from high school, the gang at Barry's
Corner, the presidents and potentates from the Washington years.
</P>
<P>
   If you ask any one of Boston College's thousands of living
alumni who did the most for their alma mater, after Ignatius of
Loyola, the answers would probably be the Rev. Donald Monan SJ,
Doug Flutie, Peter Lynch, and Tip O'Neill, in no particular order.
</P>
<P>
   Monan is the savvy priest whose deft touch guided BC through the
shoals to the Heights's present eminence. Flutie is the magical
quarterback whose pass (to beat Miami) is prologue to his present
(in Buffalo), but who made BC's reputation national and thereby
helped propel enrollment to its present heady level of 8,600
undergrads in a signature school. And Lynch is Fidelity's
Magellan-magician turned philanthropist.
</P>
<P>
   But it was O'Neill, not the fleet-footed Flutie, who put BC on
the map in D.C., where the federal pie is carved, staging whopping
fund-raising dinners that drew lobbyists, industrialists and sundry
politicians and presidents who deemed it prudent to cultivate the
then-speaker of the US House.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Dig will be impossible to top as testament to O'Neill's
steam-shovel approach to federal largesse for his home turf. But BC
was never far behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are currently helping close to 50 kids on partial
scholarships off the endowment of the O'Neill Scholarship Fund,
which stands close to $4 million,'' said Jim McIntyre, BC's senior
vice president. ``This will be a permanent exhibit. It embodies our
motto, `Men and women for others.' As speaker, he helped the needy,
the poor, did so much for health care and Social Security. The
money he raised for the scholarship fund means he'll be helping
people in perpetuity. He represented the very best in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   There'll be a reception after the 4 p.m. dedication, with Mrs.
Millie O'Neill receiving a medal and daughter Rosemary speaking for
the family, along with BC's president, the Rev. William Leahy SJ,
US Representative Joe Moakley, and remarks by professor Shep
Melnick.
</P>
<P>
   Millie O'Neill will be presented with the Joseph Coolidge Shaw
S.J. Medal, named for the old Yankee scholar who was one of
Harvard's first Phi Beta Kappas in 1840, who converted to
Catholicism and left $4,000 and 2,000 books to what was to become
Boston College. So Shaw is revered as well as O'Neill, whose spirit
is invoked at the tail end of the exhibit, where, on a folding
table replicating a backroom campaign headquarters, there's an old
tin ashtray, and a half-smoked cigar. Perfect.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
