<HEADLINE>
APPLES: THE ALL-AMERICAN FRUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Proclaimed our national fruit by Ralph Waldo
Emerson, the 19th-century poet and essayist, apples are a wonderful
mirror for what is regarded as American.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, they are far more diverse than most folks imagine;
there are more than 7,000 varieties, with more being developed all
the time. And, like so much of what we like to think of as
``American,'' apples have a rich history that predates this
country.
</P>
<P>
   Forgetting for a moment that famous land called Eden, the
ancient Egyptians planted apple trees and recorded on papyrus the
techniques they used. By 200 B.C. the Romans had cultivated seven
apple varieties.
</P>
<P>
   Yet apples remain as American as can be. New York, the second
most prolific apple-growing state in the country (top honors go to
Washington), produces on average 25.24 million bushels of apples
every year.
</P>
<P>
   But how well do we know this seemingly simple fruit? Do most of
us realize that apples stored at room temperature deteriorate 10
times faster than refrigerated apples? Or that they shouldn't be
stored with broccoli, cabbage, cauliflower, cucumbers, leafy
greens, lettuce or spinach because apples give off a gas that can
damage these vegetables?
</P>
<P>
   Each variety is unique in some ways, and apples that are tart
and crisp for eating don't always work well in pies. Here is a
primer for 10 of the most popular varieties of apple:
</P>
<P>
   _ McIntosh: Discovered in 1811 by John McIntosh, a native of
Vischers Ferry, it grows particularly well in New York's cool
climate.
</P>
<P>
   What's it like: Sweet with a tart tang, very juicy with tender,
white flesh.
</P>
<P>
   Best uses: Excellent for eating and sauce; good for salads and
pies.
</P>
<P>
   Special hint: McIntosh's tender flesh cooks down quickly. Add a
thickener if making a pie.
</P>
<P>
   _ Red Delicious: Discovered around 1870 in Iowa by a Quaker,
Jesse Hiat, the popular, very sweet apple is now grown across the
country. What's it like: Sweet, juicy, with crisp, yellow flesh.
</P>
<P>
   Best uses: Excellent for eating and salad.
</P>
<P>
   Special hint: Red Delicious look great for a long time, so they
are the favored choice for holiday centerpieces and wreaths.
</P>
<P>
   _ Empire: With the popular McIntosh and Red Delicious for
parents, the New York State Agricultural Experiment Station in
Geneva introduced this variety in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   What's it like: Blend of sweet and tart, juicy, with very crisp,
creamy white flesh.
</P>
<P>
   Best uses: Excellent for eating and salads, good for sauce,
baking, pies and freezing.
</P>
<P>
   Special hint: Small Empires are great in school lunches.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cortland: Developed at the New York State Agricultural
Experiment Station in Geneva in 1898, it is a cross between Ben
Davis and McIntosh.
</P>
<P>
   What's it like: Sweet with a hint of tartness, juicy and tender,
with snow white flesh.
</P>
<P>
   Best uses: Excellent for eating, salads, sauce, pies and baking;
good for freezing.
</P>
<P>
   Special hint: Cortlands work well for kebabs, fruit plates and
garnishes because they don't turn brown quickly when cut.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ida Red: Engineered in 1942 at the Idaho Experimental Station,
it's a cross between two old-fashioned New York state apples,
Jonathan and Wagener.
</P>
<P>
   What's it like: Sweetly tart, juicy with firm pale yellow-green
flesh that's sometimes tinted rosy pink.
</P>
<P>
   Best uses: Excellent for sauce, cooking, baking and pies; good
for eating, salads and freezing.
</P>
<P>
   Special hint: Ida Reds make a beautiful pink applesauce. Cook
the apples with the skins on and strain the sauce to get the best
pink color.
</P>
<P>
   _ Red Rome: A superb cooking apple, perfect fried apple slices
sitting next to a pork chop are probably Red Romes.
</P>
<P>
   What's it like: Mildly tart with firm, greenish-white flesh.
</P>
<P>
   Best uses: Excellent for sauce, baking and pies; good for salad
and freezing.
</P>
<P>
   Special hint: Combine Red Romes with a sweet apple such as
Golden Delicious for tasty applesauce.
</P>
<P>
   _ Golden Delicious: Juicy and honey-sweet, it is related in name
only to the Red Delicious.
</P>
<P>
   What's it like: Mild sweet flavor, juicy, with crisp, light
yellow flesh.
</P>
<P>
   Best uses: Excellent for eating, salads and sauce; good for
pies, baking and freezing.
</P>
<P>
   Special hint: You can cut down the sugar in pies and sauces made
from Golden Delicious apples.
</P>
<P>
   _ Crispin: Originally called the Mutsu, reflecting its Japanese
heritage, it was renamed in the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   What's it like: Sweet yet very refreshing, very juicy and super
crisp.
</P>
<P>
   Best uses: Excellent for eating, sauce, baking and freezing;
good for salad and pies.
</P>
<P>
   Special hint: Try Crispins for roasting whole apples or thick
slices, an accompaniment to a favorite roast.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jonagold: Another success story from the New York State
Agricultural Experiment Station in Geneva, it's a cross between
mellow Golden Delicious and tart Jonathan.
</P>
<P>
   What's it like: Honey-sweet with a hint of tartness, juicy with
crisp, creamy yellow flesh.
</P>
<P>
   Best uses: Excellent for eating, salads, sauce and baking; good
for pies and freezing.
</P>
<P>
   Special hint: Jonagolds make great fried apples. Simply saute in
a little butter and add a little cinnamon. No sugar needed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Macoun: Developed in New York in 1932, it's a cross between
McIntosh and Jersey Black and named for a famous Canadian fruit
breeder.
</P>
<P>
   What's it like: Extra sweet and aromatic, very juicy and tender
with snow-white flesh.
</P>
<P>
   Best uses: Excellent for eating; good for sauce and salads.
</P>
<P>
   Special hint: Try serving Macoun slices with cheese for an
autumn dessert.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sources: The New York Apple Association, based on Long Island,
and the Indian Ladder Farms apple orchard in Altamont, N.Y.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
