<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, Sept. 23:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-QUAKE (Taipei) _ Ledeall on aftermath of the earthquake
in Taiwan: the death toll nears 1,700; Many people remain trapped
in the debris. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-SCENE (Taichung, Taiwan) _ The scene from the big city
nearest the earthquake's epicenter. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-RDP (Dili, East Timor) _ The international aid program _
food, shelter and medical care _ is hindered by security concerns.
By Seth Myans.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The House Banking Committee holds
hearings on Russian corruption. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-ISRAEL (Oranienburg, Germany) _ On a spot where Nazi
victims were cremated during World War II, Israel's prime minister
and Germany's chancellor paid tribute Wednesday to those killed in
the Holocaust and promised to fight intolerance. The sober ceremony
at the former Sachsenhausen concentration camp was the emotional
highlight of a visit strong on symbolism. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-HAMAS (Jerusalem) _ Jordan arrested three Hamas leaders
on Wednesday as they returned to the country; a weapons cache was
reported seized; Israeli Prime Barak praises both the detention and
King Abdullah. By William A. Orme.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-POLITICS (Beijing) _ Developments at the Central Committee
meeting. China renewed its pledge to restructure and marketize
state enterprises, offering a few specific initiatives such as
incentive pay for bosses, but in language that reeked of
compromises with threatened interests. Also, Hu Jintao, 56, was
elevated to vice chairman of central military commission, yet
another sign that President Jiang is grooming him as a successor.
By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-FREE-PARIS (Paris) _ Cars were banned for a day in Paris,
Rome and scores of other European cities to celebrate a noise and
pollution-free. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   EAST-EUROPE-WOMEN (Geneva) _ The situation of women and children
in many Eastern European countries and former Soviet republics has
spiraled downward since the collapse of communism, with women
struggling with fewer unemployment opportunities, deteriorating
education and health services, increasing drug and alcohol abuse
and more violence, the U.N. Children's Fund reported Wednesday. By
Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-ASSEMBLY (United Nations) _ Developments in the General
Assembly. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-SUIT (Washington) _ Ledeall on the Justice Department
filing its suit against the tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebars as needed.
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Developments, including opening
blows in the fight to restore funding for the F-22 jet in
conference. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Developments on gun control
legislation. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-PORN (Washington) _ Show-casing its new computer crime
lab, the government announces global fraud case involving internet
pornography. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-NETWORK (Washington) _ Federal agents announce arrest of 80
to 100 people and seizure of some $19 million in cash in connection
with a cocaine-distribution network that ran from a border town in
Mexico to the Northeast and Midwest, using warehouses and produce
trucks for storage and shipment and enlisting cooperation of
Dominicans and Colombians. By David Stout.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DOLE-EDUC (Melrose, Mass.) _ Elizabeth Dole outlines her
education philosophy. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-CAROLINA (Tarboro, N.C.) _ What life without water has
been like for 44,000 people in Greenville, N.C, and other
developments in cleaning up after Hurricane Floyd. By David
Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-SWEEPSTATES-SUIT Florida sues Publishers Clearing House in a
case that shows continued government pressure on sweepstakes firms
to tone down promotions. By Douglas Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SAKS-OUTLOOK (New York) _ Saks Fifth Avenue, the venerable
clothier to the ladies who lunch, has just turned 75, but a placid
old age is not in the cards. Even with America in the midst of the
biggest income and retail boom of the century, Saks Fifth Avenue _
along with Neiman-Marcus, one of the nation's last two chains of
luxury department stores _ is struggling to make the kind of
profits Wall Street demands of retailers. The secret to
high-fashion success has always been finding the right balance
between nurturing cutting-edge design and stocking enough
money-making name brands to satisfy traditional customers. For
Saks, under new and very bottom-line-oriented management, that
balancing act has turned particularly precarious.
</P>
<P>
   OIL-PRICES (Undated) _ Higher retail prices for gasoline and
heating are expected this winter, as OPEC ministers agree to
maintain supply limits through April. By Agis Salpukas.
</P>
<P>
   MORGAN-EARNINGS (New York) _ Morgan Stanley Dean Witter reports
a 55 percent gain in third-quarter earnings, led by investment
banking and a recovery in asset management and trading a year after
Russia's default led to a worldwide bond rout. The results were 4
cents better than expected. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   XEROX-TEKTRONIX (Undated) _ Xerox agrees to buy the color
printing division of Tektronix Inc. for $950 million in a deal that
will make Xerox second only to Hewlett-Packard in the office color
printing market. By Claudia H. Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-CHIP-IMPACT (Singapore) _ From makers of cellular phones
to personal computers to Furby dolls, anyone whose livelihood
depends on electronics could end up feeling reverberations from
Taiwan's devastating earthquake this week. Story will try to get
details and estimates on the impact.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 2:15 p.m., stocks were mixed: The Dow
Jones industrial average was down 53 points, the S&AMP;P 500 up 2
points and the Nasdaq composite up 16. The 30-year bond was at 6.09
percent. European markets were lower, with London down 0.26 percent
and Frankfurt down 0.66 percent. The Nikkei tumbled 3.39 percent,
while the Hang Seng fell 1.73 percent. The dollar weakend to 103.84
yen, but was steady at 1.0511 euro. By Robert D. Hershey.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The weekly Economic Scene column. By
Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Bob Herbert's ``In America'' and William Safire's ``Essay.''
