<TEXT>
<P>
   Home Section stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Thursday, Sept. 23:
</P>
<P>
   NY-TOWNHOUSE (New York) _ On the lean, modern house Clarissa
Alcock Bronfman and her husband, Edgar Bronfman Jr., have just
built for themselves. The landmarked facade of the Upper East Side
townhouse is laced with wrought iron detailing and a neoclassical
restraint that Edith Wharton would have loved. Step inside, and you
forget the past: Where traditional wood once reigned, the vestibule
is now paneled in sheets of steel, waxed to a warm shade of bronze.
Two steps up, a steel and glass door swings open to a sunfilled
piazza. By Jule Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Dora
Galitzki.
</P>
<P>
   ARIZ-SOLAR-HOUSE (Tonopah, Ariz.) _ From the highway, it is six
miles to Brenda Black's house near Tonopah, along a dusty road
through boulders and saguaro cactus. For the first four miles, a
power line parallels the road. But then the necklace of wooden
poles and black cables _ the reassuring accompaniment to millions
of miles of American highways _ ends. The house is still 1,000 feet
away. In Arizona, it is becoming easy for ordinary families to live
``off the grid'' _ that is, without a hookup to electric lines _
and not sacrifice comfort. By Fred Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GOETHE-GARDEN-HOUSE (Weimar, Germany) _ Weimar has been enjoying
a year of being the official European ``cultural capital,'' a
designation prompted by Goethe's 250th birthday in August. Rather
than simply polish up Weimar's many landmarks, the organizers
challenged their visitors with an experimental conjuring trick.
They constructed an exact copy of the city's most famous building,
Goethe's Garden House, a hundred yards from the original. By Jan
Otakar Fischer.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With howto drawing.
</P>
