<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1714 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-COSMETICS-ONLINE-HNS &LR;      09-22 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSMETICS-ONLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN TURN BEAUTY PRODUCTS IDEA INTO ON-LINE VENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Who ever heard of buying cosmetics on line? You
can't touch them, smell them, try them. But then, if you live in
Helena, Mont., or somewhere in Guam, there probably isn't a decent
high-end cosmetics counter in sight to purchase those delicious
luxury goods that show up in Vogue, W and Harper's Bazaar. What's a
girl to do?
</P>
<P>
   Log on, of course.
</P>
<P>
   According to Women's Wear Daily, there are 18 beauty e-tailing
sites. To name just a few, there's iBeauty.com, jasmin.com
(fragrance only), eve.com, plus huge new drugstore sites _
planetrx.com, owned by powerful French conglomerate LVMH (Louis
Vuitton Moet Hennessey) and drugstore.com, which is affiliated with
amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   But by this time next year, you can be sure that some of them
will have disappeared into the Great Virtual Void. The ones that do
make it will have a lot of money behind them and experienced
cosmetic industry professionals at the helm.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, one of the most promising beauty addresses on the
World Wide Web is gloss.com, the brainchild of two former
executives with Bath and Body Works who met in Columbus, Ohio, and
escaped as fast as they could.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Columbus is such a bad place, but it did lend
itself to some daydreaming, which gloss.com's founder and chief
executive Sarah Kugelman, 35, did in abundance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came up with this idea four years ago,'' said Kugelman, a
slender New Yorker with a wild mane of honey-blond hair and that
go-go mein of someone who lives by Palm Pilot, e-mail and laptop.
</P>
<P>
   When she made a presentation to the president of Bath and Beauty
Works, a division of The Limited, about the huge retailing
potential of an on-line beauty and bath product site, ``I was told:
`It's not important.'''
</P>
<P>
   But someone else at that boardroom table heard and understood,
and told her not to lose sight of the site _ ``It's the future,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, B&AMP;BW was building retail stores. When Kugelman
arrived, there were 100; when she left, there were 750, and it is
possible that the president wasn't exactly thinking beyond real
estate.
</P>
<P>
   Kugelman did not lose her vision. Through a move to New York and
a stint in Banana Republic's burgeoning fragrance/home department,
Kugelman, with another former B&AMP;BW exec, Deanna Kangas, 33, who is
gloss.com's co-founder and vice president of marketing, worked out
a business plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sat in a drawer for two or three years,'' said Kugelman,
and then at a dinner party in January a banker heard her talking
about The Plan. ``What I didn't know was that he had raised $70
million for iVillage,'' Kugelman said. When the banker asked: ``Do
you understand what you're sitting on?'' she hardly knew what to
say.
</P>
<P>
   Within six weeks, that banker had snagged $4.75 million to
launch gloss.com. Recently, the site has gone through its second
round of funding, bringing in $20 million. One of the problems
involved in securing funding, however, was that ``men didn't
understand the impulse concept around cosmetics,'' Kugelman said.
``When we started talking about it, they'd glaze over. I had to
tell them: More women I know use lipstick than read books.''
</P>
<P>
   In building a new site, which is scheduled to be launched on
Sept. 27, it was necessary for gloss.com to secure a product. The
decision was made to go after innovative, smaller companies
(although some of the majors will eventually sign up) whose
distribution or number of ``doors'' is very small. (``Doors'' is a
cosmetic industry term for how many stores the products are sold
in.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We've told a brand like Philosophy to consider us their main
on-line `door,''' said Kangas, indicating that there has been some
education involved about the fiscal possibilities of on-line
merchandising. The only difference between a Nordstrom cosmetic
department and gloss.com is the touchy-feely aspect and the instant
gratification of being able to take the product home immediately.
</P>
<P>
   For that customer, however, who is geographically isolated and
logging on from a small town or one in which the biggest brand she
can buy is Revlon, cosmetic satisfaction is just a keystroke away.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brands include Peter Thomas Roth, a line of excellent skin
products (particularly the tinted moisturizer and sunblock)
heretofore available only from facialists and spas; Cielo, Tom and
Susan Hayward's Napa Valley Fragrances; Three Custom Color, which
will match any fabric swatch for eyeshadow or your favorite
out-of-stock lipstick; Tony and Tina, a youthful color line; Calvin
Klein fragrance; and Philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to go for prestige department store and unique
boutique and European brands _ the kind you'd find at Barney's (in
New York) and Fred Segel (in Los Angeles),'' Kugelman said.
</P>
<P>
   The home page of gloss.com has links to all the products,
arranged in five key categories: fragrance, skin care, color, home
fragrance and accessories. There is a master list of what's
available and with a simple click, each company has a brand page
with images controlled by the companies themselves, color swatches
and descriptions of each product. Part of the interactive component
is a virtual makeover where a user will be able to scan in her own
image and then experiment with different shades of lipstick, eye
shadow and blush, which is almost like being there, or so it is
hoped.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
