<P>
   Science and health stories from The New York Times News Service
for  &UR; THURSDAY &LR; , Sept. 23.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HUMAN-GENES (Undated) _ A new calculation of the number of
human genes puts the total far higher than previous estimates,
meaning that the human organism is considerably more complex than
expected. The new estimate, by Incyte Pharmaceuticals of Palo Alto,
Calif., puts the number of human genes at 140,000. An earlier
calculation, by Dr. J. Craig Venter, now of the Celera Corp., had
predicted 60,000 to 80,000 genes. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MD-HORMONE (Undated) _ A hormone produced in bone marrow
transplants in mice gives hope for a treatment for muscular
dystrophy. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CANCER-CARE (Washington) _ A study finds that patients with
terminal cancer get far better care than those with other fatal
illnesses, even though cancer causes only 23 percent of all deaths,
placing a greater burden on the families of people with other
illnesses. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
