<P>
   COUNTRY MUSIC-DOLDRUMS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ARLINGTON _ Heartbreak, hangovers and hard times are what
country music is all about. But lately, it's the state of the
industry, not the songs, that has radio programmers, artists and
Nashville executives crying in their beer. Country record sales are
bottoming out. Radio stations are dropping the format. Word is,
even The Nashville Network is planning to ax its flagship country
show in November. By JOHN AUSTIN and SHIRLEY JINKINS. Story will
move in ``e'' entertainment category &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   L I F E S T Y L E &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WORKPLACE-SURVEILLANCE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Big Brother is watching. And it's increasingly likely
that the Omniscient One is your boss. She might be recording the
casual conversations between you and a co-worker, or tracking
e-mails on your company computer, or watching the goings-on in the
staff lounge. Sound like an invasion of your privacy? Think again.
Most employee monitoring in the workplace is perfectly legal, and
happens more than most people realize. By Liz Stevens. (Accompanied
by SURVEILLANCE-WHO.) Stories will move in ``l'' lifestyle
category &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
