<HEADER>
A1743 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-BROWNFIELDS-HNS &LR;      09-22 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWNFIELDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIERRA CLUB OUT OF TOUCH ON URBAN DEVELOPMENT ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Sierra Club took an unexpected hit July 5,
when it was called elitist in a full-page advertisement in the New
York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Sierra Club were predictably indignant. They
claimed to deserve better.
</P>
<P>
   It could have been worse. ``Racist'' and ``fascist'' also were
kicked around by the militant young copywriters at the Greenlining
Institute, which bought the ad space for the big-type screed. The
institute, like the Sierra Club, is a San Francisco-based
organization with a vision of how things should be. I'm told the
authors of the ad were restrained by their boss, John Gamboa, who
sees the Sierra Club as a potential ally.
</P>
<P>
   The institute wants to transform California's estimated 30,000
fallow inner-city lots, or ``brownfields,'' into sites for
educational, commercial and recreational activities for inner-city
residents.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club could help to put this effort into orbit, but it
is balking. People at the institute think that is because the
Sierra Club is just a group of self-important white liberals who
don't have a clue about real life in the inner city.
</P>
<P>
   Which could indeed be the case with regard to some members. I
think of the Sierrans as aging tree huggers who have upgraded from
Birkenstocks to Kenneth Cole, from VWs to BMWs and from granola to
eggs benedict, as the value of their stock portfolios has risen.
</P>
<P>
   Well intended. Good at planning vacations. Not as effective as
they could be if they went farther out on a limb, politically, than
their comfortable lifestyles permit. The Greenliners, on the other
hand, see them as faux progressives who talk the talk.
</P>
<P>
   The Greenlining Institute, which has an office on Market Street
within walking distance of the Sierra Club's national headquarters
in San Francisco, is a coalition of 50 community-based civil rights
and minority small-business organizations dedicated to improving
inner-city neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   It is mainly led by Hispanics, African-Americans and Asians. In
the past, the institute has gone after insurers and banks for
redlining inner-city minorities, and much of its annual income of
about $1.5 million comes from lawsuits it wins or settles.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the institute has turned its sights on the thousands
of abandoned inner-city properties that may or may not be too
contaminated by commercial and industrial wastes to be redeveloped
lawfully and at reasonable cost.
</P>
<P>
   In the name of economic justice, the Greenliners want to ease
the laws applying to potential development on these properties so
that an African-American parochial school, say, can turn a nearby
brownfield into a playground without being forced to excavate to a
depth that breaks the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Alternatively, a small business might be encouraged to move in,
if the cost of building a parking lot on a brownfield site was not
prohibitive. The institute balances community needs with
environmental goals, favoring the former but not to the exclusion
of the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, in the last legislative session in Sacramento, the
institute backed SB 324, a measure by state Sen. Martha Escutia,
D-Commerce. SB 324 would have been a first step in turning those
fields of brown into fields of gold.
</P>
<P>
   A key feature would have written into law the practice of
calibrating cleanups to planned uses, with sites more likely to
expose people to toxins _ residential and recreational sites, most
obviously _ held to higher standards. The measure went nowhere. The
institute is convinced Sierra Club lobbyists shot it down.
</P>
<P>
   When Sierra Club director Carl Pope responded to a letter from
Gamboa inquiring about the club's concerns _ two months after it
was sent _ he indicated SB 324 was defective because it bypassed
existing safeguards and threatened liability and cleanup standards.
In other words, it was too lax.
</P>
<P>
   Gamboa claims to have gotten 300 calls or electronic-mail
messages in response to the ad, about half from Sierra Club
members, 40 percent of whom, he said, thought the criticism of
their own organization was on target.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a deep resentment against the Sierra Club that goes
back many years,'' Gamboa said. ``The theme is this is a white
elitist group telling us, again, what's good for us. How dare they?
This is a self-determination thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Pope said the ad was ``unfortunate,'' but he declined to get in
a shouting match. He emphasized the seriousness of the toxics
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a disagreement about whether particular changes in
the law will or will not expose kids to dangers,'' Pope said. ``We
might be wrong. He might be wrong. The reality is: Nobody knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Agreed. Reasonable efforts to improve the situation shouldn't be
undermined, least of all by privileged outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Scott Winokur writes for the San Francisco Examiner.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
