<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1755 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-COUNTRYMUSIC-DOLDRUMS     09-22 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNTRYMUSIC-DOLDRUMS-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
ARLINGTON, Texas: strong, McNeill said. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Industry insiders emphasize that all musical genres go through
boom and bust cycles.
</P>
<P>
   Country surged after the ``Urban Cowboy'' phenomenon in the
1970s. It lapsed for several years, compelling country supergroup
Alabama to perform a duet with pop star Lionel Richie at the 1985
Country Music Association Awards.
</P>
<P>
   The genre began working up steam again around 1986, when Randy
Travis captured the charts from Kenny Rogers, and exploding in 1989
with the likes of Brooks and Dunn and Clint Black.
</P>
<P>
   Many observers attribute some of the trouble to the fact that
once country heated up, record companies rushed to sign anybody who
looked or sounded like the new kids, whether they had the right
stuff or not.
</P>
<P>
   Fans have defected to talk radio and music competitors, and the
radio powerhouses are scrambling to bring them back.
</P>
<P>
   The crossover success of artists such as LeAnn Rimes hasn't
necessarily helped country radio either.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Rimes scored country's first multi-platinum single.
She is also only the second female recording artists to sell 3
million or more on a single. But country stations aren't
necessarily cheering her success.
</P>
<P>
   Rimes' big hit, ``How Can I Live Without You,'' received much of
its support from pop fans. And if a listener can hear a song on his
or her favorite pop radio station, there's little reason to turn
the dial to country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem comes when ... people don't have to turn the dial
to hear the kind of music they like,'' Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   However, many country radio folks think the slide has bottomed
out.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's the feeling among people like KSCS music
director Linda O'Brian.
</P>
<P>
   She is convinced that there's another corral full of talent
ready to break out of the chute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're due for another cycle,'' she said. ``I see
future Alan Jacksons and future George Straits. I don't feel that
bad about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Rogers, director of national promotions for Columbia
Records, a division of Sony in Nashville, Tenn., said that the past
six months have yielded new signs of life in country.
</P>
<P>
   His label is notching a record year so far in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like we've bottomed out,'' he said.''We're seeing a
resurgence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shipped two million copies on the Dixie Chicks,'' he said.
``That's more than we have ever shipped in Sony history.''
</P>
<P>
   And for those who have a long memory, 2 million _ or half that _
shows just how far country has come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember when 100,000 was a monster,'' North Texas
promoter Johnnie High said. And as far as he's concerned, country
music could hardly get any better. His weekly Arlington country
music revue is broadcast on seven 50,000-watt stations from Idaho
to Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, all Sony has to do is move those 2 million Dixie
Chicks CDs. Considering that the disc will probably be gold by
month's end, according to Recording Industry Association sources _
it's at No. 1 on the country and Billboard Top 200 charts right now
_ it looks pretty likely.
</P>
<P>
   And if the company can get enough Chicks fans into the record
stores, the odds are that they'll pick up a disc or two by other
new artists.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
