<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1758 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-COUNTRYMUSIC-DOLDRUMS     09-22 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNTRYMUSIC-DOLDRUMS-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTRY MUSIC HAS PLENTY OF REASONS FOR HEARTACHE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN AUSTIN 
and SHIRLEY JINKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Heartbreak, hangovers and hard times are what
country music is all about.
</P>
<P>
   But lately, it's the state of the industry, not the songs, that
has radio programmers, artists and Nashville executives crying in
their beer.
</P>
<P>
   Country record sales are bottoming out. Radio stations are
dropping the format. Word is, even The Nashville Network is
planning to ax its flagship country show in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're basically back to audience numbers that we had in
1988,'' said KYNG/105.3 FM program director Bob McNeill. ``From
spring '98 to spring '99, 11 percent of the core hour (of
listeners) has left the format.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is suggesting that country music is out _ all genres go
through boom and bust cycles, and the new Dixie Chicks CD sold
341,000 copies its first week _ but it is indisputably down,
locally and nationally.
</P>
<P>
   The slump dates back as far as 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Country music sales hit a whopping $2 billion that year, up from
$723 million in 1990. But the genre was down from what may have
been a historic peak in 1993, when Garth Brooks and his country
cousins accounted for 18.7 percent of total sales.
</P>
<P>
   Sales slipped to 16.7 percent of the market by '95 and by 1998
were down to 14.1 percent of the market, according to the Recording
Industry Association of America. Statistics for 1999 were not
available.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent telephone interview, Brooks talked about the state
of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our format is looking for its identity right now,''
Brooks said. ``When they let people make the kind of country that's
interesting, people will turn over.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks attributed part of the slump to the loss of country
stations in big markets such as Seattle. He also noted that the
number of venues for live performances has dwindled from when he
was coming up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're missing one huge element: the dance halls,'' Brooks
said. ``I don't know where the new guys are playing anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The current downturn has everybody from performers to radio
programmers wondering when _ or whether _ country will once again
pack the power to kick weaker formats off radio dials and redefine
mainstream tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks himself is making his next release a rock 'n' roll
project.
</P>
<P>
   To stanch the wounds locally, radio executives have tightened
play lists, ``rebranded'' their stations with new identities, and
added left-of-center acts such as singer/songwriter Robert Earl
Keen. But what radio is really waiting for is the second coming of
Garth _ someone who can lasso fans from other genres and still
appeal to core country listeners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big picture is not pretty,'' McNeill said. ``The last
couple of years, most of us have been sitting around wringing our
hands and saying, `Oh, gosh.'''
</P>
<P>
   As recently as five years ago, country stations held two of the
top three quarterly local ratings spots. The three top country
local radio stations consistently appeared in the top 10 quarterly
rankings.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, many of the fans who filled stadiums to see country
acts and tuned in country radio in the early and mid-'90s now
prefer genres such as rock, which has grown more listener-friendly
since five years ago, when Seattle grunge was strong, McNeill said.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
