<HEADER>
A1761 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-MLK-0923-COX     09-22 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-MLK-0923-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BOOK: SOVIET KGB TRIED TO RECRUIT, DISCREDIT MARTIN LUTHER KING
 &HT;    580&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Hoping to fuel America's racial strife during the early
1960s Soviet spies tried to influence Martin Luther King Jr. as he
led the burgeoning civil rights movement, according to a new book
by a British scholar.
</P>
<P>
   And when attempts to control King failed, the KGB concocted a
plan to discredit him among blacks by depicting him as an ``Uncle
Tom,'' the book says.
</P>
<P>
   The book, ``The Sword and the Shield,'' also contends that
communist operatives tried to influence Andrew Young when he was
ambassador to the United Nations during the Carter Administration.
The KGB didn't have much more success with Young.
</P>
<P>
   The former ambassador, now an Atlanta businessman, said
Wednesday that he found the book's assertions ironic. ``Well, for
years the FBI tried to say that Martin and I were communists, so
it's good to hear from the KGB side that they weren't able to get
to us,'' Young said. ``It's a thrill to know they tried to mess
with me and failed.''
</P>
<P>
   The book's author, Christopher Andrew, is a history professor at
Cambridge University and a frequent writer on Soviet espionage.
Andrew based this book on information provided by Vasili Mitrokhin,
a KGB archivist who retired in 1984 and smuggled hundreds of
classified documents to Britain. The book went on sale in the
United States on Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   The Mitrokhin files, which the British considered reliable
enough to share with the CIA and FBI, have offered Western
intelligence and law enforcement officials a treasure trove of
historical information about KGB operations around the world.
</P>
<P>
   One of the books most startling revelations is the case of
Melita Norwood, an 87-year-old great-grandmother who passed
information about Britain's atomic bomb program to the Soviets
during the 1930s and 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1960s, American Communist Party leaders told Soviet
officials they would try to influence King by employing ``secret
party members within King's entourage,'' the book says. However,
KGB officials determined by the mid-1960s that this strategy was
failing. To the KGB's dismay, King was arguing that the civil
rights movement should fight to include blacks in the American
Dream rather than destroying the American system.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the KGB sought to replace him with someone more
radical, such as then-Black Panther Party leader Stokeley
Carmichael, the book says. In August 1967, the Soviet spy agency
tried to discredit King by placing stories in African newspapers
depicting him as an ``Uncle Tom.'' The articles said that President
Lyndon Johnson's administration was giving King secret ``government
subsidies to tame the civil rights movement.'' The KGB believed he
U.S. media would pick up these stories.
</P>
<P>
   When King was assassinated in April 1968, the KGB switched its
approach, the book says. The agency's covert operatives in the
United States then began to portray King as a ``martyr of the black
liberation movement.'' They began circulating rumors that ``his
murder had been planned by white racists with the connivance of the
authorities.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, American Communist Party leaders boasted that they
expected to be able to influence Young, a former King lieutenant
whom Carter made United Nations ambassador. The book quotes Gus
Hall, longtime leader of the Communist Party of the United States,
as saying: ``Young himself did not know that several of his close
friends in Atlanta were covert communists, and he listened to
them.'' However, KGB officials considered Hall's assessment
exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Viktor Lesiovsky, a KGB officer working as special assistant to
then-U.N. Secretary General U Thant, met frequently with Young and
reported that he received ``important information'' from these
meetings. However, Lesiovsky reported to the KGB that Young's
attitude toward the Soviet Union was ``fundamentally negative.''
</P>
<P>
   Young said he was unaware at the time that Lesiovsky was with
the KGB. He said he did tip off the Soviets to American initiatives
coming before the Security Council as a matter of good politics.
``We never received a Russian veto of anything we were trying to
put through,'' he said. ``I worked well with the Russians and we
achieved everything we wanted to achieve.''
</P>
<P>
   The connections between King and his lieutenants and American
communists have been studied extensively before, and at least one
scholar who has studied King was unimpressed with much of what he
has read in the book.
</P>
<P>
   David Garrow, a history professor at Emory University in
Atlanta, said it all sounded pretty familiar.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really nothing new here other than the assertion that
the KGB was going to portray King as an Uncle Tom in the African
press,'' said Garrow, who wrote the 1981 book ``The FBI and Martin
Luther King Jr.'' ``And that's incredibly loony.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
