<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-KNEES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGET DOT.COM AND INVENT ARTIFCIAL KNEE LIGAMENTS! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If the cruel and capricious game of football
survives a decade or two into the 21st century, maybe some genius
will take a break from the mounting dot-com dreck and figure out a
way to make and install artificial knee ligaments for the sport's
student-athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it: super-strong, resilient knee ligaments, made of
some as-yet unknown material, capable of withstanding the front
bumper of a Lexus at 30 miles an hour, attached to your favorite
running back. The stuff would combine the elasticity of a gymnast
with the strength of steel and snap back into place with no damage
to the knee.
</P>
<P>
   They'd like some of this future fabric down in Atlanta. An MRI
of Jamal Anderson's right knee revealed a torn anterior cruciate
ligament, meaning the Falcons' running back is out for the
remainder of the season. All because he planted his foot Monday
night in Texas Stadium and his knee kept on going.
</P>
<P>
   It's an artificial turf injury, to be sure, and it underscores
the utterly evil nature of the stuff and its incompatibility with
human beings engaged in the inhuman activity of football.
</P>
<P>
   That said, ``How 'bout those 49ers?''
</P>
<P>
   Their task just got a little easier with Tuesday's news about
Anderson, who was unstoppable last season as he carried an
NFL-record 410 times for 1,846 yards. Ask Merton Hanks how
unstoppable Anderson was; he's the reason Hanks is now a Seattle
Seahawk, waived by Bill Walsh because he couldn't tackle the
235-pound Dirty Bird.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of preparing to face Anderson twice in 1999, the 49ers
will not see him at all, except on the sidelines. For Atlanta, his
loss is similar to what the 49ers are going through without
Garrison Hearst. Without a feature back, an offense loses focus and
becomes more diffuse, with several inferior people trying to make
up for what one man did so well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel badly for Jamal Anderson,'' 49ers coach Steve Mariucci
said. ``He's a heck of a player, a heck of a guy. I hate to see it
happen to anybody. You hate to see a professional athlete sit for
the year with a season-ending injury. It's a tough, tough break. We
all know as coaches and players that that sort of thing happens on
occasion and we have to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons will try to make do with Bryon Hanspard, who is not
Jamal Anderson. That puts the burden on quarterback Chris Chandler,
the human equivalent of a road sign on a lonely stretch of desert.
</P>
<P>
   That is, all shot up, dented and chipped but still standing.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler missed Monday night's game against Dallas with a groin
injury. Such injuries become worse with age and more than a few
athletes have faded into retirement because of them.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the oddity of the schedule, the 49ers do not play the
Falcons until Dec. 12 at Candlestick but then face them twice in a
three-week period. The second game wraps up the regular season on
Monday night, Jan. 3, 2000, in the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   I'm one of those folks who believes the new century begins in
the year 2000, simply because of the number 2 followed by three
zeroes. The 20th century will end on Dec. 31, 1999, with, we
believe, more people engaged in bedroom activity than at any time
in history because of the rare opportunity to, ahem, carry on from
one century to another. Now that's staying power!
</P>
<P>
   We bring up the subject of the new century because if football
is to survive, it will have to do something about the ruinous toll
knee injuries take.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for some genius in a garage or a lab to combine This,
That and The Other Thing and create something to take the place of
human knee ligaments.
</P>
<P>
   Medical science has already given us artificial hips and knees
and prosthetic devices to aid the impaired. Why not ligaments?
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is one of the young stars in the NFL, a delight to
watch but tough to tackle as he uses his low center of gravity and
his 235 pounds to punish those in his way. The league needs him
churning those thunder thighs to make its product more watchable.
</P>
<P>
   That's of no concern to the 49ers, of course. They have their
own problems, such as how to keep Steve Young healthy for 14 more
games and how to run the ball effectively without Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   While their secondary is suspect, the 49ers look like they will
be decent against the run, based on how they defended
Jacksonville's Fred Taylor (74 yards) and New Orleans' Ricky
Williams (80). And now Williams has a sprained right elbow that
might limit his ability to do such football-y things as carry the
ball in his tiny right hand and catch the darn thing as well.
</P>
<P>
   The new century figures to bring many wonderful things, starting
with horizontal hilarity on an epic scale. Football's wish list is
more modest. Artificial ACLs, perhaps?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
