<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-VULTURES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURKEY VULTURES CREATE RUCKUS IN CALIFORNIA TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL DOUGAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERCED, Calif. _ Turkey vultures have tightened their talons on
a five-block stretch of one of the busiest boulevards in this
Central Valley town, generating a neighborly conflict that could
almost be described as agitated.
</P>
<P>
   At six pounds or so of body weight, the birds are round in the
roost. They have naked little heads, alien eyes and can measure up
to six feet in wingspan, and they regurgitate their carrion prey at
the first hint of distress.
</P>
<P>
   And here they are, content in the 60-foot limbs of two parallel
lines of eucalyptus along M Street. There are at least 200 of the
big, fat turkey vultures hovering over the four-lane avenue near
the north section of Merced, a town with nearly 60,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   To some townsfolk, the birds have become a public threat; to
others they are an environmental wonder. But Monday evening, as
residents on both sides of the debate watched from their lawns or
along the narrow sidewalks of M Street, the vultures became a
target of a vulture-relocation project sought by city officials.
</P>
<P>
   Fireworks were used to roust from their roosts a multitude of
birds that, as near as anyone could tell, promptly flew back home
after flying in graceful circles overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Partch, a wildlife specialist from the U.S. Department of
Agriculture, who was in charge of firing off the pyrotechnic
devices, was not bothered. It was expected, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we're trying to do is make the birds uncomfortable,''
Partch said, adding that the fireworks would be back every night
until the birds were gone.
</P>
<P>
   The flock of the vultures has lived, for as long as anyone can
remember, in the trees long before houses were built, around 1975.
Some say that this year there are more than ever, and they have
some mighty unpleasant habits.
</P>
<P>
   When startled, turkey vultures defend themselves by
regurgitating their last meals _ dinners that were dead long before
the 5-pound scavengers with 6-foot wingspans took their first
tentative nibble. Also, they defecate and drop feathers.
</P>
<P>
   The ballyhooed effort to drive the birds out of town used what
had been characterized as pyrotechnics. Not quite.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have ones that pop and we have ones that whistle,'' Partch
said early in the program as he moved his white pickup from block
to block, stopping at each intersection to pop or whistle at the
birds overhead.
</P>
<P>
   The popping pyrotechnics were louder than a ladyfinger but
considerably quieter than a cherry bomb. The whistlers _ fired from
a Baretta-style flare gun _ sounded like airborne party favors.
</P>
<P>
   More volume came from protesters _ mostly, but not entirely,
adolescent _ who gathered along M Street and, at the first salvo,
yelled wry epithets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, there are bird droppings and there are times I have to
clear, off my car, but that's nothing to do with the environment,
so save the birds,'' declared Claudia Linke, who lives near M
Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived here two years and they keep multiplying,
especially this year,'' countered Lupe Septien, whose house
occupies a corner at M and Donna streets. ``That said, I have to go
skim my pool because all the turkey feathers are in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Long of the California Academy of Sciences in San
Francisco couldn't relate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think it's cool as heck if I had a bunch of turkey
vultures in my back yard, but I'm kind of a nut for that stuff,''
said Long, who holds a doctorate in ornithology.
</P>
<P>
   He admitted that ``it's sort of a low-grade health issue when
you have birds vomiting their food, but it's not a hazardous
situation''
</P>
<P>
   While arguing that dogs or cats ``pass more diseases to their
owners'' than turkey vultures, Long sympathized with Merced
residents on an elemental level. ``Having a bird that's the size of
a small turkey, black with a bald head, peering down at you and
throwing up bones of road kill'' might not be ideal, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
