<HEADLINE>
CHURCH SHOOTING REFLECTS OUR NATIONAL SHORT TEMPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By DIANA BUTLER BASS &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Following the Fort Worth church shooting, one woman commented,
``If something like that can happen in a church, it can happen
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans revere two public places -- school and church.
For generations, learning and faith guarded our village greens,
main streets and frontier towns.
</P>
<P>
   They embodied the national ideal of a moral democracy. To
paraphrase, ``if it can happen there, it attacks our soul.''
</P>
<P>
   School and church have been violated by a murder spree beyond
comprehension. What has happened in our most sacred places and to
children, our most vulnerable members? We are sad, confused and
exhausted by this violence. We struggle to find meaning amid the
suffering.
</P>
<P>
   On the PBS news program, ``Religion and Ethics Weekly,'' Mark
Wingfield, an editor of the Baptist Standard newspaper, reported
that many conservative Christians see the latest violence ``as
symptomatic of the larger cultural war'' in American society-- a
``spiritual battle between light and dark in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   This interpretation, being promoted by the religious right,
appeals to those most immediately affected. The slain children and
teachers did not die needlessly. They were victims of a great
cosmic drama -- the unfolding war between God and the devil.
</P>
<P>
   Theologically, this is the stuff of martyrdom. It draws
believers into a biblical epic with eternal consequences. Parents
and friends find comfort that their loved ones died for a
purpose,not at the random behest of a troubled classmate or madman.
</P>
<P>
   However theologically comforting to some, this interpretation
ignores some of the more difficult aspects of the violence.
Although conservative Christians have been targets, others have
been targeted as well.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Columbine victims was black and apparently singled
out because of his race. One religious target was not a church,it
was a Jewish daycare center. And other hate crimes? Recall Matthew
Sheperd, the gay student in Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   There is something deeper here than, as Wingfield noted, ``a
growing climate of hostility against Christians.'' There is an evil
spirit roaming the land, a spirit of violence.
</P>
<P>
   The line, however, between good and evil is not external. It is
not a matter of picking sides in a cosmic war. Rather, a line seems
to run through all of us. We have a national short temper. Bad
driving and road rage. Greed and materialism. Child abuse and
domestic violence. Rudeness, foul language, poor manners.
</P>
<P>
   The whole of society is infected with self-centeredness and less
dramatic violence. We chooseeach time we get behind the wheel of a
carwhether we will be violent people or not.
</P>
<P>
   Columbine and Fort Worth distract us by placing blame on an
external force. They gave us scapegoats -- Hollywood, video games,
guns and rock music. But if we could look in a national mirror, we
would see our own faces contorted with anger. Human beings, all
human beings, are capable of hurting others.
</P>
<P>
   Few are innocent of this ``lesser'' violence. Most -- but
certainly not all -- of us just don't pull triggers when we are
teed off. We seethe, gossip, demean, belittle and yell. We commit
acceptable acts of violence against fellow human beings.
</P>
<P>
   In his recent book, ``Ethics for the New Millennium,'' the Dalai
Lama says violence is caused by our lack compassion, which he
describes as ``a feeling of intimacy toward all other sentient
beings, including, of course, those who would harm us.''
</P>
<P>
   Compassion is the foundation of most major world religions.
Biblical traditionsChristianity, Judaism, and Islamidentify
compassion as God's primary characteristic. God is Love and loving
others embodies the divine. Eastern religions link wisdom and
compassion to enlightenment.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its universality, compassion is perhaps the most
difficult of all virtues. Our own failures to be compassionate --
we rarely love our neighbor as ourselves -- lie at the center of
all that shames us.
</P>
<P>
   We do not love as we should. So, we imagine wars in heaven. But
the main war is insidewhen we hate the guy who cuts in the grocery
store line.
</P>
<P>
   How to stop the violence? Gun control? Metal detectors? Mass
revivals?
</P>
<P>
   White Christians have much to learn from their Jewish,
African-American and homosexual neighbors. Sometimes people hate
because they hate. It does not make much sense. There have always
been and will always be Hitlers, slavery, gay-bashingand Eric
Harrises and Larry Ashbrooks.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of indiscriminate violence, weas individuals and in
communitiesmust practice compassion through personal integrity and
acceptance of others. Ending violence starts when we commit our own
hearts to peacemaking. Honest people know this spiritual battle is
within.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass writes a religion column for the Santa
Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious studies
at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is ``Standing
Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th Century
America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
