<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1809 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-BOOK-REVIEW-MYSTERIES     09-22 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-MYSTERIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY OF THE BEST MYSTERY WRITERS ARE PUBLISHED IN THE FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBIE HESS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For fans of mysteries and thrillers, fall is a joyous season
because so many of the genre's best writers are published in
September, October and November.
</P>
<P>
   September brings Elizabeth George, Robert B. Parker, Sara
Paretsky, Stephen King and Carl Hiaasen. Sue Grafton, Anne Perry
and Dick Francis get published in October. Then November brings
Martha Grimes, Edna Buchanan and Barry Siegel.
</P>
<P>
   George's latest mystery, ``In Pursuit of the Proper Sinner''
(Bantam, $25.95, 594 pages), again features Scotland Yard Inspector
Detective Thomas Lynley and his disgraced and quick-tempered
assistant, Barbara Havers.
</P>
<P>
   As ``Pursuit'' opens, Nicola Maiden has not returned from a
hiking trip in Derbyshire in time for a date with her boyfriend,
Julian Britton. Both her father, Andy, and Britton begin to search
the moors. Another hiker discovers the body of a young man in a
circle of stones known as the Nine Sisters Hedge. The hiker alerts
the police, who find Nicola's body nearby. A former officer in the
Yard's elite undercover unit, Maiden requests that his former
colleague Lynley help in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Lynley agrees to go to Derbyshire but insists that the recently
demoted Havers stay in London and do a computer search to check out
cases Maiden handled before he retired. As usual, Havers disobeys
and follows her hunches and traces Nicola's life in London as a
young law student. She also hunts for any ties between Nicola and
the murdered man.
</P>
<P>
   I'm always amazed that the very American George writes so very
British. She is an expert at delving into relationships, and in
``Pursuit'' she continues to humanize the very aristocratic and
newly married Lynley. His anger at Havers for disobeying an order
from another superior to save a child life's dominates his handling
of the murder investigation, adding an edge to a very fine mystery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hard Time'' by Sara Paretsky (Delacorte Press, $24.95, 385
pages).
</P>
<P>
   It's been five years since the last Paretsky mystery appeared
featuring Chicago private investigator V.I. Warshawski. Thankfully,
it's been worth the wait.
</P>
<P>
   When the Chicago Herald Star is bought by multimedia giant
Global Entertainment, reporter Murray Ryerson _ Warshawski's friend
and ex-lover _ seems to be selling out by becoming host of a
television talk show. Nevertheless, Warshawski shows up at a party
to celebrate the new show. After the party, Warshawski is driving
her old pal Mary Louise Neely home when she spots a body in the
street and swerves to avoid it. When the police come, they take the
women's statements, have Warshawski do a Breathalyzer test and then
give them a ride home.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, Warshawski is awakened by a call from her
downstairs neighbor saying two cops want to talk to her about a
hit-and-run-case. Detectives Pelgrave and Lemour say that they were
told she refused to take the Breathalyzer test and that no
statement had been filed at the station. When the woman in the road
dies during surgery, Warshawski is determined to find out who she
was and what really happened to her.
</P>
<P>
   Warshawski learns the dead woman was an illegal immigrant named
Nicola Aguinaldo, who supported her two children and mother by
working as a mother's helper for the Robert Baladines in an
exclusive suburb. Aguinaldo had been accused of stealing a necklace
from the Baladines, convicted and imprisoned in an upstate women's
prison. Aguinaldo had escaped the night she died.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out Baladine owns Chicago's biggest private investigation
firm and tries to get Warshawski to work for him. When she refuses,
things start to go really bad for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hard Time'' is a fast-paced look at the world of
conglomerates, corporate greed, police corruption and life in
prison. Warshawski has a sharp tongue, as do most of the characters
she meets. I haven't liked all the books in the Warshawski series,
but I'm glad to say ``Hard Time'' is great fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Family Honor'' by Robert B. Parker (G.P. Putnam's Sons,
$22.95, 336 pages).
</P>
<P>
   After 26 crime novels featuring Boston private investigator
Spenser, Parker has created a feisty new Bean Town P.I. _ Sunny
Randle, ex-cop, divorcee and aspiring artist. She's a 5-foot-6
beauty who weighs 115 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   A wealthy couple hire Randle to find their 15-year-old daughter,
Millicent, who's been gone 10 days. After checking the hospitals
and shelters, Randle is convinced that Millicent must be working
the streets and contacts crime boss Tony Marcus to find out who
Millicent's pimp is.
</P>
<P>
   Told the teen is working for Pharoah Fox, Randle tracks down
Millicent and runs into Fox, who tries to pull a knife on her.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the advantages of being a woman in this deal is that no
one takes you seriously, so they are careless. While his hand was
still in his pocket I took my gun out. I thumbed back the hammer as
the gun came out and put the muzzle up under his nose, maybe a
half-inch from his upper lip.
</P>
<P>
   ```Tell Millicent that she should go with me.'
</P>
<P>
   ```Like hell,' Fox said. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ```I'm not a patient woman,' I said. `And I haven't shot my pimp
quota this week. Tell her. Now.'
</P>
<P>
   ```You can't just shoot me on the f...... street,' Pharoah said.
</P>
<P>
   ```I'm a small blond cutie. You're a big ugly pimp. You'll be
dead. I'll say you assaulted me. Who's going to take your side?'''
</P>
<P>
   Millicent goes with Randle, who agrees not to take her home
until she's ready. When thugs try to kill them in Randle's loft, a
simple case becomes dangerous. Randle will have to use her wits and
her ex-husband's connections to the mob to keep herself and
Millicent alive.
</P>
<P>
   Parker wrote ``Family'' for actress Helen Hunt, who'll play
Sunny Randle next year in the film adaptation, which will have a
hard time matching Parker's fast-paced action and smart-mouthed
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of Spenser will like Sunny Randle _ the two could be twins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 1537EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1814 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-WORKPLACE-SURVEILLANC     09-22 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-SURVEILLANCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPLOYER SNOOPING IS LEGAL, AND THERE'S NOT MUCH YOU CAN DO ABOUT
IT
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by SURVEILLANCE-WHO) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Big Brother is watching. And it's increasingly likely that the
Omniscient One is your boss.
</P>
<P>
   She might be recording the casual conversations between you and
a co-worker, or tracking e-mails on your company computer, or
watching the goings-on in the staff lounge.
</P>
<P>
   Sound like an invasion of your privacy? Think again. Most
employee monitoring in the workplace is perfectly legal, and it
happens more than most people realize.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of misunderstanding about it,'' says William
Hubbartt, a human resources management consultant in Illinois.
``People think, `I have my rights,' but I found out after doing my
research that, unfortunately, Mr. and Mrs. Employee, you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of U.S. businesses eavesdrop on their employees in
some fashion _ on the phone, via videotape and through e-mail and
Internet files _ according to a 1999 survey by the American
Management Association International.
</P>
<P>
   And that number continues to creep upward, for several reasons.
</P>
<P>
   First, monitoring equipment is increasingly cheaper and more
sophisticated. Employers can trace everything from deleted e-mails
and voice mails to the exact computer keys a worker strikes.
Special software can follow employees' paths across the Internet,
and high-tech employee badges even let bosses track their workers'
movement within an office building. Wireless video cameras are
small enough these days to fit in pagers.
</P>
<P>
   Second, more workers use technology that lends itself to
monitoring: e-mail, the Internet and voice mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good deal of this is done because it can be done, because
the technology allows it,'' says Eric Rolfe Greenberg, director of
management studies at the American Management Association
International. ``If, 10 years ago, a CEO had put out a dictate that
everything typed (on a typewriter) had to have a carbon and the
carbon had to be filed, it would have been unenforceable.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, it's a cinch to trace computer files and digital
recordings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employers, for the most part, unless they are voyeurs, don't
set out to spy on their employees,'' says Hubbartt, author of ``The
New Battle Over Workplace Privacy.'' Most snooping ensues, he
suggests, only after an employer gets wind of an employee
transgression.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses have lots of good reasons to monitor workers: to
deter workplace crime, to protect business secrets and to make
sure, for instance, that employees aren't calling Timbuktu on the
company dime.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses concerned about workplace violence often use video
surveillance for security purposes, and those worried about the
Internet sites that employees are surfing at work can buy software
that watches employees' screens.
</P>
<P>
   Not monitoring can sometimes cost companies a bunch. After
Chevron Corp. employees sent a sexually harassing e-mail through
the company system, Chevron was forced to pay four plaintiffs $2.2
million. Had the company been monitoring employees' e-mail, it
might have caught the problem before it went to court.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem with monitoring is, ``It can go overboard,''
says Beth Givens, director of the Privacy Rights Clearinghouse in
San Diego. ``There are virtually no laws to protect employees from
the excesses of monitoring.''
</P>
<P>
   Givens and other critics of workplace monitoring say that abuses
of power run rampant, from employers videotaping workers in
lavatories and locker rooms to businesses that hire investigators
to follow workers home.
</P>
<P>
   Only one federal law addresses workplace privacy. The Electronic
Communications Privacy Act forbids employers to eavesdrop on phone
conversations and e-mail after it becomes clear that the content is
personal, says Robert Ellis Smith, publisher of ``Privacy
Journal.'' Only one state, Michigan, prohibits secret videotaping
of employees.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 31, the California Legislature became the first in the
nation to pass a workplace monitoring bill, prohibiting employers
from secretly monitoring employee e-mail and computer records. The
measure awaits the governor's signature.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens is, technology increases and the law does not
keep up,'' says Harriette Topitzes, the chief union steward for
airline reservationists at Trans World Airlines. That group
unionized in 1992, primarily as a way to protect members against
unreasonable monitoring. Now, the company must give a telephone
reservationist five-day notice before monitoring her calls.
</P>
<P>
   Spying on employees goes back to Henry Ford at the turn of the
century. The automobile magnate employed ``a bunch of goons,'' says
Smith, who tracked the off-hours behavior of Ford's assembly-line
workers. Drunkenness and adultery were grounds for firing.
</P>
<P>
   Modern workplace privacy concerns arose with the advent of
electronic devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened in the mid- to late-'80s is that technology
became available, really to any size employer,'' says Cindia
Cameron, organizing director for 9 to 5, National Association of
Working Women. ``It crossed the line to monitoring people instead
of productivity.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's technologies allow ``near ubiquitous monitoring'' if an
employer so chooses, Givens says. But there's a downside to that.
</P>
<P>
   A 1990 University of Wisconsin study showed that monitored
workers have significantly higher rates of severe fatigue and
depression than nonmonitored workers.
</P>
<P>
   And probably a more adversarial relationship with management,
Givens says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of a better way to create low morale than a
ubiquitous monitoring situation,'' she says. ``If you're being
monitored every hour of the day, there's really not a shred of
dignity you can take from your work situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Most employers expect that workers will make the occasional
personal phone call or send a nonbusiness e-mail. But employees
ought to be fully aware of the ground rules, Hubbartt says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key for the employer is, No. 1, to have a legitimate
reason for (monitoring), and define a policy in terms of what they
intend to do,'' he says. ``Then communicate that policy to
everyone, which minimizes the privacy expectation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't expect it,'' Hubbartt adds, ``then you're not as
upset not to have it.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 1546EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1815 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-BARBECUEHEAVEN-TEX     09-22 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARBECUEHEAVEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANY WAY YOU SLICE IT, `NEW' KREUTZ IS HOG _ AND BEEF _ HEAVEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOCKHART, Texas _ The old Kreutz Market was dark and ancient. It
was a smoky shrine to Texas barbecue, and worshippers came from all
corners of the state to fill themselves with the glorious products
of its pits.
</P>
<P>
   The ``new'' Kreutz Market _ just blocks from the old _ is a
bright, shining cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   The change was due to a family scrape that has been duly
chronicled. It was a brother-sister thing, and no one can expect a
brother and sister to get along forever.
</P>
<P>
   And they didn't. Rick Schmidt, the brother, owned the business;
Nina Sells, the sister, owned the building. They split, and Schmidt
moved his business off the city square, several blocks north. It
opened this month.
</P>
<P>
   Texas barbecue lovers cringed, but Schmidt never wavered. Texas
Monthly had named Kreutz Market one of the top three barbecue
establishments in the state, and Schmidt knew he could continue
that regal position anywhere he took his pits.
</P>
<P>
   Others weren't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to search out Kreutz anymore. The old place was
just a block off the town square, but hidden inside cavernous old
buildings that looked almost deserted from the outside.
</P>
<P>
   The new place, right where U.S. 183 spills into town from
Austin, sits back on a colossal parking lot that welcomes any size
vehicle, including 18-wheelers and massive motor homes.
</P>
<P>
   The building is big and bright and rivals the Wal-Mart at the
other side of town for size.
</P>
<P>
   You can't help but wonder how the deep-smoked taste of Kreutz
barbecue could be sustained in such pristine surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   Until you open the door.
</P>
<P>
   There, just as in the old place, you are met full-face,
full-lung with heavy smoke. The courtyard just inside the
double-door entry is not air-conditioned, and the curling smoke
from all three pits freely wanders the building, pushed along by
slow ceiling fans.
</P>
<P>
   The smoke permeates your clothes, your hair, your psyche. You
are one with the barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   You can sit and eat in the courtyard, or patio _ whatever it is
called. Big, substantial tables and chairs are scattered around the
massive room.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, where the line forms in front of the butcher blocks,
workers slice away at nearly blackened shoulders of beef and rings
of shiny sausage. These are the same people who worked at the old
Kreutz, and they have developed a factory mentality.
</P>
<P>
   As the lids to the pits open and close with the help of pulleys
and chains, and the fire roars with the introduction of new air,
the workers look blankly at the customers and await the orders.
</P>
<P>
   Don't try to be clever with these people. They have sliced
barbecue in their sleep. They haven't breathed a smokeless breath
in years. They have heard every funny line concerning barbecue, and
they don't find them funny anymore.
</P>
<P>
   You buy by the pound at Kreutz. Sausage, beef, pork chops.
</P>
<P>
   Your order is handed over on a piece of reddish-brown butcher
paper, and you are offered a choice of white bread or saltine
crackers. Please don't ask for sauce or beans or potato salad. They
don't have them, and you should have known that before getting in
line.
</P>
<P>
   There is no silverware either. One plastic knife is all you get,
and no one at the market is happy about that. In the old market, a
knife was chained to the table for everyone to use, but the health
department put a stop to that.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, people were stealing the knives for souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   Just as in the old place, you can still get a few side orders _
tomatoes, avocados and quartered onions. Several drinks are
available; the most popular is Big Red. All of this is available
inside the dining room, which is air-conditioned and usually
crowded.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt said he was going to keep things the same, and he did.
</P>
<P>
   The only question becomes: Is it still as good as it used to be?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, in a word: Yes.
</P>
<P>
   In what was more a publicity stunt than a culinary necessity,
Schmidt brought a shovel load of burning coals from his old market
to start the flames at the new. It was a nice touch, but didn't
ensure that the same taste would result.
</P>
<P>
   But it did. Kreutz Market is still the king. People line up just
like always, they tear the meat with their fingers just like
always, and suits and ties sit next to bluejeans and sweaty work
shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt and his family have kept the faith, and their new
cathedral to Texas barbecue is still a blessed sanctuary of good
taste.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes on food for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Write to him at: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web Site:
www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
