<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1820 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-WORKING-SFCHRON &LR;      09-22 1673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Here's a plan for getting quick meals on the table in
a hurry. Now &AMP; Later is a recipe cooked on the weekend in batches _
enough to serve 12 _ and functions as dinner on the night it's
prepared; freeze the rest for two future meals. The 30-Minute
Recipe takes a half-hour or less of preparation and Fast and
Fresh.  THE WORKING COOK: Exotic Shrimp Vie With Mom's Noodles  
   
 By Tara Duggan  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Pork chops. Egg noodles. Weren't those things that
Mom used to make with the help of a can of cream of mushroom soup?
<TEXT>
<P>
   Well, if your mother did make them, it's probably because egg
noodles cook quickly, as do pork chops. In fact, pork chops taste
best when they're not cooked too well-done, even though many of us
have grown used to eating them somewhat dried out.
</P>
<P>
   Wide egg noodles _ that yellow pasta that you will have
absolutely no luck cooking  &LR; al dente &LR;  _ are delightful in this
week's Fast &AMP; Fresh recipe, accompanying juicy pork chops glazed in
a rich, easy-to-make pan sauce.
</P>
<P>
   As the noodles cook, you can quickly pan-fry the pork chops,
then deglaze the pan with a shot of brandy. Orange marmalade and
butter complete the sauce. The bittersweet flavors of marmalade and
brandy bring out the sweetness of the pork, while the buttered
noodles taste just like home.
</P>
<P>
   The two other recipes, on the other hand, will take you far from
childhood memories of mainstream American food. Shellfish in Spicy
Saffron Broth with Israeli Couscous is inspired by the flavors of a
Moroccan tagine, a slow-cooked stew ripe with fragrant spices. In
this 30-Minute Main Dish recipe, the shellfish and spices cook
quickly yet make a surprisingly rich broth _ perfect for the
wheaty, spongy Israeli couscous to soak up.
</P>
<P>
   The Now &AMP; Later recipe, Curried Lamb and Eggplant Stew, has many
of the same spices but carries them over to India. Coconut milk and
chutney soften the heat, and eggplant, potato and tomato give
layers of texture to the dish.
</P>
<P>
   Lamb works wonders in a stew, its heady flavor permeating the
densely fragrant sauce. However, you can easily substitute beef
stew meat, which often is paired with eggplant and potatoes in
curries.
</P>
<P>
   Both recipes are pleasantly spicy, but if you prefer more of a
kick, simply increase the cayenne to suit your taste. Another way
to intensify flavor is to use whole spices and toast them in a
heavy skillet until their fragrance is released, then grind them
fresh either in a spice grinder, or in an electric coffee grinder,
which has been used only for spices.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
SAFE PORK
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Trichinosis scares in the past have caused many people to overcook
their pork, but today the disease is extremely rare due to improved
sanitation standards. Pork dries up when overcooked, so there's a
delicate balance between safety and flavor.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid worries about trichinosis, cook the chops to a minimum
internal temperature of 137 degrees. This will result in well-done
meat. (The temperature of the chops will rise 10 to 15 degrees
while they sit.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BEGIN RECIPES &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; FAST &AMP; FRESH: dinner in about 20 minutes &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ORANGE-GLAZED PORK CHOPS WITH BUTTERED NOODLES
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces wide egg noodles
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter, in 1-tablespoon slices
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 boneless pork chops, 1-inch thick, 6 to 8 ounces each (see
note)
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons brandy (see note)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons orange marmalade
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Before beginning preparation, start a large pot of salted water
to boil.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the water boils, cook the noodles on medium-high heat
according to package directions. After draining them, stir in 2
tablespoons of the butter. Season with salt and pepper and keep
warm.
</P>
<P>
   While the noodles are cooking, season the pork chops on both
sides with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Warm a nonstick skillet (large enough to fit all 4 chops snugly)
until quite hot over medium-high heat. Melt 1 tablespoon butter in
the pan. Add the chops to the pan, and cook until browned, about 2
minutes for medium (see note) or 21/2 minutes for well-done. As
they cook, press down firmly on the chops once or twice with a
spatula for more even browning.
</P>
<P>
   Flip the chops over and cook them on the other side, about 1
minute for medium, 11/2 minutes for well-done. Transfer the chops
to a plate.
</P>
<P>
   Take the pan off the heat for a few moments to allow it to cool
slightly. Add a spoonful of brandy; if it evaporates immediately
the pan is still too hot. Return the pan to medium heat and add the
rest of the brandy. Allow the alcohol to cook off until it has
reduced halfway.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in the marmalade until it melts. The glaze should have a
tamlike consistency at this point. Stir in the remaining
tablespoon butter until melted. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Return the chops and their accumulated juices to the pan, and
cook on both sides until they are heated through and coated with
the glaze.
</P>
<P>
   Serve the chops on the noodles and drizzle with the remaining
glaze.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Notes: &LR;  Pork chops vary in size. If you purchase the smaller
center-cut chops, which are sometimes only 4 ounces each, serve 2
chops per person. If you find pork chops larger than 1-inch thick,
cooking time will be a few minutes longer.
</P>
<P>
   The bitter orange of the marmalade and the sweetness of the pork
are complemented well by brandy. Substituting Cognac is a special
treat, and even bourbon is a nice substitution _ or experiment with
other liquors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 760 calories, &LR;   &LR; 46 g protein, 79 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 25 g fat (12 g saturated), 134 mg cholesterol, 210
mg sodium, 0 &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; 30-MINUTE MAIN DISH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SHELLFISH IN SPICY SAFFRON BROTH WITH ISRAELI COUSCOUS
</P>
<P>
   This recipe also works extremely well using mussels. However,
mussels take longer to prepare than shrimp since they need to be
debearded. If you do opt for mussels, scrub off any barnacles with
a wire scrubber. Then use needle-nose pliers to pull off the fuzzy
beards attached inside the shell.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   11/2 pounds peeled and deveined medium shrimp
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   4 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 pound Israeli couscous (see note)
</P>
<P>
   Pinch saffron
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chicken broth or stock
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced cilantro (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Start bringing a large pot of salted water to a boil.
</P>
<P>
   Coat the shrimp in the coriander, cumin, cayenne pepper and
paprika; set aside to marinate at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil in a large saute pan; add the onion and saute
for a few minutes, until tender, then add the garlic and saute for
another minute.
</P>
<P>
   While the onion sautes, begin cooking the couscous in the
boiling water according to package directions, just until al dente.
Take a few tablespoons of the boiling water and add it to the
saffron in a separate container.
</P>
<P>
   Mix the shrimp into the onion mixture and cook for 2 to 3
minutes over medium-high heat, until the shrimp just turn pink. Add
the stock and saffron and quickly bring to a boil. (If using
mussels, add them now and cook them until their shells open.) Take
care not to overcook the shrimp or they will become tough.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon couscous into shallow bowls and ladle the stew over each
serving. Be sure to include plenty of the saffron broth. Garnish
with cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note: &LR;  Israeli couscous is available at upscale supermarkets.
If you can't find it, substitute with orzo pasta or instant
couscous.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 690 calories, &LR;   &LR; 49 g protein, 91 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 14 g fat (2 g saturated), 259 mg cholesterol, 271
mg sodium, 1 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; NOW &AMP; LATER: dinner this week and 2 for the freezer &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CURRIED LAMB &AMP; EGGPLANT STEW
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   31/2 to 4 pounds boneless lamb stew meat, cut into 3/4-inch
cubes
</P>
<P>
   3 onions, cut in medium dice
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground cumin seeds
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground turmeric
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cardamom
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons grated fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   6 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   2 large russet potatoes, peeled and diced + 1 large russet
potato, cut into eighths
</P>
<P>
   1 (14-ounce) can coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup tamarind chutney, or fruit chutney
</P>
<P>
   1 pound thin Japanese eggplants, trimmed, cut in half, then into
1/4-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   5 Roma tomatoes, cut in eighths
</P>
<P>
   Minced cilantro for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat a large, heavy stock pot over medium-high heat until quite
hot. Add 2 to 3 tablespoons of the oil, making sure the bottom of
the pan is completely covered in oil. When the oil is almost
smoking, add some of the lamb cubes, being careful not to crowd the
pan. Saute undisturbed for 2 minutes, then turn once and brown the
other side. Remove from the pan with a slotted spoon. Repeat with
the remaining meat. You will probably have to brown the meat in 4
batches. Add additional oil if the pan becomes dry.
</P>
<P>
   When all the lamb is cooked, add the onions, coriander, cumin,
black pepper, turmeric, cardamom and cayenne to the pan and saute
until the onions are translucent, 7 to 10 minutes. Add the garlic
and ginger and saute another 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Deglaze the pan with the broth. Return the lamb to the pot. Add
the 2 diced potatoes, the coconut milk and chutney. Bring to a
boil, reduce heat and simmer until the lamb begins to get tender,
about 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the eggplant, tomatoes and the remaining potato. Continue
cooking until the lamb is completely tender and the potato is
cooked through, about 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Garnish with cilantro and serve with basmati rice.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 570 calories, &LR;   &LR; 27 g protein, 26 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 41 g fat (21 g saturated), 99 mg cholesterol, 71 mg
sodium, 3 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
