<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1821 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-LEARN-SOUP-SFCHRON &LR;      09-22 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEARN-SOUP-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Every other week, The Chronicle features ``Learning
to Cook'' by Marion Cunningham, a cooking teacher and cookbook
author best known for her revisions of the Fannie Farmer cookbooks.
This column is intended for novices in the kitchen. &HT;     
 LEARNING TO COOK: Vegetable Soup's On In 30 Minutes or Less  By Marion Cunningham  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  Even though soup is one of the easiest dishes to
make, many beginners shy away from attempting it because of the
time involved.
<P>
   It's true that soups are traditionally long-simmered affairs,
taking much of the day to cook. However, most of that time the soup
just perks along on its own, needing only a glance and a stir now
and then to make sure all is well.
</P>
<P>
   However, there are other soups that are less intimidating for
beginners because they use commercial broth _ and that means they
take just minutes, instead of hours, to cook. And they are full of
fresh-from-the-stove flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Try today's recipe for Simple Vegetable Soup and you'll see what
I mean. It uses the best of the harvest season _ green beans,
zucchini, spinach and tomatoes, along with year-round aromatic
vegetables like onions, carrots and celery. And it can be done in
less than a half-hour.
</P>
<P>
   If you want things to move along even more quickly, buy the
prewashed spinach leaves that come in packages. Then you won't even
have stems to remove.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; SIMPLE VEGETABLE SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Make this soup the first time just as the recipe reads. Then try
using parsnips and/or turnips and/or leeks or whatever. As long as
you chop the pieces of vegetable small, the soup will still cook in
20 minutes. From ``Learning to Cook with Marion Cunningham,''
(Alfred A. Knopf, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 medium-size yellow onion
</P>
<P>
   2 carrots
</P>
<P>
   2 stalks celery
</P>
<P>
   2 medium tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 zucchini
</P>
<P>
   1 handful of green beans
</P>
<P>
   1/2 bunch spinach (about 2 cups leaves)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   8 cups chicken broth or water
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Preparing the Vegetables:  &LR; Peel and finely chop the onion. Peel
the carrots; cut off and discard 1/4 inch of the rounded stem end.
Cut the carrots in half lengthwise, then cut into slices 1/4 inch
thick.
</P>
<P>
   Cut off and discard about 1/2 inch from the root end of the
celery stalks. Cut the stalks in half lengthwise, then slice the
stalks into 1/4-inch slices.
</P>
<P>
   Core and chop the tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Cut off and discard about 1/4 inch from each end of the
zucchini, cut them in half lengthwise, and slice crosswise into
1/4-inch pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Cut off the pointy tips and ends of the green beans and cut them
crosswise into 1-inch pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Rinse the spinach. Tear off and discard the stems.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Making the Soup:  &LR; Melt the butter in a medium-sized pot over
medium heat, then add the onion, carrots and celery. Cook, stirring
often, for about 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the broth (or water) and tomatoes, and simmer for another 10
minutes. Stir in the zucchini and beans and cook for 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the spinach and cook 1 minute more.
</P>
<P>
   Season with salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 8 cups.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER CUP: &LR;   &LR; 90 calories, &LR;   &LR; 5 g protein, 10 g carbohydrate, 3 g &LR; 
 &LR; fat (2 g saturated), 9 mg cholesterol, 55 mg sodium, 2 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
