<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KITCHEN-WOLF-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 COOK'S KITCHENS: Bay Wolf Founder Aims for Heart of the Home   By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 BERKELEY, Calif. _  One restaurant kitchen is enough for Michael
Wild. So when the founder/owner of one of Oakland's oldest
destination restaurants, Bay Wolf, remodeled the kitchen of his
comfortable old house in Berkeley's Elmwood district, the last
thing he wanted was a replica of his work kitchen.
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's no wood-burning pizza oven, no acres of stainless steel
and marble, no state-of-the-art espresso maker, no super-fast
dishwasher, no spigots that swing over the stove _ none of the
bells and whistles many food professionals covet for their home
kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   What Wild wanted was a kitchen that would be the heart of the
home, a place where he could read or ruminate as well as cook, and
where family and friends could linger at a spacious table over a
cup of coffee or a glass of wine.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important, he wanted a compact, streamlined work area in
a room full of light with a view of the outdoor trees, shrubs and
flowers. That last aspect _ designing the space to incorporate a
pretty neighboring yard into the interior _ duplicates what Wild
calls, ``the Japanese idea of borrowing a garden.''
</P>
<P>
   Wild and his wife, Jill, a private-label wine seller, managed to
fulfill their wish list. With light streaming in from three sides,
their medium-sized kitchen sports a large window over the sink,
affording a charming view of the well-tended next-door garden. And
a conveniently placed door makes the rear deck seem like an
extension of the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   A commodious wooden table, built by one of Wild's adult sons
from a previous marriage, comfortably accommodates eight people _
the Wilds' favorite number for entertaining _ but most of all is
the anchor point for the family's times together.
</P>
<P>
   Michael does most of the cooking at home. Jill is no slouch in
the kitchen, but the couple never cooks together. ``I'm too
territorial in the kitchen,'' Michael says with a laugh. ``I prefer
not having anybody help me.'' When he cooks, he doesn't even like
the distraction of music. ``I get things done fast,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The European-born Wild comes by his appreciation of fine food
naturally. While some American families foster togetherness by
activities like camping or playing touch football, Wild's family
bonded at the dinner table.
</P>
<P>
   Two uncles, noted gourmets, took the young boy to restaurants in
his hometown of Paris with the aim of familiarizing him with
certain specialties.
</P>
<P>
   Wild and his parents came to the United States after World War
II and settled in Southern California. He recalls his mother
cooking extra food at dinner so her son would have a substantial
midday meal the next day while she was at work. Sandwiches, in her
opinion, were not something you ate at home.
</P>
<P>
   Wild's culinary education continued with trips to France and by
the time he was a comparative literature student at San Francisco
State, he was cooking increasingly sophisticated meals for friends.
But his love of food did not translate into a career until after a
decade teaching at SFSU when he and friend Larry Goldman opened Bay
Wolf in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by Berkeley's political Cheese Board collective, they
envisioned their venture as a cheese store/cafe collective, with
Wild behind the stove.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were naive, arrogant and stupid,'' Wild says with an
engaging grin. But where other starry-eyed and often politically
motivated new restaurateurs ran aground, Bay Wolf weathered the
choppy waters of its early years and evolved into the critically
acclaimed lunch and dinner venue it is today.
</P>
<P>
   Used to academic discipline, Wild began rigorously studying
everything related to food and wine to augment his talents.
</P>
<P>
   Another culinary trip to Southern France, partly with Berkeley
wine merchant/importer Kermit Lynch, proved ``a revelation. We went
to restaurants and markets like you go to museums and cathedrals.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as his professional vision focused, Wild knew exactly where
he was going when he began the kitchen remodel in the house he
bought in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The room originally was what he laughingly describes as ``an old
hippie kitchen, with lots of redwood and hanging things _ totally
uncleanable.'' Though not an obsessive neatnik, Wild wanted things
uncluttered and easily cleanable. He covered the floor in
Marmoleum, a modern version of linoleum that's a breeze to clean
and never discolors. The counters are topped with fossil-embedded
German stone that's equally low-maintenance. Wall paint, in a
soothing butterscotch tone with red and purple accents, was
selected to be totally washable.
</P>
<P>
   The remodeled kitchen has an adequate but not state-of-the-art
refrigerator and an efficient range _ a high-end Wolf brand, but
with a modest four burners rather than the ``behemoth ranges'' of
up to 10 burners some chefs favor. The dishwasher is a Bosch,
probably the fanciest appliance in the place, Wild says. But he
likes its efficiency and the fact that it's extremely quiet. ``I
cannot stand that awful noise some of these machines make,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Noise is also one of the reasons Wild does chores like chopping,
mixing and kneading by hand rather than machine. A Cuisinart is
stashed away in a cabinet, along with an ancient _ ``I think it's
from the '40s'' _ KitchenAid. ``My wife uses it when she bakes,''
he notes.
</P>
<P>
   That KitchenAid escaped the Wilds' scrupulous weeding-out when
they stocked their redone kitchen. ``We looked at every utensil and
gadget, and if we hadn't used it in the past year _ out!''
</P>
<P>
   There is a notable exception to Wild's disdain of newfangled
gadgetry. He loves his DeLonghi toaster oven _ ``I bought it for
$99 dollars at the old Whole Earth Access'' _ which he uses not
just for toasting or reheating but for actual cooking. Any time he
fixes dinner for four or fewer people, Wild cooks at least one dish
in the energy-efficient toaster oven.
</P>
<P>
   There is one exception to Wild's predeliction for cooking alone.
Three-year-old David Wild can cook with Dad to his heart's content.
He has his own pint-sized work station with real utensils, not
toys, scaled to his small hands. Making whipped cream for Dad's
desserts is one of his specialties.
</P>
<P>
   Does Wild the elder hope that Wild the younger will follow in
his footsteps as a chef? ``I have no idea. Incidentally, I have
never called myself a chef,'' says the man who was, in fact, the
working chef of Bay Wolf for the restaurant's first 12 years. ``I'm
just a cook.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM &QL; 
 &QL; 
A typical informal dinner at the Berkeley home of Michael and Jill
Wild might feature these dishes:
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; Starters: &LR;  Nuts, olives, goat cheese crostini, radishes
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Wine: &LR;  an Oregon Pinot Gris or a Spanish Godeval
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Entree: &LR;  Dry-cured grilled tri-tip served with an autumn
vegetable ragout
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Wine: &LR;  Scherrer Alexander Valley Zinfandel or Qupe Syrah
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Dessert: &LR;  Assorted berries and fresh figs with whipped cream
flavored with vanilla and/or rum, accompanied by almond macaroons
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHAT WORKED AND WHAT DIDN'T &QL; 
 &QL; 
Restaurateur Michael Wild is very happy with the kitchen in the
one-story old Berkeley home he shares with his wife, Jill, and
their 3-year-old son, David.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHAT THEY LIKE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _Lots of natural light comes in from windows and doors on three
sides.
</P>
<P>
   _The windows and a door opening onto a spacious deck ties
indoors and outdoors together.
</P>
<P>
   _The appliances are not oversized, but an extra sink in the
pantry and a second refrigerator in the basement help when the
couple entertains a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   _Walls, counters and floors are easy to clean, meeting the
Wilds' goal of creating a child-friendly environment.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHAT THEY MIGHT CHANGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _Adding a garbage disposal in the pantry sink.
</P>
<P>
   _Creating a bigger work space on the counter between sink and
stove. ``I like to stand in one place,'' Wild says.
</P>
<P>
   _Eventually, David will outgrow his little work table, which
will necessitate a small remodel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DRY-CURED GRILLED TRI-TIP
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   11/2 tablespoons kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh marjoram
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1/2 lemon
</P>
<P>
   1 tri-tip beef roast, 2-21/2 pounds
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the salt, pepper, thyme, marjoram, chili powder and
lemon juice in a small bowl. Rinse the meat and pat dry. Rub the
spice mixture all over the meat. Cover and refrigerate overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare a medium-hot fire or heat a gas grill to medium.
</P>
<P>
   Place the meat on the grill and cook, turning frequently, to
medium-rare, 125 degrees - 130 degrees. Remove the meat from the
grill and wrap loosely in foil. Let rest about 30 minutes before
slicing.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 210 calories, &LR;   &LR; 32 g protein, 1 g carbohydrate,
8 &LR;   &LR; g fat (3 g saturated), 92 mg cholesterol, 1,700 mg sodium, 0 &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; AUTUMN VEGETABLE RAGOUT
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce dried porcini mushrooms (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil + more if needed
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound bacon, cut into small cubes
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   6 slender Japanese eggplants, 11/2-2 pounds, cut into 1/2-inch
cubes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 bunch green onions, white and light green parts, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 pound mushrooms, sliced
</P>
<P>
   Pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons grated lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch mint, half of it chopped
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   If using porcini, soak in warm water to cover for 10 minutes.
Remove and pour the soaking liquid through a tea strainer into a
small bowl. Chop the porcini and reserve the liquid.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil in a large skillet; add the bacon and saute
until translucent. Add the garlic and saute, adding 1/2 teaspoon
salt, until fragrant, about 30 seconds. Add the eggplant cubes and
saute, stirring, until lightly browned. Add the green onions,
mushrooms and optional porcini and saute about 2 minutes, adding
olive oil if mixture sticks. Season with salt and pepper; add the
lemon zest and chopped mint.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer to a greased baking dish. Bake for 30-45 minutes, until
the vegetables are tender and the top begins to crisp. Check
halfway through baking time. If the mixture seems too dry, moisten
with 1/4 to 1/2 cup of the reserved porcini-soaking liquid or
water.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer to a warmed platter. Garnish with mint sprigs.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 175 calories, &LR;   &LR; 8 g protein, 11 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 13 g fat (4 g saturated), 14 mg cholesterol, 380 mg sodium, 5 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
