<SLUG> BC-COOKSBOOKS2-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 COOK'S BOOKS: S.F. Pros Collaborate for Junior League   By Karola Saekel 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  Remember those charming down-home recipe
collections published in the days of stay-at-home moms to raise
funds for the PTA, a church group or a hospital auxiliary?
<P>
   Well, forget those books. The San Francisco Junior League's new
cookbook, ``San Francisco Flavors,'' may technically fall into the
category we used to call _ somewhat snobbishly _ do-gooder books,
i.e., books whose proceeds serve worthy causes, but it's a far cry
from those loving-hands-at-home books of yore.
</P>
<P>
   Professionally published, illustrated with line drawings and
styled color photographs, this hard-cover volume features
professional-quality recipes that have been tested and are
presented in a consistent style and format.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Bay Area's best-known chefs consulted on the book _
Hubert Keller, Thomas Keller, Michael Mina, Reed Hearon, Gerald
Hirigoyen, Maria Helm, Darcy Tizio and Arnold Wong, plus master
baker Flo Braker.
</P>
<P>
   Their tips accompany many recipes and enliven the book. A
favorite comes from Thomas Keller: ``When I lived in Italy, a
charming Italian woman taught me to make fresh pasta dough. One of
the best tips she gave me was a test for knowing when the dough has
been kneaded enough (over-kneading causes tough pasta): When the
pasta feels like your earlobe, it's ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Wine mavens Kris Harriman, sommelier for the PlumpJack
enterprises; David Pauley of London Wine Bar; and Debbie Zachareas
of EOS contributed suggestions for wines to match dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Don't look for hoary if beloved San Francisco standbys like
oyster loaf, Green Goddess dressing or Joe's Special. This book's
recipes _ many inspired by the Bay Area's cutting-edge restaurants
_ mirror the latest food trends. Fusion dishes abound; many recipes
reflect the interest in food that packs maximum flavor without
mega-calories; and throughout there is an emphasis on fresh,
locally produced food.
</P>
<P>
   Cioppino is the only San Francisco recipe we found virtually
unchanged from classic versions. Other familiar dishes are given a
decided 1990s uptick. Pumpkin cheesecake has a gingersnap crust
updated with crystallized ginger and hazelnuts; eggs Benedict are
nestled on a pancetta waffle and garnished with fresh asparagus.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the strongest chapters deal with side dishes, many of
which can be transformed into vegetarian entrees, and brunch, which
yields fine ideas for quick dishes that would also make nice
suppers.
</P>
<P>
   The list of dishes we tried and liked _ or intend to try soon _
goes on: pancetta-wrapped scallops and papaya, strawberry soup with
balsamic vinegar, Chinatown-inspired salmon in black bean sauce,
cornmeal pancakes with chevre and red pepper sauce, rose geranium
pound cake and Meyer lemon cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Like its homey antecedents, this book has an ulterior purpose:
All money raised goes to the Junior League's community projects.
Charity should always taste so good.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``San Francisco Flavors, Favorite Recipes From the Junior &LR; 
 &LR; League of San Francisco`` (Chronicle Books; 320 pages; $27.50). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BEGIN RECIPE &QL; 
 &QL; 
CORNMEAL PANCAKES WITH CHEVRE &AMP; RED PEPPER SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Serve with a fruit compote and Blanc de Noir sparkling wine for
a sophisticated brunch.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   The Pancakes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup yellow cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   11/4 cups buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped cilantro leaves
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons canola oil
</P>
<P>
   Sauce and Garnish
</P>
<P>
   2 red bell peppers, roasted and peeled
</P>
<P>
   1 cup creme fraiche
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces fresh white goat cheese, cut into 1/2-inch rounds
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh corn kernels, cooked (about 2 ears)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 200 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Mix together the cornmeal, baking soda and salt in a large bowl.
Add the egg, buttermilk, cilantro and 1 tablespoon of the oil and
stir until just moistened. Let the batter stand for 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the remaining 2 tablespoons oil in a large skillet over
medium heat. Pour 1/8-cup portions of batter into the hot pan. Cook
for 3 minutes, or until browned on the bottom. Turn and cook on the
second side until browned, about 2 minutes. Repeat with remaining
batter. You should have 12 pancakes in all. Transfer to a low oven
to keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Sauce:  &LR; Finely chop 11/2 peppers. Cook the chopped peppers
in a small saucepan over low heat for 5 minutes, or until heated
through. Stir in the creme fraiche, salt and pepper and simmer over
low heat for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the remaining pepper half into thin slices and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange 3 pancakes in the center of each warmed plate. Overlap 2
slices of goat cheese on the pancakes. Scatter some corn and
parsley over each serving. Return to the oven and warm for 4
minutes, or until the cheese and corn are warmed through. Spoon
some red pepper sauce around the pancakes.
</P>
<P>
   Garnish each serving with some of the sliced red peppers.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 665 calories, &LR;   &LR; 20 g protein, 44 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 47 g fat (24 g saturated), 163 mg cholesterol, 976
mg sodium, 5 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
