r d BC-COOKSBOOKS-SFCHRON &LR;      09-22 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOKSBOOKS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 COOK'S BOOKS: Fringale Chef Recalls Homeland, With Love   By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Perhaps one of the least explored European regions
is the Basque area that straddles France and Spain along the Bay of
Biscay. But Gerald Hirigoyen and his wife, Cameron, have brought
the food of Gerald's homeland to America with ``The Basque Kitchen:
Tempting Food from the Pyrenees.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hirigoyen, who is also the chef-owner of Fringale and Pastis in
San Francisco, gives a loving recount of his memories of growing up
and learning about food in the region. He explains the history,
including the change of control of both the French and Spanish
sides of the area, but he concentrates primarily on the food.
</P>
<P>
   According to Hirigoyen, Basque people enjoy rustic cooking in
the best sense of the term. Food is simply prepared, allowing the
ingredients to star. His recipes use many of the same ingredients _
a variety of peppers as well as tomatoes and potatoes _ to create a
backdrop for fish or lamb.
</P>
<P>
   The food sounds appealing in its simplicity: Potato and White
Bean Soup with Olive Puree, Prawns a la Pancha, Halibut Cheeks with
Garlic and Parsley, and Lamb Stew with Mixed Nut Pesto. A few
dishes get updated with upscale additions like Garbanzo Bean Soup
with Spinach and Foie Gras and Tomato Gazpacho with Lobster.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the dishes are quite easy to prepare. The Potato and
White Bean Soup, for example, takes only a few minutes to assemble
and begin cooking. It's then finished by pureeing it to a smooth
consistency and topped by an olive puree garnish.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many chef's books, ``The Basque Kitchen'' does not
require flipping back and forth for all of the components required
to make a recipe. Frequently the longest part of the recipe is the
head note, which explains where Hirigoyen first had the dish or
where he got his inspiration to create it.
</P>
<P>
   Hirigoyen is fiercely loyal to the ingredients of the region,
sometimes to a point that makes recreating the dishes difficult.
Many of the recipes call for small amounts of  &LR; piment &LR; 
 &LR; d'esplette &LR; , a small red pepper that is dried then roasted and
ground. He grudgingly writes, ``You can substitute sweet paprika or
mild chili  &LR; (sic) &LR;  powder but neither will give the delicate
complexity of this spice.'' He does, at least, give a mail order
source for obtaining the chile powder.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the book is not geared to beginning cooks. Instructions
can be vague, like not specifying how to roll fish or chicken
around a filling, and recipes frequently lack visual clues to go
with cooking times. Near the end of the Piperade recipe, cooks are
supposed to ``stir until the eggs are set and all the ingredients
have blended.'' But the next instruction is to cook for 5 minutes
longer, with no indication as to how the final dish should look.
</P>
<P>
   But experienced cooks and those who just like to read cookbooks
will find ``The Basque Kitchen'' an interesting exploration of a
lovely region rich with culinary history.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``The Basque Kitchen: Tempting Food from the Pyrenees,'' by &LR; 
 &LR; Gerald Hirigoyen with Cameron Hirigoyen (HarperCollins; 262 &LR; 
 &LR; pages; $35). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; LAMB STEW WITH MIXED NUT PESTO
</P>
<P>
   The nut pesto whisked into the reduced cooking liquid along with
butter creates a unique and delicious sauce for this simple stew.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 pounds boneless lamb shoulder, cut into 1-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 medium leek, trimmed and cut into 1/2-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, cut into 1/2-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1 medium carrot, cut into 1/2-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   4 cups veal stock or canned low-salt chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon freshly ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 garlic cloves, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup hazelnuts
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup walnuts
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup almonds
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Warm 2 tablespoons of the olive oil in a large heavy-bottomed
saucepan over high heat. Working in two batches, add the lamb and
saute until it begins to brown, about 2 to 3 minutes. Transfer the
meat to a colander using a slotted spoon. Repeat with 2 more
tablespoons of olive oil and the remaining lamb.
</P>
<P>
   Add the leek, onion, carrot and remaining 2 tablespoons olive
oil; saute for 2 to 3 minutes. Return the meat to the pan. Add the
veal stock, salt and pepper; bring to a boil. Reduce the heat to a
simmer. Cover and cook, stirring occasionally, until the lamb is
cooked through and very tender, about 50 minutes. Occasionally skim
the top to remove any fat.
</P>
<P>
   Using a mortar and pestle, grind the garlic, hazelnuts, walnuts,
almonds and extra virgin olive oil into a chunky paste.
</P>
<P>
   Strain the cooking liquid from the lamb into a small saucepan.
Transfer the meat to a deep serving platter and cover with aluminum
foil to keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Place the cooking liquid over high heat and cook until reduced
by half, occasionally skimming the surface. Add the nut pesto and
return to a boil. Reduce the heat and simmer for 5 minutes. Swirl
in the butter. Season to taste with more salt and pepper, if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the sauce over the lamb and garnish with parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 1,172 calories, &LR;   &LR; 58 g protein, 13 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 98 g fat (40 g saturated), 234 mg cholesterol, &LR; 
 &LR; 1,206 mg sodium, 3 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
