 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: The Chronicle regularly features ``Crush '99'' by
wine writers Gerald Boyd and Janet Fletcher. This column updates
wine grape harvests throughout California until crush's end around
November.  
 CRUSH '99: Wiley Weather Stumps Grape Harvesters   By Janet Fletcher  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  For North Coast producers of sparkling wine and
Sauvignon Blanc, the annual grape crush is finally under way,
albeit fitfully. Thanks to weather that has seesawed between hot
and downright chilly, winemakers say their predictive skills are
getting a workout.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I keep thinking we're going to finish by the end of the week
and then it cools off,'' says Kristin Belair, winemaker at
Rutherford's Honig Vineyard and Winery, where the grapes have been
coming in since August 26.
</P>
<P>
   Determining whether grapes will be ripe tomorrow, next week or
two weeks from now is more difficult when the weather is variable.
For one thing, temperature extremes make it hard to do accurate
sugar sampling, one of the vineyard tests winemakers use to decide
when to pick. ``This is the second year in a row I thought my
refractometer was wrong,'' says Belair.
</P>
<P>
   At Gloria Ferrer, vineyard manager Mike Crumley says the winery
picked two days' worth of Pinot Noir for sparkling wine, then
decided to stop and wait for acid levels to drop. The
higher-than-expected acidity is due to the cool growing season, he
says. To get the acid level his winemaker wants, he'll pick the
grapes slightly riper than normal.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of CRUSH 9- () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Both Crumley and Belair agree that grape quality is high, the
upside of the long, cool summer. The rain that pelted the Bay Area
recently left their vineyards virtually untouched. But yields this
year aren't what winery owners might want.
</P>
<P>
   Crumley says Gloria Ferrer's Pinot Noir crop is normal but the
Chardonnay is short. At Honig the crop is down 30 percent overall,
says Belair, and more in some vineyards. One property that yielded
30 tons last year produced only 12 tons this year. For
price-sensitive wine drinkers, that can't be good news.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; id  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Janet Fletcher is a Chronicle staff writer.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of CRUSH 9- () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
