<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POTPOURRI-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics.  WINE POTPOURRI: The Apple of a Brandy-Lover's Eye  
   
 By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Wherever apple orchards thrive and grape vineyards
struggle, you're likely to find some production of apple brandy.
Americans have distilled an apple brandy called Applejack since
Colonial times, and apple brandy is widely made in Europe. But the
most famous of all is Calvados from Normandy, France.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although Calvados has been produced in Normandy and Brittany
since the 16th century, it is not as well known as Cognac and
Armagnac, the two premier French grape brandies. For Calvados
aficionados, the complex flavors of distilled apple juice aged in
French oak is superior to any grape brandy.
</P>
<P>
   The French appellation system designates three categories of
Calvados, with Pays d'Auge, the heart of Normandy, being the best.
Surrounding the Pays d'Auge are 10 other regions that produce apple
brandy, usually labeled simply as Calvados. Outside that region is
a more general appellation producing a product called eau-de-vie de
cidre.
</P>
<P>
   Calvados du Pays d'Auge is produced in a similar manner to
Cognac _ double distilled in pot stills, then aged in Limousin oak
barrels from three to 10 years before being blended and bottled.
Pays d'Auge Calvados is distilled in small stills and aged for
shorter periods in large oak casks.
</P>
<P>
   The Coeur de Lion estate in the Pays d'Auge dates back to the
early 17th century. Today, it's owned by Christian Drouin and is
part of an old stud farm on the road from Pont L'Ev &LR; e &LR; que to
Deauville-Trouville.
</P>
<P>
   The estate has two pot stills and a traditional Norman orchard.
To obtain juice with the correct balance of sweetness, acidity and
tannins, Coeur de Lion uses more than 20 varieties of apples, with
such exotic names as Red Duret for sweetness, Joly for bittersweet,
Moulins-a-Vent for bitter and Rambault for acid.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to appellations, Calvados is labeled according to
age. Vieux (old) is the youngest at about 3 years, followed by
V.O., at least 4 years of age. V.S.O.P. and H &LR; o &LR; rs d'Age are 5
years old or more. There are also vintage-aged Calvados, many of
which are now finished in sherry and port casks.
</P>
<P>
   I recently tasted four vintaged Calvados Pays d'Auge from Coeur
de Lion. They are not inexpensive, but they are unique.
</P>
<P>
   Among my favorites are Coeur de Lion Calvados 1977 ($75), with
the smell and taste of ripe spiced apples and a lovely sweet fruity
finish from sherry cask aging. Calvados 1973 ($75) is more complex,
with vanilla and cooked-apple accents and great length. Calvados
1968 ($125) is the most elegant, with layers of flavor and a rich
texture.
</P>
<P>
   Coeur de Lion Calvados are available in many Bay Area
restaurants and fine wine shops.
</P>
<P>
   Larger Calvados distillers include Busnel and Boulard, the
latter with Pays d'Auge Grand Solage XO and Millesime.
</P>
<P>
   For a fresh taste of Normandy at a good price, look for
Christian Drouin Pomme du Jour Cidre de Normandie for $7.99. The
delicious, slightly sweet, Red Delicious apple aromas and flavors
are lifted by a refreshing palate-cleansing spritz.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Wine Basics
</P>
<P>
   The puckering astringency you feel in your mouth when drinking
red wine is from tannin. It is sensation similar to sipping strong
black tea.
</P>
<P>
   Tannins come from grape stems, seeds and skins as well as wood
tannins from aging the wine in oak barrels. New barrels give off
harsher tannins, while aging in used barrels provides a more mellow
effect. Red wines have about five times more tannin than white
wines.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
St. Clement is Sold
</P>
<P>
   One of the most eye-pleasing sights in the Napa Valley is the
yellow 1878 Victorian-style Rosenbaum House at St. Clement
Vineyards, high above Highway 29, north of St. Helena. Founded in
1975 by San Francisco eye surgeon William Casey, St. Clement has
been owned since 1987 by the Japanese brewer Sapporo.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Beringer Wine Estates purchased the St. Clement stone
winery, the Rosenbaum House (now the winery's hospitality center)
and vineyards in Carneros for an undisclosed sum.
</P>
<P>
   St. Clement produces excellent Napa Valley Chardonnay, Cabernet
Sauvignon and Merlot.
</P>
<P>
   So That's What You Call It
</P>
<P>
   In the Fall, 1999 issue of the Ojai Vineyard winery newsletter,
owner-winemaker Adam Tolmach talks about the ``International
Style'' of winemaking, meaning ``big fruited, immediately
accessible, oaky-as-hell, larger-than-life-wines.'' He also calls
these wines ``hedonistic fruit bombs.'' I couldn't have said it
better myself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
