 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Bay Area Classics profiles food-related businesses
more than a half century old. 
 
 BAY AREA CLASSICS: Classics Draw Customers to Medlyn's   By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 DANVILLE, Calif. _  Don't even try to order a double latte at Vally
Medlyn's Coffee Shop and Soda Fountain. If that's what you want,
says owner Jeannie Pizzagoni with a neighborly smile, head a few
doors down Hartz Avenue to Starbucks.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only thing double at Vally Medlyn's are the double deckers,
sturdy club sandwiches accompanied by a salad or chips (fries, 95
cents extra). The sandwiches feature combinations such as a classic
BLT, with turkey added for good measure; turkey; roast beef;
lettuce, tomato and red onion; or grilled ham and cheese with
deviled egg and lettuce. These meal-sized sandwiches, mostly priced
at $6.45, are numbered from one to 19, though there is no 13.
``We're superstitious,'' the menu explains.
</P>
<P>
   Vally Medlyn's obviously caters to pre-Blackhawk Danville
tastes. It's easy to discern who is an old-timer and who is a
newcomer: Only the latter think the name, Vally Medlyn, is a case
of faulty spelling.
</P>
<P>
   Those familiar with the local scene know that the Vally part has
nothing to do with the San Ramon Valley, but was the nickname of
founder Valentino Medlyn, who set up shop in Oakland's Grand Lake
district in 1935. When 1950s freeway construction swept his and
many other small businesses off the Oakland map, he relocated to
Danville _ name, menu and attitude intact.
</P>
<P>
   Pizzagoni's association with the shop goes way back, too. Medlyn
hired her as a waitress when she was 17. ``He treated me like a
daughter,'' she says, even after she went on to other restaurant
work at 21 and later became a medical receptionist.
</P>
<P>
   There were several owners after Medlyn's death in the mid-'70s,
and when the shop was once again for sale nearly eight years ago,
Pizzagoni and her husband, Bob, who owns a barber shop in Walnut
Creek, decided to take the plunge. ``If I had known all the things
this (owning a restaurant) involves . . .,'' Pizzagoni says, eyes
turned skyward.
</P>
<P>
   But despite frustrations caused by calamities such as a leaking
roof and problems with the soda fountain freezer _ ``In this heat,
we sell milk shakes nonstop; how are we going to make them if we
have to run to the back for every scoop of ice cream?'' _ she loves
her work and her customers, most of whom she knows by name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meet Jan,'' she says, introducing a sprightly septuagenarian
perched on a dark green stool at the red Formica counter in front
of the soda fountain. The wall behind is decorated with a retro
zigzag-plus-palm trees design.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Neill eats lunch here daily since she retired from teaching
English and Spanish at San Ramon High. ``They tell me I was their
first customer back in '50,'' Neill laughs. ``I'm not sure that's
true, but I have certainly been coming here since the '50s.'' It's
hard to beat Medlyn's good food and reasonable prices.
</P>
<P>
   To regulars like Neill, Medlyn's is a constant in a
fast-changing community, a bastion of ``plain old American food,''
as Pizzagoni calls it _ crispy hash browns, fluffy waffles with
lots of butter and syrup, moist minced ham and scrambled eggs,
creamy milk shakes and fountain sodas, cottage cheese salad piled
high with fruit or tomato and cucumber, 10 kinds of burgers, and
house-made Texas-style chili heaped with grated cheese and onions.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the Kist-Wich, which goes all the way back to
1935 _ franks quartered lengthwise, then grilled and placed on
mayo-slathered grilled bread with mustard, relish, lettuce and
potato salad. The late Vally Medlyn had it copyrighted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
