<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.   TASTER'S CHOICE: Move Over, Rice Cakes, Here Comes Popcorn 
 &HT;       
 By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  Rice cakes have been a dieter's dream for
low-calorie snacking for years. Many who aren't weight-conscious
also use the crisp snacks as a base for toppers like peanut butter
and jelly.
<P>
   So it's no surprise that their makers started coming out with
new flavors to keep boosting sales. One of the most popular in the
genre is butter-flavored popcorn cakes made either in part or
entirely of corn in the same process as rice cakes.
</P>
<P>
   Today's panel tasted four different butter-flavored popcorn
cakes, and they overwhelmingly agreed on a favorite. The biggest
complaint about the rest of the category was the unappealing
texture, which ranged from tough to chewy.
</P>
<P>
   First place went to  &UR; Hain Organic Mini Cakes &LR;  (3.6 ounces, $1.89
at many supermarkets). Four panelists particularly liked the
noticeable popcorn flavor. Others thought the texture of this cake
was superior to the other brands. However, two panelists were put
off by the chemical taste of the butter flavor. One would buy it,
and four might buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Scores dropped significantly after first place, but next in line
was  &UR; Safeway &LR;  (5 ounces, $2.29 at Safeway). Two panelists thought
the cake had a nice crunch and was well balanced with salty and
butter flavors. But others found the texture slightly stale. One
panelist described it as quite salty, but another thought it was
too bland. Two might buy it; three would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Quaker &LR;  (4.5 ounces, $2.39 at Safeway) came in third. Three
panelists compared the texture to Styrofoam, but one thought this
brand had the best texture of all the cakes. One panelist liked the
butter flavor of this cake better than others; another described it
as bland. One might buy it; four would not.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth place went to  &UR; Orville Redenbacher's &LR;  (4.2 ounces, $1.99
at Andronico's), which scored only two points lower than Quaker.
Three panelists commented on the appearance, which they described
as looking ``extruded'' and ``extracted'' instead of like bits of
puffed popcorn. Two panelists liked the corn flavor, but two others
thought the cake lacked any perceivable popcorn flavor. Two might
buy it; three would not.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Panelists were Dan Bowe, assistant culinary director, Center for
Culinary Development; John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Roland
Passot, chef-owner of La Folie in San Francisco and Left Bank in
Larkspur and Menlo Park; Kim Severson, Chronicle staff writer; and
Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San Francisco. All products are
tasted blind. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
