<SLUG> BC-SECRET-CRISP-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim. 
 
 SECRETS OF SUCCESS: The Topping's the Thing in Apple Dessert   By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Everyone who's tried Kerry Heffernan's Apple Crisp
says it's the best they've tasted. The secret is in the topping.
There's twice as much as just about any recipe I've encountered.
And why not? Isn't that what people really love?
<TEXT>
<P>
   The topping is made with flour, oats and lots of butter, with a
judicious amount of sweet spices. The filling is plump with Granny
Smith apples, lending a firm texture and tart taste.
</P>
<P>
   After an hour of baking, the crisp emerges from the oven
browned, bubbling and absolutely delicious. Serve it warm with a
scoop of vanilla ice cream on top.
</P>
<P>
   The apple crisp is one of the most popular choices at Oakland's
Autumn Moon Cafe, owned by Heffernan and Wendy Levy. They have
created a charming space that is loosely based on a movie theme,
with classic posters and photos all around the various dining
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The food celebrates American classics like grilled skirt steak
with onion rings and matzo ball soup, but whatever you order you
have to end with the crisp.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Autumn Moon Cafe, 3909 Grand Ave. (near Sunnyslope Avenue), &LR; 
 &LR; Oakland; (510) 595-3200. Open for breakfast and lunch &LR; 
 &LR; Wednesday-Friday; brunch Saturday-Sunday; dinner nightly. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Lots of topping. &LR;  No, it's not too much. It creates a warm
crunchy foil for the gooey apples.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Grating cold butter. &LR;  Grating the chilled butter for the
topping on the large holes of a grater makes it easier to
incorporate into the flour.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; AUTUMN MOON CAFE'S APPLE CRISP
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   Crisp Topping
</P>
<P>
   13/4 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   11/4 cups oats
</P>
<P>
   21/4 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon allspice
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cold butter
</P>
<P>
   Apple Mixture
</P>
<P>
   5 Granny Smith apples, peeled, cored and sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease an 8-inch square baking pan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For the topping:  &LR; Mix together the flour, oats, sugar and
spices in a large bowl. Using the large holes of a grater, grate
the butter into the bowl. Blend until the mixture just begins to
come together, being careful not to overmix.
</P>
<P>
   Toss the apples in a large bowl with the sugar, cinnamon and
lemon juice. Spoon into the baking pan and sprinkle the topping
mixture over the fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 45 to 60 minutes, or until the apples are tender and
the topping is browned and crisp.
</P>
<P>
   Serve warm with a scoop of rich vanilla ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6 to 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 620 calories, &LR;   &LR; 5 g protein, 99 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 24 g fat (15 g saturated), 62 mg cholesterol, 196 mg sodium, 4 &LR;   &LR; g
fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
