<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV26-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY GAINS AS GORE IS TAINTED BY HIS ASSOCIATION WITH CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 26)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients) ,
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In two key states, Bill Bradley, ambling along in
his laconic, Jimmy Stewart manner, has pulled almost even in the
polls with Al Gore, who unfortunately is suffering from an acute
case of guilt by association.
</P>
<P>
   The race between the two Democrats for their party's
presidential nomination is far from over. But it has taken a turn
that few experts anticipated last summer with Bradley's gains in
public opinion surveys in New Hampshire and New York and his large
accumulation of campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   Although he is an intelligent, likable fellow who was a Rhodes
scholar and a professional basketball star before becoming a U.S.
senator from New Jersey, he was not expected to provide a strong
challenge to Gore, who has had his eye on the presidency since his
aborted quest for the nomination in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   But several things have happened to tighten the race.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bradley has sought to position himself slightly to the
left of Gore, the defining difference between the two men is not
where they stand but whom they served.
</P>
<P>
   Many voters, weary of Bill Clinton and his numerous scandals,
see the vice president in the president's image. His loyalty to
Clinton thus has become a debit rather than a credit.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the issue is clemency for Puerto Rican rebels or
America's alleged role in Russia's presumed money-laundering
machinations, Republicans attack Gore just as vehemently as they do
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   They are trying to make the electorate believe that Clinton's
vices and mistakes are Gore's.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem for the vice president is his championing of
free trade, especially the North American Free Trade Agreement
(NAFTA) among the United States, Canada and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Some blue-collar workers and labor leaders, especially those
from the industrial heartland, believe they should have protection
from foreign competition.
</P>
<P>
   They do not understand that a boost in protective tariffs by the
United States could ignite a global trade war similar to the one
set off in 1930 with passage of the Smoot-Hawley tariff act. That
measure, signed reluctantly by President Herbert Hoover, raised the
general level of duties on goods entering the country to 42
percent, the highest in American history.
</P>
<P>
   The result was that the Smoot-Hawley act exacerbated the Great
Depression. Although it was meant to protect industry and farmers,
it had exactly the opposite effect.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is: Our trading partners abroad need to be able to
sell their products in America if they are to buy American
products.
</P>
<P>
   Gore scored dramatically when, during a televised debate on the
merits of NAFTA five years ago, he presented a photograph of Sen.
Reed Smoot and Rep. Willis Hawley to Reform Party presidential
candidate Ross Perot, a vehement opponent of NAFTA.
</P>
<P>
   He explained to Perot that although Smoot and Hawley looked like
nice men, their tariff is blamed by some economists and historians
for creating or expanding the Great Depression of the 1930s. Perot
was not amused.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's stance on trade is the right one, but he may have
difficulty convincing his friends in organized labor of that fact.
And he needs the support of labor, which can provide him with
money, workers and votes.
</P>
<P>
   It is ironic that some Americans seek a return to discredited
protectionism when the free-trading United States is enjoying an
unprecedented period of prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   A third problem for Gore is the fear numerous Democrats harbor
that he cannot defeat Texas Gov. George W. Bush if Bush becomes the
GOP nominee.
</P>
<P>
   It matters not that Bradley's positions on trade and other
important issues are similar to Gore's. The perception is that
Bradley stands a better chance than Gore of winning in November
2000.
</P>
<P>
   If the public opinion polls are correct, millions of Americans
do not think of Gore as a strong leader. As often happens with vice
presidents, he is regarded as a mere shadow of the man in the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the popularity of Dwight D. Eisenhower, his vice
president, Richard Nixon, lost the 1960 presidential race to John
F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later, Nixon succeeded in his quest for the White
House. But his victory was narrow because his Democratic opponent,
Vice President Hubert Humphrey, made impressive last-minute gains
after taking a position on Vietnam that was at odds _ although not
a total break _ with the policy of his president, Lyndon Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Mondale, who served as vice president under Jimmy Carter,
carried only his home state of Minnesota and the District of
Columbia when he ran against Ronald Reagan in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   When the 1988 contest began, Reagan's vice president, George
Bush, trailed Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis by 17 percentage
points. But Bush, father of the current GOP frontrunner, was able
to defeat Dukakis by hammering at him as an ideological liberal.
Bush accused him of being soft on crime and unpatriotic for vetoing
a measure that would have required Massachusetts school teachers to
lead their students in reciting the pledge of allegiance to the
flag each morning.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been the outstanding vice president in American history
_ a true partner of the man in the White House. But if he is to win
his party's nomination and then the presidency, he is going to have
to find ways to demonstrate his own leadership qualities and his
independence from his friend Bill Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
