<HEADLINE>
FAITH CLIMBS THE CHARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VANESSA E. JONES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some people might envy James ``Woody'' Green's life as a member
of Dru Hill. After being discovered in 1995, the R&AMP;B group quickly
racked up enough sales to go platinum with hits like ``In My Bed''
and ``These Are the Times.'' They spent their lives in a blur,
hopping from New York City to Washington to Chicago performing for
fans.
</P>
<P>
   But as the years wore on, the thrill of waking up in St. Louis
and going to sleep in New Orleans disappeared for Green. In April,
the singer decided to temporarily chuck fame with Dru Hill and
return to the musical roots formed when he sang his first church
solo as a 3-year-old toddler.
</P>
<P>
   He'll record a gospel album.
</P>
<P>
   Green, 22, who was raised a Baptist, says his goal with the
record is ``to make it almost, like, cool for young people to
accept the Lord and not be ashamed to say they're Christian.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Green's decision is not unusual. After all, the
relationship between black music and religion stretches back as far
as slavery, when Africans added musical oomph to Christian songs to
create Negro spirituals.
</P>
<P>
   But until recently, the only time major R&AMP;B and hip-hop artists
alluded to their spirituality was when they thanked God for winning
a Grammy, MTV, or Billboard award. Now, musicians are increasingly
giving Him more than a cursory heads up.
</P>
<P>
   Lauryn Hill read from the Bible when accepting her recent Grammy
Award for the album ``The Miseducation of Lauryn Hill'' and credits
prayer for the eruption of creativity that spawned the record.
Artists like Puff Daddy, Faith Evans, Lil' Kim, and Mary J. Blige
openly discuss their religious beliefs in interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Missy ``Misdemeanor'' Elliott recently told a journalist she
stopped smoking marijuana because God told her to. And a month
after Green announced his gospel plans, Puff Daddy protege MA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 1600EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
