<HEADLINE>
RYDER ENTOURAGE IS DRESSED TO THE 18S 
</HEADLINE>
 FASHION-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (l and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Now that the Oscars, Grammys, and Emmys have become
televised fashion shows, it only makes sense that high-profile
sporting events would be the next target. During this week's Ryder
Cup festivities, the players' wives and girlfriends are going to be
decked out Hollywood-style in head-to-toe Badgley Mischka.,
starting Wednesday night at a Four Seasons gala ball where Celine
Dion and the Boston Pops are scheduled to perform.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods's girlfriend, Joanna Jagoda, is expected to wear a
burgundy beaded velvet bodice and printed silk skirt, while captain
Ben Crenshaw's wife, Julie, is wearing a blue-and-silver
lace-and-beaded sheath dress.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of star treatment is a first for the American team,
which normally doesn't coordinate garb for its social events, and a
real coup for a design duo identified mostly with events like the
Academy Awards. ``Most of our focus is celebrity dressing out of
Hollywood,'' said Mark Badgley, who flew into Boston Tuesday with
his partner, James Mischka, to attend a Saks Fifth Avenue fashion
show and the Ryder Cup ball and opening ceremony. ``But the whole
sports world has become so important. . . This is a great way for
us to introduce ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   European origin
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like many things in fashion, the inspiration for all this drama
began in Europe. Two years ago, during the Ryder Cup in Spain, the
wives and partners of the European team all wore Escada gowns to
the gala ball, which got the Americans thinking. When Escada
offered to provide dresses for the US entourage this time, the
women declined because they wanted to support an American design
house like New York-based Badgley Mischka, which is in partnership
with the Germany-based Escada.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thrilled,'' said Julie Crenshaw, who was responsible for
coordinating the Ryder Cup women's wardrobes (including the
partners of the 12 players, herself, the assistant captain's wife,
and the officials' wives and girlfriends _ 21 women in all). ``When
you put on their dresses, you can't help but feel glamorous and
beautiful. . . We feel like princesses, I can assure you.''
</P>
<P>
   And just like princesses, the Ryder women don't have to worry
about paying for the $3,000 to $7,000 gowns. The PGA is footing the
bill for the formal dresses and coordinating handbags, as well as
for matching Badgley Mischka dresses for the opening ceremony and
women's uniforms for the games.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tough choice
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To keep the planning simple for the gala event, Badgley and
Mischka flew their entire fall collection of about 150 dresses to
Augusta, Ga., for the Masters tournament in April. There, they
lined up the dress samples _ everything from velvets to lace to
satin to beading _ on racks in a big room and let the women go
nuts. ``It was crazy,'' recalls Crenshaw. ``It was a wonderful
scene. The girls had so much fun. It was overwhelming to have so
many beautiful choices.''
</P>
<P>
   The girlfriends and wives of the top 25 US players (the Ryder
Cup team hadn't been chosen yet) were instructed to select three
dresses they loved. Ultimately, the dress they would wear was
determined by how well their men performed on the links. ``It was
based on ranking,'' Crenshaw said. ``Fortunately, we didn't have
any duplicates.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cinderella problem
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After months of eager anticipation, the Ryder women will
actually wear their gowns for only a few hours. ``The PGA has
promised the players they'll be out by 10 p.m. They want them to
start focusing on the game,'' said Melissa Lehman, wife of Tom
Lehman of Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get all beautiful and dolled up and then get whisked away
by 10. . . At the last two (Ryder) balls, the one thing I wanted to
do was dance with my husband and there wasn't a lot of that by the
time you get done with the dinner part of it. I would rather do
away with the pomp and circumstance and just party. I'd prefer to
make it like the prom. Who wants to sit in a beautiful gown and eat
dinner? That's disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
The morning after &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, at the opening ceremonies, the Ryder women will change
from their glamorous gowns into a more subdued Badgley Mischka
outfit designed specifically for the event: taupe crepe dresses
with three-quarter-length sleeves and satin waist bands and
coordinating full-length brocade jackets. ``We sort of wanted a
Jackie O. look for Boston,'' said Crenshaw. ``They are very
elegant.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, the Ryder women will sport everything from
hunter-green suede pants with yellow argyle mock turtlenecks and
matching cardigans to gray pinstriped skirts, shorts or pants,
blue-and-white striped blouses, and navy blazers. ``It's very New
England _ conservative and traditional,'' said Crenshaw.
``Everything we've done, we tried to keep in tune with New
England.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So what does one do with a Badgley Mischka evening gown after
the ball? Lehman has very specific plans. ``I'm hoping to wear it
to a George W. Bush inauguration,'' she said. ``We're part of his
campaign (team) in Phoenix.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
