<HEADER>
A1849 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-MEXICO-UNIVERSITY-BOS     09-22 1334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-UNIVERSITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS EMPTY MEXICO'S LARGEST UNIVERSITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Most of Mexico's private universities and colleges
started classes for the fall semester nearly a month ago.
Meanwhile, the National Autonomous University feels like a ghost
town.
</P>
<P>
   The buildings are dark and quiet. The lawns where students and
professors usually gather for a quick chat are empty. The entrances
to the campus are blocked with old doors, scrap wire, and pieces of
desks that have been ripped apart. And the only flickers of life
come from the dimly lit hallways and outdoor tents that have been
set up to guard against intruders.
</P>
<P>
   For five months, the hemisphere's largest institution of higher
education, with a usual enrollment above 25,000, has been held
hostage and lifeless, a bargaining chip between a group of stubborn
students who refuse to let go of the sprawling campus and
administrators who refuse to push their way in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to stay until we believe that a university
education will remain within the reach of all of Mexico's families,
rich and poor,'' said one striker, who gave his name only as Tomas
P.
</P>
<P>
   The strike began as a protest by students against the rector
Francisco Barnes's proposal last spring to raise tuition for the
first time in 50 years, from about 2 cents a year to roughly $150.
</P>
<P>
   That issue was resolved in early June, when Barnes backed down
and said the new tuition would be voluntary. By then the students
had accumulated so much attention and momentum that rather than
turn over the facilities, they drew up a longer list of demands,
including a call for Barnes's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   The new demands call for:
</P>
<P>
   --Scrapping tuition, including the voluntary one, and most
school-related fees.
</P>
<P>
   --Guaranteed admission to the National Autonomous University for
high school graduates, an old policy that was rescinded in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   --The creation of a university congress of students.
</P>
<P>
   --The resolution of differences among professors and
administrators.
</P>
<P>
   --A complete amnesty for the striking students.
</P>
<P>
   --Nullifying credit for courses that were held off-campus during
the strike.
</P>
<P>
   As the strike has worn on, frustration over the National
Autonomous University has been felt widely. Opinion polls have
found that most people want an end to the strike and to the
almost-daily marches that further clog the capital's jammed streets
with protests both for and against the strike.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators, unable to resolve the problem, have turned to a
group of eight emeritus professors, who have drafted a proposal
that includes some, but not all, of the strikers' demands. On
Thursday, the University Council approved the plan as the platform
for a new round of negotiations that could begin this week.
</P>
<P>
   The strikers, meanwhile, once unified in their demands, have
splintered into moderate, radical or ``ultra'' factions, and have
quarreled among themselves. At one meeting in the campus's Che
Guevara auditorium, disputes over not to return to the table
deteriorated into a shoving and biting match between moderates and
radicals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're feeling the pressure of a strike which has lasted longer
than I think many of us expected,'' said Laura Jaramillo, 23, one
of the strikers, said on Friday as she sat near a makeshift bunker
in the School of Philosophy. ``But we're all committed to the same
principles.''
</P>
<P>
   The costs of the strike continue to mount. According to one
estimate published this summer, about $5 million a day is lost in
revenue and grants. Nearly 500 research projects, financed mostly
by international organizations, have been postponed or canceled.
And more than 300,000 low-income patients have not been able to
receive treatment at university medical and dental clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Those students who want to return to classes have accused
administrators and even President Ernesto Zedillo of being
negligent by not forcing the strikers out and opening up the
campus.
</P>
<P>
   The antistrike groups have even tried storming the campus in
hopes of pushing out the strikers. The most dramatic clash took
place on Aug. 23, when hundreds of demonstrators faced off on
Insurgentes Avenue, a major artery that runs outside the
university.
</P>
<P>
   Several people were injured, including journalists who were
caught in the melee, while police officers stood by and watched.
</P>
<P>
   For Zedillo and many other government officials, the strike is a
delicate political and personal issue. Many of the country's top
bureaucrats and politicans are National Autonomous University
alumni, including the president. But they all seem to fear that a
show of force against the students would create a repetition of the
1968 Tlatelolco Massacre, when scores of striking National
Autonomous University students were gunned down by police and
government troops.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo, who was part of the 1968 student movement, has vowed
that force would not be used to end the current protest, and made
only a vague allusion to the dispute in his annual State of the
Union speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Mexico today, no one is censured for what he or she says,
writes or publishes,'' Zedillo said.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``The means used by this administration to address
conflicts that have so concerned public opinion will continue to be
legality, never authoritarianism; tolerance never violent
confrontation.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the National Autonomous University's 270,000 students,
those at feeder high schools and at the university's main campus,
have lost last spring's semester because of the strike. And
officials fear that if a settlement is not negotiated soon, this
semester might also be lost.
</P>
<P>
   Since its founding 450 years ago, the National Autonomous
University has long been Mexico's premier higher learning center,
producing most of the country's doctors, lawyers, intellectuals and
engineers. It has had a unique stature in Mexican society as a
training ground for the country's elite and as a gateway to
economic opportunity for many of the country's working-class
families.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is still considered the country's most storied and
valuable university, the National Autonomous University, proudly
called UNAM, has lost much of its luster, particularly as other
private schools in Mexico and the United States have recruited top
academics and students. Many private institutions in Mexico City,
where tuition can run as high as $5,000 a year, have reported
enrolling thousands of National Autonomous University students over
the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts say the seemingly uncontrollable nature of the
strike points to the university's main administrative problem _
that it has grown too big to guarantee a high-quality curriculum
and that it should be decentralized.
</P>
<P>
   Others say the dispute more accurately mirrors the broader
themes that face Mexico, a country trying hard to modernize its
economic and political institutions without abandoning its populist
history.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the striking students have said their protests extend
beyond the university to the country's move toward a free-market
society.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to seeking a more open and affordable National
Autonomous University, the students have spoken out against recent
government plans to privatize Mexico's electric industry. Some of
them have also traveled to the southern state of Chiapas to support
the Marxist Zapatista guerrillas who have been staging their own
rebellion since January 1994.
</P>
<P>
   A Mexican historian, Enrique Krauze, called the National
Autonomous University and the Chiapas rebellions ``soft
revolutions,'' where protesters have seized a small territory from
which they conduct their antigovernment campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same thing is happening with the university strike,''
Krauze wrote for this month's issue of ``Letras Libres,'' a leading
Mexican literary magazine. ``In the name of popular education, the
strikers have kidnapped UNAM.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
