<HEADER>
A1869 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-CHIMP-KEYBOARDS-N     09-22 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CHIMP-KEYBOARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEYBOARDS FOR TOUGH CUSTOMERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ga.)  (af) 
 By LISA GUERNSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several years ago a computer programmer and electronics wizard
named Ryan Sheldon was presented with the task of developing a
keyboard for a challenging crowd. It was a group that had never
used computers, that had difficulty performing fine hand movements
and that would rather romp in the trees than learn to type.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon's mission was to design a wireless keyboard for bonobos
_ small apes that are often called, inaccurately, pygmy chimpanzees
_ so they could use it to communicate. His supervisor was Sue
Savage-Rumbaugh, a scientist who has been trying to prove that the
animals are capable of developing language.
</P>
<P>
   Before enlisting the help of Sheldon, Dr. Savage-Rumbaugh and
other researchers at Georgia State University had been
communicating with the bonobos by pointing to a board arrayed with
symbols, or lexigrams, that represented words. The researchers
would touch the lexigrams while demonstrating their meanings. Their
hope was that the bonobos would also point to the lexigrams to
communicate.
</P>
<P>
   The lexigram board was not ideal, however. Dr. Savage-Rumbaugh
wanted something that would show the apes that they could generate
their own words by touching the symbols. One intermediary answer
was a joystick that the bonobos used to point to lexigrams on a
computer screen. But it was awkward and hard to transport in the
woods outside Atlanta where much of the research is done.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon's solution is a wireless keyboard that sends radio
signals to a computer that then ``speaks'' the bonobos' words by
playing recorded voice files in English.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon completed the first keyboard a year ago. Since then,
four have been built, and a couple of electronics companies have
agreed to manufacture the parts. Sheldon, who learned to program on
his own and does not have a college degree, has since opened his
own company, National Control Devices, that will continue to
develop the devices.
</P>
<P>
   Each keyboard weighs about six pounds and consists of three
panels covered with grids of colored lexigrams. There are 384
lexigrams in all, representing words from ``a'' to ``yours.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Sheldon said, the bonobos will string the words
together to communicate larger thoughts. Such word sequences, Dr.
Savage-Rumbaugh has argued, show that the bonobos are capable of
constructing sentences. (Other scientists, notably Noam Chomsky,
dispute her research, arguing that the apes are merely being
conditioned to react to certain stimuli.)
</P>
<P>
   So far, Sheldon said, the bonobos show no signs of repetitive
stress injuries or other ailments that afflict humans who use
keyboards. But at least one ape has demonstrated a tendency to take
out his frustration on the device.
</P>
<P>
   When Kanzi, a particularly vain bonobo, discovered that he was
passed up in a recent photo shoot, he tore at the keyboard with his
teeth. ``He ripped each panel just enough to stop them from
working,'' Sheldon said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 1621EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1871 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ONLINE-JOBS-NYT &LR;      09-22 0414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-JOBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOB SITE IS TO WORK ONLINE AND OFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The (plus, plus) words should be replaced by the symbol) 
(af) 
 By LISA GUERNSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As any trend-tracking economist will tell you, most employees
don't have jobs anymore; they have careers. Few people expect to
use one set of skills for the rest of their lives. Fewer still
expect to stick with one employer.
</P>
<P>
   Online job boards are paying attention. What began as simple
databases of classified advertisements have been transformed into
online career counselors, combining equal parts practical advice
and training and dime-store psychology.
</P>
<P>
   The latest entrant in this field is Brass Ring, based in New
York. It announced Wednesday that it would offer training tools,
online and off-line career fairs, job listings, information and
hiring software for companies to use to sort and manage the resumes
that come their way.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the company stand out from other job-board sites is
its corporate pedigree. Brass Ring combines the resources of
several companies: Kaplan Educational Centers, which runs career
fairs and professional training centers; The Pavement, a Web site
that offers career information for college graduates, and Hire
Systems, a company that develops hiring-management software.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was built under the belief that the world will not work
exclusively on line or off line,'' said Jonathan Grayer, Brass
Ring's chairman and chief executive. ``People lead fluid lives''
that require a combination of person-to-person communication and
online efficiency, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Grayer envisions that once the Web site (www.brassring.com) is
complete, it will be able to assist people with all career
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a computer programmer who is considering a career
shift from C (plus, plus) programming to network administration
could go to the site to determine what skills would be required and
then take an online assessment.
</P>
<P>
   The site would provide test results, links to online training
classes, job searches and resume services. Job seekers can even
meet potential employers on line before sealing the deal at
sponsored job fairs.
</P>
<P>
   Marissa Gluck, an analyst at Jupiter Communications, said that
other sites were also trying to add training options or combine
services for employers and employees. But Brass Ring has the
benefit of a large cash infusion from its corporate investors,
which most other sites are missing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 1623EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1873 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-HIPHOP-GOD-BOS &LR;      09-22 1710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIPHOP-GOD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAITH CLIMBS THE CHARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VANESSA E. JONES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some people might envy James ``Woody'' Green's life as a member
of Dru Hill. After being discovered in 1995, the R&AMP;B group quickly
racked up enough sales to go platinum with hits like ``In My Bed''
and ``These Are the Times.'' They spent their lives in a blur,
hopping from New York City to Washington to Chicago performing for
fans.
</P>
<P>
   But as the years wore on, the thrill of waking up in St. Louis
and going to sleep in New Orleans disappeared for Green. In April,
the singer decided to temporarily chuck fame with Dru Hill and
return to the musical roots formed when he sang his first church
solo as a 3-year-old toddler.
</P>
<P>
   He'll record a gospel album.
</P>
<P>
   Green, 22, who was raised a Baptist, says his goal with the
record is ``to make it almost, like, cool for young people to
accept the Lord and not be ashamed to say they're Christian.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Green's decision is not unusual. After all, the
relationship between black music and religion stretches back as far
as slavery, when Africans added musical oomph to Christian songs to
create Negro spirituals.
</P>
<P>
   But until recently, the only time major R&AMP;B and hip-hop artists
alluded to their spirituality was when they thanked God for winning
a Grammy, MTV, or Billboard award. Now, musicians are increasingly
giving Him more than a cursory heads up.
</P>
<P>
   Lauryn Hill read from the Bible when accepting her recent Grammy
Award for the album ``The Miseducation of Lauryn Hill'' and credits
prayer for the eruption of creativity that spawned the record.
Artists like Puff Daddy, Faith Evans, Lil' Kim, and Mary J. Blige
openly discuss their religious beliefs in interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Missy ``Misdemeanor'' Elliott recently told a journalist she
stopped smoking marijuana because God told her to. And a month
after Green announced his gospel plans, Puff Daddy protege
MA(dollar)E left the music business because of his faith.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, a major artist speaking about his or her belief in
God would be considered almost corny. But a slew of factors has
recently made religion positively cool.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing the trend along was a wave of spirituality in the 1990s
that encouraged people to dabble in everything from Buddhism to
kabala. A new generation of pastors has ditched the
brimstone-and-fire talk of traditional churches to connect with
younger people. And it doesn't hurt that Kirk Franklin and Whitney
Houston powered gospel albums up the pop charts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people just need it,'' says Cheryl James, the salty
half of the female hip-hop group Salt-n-Pepa, who was a guest
vocalist on Franklin's gospel-pop hit ``Stomp.'' ``This business is
so hard, it's so convoluted, and it's so dirty sometimes. It can
leave you feeling really, really empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have no choice, almost,'' continues James, who now
worships at a nondenominational church near her Long Island home.
``It's like you would really want to shrivel up and die without
knowing that there's something more.''
</P>
<P>
   The shift toward spirituality comes as black music wallows in a
moral low. R &AMP; B songs have become so sexually explicit they'd
embarrass Marvin Gaye, and rappers vie to outdo each other with
graphic portrayals of misogyny and violence. By embracing religion,
musicians have an opportunity to do something they've often
shunned: act as role models.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the cynics out there say the talk of spirituality is about
as real as the hair Houston sports in her ``My Love is Your Love''
video.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lil' Kim says she's found the Lord, yet she's still going on
the stage with her breasts hanging out and her butt hanging out,''
says Jimmi ``Jam'' Richards, a radio personality for Chicago's No.
1 urban music station WGCI-FM. ``Walk the walk that's all I say.
Live your life that way. Don't just say it in words.''
</P>
<P>
   Music and spirituality have never been distant cousins in the
African-American community. Long before Bone Thugs-N-Harmony urged
their homies to meet them at the crossroads in their hit song,
Edwin ``Oh Happy Day'' Hawkins and the Staple Singers brought their
religious ethics to the pop charts.
</P>
<P>
   Little Richard, Al Green, and Rev. Run (of Run-DMC) are ordained
ministers. And everyone from Aretha Franklin to K-Ci and JoJo
Hailey got their start singing in choirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church is the music conservatory for blacks,'' says Vicki
Mack Lataillade, the gospel record label owner who discovered
Franklin and other chart-topping gospel groups. ``Anybody pretty
much that can sing learned how to sing in the church.''
</P>
<P>
   But musicians make their living selling a hip veneer to their
listeners. Adding religion to the mix can threaten that surface
cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hip-hop has been so much about rebelling,'' says Tracii
McGregor, executive editor of The Source magazine, which delved
into the issue of spirituality and rap in 1997, ``that to say that
you are religious and that you went to church every week, you're
almost kind of playing yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow James and Woody Green have avoided that trap. Green says
people have come up to him on the street to tell him his ability to
walk away from Dru Hill's fame inspired them to step away from
their own problems. Others have asked him about God.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I have a responsibility now as an artist,'' says
Green. ``Now I have to watch what I do because people are
looking.''
</P>
<P>
   And that gaze can be pretty harsh. Some artists keep their
spirituality under wraps so their every action won't be analyzed
and criticized by the religious mafia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people have been afraid to say anything because then
you get put under a microscope,'' says James, launching into a
litany of disapproval: `` `Oh, what are you doing at the club?'
`That dress is too tight.' `She ain't really saved.'
</P>
<P>
   ``You subject yourself to a lot of that criticism,'' James
continues, ``and that's really a hard thing to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   Lauryn Hill was on the receiving end of such criticisms earlier
this year. Her lifestyle had the readers of the Internet's
Electronic Urban Report (www.eurweb.com), a chatty compendium of
black pop-culture news, in heated debate after someone called Hill
a hypocrite for having two children out of wedlock while claiming
to be religious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a woman with plenty of money,'' says Jimmi ``Jam''
Richards, who was also one of the Electronic Urban Report readers
who wrote in about Hill. ``She can afford to get married if she
chooses to. That's just something that I don't want my daughter to
think is OK. I don't want my sons to think that's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   James, who this summer gave birth to her second child, a boy,
but remains unmarried, calls that kind of attitude ``ignorant.''
She grew up going to church, but when she got involved with Salt N'
Pepa she ``felt like I didn't need church anymore,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   James soon found success was not enough. She began reading the
Bible. Then the birth of her daughter sealed her religious fate.
</P>
<P>
   James jokes that she bounced from Pentecostal to Baptist to
nondenominational churches searching for a religious base. She
couldn't find a pastor who would support her lifestyle choices.
Instead, they wrapped her in a blanket of moral rigidity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some churches put serious guilt trips on you,'' says James.
``Tell you what you're not supposed to do. And if you're doing that
particular thing and you haven't found the strength to stop doing
it, you just walk around feeling guilty and still doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   As a younger generation of pastors takes over churches
nationwide, the tone is becoming less censorious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're seeing younger `hip-hop preachers' who will flip the
language and welcome anyone into their church,'' says McGregor.
``That's the key, the church has to change.''
</P>
<P>
   As the pastors incorporate rap culture into their ministries to
entice the young, they're also reaching out to the black music
world.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin, for instance, has acted as spiritual adviser to R &AMP; B
crooner R. Kelly. Hezekiah Walker, pastor of the Love Fellowship
Tabernacle church in Brooklyn, provides religious guidance to Puff
Daddy.
</P>
<P>
   However, the moral road can get rocky when music and
spirituality meet. Take the example of Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   A Chicago Tribune review caught him testifying about his
religious beliefs during a 1997 concert: ``I've come to find out
that whatever it is you want, it's in the Lord,'' Kelly said. ``I
used to be flying in sin. Now, I'm flying in Jesus.'' But this
year, Kelly spent his summer tour simulating sex on an onstage bed.
</P>
<P>
   Puff Daddy showcases a spiritual side on his new album
``Forever'' in a song called ``My Best Friend.'' But listeners only
get to God after vignettes where a young child curses and someone
shoots people from a Bentley.
</P>
<P>
   Richards believes the artists have decided that consumer dollars
are more important than their souls. ``You have to be realistic and
say that gospel music is just not selling the way secular music
does,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the gurgles of spirituality from major artists,
gospel music is not an easy sell to the public either. Kym
Norsworthy, senior publicist at Interscope Records, is trying to
get mainstream radio and media interested in Gospel Gangstaz, a
trio of born-again former LA gangbangers who rap about God N' the
Hood.
</P>
<P>
   Norsworthy speaks about the group with the fervor of a Baptist
preacher. But few have bitten.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first instinct is that musically and lyrically it's
probably not going to be as strong as I want my rap music to be,''
says Norsworthy. ``They can't be that good if they're talking about
church and God.''
</P>
<P>
   Woody Green is trying to circumvent that treacherous dead end
with his gospel album. The eight songs he has completed so far
touch on God's positive influence on his life. But Green won't be
the moral taskmaster telling listeners ``don't have sex'' and
``don't use drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'm the right person to give them that,'' says
Green. ``They just got finished less than a year ago seeing me on
stage humping the floor and singing about making love. I'd sound
like a fool talking about `stop having sex.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
