TEST YOUR LITERARY KNOWLEDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Featured are classic American and British authors, all of whom
flourished in the 19th century. It's multiple choice, and you pass
with seven correct answers. To earn an A, you need 10 right.
Answers are on the opposite page..MDBU/.MDNM/
</P>
<P>
   1. William Makepeace Thackeray wrote (a) ``Henry Esmond;'' (b)
``Humphrey Clinker;'' (c) ``Daniel Deronda;'' (d) all of the above;
(e) none of the above.
</P>
<P>
   2. Edgar Allan Poe wrote (a) ``The Masque of the Red Death'' (b)
``A Cask of Amontillado;'' (c) ``The Tell-Tale Heart;'' (d) all of
the above; (e) none of the above.
</P>
<P>
   3. George Eliot wrote (a) ``Diana of the Crossways;'' (b)
``North and South;'' (c) ``The History of Pendennis;'' (d) all of
the above; (e) none of the above.
</P>
<P>
   4. James Fenimore Cooper wrote (a) ``The Yemassee;'' (b)
``Wing-and-Wing;'' (c) ``Ben-Hur;'' (d) all of the above; (e) none
of the above..MDBU/.MDNM/
</P>
<P>
   5. Charles Dickens wrote (a) ``Hard Times;'' (b) ``The
Moonstone;'' (c) ``New Grub Street;'' (d) all of the above; (e)
none of the above.
</P>
<P>
   6. Nathaniel Hawthorne wrote (a) ``The Bottle Imp;'' (b) ``The
Monkey's Paw;'' (c) ``The Snow Image;'' (d) all of the above; (e)
none of the above.
</P>
<P>
   7. Alfred Tennyson wrote (a) ``Locksley Hall;'' (b) ``The
Blessed Damozel;'' (c) ``Resolution and Independence;'' (d) all of
the above; (e) none of the above.
</P>
<P>
   8. Herman Melville wrote (a) ``Bartleby the Scrivener;'' (b)
``Benito Cereno;'' (c) ``The Confidence Man;'' (d) all of the
above; (e) none of the above.
</P>
<P>
   9. Charlotte Bronte wrote (a) ``Shirley;'' (b) ``Villette;'' (c)
``Jane Eyre;'' (d) all of the above; (e) none of the above.
</P>
<P>
   10. Mark Twain wrote (a) ``The Diaries of Adam and Eve;'' (b)
``Personal Recollections of Joan of Arc;'' (c) ``Following the
Equator;'' (d) all of the above; (e) none of the above.
</P>
