<P>
   TAIWAN-SCENE (Tali, Taiwan) _ This little town in central
Taiwan, near the epicenter of Monday's enormous earthquake, seems
utterly shellshocked by the damage, which killed more than 2,000
people, injured countless others, and destroyed thousands of homes.
In towns throughout central Taiwan, rescue workers tried to save
hundreds of residents trapped in the earthquake's rubble but there
were innumerable sites and the work itself was unavoidably slow and
painstaking. By Seth Faison. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-CASTES-VOTE (Jamalpur, India) _ As hundreds of millions of
Indians stream to the polls this month for national elections, one
man's parable of village life helps explain why people like him,
from the most despised, untouchable castes, are voting in greater
proportions than ever before and redefining the very meaning of the
centuries-old caste system. The rising political clout and
independence of the lowest castes, generally referred to as
``scheduled castes'' because of their enumeration in the
constitution for special benefits, is being felt, not just in north
India, but across the country. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-ISRAEL (Sachenshausen, Germany) _ Ehud Barak, the leader
of the Jewish homeland, stood elbow to elbow on Wednesday with the
German chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder, facing down the Nazis' ovens
_ now exhibitions in a grim museum. An elderly survivor, Claude
Lanzmann, chanted the Jewish prayer of mourning, accompanied by his
grandson, a uniformed Israeli soldier, after which the Israeli and
German leaders laid wreaths and pledged to stand together against
tolerance. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-SUIT (Washington) _ Following the lead of the states,
the Justice Department filed a far-reaching civil lawsuit Wednesday
against the nation's largest tobacco companies that accuses them of
fraud and racketeering. The tobacco companies agreed to settle the
state suits by paying $206 billion, but the suit filed Wednesday
claims that the federal government is forced to pay an additional
$20 billion a year for the medical care of smokers.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-PORN (Washington) _ Show-casing its new computer crime
lab, the government announced a global fraud case involving
internet pornography. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Opening blows in the fight to
restore funding for the F-22 jet. Aides privy to closed-door
discussions preceding Wednesday night's House-Senate conference
said a compromise over the F-22 could take several forms. Some deal
must be reached before the negotiators agree on a Pentagon spending
bill for the new fiscal year, which begins on Oct. 1. By Tim
Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUM-FUNDING-GIULIANI (New York) _ A shark suspended in a tank
of formaldehyde. A bust of a man made from his own frozen blood. A
portrait of the Virgin Mary flecked with elephant dung. If the
directors of the Brooklyn Museum of Art hoped to provoke the public
with such offerings in an exhibition of cutting-edge British art
that opens next week, they may have scored a publicity coup at the
expense of the museum's budget. A catalog description of the Virgin
Mary piece so provoked Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani Wednesday that he
vowed to cut funding to the private but city-subsidized museum
until its director ``comes to his senses.'' By Carol Vogel.
</P>
