<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-QUAKE-LESSONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN QUAKE MAY BE SIMILAR TO NORTHRIDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The killer earthquake in Taiwan may have
involved a blind thrust fault, the same type of fault that
triggered the Northridge earthquake in Southern California nearly
six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   These buried faults, which cause vertical ground motion, lurk
within the crust, unseen and unpredictable. By contrast,
strike-slip faults, like the San Andreas, move horizontally and are
clearly revealed by their surface expressions, such as valleys and
long, narrow lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists in the United States hope to learn more about the
behavior of such faults by studying seismic data from Taiwan. On
that island, scientists have in recent years operated impressive
networks of quake-monitoring instruments.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan is especially quake-prone because it is where giant
geological plates collide into each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taiwan is actually a fairly seismically active area,'' said
Tom Holzer, an engineering geologist at the U.S. Geological Survey
in Menlo Park. ``They're at the boundary between two of the large
(geological) plates that are moving very fast together _ the
Philippine and Eurasian plate.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the theory of plate tectonics, Earth's crust is
fragmented into giant plates, hundreds or thousands of miles
across. Plates creep along, driven at least partly by the continual
upwelling of hot matter from the planet's interior, like the
up-and-down convection of noodles in a boiling pot of soup.
</P>
<P>
   Continents sit atop the moving plates; hence continental drift,
in which continents move hundreds or thousands of miles over
millions of years.
</P>
<P>
   Near Taiwan, plate collisions compress the crust, forcing parts
of it upward, just as one can force the center of a piece of paper
upward by compressing its two sides together. The rising crust
forms mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Because of intense crustal compression caused by plate
collisions, ``Taiwan is one of the most active mountain-building
(regions) in the world,'' said Wu-Cheng Chi, a Taiwanese graduate
student studying seismology at the University of California at
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Mountains are building so rapidly on the island that if it
continued nonstop for a million years, Taiwan would rise more than
100 miles high, Chi said. That wouldn't happen in real life, he
added, partly because while the island is rising, erosion is
steadily conveying much of its surface back into the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The epicenter of the Taiwan quake is on land, near the town of
Nantou in Ji-Ji County. Taiwanese geologists were scouting the
hillsides, looking for signs of ground ruptures caused by the
fault. But if it is a truly blind thrust fault, they won't find
any.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not heard any reports of surface rupture being
observed'' on Taiwan, said Tom Yelin, a seismologist at another
USGS office in Seattle. ``The epicenter is in a very rugged area, a
very mountainous area that doesn't have a lot of roads in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, when the Northridge quake struck in January 1994,
geologists struggled to identify any surface ruptures in the nearby
Santa Monica Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the uncertainties about Monday's earthquake, quake
experts say it has no connection with the other recent disastrous
earthquakes in Turkey and Greece.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a coincidence,'' said UC-Berkeley quake authority
Barbara Romanowicz. The only reason these quakes were noticed is
because they hit populated regions, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In a typical year, she noted, about 10 similar-sized quakes
strike around the world. Almost all go unnoticed because of where
they hit: the middle of nowhere, such as a vast jungle, an isolated
steppe or the ocean bottom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
