<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1923 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-GAME-MEGAPLEXES-A     09-22 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GAME-MEGAPLEXES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT AN ARCADE, IT'S A GAME MEGAPLEX 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By DAVID KUSHNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Richard Simon needed a splashy design around the entrance
of his new amusement center in Times Square, he chose the image of
a Wurlitzer jukebox. He hoped the classic icon would set the tone
for a cleaner, friendlier video game experience inside.
</P>
<P>
   Modeled after 1930s New York, Simon's center, Broadway City, is
a fun-house amalgamation of the city's most recognizable landmarks.
Electronic baseball games await players in a circular room designed
like Yankee Stadium. Vintage 1980s arcade-game hits like Galaga
chirp near a facade of the New York Public Library.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most parents don't want to go into a dirty old arcade,'' Simon
said. ``I want to create an inviting atmosphere for the entire
family.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not the only one. While Times Square is getting its
millennial make-over, a new generation of high-tech entertainment
centers are competing to reap the rewards. Broadway City and ESPN
Zone, which has a sports theme, joined the competition this month;
two others, XS New York and Lazer Park, have been in the area since
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't call them arcades. In an industry long associated
with violent video games and delinquent teen-agers, these hubs of
the coin-operated game business are embracing a new style to reach
a larger market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Old-style mall arcades are giving way to the megaplex gaming
complex,'' said Kevin Hayes, president of Namco, the company behind
Pac-Man and other arcade hits, adding that today's businesses try
to steer clear of the ``a'' word. ``Arcades still conjure negative
associations for many people.''
</P>
<P>
   The game industry's official term for these new establishments
is location-based entertainment. Rather than solely offering games,
like shopping mall arcades, these complexes offer a blend of games
and dining in more sophisticated environments.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Spielberg pioneered this new breed of amusement centers
with his lavish Game Works arena in Seattle in 1997. That high-tech
playpen, now one in an international chain of a dozen (though none
in New York), combines the latest state-of-the-art video and
virtual-reality simulation games in a sprawling, futuristic
setting.
</P>
<P>
   The games in these new arcades are a giant step up from
plywood-boxed console games with nicotine-stained controls and a
lock bar across the coin box. They tend to offer high-powered
simulations that, for example, let game players sit on a jet ski
while a towering screen animates their path through watery froth,
or lets them strap on snow skis to have a screen create the
illusion of flying downhill.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the creators of Mickey Mouse have got into the
game as well with their own complex, Disney Quest. Opened near the
Disney World and Epcot theme parks in Orlando, Fla., Disney Quest
has games that let visitors design and ride their own virtual
roller coasters.
</P>
<P>
   Another Disney Quest is in the works for Chicago. Club Disney, a
toddler-oriented amusement chain, is open in Southern California,
Arizona and Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Disney Regional Entertainment, the division of the Walt Disney
Co. that developed Club Disney and Disney Quest, is also behind
ESPN Zone, a 42,000-square-foot dining and game complex in Times
Square.
</P>
<P>
   In the Zone, fans can watch a flesh-and-blood sports event like
a Giants game, then try their hand at computerized auto racing,
parachuting and basketball simulators. Other Zones have opened in
Baltimore and Chicago, and new locations are being developed in
Atlanta and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come here to manipulate games with skill and
athleticism,'' said ESPN Zone's director of operations, Rob Perez.
``We're an active sports playground.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a playground with considerable rules. ESPN Zone is the most
decidedly crowd-controlled game center; children under 18 are not
admitted without adult supervision. And yes, the Zone asks for
identification. ``We're very in tune with security concerns,''
Perez said. ``We aren't a hangout.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hangout,'' especially in Times Square, precisely describes the
century-old reputation that the industry is trying to shake. A
hundred years ago, hand-cranked peep shows lured a seedy crowd with
their sometimes pornographic content.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s and '60s, pinball parlors were thought of as
hangouts for ruffians. The video game craze of the early '80s led
to sensationalized fears that teen-age mobs would roam the shopping
malls.
</P>
<P>
   It was around this time that the first family entertainment
centers aimed to blast the stigma. A franchise called Chuck E.
Cheese struck a winning formula by combining a parent-friendly
pizza parlor with a well-patrolled battery of cute video games like
Pac-Man and Donkey Kong.
</P>
<P>
   By the '90s, however, entrepreneurs in the coin-op world had a
more formidable concern than juvenile delinquents: a mature and
booming home video game business. Consoles like the Sony
Playstation and Nintendo 64 are striking gold, especially with
younger players.
</P>
<P>
   Portable hardware like the Nintendo Gameboy made game players of
adolescents and business people alike. Games like Quake and Ultima
Online, a medieval role-playing epic, popularized the world of
multiplayer games, an online form of competition that enables
players around the world to go head to head by using their
computers and modems.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the computer game and video game industry is now bigger
than the film business, accounting for more than $6 billion each
year. The arcade business, in turn, has been on the decline.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent survey by Vending Times, a trade publication, there
were approximately 1 million games in arcades during 1988, but only
590,000 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business is definitely not as strong as we'd like it to
be,'' said Robert Fay, executive director of the American Amusement
Machine Association, an Illinois-based organization that represents
120 leading arcade game manufacturers and distributors.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than trying to approximate the home video game
experience, coin-operated centers are now trying to give game
players reasons to leave their living rooms: snazzier games, tonier
surroundings and, for some, a place to socialize as well as play.
</P>
<P>
   Dave &AMP; Buster's, a Dallas-based franchise that attached a bar
and restaurant to a video game arcade, is a kind of upscale Chuck
E. Cheese for adults. Happy-hour game players can munch nachos and
shoot pool, then strap themselves into a dinosaur ride _ all under
one roof.
</P>
<P>
   XS New York, which opened with great fanfare in the heart of
Times Square two years ago, has also tried to rid itself of the
traditional arcade associations. Rick Brenner, chief executive of
XS New York, said his company had taken steps to insure a safe
environment that is free of loitering teen-agers. Bright white
lights have been placed in formerly dark corners. Loud rock and
hip-hop music has been discontinued for long periods at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want people to just hang around,'' Brenner said.
``But we don't want to be a police state, either. Still, if people
see what appear to be gangs and hooligans, then a family might not
walk in.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon enough in Times Square, there will be a lot more
competition for those family dollars. The city's 42d Street
Development Project is currently transforming one of the world's
most notoriously sleazy streets into an entertainment strip that
will include a 25-screen movie multiplex and an HMV record store.
</P>
<P>
   Simon of Broadway City said he was confident that his
establishment would fit right in with the clean, modern spirit.
``We won't overwhelm people with games,'' he said. ``We want our
warmth to shine through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
