r l BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX     09-22 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLEN DENTIST SENDS HOPE _ AND HIMSELF _ TO HONDURAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Where can I contact Dr. Tom Brian of Allen, Texas, a dentist
who coordinated relief for Honduras in the wake of Hurricane Mitch?
_ J.C., Fort Worth, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to him at 720 E. Main St., Suite A, Allen, TX 75002, or
call his office at (972) 727-5001. You can send e-mail to
atbdds\Nyahoo.com.
</P>
<P>
   Brian is the founder of Send Hope, a nonprofit group that
provides food, health care, educational supplies and other
assistance to residents of the Mosquito Coast in Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   The effort began with a visit in 1991, and Brian is returning in
October to provide free dental care and bring a 12-year-old to the
United States for orthopedic surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are continually collecting things like school supplies,
dried food, shoes, bicycles and household goods,'' said his wife,
Sharon Brian. ``Anything that is nonbreakable and nonelectric.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are there any book compilations of the comic strip ``They'll
Do It Every Time'' by Jimmy Hatlo? _ M.L., Hackensack, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   A: There are at least two out-of-print books that include
Hatlo's work on the strip: the 1943 ``They'll Do It Every Time''
and a Pocket Book paperback with the same name.
</P>
<P>
   The 1943 book reprinted 100 comic strips and was published by
David McKay Co. Barnes &AMP; Noble's out-of-print book search turned up
a copy at Second Chance Books in Monmouth, Ore. Call (503) 838-5279
for ordering information.
</P>
<P>
   Hatlo, a sports cartoonist for the ``Call-Bulletin'' in San
Francisco, created the comic strip in 1929. Al Scaduto took over
the King Features Syndicate strip when Hatlo died in 1963, and it
still appears in 100 newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Other Hatlo books found by Barnes &AMP; Noble: ``Brand New
Cartoons,'' ``New Jimmy Hatlo Book,'' ``Newest Jimmy Hatlo Cartoon
Book'' and ``Another New Jimmy Hatlo Book.'' You can search the
out-of-print database on the World Wide Web at www.bn.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I find two songs from the '60s: ``My Boomerang
Won't Come Back'' and ``Tie Me Kangaroo Down Sport?'' _ R.R., via
the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: Both songs are included on an import CD, ``Best Kids Party in
the World,'' which sells for $29.49 from the online retailer CDNow
at www.cdnow.com.
</P>
<P>
   The 43-song CD also includes ``I'm Too Sexy, Cotton Eyed Joe, I
Taut I Taw a Puddy Tat'' and ``You're a Pink Toothbrush.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Boomerang'' also is included on the 1993 K-Tel release ``Dumb
Ditties,'' which also features ``Mr. Bass Man'' and ``Li'l Red
Riding Hood.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
