<HEADER>
A1949 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-OPERA-COMPUTERS-A     09-22 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-OPERA-COMPUTERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART AND COMPUTERS MELD AT THE MET AS GEEKS NOW PERFORM WITH
TENORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By ANNE EISENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some opera houses may be using sound systems to
enhance the voices of their singers, but not the Metropolitan
Opera. There the tenors still wear velvet capes, swear vengeance
and sing their arias without any help from electronics.
</P>
<P>
   But backstage, even the Met has accepted the microchip. The
hydraulic elevators, rigging and old-fashioned electromechanical
systems in use since the Met opened its doors at Lincoln Center in
1966 are gradually being joined by their digital counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   These days, computers control the mountain that moves
majestically across the stage in ``Moses und Aron,'' trick the eye
with a battery of subtly controlled lights as the ghost of a
countess rises through the floor in ``The Queen of Spades,'' move
Puck in breathtaking arcs far above the stage in ``A Midsummer
Night's Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   They drive the Met's system of seat-back translations and ease
the complexities of putting on a fully staged opera _ never the
same one two nights in a row _ on every night but Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The changes did not come easily for the opera company, which was
far slower than many European and American houses to introduce
computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been very cautious about introducing digital
technology,'' said Joseph Volpe, the general manager. ``In Europe,
where the opera is heavily subsidized by the government, if they
are having trouble with a production as a result of technology,
they can just delay an opening or do it in concert form. That's not
acceptable here. That's why we go slow with technology. We want it
to be as foolproof as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The staff workers at the opera house who handle the new
technology have backgrounds that combine musical training with an
aptitude for the digital. Nerves of steel seem to come in handy,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm part musician and part geek,'' said Thomas H. Connell III,
the company's principal stage manager, who cues each action on
stage. Connell's art requires not only the ability to read a
musical score as fluently as most people would flip through a
magazine but also the ability to keep in communication, through a
headset, with several dozen people scattered backstage while
following a console packed with video monitors and telephones and,
of course, watching the conductor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the usual eclectic Met background,'' Connell said. ``I
sang in a choir and played the viola. But I was also a Navy pilot _
that was a lot less difficult and scary than putting on some
operas.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the musical and the technical underpinnings of Connell's
world change every night. ``There are different conductors,
different cuts, different singers,'' he explained, ``not to mention
20 to 30 pages of notes and prompt lists.''
</P>
<P>
   Computer technology helps reduce production complications by
making stage positions more predictable. ``We use automated control
for certain types of moving scenery to get repeatability and exact
positioning,'' said Dana Gracey, chief electrician at the Met.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the aerial spirit Puck in ``A Midsummer Night's
Dream,'' who used to fly across the stage in a harness and rigging,
now sails 35 feet above the stage on programmable winches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can slow him down or ramp him up and know exactly where he
is,'' Gracey said. The controls permit precise acceleration or
deceleration and can be adjusted fairly quickly during rehearsal.
``It's complicated when you are setting it up, but then it makes
life a bit easier for repeatability in a house with a constantly
changing repertory,'' Gracey said.
</P>
<P>
   Computer-driven winches control not only the airy Puck but also
the more elemental bulk of Mount Sinai, complete with a singing
Moses and a burning bush that moves serenely across the stage in
Schoenberg's ``Moses und Aron.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the mountain doesn't quite match the music,'' Connell said,
``we can always override the computer and slow down the mountain
manually.''
</P>
<P>
   Computers come into play not only to move mountains but also to
handle the seat-back translations for operas sung in their original
language, which at the Met is much more likely to be Italian,
French, German, Czech or Russian than English.
</P>
<P>
   In most opera houses that permit translations, they are
projected over the proscenium arch or to the side. ``We wanted a
system that would be more personal and that wouldn't introduce a
visual conflict with the production on the stage,'' said Joseph
Clark, technical director at the Met. ``So we waited.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Clark's direction, the opera house developed a personal
computer-driven system of titles that can be viewed on a tiny
screen attached to the seat in front of each viewer. The wording of
the translations matches the action on stage fairly closely,
enabling more operagoers to follow the plot.
</P>
<P>
   Audiences that in the past were noticeably restive in the more
expository stretches of Wagner's ``Ring'' cycle have at last
quieted down.
</P>
<P>
   The people at the helm of the translation-system technology are
the callers, who give the go-ahead before each piece of text is
released from the computer and sent to the nearly 4,000 seat backs
in the house.
</P>
<P>
   The callers make sure that each translation appears and departs
when it is supposed to _ no easy job with singers who slow down and
speed up in a dozen languages.
</P>
<P>
   Computer technology has brought another benefit to the opera
house besides the translations: increased rehearsal time on stage,
a particularly precious commodity for a fully booked repertory
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``In precomputer days, we built a mock-up of complicated scenery
and then tested it on stage to make sure it worked,'' Clark said.
``We had to use scarce time _ most on-stage time is used for
musical preparation and staging _ to make sure sight lines were
clear, for instance.''
</P>
<P>
   Now computer drafting has substantially changed the way his
department spends its time. ``We spend less of the valuable
on-stage time making sure staircases fit and more on lighting and
other nuances,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Computers are at work in the lighting room, too, which was once
full of mechanical switches and levers but is now computer
controlled. Michael Hacker, the first assistant electrician, is
responsible for many of the lighting cues entered at the computer
console in the lighting booth, which is at orchestra level.
</P>
<P>
   He is also responsible for pit lighting requirements and for the
room, one level below the stage, where the dimmers are housed.
</P>
<P>
   Hacker is comfortable with the alliance of art and technology,
so often strictly separated in the world beyond the Met. The most
difficult part of his job, he said, is the human factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The variables are the people on stage,'' he said. ``They come
in late, they don't stand in the right spot. We have to add,
override and adjust continuously. The computers are the most
reliable part.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
