<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CDROM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CDs ARE POPULAR BECAUSE THEY'RE EASY TO USE _ MOST OF THE TIME  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MICHEL MARRIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If paleoanthropologists from the distant future ever start
digging in your neighborhood, they won't require exotic dating
technology to determine what part of the 20th century they are
rooting around in.
</P>
<P>
   If the scientists discover pie-size, dusty stacks of grooved
vinyl platters, they will have stumbled on a lost record store. But
if they happen upon scads of shiny five-inch plastic disks in
houses, offices, schools, stores, cars and practically everywhere
else, they can assume that they have landed in the closing decades
of this century.
</P>
<P>
   First developed for the mass market in 1985 by Philips
Electronics and Sony Electronics, CDs have rapidly proliferated.
After a slow start, they quickly became the medium of choice for
music companies and listeners because of their large storage
capacity (easily up to 74 minutes of music on a single side), ease
of use and high-fidelity sound reproduction.
</P>
<P>
   Compact disks aren't trouble free, but more about that later.
</P>
<P>
   Modest estimates place the number of audio CD's and other types
of optical disks (including those containing software or
full-length films) in the tens of billions. More than 2 billion
audio CDs are sold each year in the United States alone.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1990s, optical disks were popular among computer
software publishers looking for better ways to store computer
programs and other data, thus creating the first CD-ROM (read-only
memory). There are now almost 240 million CD-ROM drives installed
in the world's computers, according to the Optical Storage
Technology Association, an industry group.
</P>
<P>
   In the last five years, the number of uses and types of optical
disks have exploded. There is CD-R (recordable once), CD-RW
(recordable many times), DVD and DVD-ROM (very high-capacity
CD-ROM's that are used mostly to view movies), DVD-RAM (recordable
DVD) and minidisks (three-inch recordable CD's). Applications
include Playstation game disks, photo CDs and digital business and
baseball cards.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of the optical disk is obvious, said Raymond C.
Freeman Jr., who manages the Optical Storage Technology Association
and is president of his own data storage marketing and analysis
company in Santa Barbara, Calif. ``People feel very comfortable
using them, even if the people are nontechnical,'' he said. ``You
pretty much put the disk in a drive and it works.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   While optical disks are far less vulnerable to wear and tear
than vinyl records, optical disks can become scratched and dirty
enough to malfunction. For audio CDs, that usually results in a
kind of sonic hiccup, the digital equivalent of a skip on a vinyl
record. With multimedia disks, such problems can make it impossible
to read the disk at all.
</P>
<P>
   To understand what happens when optical disks do not work, it is
helpful to know what happens when they do.
</P>
<P>
   A laser head, usually mounted on a track, moves a laser beam in
micron-tiny increments a tiny distance from the face of the disk,
which, in the case of music CDs, is spinning at a rate of 200 to
600 revolutions per minute. CD-ROM's spin much faster.
</P>
<P>
   The disk's speed is automatically adjusted to keep the reading
speed constant as the laser starts reading at the inside of the
disk and reaches the outer edges.
</P>
<P>
   What this finely focused laser beam ``sees'' on the disk is a
series of pits and flat surfaces called lands. The microscopic pits
and lands are arranged in a tightly packed spiral; for a CD at full
capacity, or 650 megabytes of data, the spiral, if unraveled, would
be a thread 200 times as thin as a human hair and more than five
miles long.
</P>
<P>
   When the laser strikes a land, the beam bounces back to its
source and is picked up by a detector. When the laser strikes a
pit, the light is diffused and returns to the detector at a
significantly decreased intensity.
</P>
<P>
   As the laser tracks, the detector reads these rapid flashes of
high- and low-intensity signals as offs and ons, or zeros and ones.
That binary data are translated by a microprocessor back into
music, text, graphics or whatever else had been encoded onto the
disk.
</P>
<P>
   Optical disks like CDs are designed to have their data
oversampled _ read many times _ to help correct for errors. But
they still skip when they are dirty or damaged.
</P>
<P>
   A skip can also be caused by a bump that knocks the laser head
off track, much as a phonograph needle skips across a record when
it is bumped. Many portable CD players are equipped with what is
called shock-resistant memory, a kind of data reservoir that stores
what the laser reads. When the laser is disrupted, the player dips
into its reserve memory so the listener never hears the break in
the data stream.
</P>
<P>
   Or, at least, most of the time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
