<HEADER>
A1963 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-MAD-NYT &LR;      09-22 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MAD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAD MAGAZINE: NEW MEDIUM, SAME SMIRK
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dignified is not a word one would usually apply to Mad magazine.
Yet Broderbund, in a rare moment of new-media restraint, has
digitized the Mad magazine archive with dignity _ nay, reverence.
</P>
<P>
   Impressively packaged in a sturdy boxed set, along with a toilet
roll of vintage cartoons, the Totally Mad archive presents half a
century of the magazine on seven CD-ROMs: the Early Years; the
Early Years, but Not the Earliest; the Latest of the Early Years;
Somewhere in the Middle Years; the Earliest of the Late Years; the
Relatively Late but Not as Late as the Latest Years; and the Latest
Years.
</P>
<P>
   The spirit of the anthology is irreverent, down to the system
requirements: ``To run this program properly you should have a
computer. Your computer should also have one of those little
slide-out `snack trays.' Take the snack out and put in one of the
small round CD-ROM things that are in this package.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many digital compendiums, Totally Mad's interface never
overshadows the content. The magazine's first 375 issues are always
front and center, displayed like crown jewels.
</P>
<P>
   The covers, in a vertical array, encapsulate the last 50 years
of pop culture as a portrait of Mad's gap-toothed mascot: Alfred E.
Neuman as Desi Arnaz, Lawrence of Arabia, Patton, Fonzie, Darth
Vader, Bruce Springsteen, Max Headroom. Posing with Superman.
Posing with Gen. Norman Schwarzkopf. Posing with the Spice Girls.
</P>
<P>
   Click on a cover, and that issue of the magazine unfolds as a
series of high-resolution photographs that can be flipped, rotated,
folded and magnified with buttons on a tool bar (at the highest
level of magnification, the pages inflate to 3 by 4 feet, in case
you want to spend a half-hour scrolling across Spy vs. Spy).
Whether anything in Mad deserves that kind of meticulous attention
is debatable, but if you're rabid, it's there.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all of the magazine's content can be searched with
the Search-O-Meter or viewed categorically with a click of the More
Garbage Like This button. There's a Back button, a Print command
and a Bookmark function that saves your favorite pages to a file _
the kind of functions one would expect to find in a Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   But the interface is smart enough not to force people into
navigating through a magazine as if it were a Web site, because Web
site navigation is generally inferior to magazine navigation. Most
online information lacks any meaningful context, and that's why
it's more frustrating to click from Web page to Web page, bailing
out of useless links, than it is to flip through the pages of a
magazine. Magazines don't make you go back to the table of contents
every time you want to read a new article.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been really easy for the designers of Totally Mad
to give the ratty old-fashioned paper magazine a whole new digital
interface, with a central menu screen and pop-up windows and lists
of links. But instead of doing something different, they did
something right. They celebrated Mad as more than an interesting
collection of images and text. They celebrated it as a magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Above and beyond its tribute to a particular comic book, Totally
Mad is a celebration of magazine publishing. It's an argument for
magazine covers and their lasting impact (try remembering the
splash screen of a Web site you saw even 15 seconds ago). And it's
a reminder that interactivity predates point-and-click.
Interactivity is a Mad Fold-In (the Totally Mad interface does
include a Fold button, by the way).
</P>
<P>
   As for user-created content, Mad magazine was doing user-created
content in 1956 with the ``Make Your Own Love Story Comic.'' On one
page were generic cartoon backgrounds, and on the next page,
captions, dialogue balloons and figures: a hunk, a blond bombshell
and emotional outbursts that made Roy Lichtenstein look like a
Hallmark copy writer (``I've been such a fool ... an utter fool! I
thought I could live without you. But I know now that I was wrong!
I know now that I need you ... desperately! You and your money!'')
</P>
<P>
   You could snip and paste, and the result was customized,
user-created content. It's a joke, of course. But for entertainment
value, it compares favorably with many user-created content sites
on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   One wonders what the Mad editorial staff could do if it was
really allowed to flex its muscles online (the potential for Ebay
parodies alone is mind-boggling). But in the meantime, we have the
first half-century of the magazine. Between the boxed set and the
toilet roll, it gets the treatment it deserves.
</P>
<P>
   Totally Mad; published by Broderbund; CD-ROM for Windows 95 and
98; $59.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
