<HEADER>
A1964 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-ARTHRITIS-OINTMENT-TE     09-22 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTHRITIS-OINTMENT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIAN OINTMENT CAUSING A BUZZ AMONG ARTHRITIS PATIENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HURST, Texas _ It looks like axle grease and smells like
molasses and curry powder mixed with motor oil.
</P>
<P>
   It's messy to use and has been nicknamed ``the goo from Down
Under'' or simply, ``the goop.''
</P>
<P>
   And it costs $98 for an 8-ounce jar.
</P>
<P>
   But Arthritis Relief Plus contains many herbal ingredients
traditionally used to relieve pain and swelling, plus some credited
with rebuilding bones and joints. They are mixed in a coconut oil
base that some arthritis sufferers say carries the herbs deep into
damaged joints.
</P>
<P>
   The Arthritis Foundation classifies the ointment as an
``unproven remedy'' and says that topical pain relievers should be
used as part of a comprehensive program, but North Texas arthritis
sufferers who have used the ointment say they have found some
relief.
</P>
<P>
   Marge Beebe, 75, of Colleyville, began arthritis treatments when
she was 28. She was given cortisone injections, wore copper
bracelets and strapped on magnets seeking pain relief. In January
1984, she had her right hip replaced with a steel ball and plastic
socket.
</P>
<P>
   She says she took anti-inflammatory drugs and painkillers until
her doctor made her stop because she was developing stomach ulcers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just putting up with it,'' she says. ``Some days were
worse than others. I had to have help stepping off or on a curb. My
son put an extra step at the back door to make it easier to get in
and out of the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked in here last January with a cane,'' she says at the
Arthritis Relief Center in Hurst, which a neighbor recommended. ``I
told my neighbor that it won't work; but you hurt so bad, you're
willing to try anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Beebe says she told her doctor in July that he would laugh when
he heard how she finally relieved the pain in her right hand and
knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I don't laugh at anything that works,' '' said
Beebe, who says her arthritis pain ended after 30 days of using
Arthritis Relief Plus _ and hasn't come back.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Allen Martin, 77, of Hurst, who had his left knee
replaced and was considering a knee replacement on the right side
when his wife, Billie, dragged him over to the Arthritis Relief
Center in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Surgery relieved pain in the left leg, but it is still a little
stiff, despite six weeks of physical therapy. For a month after the
surgery, her husband declared it ``the biggest mistake of his
life,'' Billie Martin says.
</P>
<P>
   He tried Arthritis Relief Plus, but after three or four weeks he
declared it ``a good idea that's just not working.''
</P>
<P>
   Billie Martin persevered, rubbing in the cream all around his
knee and lightly wrapping it with an elastic bandage each night.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the 30th day, he said, `I hate to say this, but the pain's
gone. My leg's not hurting anymore,' '' Billie Martin says. Allen
Martin is back at work doing carpentry repairs and maintenance
around the town houses where they live.
</P>
<P>
   Arthritis Relief Plus was developed in Australia 20 years ago to
help rehabilitate injured race horses and dogs. It was reformulated
several years ago in a less grainy ointment for humans, says Marta
Matthews, an Australian native who introduced the alternative pain
relief cream in this country about 18 months ago when she opened
the Arthritis Relief Center in Hurst.
</P>
<P>
   She sells primarily over the Internet and on the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   The herbal ointment is rubbed in at night and the affected joint
is wrapped lightly to keep the ointment from rubbing off and making
a mess. As with other topical pain relievers for arthritis, it
usually takes two to four weeks to begin working.
</P>
<P>
   To what do the ointment's advocates attribute its success?
</P>
<P>
   First, it contains capsaicin, a substance found in hot peppers,
which relieves pain by interfering with pain signals to the brain.
</P>
<P>
   It also contains English oak, an astringent shown to reduce
swelling; turmeric, an astringent with anti-inflammatory and
antibiotic properties, traditionally used on sprains and bruises;
winter cherry to relieve joint and nerve pain; fenugreek to soothe
inflamed tissue; Norwegian kelp for mineral deficiencies; Solomon's
seal (''knit-bone'') to help heal bones and bruising; and menthol.
</P>
<P>
   With no known side effects, the treatment is a welcome
alternative therapy for some. A recent research review published in
the New England Journal of Medicine found that traditional
nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs administered to treat
arthritis _ including aspirin, ibuprofen and naproxen sodium _ can
cause gastrointestinal ulcers.
</P>
<P>
   The risk is low, but because huge numbers of people take these
pain relievers, especially arthritis sufferers who take high doses
for long periods, toxicity from the drugs ranks as the
15th-most-common cause of death in the United States, says a report
in the September-October issue of Fitness Matters, the journal of
the American Council on Exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arthritis is not terminal, it's just debilitating,'' Matthews
says. ``What gets you in the end are the side effects to the drugs.
This has no side effects and doesn't interfere with any other drugs
you may be taking. If your knee hurts, you put it on your knee. If
your hand hurts, put it on your hand. There's no need for it to go
through your whole system.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information, check the center's Web site at
www.arrp.com. or call (888) 876-8223.
</P>
<P>
   To contact the Arthritis Foundation's North Texas chapter, call
(800) 442-6653.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
