<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1968 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-N     09-22 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER COLUMN: STATE OF THE ART 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By PETER H. LEWIS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   This has been a big month for mice. First, a biologist at
Princeton disclosed that he had genetically engineered a smarter
mouse with improved learning, memory and intelligence skills, and
now the technologists in Microsoft's hardware division have
digitally engineered a new batch of smarter, more talented computer
mice.
</P>
<P>
   After remaining fundamentally unchanged for a long time _
millions of years, in the case of biological mice, and more than
three decades for computer mice _ we are now at the dawn of a new
era of super mice.
</P>
<P>
   The new Microsoft Intellimouse Explorer is, quite simply, the
cat's meow. The five-button Explorer mouse has a voluptuous silver
body with a glowing red tail light and a translucent red underbelly
that lights up a room at night. And this is no blind mouse: It uses
optical sensors to find its way around with greater precision than
any conventional mechanical mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Although it will not be formally released until Oct. 1, the new
mouse is starting to show up in some stores at a price just a
whisker under $75. The Explorer is just one of several new mice
being introduced by Microsoft, including a more modest optical
mouse for $55 and a new cordless mouse for $45 that is buried
somewhere under the clutter on my desk.
</P>
<P>
   I admit that $75 is a lot to pay for a mouse, especially when a
new PC system can be had for less than $500 and when serviceable
replacement mice are widely sold for less than $10. But like the
brainy rodents in the laboratories at Princeton, the Intellimouse
Explorer is no ordinary mouse.
</P>
<P>
   An ordinary mouse typically has a rubber ball embedded in its
belly. As the ball rolls over a surface, little mechanical rollers
measure the speed and direction of the mouse and adjust the
on-screen cursor accordingly. Computer mice have worked this way
since Douglas Englebart cobbled the first mouse out of wood and
wheels in the mid-1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The Explorer has no mechanical or moving parts. Instead, a small
digital camera about the size of a pinhead snaps a picture of the
underlying surface 1,500 times a second. The images are analyzed by
a super-fast chip called a digital signal processor, which compares
each new picture with the previous one and detects patterns of
movement. It measures the changes and calculates the new mouse
position with exquisite precision. Microsoft calls this optical
technology Intellieye, which proves how dangerous it can be to let
engineers name the baby.
</P>
<P>
   The result is more accurate cursor movements on the computer
screen. Granted, the typical mechanical mouse is hardly inaccurate,
and a casual mouse-pusher is not going to notice a life-changing
difference. But engineers, graphic artists and others who measure
precision by the pixel will love it.
</P>
<P>
   Another result is better mouse hygiene. Because the Explorer
mouse has no rubber ball constantly sweeping across a mousepad
gathering crumbs and fuzz, it does not accumulate the kind of
belly-button lint that causes mechanical mice to skip, get stuck or
lose their bearings. Some people enjoy tweezering the lint out of
mouse bellies. Getting this optical mouse will make it easier to
avoid them.
</P>
<P>
   Still another virtue of the new mouse is its versatility. Unlike
Macintosh mice, which use a single mouse button, or standard PC
mice, which employ two buttons, left and right, the Explorer mouse
has five buttons, including a scrolling wheel.
</P>
<P>
   The scrolling wheel has evolved in response to the World Wide
Web. Web pages rarely fit in one screen so the user usually has to
mouse over to a scroll bar and click up or down. This is not
exactly Sisyphean as hardships go, but it does become tiresome
after a few zillion pages.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, PC mice have added Web wheels between their left and
right ears. Rolling the wheel with a finger has the same effect as
clicking and dragging on a vertical scroll bar. Roll forward, and
the page scrolls up; roll backward, the page scrolls down. The
wheel also functions as a click button.
</P>
<P>
   The Explorer mouse has a wheel, but it also adds a fourth and a
fifth mouse button on its left side. The buttons are factory-set as
Forward and Back, as in, go to the next Web page, go back to the
previous Web page. As more software applications adopt a
browserlike command structure, that is a time-saver.
</P>
<P>
   Any of the five buttons can be easily customized, to Cut and
Paste, for example, instead of Forward and Back. Or Maximize and
Minimize, or Select All and Copy, or even Switch Weapons and Blast
the Aliens.
</P>
<P>
   Many people are not aware of how much silliness is programmed
into their mouse software, and the Intellisense software that comes
with the Intellimice is amusing as well as functional. Using the
mouse controls in the Windows Control Panel, for example, one can
replace the boring arrow pointer and hourglass waiting symbol with
a tap-dancer in top hat and tails and a martini with an olive. Or
one can dump the arrow in favor of an ear of corn or a snake or (my
favorite) a mouse. You can also replace the hourglass with a block
of Swiss cheese that is slowly nibbled away.
</P>
<P>
   As fond as I am of this clever, stylish new mouse, it has some
potential drawbacks. First, it threatens to make mousepads
obsolete. My beloved Grateful Dead mousepads are an integral part
of my pigpen office decor, and the Explorer mouse makes them
superfluous.
</P>
<P>
   On the positive side, the new mouse works just as well on a
Grateful Dead T-shirt (even one being worn by someone else, which
can be fun) as it does on a desktop. It navigates on trouser legs,
magazines or bare skin _ on nearly any surface with the major
exception of glass. Glass confuses the mouse's video eyeball, so
glass-top desks are out.
</P>
<P>
   The new mouse is hard cheese for lefties. The Intellimouse
Explorer is designed for right-handers only, and Microsoft says it
has no plans to create a version for southpaws.
</P>
<P>
   But there is some consolation in that the same optical
technology is being incorporated into the less flashy but equally
precise and ambidextrous Intellimouse that costs $55. The all-white
Intellimouse with Intellieye lacks the swooping curves, silver
skin, glowing tail light and fourth and fifth buttons of the
Explorer, but it does have the optical precision and a glowing red
belly button.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft initially designed the new optical mice for Windows
computers, but the Universal Serial Bus, or USB, versions can
easily replace the nasty little puck pointer that Apple ships with
its Macintosh and iMac computers, and the silver Explorer mouse
even color-coordinates beautifully with the new graphite G4 desktop
Macs.
</P>
<P>
   That joyous news is tempered somewhat by the need for Mac users
to download 1.6 megabytes worth of beta software drivers from
Microsoft to get the Explorer mouse to run properly. Final code is
scheduled to be available on Oct. 1. (Windows users must have
Windows 98 Second Edition.)
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Microsoft is also introducing a traditional mouse with
its tail cut off. This cordless radio mouse is intended for people
who prize neatness, the sort who probably got a flat-screen monitor
just to accentuate how much uncluttered desk space they have and
who probably bundle all the computer cables together with
color-coded plastic ties and hide them behind a fern. In short, the
kind of people who get pleasure from cleaning the lint off mouse
balls.
</P>
<P>
   The radio mouse comes with a receiver about the size of a pack
of cigarettes, which attaches to the computer. The mouse then
communicates with the receiver at distances up to about 5 feet and
works about as well as a mouse with a cord.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
