<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1974 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-GOETHE-GARDEN-HOUSE-2     09-22 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOETHE-GARDEN-HOUSE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASK NOT WHICH HOUSE IS REAL, BUT WHETHER REALITY IS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JAN OTAKAR FISCHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEIMAR, Germany _ Postcards of this city's most famous building
look different this year. The little pale-blue cottage is still
depicted in its verdant setting in Ilm Park, but an identical twin
structure is featured in some images. A provocative bit of text
appears, too: ``Echt?'' (``Real?'')
</P>
<P>
   The building is Goethe's Garden House, a national shrine. Weimar
has been enjoying a year as the European Union's ``cultural
capital,'' a designation prompted by Goethe's 250th birthday, in
August. Rather than simply polish up the city's many landmarks, the
organizers challenged their visitors with an experimental conjuring
trick. They built an exact copy of the Garden House 100 yards from
the original.
</P>
<P>
   The project was the brainchild of Lorenz Engell, the dean of
media studies at Bauhaus University here and a man eager to provoke
essential questions about authenticity. The intricacies of
determining what is ``real'' have particular relevance in this
postwar landscape, where great tracts of the national heritage were
destroyed and have had to be rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   Engell persuaded the organizers that a second Garden House would
be a valuable challenge to the cult of the original. The resulting
architectural pas de deux has forced everyone _ Weimar residents,
tourists and intellectuals alike _ to ponder modernist issues of
reproduction and originality. Some have been bruised.
</P>
<P>
   Goethe was a man of tremendous energy, curiosity and engagement,
not only the spur of German humanism, creator of the epic drama
``Faust'' and unsurpassed poet of his age, but also government
minister, botanist, geologist, painter, designer and philosopher.
Almost from the moment he arrived in Weimar in 1776 until his death
in 1832, his favorite place was his modest house by a bend in the
Ilm River, a short stroll from the center of what was then a
tranquil provincial capital with 5,000 inhabitants. For Germans,
the Garden House represents the blossoming and pure spirit of
German classicism, its simplicity and intimacy accessible even to
those who have never heard of ``Egmont.''
</P>
<P>
   The writer was 26 and already famous when he was summoned to the
court of Grand Duke Carl August, who immediately raised him to a
peerage, made him a minister and bought him a temporary house to
live in, at a cost of 600 taler (about $1,000 now). The house dated
back at least to the end of the 16th century, when it served as a
wine shed.
</P>
<P>
   Goethe engaged 26 workers for the renovation, including the
Duke's own cabinetmaker, J.M. Mieding. The paved rooms of the
ground floor included a foyer, a kitchen, a dining room and
servants' quarters, while the upper floor became Goethe's private
realm _ a tiny suite of library, writing room, parlor and bedroom.
Goethe was most interested in the garden, a labor of love that
engaged him until the end of his life. What was a tangle of weeds
and brush became a charming network of terraces, pebbled pathways,
lanes of vegetables and flower beds rife with hollyhocks, violets
and roses.
</P>
<P>
   Many years later, Goethe moved into a sprawling mustard-colored
mansion with its own garden on the Frauenplan. But he kept his
Garden House. There, embedded in nature, he heard the muse most
clearly, and he arranged his writing room just so, to hear her
call. Improbably perched high on a suede saddle chair of his own
design, his feet dangling and his back to a conical sheet metal
stove, he wrote many of his finest works, including ``Wilhelm
Meister's Apprenticeship,'' ``Iphigenia in Tauris'' and ``Torquato
Tasso.''
</P>
<P>
   In the garden he pondered whether there might have been a primal
plant from which all others evolved. In the dining room he talked
theater with Schiller and philosophy with Herder. In the parlor he
received his friend the Grand Duke and discussed the advent of
Napoleon, and in the bedroom he found unexpected passion with
Christiane Vulpius, a young woman with whom he lived for 18 years
before they were married.
</P>
<P>
   Weimar's cultural events are not all devoted to the writer, of
course; the highs and lows of the 20th century are also being
deeply scrutinized. But Goethe's second Garden House may be the
most quietly subversive provocation of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Volker Laier, its planner and construction manager, reproduced
everything, including the patina and traces of use, ``from the
threshold to the roof ridge,'' he said recently. The second house
has the same pale-blue plastered walls, narrow shuttered windows
and weathered gray shingles. The beige sandstone paving of the
foyer and dining room looks scuffed and pitted. On the threshold of
Goethe's dining room, the doors have scratched minute concentric
circles into the stone during centuries of pivoting. The same
circles are under the impostor's hinges.
</P>
<P>
   Laier explained that the second Garden House was designed in 73
prefabricated sections. ``You can take it on tour,'' he said. ``It
all fits into containers.'' The precision is uncanny. The wooden
staircase and the wide floorboards look raw and rounded, as if
pounded by the boots of four generations. The plain interior is
replicated down to Goethe's rostrum writing table, smoothed by a
waxy polish that might have come from the poet's own sweaty palms.
The wear and tear of 200 years is, impossibly, everywhere evident:
200-year-old grime was simulated in nooks and crannies with green
umber pigment and linseed oil.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most hurried tourist will notice the only two major
differences: the second Garden House has no guards and no garden.
Everything can be touched. You can sit on Goethe's copy saddle and
see if you are inspired. But nature is harder to reproduce. Wooden
gates, pebble mosaics and benches are here, but none of the
glorious flora that give the house its name.
</P>
<P>
   Laier now believes that ``the copy has become an original,'' a
critical folly outside the bounds of history. To Engell,
paradoxically, the original is itself a copy, since it represents
only the way people understand the house at this point in time.
Authenticity is always open to interpretation; the various
restorations and re-restorations of the Garden House _ imperial,
communist, democratic _ is evidence enough for academics. But
judging the real is no esoteric matter in Germany.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Few other countries have such expertise in reconstruction.
Gutted ruins like the Charlottenburg Palace in Berlin and the
Wuerzburg Palace were immaculately restored to glory, as if the
bombing had never happened. Dresden is turning the blackened rubble
that was once the Frauenkirche into a reassembled phoenix. There
are proposals to rebuild Berlin's Royal Palace, whose ruins were
demolished by the Communists in 1950. Aside from questions about
the cost, some have asked whether the resulting palace would still
be the palace. To what extent would visitors feel the ``aura,'' as
the German philosopher Walter Benjamin famously described the
emanation of reality, while visiting what they know to be a fraud?
</P>
<P>
   And this line of questioning extends to the darkest focus of
reproduction restoration: Buchenwald, whose rusting gates are
almost visible from the window of Goethe's writing room. Is there
not an irony involved in the retrieval of history with a
simulation? Is memory served at a concentration camp when the very
methods used to preserve it inevitably lead to the diminution of
the ``real''?
</P>
<P>
   The people of Weimar, surprisingly, have embraced the replica of
their chief cult object in the same way that federal politicians
eventually decided that Christo's wrapping of the Reichstag was not
so bad an idea after all. Seventy percent of Weimar citizens want
to keep it after the birthday year is over. At least half the
nearly 1,000 people who visit the second Garden House daily know
that it is a copy and are eager to see just how precise it is. The
unsuspecting other half pay their 5 marks ($2.65) for a quick tour
and leave, feeling the perhaps false glow of a brush with the
German bard. Others are confused or angry upon suddenly seeing the
original house across the way, with its garden and 4 marks'
admission. They too have been an essential part of the experiment.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Weimar will soon nestle under the comforting blanket of
a World Heritage Site designation. But the Sparkasse bank has not
decided what to do with the second Garden House when it is removed
at the end of October. Perhaps it will tour the world, as Laier
designed it to do, a floating signifier without a context, a shrine
in search of new pilgrims.
</P>
<P>
   Most people seem satisfied that, come what may, the appeal of
the original will remain mysteriously palpable. As Walter
Benjamin's age of mechanical reproduction becomes digital and
genetic, it is no wonder that many crave the intimacy and peace of
identity, the smell of leather and creak of wood, the nearness to
something that happened long ago and only once. As a German woman
clutching two wriggling children prepared to leave the custom-built
sleight of hand, she discovered that she had been conned.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you mean `copy'?'' she barked at a man behind the
desk. ``I want the real thing!''
</P>
<P>
   Laier just smiled and patted the lintel on his way out.
</P>
<P>
   Both Garden Houses are at Corona-Schroeter-Weg, Ilm Park,
Weimar. Information for the replica, open daily through October:
011-49-3643-81-99-17. The original is open November to March and
April to October (closed Tuesdays): 011-49-3643-54-51-03. Internet:
www.weimar1999.de.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
