<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1985 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     09-22 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV10-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., OCT. 10, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: My overhead garage door was installed when the house was
built about nine years ago. It is still working normally, but for
the past few months it has been making a lot of squealing and
squeaking noises every time I open it. I have done nothing to this
door since we moved in as I was never told that any maintenance was
required. Does this type of door require lubrication or maintenance
of any kind?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. Regular lubrication of all moving parts once every year
or two with a light oil. This includes the torsion springs or
balancing springs (depending on the type of hardware on the door),
the lock hardware and the various cables connecting the lifting
mechanism to the door. The shafts and bearings of the steel rollers
inside the tracks on each side of the door also need regular
lubrication (nylon rollers should not be oiled). However, you
should not apply oil to the inside of the tracks. When lubricating
you should also check all bolts and other fasteners to make sure
they are still tight.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In a very heavy rain I get water trickling in under my
basement window. This window faces uphill and is below ground level
and surrounded by a metal ``window well'' or low wall so that water
runs down off the hill and often accumulates inside the well. Is
there some simple way I can solve this water problem without having
to excavate and waterproof the foundation wall?
</P>
<P>
   A: Although excavating around the outside and waterproofing the
outside of this wall (in addition to installing drain tile along
the footing) is probably the best solution, you may be able to
divert the water that runs off the hill so it won't accumulate
inside the window well. Dig a 12-inch deep and 12-inch-to-18-inch
wide trench on the hill parallel to the house and at least 10 feet
uphill from the foundation. The trench should extend past the house
at each end, and should be filled with gravel. Water coming off the
hill will then be caught by the trench and diverted around each
side of the house so that it won't accumulate against the house
wall or inside the window well.
</P>
<P>
   Q: One plaster ceiling on the second floor of my old house shows
a damp spot all the time, causing the paint to peel constantly. The
spot is not near any outside wall and there are no signs of a leak
in the attic above it. Do you have any idea what could possibly be
causing this?
</P>
<P>
   A: It is most likely due to condensation developing on the attic
roof beams or under the attic insulation. This then drips down onto
the top of the ceiling and soaks into the plaster. The condensation
is often due to a lack of adequate ventilation in the attic _ maybe
because some of the vents along the eaves are blocked or because
the attic simply needs more vents along the eaves and up near the
roof ridge.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The ceilings and walls in my house have developed a number of
fine hairline cracks. What is the best way to repair them before I
repaint?
</P>
<P>
   A: If the cracks are only in the paint, then it is likely a
paint failure _ the paint itself is cracking or ``alligatoring''
due to poor application, inadequate drying time between coats,
improper thinning, or failure to prepare the surface properly
beforehand. If this is the case then sanding and filling the cracks
with vinyl or acrylic spackling compound before repainting will
usually solve the problem. If your walls are plaster then it is
also possible that the plaster under the paint is cracking, but
here again, patching with a spackling compound should do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``GARAGE DOOR OPENER'' goes with this
column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Garage door extension springs, torsion springs,
pulleys, cables and steel rollers, should all be lubricated with a
light oil every year or two.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
