<HEADER>
A1988 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-BUYER'S-EDGE23-COX     09-22 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUYER'S-EDGE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anti-theft devices improve chances that car will be there when
you get back
 &HT;    By Michelle C. Brooks
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Beep-Beep.
</P>
<P>
   Beeeeep, Beeeeeeeep, eeeeee, errrrrrrrr, eeeeEEE, errrrRRRR.
</P>
<P>
   Blip-Blip.
</P>
<P>
   In metro Atlanta, it's hard to miss the car alarm chorus. From
flashing lights to honking horns to synthesized voices stating,
``ARMED _ DISARMED,'' they've caught our attention.
</P>
<P>
   And for good reason. According to the Highway Loss Data
Institute, anti-theft devices reduce the risk of your vehicle being
stolen.
</P>
<P>
   Which means those noisemakers really do work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anti-theft devices cut theft losses by 50 percent,'' says Kim
Hazelbaker, senior vice president of the highway institute, a
private, nonprofit research organization whose funding comes from
the insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
   Once the domain of joy-riding teens and chop shops, auto theft
has become a thriving export industry in recent years. Hazelbaker
estimates that millions of dollars worth of vehicles are stolen
annually throughout the United States and taken overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Auto theft is a sophisticated export business in this
country,'' says Hazelbaker. ``(U.S.) Customs folks do a good job,
but estimate they are only finding 1 percent to 2 percent. It is a
huge problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though anti-theft devices have shown they are an important
factor in reducing theft, you won't see the savings on your
insurance rates just yet. Although laws and regulations in 13
states require a lower comprehensive coverage rate for vehicles
with anti-theft devices, Georgia is not one of these states. But,
as claims are reduced, rates will stabilize and all consumers will
benefit, says Dave Hurst, public affairs liaison for State Farm
Insurance Co.
</P>
<P>
   In an ever-pressing race to stay ahead of criminals and protect
autos, companies have responded with a wealth of anti-theft
options.
</P>
<P>
   No matter which anti-theft device you choose, make sure it is
installed by a certified professional who has had special training
to install electronic equipment in your vehicle. Look for training
and certifications such as Mobile Electronics Certified
Professional.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the type of security system, a basic line of
defense against theft is locking your doors, taking your keys with
you and keeping valuables out of sight. Most experts agree that
anti-theft devices don't necessarily prevent theft, but in many
instances they will slow the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any anti-theft device is better than none, but no anti-theft
device guarantees that your car will not be taken,'' says police
Lt. D.W. Dunlap with the Atlanta Police Department's auto theft
division. ``They just lessen the likelihood.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Brooks writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 1720EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1989 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-BUYER'S-EDGEALARM-COX     09-22 1612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUYER'S-EDGEALARM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An overview of vehicle anti-theft systems
 &HT;    By Michelle Brooks
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Alarms
</P>
<P>
   Car alarms work much like home security systems. Instead of a
keypad, the alarm is set with a remote control. When the car's
security is breached, sirens wail, horns honk and lights flash.
Depending on the type of alarm, consumers can add features such as
keyless entry, keyless locking, pain-generating sirens, window and
sunroof control and auto-start.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Burney, an installer with Gwinnett Sound in Norcross (Ga.),
says that when purchasing an alarm system, it's important to
consider the type of vehicle and the options you want to add.
``Look at what type of protection you want,'' Burney says.
</P>
<P>
   Basic alarms start at about $200 but are limited in their
features. That's why Scott Carroll, mobile electronics specialist
for American Radio Cellular &AMP; Paging in Marietta (Ga.), encourages
customers to think long term.
</P>
<P>
   Alarms have ``channels'' that enable you to add features. If you
purchase an alarm with a limited number of channels and want to add
features later on, you may end up having to replace the entire
alarm, Carroll says.
</P>
<P>
   Having an anti-theft device that depends on catching the
attention of others raises concerns that no one will notice.
Carroll doesn't give that concern much weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a load of wash, '' he says. ``It is human nature that
when you hear a noise, you're going to look.''
</P>
<P>
   For Dion Bentley of Clarkston (Ga.), having a car alarm serves
to protect his 1994 Honda Accord from small-time thieves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an alarm to stop the little would-be criminal from joy
riding,'' says Bentley, 28. ``I know it can't stop a professional,
but I am trying to prevent the snatch-and-grab criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   Passive devices
</P>
<P>
   Several auto manufacturers are equipping their vehicles with
anti-theft devices. Connected through the key, these passive
devices set automatically and require no effort on the part of the
driver. If the vehicle is broken into, the starter is disabled. The
hassle to consumers comes if the key is lost: Replacement keys can
be purchased only through the manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Having an alarm that sets itself and is not easily turned off is
what Niccole McLeod, 28, of Lilburn (Ga.) likes about the passive
system in her 1992 Acura Legend.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the car alarm is going off and I put the key in the
ignition, it will not crank,'' says McLeod. ``I have to put the key
in the door on the outside to disable the alarm. If a person grabs
my key, they can't start the car.''
</P>
<P>
   Vehicle location systems
</P>
<P>
   One of the first vehicle location systems to hit the market was
LoJack. Vehicles with LoJack are equipped with a special
transmitter hidden somewhere within the vehicle. When the vehicle
is stolen, the owner notifies authorities. The police, in
conjunction with the National Crime Information Computer Network,
activate the transmitter, which then sends out a coded signal
specific to the stolen vehicle. Police use special locators to pick
up the signal and follow it so the vehicle can be recovered.
</P>
<P>
   When Robert Walters of Griffin (Ga.) purchased his 1996
Chevrolet Blazer, he knew that the popular sport-utility vehicle is
a favorite among thieves. That knowledge prompted him to purchase a
LoJack system through the car dealer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I most definitely would recommend it,'' says Walters, 27. ``If
anything does happen, you get your stuff back _ it is guaranteed by
the company.''
</P>
<P>
   There are also several other vehicle location systems to choose
from, including OnGuard, Force Tracker and Air Command. Some of the
newer designs use global positioning technology.
</P>
<P>
   Monitoring systems
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, the U.S. Defense Department began launching a series of
tracking satellites known as the Global Positioning System, which
became fully operational in 1994. This technology an locate your
exact position anywhere on earth. Designed for military use, the
system is now also used for nonmilitary navigation and to track and
locate, among other things, stolen vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Taking this technology a step further and combining it with a
cellular telephone, monitoring systems do everything but wash the
car.
</P>
<P>
   For a monthly fee, the vehicle is connected to a fully staffed
call center. At the touch of a button, the call center can locate
your vehicle, start the engine, unlock the doors, honk the horn,
dispatch emergency assistance and even make hotel reservations for
you. If you're lost while driving, the call center can tell you
when and where to turn to find your way home.
</P>
<P>
   For emergencies, the vehicle is equipped with a panic button.
When pressed, it alerts the call center to listen in anonymously,
track the vehicle with the use of GPS and alert the proper
authorities to come to your aid.
</P>
<P>
   Two of these systems to hit the market recently are Alpine's
Mayday and OnStar.
</P>
<P>
   Steering wheel locks
</P>
<P>
   Steering wheel locks are usually made of steel and prevent the
wheel from turning. They attach in two places on the wheel and can
be unlocked only with a key. The most common brand is The Club,
whose slogan is ``If you can't steer it, you can't steal it.''
</P>
<P>
   _Michelle C. Brooks
</P>
<P>
   Types of anti-theft devices:
</P>
<P>
   Alarms
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What do they do:
</P>
<P>
   A basic alarm is connected to the vehicle's electronic system
and attracts attention through sirens, flashing lights and honking
horns when the vehicle's security is violated. Most such alarm
systems also prevent the vehicle from being started. Other features
can be added.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What's out there:
</P>
<P>
   There are a vast number of brands on the market, among them
Avital, Auto Page, Viper and Crimestopper.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Expect to pay:
</P>
<P>
   Prices start at $150 to $199 for a basic alarm, which usually
includes a control unit, a siren and a key-chain remote control.
Cost increases depending on the features added.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Effectiveness:
</P>
<P>
   ``They are fine for deterring joy riders,'' says police
detective E.S. Hopper, who oversees the DeKalb Police Department's
auto-theft unit. ``It would only be a two-second slowdown for a
professional thief.''
</P>
<P>
   Vehicle location systems
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What do they do:
</P>
<P>
   A special transmitter hidden within the vehicle sends out a
coded signal when activated. Police use a special tracking system
to pick up the vehicle's signal and follow it so it can be
recovered. Some of the newer designs use Global Positioning System
technology.
</P>
<P>
   What's out there:
</P>
<P>
   Brands available include OnGuard, Force Tracker, Air Command and
LoJack.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Expect to pay:
</P>
<P>
   Basic systems retail for around $600; extra features can be
added at extra cost.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Effectiveness:
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen it (LoJack) work,'' says Hopper. ``I thought it was
quite amazing. If you see an unmarked (patrol) car going down the
road with four antennas, it has LoJack. The LoJack company has
furnished these units to departments for use.''
</P>
<P>
   Monitoring systems
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What do they do:
</P>
<P>
   Based on the Global Positioning System, monitoring systems go a
step further. For a monthly fee, you can add a variety of services.
Hooked into the vehicle with GPS technology and a cellular
telephone, the monitoring service can offer roadside assistance,
directions and, if a panic button is pressed, emergency service.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What's out there:
</P>
<P>
   Brands recently hitting the market include Alpine Mobile Mayday,
CarCop and On-star.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Expect to pay:
</P>
<P>
   $1,000 and up depending on features.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Effectiveness:
</P>
<P>
   ``The location of the vehicle can be checked on demand,'' Hopper
says. ``One drawback with GPS: If the car is placed in a garage, it
is more difficult to locate.''
</P>
<P>
   Passive devices
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What do they do:
</P>
<P>
   Passive anti-theft devices, once activated, disable a vehicle's
ability to start. Several car manufacturers make them available as
standard or optional equipment.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors and Honda are two of the automakers who equip
their vehicles with passive devices.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Expect to pay:
</P>
<P>
   Check with your car dealer to see if this is a standard or
optional feature. Prices vary by manufacturer and dealer.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Effectiveness:
</P>
<P>
   ``It is good, but professionals have figured a way around it,''
says Hopper. ``Your joy rider is going to have problems with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Steering wheel locks
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What do they do:
</P>
<P>
   Made of steel, they lock onto the steering wheel and can be
unlocked only with a key.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What's out there:
</P>
<P>
   The best-known brand is The Club.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Expect to pay:
</P>
<P>
   These are the easiest devices to buy. They're available at mass
merchandisers including discount stores, automotive parts stores
and hardware stores. Prices start at $25.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Effectiveness:
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a basic-level anti-theft device,'' says Hopper. ``Good
for deterring joy riders; not a deterrent against professionals.
You can probably pick one up at a garage sale.''
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   For more information, visit the following sites:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Auto theft prevention and statistics:
</P>
<P>
   Highway Loss Data Institute, www.carsafety.org
</P>
<P>
   National Insurance Crime Bureau, www.nicb.org
</P>
<P>
   Federal Bureau of Investigation, www.fbi.gov/
</P>
<P>
   CCC Information Services, www.cccis.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information about the
</P>
<P>
   Global Positioning System:
</P>
<P>
   Global Positioning System Overview
</P>
<P>
   by Peter H. Dana, department of geography,
</P>
<P>
   University of Texas at Austin, wwwhost.cc.utexas
</P>
<P>
   .edu/ftp/pub/grg/gcraft/notes/gps/gps.html
</P>
<P>
   How Stuff Works, www.howstuffworks
</P>
<P>
   .com/gps.htm
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Brooks writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
