<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1991 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION2     09-22 1350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHOPPING DESTINATION: Ellijay
 &HT;    State's apple capital invites you to have a bite
 &HT;    By Sabine Morrow
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the core of this North Georgia town that calls itself the
state's apple capital is a warmth that makes visitors feel right at
home.
</P>
<P>
   With a population of less than 2,000 _ and a share of Gilmer
County's annual bumper crop of more than a half million apples _
Ellijay easily provides a charming small-town atmosphere
highlighted by a courthouse square that looks as if it could double
as a movie set. Add to this a backdrop of rolling hills shadowed by
the Chattahoochee National Forest and the Appalachian Mountains and
you've got quite a picturesque setting.
</P>
<P>
   Anchored by the elegant courthouse, built as a hotel in 1897,
the square offers plenty of shopping opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Fall is a perfect time to visit, as the apple houses outside of
town are brimming with Winesaps, Romes, Granny Smiths and Arkansas
reds along with those old favorites Red and Yellow Delicious. And
if you plan your trek in mid-October, you can drop by the Ellijay
Apple Festival.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first places you might want to visit on the square is
Apple Country Station, where you're sure to get a real home-style
welcome. Push open the door of this turn-of-the century building,
which houses a furniture and gift store, and the first item to
catch your eye is a handsome bed covered with a vast array of small
well-dressed stuffed critters from the Boyd's Bear collection.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are it won't be long before Rudy McVey, who owns the
place with his wife, Mary, comes over and welcomes you to his
``home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We set the store up like a house, so you can see how the
merchandise is going to look in your home,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if you wander to the upstairs showrooms you'll think
you've walked into someone's private home. In a way, you have.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 years ago the McVeys moved to the area from
Brooksville, Fla., and couldn't find much in the way of housing, so
they built an elegant, spacious apartment on the top floor. Today
the space is appointed with fine furnishings, collectibles and
artwork. It boasts a huge kitchen, where the McVeys hold special
gatherings for customers and locals.
</P>
<P>
   A few doors down at Antiques and More, the shopper with an eye
for ancient treasures can while away a good chunk of time browsing
through 42 dealers' booths.
</P>
<P>
   Charles and Frances Reddick own one of the booths that offers
merchandise from England.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last year and a half, Ellijay has really started to
come into its own as an antiques shopping place,'' Charles Reddick
says.
</P>
<P>
   The couple travels about twice a year to England on buying trips
and fills their booth with china, carved walking sticks and
furniture.
</P>
<P>
   At Nelle Hefner's booth you'll find a desk that once was an
organ rescued from a local chicken house, a time-worn stagecoach
writing desk, china from occupied Japan and even a corn liquor jug
that she swears was used for the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   The store also carries an impressive collection of locally
carved totem poles and coins.
</P>
<P>
   If you're lucky enough to visit while Hefner's around, you could
pick up some quick antiques know-how.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole world's made up of reproductions, honey,'' she says.
``Think about it, there's just not enough real antiques to go
around.''
</P>
<P>
   And for those who have sterling salt and pepper shakers, she
cautions never to leave salt in them for long periods of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll eat 'em up,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Ellijay also offers a little bit of Christmas year-round. At the
beautiful white Victorian called the Christmas House, decorated
trees beckon from the bay windows.
</P>
<P>
   For Lynette Davies of Lawrenceville, nothing can keep her from a
store filled with treasures for her favorite season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came up here because I heard about a new Christmas store,''
she says. ``I know it's still summer, but I love Christmas and, for
me, it's never too early to buy ornaments.''
</P>
<P>
   If you go
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: From downtown, take I-75 north to I-575. Follow
it to Ga. 515/5, then take Ga. 52 into Ellijay.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hours: Many stores are open daily from 10 a.m.-5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parking: Free parking on the square and on Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Handicapped access: Most stores are accessible.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Restrooms: Some stores have restrooms available for customers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Gilmer County Chamber of Commerce, 706-635-7400.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Just a few steps from the square, Corner Stone Cafe, 76 N.
Main St. (706-636-2233), provides a comfortable place to stop for a
lunch break. Here owners Charles and Lynn Martis offer hearty
soups, salads and sandwiches along with specialty coffee drinks.
The couple recently installed an open kitchen overlooking the
dining room's massive fieldstone fireplace. Prices range from
$2.75-$4.75. 11 a.m.-3 p.m. Mondays, Tuesdays and Thursdays; 8
a.m.-8 p.m., Fridays-Saturdays; 8 a.m.-3 p.m. Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   At Ruthie's Calico Cupboard, 52 N. Main St. (706-635-7575),
you'll find a casual, tidy diner serving up homemade pies along
with stick-to-your-ribs fried chicken, steak and gravy and
meatloaf. This is serious mountain food that should provide fuel
for shopping. Prices range from $1.25-$4.95. 7 a.m.-4 p.m.
Mondays-Saturdays; 11a.m.-3 p.m. Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond shopping
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The apple houses: Apple season is in full bloom through
October and a few miles before you get to Ellijay, you'll pass a
slew of apple houses and orchards lining Ga. 52. From Hillcrest
Orchards to Aaron's Apple House, you'll find cider, pies, apple
breads, gifts and more than a dozen apple varieties to lug home.
Some orchards offer hayrides and a chance to pick your own apples.
For more information on following the apple trail during harvest
season, call the Gilmer County Chamber of Commerce
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Festivals: The following is a sample of upcoming events.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Apple Festival. 9 a.m.-6 p.m. Oct. 9-10 and 16-17. More
than 300 vendors selling arts and crafts. Food, entertainment,
antique car show and apple products galore. Ellijay Lions Club
Fairgrounds, Ga. 5. $3 and children under 6 free. 706-636-4500,
706-635-7400.
</P>
<P>
   Trick or Treat on the Square. 6 p.m.-7:30 p.m. Oct. 30. The
event includes a costume contest and a jack-o'-lantern carving
contest. Free. 706-276-1699.
</P>
<P>
   Light Up Ellijay. 10 a.m.-7 p.m. Dec. 4. Free. Enjoy a full day
in downtown Ellijay that begins with a parade, includes strolling
carolers, an old-fashioned costume contest and a live Nativity
scene, then wraps up with the lighting of the Christmas tree on the
square. 706-635-7400.
</P>
<P>
   While browsing through Ellijay, we found ...
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Howard Miller Oak grandfather clock. $1,995. Apple Country
Station, 2 Northside Square, 706-635-1234.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Victorian chimney pot from the 1890s. $150. Antiques &AMP; More,
13-14 Northside Square, 706-635-7738.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ceramic kitchenware by Carol Endres. $6-$42. The Trading Post,
34 N. Main St. 706-276-1699
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Team Toad Collection's Georgia Bulldog croaking frog sings
``Glory, Glory to Old Georgia.'' $29.99. Mountain Tops &AMP; Country
Store, 42 N. Main St., 706-276-1939
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Element of Reason metal and glass sculpture by Eric Strauss.
$3,600. Otto's Stained Glass and Gallery, 58 N. Main St.,
706-636-2311.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Brass and wood ice cream scoop. $35. Ellijay Antiques Mall, 66
N. Main St., 706-276-7622.
</P>
