<HEADER>
A1993 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SHOPPING-GUIDE-COX     09-22 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-GUIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AJC helps you locate hard to find items
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having trouble finding a particular item? We'll try to help you
locate it. But due to the volume of mail, we cannot track down
every request. Readers whose queries are answered in the column
will receive a blue-and-cream canvas Buyer's Edge tote bag. Write
us at Buyer's Edge Find It, Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box
4689, Atlanta, GA 30302; e-mail us at buyersedge(at)ajc.com (please
include your name, the city you live in and daytime phone number);
or call 404-582-7642.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for Darbo's wild blackberry preserves, which
contain blackberries as big as the tip of your thumb. I used to
find these preserves at Kroger, but not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   _ Patricia Duren, Lawrencville (Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   A: The Darbo family of Austria has been producing all-natural
preserves and conserves since 1879 and preparing them according to
traditional, secret Austrian recipes. It's your turn to enjoy these
preserves once again. We found your 16-ounce jar of Darbo's wild
blackberry preserves ($3.99) at the International Farmers Market,
5193 Peachtree Industrial Blvd., Chamblee (770-455-1777).
</P>
<P>
   Q: My niece is looking for sunglasses for her Australian
shepherd. While I have seen visors for dogs, I have been unable to
find sunglasses. Do you know where we might find these items?
</P>
<P>
   _ Linda Chu, Snellville (Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   A: Soon your niece's pooch will be struting around in style. We
found these cool shades at Barking Hound Village, 1918 Cheshire
Bridge Road N.E. (404-897-3422). Made by Sunpups, the black lenses
with the colored sides are crafted from chew-resistant plastic
($6.95). They are kept in place with a sunglass holder ($5) that
fits comfortably around the dog's neck.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Since I was a small kid, a favorite soft drink of mine and my
family was Wink, produced by Canada Dry. I haven't been able to
locate it in Atlanta in over a year. I did see some in a Publix
store in New Smyrna Beach, Fla., last summer. Do you have any idea
where I might locate some in our area?
</P>
<P>
   _ Howard A. Reisman, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Another Wink request: I am suffering painful withdrawal from my
favorite soft drink, diet Wink. It has disappeared from the grocery
shelves! Is it still being distributed?
</P>
<P>
   _ David P. Darden, Marietta (Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   And another: I am wondering about a soda called Wink, made by
Canada Dry. It was my favorite, but I haven't seen it in a long
time. Just wondering if you had any information on it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ken Day, Marietta (Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   A: No news is not good news about Wink, the drink that is a
combo of orange, apple and grapefruit juices. Unfortunately for
those of you who love this citrus drink, including the diet
version, it's not available in our state _ except for a few places
in South Georgia, such as Thomasville. According to Jim Hahn,
director of marketing for Southeast Atlantic Beverage, Wink, which
was owned by Canada Dry, was sold all over the country for many
years. As companies merged, Canada Dry became a part of Dr.
Pepper-7-Up and ultimately Cadbury Beverages. ``And,'' Hahn said,
``since Cadbury already owned Squirt, a similar soft drink to Wink,
the company put their marketing efforts behind Squirt because it
was better known nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   However, as purists know, Squirt is sweeter than Wink. You can
still find Wink in certain pockets of Florida, Virginia and New
York. We found our 1-liter bottle for $1.09 at a Food Lion in
Lynchburg, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for a perfume called ``Caesars Woman.'' It used
to be sold at Macy's, but they no longer carry it, and now I can't
find it anywhere. Help!
</P>
<P>
   _ Jill Jurkovich, Duluth
</P>
<P>
   A: You're in luck. We stumbled onto your fragrance in Las Vegas.
Marketed through Caesars World Merchandising, Caesars Woman made
its debut in 1988, a white floral rich in rose, Egyptian jasmine,
orange flower, geranium and iris. It's set against a backdrop of
Tibetan musk, patchouli and sandalwood. Today, the scent is only
available through the company's Web site at www.shopcaesars.com or
by calling 1-800-843-1043. A 3.3-ounce cologne spray is $49.50; a
3.3-ounce eau de parfum is $55. There's a body-and-bath collection
available as well. Incidentally, Caesars Palace, the casino resort,
also markets Caesars Man, which is a combo of lavender, citrus
notes, oakmoss, sandalwood and fir balasm. A 4-ounce cologne spray
is $39.50; a 4-ounce after shave is $29.50. You can find it at the
same locations.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Could you tell me where I can find Murphy Oil Soap in a spray
bottle? I have not been able to find it in the past year. A note on
the original Murphy Oil Soap bottle says it can't be used as a
refill in a spray bottle.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jackie Pyle, Hampton
</P>
<P>
   A: For almost 100 years, Murphy Oil Soap has been cleaning the
wood floors in American homes. In 1905, a German immigrant came to
Ohio business man Jeremiah T. Murphy with a vegetable oil soap he
claimed was easy to make and was a popular cleanser in Germany.
Murphy bought the recipe and started marketing the soap, which was
originally a paste packed in a barrel. Shoppers would scoop out
their own orders. Eventually, the soap was prepacked in cans and
later in liquid form.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to cleaning wood floors and furniture, the soap can
be used in the kitchen and bathroom. And in the laundry room, use
it as a pre-spotter. We found the Murphy Oil Soap in a 22-ounce
spray bottle ($1.99) at Drug Emporium, 2953 N. Druid Hills Road
N.E. (404-636-6108). A 16-ounce bottle of the original formula soap
($1.69) is at Publix, 1544 Piedmont Road N.E. (404-898-1850). And
the 32-ounce Murphy Oil Wood Floor container ($3.89) is at Kmart,
2581 Piedmont Road N.E. (404-261-6900).
</P>
<P>
   _ Contributing: Michelle C. Brooks
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johnson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
