<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1994 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-KIDS-MUSIC-NYT &LR;      09-22 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-KIDS-MUSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM NOTES ON THE SCREEN TO MUSIC IN THE EAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BRUCE HEADLAM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a strain of Romanticism that regards children as
innocent and wonderfully intuitive creatures who are strapped to
the grim wheel of the education system and ground to dust.
</P>
<P>
   As Romantic myths go, this one is almost completely false,
except perhaps in the case of music education. As many piano
teachers can tell you, children are full of music. They sing to
themselves constantly, they dance whenever your back is turned and
can clap back almost any rhythm they hear with surprising ease.
Then the piano lessons start and pretty much put an end to all
that.
</P>
<P>
   Who's to blame for the sorry state of music education? For one
thing, it has never benefited from the kind of advancements that,
by comparison, have improved primary reading. In the 1930s, Zerna
Sharp studied how children talked and used the same repetitive
patterns in ``Fun With Dick and Jane.'' Dr. Seuss added rhythm and
rhyme. In the late 1960s, ``Sesame Street'' offered contemporary
characters.
</P>
<P>
   But piano teachers still put 5-year-olds in front of a 600-pound
piano and tell them to find middle C.
</P>
<P>
   The real culprit is far larger and more diffuse. Music, or at
least, creating music, doesn't hold a central place in our culture
anymore. ``Serious music'' is now taken seriously only by a very
narrow slice of people, and the prevalence of recorded music has
rendered music's old social role in the home obsolete. It is
possible to envision the day, if it has not already arrived, when
more children will have downloaded an MP3 file than can play an
instrument.
</P>
<P>
   One of the great promises of multimedia was that it would
revolutionize music training by helping students understand the
correlation between the notes on the staff and the sounds in their
ears. Music Ace 2, a new program from Harmonic Vision, is an
introduction to rhythm, melody and basic harmony that takes
children aged 8 and up away from their pianos and puts them in
front of their monitors.
</P>
<P>
   The program breaks theory down into 24 lessons, from note values
and key signatures to intervals and scales. Each lesson involves a
lesson followed by a game, although game is a gentle word: They are
really exercises in ear training and rhythm that are more useful
than what typically passes for entertainment on children's
software.
</P>
<P>
   And the games are not the only case in which the program's
juvenile packaging is at odds with its serious purpose. Music Ace 2
has all the anthropomorphic touches you might expect _ the
instruments have eyes and the quarter notes wear little grins _ but
the version of music it presents comes straight out of 19th-century
Vienna. The selections tend to be marches and voluntaries that
begin with Bach and end with Beethoven.
</P>
<P>
   The musical guide, Maestro Max, looks like Arthur Fiedler from
the Boston Pops and sounds like Colonel Klink from ``Hogan's
Heroes.'' ``Haydn vould be proud,'' he says, with a rolling
Prussian ``r'' after the student successfully completes a
composition exercise.
</P>
<P>
   What works, and works well, on Music Ace 2 is the screen. The
notes are fat and easy to manipulate across well-drawn staffs. The
exercises are short but well presented, even if I did find the
bouncing-ball metronome a trifle distracting.
</P>
<P>
   What doesn't work is the sound. Like almost all music programs,
Music Ace 2 relies on the MIDI files in your computer, which means
that the Bach Invention sounds less like a harpsichord and more
like the Wurlizter organ outlet at the mall. But does the sound
quality really matter in a program that's designed, after all, to
teach only music fundamentals?
</P>
<P>
   It does. What is really fundamental about music is making it.
Like too many theory lessons, Music Ace 2 becomes an excuse to put
away the musical instruments before the student really learns to
derive pleasure from playing. Give a student a piano or a drum and
she will bang away until she gets tired or until she learns to make
music. After 20 minutes of clicking my mouse in time to the
bouncing ball on Music Ace 2, all I had was a sore wrist.
</P>
<P>
   The people at GVOX have been trying to put together software
education and practical musical training for some time. Their
latest product, Ricky Recorder, tries to teach the recorder to
children with the help of a CD-ROM and a clever little microphone
that attaches to the instrument and plugs into your computer's
sound card, allowing the program to ``hear'' what you are playing
and offer lessons.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious question is, Why the recorder? For those who were
forced to learn ``El Condor Pasa'' by Simon and Garfunkel (``I'd
rather be a hammer than a nail ...'') in grade school music class,
the instrument's breathy sound can be particularly traumatic. But
it's cheap: GVOX even throws in a Yamaha recorder with the
software.
</P>
<P>
   Does it work? My microphone's operation was spotty at best. But
GVOX's idea is a good one for people who, for whatever reason,
can't find the time or money for formal lessons. But even if the
technology is seamless, the content on the CD-ROM isn't. The main
page of the program has four icons: a robin, a blue cloud with the
letters ``www'' written on it (for a connection to the GVOX Web
site, it turns out), a soggy-looking notebook and something that
looked like a sundial that threatened to shut down whatever I was
doing when I clicked on it.
</P>
<P>
   The lessons (found in the notebook, I discovered) show the basic
fingerings for the recorder with ghostly, hard-to-read hands and
throw in a healthy dose of theory, almost as much you find in the
more careful Music Ace 2. Whether many beginning players are
willing to wade through the lesson on dotted notes just to play the
first four bars of ``Hot Cross Buns'' is doubtful. After an hour
spent with Ricky Recorder, I had a change of heart. I really would
rather be a hammer.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC ACE 2
</P>
<P>
   (Harmonic Vision; $49.95; Windows 3.1 or later, Macintosh.)
</P>
<P>
   RICKY RECORDER
</P>
<P>
   (GVOX; $59.99; Windows 95 and later.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
