<HEADLINE>
ALTERNATIVES TO BASIC MICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My parents, in their late 60s, are beginning to use a
computer. They are having a hard time working the mouse; to
compound the problem, my father is left-handed and my mother
right-handed. Is there a good alternative to the standard PC mouse?
</P>
<P>
   A. There are a number of different kinds of mice and other
pointing devices available, so it's just a matter of finding
something that your parents feel more comfortable with. For any new
computer user, regardless of age, using the mouse effectively often
requires a bit of practice to learn the necessary motor
coordination and skill.
</P>
<P>
   You may want to slow down the speed of the mouse's movement and
clicking while your parents are learning. Go to the Start menu,
then Settings and Control Panel, then Mouse. There, you can also
change the default settings for a left-handed or a right-handed
user with one click.
</P>
<P>
   For alternatives to the standard PC equipment, check out options
from mouse makers like Logitech (www.logitech.com) and Kensington
(www.kensington.com). Logitech makes a cordless mouse that can be
moved from one side of the keyboard to the other.
</P>
<P>
   Some users find trackballs or computer pens and tablets easier
to manipulate than a mouse, and Kensington makes a number of
trackballs with large programmable buttons.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West 43d
Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
QandA(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
