<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON COMPUTERS AND GADGETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Compaq Joins Battle For Pocket-Size Market
</P>
<P>
   While Handspring and Palm Computing slugged it out last week,
Compaq this week unveiled a new contender in the pocket-size
category: a Windows CE device that scraps the showy color screen in
favor of a slimmer design.
</P>
<P>
   Taking its cue from the Palm V, Compaq's Aero 1530 is the
skinniest CE personal digital assistant yet. It is a half-inch
thick and sells for $299. Although that is $150 less than the Palm
V, the Aero 1530 still holds things like contact, schedule, task
and e-mail information.
</P>
<P>
   _Joe Hutsko
</P>
<P>
   A Searchable C-Span For Politics Hounds
</P>
<P>
   Read their lips: Politics junkies may want to check out C-Span's
new searchable video archives for the 2000 campaign season
(www.c-span &QL; 
.org/campaign2000/search).
</P>
<P>
   C-Span, the nonprofit cable station, opened the archives a few
weeks ago to make its broadcasts of speeches, debates, hearings and
interviews available long after candidates have left the podiums.
The searching technology, developed by the Virage Co., works by
scanning unedited transcripts for keywords and pulling up
corresponding video clips.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest material in the archive dates to the spring of 1997,
far back enough to search ``that woman'' but not ``Checkers.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Lisa Guernsey
</P>
<P>
   Licensing Issue Stirs Up A Debate Over Using GIFs
</P>
<P>
   Web developers, faced with the prospect of paying $5,000 for
using an image-file format that has become a building block of the
Web, are taking their anger public.
</P>
<P>
   The tiff is over GIFs. Most people who create Web pages are
familiar with GIFs _ the slang term for digital images that carry
the ``.gif'' extension and have been compressed using the Graphics
Interchange Format. But most people are probably not aware that the
programming code behind the GIF format is patented and belongs to
Unisys, the computer company based in Blue Bell, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   In late July, Unisys quietly posted the new policy on its Web
site. It requires any Web developers using GIF who do not have a
GIF license to get one for $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Several well-known imaging products, like Corel Draw or Adobe
Photoshop, already come with Unisys licenses. But that is not the
case for the vast majority of imaging software that can be
downloaded free. Even people who simply use GIFs by copying images
from other Web sites could be liable under the policy unless they
can prove that the images were originally created using licensed
software.
</P>
<P>
   In late August, several developers caught wind of the policy,
and angry messages streamed into Unisys and into techie-oriented
Web sites like Slashdot.org and Linuxworld.
</P>
<P>
   To many Internet denizens, the concept of patenting pieces of
computer code is equivalent to patenting mathematical equations.
They believe that such codes should be freely available.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Picher, a spokesman for Unisys, said the company had no
plans to go after people who have simply copied images and pasted
them into their sites (although, he noted, copyright holders might
have their own problem with that.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not actually going out and tracking people down,''
Picher said. But he added that if developers created a popular Web
site ``with valuation in the billions, they might expect a phone
call from us.''
</P>
<P>
   _Lisa Guernsey
</P>
<P>
   Need to Start the Wash? It's Just a Phone Call Away
</P>
<P>
   A certain long-distance communications company lets you ``reach
out and touch someone,'' but the World Wireless Communications
company is promising to let you reach out and control parts of your
house through the World Wide Web. ``The garage door on your home
could be controlled by the browser on your desk at work,'' said
Donald I. Wallace, the president of X-tra Web (www.x-traweb.com),
the division of the company introducing the technology.
</P>
<P>
   The X-tra Web system works by attaching a tiny microcontroller
called an X-Node to an appliance or machine. The X-Node then
transmits data to an X-Gate, an Internet gateway, that then can be
monitored from the Internet with a standard Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   ``The X-Node itself has a little Web page in it, so we're
actually giving the washing machine or the garage door its own
little mini Web page,'' Wallace explained. ``It has its own IP
address, just the same as any other Web page does. So all you have
to do is open your browser, type in the IP address of your garage
door and you would get back the status of the garage door.''
</P>
<P>
   The system is designed to allow control or observation of things
like automated teller machines, home appliances, office equipment,
medical monitors and security systems over the Web. The X-tra Web
technology is already being tested or used by a number of
businesses, including a vending-machine company, a fast-food
franchise and an engineering firm, but the company also has an eye
on the consumer market.
</P>
<P>
   The devices are inexpensive, about $25 per X-Node and $150 for
the gateway, and the company expects to see Web-enabled homes by
early next year. And hey, it may just get the kids interested in
housework _ just make sure little Tommy doesn't crash the dryer.
</P>
<P>
   _J.D. Biersdorfer
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Works Suite 2000 Weighs In As a Hefty Microsoft Upgrade
</P>
<P>
   With the accordianlike expansion of hard drive space on new
personal computers, software developers appear increasingly
comfortable offering consumers more huge programs that fill them
up.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Microsoft released Works Suite 2000, an integrated
collection of utility and reference applications that is a kind of
office suite for the home computer user. The program is at least
400 percent larger than Microsoft's Windows 95 operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Weighing in between 785 megabytes and 1.4 gigabytes (depending
on installed features), Works Suite 2000 promises to help users do
everything from home publishing, organizing their lives, managing
finances, planning trips, editing photographs and doing research in
an included digital encyclopedia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it is a complete solution for home users,'' said
Hillarie Flood, the product manager for Works Suite 2000. ``When
you look at the types of things that people do in their homes and
compare them with what we ship, there is really a good match
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Works Suite 2000, which includes Microsoft's Word 2000, Money
2000 Standard, Home Publishing 2000, Expedia Streets and Trips
2000, and an express version of Picture It, costs $109, which makes
it a lot cheaper than its corporate cousin. It is an upgrade
product, which means that it requires at least a copy of Word
Perfect or Word on a computer before it can be installed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Michel Marriott
</P>
<P>
   A Program That Lets You Talk Your Way Around
</P>
<P>
   Don't be alarmed if you find someone muttering ``whisky, whisky,
whisky'' at their computer. They may be using Conversa Web, which
allows users to run Microsoft's Internet Explorer Web browser with
their voices rather than their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of clicking on Web page links, Conversa Web users simply
read them out loud. For graphics that provide links, the program
generates miniature cartoon bubbles containing a number that is
read aloud to make the link _ the company calls them ``saycons.''
</P>
<P>
   Simple spoken phrases like ``go back'' operate the browser's
navigation commands. Conversa Web can be used only to operate the
browser, not for dictation.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the idiosyncratic spellings frequently used in
Web addresses (say, ``kwik'' for quick'') make it impossible to
enter them with normal speech. Instead users must spell them out
using the military-style oral alphabet (``whisky'' for ``w,'' for
example).
</P>
<P>
   Web addresses, after they have been entered orally or by typing
them in, can be put on an oral favorites list and called up with a
word of the user's choosing.
</P>
<P>
   Conversa Web 3.0 costs $59.95. It only works on Windows-based
PCs with versions 4 or 5 of Internet Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   _Ian Austen
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
