<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MILITARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH EXPECTED TO CALL FOR MORE MILITARY SPENDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush will use the Citadel in
Charleston, S.C., Thursday as a backdrop to renew his call to
``rebuild the military power'' of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and other Republican presidential candidates have accused
the Clinton administration of weakening the military.
</P>
<P>
   In his second major policy speech, Bush is expected to tell
cadets at the Citadel, a private military college, that the United
States needs to improve housing for armed forces personnel and
increase pay and training. He also seeks a new system of
intermediate range, anti-ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is still a dangerous world. There are madmen, terrorists
and missiles,'' Bush said in New Hampshire earlier this month where
he gave businessmen a taste of what he is expected to say on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will rebuild the military power of the United States of
America,'' he said in Hew Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   His speech at the Citadel will detail his vision for the
military, said Mindy Tucker, a Bush spokeswoman in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Army Gen. Colin Powell, who served as chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff under the governor's father, President George
Bush, reviewed the speech that was written by Bush and his policy
advisers, Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   Two of those advisers, Condoleezza Rice and Bob Zoellick, also
worked in the Bush White House.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has vowed ``never, ever'' to commit U.S. forces
to United Nations control _ a line that resonates with Republicans
critical of the Clinton administration's handling of peacekeeping
efforts abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Michael O'Hanlon, a defense strategy expert at the non-partisan
Brookings Institution, a Washington-based think tank, was critical
of Bush's earlier remarks on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``His defense rhetoric is not that notable, because it is
essentially repeating conventional wisdom,'' O'Hanlon said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, other Republican presidential hopefuls also have
charged that the U.S. military has deteriorated under Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona, a prisoner of War during the
Vietnam war, and Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah have accused the
administration of allowing military equipment and weapons to age,
while troops have been overextended in peacekeeping missions around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, who is seeking the Democratic nomination
to succeed Clinton, has called for quality-of-life initiatives to
boost morale, such as increased pay, better housing and better
training.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is expected to sign defense legislation this year that
would give members of the armed services a 4.8 percent pay raise.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, while endorsing the pay increase, also is seeking a boost
in benefits for the nation's veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing we do for our veterans after the battle will matter if
we don't back them up while they're in the trenches and on the
front lines, fighting for us,'' Gore told the 81st annual American
Legion National Convention in Anaheim, Calif., earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Bush postponed his defense speech last week when Hurricane Floyd
threatened the East Coast, and rescheduled it at the Citadel. South
Carolina is an early primary state that could be key to earning the
party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he is going to be talking about is the future of the
military. And who better to give the speech to than the future of
the military?'' Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, Texas first lady Laura Bush is scheduled to be in
San Antonio to address the Texas Association of Broadcasters on
early childhood reading initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   She will then attend a fund-raiser with San Antonio businessmen
that is expected to raise $125,000 for her husband's presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has raised $52 million, becoming the first presidential
hopeful to pass the $50 million barrier. President Clinton and
Republican nominee Bob Dole raised roughly $45 million each in
1996, amounts that eclipsed earlier campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor has said he will not accept federal matching
funds, a move that will allow him to spend as much as he can raise
before the GOP primaries next year.
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential hopeful Steve Forbes also has agreed not
to accept matching funds from the government.
</P>
</TEXT>
