<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WEST WING': A POWERFUL WORKPLACE DRAMA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early on in ``The West Wing,'' the camera follows Chief of Staff
Leo McGarry like a lovesick lap dog, zooming down long corridors
and short hallways, zipping around sharp corners, popping in and
out of offices, slipping in and out of doorways, maneuvering,
navigating, weaving and dodging personnel moving at the same speed
but in the opposite direction.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, McGarry (John Spencer) is talking to everyone and
everyone is talking to McGarry, and the pace is so frantic and
maddening and chaotic that you wonder: How could government work so
much in sync yet achieve so little?
</P>
<P>
   The Aaron Sorkin drama is like that. It's the workplace that
never rests, or sleeps, or shuts up. ``Sports Night,'' which Sorkin
created and writes, often goes at the same
get-out-of-the-blocks-fast pace, offers the same witty, rapid-fire
dialogue, and presents the same kind of characters, so committed
that they need to be committed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to hear talk like that in this office,'' the
president's secretary barks to McGarry, who, while sprinting
through the Oval Office, has just called the commander in chief a
``geek'' for riding his bike into a large tree and injuring an
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   In concept, ``The West Wing'' _ one of the most widely discussed
series of the new TV season because of its pedigree, its political
subject matter and co-star Rob Lowe _ owes its existence to ``The
American President,'' the sentimental feature film that Sorkin also
penned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The West Wing'' is what ``The American President'' would have
been had it focused less on Michael Douglas as the prez and more on
bouncy speech writer Michael J. Fox and his crew of image makers.
</P>
<P>
   Here, they are represented by a fine batch of actors, but we'll
get to them later. First, Lowe, the self-proclaimed ``political
junkie'' whose only connection to politics is voting and that
three-way tryst videotaped while he attended the 1988 Democratic
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe plays deputy communications director and beleaguered speech
writer Sam Seaborn. We first meet him in a bar trying to avoid a
reporter and get the attention of a woman eyeing him from across
the way. Yeah. Sex still follows this guy like a bad penny.
</P>
<P>
   Flash forward. Lowe is gathering his clothes from the woman's
apartment. A few moments later, he learns that she's a law student
and part-time bartender and call girl.
</P>
<P>
   If you think Sam is having a rough day, consider Deputy Chief of
Staff Josh Lyman, played by Bradley Whitford. He has mouthed off to
an extremist leader from the Christian right on a TV news show and
could be fired. We don't learn his fate until the episode's end,
when the president (Martin Sheen) hobbles in to address the troops.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Josh is also a former beau of political consultant
Madeline Hampton (Moira Kelly), the new troubleshooter now working
for _ and sleeping with _ the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Schiff is the hustling Toby Ziegler, a gruff
communications head whom we meet on an airplane, as he is
condescending to a flight attendant who orders him to shut down his
laptop and cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The West Wing'' kicks off as all the staff members get beeped
about the president's terrible bicycling skills. C.J. Gregg
(Allison Janney) gets her message while on a treadmill, trying to
hit on the sweaty cutie one treadmill over. That she ends up flying
off the thing while trying to check the beeper is a hit-and-run
demonstration that a single professional woman just can't get a
break.
</P>
<P>
   Sheen rounds out what I think is the most gifted cast of the new
television season. His president is a folksy populist, a shrewd
political strategist who is blunt and honest. He seems to have a
thing for spewing lengthy anecdotes while everyone around him
patiently listens.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope he keeps this to a minimum. This is the same
speechifying we get from ``Sports Night'' _ as if a cable sports
program is saving the world from evil.
</P>
<P>
   Here, at least, Sorkin can set up those kinds of scenarios:
Problems on Thursday's episode involve Cubans trying to defect to
the United States on tiny rafts, and that visit by a group of
radical Christians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The West Wing'' pilot is as sleek as television gets, a
well-written, well-executed piece of work that looks even better
because it doesn't look like most of the shows we consume.
</P>
<P>
   I can't detect any problems so far, unless the politically
active Sheen has a bone to pick with a Sorkin script and shuts down
the set with a sit-in.
</P>
<P>
   But I figure Sorkin would merely find a way to write that into
the script as well.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
