u a BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      09-22 0418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Sept. 23, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   The first day of autumn will bring a warming trend to the
Northeast. A freshening wind from the southwest will direct
unseasonably warm air from the middle of the nation toward the
Atlantic Seaboard. Sunshine will prevail near the coast, but
patches of clouds will arrive across the interior Northeast. An
elongated high-pressure system, stretching from the Carolinas to
Texas will promote bright and dry conditions over most of the
South. After a very cool morning in the northern Gulf states,
readings will rise to seasonal levels by afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and patches of showers will cover Florida as a front
remains over southern sections. The return flow of humid air around
high pressure over Texas will draw moisture into the Rio Grande
Valley. A weak disturbance over the southern Rockies will be
infused with the moistened air leading to more widespread clouds
and afternoon thundershowers from New Mexico to Nevada. Low
pressure aloft off the California coast will invite some clouds and
showers into central sections of the state.
</P>
<P>
   A surge of slightly cooler air into the upper Great Lakes will
be preceded by gusty winds and scattered showers. The cold front
marking the edge of the new cool air mass will push across the
Midwest with increasing clouds, but most sections will stay dry.
</P>
<P>
   Warm weather will dominate the interior West with sunshine in
the northern Rockies and inland Northwest. A cold front approaching
western Washington will cause clouds and onshore winds. Northern
California will be brighter, though afternoon showers should
develop over the Sierra.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Autumn Begins
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of fall at precisely 7:31 p.m. EDT Thursday means
little meteorologically. During the next several weeks, however, as
solar rays become less direct in the Northern Hemisphere, the
weather will surely respond. The sun does not heat the atmosphere
directly since the envelope of air is mainly transparent to its
high-energy radiation. The earth absorbs much of the sun's energy.
Lower energy radiation from the ground then heats the atmosphere
from below. In the weeks ahead, the diminishing solar energy at the
ground will lead inevitably to a chilling of the atmosphere above.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 1748EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0274 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2045 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-CHRIS-GAINES-ALBUM-$A     09-22 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRIS-GAINES-ALBUM-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARTH BROOKS PLAYS THE ROCKER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 26) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a music critic, the truest measure of an album's worth often
comes after the review. While writing about a record, one is
required to listen to it over and over until each song is etched
into memory.
</P>
<P>
   But afterward, be the review positive or negative, free will
takes over, and the best sign of an album's merit is how many times
the critic _ with hundreds of CDs arriving in the mail weekly _
listens to it again, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   The R.E.M. album ``Monster,'' for example, feels over-rated in
retrospect because the desire to listen to it has disappeared,
while the Neil Young album ``Ragged Glory'' deserves all the praise
it received because it survives prominently on the listening pile.
</P>
<P>
   Already it is apparent that ``Garth Brooks in ... The Life of
Chris Gaines'' (Capitol 7243-5-20051-2-3), an apochryphal greatest
hits album recorded by the country star Brooks under the pseudonym
of the rock star Gaines, is a good album that I will probably never
listen to again.
</P>
<P>
   It is like a movie one relishes while watching but completely
forgets afterward. At best, there are a few songs _ the psychedelic
pop ballad ``Maybe,'' the more traditionally Garth ``It Don't
Matter to the Sun'' _ worth putting on mix tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Conceptually, however, Brooks deserves a pat on the hat for the
undertaking. Detractors accuse him of using the pseudonym because
he is too chicken to risk failure with a rock album under his own
name. Others say it is part of Brooks' attempt to rule the
entertainment world, to sell more albums than the Beatles (the only
act that has outsold him, according to the Recording Industry
Association of America).
</P>
<P>
   But Brooks claims that the collection was released solely to
create anticipation for and familiarity with a character in a movie
he is starring in and helping to produce, ``The Lamb,'' which looks
back on the life and mysterious death of Chris Gaines, a fictitious
rock icon who found success first as a member of an '80s
one-hit-wonder band called Crush and later as a Grammy-winning solo
artist.
</P>
<P>
   The album is billed as a ``pre-soundtrack'' for the film, a
movie for which a not single frame has been shot. Brooks, who often
refers to himself in the third person as if Garth Brooks is just
another character, a middle American Everyman, has already
committed to releasing one more Gaines album, the actual soundtrack
to ``The Lamb''; if these albums are successful, he might record
the five albums that supposedly predate the greatest hits package.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it is a testament to cowardice, marketing or
megalomania, ``Chris Gaines'' is a gutsy undertaking, not only as
an attempt by an outsider to fit into another genre but also as a
greatest hits album that tries to fit into each phase of that
genre's recent history.
</P>
<P>
   Gaines may be a pseudonym _ complete with an elaborate invented
background that incorporates bits of Dylan, Beatles and Prince lore
and parallels elements of Brooks' life (the solo careers of both
begin in 1989, and both have the same number of letters in their
first and last names).
</P>
<P>
   But Chris Gaines is very much Garth Brooks, who has described
himself as a melting pot of the past. Chris Gaines represents a few
of the ingredients in that pot: James Taylor, the Eagles, the
Beatles, Boston and Aerosmith (whose ``Fever'' Brooks has covered).
</P>
<P>
   The overall impression of ``Chris Gaines'' as an album with no
aftertaste is partly the result of the concept, an exercise in
image alteration, vocal manipulation and imagination. The overly
slick songs are as much bought as they are sung; they're the sound
of one man rich enough to purchase his own rock album to sing on.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Brooks manages to sound nothing like himself
about half the time, smoothing out his country crack and twang for
a pop falsetto, a driving rock rasp and a surprising amount of
rhythm-and-blues balladeering. But on songs like the cheesy
synthesizer-rocker ``Way of the Girl,'' one can hear the gulf
between the vocalist and the material, which is so empty of meaning
that it would be hard for anyone to sing it with feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Likable but not spectacular, ``Chris Gaines'' is in keeping with
much of the work of its producer, Don Was, who is responsible for
many albums by rock stars that are released with great fanfare but
don't have staying power; among them are Brian Wilson's ``I Just
Wasn't Made for These Times,'' the Rolling Stones' ``Voodoo
Lounge,'' Iggy Pop's ``Brick by Brick,'' Bob Dylan's ``Under the
Red Sky'' and the ``Backbeat'' soundtrack, a not entirely
dissimilar exercise in which alternative rock musicians pretended
to be the Beatles during their Hamburg days.
</P>
<P>
   Musically, Brooks combines '60s melodies with '80s production
for most of the album. He rips off Dylan's ``Knockin' on Heaven's
Door'' for the verses of ``Main Street,'' mixes deadpan rapping and
the Youngbloods' ``Get Together'' for ``Right Now,'' and
incorporates the opening of the Beatles' ``Lucy in the Sky With
Diamonds'' in ``Maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   As in Brooks' country music, the influence of macho '80s rock is
everywhere: the photographs of fake album covers in the CD booklet
carry images of a straitjacketed Gaines flanked by nurses in garter
belts and Gaines with hands folded contemplatively over the chest
of a woman in a hot pink brassiere.
</P>
<P>
   Another major influence is Babyface, the rhythm-and-blues
songwriter, singer and producer whose song for the Tony Rich
Project, ``Nobody Knows,'' became a No. 1 country hit when it was
performed by Kevin Sharp and seems to be an inspiration for the
acoustic-guitar soul on this album.
</P>
<P>
   Babyface, in fact, is also a producer of ``The Lamb''; in
addition, the Nashville songwriting team that wrote most of the
album _ Gordon Kennedy, Wayne Kirkpatrick and Tommy Simms _ are
best known for the Eric Clapton and Babyface collaboration ``Change
the World.'' The first single of theirs from the Brooks album,
``Lost in You,'' previously appeared on an album by Ricky Jones, an
r-and-b singer who has worked with Babyface.
</P>
<P>
   But let's take Chris Gaines at face value and pretend that this
is an actual greatest hits album (recorded in reverse chronological
order with two new songs) by a Grammy-winning rocker with a career
spanning from 1986 to the present.
</P>
<P>
   What do we think of Gaines? He has spent too much of his career
being overproduced, he has let the same people write most of his
material, he seems to change a lot without actually evolving, his
voice is nice but his work lacks consistency and vision, and while
his music isn't disposable, it isn't valuable, either. In other
words, he's a good puppet in the hands of Brooks, an ambitious and
agile but limited puppeteer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 1750EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
