<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING BOOKS: WHEN SECRECY MEANS PUBLICITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the seemingly immutable axioms of book publishing is that
the purveyors of new books try noisily and at times shamelessly to
get as much advance, prepublication publicity as conceivable for
their product. But every season there are a handful of titles for
which there is the opposite impulse, with publishers just as
aggressively trying to suppress any early word of a book's
contents. These choice titles are embargoed. In this fall season,
less than one month old, there have already been four interesting
examples.
</P>
<P>
   The books were ``The Sword and the Shield'' (Basic Books), a
secret history of the KGB by Christopher Andrew and Vasili
Mitrokhin; ``Hitler's Pope: The Secret History of Pius XII''
(Viking) by John Cornwell; ``Dutch: A Memoir of Ronald Reagan''
(Random House) by Edmund Morris; and ``Stiffed: The Betrayal of the
American Man'' (William Morrow) by Susan Faludi.
</P>
<P>
   Generally books are embargoed because the publisher has sold an
excerpt to a magazine or made a deal with a television news
magazine program for first-use rights (called first serial rights).
But there are other reasons for secrecy. For instance, if the book
is alleged to contain news, or the mere fact of its publication is
news, then by releasing it to stores and reviewers on the same day,
a lucky publisher can orchestrate a tremendous burst of publicity,
and, hopefully, sales. (An example of this was ``Hannibal''
(Delacorte Press), Thomas Harris' sequel to ``The Silence of the
Lambs.'' It went on sale this summer but was so anxiously awaited
by readers and bookstore owners that the mere acknowledgment of its
existence produced a crescendo of book-selling publicity.)
</P>
<P>
   Of course, sometimes a book is potentially so controversial or
it is such a lemon (or both) that the publisher wants to give it
some shelf time in the stores before it is buried in a wash of bad
reviews or mocking news stories.
</P>
<P>
   There are two ways to attempt to enforce an embargo. First,
there is the confidentiality agreement. To receive a copy of the
book the recipients, usually reviewers, have to agree to look and
read but not tell until a mutually decided-upon day. That is the
most common method, and it keeps the book's secrets, yet allows
book reviewers time to read and digest it. The other way is for the
publisher simply to keep all the copies out of sight, hidden until
they are shipped, timed to arrive on the reviewers' desks and in
the bookstores on the same day. Sometimes, although certainly not
always, the secret can be kept. But publishers admit there is
nothing more deleterious to the peace and sublimity of a publishing
house than the dreaded decision to embargo a book and the worry
that the embargo will be broken.
</P>
<P>
   The embargo was placed on the KGB book, which was based on a
secret archive, because its American publisher, Basic Books, had a
contract with the original publisher, Penguin UK, to issue it
simultaneously so that the publisher on one side of the Atlantic
would not be scooped on the other side. But, alas, ABC News
independently learned about the existence of the archive, if not
its contents, and broke the story nearly a week before the book's
scheduled publication, and this led to newspaper headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Jack McKeown, president and chief executive of the Perseus Books
Group, of which Basic Books is an imprint, said: ``Frankly, in
retrospect, I don't think we were hurt. It turned out we were
better off. Hurricane Floyd would have buried us, and we wouldn't
have gotten a great amount of news coverage.'' The book had a first
printing of 80,000, but there are now 105,000 copies in print in
the United States, and the book will be No. 7 on The New York
Times' nonfiction best-seller list on Oct. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Faludi's book, ``Stiffed,'' was embargoed because Newsweek
had bought first serial rights. Lynn Goldberg, the publicist for
``Stiffed,'' said that the magazine had a two-week window to
publish it first, either on Sept. 6 or Sept. 13, plus the right to
have it on the newsstand for a whole week before the book went on
sale. ``So we had it embargoed until Sept. 21,'' she said, ``but
Newsweek ran it on Sept. 6. An embargo is not only hard to put in
place, but it's also hard to dismantle, so we kept the publication
date at Sept. 21,'' but, of course, as soon as the magazine was
out, those who wanted to broke the embargo.
</P>
<P>
   The book about Pius XII was embargoed because the publisher had
sold first rights to Vanity Fair magazine, which published an
excerpt in its September issue.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the book embargo that will have the most notoriety was
the one on the Reagan memoir. Random House refuses to discuss the
book until its publication date, Sept. 30. It was embargoed mainly
for the usual reason: Random House had sold the first serial rights
to Newsweek, and, obviously, if the book's content became known
before the magazine was in readers' hands, the bang of exclusivity
that Newsweek paid for would be lost. But there was another reason
the book's contents were guarded with such ardor. The writer,
Edmund Morris, placed himself in the book as a fictional Zelig-like
narrator who first met the future president on Reagan's high school
football field, which was long before the real Morris was born.
</P>
<P>
   So in this case the main reason for the embargo was that the
contract with Newsweek mandated one, but there was also the desire
to get the book into the stores with some momentum before reviewers
could decipher what was history and what could well have been
borrowed from Woody Allen.
</P>
<P>
   The book embargo has a relatively short but nonetheless
illustrious history. In 1979, The Nation magazine printed an
article based on a pirated copy of President Gerald R. Ford's
then-unpublished memoir, ``A Time to Heal'' (Harper &AMP; Row and the
Reader's Digest Association), which had sold first serial rights to
Time magazine. An appeals court eventually upheld The Nation's
right to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   But the first book that anyone remembers being embargoed was
``All the President's Men'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster), the seminal 1974
Watergate book by Bob Woodward and Carl Bernstein. How vigilant
does a publisher have to be to keep an embargo? Well, in that case,
according to someone associated with that publication, a man
purporting to be a reporter for one news organization was caught
climbing over the wire fence surrounding the warehouse where the
book's copies were stashed away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
