<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2057 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-     09-22 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOICES IN PRESSURE-TREATED LUMBER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wood in contact with the soil will eventually rot. Builders try
to prevent this by supporting framing members of a house, porch or
deck on masonry footings or a concrete foundation. Even with these
precautions it is possible for wood to rot if it gets wet enough
and if the temperature rises above the freezing mark.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that colonial homeowners were less troubled with wood
rot than we are today. It may have something to do with the fact
that the early settlers built their homes from timber cut from
first-growth trees _ trees that had been standing in the forest for
a century or more. The lumber from these naturally aged trees had a
dense cell structure that resisted water and rot.
</P>
<P>
   Other historians point out that colonial homebuilders took the
time to season wood before using it in a structure. The most common
method was a ''water-cure'' process in which the newly cut wood was
submerged in water, ideally a stream with moving water, for about
two weeks. The boards were then removed and allowed to dry in the
hot sun for a couple of months.
</P>
<P>
   Many builders are aware that certain woods _ cedar, redwood and
cypress _ have a natural resistance to rot and insect damage.
Builders favor these woods in areas where moisture and warm
temperatures make wood rot and insect damage a serious problem. Yet
these woods are expensive primarily because they come from
slow-growing trees and are in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to make wood resistant to rot and insects, timber
suppliers have tried to treat boards with various chemicals. The
first chemical to be used was ordinary salt. It was sometimes added
to the water in the water-cure method and the boards were allowed
to soak and absorb the salt.
</P>
<P>
   In 1831, creosote a thin, tar-like fluid obtained from the
distillation of coal tar, was patented. At first it was simply
brushed onto the surface of the wood. Later, a pressure-treatment
method was developed where the lumber was immersed in the liquid
under pressure in containers. Pressure treatment forces the
chemical deep into the fibers of wood to make the board almost
invincible to the attacks of rot, fungi or insects.
</P>
<P>
   Though creosote is an effective deterrent, it has serious
drawbacks: it is flammable and boards treated with creosote cannot
be painted. Even more important, creosote has been determined to be
a health hazard. Today it is only used for industrial applications,
like in railroad ties, trestles and pilings.
</P>
<P>
   Lumber companies and the building trades looked for other
chemicals to replace creosote in pressure-treated lumber. One
option that was developed e was chromated copper arsenate, which is
accounts for about 20 percent of treated lumber sales.
</P>
<P>
   Another chemical that is used to make pressure-treated wood is
ammoniacal copper zinc arsenate.
</P>
<P>
   These compounds contain chromium, arsenic and copper _ all
toxic. They have to be toxic to kill insects and fungus, but many
people want to know if the treated lumber is safe to use around the
home.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Environmental Protection Agency maintains that,
according to their test results, the chemicals in pressure-treated
lumber remain fixed within the wood fibers and only small amounts
leak out. Still they caution that this wood cannot be used for
kitchen countertops, cutting boards or for food storage.
</P>
<P>
   Some environmental groups feel that the Environmental Protection
Agency tests are not accurate enough. These groups have conducted
independent tests, reaching the conclusion that significant amounts
of chemicals can leech out from pressure-treated wood and
contaminate surrounding soil. For this reason, they caution
homeowners from using this lumber around vegetable gardens. In
addition, other safety authorities feel that is not advisable to
walk barefooted on decks made with pressure-treated lumber.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, manufacturers introduced another chemical, alkaline
copper quat, which they claim is less toxic; but even wood treated
with that chemical includes a number of safety precautions. Some
builders maintain that wood treated with alkaline copper quat is
less rot- and insect-resistant than traditional pressure-treated
lumber.
</P>
<P>
   Guidelines for buying and working with pressure-treated lumber
will be discussed next week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
