<HEADER>
A2059 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-NY-TOWNHOUSE-1040(2TA     09-22 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TOWNHOUSE-1040(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRONFMANS TAME A TOWN HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Greetings exchanged at the door with a private
security guard ricochet off the towering walls. A woman's heels
scrape stone as she trots up two flights. An alarm is briefly
triggered. It is move-in day, and the host, Clarissa Alcock
Bronfman, sweeps into the living room to greet her first visitor in
the lean, modern house she and her husband, Edgar Bronfman Jr., the
chief executive of Seagram Co., have just built for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The landmarked facade of their East Side town house has a
neoclassical restraint Edith Wharton would have loved. But step
inside, and you forget the past: Where wood once reigned, the
vestibule is now paneled in waxed sheets of steel in a shade of
warm bronze. Two steps up, a steel and glass door swings open to a
sun-filled two-and-a-half-story atrium court, replacing a
decorator-done parlor and as foreign to a hard-core Manhattanite as
Oz was to Dorothy.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a loft, the fashion these days for nearly all
residential renovations. Nor is it a typical town house, dark and
cloistered. The piazza contains a striking skylight and little
else: there are broad limestone steps flanked by two wide ledges
holding a larger-than-life-size Nigerian fertility statue and an
artist's carved spheres of polished roots.
</P>
<P>
   The living room is almost as spare, dominated by a Corbusier
chaise beneath a monumental Roberto Matta painting. ``I don't want
any more things in here _ I want it to be about the architecture,''
Ms. Bronfman, 33, said, adding with a sporting sense of challenge,
``I'll just figure out another way to make it more intimate.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how easy it will be to feel at home under the eyes of a
private guard and a house manager who materializes with a cell
phone clipped to his belt (the millennium edition of the bygone
butler and the bell cord) is still unresolved. But Ms. Bronfman is
trying. When the major-domo proffered bottled water, she uncapped
it and swigged. Their architect, Peter Rose, had done his part: at
the urging of Ms. Bronfman, who is Venezuelan, he removed the core
of the house to create a courtyard ``piazza'' that echoes the
leisurely comings and goings of Mediterranean life. ``Give me a
court in the middle, in honor of my Latin upbringing,'' she had
said. ``Light means happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   For Rose, it was a chance to break out of the stuffy hierarchy
of a grandiose parlor floor and a layout in which family members
are removed from one another's view. ``The model of the town house,
for all its aspirations, is uncomfortable,'' said Rose, 56, who
tries to capture the magic of moving through unhindered spaces with
constantly changing viewpoints. ``I never loved the stacked sixplex
with its grand stair going up to something not very important. I
wanted to create options and a momentum so that all the power isn't
turned over to a living room that isn't used much.''
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate this scrutiny-shy couple with three children who
wanted an absolute division between public and private realms, Rose
conceived a plan with the complexity of a Chinese puzzle. The lower
three public rooms _ dining room, then living room and library _
lead off the soaring sky-lighted atrium court. And each room has a
view of another across the court, and of the street or garden
beyond. The library, which has an interior window and a balcony, is
meant to be a pivotal in-between space where the family can spend
time with close friends.
</P>
<P>
   The skylight actually works as a kind of false ceiling. Visitors
would hardly suspect that there are two-and-a-half stories of
bedrooms above, reached only if you know which white panel is a
secret door to a network of back stairs and hallways.
</P>
<P>
   The rooms above the skylight feel secluded as well as airy
because the architect arranged them around a second courtyard open
to the air. The children's playroom has a small terrace; the master
bedroom has an inward-facing balcony.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Bronfman Jr.'s family has a reputation for bold
architectural one-upmanship. It was his aunt, Phyllis Lambert, who
commissioned Mies van der Rohe to design the Seagram Building in
1958, the paragon of a modern office tower. So why not reinvent the
town house, too?
</P>
<P>
   The rooms are surprisingly small for a house pushing upward of
15,000 square feet _ who ever heard of a master bedroom on the
Upper East Side too small for anything but a bed, a fireplace and a
bookcase? ``I'd be happy if there was only a bed,'' Bronfman said
graciously (his wife happened to design theirs, a curvaceous wenge
wood platform).
</P>
<P>
   As one moves about the house, getting there is half the fun _
and the challenge. On the first of three landings, doors give way
into the narrow dining room and backyard beyond, with four linden
trees (a Weber barbecue parked beneath one) to block the neighbors'
view.
</P>
<P>
   The stairs continue climbing the wall, like a vine, to the
average-size living room. On the last flight, to the library, the
steps become narrower, with a four-inch gap between the tread and
the wall. It could almost be a goat path in the Italian Alps.
Bronfman loves the look; his wife worries about the safety of their
three small children, but the architect recently added a plastic
safety guard. (Attaching bungee cords to the children could work as
well.)
</P>
<P>
   The courtyard feels something like a minimalist opera set for
``Cavalleria Rusticana.'' But the placement of these small rooms,
all on different levels, dispels the theatrics of the large central
space. Rose is known for his artisan's love of solid building
materials, craftsmanship and old-fashioned building methods: He was
the architect of the Canadian Center for Architecture, a museum in
Montreal founded by Ms. Lambert. She put her nephew in touch with
Rose after Bronfman admired the museum's logic and elegance. ``With
Peter, there's so much care about detailing and a sense of space,''
Ms. Lambert said. ``You always know where you are and where you're
going.'' She had expected her nephew to go for a more conservative
choice, she told Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, she said more recently: ``Edgar does come from the
Seagram Building _ it's part of his life. And Clarissa's there
pushing him towards modernism, too.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bronfman, whose uncle is a prominent architect in Caracas,
remembered how shocked she was to discover, while the pair were
dating six years ago, that her future husband's office in the
Seagram Building was decorated with English antiques. (She insisted
that he remodel it in a more contemporary style.) When they
contemplated living in a modern town house, Ms. Bronfman said, ``At
first, all Edgar wanted to know was, `Where's the molding, where's
the chair rail?'''
</P>
<P>
   The project took an excruciating four years, during which
Bronfman was re-focusing Seagram's from a liquor maker into an
entertainment giant, with the purchase of Universal Studios and
Polygram, to reflect his own love of show business.
</P>
<P>
   As the uncertain fortunes of Universal kept the family on the
verge of moving to California, Bronfman apparently underwent a
design conversion. By the end, he was requesting a steel wall in
the vestibule and a powder room sink of wenge. ``I told Peter two
things,'' Bronfman said. ``It had to be anti-artifice, no faux
anything. And it had to be noble, not grand, but something that
speaks for itself eloquently and quietly.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose admitted that he never exactly understood what
``anti-artifice'' really meant. ``But I know I've responded to
it,'' he said, in the voice of someone well-acquainted with the
demands of powerful businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   The details, executed with exacting authenticity, range from the
load-bearing walls (16 inches at the base tapering to 12 inches at
top) to leather-topped slide-out ledges in the library bookcase.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bronfman is interested in the details, too, especially the
practical ones. ``To architects, it's always all about esthetics,''
she said of her battles with Rose over everyday amenities like
broom closets on every floor (``I don't want to see any mop buckets
in the elevator.''); a place for clotheslines (How about those
bedroom balconies?); drains in the bathroom floor so her children
can splash at bathtime, and a pantry with bulk capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Venezuela, you never knew from day to day what the
political situation was going to be,'' Ms. Bronfman said, ``so you
always bought in bulk.''
</P>
<P>
   And she is determined to counteract the house's formidable
tendencies. ``I never want it to be so neat and perfect that there
can't be Legos in the library or a stroller at the front,'' Ms.
Bronfman said.
</P>
<P>
   She admits to some initial angst about doing a contemporary
house. ``So many end up with a cold feeling,'' she said, adding
optimistically, ``But being a Latino, there are always going to be
a lot of people coming and going without announcing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always going to be something happening,'' she said.
``That is going to be the life of our home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
