<HEADER>
A2065 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BRIGGS-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     09-22 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIGGS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ETHEL &AMP; ERNEST': MUM, DAD AND NOT ALWAYS SO MERRY OLD ENGLAND
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Publication notes at end of article.) 
(nk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   So at last we meet the models for the amusing working-class
characters in Raymond Briggs' inimitable comic-strip books for
children and adults, ``Father Christmas'' and ``Father Christmas
Goes on Holiday,'' among others, and even the terrifying ``When the
Wind Blows'' (1982), about an English couple living and dying in
the wake of a nuclear holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   These models are Ethel and Ernest Briggs, the artist's parents,
and while they don't experience an atom-bomb attack in ``Ethel &AMP;
Ernest: A True Story,'' they suffer all the other vicissitudes of
civilization from the late 1920s until their death in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   In sequences of expressive cartoon panels punctuated with
frequent vaudeville-like word-balloon exchanges, the two of them
meet in London in 1928, fall in love and decide to marry.
</P>
<P>
   She ends her employment as a parlormaid:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like leaving them,'' she tells Ernest. ``They're so
helpless.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Serve em right,'' he responds. ``Bloated plutocrats!''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no need to swear, Ernest.''
</P>
<P>
   He keeps working as a milkman:
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think you'll ever be promoted?'' she asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``No bloomin' fear! Not me! Yard foreman? Stuck in a tin shed
all day, adding up rows of figures? Blow that for a lark. I like
the fresh air.''
</P>
<P>
   They buy and furnish a house, bear and rear a son, survive the
Depression and World War II, adjust to the advent of the nuclear
age, the Cold War and the welfare state and cope with technological
change and the waywardness of their artistic son:
</P>
<P>
   ``Art school! Oh, blimey,'' says Ernest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a shame,'' responds Ethel. ``He might have gone to
Oxford and Cambridge and got a nice job in an office.''
</P>
<P>
   In time they get used to their son's ways, although Ethel can
never give up offering him a comb for his long hair or accept that
because of his wife's emotional illness, she will never make her a
granny. At the end, Ethel and Ernest grow old and die.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary existences lived countless times. Yet in the details of
Briggs' sparkling cartoons, the characters become richly specific
and endearing. For instance, the couple's dumbstruck reaction to
their first glimpses of each other is caught in the near-wordless
opening 35 panels, where she cleans house and catches sight of him
bicycling by: She waves at him with her dust rag; he doffs his cap
and grins jauntily. They quickly come to count on their greetings
and grow disconsolate when by chance they miss seeing each other.
</P>
<P>
   So you expect Ethel to be overwhelmed when Ernest shows up at
the front door on Saturday asking her, ``How about coming to the
pictures with me?'' But impishly, Briggs makes her more impressed
by the bouquet he is carrying than by his invitation, although of
course she happily goes with him.
</P>
<P>
   This subtly establishes how much more important to her are the
outward signs and symbols of behavior than their inner meaning, an
attitude later comically reflected when Ernest, reading the
newspaper, remarks: ``At last! Churchill's taken over: `Blood,
toil, tears and sweat.''' And she, bearing cookies from the oven,
responds: ``ERNEST! Don't! Disgusting.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet she can appear almost noble in her devotion to proper
appearances, especially in a scene in which on a blustery day she
puts out newly washed sheets on the clothesline and looks for all
the world like a graceful yachtsman unfurling a spinnaker.
</P>
<P>
   The effect is similar to ``When the Wind Blows,'' with the
characters appearing both pathetic and heroic in the face of
overwhelming events. Come war or reduced rations or the
``tele-vision,'' they carry on, Ernest hoping for the best from
Labor, Ethel with her faith in Churchill.
</P>
<P>
   He: ``We'll own all the coal soon. They're going to nationalize
it.''
</P>
<P>
   She: ``I bet we still have to pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   He: ``Well, course we'll have to PAY for it, you daft
ha'porth!''
</P>
<P>
   She: ``So we won't OWN it, then, will we?''
</P>
<P>
   He: ``Well, um ... not exactly ... but it means the profits will
go to the government instead of lining the pockets of the bosses!''
</P>
<P>
   She: ``And then the government gives the money to us?''
</P>
<P>
   He: ``NO!''
</P>
<P>
   She: ``So what's the difference then?''
</P>
<P>
   But finally the details of the illustrations are what make you
read through ``Ethel &AMP; Ernest'' over again. For instance, there's a
cat that shows up first when the couple are exclaiming over the
garden they've acquired with their house. As they get older and
settle into their routines, the cat shows up more often, lying on
their bed or sitting in front of the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after Ethel dies, the cat acquires the name Susie and
becomes Ernest's substitute companion, even curling up next to him
at night and lying across his shoulders as he eats. In the last
three panels of Ernest's life, the cat can be seen leaping away
from him as he rises from the table with some sort of chest or
stomach attack, then pressing on the kitchen door to get out as
Ernest retches over the kitchen sink and finally, months later,
walking out into the spring garden as Ernest collapses to the
floor. Not cruel, this shadowy animal, but as seemingly indifferent
to the passing of a brave but insignificant life as is the great
wide world.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ETHEL &AMP; ERNEST: A TRUE STORY'
</P>
<P>
   By Raymond Briggs
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 103 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $21.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
