<SLUG> BC-FURNITURE-LEATHER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEW CAN BEEF ABOUT TODAY'S LEATHER-BOUND FURNITURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN PHINNEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cows are moooving into homes across America. Most are arriving
five hides at a time, stretched across sofas that lounge in family
rooms, dens and living rooms.
</P>
<P>
   At Seattle-based Bon Marche stores, leather-upholstered pieces
are 45 percent of their furniture business, up from about 17
percent in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Shop for leather furniture today and the reasons for this surge
are obvious. These leathers are so soft and supple it's hard to
believe they're related to the cold, hard leather chairs and sofas
once found sagging around fraternity houses and waiting rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Today's leathers also come in styles ranging from contemporary
and transitional to traditional. Shoppers can pick colors ranging
from coral to plum along with the blacks, beiges and dark greens
that seem to dominate furniture showrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these new leathers even come with pedigrees. Fashion
designer Ralph Lauren has put his label on leathers for the home.
Coach, a name synonymous with durable handbags, launched a leather
line earlier this year with Baker Furniture _ a well-known United
States maker and distributor of fine furniture.
</P>
<P>
   John Black, vice president of design and development for Baker,
says Coach wanted furniture as classic as its handbags. ``It's
leather from an American point of view, scaled to the American
home,'' Black says.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Hatfield, divisional vice president of furniture for The
Bon, says his company decided in the early 1990s to offer better
quality and more styles of leather to customers. For years leather
had been associated with contemporary decor.
</P>
<P>
   Aggressive retailers, prices under $1,000, more styles and
dramatically improved leather quality have made this furniture even
more appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Add wearability and versatility into the mix and it becomes
``must have'' for more and more shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Baron, the U.S. executive for Natuzzi leathers of Italy,
says leather sales escalated in the 1980s when Macy's department
store and Natuzzi came up with a leather sofa to retail for $999.
``That was the shot heard 'round the world,'' Baron says.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 10 years, leather has become just another all
natural upholstery option, like wool, cotton or linen.
</P>
<P>
   According to research by Ikea, a leather sofa can last about
four times longer than an upholstered piece. But shoppers need to
consider how it's going to be used. Subject even the hardiest
leather sofa to climbing toddlers, large dogs and constant use and
it's not going to last forever.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Morrissey, furniture manager for Ikea, says sales of
leather furniture are up about 30 percent over last year. Her store
focuses on three grades:
</P>
<P>
   _Entry-grade leather that's treated to make it stronger, and may
have a pattern embossed on the hide.
</P>
<P>
   _An intermediate-grade that is more supple and feels and smells
like leather.
</P>
<P>
   _And Ikea's top of the line _ untreated buffalo leather with a
very natural look.
</P>
<P>
   According to Hatfield, the most luxurious and expensive hides
tend to be fully dyed analine leathers _ hides that have been
vat-dyed after tanning, so that color permeates the skin. That
means a scratch is less likely to be noticeable.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the selection of hides that makes the most visible
difference in a piece of furniture. Some are thicker than others.
Some hides have scars from insect bites or cuts. A hides buyer has
to be selective, Hatfield says. And when it takes about five hides
to make a sofa, it's important that they're very similar.
</P>
<P>
   Leather furniture made from cattle hides is a booming business _
jumping from $2.9 billion in U.S. retail sales in 1996 to about
$3.7 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Myers, president of Leather Industries of America, says
leather furniture is a rapidly growing market worldwide. U.S.
demand is so great that foreign companies are setting up factories
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leather upholstery has taken off like Boeing,'' he says from
his Washington, D.C., office.
</P>
<P>
   Myers says he has a favorite leather sofa, one that's only
gotten better with age. He's told his family he wants to be
shrink-wrapped with the sofa and buried in it.
</P>
<P>
   Leather furniture shouldn't be an impulse buy. It's a major
investment that lasts a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for a standard three-seat sofa range from $899 to about
$8,000 for a top-of-the-line model with a designer label. In
between are quality leather sofas made with hides from Italy for
about $2,499.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike fabric, however, which comes with tags announcing fiber
content, leather has a different vocabulary: Analine dyed, suede,
nubuck, embossed (that means the pattern is imprinted on the hide)
_ to mention a few terms frequently seen and heard.
</P>
<P>
   When buying leather for the home, consider how it's going to be
used and where. Cow hides shouldn't be too near a heat source, or
placed in direct sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   And remember that not all leathers are created equal. Suede
finishes, for example, are soft, luxurious and sturdy but they
can't take spills. A greasy cookie or dropped hors d'oeuvre could
be disastrous. That's why suedes are more likely to be found in
low-traffic areas, or in homes without dogs or children.
</P>
<P>
   Although suedes can be treated with a stain guard, Jerry
Hatfield of The Bon Marche says to proceed with caution. It could
change the color.
</P>
<P>
   As in all upholstered pieces, the frame can't be examined when
you're buying, so ask if the frame is hardwood that's been fit
together with dowels and glue _ a sign of quality.
</P>
<P>
   Sit on a sofa arm _ see if it feels sturdy. Ask about the finish
and how to care for it. Most stores sell care kits with the
furniture at prices from $10 to $45.
</P>
<P>
   It's important to buy a leather sofa with a warranty, and to buy
from a retailer who's been around for a while and likely to be
there if needed.
</P>
<P>
   And you don't have to have black, brown or beige. They may be
very forgiving colors, but if you like off-white, remember that
leather is easier to maintain than a fabric of the same shade.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say a leather sofa needs regular dusting, and an annual
cleaning according to manufacturer's directions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
