<HEADER>
A2074 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-TV-LAWORDER23-COX     09-22 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LAWORDER23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Law &AMP; Order's new hunk in volatile position
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Talk about pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse L. Martin is certainly under it. As ``Law &AMP; Order'''s new
hunky detective, the 30-year-old Martin is stepping in where the
equally hunky Benjamin Bratt stepped out as detective Rey Curtis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess there's supposed to be pressure,'' says Martin,
shrugging his coat-rack shoulders. ``You know, I'm going into a
slot once inhabited by Benjamin Bratt, who's one of the more
beautiful people in the world and everybody loved him.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Martin smiles ... slowly. It's one of those smooth ladies
man smiles you see in dimly lit nightclubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you know, I got my own thing, too.''
</P>
<P>
   That he does. Martin, perhaps best known for playing Ally's
doctor boyfriend on ``Ally McBeal,'' makes his ``Law &AMP; Order''
debut tonight (10 p.m. EDT) as hot-headed detective Edward Green.
</P>
<P>
   And in typical ``Law &AMP; Order'' fashion, no big deal is made of
Green's arrival. When the episode begins, Green is already working
with Briscoe (Jerry Orbach) on a case where a gunman has shot
several women in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   So, how did Martin, who in 1994 turned down a small ``Law &AMP;
Order'' role as a car stereo thief, get the gig?
</P>
<P>
   ``It sort of came about because a little birdie told me that
there may be some cast changes on `Law &AMP; Order' and I went to Dick
(Wolf) and just asked for it and lo and behold, I got the job,'' he
says. ``If you talk to any New York actor, ``Law &AMP; Order'' is one
of those shows you've either been on or want to be on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Practice'''s Steve Harris better watch out. ``Law &AMP;
Order'''s Green has the potential to be one of TV's most complex
African-American characters. In the opening episode, we already
learn that he likes to gamble (while on a case he high-tails-it to
Atlantic City to play poker), is prone to using excessive force (he
makes ``NYPD Blue'''s Sipowicz look like an aging neighborhood
watch patrolman) and has a smart mouth (he calls Briscoe ``Old
Spice''). Oh, and we'll learn later that he and Van Buren (S.
Epatha Merkerson) will bump heads in the squadroom.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Wolf, ``Law &AMP; Order'''s creator, says there will be a
generational and attitudinal difference between Green and Van
Buren.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never had two African-Americans in the front who are not
going to be in lockstep,'' says Wolf. ``It's not going to be
racial, it's going to be two African-Americans disagreeing
strenuously about the way business should be conducted, which I
think is interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect those juicy storylines to play out quickly.
``The character information is going to be dealt out in eyedroppers
rather than soup ladles,'' says Wolf, ``but I think that gives the
writers a chance to go into areas that they haven't explored since
Jesse's character is a little bit more flawed than Ben's.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Martin: ``This guy's not perfect, and he's got a track
record of excessive force because he thinks he's doing the right
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin has certainly done a lot of right things in his brief
career. Besides playing Ally's main squeeze, Martin was an original
cast member of the Pulitzer Prize and Tony Award-winning Broadway
musical ``Rent.'' He played an AIDS counselor on ``413 Hope St.,''
Fox's ill-fated drama and recently played an alien baseball player
in an ``X-Files'' episode directed by David Duchovny.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, however, took some heat while on ``Ally McBeal.'' The
show was criticized by some since race was never raised during Greg
and Ally's relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was actually very glad that I didn't have to work under that
weight,'' he says. ``I suppose as a white actor, you never have to
go into a relationship on television and say, 'Wow, I'm a white
actor and you're a white character. That's wild that we're working
together, right?' One of the cool things about doing that show was
that (it) never came up. It was more about the relationship than
anything else. Everybody in th
</P>
</TEXT>
