<P>
   HURRICANE FLOODING AFTERMATH
</P>
<P>
   FLOODS-MAIN _ Latest developments in eastern North Carolina as
residents cope with flooded homes and businesses and the threat of
disease from water contaminated by animal waste. (Rocky Mount
Telegram, Greenville Daily Reflector and Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: The main story will be written in Atlanta based on
reporting from Rocky Mount, Greenville and Atlanta. Greenville has
budgeted the stories listed below. CoxNet will wait until later in
the news cycle to determine which of Greenville's stories to move
separately on the wire based on how localized the final versions of
these stories are written. If one of these sidebars is of
particular interest in your market, call CoxNet at 404 526-5456 and
we will be sure to send it.
</P>
<P>
   FLOODS-UTILITIES _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ The worst appears to have
passed. Power is still tenuous and water pressure is building up
again in lower areas. (Bryant, Greenville Daily Reflector).
</P>
<P>
   FLOODS-DEATHS _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Some 40 people are known dead
as a result of flooding after Floyd. How much will the death toll
rise when the water recedes. (Fain, Greenville Daily Reflector).
</P>
<P>
   FLOODS-TOWN _ PINETOPS, N.C. _ This crossroads community was
burying Keisha Vines today, along with her parents Ben and Vivian
Mayo. A look at how North Carolina is dealing with its human dead,
when grave stones and caskets have been unearthed by Hurricane
Floyd's flood waters. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
AJC PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   FLOODS-ANIMALS _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Magnitude of animal waste
problems after the flood. (Batchelor, Greenville Daily Reflector).
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   FLOODS-ILLNESS _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ How much tetanus, typhoid
and other illnesses associated withflooding can be expected? (Hunt,
Greenville Daily Reflector).
</P>
<P>
   FLOODS-CAMPFLOYD _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Trailers and campers are
on their way to Greenville to house those without homes, courtesy,
state and federal disaster aid. With updates from FEMA and state
leaders. (Moscoso, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   FLOODS-BUSINESSES _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ How are industries coping
with workers cut off from workplaces. (Savage, Greenville Daily
Reflector).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-QUAKE _ PULI, Taiwan _ Taiwanese by the thousands
threaded across half-ruptured bridges Wednesday, past fresh
rockslides and across miles of rippled asphalt to search for
relatives at the epicenter of the Taiwan earthquake. They found
that nature had dealt capriciously with this mountain town of
89,000 people closest to the quake's ground zero. Here and
elsewhere in Taiwan's hardest-hit Nantou County it looked as if the
quake had hopscotched across the landscape like a giant tornado,
devastating one place while leaving adjacent territory seemingly
untouched. Developing. (Kunstel/Albright, Cox News Service). 30.
WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 5 p.m. EDT; updated at 7:30 p.m. EDT
and 9:30 p.m. EDT
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-MLK _ LONDON _ Soviet spies attempted to recruit the
Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. to their anti-American cause and
when they failed tried to discredit the civil rights leader as an
``Uncle Tom,'' according to a new book by a British scholar who has
researched KGB files. The book also says that Soviet agents tried
but failed to influence Andrew Young when he was the U.S.
ambassador to the United Nations under President Jimmy Carter.
(Roughton, Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-SUIT _ WASHINGTON _ Alleging a ``coordinated campaign of
fraud and deceit,'' the Justice Department filed a civil lawsuit
against the major tobacco companies Wednesday in a bid to recover
billions of tax dollars it spent on treating smoking-related
illnesses. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WACO-PROBE _ WASHINGTON _ In a sign of startup difficulties for
the investigations into the 1993 Waco siege, special counsel John
Danforth complained that Senate investigators went to Texas
``without even troubling to give me a call.'' Senate Judiciary
Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, sent back a message that he hadn't
known about the visit, either. Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Penn., had
sent the aides. Senators were divided on whether to conduct their
probe through a special task force or in the Judiciary Committee.
(Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   TRAFFIC _ WASHINGTON _ Major road construction projects often
cause such long traffic delays that drivers can never make up the
lost time, the Surface Transportation Policy Project said in a
report Wednesday. (Hill, Cox News Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   LIFE IN AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   CoxNet will distribute a series of reports on life in small-town
America _ the values, the stories and the characters _ at the end
of the millennium. The stories will be taken from newspapers
throughout the Cox chain. Photos and a sig/locator map will be
available through Locations or via the Budget Tool. CoxNet is also
seeking story candidates. If your paper has a story that should be
submitted, please contact us. Any questions, call Todd C. Duncan at
404 582-7282 or 404 526-5456
</P>
<P>
   LIFE-IN-AMERICA23 _ DAYTON, Ohio _ David Eldridge never thought
of high school football as a healer. The Lebanon High School
football parent, however, had his eyes opened last season when he
said last year's state champions transformed a town divided over a
school levy and other matters. ``It brought the community together.
It gave us something to rally around. People put their differences
aside and the school is better for it,'' Eldridge said. ``If the
football team is down, there's not that aura of cooperation amongst
everybody.'' He said football lets people cast aside prejudices
rooted in educational or financial differences. Respect becomes
performance- and effort-based. Ned Drees could have told Eldridge
all about the power of high school football. (Reines, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED.
</P>
