<HEADER>
A2083 &Cx1f; tth-z
r l BC-KIDS-BOOKS-SPI &LR;      09-22 1712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-BOOKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTS OF GOOD KIDS' BOOKS OUT THERE BEYOND `HARRY POTTER' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CECELIA GOODNOW  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Poor child. All summer you pranced like a racehorse nervously
awaiting the bell, then bolted to the bookstore the minute the
third ``Harry Potter'' went on sale.
</P>
<P>
   You raced through it faster than you can say ``Harry Potter and
the Prisoner of Azkaban,'' wishing the home stretch would never
come and then ... it ended, at page 435.
</P>
<P>
   Just days after the book's Sept. 8 release, you've already read
it. Maybe twice.
</P>
<P>
   Now what? It'll be a whole year before Scholastic publishes the
fourth installment of J.K. Rowling's phenomenal ``Harry Potter''
series.
</P>
<P>
   And next time you can't cheat and buy the British edition ahead
of time, because future books in the series will be published
simultaneously in both countries.
</P>
<P>
   Gosh, you might have to _ dare we say it? _ READ SOMETHING ELSE!
</P>
<P>
   Happily, there are lots of terrific books right up your alley _
full of fantasy, humor, adventure and pluck.
</P>
<P>
   To help us steer you straight to a great read, Christy McDanold,
owner of Secret Garden Children's BookShop in Ballard, gathered a
crateful of must-reads for ``Harry Potter'' fans.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring you'd already heard of Roald Dahl and Lloyd Alexander _
No? What a ghastly omission _ we selected some others that
especially piqued our interest.
</P>
<P>
   We also polled other booksellers and threw in a couple of our
personal favorites. Unless noted, most titles are for ages 9 to 12.
</P>
<P>
   So power up your Firebolt racing broom and let's get going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Firegold,'' by Dia Calhoun (Winslow Press, 286 pages, $15.95
hardcover, $9.95 paper)
</P>
<P>
   Everyone dreams of discovering the talented ``unknown'' who's
destined for great things. McDanold thinks she's found one in
Calhoun, a first-time author from Tacoma whose originality and fine
writing compensate for the low-budget look of this fantasy novel
from a startup press.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathon, haunted by the sense that he is different, wonders if
he is descended from the dreaded Dalriadas, the mountain folk with
magnificent horses and mystical powers. When everyone blames him
for a blight that destroys the valley's apple orchards, he escapes
to the Red Mountains in search of answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dark Is Rising,'' by Susan Cooper (Simon &AMP; Schuster, 244
pages, $3.95 paper)
</P>
<P>
   On his 11th birthday, Will Stanton learns he is the last of the
Old Ones, immortals dedicated to thwarting evil. Now he must find
six magical signs that will aid in the final battle against the
Dark. A Newbery Honor, Carnegie Honor, and Boston Globe/-Horn Book
Award winner. ``The excitment (sic) went on and on,'' wrote one
young reader on Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   P.S.: ``The Grey King,'' from the same series, won the 1976
Newbery Medal. Put this author on your list.
</P>
<P>
   P.S.S.: Cooper's new book is a time-travel adventure called
``King of Shadows'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, 186 pages, $16). Check it
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dragonslayers,'' by Bruce Coville, illustrated by
Katherine Coville (Pocket Books, 119 pages, $3.99 paper).
</P>
<P>
   Coville has many books to tantalize ``Harry Potter'' fans,
including ``Jeremy Thatcher, Dragon Hatcher,'' and a new series
called ``Into the Land of Unicorns.'' The second title in that
series, ``Song of the Wanderer,'' is due out next month.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, slightly younger kids will find an easy route to
excitement in ``The Dragonslayers,'' a light-hearted adventure
about an old squire, a young page boy and a willful princess who
must stop arguing long enough to dispatch a spiteful
witch-turned-dragon. Opening line: ``Do you have the lizard snot?''
asked Grizelda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep Wizardry,'' by Diane Duane (Harcourt Brace, 356 pages, $6
paper)
</P>
<P>
   In this second book of Duane's ``Wizardry'' series, two
13-year-olds on summer vacation join with a whale wizard and become
whales themselves to battle the sinister Lone Power. ``A powerful
tale of sacrifice and redemption,'' says School Library Journal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elidor,'' by Alan Garner (Harcourt Brace, 173 pages, $6
paper).
</P>
<P>
   Four children explore an abandoned church in a Manchester slum,
then are drawn into another world, where they must try to overcome
evil and guard the unicorn Findhorn. First published in Britain in
1965 and shortlisted for the Carnegie Medal, it's out in a new
American paperback edition. ``Intelligent, rich and terrifying,''
says the (London) Times Literary Supplement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ella Enchanted,'' by Gail Carson Levine (HarperTrophy, 232
pages, $5.95 paper)
</P>
<P>
   This acclaimed novel for ages 8 and up tells how a spunky
princess tries to break the curse of a well-meaning but foolish
fairy who has ``gifted'' her with obedience. ``If you commanded me
to cut off my own head, I'd have to do it,'' Ella tells readers.
``I was in danger at every moment.'' A 1998 Newbery Honor book, it
also made best-of-the year lists of the American Library
Association, the School Library Journal and Publisher's Weekly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bad Beginning,'' by Lemony Snicket (HarperTrophy, 164
pages, $8.95 hardcover).
</P>
<P>
   In a tone of delectable doom, the author (who's coming to
Seattle next month) warns readers away from this first volume in
``A Series of Unfortunate Events.'' Here the three Baudelaire
children suffer the sudden loss of their parents (whom we never
meet) and must thwart the wicked guardian who pursues their
fortune. Also out: Book 2, ``The Reptile Room.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Reader,'' writes Snicket (pen name in cheek), ``I'm sorry
to say that the book you are holding in your hands is extremely
unpleasant. It tells an unhappy tale about three very unlucky
children. ... One might say they are magnets for misfortune.'' Put
the book down at once, Snicket advises, and ``read something happy
if you prefer that sort of thing.'' As if.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mossflower,'' by Brian Jacques (Philomel, 431 pages, $21.99
hardcover. $5.99, editions by Avon and Berkeley)
</P>
<P>
   For the past decade, Jacques (pronounced ``Jakes'') has
enthralled preteens with his acclaimed Redwall series, featuring
bold-hearted, talking animals and scheming villains in days of
yore. The plots are meaty, with plenty of good-vs.-evil and
characters with unpronounceable names and dialects. Kids eat it up.
``Mossflower,'' the prequel to ``Redwall,'' pits Martin the Warrior
against two ruthless felines for leadership of the abbey. In
January look for book 12 in the series, ``The Legend of Luke.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Honus and Me,'' by Dan Gutman (Avon, 137 pages, $4.99 paper)
</P>
<P>
   A boy cleans out his neighbor's attic and finds a rare and
valuable T-206 Honus Wagner baseball card. The card magically puts
Joe in contact with Wagner himself, in a ``Field of Dreams'' sort
of way, and helps Joelay to rest a sad mystery. Original,
thought-provoking and a quick read.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Wizard of Earthsea,' by Ursula K. Le Guin (Bantam, 184
pages, $6.99)
</P>
<P>
   The Earthsea Cycle, with more than a million copies in print,
invites comparisons with Tolkien and C.S. Lewis. Here, in book one,
the great sorcerer Ged is recalled as a power-hungry youth who
unleashes a terrible shadow over the world. Reader comments on
Amazon.com range from ``It STUNK!'' to ``These books will stay with
you for the rest of your life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Wedding for Wiglaf,'' by K.H. McMullan (Grosset &AMP; Dunlap, 91
pages, $3.99)
</P>
<P>
   Here's light-hearted action for the younger set _ say third
grade. In book four of the Dragon Slayers' Academy series, Princess
Belcheena seeks a husband with red hair who has killed at least two
dragons and whose name begins with ``W.'' When the headmaster of
the Dragon Slayers' Academy hears there's a matchmaker's reward,
guess whom he nominates?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Well-Wishers,'' by Edward Eager (Harcourt Brace, 220
pages, $6)
</P>
<P>
   Eager's magical novels, dating back 40 years, are out in a new
Young Classics paperback edition. In this sequel to ``Magic or
Not?'' a group of children plunge into further outlandish
adventures through the magic of an old wishing well.
</P>
<P>
   Eager, who died in 1964, considered E. Nesbit the finest
children's book writer of all time and often cited her as his
inspiration. So it's timely that Nesbit's classic novel, ``Five
Children and It,'' has been reissued this month in a deluxe
hardcover edition illustrated by Caldecott Medalist Paul O.
Zelinsky (Morrow Books of Wonder, 242 pages, $22).
</P>
<P>
   ``Protector of the Small: First Test,'' by Tamora Pierce (Random
House, 216 pages, $16).
</P>
<P>
   ``First Test'' advances the plot of ``Alanna: The First
Adventure,'' (Random House, $4.99 paperback), about a girl who
disguises herself as a boy to become a knight. Moving ahead a
generation, ``First Test'' introduces Kel, the first girl to train
for the knighthood. Unfortunately for her, the narrow-minded
trainer Lord Wyldon isn't big on affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mirror of Merlin,'' by T.A. Barron (Philomel, 320 pages,
$19.99)
</P>
<P>
   New this month: the fourth book in Barron's well-received series
about Merlin's early years. Other titles are ``The Lost Years of
Merlin,'' ``The Seven Songs of Merlin'' and ``The Fires of
Merlin.'' Booklist says this series ``just keeps getting richer in
characterization, ambience and Celtic lore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Golden Compass,'' by Philip Pullman (Knopf, 416 pages, $20
hardcover, $5.99 Ballantine paper)
</P>
<P>
   Darker and more complex than ``Harry Potter,'' this rich fantasy
and its sequel, ``The Subtle Knife,'' have a large adult following.
Still to come: the final installment of the trilogy, collectively
titled ``His Dark Materials.'' The series describes the sometimes
bleak adventures of two children, Lyra and Will, whose ability to
slip between worlds sets them on a perilous quest to find the
origins of the universe and halt the course of evil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tuck Everlasting,'' by Natalie Babbitt (Farrar Straus &AMP;
Giroux, 139 pages, $4.95 paperback, $16 hardcover)
</P>
<P>
   In this profound and beautifully crafted novel, 10-year-old
Winnie Foster stumbles onto a family that has drunk from a fountain
of eternal youth. Between being kidnapped and helping an accused
murderer out of jail, Winnie must decide whether to accept an offer
of everlasting life with all its burdens and complexities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
