<SLUG> BC-SF-MAYOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATE SUES NEWSPAPER FOR LACK OF COVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Martin Eng, one of 14 candidates running for
mayor, is suing the San Francisco Chronicle, saying that the
newspaper has ignored his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed Sept. 15 in San Francisco Superior Court,
accuses the Chronicle of being negligent in its duty and of
violating Eng's civil rights by excluding him from its coverage of
the mayor's race. Eng seeks compensation for ``economic loss,
humiliation, harm to reputation and emotional distress.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle ran profiles of the three leading candidates _
Mayor Willie Brown, Clint Reilly and former Mayor Frank Jordan _
earlier this month. None of the other 11 candidates was profiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I win this suit all the way, I think it will change the
whole fundamentals on news reporting on candidates,'' said Eng, a
real estate broker who was president of the Chinese-American
Republican Club in the mid-1990s but is now an independent.
</P>
<P>
   Eng suggested the Chronicle's actions were related to his being
the only Chinese-American candidate but would not elaborate on the
connection. His lawyer, Edward Simpson of San Francisco, also would
not clarify any aspect of the complaint.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit says: ``The actions of the Chronicle in not
reasonably and fairly reporting with respect to Eng's candidacy ...
are on information and belief due to Eng's race and are thus
discriminatory. ...''
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle's general counsel, Ronald Ingram, said he would
not comment on litigation and has not yet been served in the case.
</P>
<P>
   But Barbara O'Connor, a professor of communications at
California State University at Sacramento, said of the lawsuit:
``There isn't a chance in hell they'll prevail. There's no legal
grounds that will be sustained in court.''
</P>
<P>
   Media lawyer Kelli Sager said newspapers have a right to print _
or not print _ whatever they want, a right guaranteed under the
First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. Supreme Court has very clearly ruled on this issue,''
said Sager, who is based in Los Angeles. ``They have said that a
newspaper is not obliged to run information about anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, O'Connor said, ``There's a real danger from the public
policy perspective when legitimate voices are silenced. I do think
the media has a responsibility to open up the dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle Managing Editor Jerry Roberts referred coverage
questions to Linda Strean, an assistant managing editor, who did
not return a call for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Eng, a founder of an Internet business that owns more than 100
domain names, including brucelee.com, modelswatch.com and
beautypageant.com, said the Chronicle had the power to shape public
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole thing is, I want justice,'' he said.
``Chinese-Americans are the most discriminated minority in this
country. Chinese never get their fair share of anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 1814EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0289 </DOCNO>
