r e BC-TV-MAD-SPI &LR;      09-22 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MAD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STARK RAVING MAD' LIKELY TO SUCCEED DESPITE ITSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The worst that can happen to a new show is to be guaranteed
success from the get-go. Creativity suffers. Complacency sets in.
The show nevers seems to fire on all cylinders.
</P>
<P>
   It happened to ``Veronica's Closet,'' which started strong two
years ago but pulled up lame a few furlongs into its first season.
It stayed on the air because it had the NBC equivalent of Most
Favored Nation status: the 9:30 slot on Thursday nights.
</P>
<P>
   Better than a Nobel Prize, the time slot means huge ratings
(which allow the network to overcharge advertisers), enormous
paydays (which allow the actors to buy Porsches), and the
possibility of syndication royalties ad infinitum (which allows the
actors to pay for detailing on their Porsches).
</P>
<P>
   Now that ``Veronica's Closet'' has been shuffled off to Monday
nights, the new beneficiary of the slot between ``Frasier'' and
``ER'' is ``Stark Raving Mad,'' a remarkably standard,
unspectacular new comedy that will probably finish the season in
the Nielsen top 10, possibly the top five.
</P>
<P>
   It's about a prissy, multiphobic book editor named Henry McNeely
(Neil Patrick Harris), whose principal client is a best-selling
horror writer named Ian Stark (Tony Shalhoub), who likes nothing
better than scaring the beluga out of McNeely, all in the name of
research.
</P>
<P>
   As the Felix Unger of this odd couple, Harris proves he's good
at slapstick, falling over furniture with the aplomb of an early
Dick Van Dyke. But Shalhoub, who's good at everything he does,
seems uncomfortable in the Oscar Madison role.
</P>
<P>
   It takes good chemistry between actors for the audience to think
there's no chemistry between characters. If Harris and Shalhoub are
waiting for spectacular ratings to help fuel their chemical
reaction, then they really are stark raving mad.
</P>
<P>
   Stark Raving Mad. Half-hour comedy series about a prissy book
editor and an earthy horror novelist. Starring Neil Patrick Harris
and Tony Shalhoub. Season premiere Thursday night on NBC. Parental
guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
