<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2095 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MENCKEN-POLITICIANS-N     09-22 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENCKEN-POLITICIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: WITH MENCKEN AROUND, POLITICIANS DIDN'T HAVE A
PRAYER
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every so often, usually in the slough of a political campaign, I
find myself returning to the works of H.L. Mencken. It is not any
ideological affinity that draws me but the inimitable effervescence
of the man's language. Particularly in the current combat, with so
many presidential claimants sporting religious credentials,
Mencken, who died in 1956, remains as impertinent and as pertinent
as ever.
</P>
<P>
   The journalist assigned to cover the campaigns of George W.
Bush, Al Gore or Elizabeth Dole, of Gary Bauer, Patrick J. Buchanan
or others must perforce tread carefully when the candidates allude
to alliances with religion. Who in the press is about to express
public skepticism about anyone's faith? Even the most impudent
critics, who feast on financial finaglings and sexual
indiscretions, shy away from questioning or giving offense when it
comes to professions of piety.
</P>
<P>
   Mencken had no such compunctions. Religion, particularly as
practiced by American go-getters, was his specialty, and skepticism
was a commandment. He hailed the skeptical approach as ``socially
very valuable, immensely more valuable, in fact, than any known
sort of faith.'' He rarely acknowledged that politicians might be
sincere about their religious beliefs, and, anyway, for him
sincerity was no excuse for what he deemed outlandish notions.
</P>
<P>
   The booboisie, as he liked to call his fellow Americans,
provided him with ``unfeigned delight,'' and in any period of
campaign smog his prose was an air purifier. For readers
unacquainted with his range, spirit and invective, here, from a
1922 essay, is his summary of American public manners: ``the
unending procession of governmental extortions and chicaneries, of
commercial brigandages and throat-slittings, of theological
buffooneries, of aesthetic ribaldries, of legal swindles and
harlotries, of miscellaneous rogueries, villainies, imbecilities,
grotesqueries and extravagances.'' He wrote, ``Only a man who was
born with a petrified diaphragm can fail to laugh himself to sleep
every night.''
</P>
<P>
   What he called ``theological buffooneries'' occupy many pages of
his work. The exhibitions of religious fervor as primaries approach
sometimes bring to mind the knee-bendings of football players who
seem to believe that God cares who scores a touchdown. Many
assuredly must be in earnest, but it is not always easy to sort
faith from ambition.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mencken evinced little admiration for the practices of
Roman Catholics and Jews, as a specialist in genus Americanus he
directed most of his animadversions at various manifestations of
Protestantism. In his book ``Treatise on the Gods'' he boasted that
he could invent any number of new sects ``and all of them would be
10 times as plausible'' as any then in existence.
</P>
<P>
   Mencken's views of religious fundamentalism became famous
through his dispatches on the 1925 Scopes ``monkey trial,'' but he
went beyond the creationists when he took on ``the corps of
evangelical pastors ... a body devoid of sense and lamentably
indifferent to common honesty.'' He tells a story of a Frenchman
who was leaving the church of his fathers. When asked what variety
of Protestantism he planned to patronize, he replied, ``I have lost
my faith but not my reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then it has become impermissible for members of one
denomination to come out so rudely against the competition. But
Mencken, that ecumenical insulter, would surely have mined laughs
from a president's taking counsel with his pastor about his
relations with a young intern or of a vice president's sudden
appreciation of generous Buddhists.
</P>
<P>
   Why has Menckenism gone out of style? One reason, of course, is
a deficiency of talent. Few journalists have written so bitingly or
humorously about public figures. But probably more important, by
the time of his death America's constraints on his sort of
invective had become more severe, and there were signs of further
constriction on the way.
</P>
<P>
   The casually disparaging cracks about selected groups to which
Mencken was prone had gone out of style. After the Holocaust it was
harder to make jokes about Jews, and as the civil rights movement
gained force, the nation became more considerate about references
to blacks. So, too, did sensitivity increase about Asian-Americans
and Latinos, the gay and the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Even admirers of the Mencken spirit can welcome the increased
shows of tolerance, respect and diversity in America. Most people
take pride in the ability of different races and religions to live
together in reasonable tranquillity, well worth the loss of a
little easy humor. And yet, particularly when the political juices
are flowing and language turns to jelly, Mencken is missed.
</P>
<P>
   In his gentler moments Mencken could praise the Old Testament
for its literature and Christianity for its spirit of charity. But
mostly, by his accounting, the religious squadrons were composed of
con artists and their gulls. When it came to politicians, he found
religion being pressed into service ``as a sanction for moral
theories, for political and economic dogmas, for reforms (or
opposition to them) in laws and manners, for social protests and
revolutions and even for purely private enterprises, including the
commercial and the amorous.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting elected must be among the less discreditable of those
goals, but not even the naughtiest pundit these days is about to
echo Mencken's opinion that in America, religion ``is used as a
club and a cloak by both politicians and moralists, all of them
lusting for power and most of them palpable frauds.''
</P>
<P>
   All right, that's a broad-brush judgment, unfair and typically
Mencken. But in these months of piety ascendant, with politicians
and athletes and actors competing for heaven's support, it comes as
a breath of refreshing irreverence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
