<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 1826EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2099 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WATCH-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      09-22 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WATCH-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THIRD WATCH': FROM THE PRODUCERS WHO BROUGHT YOU `ER' 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lh) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a lot to keep track of during the first episode of
``Third Watch.'' The principal characters (there are at least nine)
keep materializing and disappearing, darting from emergency to
emergency while they dodge the traffic, the smoke, the bullets, the
fire, the blood and the vomit. Maybe your head will spin. Maybe
that's the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Here's some advice: Don't try to keep everyone straight. Things
will begin to sort themselves out by the end of Thursday night's
introductory hour on NBC. And here's a prediction: As this series
settles into its regular Sunday night slot, starting this weekend,
you will begin to care about these imaginary people nearly as much
as they care about one another.
</P>
<P>
   This ensemble drama series is about police officers and
paramedics on the 3-to-11-p.m. shift (the third watch) in a very
fictional New York City. They work in and around the 55th Precinct
station house and, just across the street, a firehouse known as
Camelot because it's at the corner of King and Arthur.
</P>
<P>
   What borough is that in? Fuhgeddaboudit. In this neighborhood _
which includes avenues called Lexington and Riverside and shiny,
silver elevated trains _ every municipal employee has a heart as
big as all Gotham and looks like, well, an attractive Hollywood
actor. But hey, don't hate them because they're beautiful. These
dedicated civil servants delight in the lives they save and agonize
over the ones they don't.
</P>
<P>
   No, these cops and ambulance jockeys aren't as gritty or
dyspeptic as the officers on ``NYPD Blue.'' These are more like the
doctors and nurses of ``ER.'' That's no surprise. The executive
producers of ``Third Watch,'' John Wells and Christopher Chulack,
are part of the team responsible for ``ER,'' NBC's dependable meal
ticket in these hungry times for network television.
</P>
<P>
   They borrow liberally from the ``ER'' prescription: appealing
characters tested in life-or-death crises, one after another. But
in sure hands the formula works.
</P>
<P>
   That formula depends heavily on strong casting, and judging from
Thursday night's episode, this team has what it takes. At Camelot,
you'll find a pair of bantering young paramedics named Kim (Kim
Raver) and Bobby (Bobby Cannavale), the only two cast members whose
characters share their own first names, as well as the veteran Doc
(Michael Beach), who is helping the sensitive rookie Carlos
(Anthony Ruivivar) learn the ropes. Over at the police station
you'll meet the hotheaded Bosco (Jason Wiles) and his partner Faith
(Molly Price), the overworked mother of two small children, as well
as the fatherly Sully (Skipp Sudduth), who has taken under his wing
young Davis (Coby Bell), the son of Sully's revered partner, who
died in the line of duty.
</P>
<P>
   Confused? Don't fret. And don't worry about Kim's ex-husband,
Jimmy the randy fireman (Eddie Cibrian), or about Mantooth, the
firehouse Dalmatian who likes doughnuts but not dog food.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's script, by Wells, flings the characters into
crises from a car wreck to a tenement fire to a birth on the floor
of a subway car. All this gives them opportunities to display the
human qualities that bind them to one another and, more important,
to the viewer.
</P>
<P>
   The most fascinating dynamics involve the two interracial
pairings of mentor and novice: the black Doc with the Latino
Carlos, and the white Sully with the black Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's our job?'' Sully demands of his pupil at one point.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, fresh from the academy, answers without hesitation,
``Enforcing the law.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No!'' Sully snaps. ``We're solving problems. We go from job to
job solving problems as quickly as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   That may not be an accurate or complete description of police
work. But it sounds like a solid foundation for a television
series.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THIRD WATCH'
</P>
<P>
   10 p.m. ET Thursday on NBC
</P>
<P>
   Created by John Wells and Edward Allen Bernero; Wells and
Christopher Chulack, executive producers; John Romano, co-executive
producer. Produced by John Wells Productions in association with
Warner Brothers Television.
</P>
<P>
   With: Kim Raver (Kim Zambrano), Bobby Cannavale (Bobby Caffey),
Michael Beach (Doc Parker), Anthony Ruivivar (Carlos Nieto), Jason
Wiles (Bosco Boscorelli), Molly Price (Faith Yokas), Skipp Sudduth
(Sully Sullivan), Coby Bell (Ty Davis) and Eddie Cibrian (Jimmy
Doherty).
</P>
