<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-COMMENTARY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFLECTIONS FROM ONE WHO CALLS WEDGWOOD HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETSY FRIAUF 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ There's no place in my world, no niche in my
psyche for this: a massacre in a church, across the street from my
old grade school. Kids from my old high school gunned down while
praying.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Shulkey Elementary, named for someone my mother-in-law
knew: a battle zone. Suddenly. In a neighborhood where nothing ever
happened.
</P>
<P>
   Cognitive dissonance, psychologists might say. Mourning,
ministers might say. Unimaginable, I say. The image of the
space-suited firefighter going into a church to look for a bomb is
the stuff of recurrent nightmares. And that was the mildest of the
scary things. So many people suffered so much and will suffer
immensely in the months and years ahead. I'm just a whiny lamenter,
a 1999 Greek chorus.
</P>
<P>
   When my family moved to Wedgwood in 1960, we were on the edge of
development. Our beagle roamed cow pastures and brought home trophy
rabbits. Wedgwood was a huge middle-class family place. Daddies
worked at General Dynamics (now Lockheed Martin) or Carswell Air
Force Base or sold insurance. It seemed unanimous that the moms
stayed home.
</P>
<P>
   I walked to Shulkey every day. Sometimes friends walked with me;
sometimes I walked alone. It didn't matter; nothing ever happened.
</P>
<P>
   We went to church every Sunday unless we were deathly ill. Most
everyone in the neighborhood did. We went swimming on summer
Saturdays. I learned to ride an old blue bike that got passed
around the neighborhood, with daddies running alongside. After a
movie theater opened in Wedgwood, our parents dropped us off, even
elementary-school kids, and picked us up hours later. Nothing ever
happened.
</P>
<P>
   We caught horned toads and dropped them when ``blood'' came out
of their faces. During the Cuban missile crisis, my friends and I
dug bomb shelters until we hit solid limestone. But nothing ever
happened.
</P>
<P>
   I grew up. I'm old enough to know that no place is safe from
violence. I know that the world has changed; I was night city
editor at this paper during Fort Worth's highest-crime period this
century. But when I drive to Wedgwood, I still feel immune.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting my mother four blocks from Wedgwood Baptist, taking my
children to YMCA summer camp at Shulkey, shopping in the fabric
store, I feel in my soul that Wedgwood is a safe place. This year,
no one killed anyone, January through August, in my old
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing ever happened there.
</P>
<P>
   Now something has.
</P>
<P>
   What do I do? What do I say?
</P>
<P>
   All I can tell my children is that you are as safe as Mommy and
Daddy can help you to be. And there's no cocoon anyone can put
around another human. In the face of inexplicable acts by people
with minds that aren't right, all we can do is seek to be part of
the solution.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
