<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0299 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2105 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-FAITH-AND-TRAGEDY-TEX     09-22 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAITH-AND-TRAGEDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINISTERS TELL CHILDREN NOT TO LOSE HOPE IN WAKE OF TRAGEDY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSIE MILLIGAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The Rev. David Hunt of Bethany Fellowship
Assembly of God
</P>
<P>
   prays with his 12-year-old son before school every morning, but
few mornings more fervently than the morning after the mass
shooting at a Fort Worth church.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the slayings, father and son closed their eyes
and said aloud:
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no fear. I have power, love and a sound mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents are bound to be worried about their children's faith in
the aftermath of last week's tragedy, in which a gunman fired
repeatedly into a crowded youth rally, killing seven before turning
the gun on himself. Ministers say that the days after a tragedy _
particularly a slaying in a sanctuary _ are an appropriate time to
teach youth about the sometimes complex aspects of developing a
spiritual life, especially if children are mature enough to begin
questioning religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do worry that young people just discovering religion will
begin to doubt God's love,'' said the Rev. Lloyd Taylor of
Southwood Baptist Church in southwest Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, ministers say, young people need to know they
are loved and have not been abandoned by God. And they need to know
that faith and hope are made for troubled times.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jonathan Ogujiofor, priest at St. Simon of Cyrene
Episcopal Church near Lake Arlington, said he was shaken as the
lights of police cars and ambulances swirled across his southwest
Fort Worth neighborhood after the shootings. He lives next door to
Wedgwood Baptist Church, where the killings took place.
</P>
<P>
   Three friends of Ogujiofor's 15-year-old son and 17-year-old
daughter were killed at the neighborhood church. The family prayed
that night, but Ogujiofor did not want to press too deeply into
spiritual concepts as the night grew late.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were still too traumatized,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So he gave comfort first and, 24 hours later, he sat the
children down to talk.
</P>
<P>
   He told them: ``This is life, this is the way life comes and
goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Their friends did not die because they were bad people. We all
die. The goal is to live well while we are here, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``God can and does allow things like this to happen. He teaches
us that `You cannot count on life, but you can count on me. If you
keep still, you will know I am right there, and you will know from
the comfort I will give you, from the power you receive by your
ability to overcome and bear suffering. You will know that I am
here.' '' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The words don't come easily. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone will find that same eloquence when talking with a
child. Ministers say that's OK.
</P>
<P>
   At east Fort Worth's Hope Community Church _ where the
receptionist answers the telephone, ``Welcome to Hope'' _ the Rev.
Harold Bullock said: ``Don't just drop the facts on them and run.
Talk to them when there is a lot of time for them to ask
questions.''
</P>
<P>
   He spoke to his own children, ages 13 and 10, and explained that
tragedies remind us how vulnerable we really are.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no guarantees to our safety.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that although there is pain, there is also a
great deal of beauty in life. It is normal to have both, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some may want to blame God. They should know that being a
Christian does not mean they will be immune from tragedy,'' said
the Rev. Bill Bowers of Wedgwood Church of the Nazarene, which is
near Wedgwood Baptist. Bowers was preparing to offer a prayer
before the Fort Worth City Council meeting the night after the
shootings. But he paused to contemplate what we should tell the
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Painful things will happen. The main goal is for our soul to
be right, however long we have on this earth,'' Bowers said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sundays, the Rev. Paul Gomez stood in front of his
congregation, housed for now in the United Artists Fossil Creek
movie theater, and in front of the screen that normally flashes
scenes of violence, adventure and romance. In the stillness of the
theater, he often explains to his CrossRoads Church congregation
that humans were put on the Earth with the power of choice, and
thus bear a great responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone had to choose to pull that trigger. They were not made
to do so,'' Gomez said.
</P>
<P>
   People can also chose to remain faithful, even in troubling
times.
</P>
<P>
   Ministers say they are concerned that Wedgwood Baptist tragedy
will send ripples of fear through the community.
</P>
<P>
   At Meadowbrook United Methodist Church south of downtown Fort
Worth, the Rev. J. Neil Norman told his teen and pre-teen children
that the answer is not to build bigger walls and better security
systems to keep gunmen out of sanctuaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get closer to people, not push them away,'' Norman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Norman said he is encouraging his children, and his
congregation, to spend less time on their own entertainment and
more time volunteering to help people in need, people who could
turn to desperate measures if they do not find some kindness at
some turn in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christ connected with people who are outcasts, but we don't
take the time,'' Norman said.
</P>
<P>
   At Southwood Baptist, Taylor agrees. Times like these, he said,
should strengthen our resolve to work for a better world.
</P>
<P>
   And ministers say that the belief that we can bring about new
beginnings through our own actions is a large part of what
Christian faith is about.
</P>
<P>
   So when Hunt prays with his son in the mornings, he takes time
to tell him: ``Faith is no good unless it's tested. Hope is no good
unless you get to use it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
