<HEADER>
A2107 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-UPSIDE-DOWN-DANCE-ART     09-22 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPSIDE-DOWN-DANCE-ART-2TAKES-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAKING THROUGH TO THE TOP AT A SINGLE BOUND  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 26) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
Valerie Gladstone's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was
about Leonard de Paur and the Lincoln Center Out of Doors
Festival. 
 By VALERIE GLADSTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To the propulsive beat of the Nigerian Fela Anikulapo
Kuti's music, the choreographer Ronald K. Brown led his 12 sinuous
dancers across the floor in fast, rhythmic movements, each stride
increasing the tension in the studio.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, horns and sirens blared on lower Broadway, and rain
lashed against the windows. Oblivious, the group advanced as one
and then froze, eyes lowered, their only movement the small,
nervous gestures they made with their hands.
</P>
<P>
   The spectators were caught off guard. Just five minutes into
``Upside Down,'' Brown had already reached a wrenchingly emotional
place. It is a place he fruitfully visits often. ``Upside Down,'' a
section from a larger work, the 1998 ``Destiny,'' illustrates the
enormous effort and energy it takes to move toward inner peace in a
chaotic world. Like all of his work, ``Upside Down'' is, to Brown,
evidence of the human struggle.
</P>
<P>
   When Brown's aptly named company, Evidence, begins its one-week
engagement at the Joyce Theater on Tuesday, it will present
``Upside Down'' as well as two other Brown works: ``Ebony
Magazine,'' to a score by the British composer Wunmi Olaiya, and
the New York premiere of ``Water,'' to music by the jazz composer
Philip Hamilton, the Nigerian composer Fahali Igbo and the a
cappella ensemble Sweet Honey in the Rock. Cheryl Boyce Taylor will
accompany ``Water,'' reading the poem she wrote for it.
</P>
<P>
   Each piece in the Joyce program exhibits the joyous physicality
and sensitivity to contemporary anguish that have made Brown, who
is 33, one of the hottest choreographers now working in modern
dance. All told, he has had an extraordinary year.
</P>
<P>
   It started last fall with a three-week season at Dance Theater
Workshop and continued with commissions from Philadanco and the
Dayton Contemporary Dance Company. He also made new works for the
Spoleto U.S.A., Celebrate Brooklyn and Jacob's Pillow festivals.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater will feature
his newest piece, ``Grace,'' during its season at the City Center. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What thrust Brown into the spotlight? A combination of forces,
according to people in the dance field. ``Besides Ron's being a
gorgeous performer,'' said Martha Myers, dean of the school of the
American Dance Festival, ``he deals frankly with racial and sexual
issues. It's made him noticed.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Maureen D. Knighton, executive director of 651 Arts
in Brooklyn, asked Brown to be artist in residence. ``He creates a
partnership with audiences,'' she said. ``He helps them process
complex subjects like racism, AIDS, love and loss. His work is
charismatic.''
</P>
<P>
   David R. White, executive director of Dance Theater Workshop,
began presenting him 10 years ago. ``Ron frames his works as
rituals,'' he said. ``This gives them resonance, a timeless
quality.'' Brown's series at the Joyce's Altogether Different
Festival in 1998 both packed the theater and pleased the critics.
The impressive showing encouraged Linda Shelton, the Joyce's
executive director, to ask him to open the season this fall.
</P>
<P>
   To win wide exposure, artists obviously need talent. But finding
presenters to support them is also critical. In the small field of
dance, most presenters know one another. ``We talk with each other
a lot,'' said Ella Bass, executive director of Jacob's Pillow,
``and often rally around an under-recognized artist to help find an
effective presence in the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, an artist who shows work at Jacob's Pillow will
probably also be seen at the American Dance Festival, P.S. 122, the
Kitchen, Dance Theater Workshop and eventually at the Joyce or the
Brooklyn Academy of Music. Does a choreographer automatically
ascend a ladder, starting with small venues like P.S. 122 and then
climb to the Joyce and the Brooklyn Academy? White responded with a
definite ``no.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It all depends on what they want to present,'' he said. ``Some
works do better in one place than in another.''
</P>
<P>
   Joan Meyers Brown, artistic director of Philadanco (and not
related to Brown), isn't convinced that consensus among presenters
is a good thing. ``I think it often simply comes down to `flavor of
the month,' especially with black artists,'' she said. ``It seems
there's only one `black star' chosen every few years.''
</P>
<P>
   She mentioned Garth Fagan and Bill T. Jones as examples. But her
concern goes deeper. ``I worry that some of these overnight
successes aren't up to making back-to-back ballets. More is not
always better. They need time to stop and work on their art.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent hot, rainy day, Brown would have definitely agreed
that he needed more time after being rudely rushed out of a studio
for running a few minutes late in rehearsal. But for someone under
pressure, he seemed unusually composed as he sipped an ice coffee
in a nearby SoHo restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
