<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2108 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-STARCALLEDHENRY-REVIE     09-22 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARCALLEDHENRY-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOYLE'S `STAR' SHINES DARKLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A Star Called Henry''
</P>
<P>
   by Roddy Doyle
</P>
<P>
   Fiction
</P>
<P>
   Viking, $23.95
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans who remember Roddy Doyle at all don't even
remember him, but rather the ``The Commitments,'' a marvelous 1991
movie based on his novel of the same name.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Commitments,'' film and book, concerns a scruffy bunch of
Irish teens from a resolutely working-class area of Dublin north of
the River Liffey. Enamored of people like Wilson Pickett, they form
a band, argue a lot, play one gig and sunder.
</P>
<P>
   At once hilarious and bittersweet, ridiculous and utterly
believable, the novel established Doyle as an Irish writer to
watch; his dialogue was utterly perfect, his narrative brisk, his
tone wonderfully conversational.
</P>
<P>
   If you'd ever been to Dublin, you could again smell the streets,
hear the musical-but-gruff voices of the streets and the pubs, and
see the children (who possess the liveliest, laughingest eyes of
any children anywhere) and young women, who are the most beautiful
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Wonderful as ``The Commitments'' was, though, it was merely
Doyle establishing a voice: warming up, taking batting practice, as
it were. He's written four novels since then, each as good as or
better than the last, culminating with ``The Woman Who Walked Into
Doors,'' one of the bleakest, saddest looks at family abuse ever
set to print.
</P>
<P>
   But all are connected by being set in modern (or at least
recent) Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Star Called Henry,'' then, is a departure; the novel is set
in the Ireland of the first two decades of the century, a time of
monumental changes, including rebellion, civil war and the
establishment of the Irish nation.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all _ horrible tenement poverty, murders, back
streets, assassinations, underground rivers, dead children,
reprisals, ambushes and secret alliances _ moves Henry Smart. Born
of a mother slowly going crazy from seeing so many of her infants
die, and a one-legged dad who guards the door of a whorehouse and
kills people for a shadowy underworld character, Henry grows up
fending for himself on the streets from the age of 5. He is in the
thick of things during the failed rebellion of 1916, and the years
of guerrilla warfare that lead to the establishment of the Irish
nation.
</P>
<P>
   How to describe ``A Star Called Henry?'' Think, perhaps, of a
cross between ``Angela's Ashes'' and Thomas Berger's ``Little Big
Man'' _ mixed in with a killer's-eye-view of the Irish revolution
and a fascinating look at Dublin street life. In Smart, Doyle has
created a fantastic character who inhabits the Irish night and the
margins of history: An impossibly handsome man who becomes a legend
mere hours after his birth, Smart rides like a cypher through the
smoke and gunfire of the war years without being photographed, his
presence unrecorded, training rebels in the countryside, sleeping
with dozens of women (including, in one vivid scene, his onetime
teacher, Miss O'Shea), haunted by memories of his youth and the
death of his brother Victor.
</P>
<P>
   The narrative might well disappoint those who hunger for some
sort of moralistic story about the Revolution, or of a kid fighting
his way out of poverty, as in ``Ashes.'' To me, Smart's moral
ambivalence _ and Doyle's ability to put him in a particular place
in Irish history without turning him into a martyr or a symbol _ is
the book's greatest strength.
</P>
<P>
   Smart is motivated as much by lust and adventure and simply
getting the heck out of poverty as by any lofty moral ambitions.
he's more than happy to have sex with Miss O'Shea while the
Revolution rages around him, for example, and he abandons his
fellows at the first opportunity for the rivers running under
Dublin, which his dad once showed him.
</P>
<P>
   The product of a sad, restless age, Smart knows abandonment and
has no qualms about killing. Doyle makes him and his story
thoroughly believable and involving, both by playing his fictional
story against history and through the use of vivid dialogue,
scene-setting and a cast of characters that includes tenement
women, fledgling revolutionaries, a deadbeat father, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Star Called Henry'' is a gem, a novel one simply hates to
see end, but it is an uneasy one. It offers perhaps Doyle's finest
and most memorable and contrary character, thrown into a momentous
moment in European history and always trying to run one step ahead
of disaster _ a fully realized human being who will not be beaten
by a life he never asked for nor fully understands. Smart is cruel,
he is sweet, he is devious, he is unbearably sad. He lives by
night, and to read only a few pages is to be consumed by his
endless struggle to survive against all odds.
</P>
<P>
   And among today's novelists, Roddy Doyle is the man. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is the Star-Telegram's' pop music critic. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 1831EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0302 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2109 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-UPSIDE-DOWN-DANCE-ART     09-22 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPSIDE-DOWN-DANCE-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: SoHo restaurant.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's funny how all this attention feels on the inside,'' he
said. ``My dancers and I are more conscious of how some of us will
pay the rent and where's the next gig.'' He paused. ``I only hope
it brings other kinds of support.''
</P>
<P>
   His wish list includes fall and spring seasons in New York,
workshops in the winter and his own space, with a theater, where he
could establish an arts center. But right now, a consistent,
affordable place to rehearse would be quite enough.
</P>
<P>
   Relieved to put his worries aside for a moment, he talked about
the past. His love of dance goes back to childhood, he said. As a
boy, he and his cousins made up dances in his Brooklyn living room,
and he had fun at the Police Athletic League learning routines from
a dancer from the Broadway show ``The Wiz.''
</P>
<P>
   But when his mother went into labor with his younger brother on
the day he was supposed to audition at Dance Theater of Harlem, he
took it as an omen that he should forget such a ``sissy'' pursuit
and be ``a manly big brother.''
</P>
<P>
   An avid reader and writer, he decided to become a journalist
instead. His resolution didn't last long. A dance teacher talked
him out of it when he was 16, and he began studying ballet and
modern dance with Mary Anthony. In 1985, only 19, he established
his own troupe and named it Evidence because his dancers were
trained to embody ``evidence'' of their lives and times in their
movements. When he didn't get gigs, he performed with Ms. Anthony's
company and Jennifer Muller/The Works.
</P>
<P>
   Bessie Schonberg, the celebrated teacher, taught Brown to
choreograph. ``She was tough,'' he recalled. ``She'd ask: `What do
you want? What did you expect me to see?' If I was silent, she'd
say, `Speak up for yourself.''' He gained confidence and began to
tell stories about humanity, combining dance with danceable music
and poetry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Words,'' he explained, ``give people another element to grab
onto.'' His integration of movements from African and Caribbean
dance with his own sensuous, high-energy style began to make his
choreography more and more distinctive.
</P>
<P>
   His social commitment also set him apart. ``I want society to
get better,'' he said. ``I want to move things forward.'' His sense
of mission doesn't burden his work. The dance ``Ebony Magazine''
criticizes the values of glossy magazines but does so with humor.
``Choreography has to be about what can't be written or painted or
sung,'' he said. ``Ultimately, it has to be its own thing. I don't
want to tell you what I'm feeling; I want you to see what I'm
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's ideas come to him as images. ``Water'' originated in
Brown's mind as scenes of men in bloody clothing running down the
street and wrestling with one another. ``Make a contemporary
warrior dance,'' suggested his friend the composer Fahali Igbo,
when Brown revealed his thoughts. ``Show how young black men are
wasting their warrior natures and can do something better.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, water images came to him, memories of people he'd seen
washing for prayer in West Africa. He called Ms. Taylor, told her
his impressions and asked her to write something for his new work.
The next day, she delivered the 10-page poem that accompanies
``Water.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Joyce, ``Water'' won't be the same piece that was seen at
Jacob's Pillow last summer. ``I'm still changing it,'' Brown said.
``My dances aren't fixed; they're physical journeys. They're my
sole focus. Recently, a friend got angry with me because I said I
didn't want to perform at the Met. I guess I'm supposed to have
grand ambitions now.'' He laughed, as if to say, ``Isn't making
dances wonderful enough?''
</P>
</TEXT>
