<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2118 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-TRUDEAU-BUSH-TEX     09-22 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUDEAU-BUSH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOONESBURY CREATOR CAN'T RESIST BEATING AROUND THE BUSHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, D.C. _ Former President George Bush says cartoonist
Garry Trudeau is ``spoiled, derisive, ugly and nasty.'' Florida
Gov. Jeb Bush once called him ``the slime of the Earth.'' Barbara
Bush says the Doonesbury creator has devoted his life to ``cutting
down'' other people.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Bush family has another reason to scorn Trudeau _ in
fact, a whole series of them.
</P>
<P>
   After recently tweaking Texas Gov. George W. Bush over unproved
allegations of past drug use, Trudeau has devoted this week's comic
strips to a long-forgotten controversy from the days when he and
Bush were students at Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   The running gag revolves around the allegation _ first raised by
the Yale Daily News in 1967 _ that Bush and fellow members of the
Delta Kappa Epsilon fraternity were branded with a frat symbol.
Bush says it never happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any brands on me,'' Bush said in an October
interview with the Star-Telegram. ``There was a kind of rush-week
silliness that goes on, but there was no branding.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides and friends of Bush said the governor has not voiced any
opinion about Trudeau's version of Yale fraternity life. In
Thursday's comic, a character says that Bush ``once presided over
savage initiation rites that included beatings and the searing of
flesh.'' The plot line will continue through Saturday's strip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't read Trudeau's stuff, and I don't think George does
either,'' said Clay Johnson, who joined the Yale fraternity with
Bush and remains a close friend.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said the branding story stemmed from an initiation rite
that was intended to frighten pledges. Recruits were shown a
red-hot branding iron and told that they were going to be branded.
Instead, Johnson said, they were touched with a heated clothes
hanger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like taking a match, lighting it and touching the
blown-out match to your skin. They fake you out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush has kept his views about the current Doonesbury
series to himself, it is no secret that he shares his family's low
opinion of the cartoonist. Trudeau provoked the family's ire in
1984 with a cartoon suggesting that then-Vice President Bush had
placed his manhood in a blind trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to go up and kick the hell out of him, frankly,'' the
target of the barb admitted later, after he had cooled off. George
W. Bush took his complaints directly to Trudeau.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't like it. I didn't like it at all. And I made it
absolutely clear to Mr. Trudeau. And if he didn't like me telling
him that, I don't care,'' a still-seething Bush told an interviewer
a decade after the offending cartoon was published.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for United Features Syndicate, which distributes
Doonesbury, said Trudeau does not give interviews. But the Pulitzer
Prize-winning cartoonist talked about his feud with the Bushes in a
1991 essay in The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   Trudeau chided the Bushes for ``being so prickly,'' suggesting
that if they cannot laugh off his barbs, they should try to ignore
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``With me, it's never personal,'' he wrote. ``At the risk of
sounding like Sonny Corleone, it's my job. I've been doing the same
thing for over 20 years. I was whacking public figures back when
Dan Quayle was still whacking golf balls through law school.''
</P>
<P>
   Trudeau's career as a cartoonist began during his junior year at
Yale in 1968, the same year George W. Bush graduated. The comic
strip debuted in the Yale Daily News under the name Bull Tales, but
some of the characters have since become nationally known as part
of the Doonesbury cast.
</P>
<P>
   The list includes B.D., a helmet-wearing athlete based on Brian
Dowling, Yale's star quarterback during the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Trudeau's political satire that generates the most
controversy, especially with the Bush family. In addition to
targeting the former president, Trudeau has turned his sharpened
pen on Barbara Bush and three Bush sons, George W., Jeb and Neil.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, some Florida papers refused to run a Doonesbury episode
that accused Jeb Bush of trying to block a fraud investigation
involving a business associate. The allegation, which Doonesbury's
distributor later acknowledged was ``misleading,'' was particularly
sensitive because it came during the final days of Jeb Bush's first
campaign for Florida governor. He lost.
</P>
<P>
   Trudeau says he considers virtually everyone fair game for his
satire, with a few notable exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never, ever make fun of my wife, Jane Pauley,'' he said in
an Internet question-and-answer feature sponsored by United
Features Syndicate. ``A corollary of that is that I generally stay
away from broadcasters perceived as her direct competitors _ Diane
Sawyer, Barbara Walters, et. al., on the grounds that it would make
it harder for her to maintain a professional collegiality she
greatly values.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Bushes aren't bound by such constraints. Barbara
Bush couldn't resist a shot at Pauley and her husband when she felt
Pauley mistreated her during an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a perfect pair,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 1838EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
