<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0307 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2120 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LIVINGSTON-FILM-ART-2     09-22 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVINGSTON-FILM-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW A FILM INDIE SHOPS FOR A BACKER
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The meeting room on lower Broadway was alive with
movie people as the filmmaker Jennie Livingston settled in across
the table from Rudy Tjio, the head of acquisition of Time
Medienvertriebs G.m.b.H., a German film company. Based in Munich,
Tjio had gone to the Independent Feature Film Market, now in
session at the Angelika Film Center and various places around lower
Manhattan, looking for movies to back. Ms. Livingston, director of
the highly acclaimed documentary ``Paris Is Burning,'' had one to
propose.
</P>
<P>
   Noted films like ``Blood Simple,'' ``The Brothers McMullen,''
``Clerks,'' ``My Dinner With Andre,'' ``Roger and Me'' and
``Welcome to the Doll House'' were discovered at the market. So was
``Paris Is Burning.'' Her new film, ``Who's the Top?,'' hasn't been
made yet. Ms. Livingston needs money for that, and on the advice of
her producer, Ruth Charny, she has made a 15-minute clip of the
work in progress and entered it in the market's ``no borders''
program, which allows more experienced filmmakers to meet
representatives of hundreds of movie and television companies that
might finance their work.
</P>
<P>
   No one here needs to be reminded that it is tough to get a deal.
The market directory lists 335 projects _ finished features, works
in progress, shorts, scripts, documentaries _ by 381 filmmakers.
Some are newcomers. Ms. Livingston's reputation is based on one
film, which in the current commercial climate doesn't necessarily
open checkbooks for the next one.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, as well known as Ms. Livingston is, ``Paris Is
Burning'' is her only full-length film, and it is a documentary.
``Who's the Top?'' will be her first dramatic feature, a vastly
different proposition. Also, ``Paris Is Burning'' was released in
1991, and at times over the last several years she has been
involved in other fields and didn't promote herself as a filmmaker.
</P>
<P>
   This week, a deal would be nice, but she's not expecting one.
``They could be interested or they could just be tracking you,''
Ms. Livingston, 33, said.
</P>
<P>
   At the market the object of the screenings, meetings and
partying, which began Sept. 17 and ends Friday, usually is more to
make contacts that could pay off in the future. ``I'm really
confident but also really sanguine,'' she said. ``I go my path. If
something happens, something happens. If not, then I've done what I
can do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Paris Is Burning,'' about competitions among gay black and
Latino men at drag balls in New York, was shown at the market in
1989 and released commercially in 1991. It made $4 million at the
box office and helped widen opportunities for gay films in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Tjio's company distributed ``Paris Is Burning'' in Germany. But
that takes Ms. Livingston only so far. ``Who's the Top?'' is about
sexual stress in a lesbian relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``How important is story?'' Tjio asked Ms. Livingston at their
sit-down. A press release prepared for the market describes ``Who's
the Top?'' as ``the first lesbian S-and-M musical comedy.'' Tjio
had read a synopsis but hadn't seen the clip, which includes an
appearance by Steve Buscemi, who may have a role, and the clip will
be screened at the Angelika. (Videotapes have also been available
in the market library.)
</P>
<P>
   Storytelling being everything to Ms. Livingston, she carefully
explained her film to Tjio. One of the women is fairly
straightforward in her needs, while the other acts out her kinky
proclivities in dream fantasies staged as musical production
numbers. Ms. Livingston mentioned Federico Fellini's ``8{'' and
Luis Bunuel's ``Belle de Jour'' as kindred films. In the scenes
already made, a bottom is spanked and dancers move to suggestive
lyrics. ``I used to think kinky sex was a cure for capitalism; now
I make whips for a living,'' a woman says.
</P>
<P>
   Tjio wanted to know about the sadomasochism. How much was there?
Ms. Charny, the producer, told him that Ms. Livingston saw
sexuality and eroticism through a particular esthetic sensibility.
``She takes things that are taboo and makes them familiar,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Then Ms. Livingston got straight to the point of the film,
saying, ``They love each other and have to work this out.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview before her meeting with Tjio, she acknowledged
that movie companies were cautious about sadomasochism but said
that this element did not carry the film. ``It's a story about a
couple of women who don't see eye to eye sexually,'' she said.
``How do you deal with having different sexual inclinations? It's
an adult issue that any person who has been married or in a mature
relationship has encountered.''
</P>
<P>
   Tjio asked about budget. Ms. Livingston said they were planning
on $1.2 million. They have already spent about $30,000 on the clip.
Tjio requested a tape and the script. Did he seem interested?
``Most of these things are long shots,'' Ms. Charny said later.
``They're to establish long-term relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Gay themes are not the obstacles they once were in raising
money, Ms. Livingston said. ``People are way sophisticated,'' she
added. ``No one's going to be homophobic if they think they can
make money.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ms. Livingston says, there are hurdles for women. ``The
carpet is laid out for a young male with talent,'' she said.
``Blocks are put up for the young female.'' She said, ``For anybody
who's trying to present a point of view that's original or
political or tell a story in an unusual narrative way, it's not
easy.''
</P>
<P>
   All films at the market, from finished features to snippets, are
screened at the Angelika, and Thursday. Ms. Livingston will have
her turn. ``What's so great about having this clip is that you can
like it or not,'' she said. ``The advantage is that I'm not saying,
`Imagine this or imagine that.' I'm saying `You see it. Take it or
leave it. Jump on the bandwagon or don't.'''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the week, a dozen film companies had already requested
meetings with Ms. Livingston and Ms. Charny, including Fine Line,
Miramax, Artisan Entertainment, Fox Searchlight and Film Four from
England.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in some cases people are going to be serious
contenders for paying for this movie,'' Ms. Livingston said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The movie companies also feel pressure to identify suitable
projects at the market. ``It's hard to find films that will have a
theatrical life,'' said Peter Broderick, president of Next Wave
Films, a 2-year-old company that is owned by the Independent Film
Channel and backs movies for theatrical distribution. ``When we
find a film like that, we essentially get married to the
filmmaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Will they get hitched to Jennie Livingston? Next Wave, based in
Santa Monica, Calif., has five representatives at the market. All
had seen her clip by the time they gathered with Ms. Livingston and
Ms. Charny on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were great at the meeting,'' Broderick said. ``It's a
totally unique clip, very stylishly done, not like any movie I've
seen before. That always gets our attention.'' The sadomasochism
presented no problem. ``Some people felt that `Paris Is Burning'
was shocking,'' he said, ``but it changed the way people thought.
This one will make people think differently about gender issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Money was a problem, however. ``The budget is higher than Next
Wave is ready to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In 1988 Ms. Livingston, then 22 and a recent graduate of Yale,
arrived with a trailer and a flier for ``Paris Is Burning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a couple of meetings out of it,'' she said. ``It didn't
lead to anything, but it was a good experience to be out there
hustling.''
</P>
<P>
   After finding backing elsewhere, she returned with a complete
film in 1989 and screened it at the Angelika. A run at the Film
Forum led to appearances at the 1990 Sundance and Toronto Film
Festivals. The next year ``Paris Is Burning'' was on many
10-best-film lists.
</P>
<P>
   Since then Ms. Livingston has been working in and around film.
She wrote a script that went unproduced. ``It was a satire,'' she
said. ``We couldn't get the money. It happens to every filmmaker,
the pet project that doesn't get made until 10 years later. That
ate up two or three years in terms of focus.'' Later she made short
films, went to Germany on a grant and lectured at Yale and many
film schools. Now she is writing a documentary for the American
Movie Classics Channel on film fans and the nature of celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   For a while she questioned her resolve. ``Is this film stuff,
which is so much about performance and competition, something that
I can keep doing, knowing how difficult it is when you tell stories
people don't necessarily want to hear?'' she said. ``In my time of
searching, I decided, yeah, this is what I want to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
