<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2125 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-TOBACCO-SUIT23-COX     09-22 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-SUIT23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. SUES TOBACCO INDUSTRY TO RECOVER HEALTH COSTS
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Charging cigarette makers with a ``campaign of
fraud and deceit'' stretching back to 1954, the Justice Department
sued the tobacco industry Wednesday for federal health costs
totaling hundreds of billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   An industry spokesman said the action was a politically
motivated attempt to raise money through the courts and to sink the
$50 billion cigarette industry. He said it would fight the suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not succumb to politically correct extortion. We will
not settle this lawsuit,'' said Greg Little, associate general
counsel for the nation's largest tobacco company, Philip Morris
Inc., of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``This lawsuit should be dismissed, and we believe it will,''
Little told reporters at a press conference to rebut the lawsuit's
allegations. ``We are right on the law, we're right on the facts,
and we fully expect to prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton _ who telegraphed the possibility of the
lawsuit last January in his annual State of the Union address _
stayed mostly out of sight Wednesday, nursing a hoarse voice.
</P>
<P>
   Through his press office, Clinton issued a terse statement
supporting the suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Justice Department is taking the right course of action,''
the statement said in part. ``It is time for America's taxpayers to
have their day in court.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's spokesman, Joe Lockhart, made clear that the
administration also plans to press the cigarette industry on
another front: higher cigarette taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to continue to push it,'' Lockhart said of a White
House proposal to gradually raise cigarette taxes by up to 50 cents
a pack. ``I think you'll hear more about it in the days to come.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference to announce the lawsuit, Attorney General
Janet Reno denied that it had political overtones. She said it was
an effort, ``based on the evidence and the law,'' to recover money
that taxpayers have spent to care for smokers who were lied to for
decades by cigarette makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the past 45 years, the companies that manufacture and sell
tobacco have waged an intentional coordinated campaign of fraud and
deceit,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have conducted themselves without regard to the truth,
without regard to the law, and without regard to the health and
life of the American people,'' said Reno. ``The consequences have
been staggering.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno asserted that 400,000 Americans die each year from smoking
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result, each year the federal government alone spends
more than $20 billion in taxpayer money just to treat diseases
caused by cigarettes,'' said Reno. ``Today, on behalf of the
taxpayer, we're asking the tobacco companies to pay their fair
share.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department suit, filed Wednesday in U.S. District
Court here, names Philip Morris; the R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co., of
Winston-Salem, N.C.; the Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp., of
Louisville, Ky.; the Lorillard Tobacco Co., of Greensboro, N.C.;
the Liggett Group, Inc., of Durham, N.C.; the American Tobacco Co.,
of Louisville, Ky., and five other companies.
</P>
<P>
   The suit alleges that the companies conspired, beginning with a
1954 meeting at the Plaza Hotel in New York, to deceive the
American public over the health risks of smoking, conceal the
addictive qualities of nicotine and target children in their
marketing and advertising campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all relevant respects, defendants acted in concert with
each other in order to further their fraudulent scheme,'' the
Justice Department alleges in its 88-page filing.
</P>
<P>
   In a 43-page appendix to the suit, the Justice Department
alleges 116 separate violations of federal racketeering laws by one
or more of the companies named in the complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Under the provisions of the federal Racketeer Influence and
Corrupt Organizations statute, the United States may force
violators to repay so-called ``ill-gotten profits,'' shown to be
earned as a result of fraudulent practices.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the federal Medicare Care Recovery Act allows the
U.S. government to sue to recover medical costs in cases in which a
third party causes injury or disease to a person and the U.S.
government is authorized by law to pay for the victim's medical
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was applauded by public health advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It once again puts the pressure on the tobacco companies,
first of all, to pay for a greater fraction of the harm that
they've caused,'' said Richard Daynard, chairman of the Tobacco
Products Liability Project, which has been advocating legal action
against the cigarette makers since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are companies that have made hundreds of billions of
dollars over the years in profits, while they were imposing
trillions of dollars of financial costs _ and that's just financial
costs _ on the country,'' said Daynard, a professor of law at
Northeastern University in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the case has a sound legal basis,'' said Daynard.
``There's no question the factual predicate is there.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris's lawyer, Little, disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   He accused the Clinton administration of ``blatant'' politics
and said the suit suggests that ``this is an administration that is
trying to run these particular manufacturers out of business.''
</P>
<P>
   Short of that, Little said, the suit has the potential to leave
the cigarette makers too strapped to pay debts they owe to
individual states under a series of legal settlements reached over
the past year.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1998, the industry reached a settlement with the
attorneys general from 46 states under which the cigarette makers
would pay an estimated $196 billion between 1998 and 2025. The
money would be shared among the states.
</P>
<P>
   Four other states _ Florida, Texas, Minnesota and Mississippi _
are to share an estimated $40 billion in industry payments under
separate settlements.
</P>
<P>
   The payments to states are based in large part on the
tobacco-related medical bills paid out by Medicaid, the federal
health insurance program for low-income families.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said federal programs other than Medicaid _ such as
Medicare, the federal health insurance program for the elderly, and
the Department of Veterans Affairs _ have also accrued huge
tobacco-related expenses over the years.
</P>
<P>
   She gave no dollar estimate for those expenses. But Clinton, in
his January speech, said overall federal outlays due to
smoking-related illness and disease totalled in the ``hundreds of
billions of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the industry agreed to pay an estimated $368.5 billion
over 25 years to the federal government. That proposal collapsed in
Congress, however, after lawmakers sought additional provisions
that the tobacco industry rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
