<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2126 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-GAY-AIDS-FILMS-$ADV26     09-22 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-AIDS-FILMS-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAMATIZING THE AIDS CRISIS WHEN IT SEEMS PASSE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 26) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
David Bahr most recently wrote for Arts &AMP; Leisure about the film
``The Acid House.'' 
 By DAVID BAHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, ``Three Thousand Scripts Against a Virus''
ruffled more than a few feathers in France. Begun by the French
government as a screenplay competition to promote AIDS awareness,
the project was intended to produce a series of AIDS-related
public-service shorts for television and movie theaters. Of several
thousand submitted scripts, approximately 30 were made.
</P>
<P>
   Yet hardly any involved gay characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really shocking and absurd,'' says Pierre Salvadori, a
French director and critic of the project who is himself not gay.
``I think one of the films dealt with a bisexual. But for the most
part, they totally ignored a major part of the population that was
sick or infected.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the Association of Lesbian and Gay Pride Films, an
activist group, responded by organizing its own screenplay
competition, also financed by the French government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought that we should do something to complement the first
project because there was nothing geared to the gay and lesbian
population in the context of AIDS,'' says Pascal Dutertre, the
association's president. The result of their politically charged
labor is ``L'Amour Est a Reinventer'' (``Love Reinvented''), a
series of 10 short films first shown on television and then
released theatrically in France in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal was to have these films originally shown on French
television _ something organized by the state to sensitize a very
large audience,'' Dutertre says. ``But it was broadcast late in the
evening, so it was pretty much a failure in terms of our original
objective. But theatrically it's been one of the greatest successes
of its type, compared to public service projects like those on
drugs and racism.'' A year after its release, it's still running.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``L'Amour Est a Reinventer,'' which opens in New York on
Friday with two additional shorts _ ``Close To,'' by the American
director David Ottenhouse, and ``Cherish,'' by the Australian
filmmaker Stephen Jones _ is an AIDS-crisis project arriving in
America in a post-crisis climate.
</P>
<P>
   Made in 1996, the French films were in production just as
protease inhibitors, the powerful combination of drug therapies,
came into use. Since then, AIDS-related deaths have declined
significantly, and gay writers like Andrew Sullivan and Dan Savage
have even proclaimed that the health crisis is over.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Castle, the co-president of Jour de Fete Films, the American
distributor of ``L'Amour Est a Reinventer,'' acknowledges that
movies about AIDS seem increasingly passe. ``Obviously the days of
`Longtime Companion' are over,'' he says, referring to the 1990
drama about a group of dying HIV-infected gay men. ``And no one is
making those films anymore anyway. ``There's so much optimism now
in terms of people getting better that the last thing people want
to be reminded of is that you die from it and people still die from
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Castle believes that ``L'Amour Est a Reinventer'' remains
relevant, both as a work of activism and as an auteur showcase.
``Many of the films are exceptionally strong,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Dutertre agrees: ``Of course, in terms of drug treatments, these
films are a bit old. But in terms of the gay community and the
artistic quality of the films, they remain interesting and
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the most effective shorts are Jean-Claude Guiguet's ``Une
Nuit Ordinaire'' (``An Ordinary Night''), about a man who visits
his lover in the hospital; Salvadori's ``Un Moment'' (``One
Moment''), about a couple who engage in unsafe sex in the heat of
passion, and Anne Fountaine's ``Tapin du Soi'' (``Night Hustler''),
about a condom-toting male prostitute looking for affection.
</P>
<P>
   These succeed not because of any message but because of their
skillfully rendered narratives. In fact, with ``Une Nuit
Ordinaire,'' one of the project's more affecting works, AIDS takes
a back seat to the film's prime focus: the tender, erotic love
shared by two men.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 1843EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0312 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2127 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-GAY-AIDS-FILMS-2NDTAK     09-22 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-AIDS-FILMS-2NDTAKE-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: two men.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We worked on the screenplay and made the story about an
amorous relationship that went beyond sex,'' says Guiguet. His
short shows a young man on a bicycle on his way to make love to his
partner in the hospital while singing to a recording of ``J'ai
Rendez-Vous Avec Vous'' (``I Have a Date With You'') by the postwar
chanteuse Patachou.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was to conjure death while it was imminent,'' Guiguet
says, ``but to push back the inevitable by a few hours, showing how
love and desire are the only means of staying alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Guiguet avoids making any explicit references to AIDS and death
in his film, a choice, he believes, that allows the film to
transcend time and place. ``The film was completed in 1996,'' he
says. ``The therapies had just come out, and no one yet knew if
they were going to work. But because there are no rules about
healing, I left it open in my film.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly universal, Salvadori's ``Un Moment,'' shot from the
perspective of an unseen protagonist who engages in unprotected sex
with a younger man, raises the issue of condom-use fatigue. ``It
shows a moment of passionate merging and loss of responsibility,''
says Salvadori, ``which is followed by isolation and fear. After
the sex, the boy turns his back on the man, leaving him to himself.
It's absolutely unsentimental. Both heterosexual and homosexual
audiences have responded to it because there is an immediate
identification with what happens. It shows something very human.''
</P>
<P>
   Originally 56 minutes long, ``L'Amour Est a Reinventer'' was
extended to 72 minutes with the two extra shorts, making it long
enough for an American release. The first of the two, ``Close To,''
is based on excerpts from David Wojnarowicz's book ``Memories That
Smell Like Gasoline.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, about a young man who has anonymous sex with a
deaf-mute pickpocket, was screened at the Cannes and Toronto film
festivals. The closing film, ``Cherish,'' which opened at the 1998
Gay and Lesbian Film Festival in San Francisco, concerns a white
Australian mourning the death of his Aboriginal lover. Although
neither film originated with the French project, they were chosen
by Jour de Fete for their related themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The collection shows the whole range of what happens with
HIV,'' explains Castle. ```Close To' reveals the dangerous elements
of anonymous sex, while `Cherish' shows the aftermath, how one
carries on with the spirit of a person lost.''
</P>
<P>
   For Jones, who at 35 has lost several friends to the disease,
there was a particular pertinence to his film's being included in
the program. ``I was motivated by an awareness that a lot of people
haven't actually dealt with their grief in the gay community,'' he
says. ``In making `Cherish,' it was important for me to do
something useful with my grief and to tell my generation's stories
to younger people.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who wrote ``Cherish'' with the Aboriginal poet Romaine
Moreton, hopes his film encourages others to tell their histories.
He feels that many important films about AIDS have yet to be made.
``I think there is a need to look beyond the western world,'' he
says. ``Those are the people now most in need of help and having
their stories heard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
