<HEADER>
A2150 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-TRAFFIC-0923-COX     09-22 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAFFIC-0923-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GROUP SAYS ROAD CONSTRUCTION PROJECTS OFTEN INCREASE TRAFFIC
CONGESTION
 &HT;    By RAVEN HILL
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Creeping along through road construction projects
is worth the hassle once they're completed, right? Not necessarily,
according to a new study being released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Construction delays often cost drivers more time in the long
run, say officials at the Surface Transportation Policy Project, a
private group that commissioned the study.
</P>
<P>
   Using figures provided by state transportation departments and
selected case studies, the group concluded that new, improved roads
rarely result in easier commutes.
</P>
<P>
   Results indicate that road expansion projects ``often deliver
scant time savings to people who use the road everyday, while
allowing and even stimulating significantly more traffic once the
construction project is completed,'' the group said.
</P>
<P>
   As a rule, most communities haven't adequately discussed the
costs and benefits per individual driver, said Barbara McCann, a
spokesperson for the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most planning is done by engineers who focus on traffic flow,
average daily traffic and level of service, which doesn't address
the concerns of individuals and quality of life issues,'' McCann
said.
</P>
<P>
   McCann said that while easing traffic congestion is often given
as the reason for road expansion projects, they don't always result
in faster commutes. Once the projects are completed, they can end
up luring more cars on the road, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the new road has done is bought a few years of time,''
McCann said.
</P>
<P>
   The project team recommended that transportation officials
solicit more public comment about alternatives to construction
projects. They also urged that officials place a higher priority on
reconfiguring roads to reduce construction delays and that they
explore other ways to relieve congestion during construction
projects. Road expansion projects should not be undertaken until
officials consider the impact of construction delays and increased
travel, the group said.
</P>
<P>
   However, some transportation officials questioned whether the
group could authoritatively speak on such issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here you have a self-appointed transportation planning group
in Washington, D.C., that's telling local governments how to
address their transportation issues,'' said Matthew Jeanneret, a
spokesman for the American Road and Transportation Builders
Association. ``Road construction projects are not a haphazard
process.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to allowing for public comment and participation,
Jeanneret said road construction projects must also adhere to state
and local regulations, as well as environmental concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanneret said the group's goal appears to be delaying
transportation projects, which he said is not the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kills,'' he said. ``The (U.S.) Department of
Transportation estimates that poor and obsolete roads result in
12,000 deaths each year. By delaying them, you run the risk of
prolonging unsafe roads and having worse congestion and
pollution.''
</P>
<P>
   He called the study ``a slap in the face'' to local communities
and governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know best what their needs are and how to evaluate
them,'' Jeanneret said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
