<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LULAC-KIDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LULAC URGES HISPANIC PARENTS TO TURN OFF TV AS WAY OF HELPING
SCHOOLCHILDREN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Hispanic schoolchildren spend too much time
watching television and not enough time doing homework, a Hispanic
civil rights group said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   So the League of United Latin American Citizens is encouraging
Hispanic parents to turn off the television, especially during
hours children should be doing homework.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time that Hispanic parents and Texas schools change their
habits,'' said Linda Chavez, LULAC's regional director from Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The turn-off-the-tube effort is the first component of an
education plan that LULAC plans to introduce by the end of the
year. Its education efforts will focus on improving Hispanic
children's performance in Texas schools, and the group's main
thrust will involve bilingual programs in Texas schools and school
dropout rates.
</P>
<P>
   LULAC offered no specifics on how it might address its concerns
with bilingual education or dropout rates.
</P>
<P>
   However, Robert Gamboa, LULAC's Waco director, said the
education establishment has failed to deal with those issues.
</P>
<P>
   Gamboa said LULAC will form a task force of Hispanic groups and
legislative leaders to address school &UR;  &LR; dropout concerns.  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; He called the dropout rate ``extremely tragic. We've had any
number of years in allowing the public school system of the state
of Texas to make an effort to address the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Texas Education Agency in the past has obscured the
dropout problem by categorizing children who leave school in a
variety of ways.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander earlier this week
announced the formation of a Public Education Integrity Task Force
to study, among other things, what she termed ``bogus dropout
rates.''
</P>
<P>
   LULAC's call for Hispanic parents to get their children to spend
more time doing homework and less time glued to the television
comes during a 10-day boycott of major television networks. The
boycott was initiated by the NAACP and the National Council of La
Raza and is supported by LULAC. Dubbed a ``brownout'' by Hispanics,
the boycott started Sept. 15 in Houston and extends through
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are continuously portrayed in negative roles (on
television) _ that is when we do have roles,'' Chavez said.
</P>
<P>
   LULAC and other organizations criticized the season premier of
NBC-TV's ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' in which a white character referred to a
Hispanic maid in a racially derogatory manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prime time television not only robs our children of valuable
study time, but it also erodes their positive sense of identity,''
Chavez added.
</P>
<P>
   However, LULAC representatives didn't offer specific suggestions
on how many hours a day children should be allowed to watch
television, saying that decision should be made by each family.
</P>
<P>
   A survey earlier this year by Nielsen Media Research found that
American teen-agers spend, on average, 3 hours a day watching TV,
and children ages 2 to 11 spend about 7 1/2 hours a day viewing
television.
</P>
<P>
   Another study conducted in 1998 by the University of Michigan's
Institute for Social Research found that overall, children average
about 90 minutes in front of the television on weekdays. But that
study concluded TV time occupied far more of a child's time than
schoolwork or reading.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
