<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-ZUCKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCIS J. ZUCKER, 77; ACCLAIMED PHYSICIST, PHILOSOPHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Francis J. Zucker of Belmont, Mass., a noted physicist and
philosopher, died Friday at his home. He was 77.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Vienna, Mr. Zucker came to the United States in 1938
and received a bachelor's degree in physics from Columbia
University in 1943.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, he taught physics to Air Force cadets at
Hamilton College in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   He received a master's degree from Harvard University in 1946
and joined the Air Force Cambridge Research Laboratory, where he
worked in electromagnetic theory, focusing on antenna theory and
surface waves.
</P>
<P>
   In 1965, Mr. Zucker's interest in the philosophy of science took
him to Germany to study with renowned physicist and science
philosopher Carl Friedrich von Weizsaecker.
</P>
<P>
   He then joined the Planck Institute near Munich until 1978, when
he returned to Boston to rejoin the Air Force laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   A mainstay of the Boston Colloquium at Boston University, Mr.
Zucker was also the author of articles on applied physics and on
the philosophy of science. With Robert E. Collins, he co-edited the
two-volume ``Antenna Handbook,'' considered the definitive work in
the antenna field.
</P>
<P>
   He also translated von Weizsaecker's book ``The Unity of
Nature'' into English and co-edited a collection of essays,
``Goethe and the Sciences, A Reappraisal.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Zucker leaves his wife, Ilona K. of Belmont; and a sister,
Lily Munford of Pleasantville, N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 1902EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
