A2163 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-BARAK-GERMANY-BOS &LR;      09-22 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARAK-GERMANY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ISRAELI PRIME MINISTER TOURS WWII DEATH CAMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ When he campaigned for chancellor last year, Gerhard
Schroeder suggested that Germany had to move beyond its past, to
stop wallowing in the guilt felt over what happened in Germany
under the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, as he accompanied Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak around what used to be the Sachsenhausen concentration camp,
the German chancellor acknowledged there was no letting go of a
legacy that includes the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only one way to deal with this unimaginable crime. We
must remind ourselves and everyone else of it again and again,''
Schroeder said. ``There must never be another Sachsenhausen,
another Auschwitz, another Treblinka, in any place on earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by their wives and three survivors of Sachsenhausen
who now live in Israel, the two leaders entered the camp by passing
through a black wrought iron gate with the Nazi admonition that
``Work Will Set You Free.'' In fact, it killed about half the
200,000 slave laborers who were interned in Sachsenhausen between
1936 and 1945, about 10 percent of them Jewish. Some were murdered,
others literally worked to death.
</P>
<P>
   Like Barak, Schroeder wore a skull cap, and both men laid
wreaths to commemorate the victims. While Schroeder said Germans
should never forget what happened at Sachsenhausen, Barak, Israel's
most decorated soldier, said Jews would never allow themselves to
be in such a position again. Among those listening were two
grandchildren of Sachsenhausen survivors who now serve in the
Israeli Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never will we leave ourselves without the means to defend our
lives or at the mercy of other peoples,'' said Barak. ``We will
always defend ourselves and every Jew, wherever they may be. We
swear that as long as we can still draw breath, there will be never
be another Auschwitz, no Jews on death marches to the gas chambers,
no mass graves.''
</P>
<P>
   Yirak Bahir, 76, was the only member of his family to survive
Sachsenhausen. A Polish Jew now living in Israel, he brought his
grandson along and reflected on how he survived when so many did
not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was either an accident or a miracle, but in any case it
wasn't any thanks to God, because God wasn't here,'' Bahir said.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder and Barak seemed equally anxious to have the Israeli
leader be the first foreign head of state to visit Berlin since the
city resumed its position as the German capital this month.
</P>
<P>
   For Schroeder, it was an important symbolic way of reclaiming
Berlin, the place where the Final Solution was devised. It also
answered critics who say Schroeder is so determined to reposition
Germany as an international power that he shies away from
confronting the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   For Barak, it was his first visit to continental Europe since
taking office in July. While he offered warm words for the German
democracy that has matured over the last half-century, he also said
Germany had an obligation to be vigilant against the sort of
extremists who torched an exhibit at the camp shortly after one of
his predecessors, Yitzhak Rabin, made an official visit in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a duty to crush any'' Nazi ``and anti-Semitic bud,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barak left Germany Wednesday for Paris, where he and French
officials will meet to map out a way for the resumption of peace
talks between Israel and Syria after a three-year hiatus.
</P>
<P>
   Barak called his visit to the concentration camp ``a moral
necessity,'' and turned down offers to meet with German business
leaders and visit the Reichstag, the newly rechristened home of
German parliament, so he could go to Sachsenhausen.
</P>
<P>
   He and Schroeder urged German businesses to settle compensation
claims filed by those who worked as slave laborers under the Nazi
regime. About 35 German firms have indicated they will contribute
to a compensation fund, but many others want assurances that they
will not be subject to additional claims if they become part of the
fund.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and his wife, Nava, brought along three survivors of
Sachsenhausen, including 82-year-old Eli Carmel, who described his
return to Germany as the end of his exodus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
