A2177 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-KIDS:CHURCH-KILLINGS-     09-22 1892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS:CHURCH-KILLINGS-REACT-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AREA KIDS' REACTIONS TO FORT WORTH CHURCH KILLINGS 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 By JESSAMY BROWN 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a gunman opened fire in a church in Fort Worth, Texas,
killing seven people before taking his own life, children and
adults in this North Texas community reacted with shock, hurt and
anger. Here, students from local schools share their responses to
the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   I just moved here, and we're two blocks away from the church.
And we were at the church last week for a meeting. I was just
floored. I'm probably not going back there ever. I was so freaked
out, I couldn't sleep. I was just scared. There were helicopters
circling all night, police cars, lights. There was commotion until
4 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   You hear about Columbine, you hear about Kentucky _ that's
really sad, but it's in another state. But when it's down the
street, it hits close to home.
</P>
<P>
   I saw my friend on TV. She was on there crying. They were
putting cameras in people's faces, especially when parents would
find their kids. I think it's insensitive. People want a little
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   A church is a holy place. People let their guards down. They're
praying. That's a place you wouldn't want to have to worry about
getting shot.
</P>
<P>
   _ Asha McElfish, 11, home school, Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   I think it's senseless. I see no reason for this. It's just a
waste. I feel sad about it but I don't feel that disturbed about
it. It's going to happen, and there isn't anything we can do about
it. I like to think they are in a better place now.
</P>
<P>
   _ Adam Douglas, 17, high school, Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   I just think it's sad that you can't even pray without being
interrupted by somebody crazy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Justin Kirby, 12, junior high school, Arlington, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably one of the most appalling things I've ever seen. I
really hate to see this happen. You would think you could go to
church and be safe and have sanctuary. This is going to affect a
lot of people for a long time. This is going to scare a lot of
people away from going to church.
</P>
<P>
   _ Evan Sustaire, 15, high school, Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to believe because, after hearing about all these
high school shootings, it's not a shock to hear about shootings at
schools. But at a church _ it's somewhere safe, where people can be
at peace. Now, that's been violated. If you can't be safe at
church, where can you be safe?
</P>
<P>
   The next day at school, people talked about it. They tried to
keep it out of the classroom, but it kind of loomed over the whole
day. I know people who went to see one of the counselors. They
needed to talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   _Angelica Lara, 15, high school, Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   I was just baffled. I was surprised because it was a church, and
there were a bunch of kids in there. I watched the news until it
was time to go to bed because some friends had talked about going
and it was all crazy in the beginning and nobody knew who was safe.
At school today, we spent the whole World Geography period talking
about it.
</P>
<P>
   Shayna Reasoner, 14, high school, Azle, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   You just saw students crying all day. We talked about it in
every class. Our teachers feel it's best to go back to routine.
They said we'll take it slow. There was counseling available
because it was just so close to home. I think people just all
needed to be together.
</P>
<P>
   At my synagogue, after the shootings in Los Angeles, it's kind
of like you're in prison. Doors are locked, there are security
guards. It's just really scary. It makes me feel safer but it
doesn't feel like a religious service anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Illana Stein, 15, high school, Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   We have lost that feeling of being safe in school, being safe
when you go outside. But the church was the last place you could
feel safe. I've never felt unsafe going to church. Now that's taken
away from us.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Chapman, 16, high school, Hurst, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   I think that these shootings represent a flaw in American
society. This flaw may not be caused by any one thing. It's a
combination of many factors _ guns, bad families, lack of religion,
etc. each contributing equally to the problem. Until America can
come together and take stock of itself and decide what should
happen to get rid of this violence in society, and then act on it,
nothing will change. It's useless to point fingers. We've had
fingerpointing for years. Now we need action.
</P>
<P>
   Thane ``Woody'' Tuttle, 16, private school, Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   I used to go to that church for about five years, when we lived
in Fort Worth. When I found out I was really upset. Someone was
maybe unhappy about their life and they took it out on them. It was
a real shock. It's devastating.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Lohmer, 16, high school, Meridian, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   To me it's just really scary because I also go to a Baptist
church. That Wednesday night service was really a time to reflect
on what we did at See You at the Pole, and people were excited.
Now, Fort Worth is going to be synonymous with this tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   It makes you come to the realization of `What if this is my last
day? What would I say to my friend if I knew she was going to get
shot dead today?' Things do happen and you can't plan everything.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kassi Nopratvarakorn, 16, high school, Keller, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   If we're not safe at school, if we're not safe at home because
of the drive-by shootings, and if we're not safe at church, where
are we safe? That's the place where you least expect to be looking
over your shoulder. It is kind of scary to know it could be
anywhere. You never know who could be carrying a gun _ some kid,
some crazy person.
</P>
<P>
   _ Christopher Kellerman, 14, junior high school, Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   It's really sad that this stuff has happened so much that I
didn't hear much talk about it at school. It was no surprise. It's
getting to be every other week nowadays. I went home from a
Fellowship of Christian Athletes meeting and the TV was on. I just
turned the TV off. It is just depressing. It's not even a shock.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Luper, 17, high school, Hurst.
</P>
<P>
   I was in our own church rally at the time I heard about it, and
it scared me. I think everyone in the auditorium tensed up, and
every noise we heard, we looked behind us to make sure it wasn't a
gunshot. I was angry that some man had the nerve to go into a
church and display his hatred and anger. It gives me a sense of
peace about the situation because they were in the House of God,
and I know God was watching over everyone and is taking care of the
ones that are now with him.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shelley Nelson, 15, high school, Denton, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   I think it's sad that this is what the world has come to today.
I think it's devastating when such innocent people die. When the
shooting happened in Colorado, I know I thought, `How sad,' but it
really didn't hit me. To know this happened just 45 minutes away
really hits me at home.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jordan Wohlgemuth, 17, High School, Denton
</P>
<P>
   Fifth grade students at Greenbriar Elementary School, in Fort
Worth, wrote essays on their feelings about the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   I feel very sorry for the people at Wedgwood Baptist Church. I
hope our school doesn't have a shooting because this world is just
getting worse. I wish guns weren't invented because they are
tragic.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jeremy McGee.
</P>
<P>
   I feel very sad for that church because that could have been my
church and I could have been killed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mikael Cole.
</P>
<P>
   Where was God that night?
</P>
<P>
   _ Abraham Reyes.
</P>
<P>
   When I first heard about the shooting at the church I was
shocked. There were several people killed because of one man's
anger. Now I am scared. I wonder if that will happen to me. I am
sad because my baby sitter's best friend and other people were
killed in that tragedy. One question keeps going through my mind:
Why?
</P>
<P>
   _ Cayce Oswalt.
</P>
<P>
   I feel sorry for the families of the victims. It was a real
tragedy. Hopefully, that man was a Christian and just had the devil
in him.
</P>
<P>
   _ Megan McCuller.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing in the news what happened at the Wedgwood Baptist
Church, I was very sad for all the people that were in the church
when this happened. Many children were there. Some of my friends
were there. God bless everybody.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gustavo Perez.
</P>
<P>
   My sister's friend died that night and he wasn't even 20. When I
found out about what happened I started to cry. I miss him.
</P>
<P>
   _ Patricia Graham.
</P>
<P>
   I feel sorry for the people who died that were in the church.
And I feel sorry because the people that died had more time to
live. And why would somebody kill in the house of Jesus?
</P>
<P>
   _ Ramiro Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   I thought that the Wedgwood Baptist Church shooting was not fair
at all. My family members' friends died in this tragic shooting.
Wedgwood School members were bawling over lost family.
</P>
<P>
   _ Markus Viramontes.
</P>
<P>
   This really affected me, because it is a rare possibility that a
thing like this could happen in a church. My opinion of this
terrible incident is that it was an ignorant act. It is cruel to
take someone's life and then take your own.
</P>
<P>
   _ Branda Williams.
</P>
<P>
   When I discovered the dreadful news that Wedgwood Baptist Church
had experienced a dreadful shooting massacre, I was in complete
devastation. Some of my fellow neighbors had been at the church on
the day of the shooting. One of them was a horsehair from being
shot, and another one got shattered by glass as the pipe bomb went
off. The gunman had absolutely no right to interrupt a prayer
meeting and concert to kill people because of his own emotions and
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   My heart was crying out to those emotionally and physically
hurt. To those who were not there and to those who were, now is a
time of hope and prayer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Justin Groth.
</P>
<P>
   I think it was a tragic moment for everyone. It also made me
mad, upset and angry. This was the worst moment of my life, because
I have friends who go to that church, but they did not attend the
evening of the killings. Thank heavens! I was thankful that he did
not demolish the church, and I'm glad the policemen got there
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Brandon Sims.
</P>
<P>
   My mom explained to me that bad things can happen anywhere, and
from her verbal lesson, I learned to be prepared for anything that
happens.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tori Whitmore.
</P>
<P>
   This bothered me terribly. I felt sorry for everyone who was
shot, even the murderer. I just couldn't believe this abominable
attack.
</P>
<P>
   _ Corben Henry.
</P>
<P>
   This tragedy has affected kids like you all over the country. If
you want to share your own feelings about the Wedgwood shooting,
send your thoughts in writing to: Jessamy Brown, Class Acts
Coordinator, Fort Worth Star-Telegram 400 W. Seventh St. Fort
Worth, TX 76102. Please include your age, grade, school and home
phone number with area code so we can verify your letter.
</P>
