<HEADER>
A2178 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-KIDS:GUN-CONTROL-ISSU     09-22 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS:GUN-CONTROL-ISSUE-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GUN CONTROL ISSUE 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 By LIZ STEVENS 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUN CONTROL STATISTICS
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, firearms killed 32,436 people in the United States,
according to the most recent statistics from the national Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Every day in America, 15 children are killed with firearms,
according to a 1996 Children's Defense Fund report.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, 361 children in Texas died as a result of firearms,
according to Handgun Control Inc., a nonpartisan organization that
lobbies in favor of gun regulations at the state and national
level.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Texas hosted 472 gun shows, far more than any other
state in the nation, according to Handgun Control.
</P>
<P>
   Firearms account for 27 percent of the 20,000 fatal injuries
each year to children ages 1-19, according to a 1996 Johns Hopkins
School of Public Health Injury Prevention Center report.
</P>
<P>
   The same study found that having a gun at home increases by
tenfold the risk that a teen-ager may commit suicide.
</P>
<P>
   A September poll by The Washington Post and ABC News found that
63 percent of Americans want stricter gun control laws, 77 percent
want to ban the sale of assault weapons, 49 percent want to ban
people from carrying concealed weapons, and 32 percent want a
nationwide ban on the sale of handguns.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S THE ISSUE?
</P>
<P>
   The Second Amendment to the U.S. Constitution, ratified in 1791,
begins, ``A well regulated Militia being necessary to the security
of a free State, the right of the people to keep and bear Arms
shall not be infringed.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1960s, Americans have increasingly questioned how that
amendment ought to be interpreted.
</P>
<P>
   Some gun-rights advocates argue that it means exactly what it
says: Citizens have a right to bear arms, without interference from
the government. Some gun-control supporters say the amendment is
outdated because it was written when the country called upon
private citizens to protect its interests. Those citizens, of
course, would need to be armed.
</P>
<P>
   There are lots of opinions that fall between those two opposing
viewpoints. Violence in the media, poor parenting, and cultural
attitudes all have been blamed for rampant gun violence in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Today, guns-rights groups such as the National Rifle Association
insist that simply enforcing the gun-control laws already on the
books will lower the chances that guns fall into the wrong hands.
They argue that law-abiding gun owners are unjustly penalized by
more restrictions, and that gun-owning citizens can actually thwart
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of stricter gun control believe that only new laws
will reduce deaths and injuries by firearms. They endorse measures
such as waiting periods, background checks, requiring manufacturers
to add safety locks to guns and raising the age limit at which
people can buy guns. Gun control advocates point to countries like
Japan and England, where owning guns is highly regulated or
illegal, and gun crimes are almost unheard of.
</P>
<P>
   A LITTLE BACKGROUND
</P>
<P>
   Congress passed the first major gun control legislation in 1968,
in the wake of the assassinations of Martin Luther King Jr. and
Sen. Robert Kennedy. It prohibited certain people, such as
convicted felons, from buying guns; set standards for gun dealers;
and placed other restrictions on the sale and use of firearms.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1994, the federal Brady law took effect. The law is
named for James Brady, White House press secretary under President
Ronald Reagan who was shot in the head and partially paralyzed in
1981, during the attempt on Reagan's life. The Brady law
established a waiting period of five business days for those who
want to buy guns and required background checks for people buying
guns through licensed dealers.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1998, the five-day waiting period was replaced with
an ``instant'' check on gun purchasers, which can be done by
computer. Many gun sellers at gun shows are not licensed dealers,
so background checks and waiting periods do not apply to the people
who buy guns from them.
</P>
<P>
   About 19 states still enforce waiting periods on the purchase of
guns and/or permits to buy guns. Texas has no waiting period and
does not require a permit to buy a gun. To carry a concealed weapon
in Texas, you must be over 21 and qualify for a state license. But
it's illegal to carry guns into ``a place of worship'' if such a
place posts a sign that handguns are prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE DO THE POLITICIANS STAND?
</P>
<P>
   President Bill Clinton favors strengthening the country's
gun-control laws, including restricting gun buyers from purchasing
more than one handgun a month. He recently announced a federal plan
to buy guns from their owners, estimating that the program could
bring in 300,000 weapons. But the push to increase national
gun-control laws since the April shootings at Columbine High School
has been unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the U.S. Senate passed a gun-control bill that would
have required a three-day waiting period and background check for
people buying guns at gun shows. The House of Representatives
proposed shrinking the waiting period from three days to 24 hours,
but the House bill never came to a vote. Senators and
representatives are now trying to devise a compromise bill.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT HAVE OTHER COUNTRIES DONE?
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Britain made it illegal for citizens to possess any
handgun larger than a .22 caliber; Ireland has a similar law. In
1996, Australia outlawed semi-automatic weapons and pump-action
shotguns.
</P>
<P>
   Canada makes gun buyers wait 28 days and submit to a background
check before they can have their weapons. In Japan, only licensed
shooting teams can own handguns. Since 1994, the United States has
banned 19 types of assault weapons.
</P>
<P>
   (SOURCES: Handgun Control Inc., www.handguncontrol.org; The
National Rifle Association, www.nra.org; Center for Responsive
Politics, www.opensecrets.org/news/guns/index.htm; ABC News.com,
http:/abcnews.go.com/sections/us/guns/guns_intro.html; National
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, www.cdc.gov)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
