<SLUG> BC-KIDS:FACES:TOY-INVENTOR-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN-AGE INVENTOR, ALEXANDER RIVES, HAS LOTS OF ENERGY 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 By JESSAMY BROWN, with information from the ``Seattle
Post-Intelligencer'' 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Name: Alexander Rives.
</P>
<P>
   Claim to fame: toy inventor.
</P>
<P>
   Hobbies: crew team, photography.
</P>
<P>
   Hometown: Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Age: 18.
</P>
<P>
   Current project: creating a volcano toy
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Rives makes sparks fly. Literally.
</P>
<P>
   He is the inventor of The Lightning Machine, a hand-held
miniature lightning maker sold through his parents' toy company,
Scientific Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   The company has sold more than 30,000 of the science kits since
April through retail outlets including Discovery Channel and Museum
Company stores. The Lightning Machine, which sells for $19.99 and
looks like a foil-coated plastic tube with two long copper wires
poking out the top, helps kids learn the basics of static
electricity. It's a 21st-century version of the first device used
to store electricity. Invented in the 1740s at the University of
Leyden in the Netherlands, that gadget was called a Leyden jar.
</P>
<P>
   To make sparks fly, the toy is run across a television screen to
collect electrons, and then the two balls on the top are touched
together to create an electrical arch.
</P>
<P>
   Inventing the toy was pretty easy, Alexander says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't have much homework one week,'' he says, ``and it
just sort of happened.''
</P>
<P>
   His newest project, a toy volcano, also seems to have just sort
of happened. This summer, as a volunteer, Alexander went to Iceland
to investigate the interaction between glaciers and the island's
volcanoes.
</P>
<P>
   Although science is one of Alexander's better subjects at the
private school he attends in Seattle, it's not his favorite
subject. He wouldn't divulge his cumulative grade-point average but
admitted it was close to a 4.0.
</P>
<P>
   When he isn't exploring science and inventing toys, he's
probably at his computer. Alexander is a computer arts whiz and has
a Web site called Beyond Reality that shows off some of his work.
(www.halcyon.com/alrives/).
</P>
<P>
   He also runs his own Internet business, offering tips to others
interested in computer-generated graphics.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
