<HEADER>
A2184 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-VIEQUES-HNS &LR;      09-22 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-VIEQUES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR ACCUSES CLINTON OF POLITICS IN VIEQUES CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. James Inhofe, R-Okla., accused President
Clinton Wednesday of preparing to close a 58-year-old target range
on the Puerto Rican island of Vieques in order to cultivate
Hispanic political support for the prospective New York Senate
campaign of First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Inhofe, chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee's panel
on military readiness, released a handwritten note from the
president to national security adviser Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger
dated July 26 in which Clinton said it would be ``wrong'' for the
Navy to resume combat training with live munitions on the Caribbean
island with 9,300 civilian residents.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is awaiting recommendations from the Pentagon on the
future use of the Vieques target range, shut down since April when
a Marine pilot mistakenly bombed the range observation post,
killing a civilian Puerto Rican security guard and injuring four
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, I fear that a decision will be made on politics
rather than national security,'' Inhofe said at the outset of
Senate and House hearings into the politically explosive stalemate
that pits the government of Puerto Rico against the U.S. Navy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned that this administration may take action that
will place at risk the lives of sailors and Marines simply to court
the popular vote in favor of candidates with close ties to this
president,'' Inhofe said. He also accused the president of seeking
to build Hispanic political support for the campaign of Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican lawmaker, citing Clinton's clemency for
imprisoned Puerto Rican nationalists last month, condemned what he
said was the chief executive's willingness ``to place American
lives and interests at risk in order to garner votes for his
friends and family.''
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics are a powerful political force in New York, where Mrs.
Clinton is weighing a campaign to succeed retiring Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y. Hispanics also represent an influential
political constituency in electorally important states such as
California, Texas, Florida, New Jersey and Illinois that would be
crucial to Gore's political fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   James Fallin, an assistant White House press secretary and a
spokesman for the National Security Council, called Inhofe's
allegations ``unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Fallin added: ``To leap from the hand-written remarks to a
conclusion that the president has made up his mind or that the
president is politically motivated is both unreasonable and without
basis in fact.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House official said Clinton's note to Berger was in
response to a ``compelling'' letter from Puerto Rico Sen. Ruben
Barrios appealing to the White House to order Navy withdrawal from
the island, where 9,300 civilians live.
</P>
<P>
   The Baltimore Sun, which first reported Clinton's note in a
story published Wednesday, said Clinton's note was in response to a
July 21 letter from Barrios in which the Puerto Rican activist, a
fellow graduate of Georgetown University and Yale Law School, told
Clinton that Puerto Ricans are ``forced to live under constant
threat to their lives in a narrow strip of land'' sandwiched
between Navy-owned property on Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sandy, I agree with this,'' Clinton wrote Berger. ``This is
wrong. I think they don't want us there. That's the main point. The
Navy can find a way to work around it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., challenged Inhofe's remarks,
calling on members of Congress to ``judge the issue on the merits
and not inject a shoddy type of politics into it.''
</P>
<P>
   There were these related developments:
</P>
<P>
   _ Representatives of more than 30 Hispanic and civil rights
organizations joined six Hispanic members of Congress, including
Rep. Jose Serrano, D-N.Y., to demand a permanent end to Navy
operations on Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time to free the people of Vieques from the military
occupation of their home,'' said Rep. Nydia Velasquez, D-N.Y.,
adding: ``When you violate the civil rights of the Puerto Rican
community, the entire (Hispanic) community is united behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Members of Congress joined Navy Vice Adm. William J. Fallon
and Marine Lt. Gen. Peter Pace to appeal to Puerto Rico Gov. Pedro
Rossello to open negotiations on a compromise solution. Rossello,
insisting the Navy must withdraw from Vieques, ruled out compromise
during a visit to Capitol Hill last week.
</P>
<P>
   To encourage negotiations, Senate Armed Services Committee
Chairman John Warner, R-Va., announced that he has asked the Senate
leadership to reserve $27 million to provide economic assistance to
Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fallon, commander of the Atlantic fleet, and Pace outlined
proposed Navy concessions, including reduced training operations
from 180 days a year to 120 days a year; cutting the number of
rounds from warships' 5-inch guns by 50 percent to roughly 100
rounds per vessel; and returning to Puerto Rican authorities an
8,000-acre ammunition storage site at the western end of the
island.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a solution here,'' Pace told Congress. ``We can sit
down and accommodate the legitimate needs of the citizens of
Vieques and the needs of national security.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The military leaders warned that the combat readiness of
departing aircraft carrier battle groups would continue to
deteriorate without immediate resumption of integrated sea, land
and air combat rehearsals on Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   The armada centered around the aircraft carrier USS John F.
Kennedy that is en route to the Mediterranean and the Persian Gulf
includes only one ship, the destroyer USS John Hancock, that lacks
required qualification for gunfire support with its 5-inch guns,
according to the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   But five of the six surface warships accompanying the aircraft
carrier USS Dwight D. Eisenhower in February will fall short of
required qualification for gunfire support, a Navy officer warned,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   As Fallon put it: ``We're seeing for the first time the
implications of not being able to use this range on Vieques.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton awaits recommendations on the future of Vieques and
alternatives to the site from a four-member Pentagon review panel
that was appointed at his request in June.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart Powell can be reached via E-mail at
stewart(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
