<SLUG> BC-CISCO-WEBLINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CISCO SYSTEMS BUYING WEBLINE COMMUNICATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cisco Systems Inc. plans to buy closely held WebLine
Communications Corp. of Burlington, Mass. for $325 million in
stock, the latest buyout of a Bay State start-up by one of the
technology sector's giants.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1996 by two graduate students at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, WebLine makes software to help companies
like Fidelity Investments and retailer Lands' End manage their
e-mail, develop their Web sites, and provide other communications
services.
</P>
<P>
   Now WebLine and its 120 employees will be merged into a Cisco
software unit based in Lowell, Mass. Headquartered in San Jose,
Calif., networking-gear maker Cisco has about 1,200 employees in
the Bay State and plans to employ as many as 5,000 workers here
within five years.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase price represents a return nearly 12 times greater
than the $28 million in financing WebLine has raised from firms
including Highland Capital Partners, Advent International,
Information Technology Ventures, and Draper Fisher Jurvetson.
</P>
<P>
   Intel Corp. and MCI Worldcom Inc. also hold significant stakes,
though WebLine declined to break down specific ownership or to
disclose its revenue or whether it is profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Like other electronic-commerce companies, WebLine had been
considering an initial public offering of stock, but decided a sale
would give it faster access to more people to sell and distribute
its products.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the only way to grow quickly enough to meet the market
demand,'' WebLine chief executive Dan Keshian said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   No layoffs are expected as a result of the deal, said John
Thibault, Cisco senior vice president. Thibault said the purchase
will complement Cisco's acquisition in April of GeoTel
Communications Corp. for $1.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That deal came amid a string of acquisitions of local technology
companies; another major acquirer was Lucent Technologies, which
has purchased six Massachusetts companies this year, the latest
being Excel Switching Corp. of Hyannis, which agreed to be bought
in August for $1.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco expects to continue its acquisition spree and reiterated
its plans to build a large central campus somewhere in
Massachusetts soon, Thibault said.
</P>
<P>
   The terms of the agreement call for Cisco to issue stock worth
$325 million to the local company's various equity holders, with
the exact number of shares exchanged to be determined at a later
date. The deal is expected to be completed by the end of January.
</P>
<P>
   Beneficiaries will include WebLine's two founders, Firdaus
Bhathena and Pasha Roberts, who met in an entrepreneurship course
at MIT and won the school's $50K business plan competition in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Bhathena, 29, earned a master's degree in computer science from
MIT and is WebLine's product vice president. Roberts, 37, completed
a year of MIT's Sloan School of Management before leaving to join
WebLine; he now works as a specialist for computer telephony.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
