<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-PRESSURE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY FELT REAL PAR PRESSURE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (Repeating for San Jose and all needing.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Somehow, he had been chosen to be a stage
prop for someone's warped sense of humor. David Feherty could think
of no other reason why he was the third player in a group that
featured Bernhard Langer and Hale Irwin.
</P>
<P>
   Four days earlier, Langer and Irwin had played starring roles in
arguably the most intense golf competition ever _ the 1991 Ryder
Cup at Kiawah Island, S.C. _ and here they were again, paired in
the first round of the German Masters.
</P>
<P>
   Feherty had also played at Kiawah, and in Germany, his stomach
still churned. He wasn't about to complain to veterans, however,
for surely they would laugh if they knew he had carried emotional
scars across the Atlantic. There was no mention of Kiawah on the
tee, so Feherty assumed it was ancient history.
</P>
<P>
   On the first green, Feherty would be the second player to putt,
and he watched Irwin lag to within inches. Out of courtesy, Feherty
told Irwin he could either mark or putt out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever you want to do,'' said Feherty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to throw up. Still,'' said Irwin, before tapping in.
</P>
<P>
   Feherty laughed. So did Langer. Irwin, too.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first sense of relief in four days for these Ryder
Cup players, all of whom had experienced agonizing pressure at
Kiawah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryder Cup players feel they're members of a very special club,
I think,'' said Feherty. Which means those who have played in it
have to find ways to describe the experience to those who haven't.
</P>
<P>
   Payne Stewart, who will be on his fifth Ryder Cup team, explains
the aura: ``When I lost the US Open (in 1998), the only one I let
down was myself. I didn't let down 11 other teammates, my captain,
my country.''
</P>
<P>
   Such was the heavy burden Mark Calcavecchia put on himself at
Kiawah. Eight years later, the tears have dried, but the memory
hasn't faded. He was dormie against Colin Montgomerie with four
holes to play. His was going to be the match that stopped the
European momentum, because the two matches ahead of Calcavecchia
had ended in losses; the US trailed, 10-8.
</P>
<P>
   Then, disaster, the sort that can be attributed to a swing that
fails to hold together under pressure. Calcavecchia bogeyed 15 and
16, both won by Montgomerie's pars. At the difficult par-3 17th,
Calcavecchia hit into the water twice. Then he lost the 18th as
Montgomerie miraculously salvaged a half-point for Europe.
Calcavecchia didn't stop the momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Through tears he tried to determine the ramifications of his
collapse. ``At that time I had a feeling, the way things were
unfolding, we were going to lose by half a point,'' said
Calcavecchia, who was 31 at the time and a 10-year veteran of the
PGA Tour. He knew how to play in white-knuckle time, having won the
1989 British Open in a playoff against Greg Norman and Wayne Grady.
He knew heartache, having finished second 12 times.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't know how to handle this scene.
</P>
<P>
   So he cried. And he cried some more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went up to Mark. He was visibly upset,'' said Stewart, who
played in the first singles match that day and had also lost, to
Feherty. ``But I tried to explain it was a team event. `Don't worry
about it,' I said, `It's not about you. It's about the team.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't penetrate. It only reminded Calcavecchia of The Belfry
in 1989. There, Calcavecchia had lost to Ronan Raferty, the middle
match of five straight singles victories that allowed Europe to
maintain the Cup. ``I never want to go through this again,'' he
said following that defeat, but here he was two years later. Deja
vu all over again? No, and yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1989 we tied,'' said Calcavecchia, ``but that was the same
as losing. At Kiawah, we won, but that didn't feel like we won.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor did it look it, not when one considers the memory of Irwin,
standing greenside amid celebrating teammates, flying corks, and
flowing champagne. When Langer's 6-foot putt for par slid wide,
Irwin had halved their match and secured the half-point needed for
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Victory? He looked like he had been battered and beaten.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never been through anything like it,'' said Irwin, who
had withstood enough pressure to win three US Opens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's stressful,'' said Calcavecchia, who was playing on his
third Cup team at Kiawah (he hasn't qualified since), though his
experience had obviously not been a factor. ``I took the Ryder Cup
the wrong way. I just wanted to win so bad that sometimes you get
in your own way. I really didn't enjoy the hoopla of the matches.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like Langer, Brad Faxon lives with the memory of missing a key
putt in Ryder Cup competition. In 1995, Faxon went to the 18th 1
down against David Gilford, but he was in position to win the hole
and secure a half-point for the US.
</P>
<P>
   Had he made his putt, the US would have ended up with 14 points
and regained possession of the coveted Cup. Instead, Faxon missed
his par-save at 18, Gilford earned a 1-up victory, and Europe
prevailed, 14 1/2-13 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Faxon concedes that the pressure at times was unbearable. But
not during that putt. ``I wasn't nervous over that putt,'' he said.
``If anything, I felt comfortable. I saw the line and just made a
bad putt.''
</P>
<P>
   No, the pressure had come earlier in the week during the first
practice round. Standing on the first tee, Faxon did something he
rarely did _ he began talking to himself. He told himself it was no
big deal, that it was just a practice round. So why, he answered,
are you about to squeeze the grip off the club?
</P>
<P>
   Faxon told himself to relax because no one was paying attention.
Who are you kidding? he answered. There are two eyes burning holes
in your back. Out of the corner of his eye, Faxon caught a glimpse
of somebody watching him. Not just anybody, either. Lanny Wadkins.
The team captain, thought Faxon, is staring right at me. It was the
most infamous stare in golf, one that for years had turned
opponents into freeze-pops on even the most stifling of days.
</P>
<P>
   Damn, thought Faxon, this is serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, it was the most nervous I was, standing there on the
first tee of the first practice round. I realized Lanny was judging
every shot I made. I felt pressure on every shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressure, said Tom Watson, that did not subside with revisits.
He played on four teams. ``I felt more pressure as I got older,''
he said. ``I'm not sure why. But the Ryder Cup is the only event in
the world that will make your legs shake.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard to believe, said Jim Furyk, who will play on his second
Ryder Cup team this weekend at The Country Club, because pressure
comes with the job. ``We all deal with (it), golf-wise, on a daily
basis. Whether it's getting through Q School, making the cut,
keeping your card, making the Tour Championship, having a putt to
win a tournament . . . it's always some inherent pressure to being
a golf professional.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, said Furyk, ``The extra incentive really is playing for
that team. Then you also could add on however many millions viewers
in the US are pulling for the US, and you're part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Which hits at the heart of the Ryder Cup pressure _ loyalty. At
weekly tournaments, fan support is usually spread out among dozens
of players. Some people want to see Tiger Woods win, others want
Justin Leonard, or Fred Couples, or Davis Love, or David Duval, or
so on. In the Ryder Cup, however, the line of support is clear.
You're on one side or the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're playing for your country and your Tour,'' said Corey
Pavin, who played on three teams (1991-93-95), ``and all your
fellow professionals who you play with.''
</P>
<P>
   PGA Tour commissioner Tim Finchem said ``it is riveting''
competition, which the TV audience loves. ``Weekly on our tour, the
final 2-3 hours comes down to 2-6 guys who can win, 2-6 guys whose
feet are in the fire. On the final day of the Ryder Cup, there are
24 guys whose feet are in the fire. People love that.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
