<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-PRESSURE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 (Repeating for San Jose and all needing.)  
 BROOKLINE, Mass.: ... love that.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They also love patriotism, that Us-vs.-Them mentality that has
turned up the dial on the pressure cooker. Not that pressure didn't
always exist. On the contrary. The late, great, and outrageously
tough Lloyd Mangrum once uttered: ``I will never, never captain an
American team again because of the 9,000 deaths I suffered in the
last hour.''
</P>
<P>
   That was in 1953, after a US victory, no less, but it offers
proof that the event was always taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   In recent times, however, it has grown into something else.
``It's gotten personal,'' said Paul Azinger, a member in
1989-91-93.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't so personal in 1983, when Jay Haas made his Ryder Cup
debut. He was 29, with seven years on the Tour. ``It was a forgone
conclusion that we would win,'' he said. Which the Americans did,
though by only 1 point.
</P>
<P>
   When he finally returned to the team, in 1995 at Oak Hill, Haas
discovered that the Ryder Cup atmosphere had changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I played in '95, we walked out of the locker room on
Tuesday morning at 9, there were 25,000 people there watching our
practice round and chanting, `Go USA,' and, `Go, Jay.' I mean, the
hair stood out on the back of my neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that regard, it was so different from what I had
experienced in '83, and right away that almost put more pressure on
us, because here are all these people so behind us. Let's not let
them down.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lehman was a Ryder Cup rookie that year, though at 36, he
was no stranger to pressure. A spot in the final pairing at the US
Open a few months earlier, as well as a Sunday duel at Augusta with
Jose Maria Olazabal the year before, had surely hardened him, yes?
Not quite. ``I was so nervous, I could hardly breathe,'' said
Lehman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different kind of pressure. Very simply, I think, when
you're playing on your own, you learn to be your own best friend.
You hit a bad shot, you forgive yourself, you go on. You play with
a teammate, you tend to really get a lot more hard on yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Haas understands. Not long after Faxon had failed on the
finishing hole, Haas came to 18 with a chance to give his teammates
a victory. He needed to win the hole, but first he needed to drive
it in the fairway. Normally, no problem, but this was no normal
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That pressure was probably the most I ever felt,'' said Hass,
a nine-time winner on Tour. ``I had a multitude of emotions going
through my mind right at that moment. Should I swing easy and hit
the fairway? Or swing hard? I thought too much. I tried to calm
down and tried to use my experience and not hit until I was ready
and all that stuff, but . . .''
</P>
<P>
   His soft, easy swing produced a pop-up drive into the left rough
a mere 200 yards away. Haas had to lay up with his second, then his
third shot hit the green and sucked back down a steep slope. When
his last-ditch chip attempt did not go in, the match belonged to
Philip Walton, the cup to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Haas is not the reason the US lost that year. Just as Costantino
Rocca was not responsible for the European loss in 1993. But with
so much passion and so much emotion on the line, someone has to
take the blame. Why not play wonder ball and blame whoever has the
pressure last?
</P>
<P>
   ``When I played in 1993, I lost to Davis Love,'' said Rocca.
``People supposed I lost the Cup. I'm sorry I lost to Davis Love,
but I was not the whole team. I was 1 up on the 17th tee, missed a
short putt on 17, then bogeyed 18. The other players on the team
helped me. They said, `Don't tell me this is your fault. It's not
your fault.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I got on the plane the Monday after the '93 matches. I see the
papers, and I'm on the front page. But looking back, sometimes
you're more famous for one shot than if you win.''
</P>
<P>
   At least Haas and Rocca can remember their shots, said Feherty.
The Irishman, now an analyst for CBS, defeated Stewart in their
singles match at Kiawah, though he isn't sure how.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 4 up with four to play, just like Calcavecchia against
Monty right behind us. Then, like Calcavecchia, I lost 15 and 16
and got to 17, which was the hardest par 3 in the history of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit a 1-iron. I have absolutely no recollection of the
swing. None. I just remember the crowd going berserk when the ball
hit the green. It was more like a football game than golf. A
terrifying moment.''
</P>
<P>
   After all these years, it hasn't turned pleasant?
</P>
<P>
   No, said Feherty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still shaking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
