<HEADLINE>
TEXAS PASTORS HAIL NEW NATIONAL BAPTIST LEADER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Local church officials say the new president
of the National Baptist Convention USA, the Rev. William J. Shaw,
will help the denomination rise above a damaging scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Shaw is one of the finest men in the country, and he will
make the changes needed to bring our denomination into the 21st
century,'' said the Rev. Cedric Britt, pastor of Mount Gilead
Baptist Church in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, 65, pastor of White Rock Baptist Church in Philadelphia,
was elected last week to succeed the disgraced former president of
the convention, the Rev. Henry J. Lyons.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Marshall in East Texas, Shaw has dedicated himself to
the ministry since childhood. He preached his first sermon at 11
and was ordained as pastor of Oak Hill Baptist Church near Marshall
at 17, according to a biography supplied by his Philadelphia
church.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw graduated summa cum laude at 19 from the old Bishop College
in Dallas with a major in philosophy and religion. He also holds a
master of divinity degree from Union Theological Seminary in New
York and a doctor of ministry degree from Colgate Rochester
Divinity School at Crozer Theological Seminary in Rochester, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Britt said Shaw will help the National Baptist Convention
recover from the damage caused by Lyons' actions.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons is serving 51/2 years in a Florida state prison after
being convicted of racketeering and grand theft. He was found
guilty of stealing more than $4 million from corporations wanting
to do business with the 3 million-member denomination of
predominantly African-American churches.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons was also found guilty of taking nearly $250,000 in
Anti-Defamation League funds intended to help rebuild black
churches burned by arsonists. Also, he admitted to an improper
relationship with one of his female aides.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the presidential candidates at last week's gathering
vowed to make major changes in the way the convention handles
money.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his first acts, Shaw promised an immediate,
independent audit of the convention's finances.
</P>
<P>
   Britt attended the national convention in Tampa, Fla., and
supported another candidate, the Rev. E.V. Hill of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy about the outcome of the election, though,''
Britt said, because Shaw has committed himself to restructuring the
denomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make our denomination more user-friendly to local
churches,'' Britt said. He favors giving loan assistance to help
start churches in developing communities.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. B.R. Daniels, pastor of Beth-Eden Baptist Church in
Fort Worth, also attended the national convention and strongly
supported Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``The convention is back on the way it ought to be under Bill
Shaw,'' Daniels said. ``I'm very grateful to the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw won by about 200 votes over the Rev. W. Franklyn Richardson
of Mount Vernon, N.Y. Hill came in third.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels believes that Richardson hurt his candidacy by speaking
out too harshly against Lyons.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a man is already down, you don't need to kick him,''
Daniels said.
</P>
<P>
   During the meeting, delegates took up an offering to help pay
Lyons' legal expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw has called for a national summit of pastors to discuss
changes needed in the denomination, Daniels said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the old system, the board of directors was a rubber
stamp for the president,'' Daniels said. ``We need to put the
convention back in the hands of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Many churches have been giving token amounts to the national
denomination because they felt they were not getting enough out of
it, Daniels said.
</P>
<P>
   Some National Baptist churches are becoming aligned with the
Southern Baptist Convention because of the assistance that
denomination gives pastors and churches, Daniels said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
