<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-AWARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVEN SPIELBERG AND AUGUST WILSON AMONG ARTS MEDAL WINNERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (md) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The playwright August Wilson, the filmmaker Steven Spielberg and
Jim Lehrer, anchor of ``Newshour'' on PBS, are among the winners of
this year's National Humanities Medals, the White House announced
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It also named the recipients of the 1999 National Medal of Arts,
who include the singer Aretha Franklin and Harvey Lichtenstein,
former president of the Brooklyn Academy of Music.
</P>
<P>
   Those receiving the medals are selected by the president from
lists of nominees presented by the National Endowment for the
Humanities and the National Endowment for the Arts, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The humanities medals honor ``gifted people with extraordinary
powers of creativity and vision,'' said William R. Ferris, chairman
of the Endowment for the Humanities. The National Medal of Arts,
established by Congress in 1984, honors those who have made
``outstanding contributions to the excellence, growth, support and
availability of the arts in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The awards are to be presented at a White House ceremony this
coming Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The other 1999 National Humanities Medal recipients are:
</P>
<P>
   Patricia M. Battin, a librarian who led a national campaign to
save disintegrating books.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor Branch, a writer and authority on the civil rights
movement.
</P>
<P>
   Jacquelyn Dowd Hall, the founder of the Southern Oral History
Project at the University of North Carolina, Chapel Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Garrison Keillor, the creator and host of ``A Prairie Home
Companion'' on public radio.
</P>
<P>
   John Rawls, a political philosopher.
</P>
<P>
   The other 1999 National Medal of Arts recipients are:
</P>
<P>
   Irene Diamond, an arts patron.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Graves, the architect and designer.
</P>
<P>
   Odetta, the singer and music historian.
</P>
<P>
   The Juilliard School.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Lear, the producer, writer and director.
</P>
<P>
   Rosetta LeNoire, an actress and producer.
</P>
<P>
   The singer Lydia Mendoza.
</P>
<P>
   The sculptor George Segal.
</P>
<P>
   The ballerina Maria Tallchief.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
