<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2204 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-JUDGING-AMY-TEX     09-22 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDGING-AMY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW COURTROOM SHOW HANDS THE GAVEL TO STRONG WOMEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amy Grey, played with a tinge of charm and vulnerability by Amy
Brenneman, is a superior court judge in need of answers.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of her first day on the job, Amy stands before
her full-length mirror in her long black robe _ and freaks. She
then leaps back into bed, pulling the covers over her head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't oversleep,'' she explains later to her
eyebrows-raised mother. ``I'm in denial.''
</P>
<P>
   Amy is in denial about a lot of things, actually, and this is
what makes all those notions about ``Judging Amy'' being a clone of
``Providence'' unfair and just plain wrong. Like the lead character
in NBC's midseason surprise, Amy left a man and job to move from
the big city to her medium-size hometown (Hartford, Conn.), where
her mother and brother wait with open arms.
</P>
<P>
   But the comparisons stop there. ``Judging Amy'' isn't merely
connect-the-dots entertainment shrewdly designed for a demographic.
It delivers a strong point of view from two strong-willed women,
based largely on the fact that Brenneman is using her real-life
mother's professional life as a dramatic guide.
</P>
<P>
   The actress, who grew up in Hartford, always found her mother's
work as a juvenile court judge interesting and demanding,
particularly for a woman trying to raise a family and find time for
herself.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Judging Amy,'' Brenneman, who is one of the executive
producers, merely wonders what we all wonder, no matter what our
profession: When will someone come in and say we don't belong
there?
</P>
<P>
   In the series, Amy has reason to question it even more. She was
a corporate attorney working in Manhattan when a Harvard chum
pushed her for a judgeship. Because of a need for female judges,
she was moved along somewhat quickly. There's a scene at the dinner
table that explains this rather well, with her social worker mother
Maxine (Tyne Daly), fed up with unprepared, politically placed
judges, questioning her quick placement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't win it in a raffle,'' Amy explains, even going so far
as to defend her intellect. ``In order to have a friend from
Harvard, you have to get into Harvard.''
</P>
<P>
   But after Day One on the bench, during which protocol is
completely lost on her and a decision regarding the care of a child
unnerves her, she confides to her ex-husband: ``All those people
looking at me expecting me to know stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Available help her are Bruce (Richard T. Jones), a by-the-book
court services officer, and her free-spirited brother (Dan
Futterman), a high-minded college graduate who, for reasons
unrevealed as of yet, washes dogs for a living. Both serve their
purposes well. Oh, yeah. Complicating matters is Amy's 6-year-old
daughter, Lauren, played by Karle Warren.
</P>
<P>
   Brenneman says ``Judging Amy'' is more about the people she met
in her mother's court: probation officers, social workers,
attorneys, families under siege. About half the time, we'll see the
work venue; the other half will zero in on the home front, with Amy
dealing with her daughter, and particularly her mother.
</P>
<P>
   Now to Daly. I can't remember ever witnessing a performance from
this actress that wasn't well-defined and striking. She strides
through the first two episodes firing opinions as though shot from
a cannon.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is anorexia?'' Lauren wants to know. ``It's a disease
women get when they read magazines,'' Maxine says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are you so grouchy?'' she's asked. Maxine: ``Because I've
earned that privilege.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly does this sort of thing with such charm that you don't mind
that her character really is something of a grouch. When we first
meet her, she's a chain-smoking former social worker trying
retirement. She spends most of her time in the garden or Internet
chat rooms, or dissecting the lives of her children.
</P>
<P>
   By the second episode, Maxine is contemplating a return to
social work, which will put her in Amy's line of fire in the
courtroom as well.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from these two women, what I like most about ``Judging
Amy'' is its assertion that we're all looking for answers and
formulas, that how-to manuals come with kids' toys and elaborate
shelving, but not with jobs and marriages and families.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't gonna work,'' Amy says at one trying point. ``Do
they let just anybody do this job?''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
