<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2206 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-GERMANY-ISRAEL-ART-NY     09-22 1270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-ISRAEL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYMBOLISM ABOUNDS AS BARAK MAKES FIRST STATE VISIT TO BERLIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACHSENHAUSEN, Germany _ ``How come I am alive?'' Eli Carmel,
82, asked Wednesday as he stood, hunched with age, outside the
gates of the concentration camp he survived 60 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Carmel, an Israeli, answered his own query as he headed toward
the brick remains of the crematory, trampling the grassy fields
where he was once forced to shovel snow until he was paralyzed, but
only with cold; he was one of the lucky ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day I was beaten unconscious and I fell in the snow,'' he
said. ``I was taken with the other stiffs back to the barracks and
we were stacked up, all the corpses. But I woke up in the night,
and I crawled out. How come I am here when so many were killed?
There is no explanation.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a milky gray sky, Carmel proudly traveled back to the
scene of his darkest memories because Ehud Barak, the prime
minister of Israel, had invited him along with two other survivors
and their families as guests on his first diplomatic trip to
Europe. It was, as Barak and the survivors said, history come full
circle:
</P>
<P>
   Barak, the leader of the Jewish homeland, stood elbow to elbow
with German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, facing down the Nazis'
ovens _ now exhibitions in a grim museum. An elderly survivor,
Avraham Lanzmann, chanted the Jewish prayer of mourning,
accompanied by his grandson, a uniformed Israeli soldier, after
which the Israeli and German leaders laid wreaths and pledged to
stand together against intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, that you could see,'' Barak said in Hebrew, speaking to
the camp's ghosts, ``the representatives of the state of Israel,
the Holocaust survivors and the Israeli soldiers here in
Sachsenhausen, the killing camp next to Berlin.''
</P>
<P>
   On his second day in Germany, Barak made clear that the purpose
of his trip was to cement his new government's relationship with
what he sees as Israel's key ally in the European Union. Building
explicitly on the twisted bonds of history that link the two
countries, the Israeli prime minister wanted to broadcast his
alliance with Schroeder before continuing on, later Wednesday, to
France, with which Israel has a far rockier relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder, in turn, had his own symbolic agenda. He chose Barak
to make the first state visit to the German capital since the
government moved to Berlin. It was a conscious move to rehabilitate
the lingering negative image of Berlin as the former seat of Nazi
power. And, wearing a yarmulke on his head, he accompanied Barak to
the concentration camp here to underscore just how far Germany has
traveled from its past.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy to speak here at this place,'' Schroeder said
Wednesday morning. ``There is only one way to deal with the
unimaginable magnitude of the crimes committed here. We and all
others have to remember again and again. We owe it to the dead but
also to ourselves and to our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Much like Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader who travels
constantly in a campaign to enlist support, Barak seeks personally
to recruit international backing for his ambitious goal of a quick,
broad peace with Israel's neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Both Germany and France play a critical role in this _ by
providing development assistance to the Palestinian Authority,
which theoretically gives both countries some leverage over Arafat,
and by exercising some influence on the governments of Syria, Iran
and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, Barak faced some criticism from opposition leaders
for not declining a chance to have his name marked down in history
as the first leader to pay a diplomatic visit to a city with such
painful associations for many Israelis. Some Israeli reporters
chided him for staying in the luxurious Adlon Hotel, saying that it
had once been a Gestapo stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   But Barak said that while ``the guilt of the Germans who carried
out these crimes will never be expunged,'' it was still desirable
to move into the future while remembering the past. ``I think no
one today is seriously afraid of German manipulative power games,''
he told Der Spiegel in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has new concerns, he said Wednesday, including a desire
to become a more active trade partner with Europe _ with what he
hoped would be a preferred status, not as a member but a friend of
the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deeply moved in my first visit to Berlin as the Prime minister
of Israel,'' Barak scrawled Wednesday in the guest book at the
residence of President Johannes Rau.
</P>
<P>
   Switching gears completely after the memorial service at
Sachsenhausen, he went out of his way to request that German
reporters transmit a tourism sales pitch to young Germans to visit
Israel in the year of the millennium. ``Jerusalem,'' he said, ``the
place where the historic countdown started.''
</P>
<P>
   Yitzhak Rabin, the late prime minister and Barak's mentor,
preceded him in a visit to Sachsenhausen seven years ago,
accompanied by Helmut Kohl, who was then German chancellor. But
soon afterward, neo-Nazi youths burned down the barracks he had
toured, and Barak implied Wednesday that the act was directly
linked to Rabin's visit.
</P>
<P>
   These were the barracks, number 38 and 39, to which Carmel, a
retired electrical engineer who now lives in Tel Aviv, had been
assigned in 1939. Born in Vienna, he had been living in Switzerland
when the Swiss police arrested him and turned him over to the
Gestapo, literally carrying him across the border at Basel, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1940, because his parents had obtained an exit permit for him
to travel to Shanghai, Carmel, like other Jews with legal papers to
leave Europe, was released from the camp by the Germans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a training ground for the SS,'' Carmel said. ``They
learned the business here. From killing 20 to 30 of us a day, they
went on to trainloads later.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not Carmel's first trip back. He is head of a
130-member Sachsenhausen survivors' group in Israel. But he said he
had eight sleepless nights from the time he got the call from the
prime minister's office about the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Barak asked Carmel to track down survivors with grandchildren
who were Israeli soldiers; the prime minister, a former general who
threw back his shoulders and snapped to attention when a German
honor guard welcomed him, believes that Israel's military strength
is the best revenge on history.
</P>
<P>
   Carmel found two such survivors. One grandson soldier, Yuval
Ronen, 19, tenderly helped his grandfather, Yerachmiel Bahor, on
and off his chair during the memorial service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud to come here,'' Ronen said. ``I know it's important
to him, and it's important for me to see where he was and how he
suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``To come here as a soldier of Israel is to show
that now is not like then. Then we had no country and Jews were
spread all over the world. Today there is a country. It is strong.
And the Holocaust cannot be repeated.''
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a cranberry velvet skullcap, Carmel, slightly bent,
stood at the site of the camp's former shooting trench and gallows.
A young Israeli woman from the northern border town of Qiryat
Shemona, stood at a microphone and hummed the national anthem,
``Hatikva.''
</P>
<P>
   The haunting tune floated through the camp.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Schroeder's presence and the traditional protocol for
meetings of two heads of state, ``Hatikva'' was not followed by the
German anthem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
