<SLUG> BC-EAST-EUROPE-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN IN EASTERN EUROPE HAVE FARED POORLY SINCE END OF COMMUNISM,
UNICEF SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (md) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ The situation of women and girls in much of Eastern
Europe and the former Soviet Union has spiraled downward since the
collapse of communism, with increasing joblessness and abuse and
deteriorating social services, Unicef said Wednesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unicef studied 27 countries in the region, examining a range of
social and economic issues affecting women and girls, and concluded
that while communist policies did not guarantee sexual equality,
women are generally worse off now. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In the transition to a market economy, the status of women is
eroding further,'' said Carol Bellamy, head of Unicef.
</P>
<P>
   With the collapse of state-supported services and the economic
crises of the past decade, many women in the region are facing
unemployment for the first time, the report says.
</P>
<P>
   Some 25 million jobs have been lost in the region in the last
decade. Of these, an estimated 14 million were jobs held by women,
it says. In addition, part-time work has increased; some women hold
full-time jobs that exist only on paper and pay marginal wages.
</P>
<P>
   The study is the sixth by Unicef, on various aspects of
post-communist Europe, and Ms. Bellamy said it was the first
comprehensive look at the range of economic and social issues
affecting the 150 million women and 50 million girls in Central and
Eastern Europe, the Baltic states, the Caucasus and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the decrease in economic self-sufficiency, women
have reduced life expectancy in 16 of the 27 countries studied.
While the decline was temporary in some countries, it has persisted
in about one-third of the countries where data were available.
</P>
<P>
   The chief reasons are increased smoking, alcohol consumption,
drug abuse and unsafe sexual activity. Ms. Bellamy singled out
HIV/AIDS as one of the region's biggest problems. Five years ago,
30,000 cases of HIV, the virus that causes AIDS, were registered.
At the end of 1998, there were 270,000, nine times as many,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   In Russia and three other countries, one of every 100 girls is
infected with syphilis, said John Micklewright, one of the authors
of the study. Increased trafficking in women worsens the situation,
the report says.
</P>
<P>
   Women's power to improve their lot has also been set back, with
the number of women who are lawmakers declining about one-third to
an average of 10 percent in countries studied, according to the
report. Turkmenistan had 18 percent, while Kyrgyzstan had only 1
percent of parliament members who were women. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the few bright spots, Ms. Bellamy said, are the rise in
the number of women entrepreneurs and the increase in grass-roots
organizations that are beginning to take the lead in combating
domestic violence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
