<P>
   AUTO-LABOR-ASSESS (Undated) _ On the surface, the tentative
agreement that the auto workers' union reached with DaimlerChrysler
last week was just the type of extravagant contract that President
John F. Kennedy had once warned the United Auto Workers against.
But the DaimlerChrysler agreement has not set off inflation alarm
bells the way it might have in the Kennedy era partly because a
contract reached with an automaker no longer sets a lockstep
nationwide pattern. Unions in most industries are far weaker than
in the 1960s _ they represent 13.9 percent of the work force, down
from more than 30 percent then. By Steven Greenhouse.
