<SLUG> BC-RADIO-GIANT-ART-570(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A POIGNANT RADIO HOMAGE TO THE `JEWISH GIANT' 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By AMY WALDMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``He was brilliant, brilliant,'' Dorothy Carchman
said, looking at a copy of a Diane Arbus photograph of her nephew,
Eddie Carmel. ``He was exceedingly bright.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not what most people see in the famous Arbus photograph,
whose caption refers not to Eddie Carmel but to ``A Jewish Giant at
Home With His Parents in the Bronx, N.Y.'' When the photo was taken
in 1970, Carmel was around 8 feet tall and weighed more than 300
pounds. In the claustrophobic scene, he towers over his mother and
father, his head bowed to avoid hitting the ceiling, a cane
supporting his weight.
</P>
<P>
   His dimensions were the result of acromegaly, caused by a tumor
on the pituitary gland that produced an excess of growth hormones
and made his lips, jaw, hands and feet swell. By 1970, his body was
so weighed down that he was barely mobile and virtually homebound.
Two years later he died of a heart attack at 36.
</P>
<P>
   The Arbus photo, which hangs in the Museum of Modern Art, gave
him a bit of immortality, all the more so because when he died his
family, steeped in the pain of his life and death, stopped talking
about him. (The Arbus estate would not allow The New York Times to
reprint the photograph.) But now that silence has produced a new
sort of immortality, a powerful 25-minute audio documentary written
and narrated by a cousin who never met him but who became
interested in his life because of the shroud her family had drawn
over it.
</P>
<P>
   The piece will have its premiere Thursday at a sold-out event at
the Jewish Museum in Manhattan and will air on National Public
Radio on Oct. 6. It tells Carmel's story through those who knew
him, including Mrs. Carchman, who is now 85, and her son, Philip,
who was Carmel's cousin and close friend. Carchman's daughter,
Jenny, who is 28, reported and narrated the piece.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary is the culmination of a fascination that began
when Jenny Carchman was 8, saw the Arbus photo, learned that Carmel
was her cousin and asked her father about him. He told her they had
been close, began to cry and that was that: even an 8-year-old can
sense a taboo, and Ms. Carchman said she never raised the subject
with him again. But as Ms. Carchman pursued her own photographic
career, the Arbus photo surfaced again and again, and she decided
to explore Carmel's life. She began filming a documentary about him
but abandoned it in favor of the radio piece, which was produced by
a friend, Stacy Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   Radio may seem a strange medium to tell the story of someone
whose plight was so acutely visual. But telling Carmel's story
through words alone has a beautiful logic: it finally disembodies
him. Listeners focus on who he was, how he felt. How he looked is
left to the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you suspend your immediate impressions,'' Ms.
Abramson said.
</P>
<P>
   Such a suspension is all the more fitting because Carmel was
what one sideshow operator called ``an educated freak,'' an
intelligent, creative man with a talent for words and poems and
jokes. (``My luck, I have to have midget parents,'' he said of the
Arbus photo.) But in life, his mind was continually overshadowed by
his body.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Carchman, his aunt, said that his intelligence also
heightened his pain. ``That was one of the tragedies, that he was
so sharp and understood what was wrong,'' she said. ``He understood
that his life would be different than anyone else's.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
