<HEADER>
A2216 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-JAKOB-LIAR-REVIEW-LAD     09-22 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAKOB-LIAR-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By GLENN WHIPP 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Talk about bad timing. ``Jakob the Liar,'' a sober
comedy set during the Holocaust, finished filming nearly two years
ago and has since sat on the shelf while its filmmakers watched the
similarly themed ``Life Is Beautiful'' steal its thunder.
</P>
<P>
   And while the two films share only a time period and,
occasionally, a tone, the comparisons to Roberto Benigni's
Oscar-winning film are inevitable and, unfortunately, rather
damning. ``Jakob's'' backdrop, as imagined by Oscar-winning
production designer Luciana Arrighi, is a horrible wonder to
behold, but the awkward balance of the film's story only
underscores the tremendous (and unlikely) accomplishment Benigni
managed to pull off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jakob'' began its life as a novel by an East German writer,
Jurak Becker, and was made into a movie, ``Jakob Der Lugner'' 25
years ago. Hungarian-born director Peter Kassovitz obtained the
rights to make it into an English-language film and has been
working on doing just that, in between making feature films and
television projects from his home base in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's long gestation is evident in its remarkable visual
conception, which frightfully evokes the setting, a Polish ghetto
in the waning days of World War II. In this unnamed locale lives
Jakob (Robin Williams), one of the thousands of Polish Jews living
in the grim, Nazi-controlled slum. Relatively speaking, these
survivors are lucky. Most of their neighbors and family (including
Jakob's wife) have been shipped to the death camps. (Kassovitz
vividly captures the fearful spectre of the trains throughout the
film.)
</P>
<P>
   One day, Jakob overhears a forbidden radio news bulletin
announcing the Russian army is a mere 400 kilometers from his
ghetto. Jakob excitedly shares the optimistic news with his
despondent friends, and the friends soon extrapolate that Jakob
must have a radio himself. Now, this is bad news for Jakob because
if the Gestapo buys into the radio rumor, he will find himself
taking a one-way trip to the gallows.
</P>
<P>
   Jakob will have none of this. He lives by the creed ``the best
thing to do is nothing.'' But as word spreads about his radio, hope
_ an almost-extinct commodity _ returns to the ghetto. Thus, Jakob
faces a dilemma, one compounded by his sudden custody of a
10-year-old refugee girl (Hannah Taylor Gordon), whose belief in
the radio, and Jakob's steady stream of fictitious announcements,
keeps her going.
</P>
<P>
   Inherent in the movie's tightrope act is its mixture of
melodrama and Holocaust hijinks, as well as Williams' presence,
which has come, to some, to represent a low standard in shameless,
lip-quivering mugging. ``Jakob's'' biggest problem, though, is the
limitations imposed by its story. A capsule summary: Neighbors
think Jakob has the radio, Jakob protests, neighbors persist, Jakob
makes up comical bulletin. Repeat ad nauseam.
</P>
<P>
   The subplot involving the little girl is another weak element,
seemingly lifted straight out of the pages of ``The Diary of Anne
Frank.'' Whenever the film is running low on pathos, Taylor Gordon
and her saucer eyes are trotted down from the attic for some
teary-eyed theatrics. It's the movie's one odious concession to
blatant sentimentality, and it never comes close to priming the
audience's tear ducts.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, thankfully, delivers a restrained performance, aided
by a fine ensemble cast that includes Alan Arkin, Bob Balaban, Liev
Schreiber and Armin Mueller-Stahl. But these talented actors are no
match for the ghastly ghetto. The gravity of the place and the
period simply overpowers the lightweight story, leaving the
audience mindful that the Holocaust stands as shaky ground upon
which to build a feel-good concept. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The film: ``Jakob the Liar'' (PG-13; violence, disturbing images). &QL; 
The stars: Robin Williams, Alan Arkin, Bob Balaban, Armin
Mueller-Stahl. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Peter Kassovitz. Screenplay by
Kassovitz and Didier Decoin. Released by Columbia Pictures. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 54 minutes. &QL; 
Playing: Citywide. &QL; 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 1947EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0351 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2217 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-RADIO-GIANT-ART-2NDTA     09-22 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIO-GIANT-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: anyone else's.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Sept. 15, Mrs. Carchman and her son came to the East Village
studio of Sound Portraits Productions, where the audio piece was
produced, to hear it for the first time. Jenny Carchman was there,
as were Ms. Abramson and Dave Isay, the founder of Sound Portraits,
acclaimed for the innovative use of radio to chronicle the lives of
inner-city boys and the denizens of a Bowery hotel, among others.
Isay was the executive producer on ``The Jewish Giant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you excited?'' he asked Carchman, now a 57-year-old
appellate judge who lives in Princeton, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's like my dentist saying to me am I excited,'' Carchman
said. He was apprehensive, he said. Next to him on the couch,
facing a copy of the Arbus photo, his mother clutched tissues she
had brought.
</P>
<P>
   The piece started with a sound montage of reminiscences about
Carmel, beginning with this: ``Eddie was a little bit on the
grotesque side.'' Almost immediately, the Carchmans began nodding
in recognition and their eyes began filling with tears.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Carchman mouthed along with her quotes. ``He was
gorgeous,'' she says in the piece. ``He was _ he was beautiful,''
she whispered as she listened.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary tracks Carmel's experiences as he grows,
mushrooming during high school so that he can barely fit through
the classroom doors at the William H. Taft High School in the
Bronx. He studied for two years at City College, but he could no
longer pretend he was normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a freak,'' Mrs. Carchman recalls him telling her late one
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie, you are the tallest person I know,'' she said she
replied. ``If you want to call yourself a freak, so be it. Now what
are you going to do?''
</P>
<P>
   What he did was recognize that he was too big to hide. He went
out into the world and accepted the minor celebrity that came his
way, always trying to parlay it into something more. ``Eddie
Carmel, Tallest Man on Earth, Wants Booking on Talent Alone,'' one
headline read. He tried stand-up comedy and voice-overs, recorded a
song called ``The Good Monster'' and in 1963 had a bit part in a
movie, ``The Brain That Wouldn't Die.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the end Carmel was simply too big to succeed in show
business. He turned to the circus and sideshows, unhappily, by all
accounts. His health deteriorated _ first one cane, then two, then
a wheelchair _ and so did his mood. Those who knew him at the
sideshows described him as bitter and angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got a look,'' Irwin Sherman, his best friend, says in the
documentary, referring to Carmel's dawning realization that he was
going to die. At that point, the Carchmans, listening to the
audiotape, had a look too.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Abramson and Ms. Carchman went to great lengths to track
down pieces of Carmel arcana, even finding the sideshow collector
who purchased his clothes, underwear and all, from the Carmels
after their son's death.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Abramson posted notices on Web sites like
www.backinthebronx.com, where former Bronx residents exchange
sepia-toned memories about candy stores and marbles tournaments,
and was deluged with messages from people who remembered Carmel.
For many, he seemed to evoke the Bronx of the 1950s and 1960s,
nostalgically remembered as a place of shtetl-like neighborhoods
where everybody knew everybody _ and everybody knew Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once people started coming out of the woodwork, no one could
get enough of talking about him,'' Ms. Abramson said.
</P>
<P>
   One of Eddie's last appearances, in the early 1970s, was at the
opening of a shopping center in Co-op City in the Bronx. Carmel was
so sick, so heavy, at that point that he could not even get out of
his chair. Two thousand people booed and threw cups at him. ``You
expect the man who is eight-three to stand eight-three, that's part
of the deal,'' the man who had hired Carmel told Ms. Carchman and
Ms. Abramson, explaining why he did not want to pay for the
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Such stories are a reminder of the cruelty that shadowed him. At
the circus, people would stick pins in his feet to see if he was
real. Carmel would lean over to his friend, Sherman, and say, ``And
they call me a freak?''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Carchmans both said the piece showed them that Carmel,
who to them was gentle, gregarious and good-natured, endured more
pain than they realized. The indignities did not end with his
death, when a coffin had to be custom built as his clothes had been
custom-made in life.
</P>
<P>
   At Carmel's funeral, a cousin who barely knew him delivered a
eulogy calling his life a tragedy, a waste of a human life.
Carchman, then 30, had sat silently, wanting to stand up and say
that his cousin's life was not a tragedy, not a waste, but much
more. He did not, and it has pained him all these years, largely
accounting for the long silence his daughter has now penetrated.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Carmel's death, his parents, now dead, moved to
Israel, where their son had been born. The day before they left,
Carchman said he told Carmel's mother what he had wanted to say at
the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, why didn't you?'' she yelled.
</P>
<P>
   Carchman cried that day, he said, and he cried again the other
night listening to the audiotape. Ms. Carchman and Ms. Abramson had
tracked down the cousin, and he had reprised his eulogy almost
exactly, once again saying that Carmel's story was ``of a tragedy
of a human life.''
</P>
<P>
   But finally Carchman has his say. ``His life was not a tragedy _
he was not a recluse, he didn't hide in a cave,'' he says in the
documentary. ``He took what God had given him'' _ Carchman starts
crying, then finishes _ ``he did what he could. Everyone left that
funeral thinking that this was an empty, tragic life, and it
wasn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
