<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MUMFORD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUM'S NOT THE WORD FOR `MUMFORD' PSYCHOLOGISTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Writer-director Lawrence Kasdan has dabbled in a variety of
genres, but his favorite theme is the angst of middle-class
(usually white) people. Kasdan's latest, the genial seriocomedy
``Mumford,'' is his best take on the topic, avoiding the
self-satisfaction that marred ``The Big Chill'' and the
self-importance that hindered ``Grand Canyon.''
</P>
<P>
   Mumford _ the title refers to a picturesque California town and
to the unorthodox psychologist who treats some of its residents _
works simply because it's so relaxed. Loren Dean _ who has somehow
gone from looking like Matthew Modine's brother to looking like
Charles Grodin's more handsome son _ plays the amiable doc, whose
methods include cutting off patients when they begin to bore him
and kicking them out when they get on his nerves. He's also not
above divulging their secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mumford is a small town, it has enough neurotics to
keep the doc's practice jumping. They include a pharmacist (Pruitt
Taylor Vince) with a highly developed (albeit old-fashioned) sexual
fantasy life; a lawyer (Martin Short) who's so egotistical that
when he dreams, everyone else is naked and he's the only one who
has studied for the test; a compulsive shopper (Mary McDonnell);
and an anorexic teen-ager (Zooey Deschanel, daughter of celebrated
cinematographer Caleb). The only well-adjusted person in town seems
to be the diner owner (Alfre Woodard), who's the doctor's best pal.
</P>
<P>
   Doc Mumford's two newest patients have as much effect on him as
he does on them. One is a lonely, boyish computer tycoon (Jason
Lee) who just wants someone to play with; another is a woman
suffering from chronic fatigue syndrome (Hope Davis) who sparks an
instant attraction in the shrink.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the doctor tells the fatigued woman that he can
instantly give himself a headache by having two conflicting
thoughts, which kind of describes my feelings about Kasdan. His
talents for interesting characters, sharp dialogue and ambitious
topics are admirable; his tendency to make his actors emphasize the
profundity of that dialogue, as if they were in diction class, is
an irritating sign that he's a little too enraptured of his own
intelligence. Fortunately, Kasdan also has a knack for assembling
great casts that can overcome some of his more troublesome habits.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Dean's laid-back, almost deadpan interpretation of
Mumford is off-putting, but it soon becomes clear how well his
underplaying serves the role, which could easily have turned into a
sanctimonious, Robin Williams-style portrayal of One Man Against
the Establishment. Dean anchors a perceptive ensemble that's topped
by Davis _ who can make you believe that the word ``winsome'' was
invented for her _ in yet another of her keenly observed
performances. Only Lee _ so good as a jerk in ``Chasing Amy,'' so
miscast as a nice guy in ``Kissing a Fool'' _ seems uncomfortable
with his part as the wide-eyed, unshaven computer geek.
</P>
<P>
   If Kasdan is like Mumford, he must give himself headaches
easily, because he also seems to be in conflict with himself here _
the Hollywood director struggling to reconcile the offbeat with the
conventional. Much of Mumford shines with originality, but it risks
collapse with a subplot in which the lawyer (Short, who's badly
used here) attempts to conspire with the town's two other shrinks
to discredit Mumford. The crowd-pleasing ending is also a little
too pat; Kasdan is still more screenwriter than director, and he's
far too keen on tying up all his loose ends rather than leaving any
mess behind.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Mumford'' is such an easygoing, loose movie that it's
tough to mind Kasdan's indulgences. And he manages to say a lot
about psychobabble, consumerism, sex, vanity and even Hollywood
without losing his way or cramming things down our throats. His
ultimate message in ``Mumford'' is that we should learn to listen a
little better; it should be obvious, but it isn't, and so it's a
message we can all bear to hear _ especially when we're being
entertained so well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mumford'' is rated R for nudity, strong language and sexual
situations.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
