<HEADLINE>
WHAT IS IT LIKE TO BE A TELECOMMUTER? 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Friday, Sept. 24.) 
(lh) 
 By DAVID GRIMES    
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before we begin, we should define the word ``telecommuter.''
Some of my jealous colleagues at the newspaper define it as ``a
person who is paid to sit around the house watching daytime
television in his pajamas.'' While there is some truth to that
definition, it does not really capture all of the grim realities of
the telecommuting experience, such as dragging oneself out of bed
at the crack of 11:30 and the strict rule forbidding the
consumption of blender drinks while operating the laptop.
(Pineapple juice makes the keys sticky.)
</P>
<P>
   It is important to stress the grim realities of telecommuting to
those unfortunate drones who continue to toil away in grim, gray,
blender-free offices because to them it sounds like dying and going
to heaven:
</P>
<P>
   _ No twitchy boss on his eighth cup of Folgers breathing down
your neck.
</P>
<P>
   _ No white-knuckled drives through rush-hour traffic.
</P>
<P>
   _ No filthy public bathrooms. (Your filthy bathroom is for your
use and yours alone.)
</P>
<P>
   _ No more working in a cramped, soulless cubicle. (From now on
you get to work in a cramped, soulless spare bedroom.)
</P>
<P>
   So what are the grim realities? For one thing, working alone at
home all day, you sometimes get a little desperate for human
companionship. Some telecommuters actually look forward to calls
from telephone solicitors so they have someone to chat with. The
monthly visit of the bug man is as special to the telecommuter as a
visit by the queen might be to someone more socially connected.
</P>
<P>
   Over a period of time, the telecommuter begins to take on the
appearance of Ben Gunn, the marooned castaway in ``Treasure
Island.'' The scraggly hair; tattered, disheveled clothes (or
pajamas, as the case may be); halting speech and wild, frightened
eyes, like those of a rat just before it's flattened by a semi, are
typical of a person who spends his or her days alone in a big,
empty house with nothing but a computer, television, stereo,
fully-stocked refrigerator, swimming pool, books, newspapers,
magazines and video games to break the monotony.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite these grim realities, telecommuting can be a
pretty sweet deal. If you're a disciplined, self-motivated person
(i.e. no more than two Bloody Marys before 8 a.m.) and you've got
the right kind of job (i.e. writing three weekly newspaper humor
columns that require no research or interviews), then telecommuting
may be for you.
</P>
<P>
   But take my advice: On those days that you've got to pop into
the office, try to remember to wear clean pajamas.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
