<SLUG> BC-FIRE-ANT-THREAT-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRE ANTS IN THE HOME CAN BE DANGEROUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DORIS CHANDLER    
 Gainesville (Fla.) Sun    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ Fire ants can pose a threat in nursing homes
and places where people are bedridden or otherwise immobile,
researchers reported this week in the issue of Annals of Internal
Medicine,
</P>
<P>
   Since 1989, 10 people have been attacked indoors by fire ants,
including four residents of nursing homes. Two of the nursing home
residents died, the researchers found. Three of the reported
attacks occurred in apartment complexes; one happened in a hotel;
and two were in private homes _ including an attack on a 5-day-old
infant in a crib.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the people attacked had pre-existing neurological
impairments, including Alzheimer's disease, dementia and
developmental disabilities, according to the report, which examines
indoor fire ant attacks on people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fire ants are all over the southeastern United States and
California, and we're not going to completely eradicate them,''
said David F. Williams, a co-author of the report and a
Gainesville-based research entomologist with the U.S. Department of
Agriculture. ``But we need to be aware if they are in schoolyards,
inside nursing homes and clinics, or anywhere people are bedridden
and can't defend themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said that in times of drought, fire ants don't find
much food and water outside, so they move inside. Bedridden
patients might have bits of food around them that would attract the
ants, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``One or two fire ants come in and find the food source, and
soon a trail of them are coming in. These are aggressive fire ants,
and when the patient moves, they begin to sting,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   He said most pesticides available for destroying fire ant mounds
are nontoxic to humans and can be used safely.
</P>
<P>
   Williams co-wrote the article with Dr. Richard D. deShazo,
professor of medicine and pediatrics at the University of
Mississippi Medical Center in Jackson, and Dr. Edward S. Moak, a
private-practice physician in Brookhaven, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Fire ants have expanded their territory into states such as
California and Virginia, where people are not as familiar with
them, said deShazo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Southerners are pretty much aware of the problem, but the
fire ants are expanding their range so rapidly that there are a lot
of neophytes now becoming acquainted with them, and we want to make
sure that as many people as possible in the medical community are
aware of the medical consequences,'' deShazo said.
</P>
<P>
   Another goal of the report is to make sure people understand
that these ants sting inside dwellings as well as outside, he said.
``They're just as mean inside as they are outside,'' deShazo said.
</P>
<P>
   DeShazo said professional extermination services should be
sought if fireants are found inside a building.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they have ants inside, then they have an active fire ant
colony either in the wall or in the foundation,'' deShazo said,
``and you can't take care of the problem with sprays, because you
have to kill the queen.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Sun in Gainsville, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 1951EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0358 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
