A2227 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOODS-DEATHS-COX     09-22 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOODS-DEATHS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    College student's body recovered; at least 40 dead
 &HT;    By Travis Fain
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ East Carolina University police pulled a
student's body from the water near the campus Wednesday, bringing
Pitt County's death toll from Hurricane Floyd to three with one
other man presumed dead.
</P>
<P>
   Child's death is one of more than 40 in eastern North Carolina
attributed to flooding and Hurricane Floyd. In Pitt County, two
Hispanic men were found dead in their car near Grimesland Friday.
Their names have not been released pending notification of the
families.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses saw a fourth man swept off a collapsing bridge on N.C.
33 near the entrance to the Brook Valley neighborhood last
Wednesday night. Police have called off their active search, which
once included a scuba diving team and an officer's personal fishing
boat, for the unidentified man, . A detective is still
investigating the case, said Capt. K.M. Smeltzer from the
Greenville Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Child, 18, was a freshman at ECU. The medical examiner's
office ruled his death an accidental drowning.
</P>
<P>
   Child had been missing since around 2 p.m. Thursday when he
disappeared from his brother Adam's apartment, his mother, Tina
Child, said Monday. He'd been taking a nap and his wallet and keys
were left in the apartment, she said.
</P>
<P>
   His mother put up posters, purchased an ad in a newspaper and
got Aaron's name, picture and age on local news broadcasts in an
effort to find her son.
</P>
<P>
   His body was found around 9 a.m. Wednesday in water near the
intersection of 10th Street and College Hill Drive, ECU police
said.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of other missing people continue to be called in to
sheriff's deputies and Greenville police. Many reports are from
family members who can't locate people displaced by the flood.
</P>
<P>
   But the county's death toll is likely to rise as the water
recedes, officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not get overly optimistic about this,'' Pitt County
spokesman Barry Gaskins said. ``We've got a vast area that is under
water right now ... it would be very premature and prematurely
optimistic to think (the three confirmed fatalities are) all.''
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how many are dead, said Rick Fisher, sheriff's
department chief of Community Patrols.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing would tickle me more than to send our teams in and
come up with a big goose egg,'' Fisher said. ``I don't guess it's
realistic, but it's hopeful and still entirely possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is a county-by-county list of the dead.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bertie County _ A man who went to help someone with a stalled
vehicle in Windsor was swept away by floodwaters from the Cashie
River. Another man died after bailing water from a stalled car;
possibly was due to a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   _ Columbus County _ A man had a fatal heart attack after being
rescued in his car.
</P>
<P>
   _ Craven County _ Badger J. Chandler, 76, of Vanceboro, was
washed away while traveling on a flooded road.
</P>
<P>
   _ Duplin County _ A man was found in a ditch in Wallace,
possibly drowned. There are three other confirmed deaths here,
though details are not available.
</P>
<P>
   _ Edgecombe County _ Six drowned after a boat carrying 12 people
from their flood-threatened homes near Pinetops capsized. The
victims include Teshika Vines, 5, Ben Mayo, Vivian Mayo, Keisha
Mayo, 24, Cabrina Flowers and Destiny Flowers. A woman was killed
in a collision on a wet highway. Another motorist was killed in an
accident blamed on high water.
</P>
<P>
   _ Halifax County _ James Stokes, 65, of Hobgood, drowned after
being trapped in his vehicle in Scotland Neck.
</P>
<P>
   _ Johnston County _ Paul Wesley Mobley, 31, of Clayton, and his
daughter Emily Mobley, 5, died when the vehicle they were in on
Rural Rd. 1525 was carried into Swift Creek. Eusebio Maldonado, 30,
of Clayton, died when his vehicle struck the water near Rural Road
2339 and sank into Little River Creek.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jones County _ James Wilder, a 70-year-old state Department of
Transportation worker from Trenton, was killed while helping a
stranded motorist.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lenoir County _ Lynwood Earl Gooding, 56, of Kinston, drowned
when his car ran into several feet of water on U.S. 70.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nash County _ A woman died after her car stalled on Interstate
95 in 4 feet of water; possibly due to a heart attack. Two
motorists in a vehicle on U.S. 64 just east of Nashville were
washed away by a swollen creek. One motorist in a vehicle on U.S.
64 in Rocky Mount was taken off the highway into floodwaters. One
motorist in a vehicle on N.C. 48 was swept away by a swollen creek.
Richard Phillips, 40, was found Tuesday off U.S. 301.
</P>
<P>
   _ New Hanover County _ William T. Jones, 31, a worker with
Haynes Electric Utility Corp. in Asheville, was electrocuted when
an accidental charge came off a line where he was working near
Castle Hayne.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pender County _ William Nixon, 47, drove his vehicle into high
water on Penderlee Highway and was swept away by flood water.
Another man was swept away by flood water on I-40.
</P>
<P>
   _ Robeson County _ Marvin Moody, 43, and Regional Wayne Jones,
37, died when their vehicle ran into a fallen tree right after the
hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sampson County _ A man driving at night hit a fallen tree on
an Autryville road.
</P>
<P>
   _ Warren County _ George Clinton Jones and Lou Giggets Hargroves
were swept away in their vehicle while attempting to cross RP 1600
south of Warrenton.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wayne County _ Kenneth Norwood Denning, 51, of Mount Olive,
died when he drove through a washed-out section of road Thursday.
Sheryl Ann Whitley, 42, of Goldsboro, died under similar
circumstances. Her car was found Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
