<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2228 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOODS-UTILITIES-COX     09-22 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOODS-UTILITIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    City water crisis nears end
 &HT;    By Dawn Bryant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Water pressure in some Greenville homes _ hit
hard by rains from Huuricane Floyd _ increased Wednesday and could
be restored fully by Thursday morning, Greenville Utilities' top
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Utility officials shifted systems from the now stabilized
electric substation, which has survived threats from floodwaters,
to its submerged water treatment plant, which still is battling the
Tar River's wrath.
</P>
<P>
   GUC crews shuttled by boat to the water plant while trying
Wednesday to dry out the facility and reactivate water pumps that
treat water from the Tar River.
</P>
<P>
   If overnight efforts are successful, residents could have full
service restored Thusday, said Malcolm Green, GUC's general
manager/CEO. But the plant also must fill elevated storage tanks _
which hold 3 1/2 million gallons _ and find and repair broken
distribution pipes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   That makes it difficult to pinpoint when the water will be
restored, Green said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows that one,'' he said. ``If everything works right,
by morning they could see everything back right.''
</P>
<P>
   The water loss is the latest of the hurdles Greenville residents
have endured since Hurricane Floyd dumped 13 inches of rain on the
area a week ago. The downpours fell on an already saturated ground
from Hurricane Dennis' repeat visits and other recent rain.
</P>
<P>
   The combination produced the worst flood in Greenville's
history. Three Pitt County residents have died, another is presumed
dead, and preliminary damage estimates have topped $1.6 billion for
Pitt County alone.
</P>
<P>
   The overflowing Tar River, which peaked at 29.72 feet Tuesday at
five feet above the 100-year floodmark set in 1919, has forced
thousands of residents from their homes and engulfed houses,
apartments and offices.
</P>
<P>
   A boil-order still remains for residents who do have water.
Customers of Eastern Pines and Bell Arthur water corporations also
should boil water for three minutes to kill any bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   In Greenville, water heaters shouldn't be turned back on until
residents see water flowing at a normal rate, Green said.
</P>
<P>
   One of three submerged pumps that bring water from the Tar River
to be treated was restored by early Wednesday, and filters were
cleaned of debris.
</P>
<P>
   The combination resulted in pressure increasing for some of the
26,130 water customers.
</P>
<P>
   While the city again asked most businesses to voluntarily close
because of fire concerns, the Pitt County Health Department lifted
a restriction Wednesday on restaurants because many have regained
water service.
</P>
<P>
   But they must have enough water pressure to adequately clean
dishes and flush toilets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can't be just dribbling out of the faucet,'' said Jack
Weathersby, of the food and lodging section of Pitt County
Environmental Health.
</P>
<P>
   Officials were making spot checks, but had found only a few
minor problems, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these people are cooperating with us,'' Weathersby
said. ``That has not been too much of a problem today.''
</P>
<P>
   Retailers like grocery and convenience stores and pharmacies,
all of which sell food, beverages and necessary toiletries, are
exempt from the city's voluntary closure request.
</P>
<P>
   While the fire department has arranged for back-up supplies from
the west, it doesn't want to take chances. On Wednesday,
firefighters only had one-tenth of the pressure they need.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taking them a long time to restore the pressure that they
need,'' said Katie Veilleux, the city's public information officer.
``We still have a ways to go.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Greenville Utilities shifted the focus of their
creative engineering from the electric substation to the water
treatment plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having trouble, believe it or not, getting water out of
the river,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pitt-Greenville Airport is submerged, with boats replacing
airplanes over the runways. GUC's Mumford Road operations center
also is flooded.
</P>
<P>
   The water has shut down roads throughout the county, including
most bridges in and out of town. Even when the water recedes, some
roads could remain closed because of water damage.
</P>
<P>
   With the crisis catching the attention of national media,
agencies from as far away as Alabama have offered to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had people all over the country volunteering to bring
water in,'' Veilleux said.
</P>
<P>
   It's the other type of water residents and officials wish would
go away. After cresting Tuesday, the Tar River receded more than
four inches overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just a drop in the bucket, but it is going in the right
direction,'' said Jones, GUC's electric director.
</P>
<P>
   Once the water is gone, the cleanup will begin. On Wednesday,
the city assembled three-member assessment teams that must inspect
dwellings for safety and damage before residents will be allowed to
return.
</P>
<P>
   Officials already are concerned about snakes, dead animals and
dozens of other hazards the water potentially could leave behind,
Veilleux said.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors in Rocky Mount found two dead bodies in two days,
City Manager Ron Kimble said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what is under this water,'' Veilleux said. ``Now
the water is receding and we are entering into another phase of
this disaster. This is just going to be a huge job.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
