<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2232 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-TAIWAN-QUAKE-0923-1st     09-22 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-QUAKE-0923-1stLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GRIEVING TAIWANESE STRUGGLE TOWARD QUAKE'S EPICENTER TO AID
RELATIVES, RESCUERS FIND MORE BODIES
 &HT;    EDS: Updates with fresh casualty figures in 4th graf
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PULI, Taiwan _ Taiwanese by the thousands threaded across
half-ruptured bridges here Wednesday, past fresh rockslides and
across miles of rippled asphalt to search for relatives at the
epicenter of the Taiwan earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   With rescue efforts complicated by Wednesday's aftershocks, they
found that nature had dealt capriciously with this mountain town of
89,000 people closest to the quake's ground zero. Here and
elsewhere in Taiwan's hardest-hit Nantou County it looked as if the
quake had hopscotched across the landscape like a giant tornado,
devastating one place while leaving adjacent territory seemingly
untouched.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what seemed just as remarkable was that anyone could have
survived the epicenter's fury Tuesday, and then three jolting
aftershocks measuring 6.8, 6.1 and 6.0 _ the strongest of more than
2,000 that have rocked the island _ on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The aftershocks were feared to have triggered mudslides, cracked
one of Taiwan's largest reservoirs and forced evacuations, as the
death toll from Tuesday's quake climbed to 2,032 people, officials
said. There were estimates that more than 6,500 were injured. Some
2,600 people were believed to be trapped in rubble more than 200
were still missing, but rescuers were finding more bodies than
survivors as they bored into collapsed houses and high-rise
apartment complexes across central Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-afternoon Wednesday, relatives and rescue workers here in
Puli had pulled out 180 dead bodies from the wreckage of more than
1,000 squashed buildings. Another 1,020 people have turned up
injured, and the scent of decaying bodies indicates that at least
some others remain in the wreckage of buildings that seemed to have
collapsed to their knees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the people remaining under the rubble are all
dead,'' Mayor Hung Ming Chang told reporters about 40 hours after
Monday's quake that measured 7.6 on the open-ended Richter scale.
The mayor estimated that one-fourth of his town had been totally
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on this island of 22 million, rescue efforts yielded
just nine people pulled alive from the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   Much-needed rescue crews from Fairfax Co., Va., and Miami-Dade,
Fla., arrived in Taiwan Wednesday and rescued a man who had been
trapped 48 hours inside a caved-in apartment building in the town
of Touliu.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened to my building?'' 33-year-old survivor Hsu
Tse-kai asked repeatedly, according to the Associated Press, as the
crews spent eight hours digging him out of a four-story chunk of
building that had been compressed into about 10 feet of rubble.
</P>
<P>
   The rescue workers then started digging deeper in search of a
1-year-old boy, saying they were encouraged by listening devices
that appeared to pick up the sound of a child's toy, the Associated
Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   Some 14 countries have sent earthquake specialists to the
island, including the United States, Russia, Switzerland, Turkey,
Japan, Singapore, South Korea, Israel and the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   The Central News Agency placed the number of foreign specialists
in the country at about 500, with more scheduled to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Puli, at least, the fast-moving relief effort seemed
markedly more effective than the near-paralysis that beset Turkish
agencies when a 7.3-magnitude earthquake struck central Turkey in
August, killing more than 15,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   And by whatever quirk of the way nature's tectonic plates
collided in the belly of the earth, many of Puli's inhabitants
lived to tell about it. And although most buildings suffered cracks
in interior walls, most looked relatively undamaged from the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   To reach Puli, desperate relatives had to drive their cars or
motorcycles across a dozen precarious bridges whose pavement had
sunk or collapsed. Some were passable only because workers laid
down patches that looked like steel band-aids across gaps in the
joints of bridge sections.
</P>
<P>
   For some, it was a journey to grief.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sister is still buried there in the first floor,'' said Luo
Jian Zhe, a 33-year-old salesman, clutching an incense stick as he
watched Japanese and Taiwanese rescue crews drilling into his
prosperous in-laws' collapsed four-story home. Luo watched rescuers
haul out the corpses of
</P>
<P>
   four of his in-laws, only to learn that his sister, too, had
been found crushed to death.
</P>
<P>
   For others like semiconductor engineer Child Lee(CQ), joy was at
the other end of the perilous ascent from western Taiwan's
relatively untouched coastal flatlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't know what was going on here because we couldn't
connect by telephone,'' said Lee, 33, ``so we had to come up here
somehow to see.'' Lee found that his sister's father-in-law, a
retired bank executive, had survived unhurt and with most of his
possessions intact within a few miles of the epicenter of one of
Taiwan's deadliest quakes since a 7.4 magnitude tremor hit the
island in 1935, killing 3,276 people. Taiwan is hit by dozens of
quakes each year, but most are centered in the Pacific Ocean east
of the island and cause no damage.
</P>
<P>
   The ravaging of this Puli alone, accounted for nearly one-tenth
of the deaths due to the earthquake throughout Taiwan, and
one-fourth of the island's earthquake injuries.
</P>
<P>
   With Puli emerging on Taiwanese television reports as the center
of devastation, the high command of the Taiwanese Army flew and
trucked in hundreds of soldiers to mount a formidable
military-style relief effort for Puli and surrounding villages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We treat this calamity like a war,'' said Maj. Gen. Wu Se Hui,
one of a procession of senior commanders who have been arriving
aboard helicopter relief flights to supervise local aid efforts.
``Once the order comes down from the top, we can move very
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 24-hour period, the Taiwanese Army landed more than 60
helicopter loads of food, bottled water, tents, frozen blood and
other supplies in Puli's makeshift rescue center in an athletic
field behind an elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   With the morgues and hospitals in Puli overflowing with scores
of corpses, the Army began flying in blocks of ice and body bags to
prevent the victims from decomposing before they could be examined
by forensic investigators and then buried.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
