u s BC-GLF-RYDER-WOODS-BOS &LR;      09-22 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-WOODS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TY-GAH WOWS 'EM AT TCC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE _ He never knew his name had an H in it until he got
to Clyde Street. ``Ty-gah,'' people kept shouting at Tiger Woods as
he strode along The Country Club's sodden fairways Wednesday
morning. ``Ovah heah, Ty-gah.''
</P>
<P>
   A glance, a nod, a wave, anything. They'd risen before dawn.
hundreds of them, and clambered onto shuttle buses and now they
were standing half a dozen deep along the ropes in the drizzle and
dribble, watching a Ryder Cup practice round.
</P>
<P>
   These were the people who couldn't get tickets to the main event
on the weekend, who didn't know a banker or a lawyer who could
sneak them into a corporate pleasure dome between the crab legs and
the Chardonnay. These were the guys who play weekends at Ponky and
The J. These were the kids from the city who can pick one golfer
out of a lineup.
</P>
<P>
   For one day, they could get within a chip shot of Ty-gah, close
enough for a Kodak moment, close enough to hear his club head
whistle off the tee. ``Amazing,'' said Todd Boulay, after watching
Woods launch an ICBM on 12, the course's toughest hole. ``He just
crushed the ball. He's awesome, that's all there is to it. It's
much more impressive seeing it from behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Boulay had come from Worcester with his friend Wayne Humphrey,
who had gotten two tickets to the whole week through the lottery.
``My mother called me and said, you've got some junk mail here that
says Ryder Cup on it,'' Humphrey said. ``I said, don't throw it
away. I'll be right over.''
</P>
<P>
   Trenton Patterson had no idea he was competing for a place in
the Woods entourage when he wrote a school essay on teamwork. ``I
heard the prize had something to do with golf,'' he shrugged. What
he won was a day at The Country Club for his entire class at
William Barton Rogers Middle School in Hyde Park.
</P>
<P>
   That meant Rickey Woods, who says he's Tiger's cousin ``but he
doesn't know it yet.'' That meant Norman Leitao, who has 45
pictures of Woods in his bedroom. That meant Joe Fitzpatrick,
who'll gladly play alternate shots with Woods if he shows up at the
George Wright.
</P>
<P>
   They may play the game, but none of the rapt faces behind ropes
Wednesday play Tiger's game, with its fearful symmetry. None of
them reach a par 4 in one. None of them dig a ball out of wet rough
with a slick grip and then putt for birdie. None of them can hit a
wedge shot from under a tree and drop it to within 2 feet of the
pin. Not every round. Not every hole.
</P>
<P>
   This was a priceless chance for a free tutorial from a young
master. Watch and learn. ``Day off for you guys?'' someone asked a
threesome from the Foxboro High golf team. ``Well . . .,'' one of
them said.
</P>
<P>
   Just an unscheduled field trip to see Tiger in his natural
habitat. He turned up precisely at 9 for the day's first foursome,
wearing a blue ballcap, cream windbreaker and mocha trousers. ``The
rain'll hold off,'' a hole marshal assured him. ``Yeah,'' Woods
replied dubiously, glancing up at weeping leaden skies.
</P>
<P>
   This was no day for bantering with the gallery. Woods had
twiddled his thumbs behind the Europeans on Tuesday and ended up
hopscotching around the course. Wednesday, he proceeded
purposefully from tee to green, chewing a wad of gum and trying to
avoid pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger, get over here and shake my hand,'' implored Bob
Lavalette, who'd driven down from Burlington, Vt. with his buddies.
Woods kept walking. ``I got shunned by The Man,'' Lavalette
groaned. ``Witnessed by Navin, Madden, and Mahoney,'' one of his
buddies said.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing personal. But this was the back nine and this was
foursome format, with Woods and Steve Pate dueling David Duval and
Phil Mickelson. ``I want to go first,'' Pate informed Woods as they
approached the 10th tee. ``I want you to enjoy some of the places I
see.'' Woods assented, then headed for a porta-potty. Moments
later, Pate was banging on the door. ``Change of plans,'' he told
Woods. ``You're starting.''
</P>
<P>
   He was a 21-year-old rookie two years ago at Valderrama, but
Woods is Da Man this time. He will play all five matches and he
will have a following that will equal Arnie's Army back in the day
and he will hear his name shouted and murmured as it has never been
before _ with a dropped R.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 1956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
