<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2236 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-22 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: DARK CLOUDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I remember my mother coming in from a storm one night many years
ago and telling us, ``You don't want to know what's going on out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   I think there's a tendency to take a similar approach to the
undeniable warming of the earth's oceans and atmosphere, and the
extreme weather events that scientists believe are associated with
it. If you watch television or read the newspapers or step outside
you might begin to think a plague of biblical proportions is under
way.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey is trying to recover from some of the worst flooding
in its history. And just a month ago New York City was brought to a
virtual standstill when, as reported in The New York Times,
``clouds like those that had merely puckered overhead all summer
suddenly discharged up to four inches of rain in less than three
hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurricanes, heat waves, droughts, torrential downpours and
flooding, raging forest fires, deadly disease outbreaks _ all
descending on us in frighteningly rapid succession. You can be
forgiven for not wanting to know what's going on out there.
</P>
<P>
   But pull yourself together. This is serious.
</P>
<P>
   The outbreak of St. Louis encephalitis, the potentially deadly
viral disease that is spread by mosquitoes, was so unexpected in
New York that doctors at first were unsure of what they were
seeing. But a paper published in March 1998 in the Bulletin of the
American Meteorological Society noted that climate warming and
outbreaks of extreme weather could be expected to have serious
implications for the spread of such diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The paper was titled, ``Biological and Physical Signs of Climate
Change: Focus on Mosquito-Borne Diseases.'' It said, ``Throughout
this century public health researchers have understood that climate
circumscribes the distribution of mosquito-borne diseases, while
weather affects the timing and intensity of outbreaks.'' Among the
diseases mentioned in the paper was St. Louis encephalitis, which
has been detected in recent weeks not only in New York City but in
suburban Westchester County and Connecticut as well.
</P>
<P>
   The lead author of the paper was Dr. Paul Epstein, associate
director of the Center for Health and the Global Environment at
Harvard Medical School. He stressed in an interview this week that
you cannot say that global warming ``caused'' the outbreak of St.
Louis encephalitis or any other event. But it is known that the
metropolitan area experienced the precise weather conditions
favorable to such an outbreak _ a mild winter (during which some of
the mosquitoes hibernate in the subways, believe it or not)
followed by a very hot and very dry summer (July was the hottest on
record), which encourages breeding, reduces the prevalence of the
mosquitoes' natural predators and speeds up the maturation of the
virus.
</P>
<P>
   And those conditions are the ones associated with the climate
change that is believed to be taking place.
</P>
<P>
   Much more serious public health consequences from extreme
weather events have been occurring in developing countries. The
incredible rains and flooding that accompanied Hurricane Mitch,
which killed more than 11,000 people in Central America last year,
led to outbreaks of cholera, malaria, dengue fever and other
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Epstein said it is important to recognize the serious threats to
public health that are among the consequences of climate change and
extreme weather events. That awareness can lead to better
surveillance and earlier and more effective public health
responses.
</P>
<P>
   The threat to public health combined with the enormous economic
costs of these extreme weather events would, if people were
sensible, prompt us to develop environmental and energy policies
designed to alleviate such problems. We'll see.
</P>
<P>
   We are learning that ``climate change is not a gradual
process,'' said Epstein. He said he hopes the brutal consequences
of the weather extremes that we are experiencing will ``motivate us
to move toward a transition to clean energy and energy efficiency
in a much more rapid fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
