<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2237 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOODS-ANIMALS-COX     09-22 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOODS-ANIMALS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Environmentalists concerned over animal waste in lagoons
 &HT;    By T. Scott Batchelor
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Environmental groups say recent flooding
points up the inherent dangers of storing animal waste in lagoons,
but farmers say the system works fine if they follow the rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``The environmental loss ... is staggering,'' said Rick Dove,
who works for the New Bern-based Neuse River Foundation as the
Neuse's ``keeper.''
</P>
<P>
   Because lagoons can flood, they shouldn't be built anywhere near
a river or its tributaries, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never been a question of if, it's always been a question
of when,'' he said. ``We don't need to have them in the flood
plain. It doesn't make any sense.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Smith, president of Rex Smith Farms in Winterville,
said that leaves a big question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which flood plain? The 100-year flood plain? The 500-year
flood plain?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   State officials have been scrambling this week to develop
accurate figures on flooded lagoons.
</P>
<P>
   Daphne Cullom, an environmental specialist in the Washington
office of the state Division of Water Quality, said there are swine
lagoons in Pitt County that flooded as a result of Floyd, but she
did not know exactly how many.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the farmers have lost their lagoons and their
animals,'' Cullom said.
</P>
<P>
   Family and friends rallied to the aid of Rex Smith Farms in
Winterville as floodwaters rose from Contentnea Creek, a tributary
to the Neuse, and threatened the nearly 5,000 hogs in houses about
100 yards away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had enough men and boats so all night we got most of them
out,'' said Rex Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest animals were ferried from the stalls to dry ground,
while others were let loose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We turned them right out in the high field,'' Smith said,
adding that water reached five feet in the houses where the animals
are kept.
</P>
<P>
   The farm lost less than 100 hogs in all, not much more than die
in a typical day, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We buried them 30 feet deep the very same day,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Contentea Creek rose into one waste lagoon and threatened
another one, said Mark Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said current regulations governing the management of
animal waste protect the environment if they're followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like the rules,'' he said. ``We like to protect the
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Several hog farms were under water in the Neuse basin, said
Marion Smith, executive director of the Neuse River Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   She said a flood of this magnitude is the worst possible
scenario for lagoons.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many words for disaster do you know?'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Aerial views reveal ribbons of pink _ the characteristic color
of hog waste _ streaming from lagoons where flood waters barely
cover the pits, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Others that are completely submerged are indistinguishable from
the surrounding waters, said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Flooding from the Tar River has not been a problem for at least
one Pitt County hog farmer, Charles Gaskins of Black Jack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had just got through pumping my lagoon down where it was
supposed to be (before Floyd struck),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the hurricane's torrential rains quickly brought the
levels back up, threatening to break the lagoon walls and prompting
a call to state Division of Water Quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave me permission to pump it back down,'' Gaskins said.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers are not normally allowed to spray lagoon water on
already soaked fields because the waste would run off into ditches,
potentially finding its way into rivers and their tributaries.
</P>
<P>
   Gaskins said state regulators preferred to have the waste
released in a controlled manner than to risk a breech in the lagoon
wall.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups have long complained that open lagoons pose
a risk of spilling nitrogen-rich waste into waterways. Nitrogen is
a nutrient, and both the Neuse and the Pamlico have been declared
nutrient-sensitive waters by state officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping no federal funds will be available for rebuilding
these lagoons in the flood plains,'' said Michelle Nowlin with the
Southern Environmental Law Center in Chapel Hill.
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Smith said he scrupulously monitors the water level in
the farm's lagoons to make sure none of it spills out.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daddy's an old-time fisherman,'' Smith said. ``He knows
what it means to keep clean water.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
