<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENTIFIC-ATLANTA23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scientific-Atlanta adds digital gaming
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Scientific-Atlanta will add interactive computer
gaming to its new digital network as part of an ongoing effort to
pump up sales to cable TV operators.
</P>
<P>
   The interactive gaming will be provided by ICTV, which joins 16
other programmers the Duluth-based company has recruited to enhance
its digital system, called Explorer 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific-Atlanta won't sell ICTV's services but instead will
make sure ICTV's games work through Explorer 2000. The company is
betting that services such as interactive gaming will make Explorer
2000 more attractive to cable TV operators trying to reach new
subscribers with new digital services.
</P>
<P>
   Cable TV providers are looking for offerings that will tempt
subscribers to sign up for the more expensive digital packages
they're now offering. Typically, digital packages start at about
$10 a month, on top of what subscribers already pay for cable TV.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Scientific-Atlanta hopes that ICTV's services
will help cable TV operators with Explorer 2000 sell their new
digital packages to families with children.
</P>
<P>
   The company has licensing deals with computer game giants such
as Acclaim, which makes titles for Nintendo, Sega and Sony
including the sports series NFL Quarterback Club and NBA Jam.
</P>
<P>
   ``ICTV will offer cable subscribers the ability to experience
full-fledged gaming at incredible cable speeds,'' says Michael P.
Harney, Scientific-Atlanta's corporate vice president and general
manager of its digital subscriber networks unit.
</P>
<P>
   ICTV, based in Silicon Valley, makes applications that include
Internet access, e-mail, a large assortment of CD-ROM games, local
community information, educational content, and transaction
processing for home shopping and banking, games and other software
that can be used via the new digital networks. Among cable
operators building these networks are Atlanta-based Cox
Communications, MediaOne and Comcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our suite of applications will feature high-resolution video,
complete with 3-D graphics and stereo sound effects,'' said ICTV
President Wes Hoffman. ``Because Scientific-Atlanta has developed a
truly interactive network, based on Internet protocol standards,
we're able to bring a virtual arcade into people's homes.''
</P>
<P>
   ICTV's service works through a television connected to a digital
cable network. Users play games against other players with a
wireless keyboard and mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific-Atlanta shares closed up 37 1/2 cents at $53.37 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT SCIENTIFIC-ATLANTA
</P>
<P>
   Headquarters: Duluth
</P>
<P>
   Business: Provides hardware and software systems to the cable
television industry
</P>
<P>
   President/CEO: James MacDonald
</P>
<P>
   Employees: 6,200
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
