<HEADER>
A2241 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LAD     09-22 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OLD NFL ACQUAINTANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As I walked through the Bellagio Hotel in Las Vegas last Friday
afternoon, I spotted a person walking toward me who looked vaguely
familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, we made eye contact and I felt a chill knife through
me, as old football memories suddenly flooded across my mental
screen.
</P>
<P>
   This couldn't be the heathen who back in 1987 underpaid the best
running back in the NFL, Eric Dickerson, so scandalously that a
disgruntled Dickerson eventually forced the Los Angeles Rams to
trade him to the Indianapolis Colts, could it?
</P>
<P>
   This couldn't be the Benedict Arnold who was solely responsible
for cleverly orchestrating for Georgia Frontiere the Rams' shocking
move to St. Louis, could it?
</P>
<P>
   This couldn't be Frontiere's heartless financial hitman I once
dubbed as Ram Public Enemy No.1, could it?
</P>
<P>
   ``John Shaw!'' I said, as the president of the St. Louis Rams
moved past me lugging a suitcase.
</P>
<P>
   He stopped, turned around in acknowledgment and broke out in a
smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you like St. Louis?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't L.A.,'' he replied congenially. ``I miss L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether you like him, despise him or are indifferent to him, the
bottom line with John Shaw is that he's had a colossal impact on
Southern California athletics. The daily soap opera that has become
L.A.'s begging attempt to land an NFL expansion franchise can be
traced to the actions of Shaw, who persuaded Frontiere she could
make a ton of money by moving the Rams to a city willing to forfeit
its financial soul for an NFL team.
</P>
<P>
   When the good burghers of St. Louis decided to take such a tack,
Shaw took the Rams to Missouri after the 1994 season, leaving the
L.A. basin wide open for Al Davis and his Raiders. But Davis, in
what has to rank among the most scandalous miscalculations in
sporting history, implausibly decided to return the Raiders to
Oakland, leaving a pro football vacuum here that exists to this
day.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' decision made no sense at the time and still doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   It would be tantamount to a blackjack player, with a 10 card
showing and an ace in his hand, requesting a hit from the dealer,
or to the L.A. Dodgers deciding to trade perhaps the best hitter in
the history of their franchise and top gate attraction, Mike
Piazza, for Gary Sheffield and a bunch of nobodies.
</P>
<P>
   No one would commit such folly, except, of course, Al Davis, and
those rollicking minstrels who make up the Dodger hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'd have known Al were going to move, I'd have found a way
to keep the Rams in Southern California,'' said Shaw. ``I tell you,
we'd have never moved. I still find it hard to believe Al left.''
</P>
<P>
   I myself still find it difficult to comprehend, especially since
Davis was destined to have a stadium built for him at Hollywood
Park and especially since Davis suddenly had this massive area all
to himself.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Davis, ever the visionary, found it impossible to
resist an offer from the sterling politicians of Oakland a $34
million low-interest loan to be paid off whenever and renovation of
the Oakland Coliseum and now finds himself in a venue from which he
yearns to extricate himself.
</P>
<P>
   There is recurring speculation that it will be Al Davis' Raiders
who eventually will bring NFL football back to L.A.
</P>
<P>
   While Al Davis is keeping his fingers solemnly crossed in hopes
that happens, there is one severe legal barrier mitigating against
such a development that multi-year stadium lease the Raiders signed
with Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   A more realistic probability is for L.A. to wind up with an
expansion franchise, which the NFL commissioner, Paul Tagliabue,
wants and which the Coliseum advocates like Mark Ridley-Thomas and
Richard Riordan want even more passionately.
</P>
<P>
   All that has kept the NFL from giving L.A. a team is money, a
lot of it, like that cool $600 million franchise fee that no one
around here seems willing to cough up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be surprised if Marvin Davis decides to do it,'' said
Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Davis?
</P>
<P>
   He's the multi-billionaire whose name in recent years inevitably
winds up being linked to almost every high-profile business that's
been put up for sale in America. If Marvin Davis bought up
everything he was rumored to desire, he'd be worth more than Bill
Gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, and I'm sure Marvin Davis is interested in buying
Disney, Viacom, CBS, Chrysler and Microsoft,'' I said to Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seriously, I've heard from a couple of owners that he's
serious about wanting an expansion team for L.A. and that he would
be willing to put up his own money,'' said Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Davis willing to put up $600 million of his own money?
</P>
<P>
   That's about as likely to happen as Al Davis being named Man of
the Decade by the L.A. Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
