<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2244 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOODS-ILLNESS-COX     09-22 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOODS-ILLNESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Floods create health hazards for residentsd
 &HT;    By Jenna Hunt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE. N.C. _ Flooding from Hurricane Floyd and other
recent rains have created many health hazards, including
bacteria-related diseases, health officials say.
</P>
<P>
   People working in floodwaters, returning to flooded homes or
working with machinery increase the risk of cutting themselves and
will need a tetanus shot, health officials said.
</P>
<P>
   After the severe flooding in Grand Forks, N.D., in 1997, a large
majority of the evacuated city and all rescue workers received
tetanus shots, said Dan Shields, Grand Forks public health
director.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a serious health concern after the flood,'' Shields
said. ``Virtually everyone got a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   The other health hazards in the cleanup effort lasting months is
the growth of mold and spores, which causes respiratory conditions.
They can cause complications for people with allergies and asthma,
health officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a jillion of molds that are going to come up in
(eastern North Carolina),'' said Dr. John Meredith, Pitt County
Memorial Hospital disaster chief.
</P>
<P>
   Another health issue may arise after an infestation of
mosquitoes in the area in the next week, Meredith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a nuisance for people working outside,'' he
said. ``There can literally be a thick swarms of mosquitoes.''
</P>
<P>
   The state is preparing to spray the area for mosquitoes in the
next few weeks, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But the No. 1 cause of death after a flood is drowning as people
try to get back to their homes, said Dr. John Morrow, director of
the Pitt County Health Department. The second cause of death after
a flood is electrocution, he added.
</P>
<P>
   He said families need to be careful and make sure their
structures in the area are secure and safe before entering because
there could be live wires.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one needs to risk their lives to go back for material
things,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There is no need for any special immunizations, other than
tetanus, in the wake of Hurricane Floyd, state and local officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``National experience from multiple flood disasters demonstrates
that residents exposed to floodwater are not at a greater risk for
hepatitis A or typhoid fever,'' said State Health Director Dennis
McBride. ``We want to lay this matter to rest. There is no need for
any special immunizations as a result of the severe flooding we've
experienced down east.''
</P>
<P>
   Typhoid fever is a life-threatening illness caused by the
bacterium Salmonella Typhi. In the U.S., about 400 cases occur each
year, and about 70 percent of these are acquired while traveling
internationally, according to the Centers for Disease Control. You
can get the disease if the bacteria gets into the water used for
drinking or washing food.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, this disease has not been associated with floods,''
Shields said. He said his city didn't have any outbreaks in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Typhoid fever is more common in areas around the world with less
sanitation or contaminated sewer systems. Symptoms of the disease
include fever, chills, fatigue, cough, headache, sore throat and
diarrhea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more likely that you won't get diarrhea,'' said Dr.
Christopher Ohl, an associate professor of medicine and infectious
disease with the East Carolina University School of Medicine. ``We
are not anticipating any outbreaks.''
</P>
<P>
   The county rescue workers, police, sheriff's deputies and
Greenville Utility employees working in floodwaters received
tetanus shots the last few days as a precaution, said Rick Fisher,
Pitt County Sheriff Department chief of community patrol.
</P>
<P>
   In Grand Forks, about 650 people reported to the local health
department for shots as the cleanup started, Shields said. He said
it is better to be safe and cautious than wait and experience the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Sahni said the emergency room has treated minor flood injuries
that will increase as the water recedes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not experiencing an increase in skin diseases or rashes
from the flood,'' he said. He said they have had rescue workers and
local residents with fire ant bites and minor snake bites.
</P>
<P>
   The Pitt County Health Department will be giving tetanus shots
to the public today and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Mosquitoes
</P>
<P>
   The large amount of floodwater remaining will lead to an
increase in the already rampant mosquito populations. Mosquitoes
are most active at sunrise and sunset and will be pests. The CDC
says the majority of mosquitoes do not carry communicable diseases
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   One health concern officials is the spread of mosquito-related
diseases, including encephalitis, Shields said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be our only concern for the southeast area,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials recommend wearing long sleeves and insect
repellent containing DEET. Also, residents should drain all
standing water in containers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been incidents in other floods of up to 20
mosquitoes landing on people in under one minute,'' said Ohl.
</P>
<P>
   Mold growths
</P>
<P>
   Mold can be harmful for adults, children and especially infants.
One mold called stachybotrys chartarum is especially harmful and
takes time to spread and grow.
</P>
<P>
   As it grows, it releases millions of spores into the air that
can attack the lungs, especially in young children and infants.
</P>
<P>
   Immediate cleaning with bleach can help prevent the spread of
all types of mold in homes that have been flooded, health officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   In Grand Forks, a city of 50,000, about 450 people experienced
respiratory problems related to mold, Shields said. He said young
children are more susceptible to lung problems related to mold
growths and should be kept away from flooded homes during cleanup
for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Clean, sanitize, and dry water-damaged materials as quickly as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   All flooded carpets, dry-wall, and some furniture needs to be
thrown away after returning home to prevent mold growths, health
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, do not move back into the flooded home until it is
properly cleaned and sanitized, Sahni said.
</P>
<P>
   Stachybotrys is a black slimy mold that only grows in
water-soaked cellulose materials (its food source) such as wood,
paper, ceiling tile and cotton products.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC has linked this mold to several cases of infant deaths
diagnosed as Sudden Infant Death Syndrome. Not all molds are as
deadly as stachybotrys, but many cause heath problems such as
headaches, dizziness, asthma, allergies, as well as other symptom,
said health officials.
</P>
<P>
   Mold needs three things to grow and produce spores: air, food
and water _ humidity doesn't count as a water source.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
