<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-USNOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUCH-AWAITED PAIRINGS DUE THURSDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Opening ceremonies for the Ryder Cup,
including the announcement of Friday morning's pairings, will be
held at 4:30 p.m. Thursday on the practice range at The Country
Club. Entertainment, highlighted by singer Glen Frey, will begin at
3:30. The ceremonies will feature a procession of national flags
carried by West Point cadets, the playing of anthems by members of
the Boston Pops, the introduction of the 12-man teams from the US
and Europe, speeches by the captains, and a flyover (at
approximately 5:15) by Navy F-14 Tomcats from Squadrons 32 and 213.
</P>
<P>
   Bleacher seating will be available to tickholders on a
first-come basis and the ceremonies will be shown on Jumbotrons on
the course and also televised live on The Golf Channel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First tough call
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   US captain Ben Crenshaw said his toughest decision will be to
sit four players for the first four groups of matches. ``I said
before I didn't think it was plausible or possible that 12 fellows
could be playing well at one time,'' said Crenshaw. ``We had a few
pairings today I wanted to see work together. The problem I have
right now is leaving four guys out the first day because I feel a
lot of guys are playing well.'' And the prospects of Tiger Woods
and David Duval in one pairing? ``It's certainly a possibility,''
said Crenshaw. ``For months and months, I've struggled with the
round. You take four or five of our best players and you can either
put them together or split them throughout the lineup. Those are
the things you wrestle with. It's very safe to say that both of
them are going to play a lot but, at this point, I don't think that
it's going to happen in the first match. I don't know if you're
going to see that pairing in the first round.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Love of the Cup
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even as the doctor was treating the pinched nerve in his neck,
Davis Love could think about nothing but playing in the Ryder Cup.
``I said, `I'm going to be ready for this Ryder Cup. If this is the
only thing I do the rest of the year, I'm going to play,' '' said
Love. ``I knew if I did what the doctor said, I would be ready. I
was going to actually give up going fishing to play in this Ryder
Cup and that's a big sacrifice. I think that helped me when I first
started hitting balls again. I'd been thinking every day, I'm going
to be ready for this Ryder Cup no matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   His recovery has been slow but Love is optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The pinched nerve) led to me kind of losing some feeling in
my fingers in my left hand and losing some strength,'' he said. ``I
was told I needed to take two to three weeks off to let it get
better. I started back hitting balls last Friday. I'd be lying if I
said I'm 100 percent, but I'm probably 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hitting the ball as good or better than I have all year.
As long as I don't do anything to reinjure it, I think I'm in very
good shape and I'm excited about the way I'm hitting it. I've never
really come back hitting the ball this good from a layoff. I was
having problems that were affecting my swing. Now they've gone away
and my swing's getting better. I may have have lost a little bit of
length with the driver, but maybe the length will come back a
little bit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Compiled by Joe Concannon and John Powers of the Globe staff.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
