A2253 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOODS-BUSINESSES-COX     09-22 0330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOODS-BUSINESSES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Greenville area restaurants, businesses reopen
 &HT;    By Stuart Savage
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Many businesses, including banks and
restaurants, were open in Greenville on Wednesday after Hurricane
Floyd caused interruptions due to the lack of electric power and a
lack of running water.
</P>
<P>
   The Pitt County Health Department's environmental health
division ordered restaurants to close Tuesday when the water
pressure in areas dropped.
</P>
<P>
   But Jack Weathersby, a supervisor with the county's
environmental health division, said Greenville area restaurants
were notified that they could reopen Wednesday, provided they had
water pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they get any pressure up, they can operate,'' Weathersby
said. ``As long as they have running water under pressure. And they
have to have pressure on the toilets or Portajohns.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to be cleaning pots, pans, dishes, you have to
have pressure and hot water. If you don't have that, you can't
sanitize food contact surfaces,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Weathersby said if the water is contaminated, restaurants can't
use it for cooking unless they boil it for five or six minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot of precautions, especially when the pressure is
out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Weathersby, the health department is using the
honor system with restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the pressure drops to a trickle, they have to shut down,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to restaurants, The Plaza mall and Carolina East
Mall, with the exception of Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co., were closed
Wednesday because of the lack of water and restroom facilities.
</P>
<P>
   But a visual survey of several areas indicated that many other
businesses were open.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses and banks that opened Wednesday included: Kmart,
Wal-Mart, Sam's Club, Target, Lowe's Home Improvement Warehouse,
Wachovia Bank and Bank of America.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
