<HEADER>
A2254 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-WEBRATE23-COX     09-22 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBRATE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ACNielsen to buy 10% of NetRatings
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ACNielsen, the world's top media research company,
will buy 10 percent of NetRatings for $12.5 million and form a
joint venture to measure Internet traffic around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   The new company will be called ACNielsen eRating.com and will
track Internet and Web usage from users in Europe, Asia, Latin
America, Africa and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen's international venture is aimed at helping close the
gap with New York and Atlanta-based Media Metrix, now widely
accepted as the industry standard for Web measurement. Nielsen and
NetRatings, which currently collaborate to provide Web tracking
services in the U.S., said they plan to spend $50 million over the
next two years to get the international version of
Nielsen/NetRatings service up and running. The goal of the new
company is to establish itself as the Web measurement company of
record outside the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   ACNielsen will own 80 percent of ACNielsen eRating.com, while
closely held Stamford, Conn.-based NetRatings will own 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Nielsen/NetRatings, which launched earlier this year
offers a comprehensive suite of measurement services for its
clients, they still run second to Media Metrix. Media Metrix, which
merged with Atlanta-based Relevant Knowledge in 1998 has been
watching Web traffic since 1996. Jupiter Communications analyst
Michele Flack says Nielsen/NetRatings' move into the international
arena is a smart move.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing a greater and greater interest in international
markets,'' she says. ``The Internet has been dominate in the U.S.,
but there has been a great increase in Australia, Europe, the
Pacific Rim and Latin America in terms of how fast people are
coming online.''
</P>
<P>
   Flack says if Nielsen/NetRatings can move quickly into overseas
markets and establish itself as the No. 1 Web measurement firm, it
could help their own battle with Media Metrix stateside.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is a new player in the Web measurement field,
Nielsen/NetRatings is off to a good start, providing clients with
near-overnight information on Web events such as tracking Web usage
for the four days Hurricane Floyd swept up the East Coast and
analyzing the Web buzz generated by the surprise summer movie hit
``The Blair Witch Project.'' Nielsen can also deliver advertising
information and reports on how much time users spend on a site,
which is becoming more and more important as commercial Web sites
compete not just for users but for their time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nielsen does some really cool things,'' Flack says.
``Especially it reports showing where your competitors are
advertising. They do deliver above and beyond what Media Metrix
delivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Media Metrix doesn't offer advertiser reports or the
near instant analysis of Web usage, it does offer the all-important
workplace sample which Nielsen maintains cannot be measured
accurately. Still, with more and more users logging on at work, the
need for some measurement standard in the workplace is as vital as
advertising information.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the typical follower dilemma,'' Flack says. ``When
something is the standard it's hard to come in and play catch up.
If Nielsen can get out there in the international market and become
the international standard, Media Metrix will have to catch up with
them. It will also help them in the national U.S. market as well.
Their measurement system may solidify their standard in the U.S.
and bolster it,'' Flack said. ``If people get used to
Nielsen/NetRatings for international ratings, they might not be so
wedded to Media Metrix in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
