r w BC-CHURCHSHOOTINGS-CHRIS     09-22 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTINGS-CHRISTIANS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCH SHOOTING SEEN AS LATEST IN WAVE OF HATE CRIMES AGAINST
CHRISTIANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The seven slain worshippers at Wedgwood Baptist
Church have become a rallying point for evangelical Christians who
view them as the latest victims in a wave of hate crimes against
churchgoers.
</P>
<P>
   A host of Christian conservative leaders have cited the Sept. 15
shootings as evidence of a climate of hatred against believers. The
Fort Worth incident was the third recent mass shooting targeting
youthful Christians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real hostility today, the real hate crimes, are against
people of faith,'' said the Rev. Jerry Falwell, a prominent
evangelist. ``I believe the worst is yet to come. There will be
other incidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics accused Falwell and his allies of trying to exploit the
slayings for political reasons. Peter Montgomery of People for the
American Way, a liberal organization, said talk of anti-Christian
hatred is a recurring theme among religious right activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is so far beyond reason when you look around this
country. Most Americans are Christians,'' Montgomery said. ``I
think they're trying, for political reasons, to equate criticism of
their political agenda with anti-Christian hatred.''
</P>
<P>
   The feeling that Christians are under attack is coupled with a
belief among some Christian conservatives that the Fort Worth
shootings have failed to provoke the kind of national outrage that
followed last year's killings of James Byrd in East Texas and
Matthew Shepard in Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, an African American, was dragged behind a pickup. Shepard,
a homosexual, was beaten and left tied to a fence in freezing
weather. In Fort Worth, gunman Larry Gene Ashbrook, killed seven
worshippers and wounded seven others before sitting down in a pew
and killing himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lesser crime to shoot up a church. The media doesn't
see the church and the gospel and all that it has stood for as
being valid,'' said the Rev. Lou Sheldon, chairman of the
Traditional Values Coalition, an organization that claims 43,000
member churches. ``To me, there's no question this was a hate crime
against righteousness.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the Christian right movement agreed that the Fort
Worth shootings qualify as a hate crime, but they disputed
assertions that the church deaths were quickly forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't buy the argument that there's less outrage than there
was in regard to Matthew's murder or James Byrd's murder,'' said
David Smith, a spokesman for the Human Rights Campaign Fund, the
nation's largest gay rights group. ``The country is shellshocked.''
</P>
<P>
   Although most news reports have characterized the Fort Worth
slayings as an isolated incident involving a troubled loner,
Falwell and other evangelical leaders see it in the context of
other shootings that claimed the lives of active Christians.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, a gunman killed three teenagers and wounded five other
participants in a prayer group at Heath High School in West
Paducah, Ky. Anti-Christian bias also seemed to have played a role
in the April shootings at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   In the most widely known incident, Cassie Bernall, a born-again
Christian, was shot after saying ``yes'' when one of the gunmen
asked her if she believed in God. Falwell said 11 of the 12
shooting victims at the school were evangelical Christians.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Knight of the conservative Family Research Council said
the Fort Worth shootings should erase any doubt that Christians
have become a prime target for hatred.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the straw that broke the camel's back in terms of a
recognition that there's a pattern of violence against
Christians,'' he said. ``What's going on is Christians are being
painted as bigots and haters and some people are taking it to heart
and attacking Christians as a result.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight also accused the media of downplaying the Fort Worth
shooting spree.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seems to be a smug satisfaction in some parts of the
media that, gee, the Christians are getting theirs,'' he said.
``The media have been almost silent as to the motive of the
crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Falwell said he is convinced that the Fort Worth case would have
attracted far more attention if the victims had been homosexual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had those seven students at Wedgwood Baptist Church been gay
or lesbian we wouldn't have been able to get a weather report on
any station. But because they were Christians, it was treated as no
big deal,'' he said, adding that the incident has become ``just a
blip'' in history.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth leaders disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth Mayor Kenneth Barr said on Wednesday that the
shooting was far more that a historical footnote to the people of
Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big deal here,'' Barr said. ``People in this
community are grieving about what happened here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, Mr. Falwell is entitled to his opinion, but I am
frankly not concerned about what \Rhe\S thinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr said that he doesn't know whether the shootings at Wedgwood
Baptist fit the standard definition of hate crime, but that that is
irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, what does it matter?'' Barr said. ``The point is that
good, religious people, who were making a difference in the
community, and living out their lives, are needlessly dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need to sit down and try to figure out what can be
done so hopefully this will not happen again, no matter who the
target is.''
</P>
<P>
   Most experts agree that the Fort Worth shootings meet the
definition of a hate crime because the assailant seemed to target
his victims for their religious beliefs. Under federal law, crimes
motivated by race, religion, national origin and ethnicity can be
considered hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The designation can trigger FBI involvement in the investigation
and tougher penalties in the event of a conviction. Both
possibilities are moot in the Fort Worth case since the shooter
killed himself.
</P>
<P>
   Ashbrook, who was reared in a devoutly Christian home, ripped
the pages from a Bible in his home before setting off on his
shooting spree. He denounced religion and ridiculed his victims for
their beliefs as he sprayed the church with gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all likelihood, this is a hate crime. The victims were
targeted because they were in a church and because they were
Christians,'' said Jack Levin, a hate crimes expert at Northeastern
University in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But becoming the victim of hate crimes has not altered the view
among Christian conservatives that the entire concept of hate
crimes is wrong. Evangelical leaders steadfastly oppose efforts in
Congress to expand crimes motivated by sexual orientation to the
list of possible hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole hate crime concept is wrongheaded,'' Knight said.
``I might feel it was particularly odious to attack a house of
worship, but in the eyes of the law, we should all be entitled to
equal protection.'' Staff writer Ginger D. Richardson contributed
to this report.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
