<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Technology hot again in investment advice
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Investment advice from the latest batch of business
publications has a decidedly high-tech ring.
</P>
<P>
   Smart Money (October) looks at the ``Internet stars of the
future,'' suggesting that the latest Internet sell-off is ``another
buying opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine says these Web stocks are worth considering:
Amazon.com, Ariba, eBay, Exodus, Inktomi, Red Hat Software and
Yahoo!.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg Personal Finance (October) also looks at tech stocks
and finds that Dell Computer ranks first in ``wealth creation'' by
generating the most value for shareholders. Others in the top five
are Yahoo!, Infoseek, Microsoft and America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Kiplinger's Personal Finance Magazine (October) takes a look at
real estate investment trusts and finds that, after taking a
beating, ``they're poised for a comeback.'' The REITs it recommends
are Apartment Investment and Management, Chelsea GCA, Equity Office
Properties, General Growth Properties and Spieker Properties.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual Funds (October) puts a microscope on mutual fund families
_ companies that offer a broad menu of mutual funds _ and concludes
that Fidelity, with almost $800 billion in assets, is the best.
Others include Janus, T. Rowe Price and Vanguard.
</P>
<P>
   A tiger by the tail
</P>
<P>
   Why can't everybody be happy in a booming economy in which
profits are soaring? Because of ``the prosperity gap,'' says
Business Week (Sept. 27). That's the gap between what workers make
in the ``new economy'' _ built on computers, software and
communications _ compared to wages in the ``old economy'' _ focused
on construction, education and transportation.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a happy situation and will get even worse the next time
the economy takes a dip, Business Week says. One result could be
the creation of new, fringe political parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as movements in continents produce earthquakes and
volcanoes, so will the growing prosperity gap create social
upheaval for years to come,'' says the magazine. ``We will be
riding this tiger for years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
