<HEADER>
A2267 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-FLA-SWEEPSTAKES-SUIT-     09-22 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-SWEEPSTAKES-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 FLORIDA ACCUSES   PUBLISHERS CLEARING HOUSE OF DECEPTIVE
PRACTICES 
</HEADLINE>
  (md) 
 By DOUGLAS FRANTZ    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Publishers Clearing House, one of the two largest
sweepstakes companies, was accused Wednesday in a civil suit filed
by Florida's attorney general of using deceptive practices to sell
magazines and other merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   The suit said that the company's mailings were designed to
entice people to make purchases by fooling them into thinking they
had won millions of dollars and that the company focused on older
people, who often misunderstand its sophisticated mass mailings.
</P>
<P>
   One technique singled out was the company's highly publicized
Prize Patrol, which delivers multimillion-dollar prizes to winners.
The suit said the company's request, in mailings, for specific
directions to customers' houses for the Prize Patrol gave hundreds
of thousands of people the illusion that they had won.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed in Pinellas County Circuit Court in Tampa, seeks
at least $40 million in restitution for customers and civil
penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Florida is the fifth state to sue Publishers Clearing House,
which is based in Port Washington, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher L. Irving, the company's director of consumer
affairs, said that its mailings were not deceptive, that they
stated clearly the odds of winning and that no purchase was
necessary to win. Irving also said that mailings said clearly that
the odds of the Prize Patrol coming to the letter recipient's house
were very long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers understand that a mailing from Publishers Clearing
House is an opportunity to enter a sweepstakes and that no purchase
is necessary,'' Irving said.
</P>
<P>
   The sweepstakes industry sells millions of dollars worth of
magazines and merchandise every year through mass mailings
containing attention-grabbing graphics and language designed to get
recipients to buy magazines and other merchandise and enter a
sweepstakes contest. In smaller print, the mailings specify that no
purchase is necessary to enter the contest and that the odds of
winning are very long.
</P>
<P>
   But the contents of those mailings have been challenged as
misleading and deceptive on several fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the U.S. Senate unanimously passed legislation that
would impose new restrictions on sweepstakes companies as well as
stiffer penalties for fraudulent mailings. The legislation calls
for printing clearly and conspicuously that winning is not
automatic and that buying merchandise does not improve the very
long odds of winning. Backers of the legislation hope the House
will also approve the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Several state attorneys general have used consumer-protection
laws to go after the sweepstakes business. Last May, Florida and
three other states settled similar complaints with American Family
Publishers, the other leading sweepstakes company. As part of that
settlement, American Family Publishers paid $4 million and promised
to stop telling recipients of its mailings that they are winners
unless it is true.
</P>
<P>
   The suit against Publishers Clearing House was filed after a
breakdown in negotiations between the office of Attorney General
Robert Butterworth of Florida and lawyers for the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Months of negotiations with Publishers Clearing House have
failed to produce any meaningful changes to the deceptive
solicitations mailed out by the company,'' Butterworth said.
</P>
<P>
   Irving said an agreement with Florida had been within reach. He
also said that Publishers Clearing House had voluntarily taken
steps to remove high-volume customers from its mailing list and
added information to its mailings emphasizing that recipients had
not yet won.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for the elderly say an older person can often spend
thousands of dollars buying unneeded magazines and other
merchandise in order to enter sweepstakes and similar contests
because they are fooled into thinking they are going to win or have
won.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Wright, who lives in Lauderhill, Fla., said his
great-aunt had squandered her life savings of $87,000 over the last
three years buying unnecessary merchandise from Publishers Clearing
House and entering Canadian lotteries pushed by telemarketers.
</P>
<P>
   ``She still says that she's on the next step to be the winner,''
Wright said. ``It's so sad because she would rather send in checks
than pay for her medication.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
