<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2273 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-CD-9INCHNAILS-TEX     09-22 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CD-9INCHNAILS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TORTURED SOUL SINGS ITS LAMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The telling moment of Trent Reznor's life of pain and music, and
his intertwining of the two, unfolded three years ago in Dallas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone I know, goes away, in the end,'' he murmured from the
stage at Fair Park Coliseum during the cryptic ``Hurt,'' while
portraits of a rotting animal carcass flashed across a screen and
lights turned from hopeful white to sea-of-blood red.
</P>
<P>
   It was a desperate and beautiful moment, an image of an
unimaginably tortured person trapped inside a pretty melody.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1989, Reznor _ the one-man-band behind industrial
juggernaut Nine Inch Nails _ has been turning his
perhaps-autobiographical tales of splintered relationships, fury,
loneliness, alienation and disappointment into art of the highest
form: It's believable.
</P>
<P>
   That's why so many young fans fell in love with NIN, because
Reznor was living proof that they're not the only ones trying to
survive one trauma after another. NIN definitely attracted its
share of bandwagon-jumpers. But there's a circle of fans that can
truly relate to Reznor, who once said one of the greatest things a
fan ever said to him was, ``Your music makes me feel like I'm not
alone.''
</P>
<P>
   On ``The Fragile,'' NIN's first effort in five years and
first-ever double CD, Reznor is alone again, questioning, doubting,
distrusting everyone and everything. ``Everything that swore it
wouldn't change is different now,'' he bellows on the first track,
the raging Somewhat Damaged. ``I'm too ------ up to care anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the two discs, Reznor continually second-guesses _
himself, those close to him, those he wants close to him, those who
want to get away from him. It's not all self-pity, though: The
album's title track is about saving someone from ending up like
him. ``I won't let you fall apart,'' Reznor sings.
</P>
<P>
   Although the musical landscape has considerably changed since
NIN's first disc, 1989's ``Pretty Hate Machine,'' Reznor has
changed little. He still saturates his songs equally with gritty
noise (distorted vocals, ferocious guitars, hammering drums) and
ambient sound waves. He's one of the few artists who realize that
the rage of noise can be just as effective as the subtleties of
silence _ and he's a master at manipulating both.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike far too many other two-CD collections, this one has
little filler material. The songs are spliced like chapters in a
book, each one segueing into the other, elegantly shifting from
stormy to quiet. But the lyrics remain Reznor's strong point.
``Tried to save myself,'' he laments on ``Into the Void,'' ``but
myself keeps slipping away.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 2014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
