<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-CAROLINA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CITY'S BATTLE TO KEEP ELECTRICITY RUNNING AND WATER FLOWING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT4 and NYT5 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ For all its saturated misery, this city has a
group of sweaty and sleepless heroes: the civil engineers and
laborers, even prison inmates, who worked frantically for the last
week on precarious schemes to keep electricity and tap water
flowing through the greatest flood in state history.
</P>
<P>
   If the desperate methods concocted by Malcolm A. Green and his
crew at Greenville Utilities had failed _ and they came within 2
inches of calamity _ there probably would have been no electricity
for the city's 55,000 residents for a long time to come. The city's
water supply _ now barely returning to normal after being out for
most of Tuesday _ would have been out for weeks. Greenville would
have been unlivable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still can't believe how close we came to disaster,'' said
Green, the general manager of the utility, as an aide brought in an
armful of crayoned thank-you notes from schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   The enormous rush of water that Hurricane Floyd produced
throughout eastern North Carolina, which has now killed 41 people
and made 6,000 homeless, has created havoc with the most
fundamental utilities of modern life. Repair crews are accustomed
to fixing power lines blown down by high winds, but are they
virtually helpless when entire substations and waterworks become
submerged. Some pumping and power stations have been ruined by the
water and will have to be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 10,000 people around the state have been without power
for most of a week. One lineman has already died, and another was
injured trying to restore power in the southern part of the state.
More than 40,000 customers in at least five counties either have no
water or must boil their tap water because of contamination. In
Duplin County, southwest of here, the flood has damaged
distribution pipes in more than 50 places. County officials say it
could be days or weeks before normal service is restored, because
crews cannot even get close to all the breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Greenville has been one of the hardest-hit cities in the state,
because the Tar River runs directly through the middle of town. The
northern and southern sections of the city are cut from each other,
and 3,000 city residents have been forced from their homes to
shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Because it uses the Tar River as its source for drinking water,
the city's water plant is located near it, and the power substation
is similarly near the middle of town for ease in transmission. Both
facilities are on 100-year flood plains, high enough to withstand
floods so severe that they would occur only once a century. But
with the current flood considered to be a 500-year flood, higher
than any ever recorded, the utilities' locations near the Tar meant
that they were among the first casualties.
</P>
<P>
   All of the city's electrical power flows through the main
substation, a maze of transformers and wires. When the water began
pouring in on Saturday, Green knew he could not save the circuit
breakers that act as safety devices in case of overloads. But with
power still in the lines, he devised a plan to use a circuit
breaker outside the station, which posed significant risks to the
city's transmission system.
</P>
<P>
   The scheme would only work, however, if the water stayed
underneath the main cables, which carry 230,000 volts. The utility
stationed a man in a boat at the station to call in with constant
reports on the water level. If it approached the wires, Green would
order all power to the city cut off. If it touched the wires, it
would create a short circuit and arcing that could destroy the
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole city was on pins and needles all weekend,'' said
Green, following along on radio and television as the utility
waited to see whether the system would hold together. The water
edged up to within 2 inches of a blackout. Wildlife officials had
to keep sightseers from the area, worried that their boats and jet
skis could create a wave that would touch the wires. An oil slick
moving downstream created fears of a conflagration, but the utility
quickly created a floating boom to move it away.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, as if held together by chewing gum, the electrical
system has worked for five days. But meanwhile, the utility's water
plant was also becoming submerged.
</P>
<P>
   The utility mobilized a small army of city workers and prisoners
in detention centers to begin filling 25,000 sandbags, which were
themselves an ordeal to find and fly in by military helicopters.
The bags formed a 6-foot wall around the most crucial areas of the
water plant, and though the flood crept inside, the pumps never
fully stopped.
</P>
<P>
   But the filters that keep sediment out of the drinking water
quickly became clogged, because the high water outside prevented
them from being flushed and drained. By Tuesday, the water was
moving so slowly through the filters that most of the town in
effect had no water pressure, and there were fears that the whole
city would be unable to bathe. Two shelters housing 3,000 people
were evacuated, restaurants and businesses closed, and many
residents prepared to move out.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday morning, however, the engineers at the utility had
devised yet another jerry-built system to clean the filters with a
maze of plastic pipes. Extra-chlorinated water began flowing, first
into homes in low-lying areas, and then up the incline to the
higher areas south of town. Green himself had his first shower in
several days on Wednesday, all the while worrying that the water
pressure was too low to fight fires.
</P>
<P>
   But even though the utility pulls its water from the lower part
of the riverbed, which is generally free of most of the
contaminants floating on top, the water is not considered safe to
drink. Residents are required to boil their tap water before
drinking it, and thousands lined up for free gallons of bottled
water being distributed by McDonald's and other companies at points
around the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just got a trickle of water, and I'm old enough not to
mind heating it up on the stove to take a bath,'' said Sylvia
Corey, who lives in the Westhaven neighborhood on the south side.
``But I've been watching Green on TV, and I know we are lucky to
have what we've got.''
</P>
</TEXT>
