<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dell launches ads to push PCs targeted at consumers
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Until recently, Dell Computer Corp. considered
most consumers to be more trouble than they were worth.
</P>
<P>
   The company was content to focus on large accounts in business
and government that ordered PCs by the hundreds or thousands, and
didn't require a lot of costly technical help.
</P>
<P>
   But changes in Dell's approach to customer support and
burgeoning consumer interest in the Internet have helped turn
around the company's view of that market.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Dell announced its broadest effort to capture
consumer business by backing what it calls ``the most
consumer-friendly PCs'' with a major U.S. advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The products, which include a PC ``juke box'' system that allows
users to create CDs of their favorite music, and portables in gray
or blue, will be available beginning this weekend, when Dell's
advertising campaign begins.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Mountain, general manager of Dell's consumer business,
said its so-called Dell4Me program marks a shift to emphasizing
what technology offers rather than merely touting products.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we wanted to do is to be much more explicit about letting
consumers see how they're going to use technology in such a way
that brings benefit to them,'' Mountain said during a press
conference in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Dell said it is the first major computer maker to offer PCs with
cable modems, a feature that will be available in limited areas
where Excite(at)Home offers cable access to the Internet. In
addition, Dell will sign customers up for the high-speed Internet
service. Dell also said a new Inspiron model will be available in
grey and blue, taking a lesson from Apple Computer Inc.'s success
with multicolored iMacs.
</P>
<P>
   Dell's courtship of consumers in recent months has included
Internet access through DellNet, while DellAuction.com, lets
customers buy and sell used and refurbished Dell PCs. These
features make the consumer business more attractive because
Internet access brings Dell monthly revenue, while the auction and
Gigabuys.com, Dell's online PC product store, expand sales
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Dell's overriding goal is to be the source of all its customers'
computing needs and to build customer loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   While Dell's consumer sales doubled in the past year, they still
account for only 15 percent of revenue. Dell ranks fourth in the
consumer business, according to research group Ziff Davis
Infobeads.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Kay, an analyst with the Boston-area research firm
International Data Corp., said research in Japan shows Dell is
perceived as efficient but impersonal _ a perception that may be
tough to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``To deal with consumers, they have to slow down and be sort of
friendly,'' said Kay.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
