<HEADLINE>
FANS IGNORE WEATHER FOR A VIEW OF THE STARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Weather permitting or not, fans follow Tiger
Woods, Phil Mickelson, Sergio Garcia, and the rest of the Ryder Cup
competitors in hearty numbers. Intermittent rain may have
inconvenienced some spectators Wednesday, but it did not keep them
from finding their favorite players, especially Woods. The most
popular player on the US team again drew a large gallery. Lots of
large golf umbrellas simply added to the challenge of getting a
good view.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been bothered so far, but I wouldn't want to be
behind us,'' said John Gunderson of Weston, who huddled under an
umbrella with his wife Susan. ``It would be helpful to know the
course, to know the best spots to go from one Tiger watching spot
to the next. It's impressive, having not been to an event like this
before, how the crowd seems to move with their favorite players.''
</P>
<P>
   The only concession made to the rain was the pace at which
Woods's gallery moved. In order to get an unobstructed view, some
spectators skipped every other hole. For many, the conditions
required better preparation. The Gundersons brought rain suits, two
umbrellas, and lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to anticipate (problems that come with bad
weather),'' said Greg Pratt of Bedford, N.H. ``It's part of the
game. I've played in worse than this. I'm a serious golfaholic. It
makes it a little more difficult to get around, but you prep for
it. If anything, it keeps crowds down and makes it a little easier
to get around.''
</P>
<P>
   The PGA estimated Tuesday's crowd at 25,000-30,000. Wednesday,
it was 20,000-23,000 out of a possible 30,000.
</P>
<P>
   For those fans who had only one day to enjoy the event, the
light rains were considered bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   `It figures. This is the only day I'm going,'' said Steven
Ritucci of Walpole. ``But I was still going to come. I wouldn't let
the weather stop me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   False alarm
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Around 2 p.m., police and fire officials feared a blue backpack
might contain a bomb. The worrisome piece of luggage was left under
a tree between the 16th tee and a broadcast booth. After a dog was
brought in to sniff the backpack, police determined it did not
contain dangerous materials. Within 20 minutes the bag was returned
to its owner. ``Obviously, we have a plan for everything,'' said
Brookline police chief Daniel O'Leary. ``The Marshall made the call
and everybody responded. This is a major event. We have lots of
contigency plans. We're looking for a very happy and safe event.''
A group of Brookline firemen and policemen, including
representatives from the bomb squad, blocked off the area for 15
minutes. Spectators were then allowed to pass through the area
again, unaware of the incident . . . Despite the rain, celebrities
still found their way to The Country Club. Former Boston University
hockey player Travis Roy, who was paralyzed in his first collegiate
game, was spotted on the 16th hole. And LPGA Hall of Famer Pat
Bradley of Westford took in the practice round.
</P>
</TEXT>
