<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: DOES DEAL WITH AUTOWORKERS HAVE SOMETHING FOR ALMOST
EVERYONE?
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mich.)  (rk) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the surface, the tentative agreement that the autoworkers'
union reached with DaimlerChrysler last week was just the type of
extravagant contract that President John F. Kennedy had once warned
the United Auto Workers against.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1962 speech to a UAW convention, Kennedy called for
``responsible unionism'' and cautioned the union that it could set
off an inflationary spiral if it used its bargaining muscle to
extract wage increases that far outpaced inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The four-year agreement reached last week seems to do just that,
awarding some of the best raises obtained in a union contract in
years: annual wage increases of 3 percent on top of cost-of-living
adjustments that nearly match inflation. Those impressive raises,
union officials say, are likely to ensure ratification when
DaimlerChrysler workers vote on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The contract is expected to serve as a model for the union's
ongoing negotiations with General Motors and Ford Motor, meaning a
total of 400,000 autoworkers are likely to receive such inviting
raises. So are thousands of additional Canadian autoworkers, whose
union used the DaimlerChrysler agreement as the basis for an accord
with Ford on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the unusual generosity of the DaimlerChrysler pact,
however, hardly any economists, auto executives or industry experts
are warning of disaster on the inflation front or to the industry's
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The DaimlerChrysler agreement has not set off inflation alarm
bells the way it might have in the Kennedy era partly because a
contract reached with a Big Three automaker _ or with one of the
big steelmakers that Kennedy used to jawbone _ no longer sets a
lockstep nationwide pattern. In the past, coal, chemicals, rubber
and other industries would play follow the leader and often award
the same percentage raises the Big Three granted.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, however, unions in most industries are far weaker than
in the 1960s _ they represent 13.9 percent of the work force, down
from more than 30 percent in the 1960s. This makes it harder for
unions with upcoming negotiations, like Lockheed's machinists or
Southwest Airlines' ramp operators, to match the gains made by the
UAW, which still maintains a vise-like grip on the auto industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the autoworkers negotiate a major agreement, it doesn't
carry over like in the '50s and '60s because other unions are
getting creamed by membership losses, growth in the nonunion sector
and the fear they'll lose their jobs to permanent replacement
workers if they strike,'' said Harry Katz, a Cornell University
professor of industrial relations.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor allaying fears of an inflationary spiral is that
corporations, facing intense competitive pressures from
globalization, have gotten far tougher about agreeing to wage
increases pushed by unions. Corporate America has changed its ways
since the 1950s and 1960s, when many companies rolled over in the
face of union wage demands, knowing they could always pass on added
costs to the consumer. Back then, companies hardly had to worry
about competition from imports, and most Americans had not yet
heard of Hondas or Toyotas.
</P>
<P>
   While it will be difficult for other unions to match the UAW's
percentage wage increases, labor leaders are sure to point to the
autoworkers' impressive gains to pressure employers to be more
generous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very good agreement,'' said Harley S. Shaiken, a
professor of industrial relations at the University of California
at Berkeley. ``It will become a benchmark for other contracts, but
that doesn't mean it will be replicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the old contract, autoworkers typically earned between
$50,000 and $80,000 each year, depending on how much overtime they
worked.
</P>
<P>
   In labor circles, the agreement not only will become a powerful
symbol of a union delivering for its members, but also could boost
union members' morale and serve as a beacon that union organizers
point to during unionization drives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unions were largely written off after their debacles of the
1980s, but this contract shows that unions can still have real
clout,'' Shaiken said. ``This shows that in its core industry, the
U.A.W. still packs a wallop.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The union has not secured such annual across-the-board increases
from the Big Three in two decades. Indeed, in obtaining ``inflation
plus 3 percent,'' the union obtained a formula common in the '50s
and '60s and first negotiated in 1948 by Walter Reuther, the
legendary autoworkers' leader, when the union's power was at its
pinnacle.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, during Detroit's depressed 1980s, the union often
accepted pay freezes, and earlier this decade, the pattern in the
UAW's three-year contracts was a lump-sum payment but no raise in
the first year, and an annual increase in the second and third
years.
</P>
<P>
   It shouldn't be surprising that last week's agreement is the
UAW's best in years because the Big Three's sales and profits are
booming and because Detroit, with its high-flying sport utility
vehicles, has Japan's automakers on the defensive. What is more,
the UAW's hand was strengthened, knowing the last thing Detroit
wanted was a strike when so many auto plants were unable to keep up
with demand.
</P>
<P>
   All this is a sharp contrast to the 1980s when the union's
bargaining clout was weakened by high unemployment and anemic
industry profits. It was a time when Japan's automakers acted like
Pac-Man characters, devouring the Big Three's market share. In
addition, UAW negotiators could not be deaf to all the experts who
declared that Detroit's labor costs and productivity levels were
out of line with Japan's.
</P>
<P>
   Although it could be short-lived, one factor that may help the
Big Three absorb the wage increases is the recent surge in the
Japanese yen, which makes Japanese goods more expensive. In
addition, Japanese auto assembly plants in the United States are
expected to match the DaimlerChrysler wage provisions as part of
their strategy to keep the UAW out, although their benefits remain
inferior to the UAW's.
</P>
<P>
   All this said, there is another reason that last week's
agreement has not caused Detroit to panic about soaring costs or
plummeting competitiveness: the accord gives DaimlerChrysler
considerable leeway to increase its productivity by reducing its
work force through attrition. The UAW's 1996 contracts placed harsh
restrictions on the Big Three's ability to cut employment at many
factories by more than 5 percent, except in the case of recession.
</P>
<P>
   By some measures, the new agreement gives DaimlerChrysler more
latitude to trim its work force through attrition, although many
details have not yet been fully explained by the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   The pact also sweetens pensions to such a degree that it will
inevitably encourage many retirements. To allay the union's fears
about employment falling too steeply, the contract does require the
company to hire new workers _ sometimes one for every three
retirees, sometimes one for every two, sometimes one for one _
depending on how much employment falls at certain plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the opportunities this agreement creates for
DaimlerChrysler to get leaner, the corporation will not only be
able to absorb the cost of these wage increases, but will be able
to increase productivity and profitability,'' said Daniel Hoffman,
a former autoworker who is a professor of labor relations at
Michigan State University. ``The consumer shouldn't see any type of
price increase because this contract allows the corporation to save
so much money by allowing it to reduce its work force by
attrition.''
</P>
<P>
   Some industry analysts hail the contract as a win-win agreement
that other industries might seek to emulate. The reason: it allows
the autoworkers to share the fruits of productivity (in the form of
hefty wage increases) while letting automakers slim down further to
increase productivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is an agreement that will make the companies
more, not less, competitive,'' Shaiken said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
