<SLUG> BC-XEROX-TEKTRONIX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
XEROX TO BUY TEKTRONIX INC.'S COLOR PRINTING BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore., N.Y.)  (md) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Xerox Corp &UR; . &LR;  said Wednesday that it would buy Tektronix Inc.'s
color printing business for $950 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the combined business will have about $6 billion in
sales. They expect it to have about a 30 percent share of the
fast-growing networked color printer market, well below the 70
percent that Hewlett-Packard Co &UR; . &LR;  claims as its share, but a big
step up from Xerox's 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition doubles Xerox's distribution network, to 16,000
dealers across the globe. It lets Xerox capitalize on Tektronix's
solid-ink technology, a low-cost printing method that melts
crayon-consistency ink into droplets that resolidify on paper. And,
perhaps most important, it gives Xerox, which has a strong presence
in the low and high end of the color printer market, its first
major midprice products, which sell for $4,000 or so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a blockbuster, but it's a good deal in terms of
product, technology and marketing fit,'' said Peter J. Enderlin,
who follows Xerox for First Albany Corp &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Tektronix, which is best known for testing and measurement
devices, lacks brand recognition outside of engineering circles.
Xerox and Tektronix had been discussing a deal that would let Xerox
sell Tektronix printers under the Xerox brand name. The idea for
the acquisition was born in June, when Tektronix disclosed plans to
spin off its $750 million printing business to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking to invest half a billion to develop this
market anyway, so when the opportunity to buy Tektronix came up, we
jumped all over it,'' G. Richard Thoman, Xerox's chief executive,
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Tektronix printer business, which is in Wilsonville, Ore.,
will become the headquarters of Xerox's office printing business,
and will be run by Gerald K. Perkel, a Tektronix executive. ``We
can now deploy the money we were spending to build a brand name
into developing products that offer customers more alternatives to
H. P.,'' Perkel said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Thoman told analysts that the combination would yield
$40 million in unspecified saving, he said in an interview that it
would not result in significant job losses at Xerox's current color
printer headquarters in Webster, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal is about growth, not consolidation,'' Thoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Thoman said the deal would not dilute earnings and would add to
them in 2001. He chose the all-cash route, he said, because he
thought Xerox's stock, which had sunk well below the 52-week high
of nearly $64 that it hit in May, was undervalued, and because tax
benefits of stock deals are not applicable unless an entire company
is acquired.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry J. Meyer, the Tektronix chairman, said he would distribute
the proceeds of the sale _ probably around $600 million after
taxes, closing costs and debt payments _ to Tektronix shareholders,
either through dividends or a share buyback.
</P>
<P>
   Tektronix shareholders seemed more enthusiastic than Xerox's.
Xerox's shares closed at $42.5625, up 56.25 cents. Tektronix shares
closed at $36.1875, up $1.3125.
</P>
<P>
   Other printer companies do not seem particularly worried. ``This
is just a consolidation of competitors that we've fared well
against in the past, and what Xerox has really bought is just a new
channel of distribution,'' Nolan M. Sundrud, a Hewlett-Packard
spokesman, said.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Lexmark International Inc., a smaller but
fast-growing printer maker, seemed similarly unfazed. ``This deal
won't have any impact on our strategic direction, particularly
since Hewlett-Packard is still our biggest competitor,'' Roger
Rydell, a Lexmark spokesman, said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, printer industry experts expect the deal to be beneficial
to customers. ``Coupling Tektronix's color savvy with Xerox's name
and marketing programs will yield increased competition that will
drive everyone's product quality up and prices down,'' said Jay
Ingalls, a research director at Gartner Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
