<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-LAWSUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT HITS TOBACCO INDUSTRY WITH LAWSUIT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Justice Department filed a multibillion-dollar
lawsuit against the tobacco industry Wednesday, claiming that
cigarette makers have waged a 46-year ``public campaign of deceit''
to hide the lethal hazards of smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno, who called a news conference to
announce the lawsuit, said the federal government spends $20
billion annually on smoking-related diseases that could have been
avoided if industry leaders had been honest about what they knew
about their product's dangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have conducted themselves without regard to the truth,
without regard to the law,'' Reno said. ``They placed profits above
the public health.''
</P>
<P>
   But Greg Little, a lawyer for tobacco giant Philip Morris Inc.,
assailed the lawsuit as ``baseless.'' He vowed his company will not
settle the case but instead will go to trial and rebuff the
government's allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Little also accused President Clinton of being more interested
in winning political points than with upholding the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   ``This blatantly political lawsuit ... is nothing more than the
height of hypocrisy,'' Little said. ``... In fact, the government
has profited from the sale of cigarettes for decades through
collection of excise (sales) taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who said in January that the government would sue the
industry by the end of the year, hailed the department's lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Justice Department is taking the right course of action,''
Clinton said. ``It is time for America's taxpayers to have their
day in court.''
</P>
<P>
   In its lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court in Washington, the
Justice Department seeks to recover more than $100 billion in
health-care compensation from the tobacco industry and for what the
government calls the industry's ill-gotten gains from lying about
smoking's dangers.
</P>
<P>
   Government lawyers claim the industry's deceit began Dec. 15,
1953, when the heads of the major tobacco companies met in New York
City and agreed to mount a long-term public-relations campaign to
discount emerging studies linking cigarettes to lung disease.
</P>
<P>
   That ``intentional, coordinated campaign of fraud and deceit''
continues today, Reno said. ``The truth poses a mortal threat to
their business.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department said, without further explanation, that
it has no pending criminal investigations of the tobacco industry.
The agency also said the litigation is not intended to drive the
industry or any of its members into bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Spurring the Justice Department's filing of the lawsuit was the
success Texas and other states have recently had in securing
out-of-court settlements totaling $246 billion with the tobacco
industry. But the federal government's litigation also follows a
string of defeats for the Clinton administration in its effort to
recover compensation for smoking related health-care costs.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the states that have settled with the industry have
rejected Clinton's request that they pay 25 percent of the
recovered money to the federal government. Texas Republican Sen.
Kay Bailey Hutchison and state Attorney General John Cornyn have
told Clinton that the federal government is entitled to none of the
$17.6 billion the state recovered from tobacco companies after
lengthy and expensive negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, tobacco-industry leaders last year withdrew support
for a proposed $368.5 billion nationwide settlement of cigarette
litigation. The companies backed away after the Senate began
considering legislation that would cost the industry $516 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Little said his industry willingly entered into the settlements
with the states as part of a good-faith effort to resolve an honest
dispute between the states and the companies regarding health-care
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the federal government, unlike the states, has not
tried to broker an agreement with the industry. Instead, the
Clinton administration has chosen litigation that has ``no basis in
fact, no basis in law,'' Little added.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a sad day for our Justice Department and a sad day for
our legal system,'' Little said.
</P>
<P>
   In its federal lawsuit, the Justice Department did not
specifically state how much money it hoped to recover from the
industry but said that it expects the figure to run into the
``billions of dollars.'' The court would have to calculate the
precise figure based on evidence presented at trial, said David
Ogden, acting assistant attorney general for the civil division.
</P>
<P>
   Ogden also refuted Little's argument that the government
possessed adequate information about smoking's dangers, saying that
the industry had ``superior knowledge'' of the addictive quality
and harsh consequences of cigarettes. With ``deliberate
falsehoods,'' the industry encouraged people to keep smoking and
kept the full truth from the public, Ogden asserted.
</P>
<P>
   The government claims in its lawsuit that tobacco-industry
leaders violated the major federal anti-racketeering law. They
conspired in a ``widespread scheme to frustrate public scrutiny by
making false and deceptive statements'' of what they knew to be the
dangers of cigarettes, the suit states.
</P>
<P>
   The companies also concealed documents and internal research
that showed smoking to be even more hazardous than the government
and consumers suspected, the lawsuit alleges.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to recovering money, the Justice Department is
asking the federal court to order the industry to disclose all its
research on smoking's hazards and to fund advertising campaigns
aimed at discouraging people, particularly teenagers, from smoking.
</P>
<P>
   The government says 3,000 teen-agers per day take up the habit
of smoking and that 1,000 of them will eventually suffer from a
smoking-related illness, such as lung cancer, emphysema, heart
attacks and strokes.
</P>
<P>
   But Little, of Philip Morris, said the government has a strong
burden of proof to overcome in its lawsuit. Federal lawyers will
have to show that the tobacco industry misled the government about
the dangers of smoking or prove that individual cigarette consumers
were unaware of the hazards, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Little added it will be difficult for the government to argue it
was misled, in light of its massive advertising campaign during the
past 35 years to warn the public of the health risks of smoking.
Also, it would be a logistical and expensive burden for the
government to have the cigarette consumers come to court and
testify that they were deceived by the tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will attack the legal sufficiency of the complaint
immediately and we believe it should be dismissed immediately,''
Little said.
</P>
<P>
   R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. issued a statement that echoed
Little's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe the federal government has any basis for
filing a lawsuit against the tobacco industry,'' the company said.
``We will vigorously defend against this suit in court; we are not
going to settle it.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Philip Morris and R.J. Reynolds, the Justice
Department is suing Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp., Lorillard
Tobacco Co., The Liggett Group Inc., American Tobacco Co. and
British American Tobacco P.L.C.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
