<HEADLINE>
EDUCATORS, BUSINESS DENOUNCE PLAN TO CUT RESEARCH FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fearing a loss of federal research funding that they say would
jeopardize 180,000 jobs in Massachusetts alone, universities joined
business and science groups Wednesday in a flurry of lobbying
efforts in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The universities say that with Congress under pressure to stay
within spending caps approved in the Balanced Budget Act of 1997,
New England stands to lose $1.5 billion in research and design
money, about a third of the money university research here now
receives.
</P>
<P>
   While Massachusetts would be especially hard hit, the American
Association for the Advancement of Science says that nationwide,
universities and companies that work with them will be socked with
a 12.5 percent cut in non-defense research and development
spending. University-run research across the country gets about $75
billion now. Massachusetts, which gets the lion's share of New
England funding, receives $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   About 285 companies or research centers in Massachusetts work
with universities in federally funded projects, according to the
Boston Chamber of Commerce, receiving about 72 percent of their
money from the federal government. In total, 180,000 Massachusetts
residents hold research jobs, the chamber says.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Harvard University president Neil Rudenstine and Tufts
University president John DiBiaggio, representatives of 40
universities joined the Boston Chamber and several science
organizations in trying to convince members of Congress and White
House staff that the effect on the New England economy would be
``dramatic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Federal research money works harder than any other dollar,''
said Kevin Casey, senior director for state and federal relations
for Harvard, which receives about $270 million a year in federal
research funding. ``It works toward solving the problem you've
asked it to, it trains the young people working at the universities
to be the next generation of innovators, and, down the road, many
times it results in a commercial application that reverberates in
the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   For Congress, the options are to override the caps, or to spend
the surplus to fund research. But some lawmakers have argued that
the surplus is better spent on tax cuts or Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're saying is, that's short-sighted,'' Casey said.
``Because the only way we'll realize those surpluses is if the
research continues.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress has spent more than the caps in the last two years,
leaving it even farther behind in trying to meet the balanced
budget targets this year, and increasing the pressure to stay
within the caps.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle to keep up funding is pitting various federally
funded research agencies against one another. The Senate recently
restored cuts to NASA and the National Science Foundation in its
version of an appropriation bill, but in doing so it took $20
million from the budget of the National Institutes for Health.
</P>
<P>
   University presidents, as well as some undergraduates and
graduate students involved in research, met Wednesday with White
House Chief of Staff John Podesta, as well as with members of the
Massachusetts congressional delegation and the Senate leadership,
arguing for an increase of at least the rate of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The universities and related businesses say the cuts, if
approved in final appropriations bills, would not mean immediate
layoffs, but they would have a long-term effect on the economy.
University-based research, they argue, is at the heart of the boom
in biotechnology and telecommunications, responsible for
developments ranging from cellular telephones to laser eye surgery.
About 50 percent of the growth in the economy comes from
technology, much of it spinoffs of university research, said Ed
Pignone, chief of staff for the Boston Chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only is this a university issue, but it's an
economic-growth issue,'' said Paul Guzzi, president of the chamber.
``Research happens in the labs, it's then used to create companies.
These jobs wouldn't be eliminated immediately, but clearly in terms
of reductions those jobs which are very directly dependent on
funding would be at risk, at universities, in the defense industry,
in the private sector, at the vendors for those institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   The universities say they may be the victim of their own
success. Last year was a boom year in federal spending for
university-based research. Agencies that control federal grants all
received increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people feel they gave us a good influx of money, so they
can take a year off and fund other priorities,'' Casey said. ``But
consistency is the most important thing. The worst thing for
research is to have big peaks and valleys in funding. You build
programs, and if the money dries up, you're left out there. What's
going on in discovery right now, it's happening faster. It's the
wrong time to reverse the trend.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
