<HEADER>
A2297 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-WACO-PROBE23-COX     09-22 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-PROBE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STARTUP TROUBLES FOR SENATE'S WACO PROBE
 &HT;    280&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Investigations into the 1993 Branch Davidian siege
at Waco, Texas, appeared Wednesday to be running into a traffic jam
at the starting line. Among the signs:
</P>
<P>
   _ Special counsel John Danforth has complained in a bluntly
worded letter that Senate investigators traveled to Waco last week
and interviewed witnesses ``without even troubling to give me a
call.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, who
is supposed to have jurisdiction over the Waco matter on his side
of Congress, said Wednesday that no one told him about the Senate
aides traveling to Texas either.
</P>
<P>
   _ In fact, the congressional investigators had been sent by Sen.
Arlen Specter, R-Pa., who has been angling to lead a special task
force to examine Waco. But Specter wants to expand the panel's
scope to include a slew of other controversies, including campaign
finance scandals and spying at the national weapons labs.
</P>
<P>
   _ That plan is criticized by Democrats, who would prefer that
the Judiciary Committee conduct the probe.
</P>
<P>
   With these issues still unresolved Wednesday, an impatient
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., told a gathering of
reporters that the decision about how to conduct the investigation
would be announced at 6 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to move on. I spend an inordinate amount of time on
it,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've really got to go,'' he said after an aide put a note in
his hand advising him that a group from the Fruit of the Loom
apparel company was waiting in his conference room.
</P>
<P>
   However, 6 p.m. came and went with no announcement. The debate
over the scope and form of the Senate investigation continued
behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   These are just some of the complications delaying a Senate
investigation of FBI actions during and after the April 19, 1993
attack on the Branch Davidian compound near Waco that left sect
leader David Koresh and 75 followers dead.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth has already sought delays of a civil lawsuit by
survivors and families of the tragedy against the federal
government so that his teams can interview witnesses first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I strongly believe that my investigation as Special Counsel is
best served if my staff can conduct interviews before witnesses are
interviewed by Congress or deposed in civil litigation,'' Danforth
wrote in his Sept. 17 letter to the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth, a former Republican senator from Missouri, asked
``forbearance as I attempt to get on with the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Reassuring the senators that he had been moving
``expeditiously'' since he was named to his post on Sept. 9,
Danforth laid out his progress so far. He said he has chosen eight
staff members, found office space in St. Louis, and arranged with
the U.S. postal inspector's office to provide investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth took a trip to Waco himself last Monday to inspect the
scene.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, his relations with yet another Waco investigation
appeared to be smoother. The House Government Reform Committee has
kept in contact with Danforth's office, said committee spokesman
Mark Carollo.
</P>
<P>
   The House committee has sent investigators to Austin to examine
evidence stored by the Texas Rangers, but the House has not tried
to question Waco witnesses, Carollo said. He said that the
committee was currently focusing on boxes of documents provided by
the Defense Department on its role in the Waco siege.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
