<SLUG> BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSIONAL LEADERS WEIGH COSTLY FIGHTER'S FATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Note to editors: this will sub if warranted) 
(md) 
 By TIM WEINER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A secret House-Senate conference that will decide
the fate of the Air Force's $70 billion F-22 fighter jet program
met late into the night Wednesday, with Republican leaders pushing
hard to save the plane.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders were leaning on one man: Rep. Jerry Lewis, a
California Republican and chairman of the House Appropriations
Committee's military spending panel, who led a successful fight in
the House to delete $1.8 billion in spending to buy the first six
of the warplanes.
</P>
<P>
   But the Senate voted to spend the money and buy the planes, and
now a deal must be forged between the plane's supporters and
opponents. Republican senators, backed by senior House Republicans,
the Air Force, and the plane's prime contractor, Lockheed Martin
Corp., want all of the $1.8 billion restored now.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who argues that the F-22 is too expensive and too
untested to be built as planned, convinced the House this summer to
support a one-year pause in its production, so that the Air Force
and the Pentagon could reconsider plans to build three new fighter
jets in the coming decade, at a total cost of $350 billion, a sum
far greater than the annual Pentagon budget.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force argues that a pause would kill the F-22 program.
It has already spent close to $25 billion developing the plane, but
has completed roughly five percent of the necessary flight tests.
Over the next decade, it plans to spend $40 billion or more
building 339 of the the aircraft. That puts the price tag of each
F-22 at close to $200 million, making it the costliest fighter jet
ever conceived.
</P>
<P>
   Aides privy to closed-door discussions preceding Wednesday's
House-Senate conference said a compromise over the F-22 could take
several forms. Some of the $1.8 billion could be restored, enough
to buy two or three planes, instead of six. All the money could be
restored, but a substantial portion would go for more research and
further tests of the aircraft, under a ``fly before you buy''
rationale.
</P>
<P>
   A compromise could also reduce the number of planes to be built
from 339 to roughly 250, reducing the overall cost of the program,
but increasing the cost per plane.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ted Stevens, the Alaska Republican who is chairman of the
Senate Appropriations Committee, said Wednesday night that he was
``ready to offer a new position'' on the F-22. ``We're trying to
work it out,'' he said, but added that Lewis was ``standing firm.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, a Texas Republican who supported full
funding for the F-22, said that Stevens and Lewis were ``not very
close together. They're far apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Some deal must be reached before the negotiators agree on a
Pentagon spending bill for the new fiscal year, which begins on
Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted to back Lewis' plan to spend the $1.8 billion on
other less expensive aircraft, and House Specker Dennis Hastert
supported that idea. But Air Force officials managed to change
Hastert's mind, and he ordered Lewis to find a way to restore some
of the money for the F-22, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   The F-22 has also been strongly supported by House Majority
Leader Dick Armey, and House Majority Whip Tom DeLay. Both are
Texas Republicans; many billions for the F-22 program would be
spent at Lockheed Martin's plant in Fort Worth, Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 2031EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
