<SLUG> BC-SOC-INTLNOTES23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gates in TV rights chase
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You think the feud between Ted Turner and Rupert
Murdoch is nasty? Wait until Microsoft co-founder and World's
Richest Man Bill Gates begins his assault on Murdoch's stranglehold
on live English Premier League television rights.
</P>
<P>
   Gates is assembling an American team of cable and broadcast
parties to challenge Murdoch, whose News Corp. subsidiary British
Sky Broadcasting is in the fourth year of a five-year, $1.2 billion
deal with the English Football Association.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Sunday Times of Singapore, an FA official said
the Gates group is planning to bid $1.62 billion next season. With
the big boys wanting in on the action, don't expect FIFA head Sepp
Blatter to be able to pull off his goal of reconciling the global
soccer calendar all that easily.
</P>
<P>
   The increasing appetite for televised soccer figures to make it
even more difficult for clubs to rest players from matches and
adjust to hectic travel. The European Champions League was expanded
this year to head off efforts by television moguls to start their
own super league. The 32 clubs will play in two different group
stages through March, while continuing a heavy slate of
domestic-league and cup action. The two teams in the May 24 finals
will have played 16 Champions League matches.
</P>
<P>
   Some notable clubs, especially defending European champion
Manchester United, already are taking a heavy toll. No fewer than
nine Red Devils are on the injured list, which grew Tuesday when
key midfielder Ryan Giggs went down for six weeks with a hamstring
tear. ``This spiral cannot go on forever,'' Blatter told the Swiss
newspaper Sonntags Zeitung over the weekend. ``There has to be one
time each year when there is no football. Only then can the desire
for the game be maintained in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   Champions League Barcelona got two goals in three minutes from
Rivaldo to thrash Fiorentina 4-2 Wednesday to take the lead in
Group B. Although tied on points with Arsenal, a 3-1 winner over
AIK Stockholm, the Spanish champions are at the top by virtue of
five total goals. In London, Thierry Henry came on in the 68th
minute and scored the winner for Arsenal at the end of
regulation.... Injury-plagued captain Roy Keane returned to the
Manchester United lineup and scored early in the first half in a
3-0 Group D rout at Sturm Graz. ... Fredi Bobic had two goals in
Borussia Dortmund's 3-1 win over Boavista in Group C, while Marcelo
Salas got the winner for Lazio in the 72nd minute in a 2-1 Group A
decision over Dynamo Kyiv.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, midfielder Michael Tarnat was forced to finish out
Bayern Munich's 2-1 Bundesliga win over Eintracht Frankfurt in the
nets because all three of the club's full-time goalkeepers were
injured. Stefan Wessels, called up from Bayern's amateur side,
stood in goal Tuesday as Tarnat got the equalizer off a deflection
with a minute remaining in a 1-1 draw in Group F with Rangers in
Glasgow.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Tuesday, Chelsea lost 2-1 in Group H at Hertha Berlin,
with Ali Daei scoring in the third and 70th minutes. In the same
group, Leonardo and Andrii Shevchenko scored in the last two
minutes of the first half as AC Milan beat visiting Galatasaray
2-1.... In Group E, Savio had two goals as Real Madrid routed
Norwegian surprise Molde 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   England: Shearer takes five
</P>
<P>
   New manager Bobby Robson's home debut Sunday for Newcastle was a
badly needed boost of confidence for slumping England captain Alan
Shearer, who exploded for five goals as the Geordies routed
Sheffield Wednesday 8-0 for their first Premier League win of the
season. France: Les Bleus shakeup
</P>
<P>
   Upset over lackluster play in Euro 2000 qualifying, French coach
Roger Lemerre is serious about lineup changes for the Oct. 9 finale
vs. Iceland. The World Cup champions, in danger of missing next
year's finals, need a win plus a draw between the Ukraine and
Russia to advance. Lemerre is peeved at defender Frederic Dehu and
keeper Fabien Barthez, both sent off in last week's surprisingly
tough 3-2 win at Armenia. ``We left a bad image,'' Lemerre said.
``The respect due to the (World Cup) team has been tarnished.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
