<SLUG> BC-FILM-WILLIAMS-360&AMP;ADD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBIN WILLIAMS YEARNS TO BE A STAND-UP GUY 
</HEADLINE>
   By RUTHE STEIN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ ``I'm getting so excited, I'm going to use the
bathroom,'' says Robin Williams, leaping out of his chair in a
Toronto hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   However, it's not talk of his new movie, ``Jakob the Liar,'' or
any Williams movie that has his juices flowing. His exuberance
springs from a dramatic career move he is about to make.
</P>
<P>
   After starring in huge box-office hits like ``Patch Adams'' and
``Mrs. Doubtfire'' and winning an Oscar for ``Good Will Hunting,''
Williams, 48, is about to give up acting for a while to return to
his first love: stand-up comedy. ``Sometime after the first of the
year, I'm going to just write and perform. I have to stay focused,
which means I can't be doing a movie (set ital)and(end ital)
stand-up,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   So far, there haven't been any movie offers to turn down.
``Maybe because it's a dry period or maybe people are going,
`That's enough,''' he says with the carefree laugh of someone who
doesn't define himself by what Hollywood thinks of him.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to go back to comedy came from Williams' feeling
that he might be losing his edge. He has an ambitious agenda to
premiere his new routine at a club in San Francisco and then take
it on the road ``to see what flies in other places.''
</P>
<P>
   The scary thing about comedy, Williams says, is that there is no
one but yourself to blame if it flops. ``You can't say, `Oh, the
script wasn't right' or `It's the director.' No, it's you. You get
a grace period of maybe five minutes of people going, `Yeah, I know
you. You're famous.' But then if you don't have the chops, it gets
really interesting and you start to sweat and you start finding
stuff that works. It's a process. I need to do that. I have to. I'm
getting the bug again in me.''
</P>
<P>
   While at the Toronto International Film Festival for the
premiere of ``Jakob the Liar'' last week, Williams seemed to be
trying out new material _ for example, a Viagra joke that, without
the cruder references, goes something like: ``It's amazing that
they've developed a pill to (increase your potency) but they don't
have one to increase your thought processes. A guy goes, `I'd
rather have a stiff (organ) than a big mind.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``As we get near that time _ the end of the millennium _ there
is a lot to talk about, and you've got to find it,'' says Williams,
who will be the subject of a tribute October 14 at the Mill Valley
Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As with every major decision, this career change was made after
long discussions with his wife, Marsha Garces Williams. ``Even
though Robin hasn't really been doing comedy in the last decade,
it's an important, rejuvenating part of him,'' she says, explaining
why she encouraged him even though his new gig will take him away
from their San Francisco home and two children, ages 10 and 7.
(Williams also has a teenage son from his first marriage.)
</P>
<P>
   Garces Williams, 43, is soft-spoken and almost somber. As she
archly points out, ``Anyone seems serious compared to Robin.'' She
and Williams met when his first wife hired her as their nanny. They
became reacquainted after his divorce and married 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Garces Williams struck gold the first time she produced one of
her husband's movies, ``Mrs. Doubtfire,'' which grossed $219
million. Nobody is expecting that kind of bonanza for ``Jakob the
Liar,'' a tragicomedy about Polish Jews during the Nazi occupation,
which she also produced.
</P>
<P>
   After the film had been shot in Eastern Europe, they learned of
another tragicomedy about the Holocaust, Roberto Benigni's ``Life
Is Beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What are the odds that after 55 years there is another movie
about that time to have elements of humor? What luck,'' Williams
says with a sigh. ``People have said to me, `Did your heart sink
when Roberto won the Academy Award?' I said no. It's an
extraordinary movie, an outrageous statement for Roberto as a
comedian. But our movie is more of a drama with moments of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   Filmmaker Peter Kassovitz sent the ``Jakob the Liar'' script to
Williams, incorrectly assuming that he is Jewish. Garces Williams
read it and persuaded her husband to take on the role of an
out-of-work cafe owner in the Jewish ghetto who, to keep up his
friends' spirits, pretends to have a radio beaming good news from
the front.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marsha has great instincts about roles,'' says Williams,
recalling how she encouraged him to do ``Good Will Hunting'' when
he was wavering. ``She'll say to me, `This is different. I haven't
seen you do that.'''
</P>
<P>
   She watched the rushes every day on the set of ``Jakob'' and
told him when something worked and when it didn't. Williams says he
especially appreciates her honesty in a business where it is
sometimes hard to believe what people tell him. ``The difference is
Marsha loves me and they don't. They are not your friends. They are
looking at you from a distance.''
</P>
<P>
   Garces Williams calls it ``fortunate'' that they work well
together but doesn't think being his producer has strengthened
their marriage. ``Our marriage is strong because of love and
determination and respect and beautiful children and humor, because
if you can't laugh at yourself in a marriage, you are missing out
on a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   In a life that can be ``so surreal because of the nature of
fame,'' Williams credits his wife with ``gently and sometimes not
so gently bringing me back to earth. I can go off and be wild and
to do these riffs that I do. Then she'll go, `Psst, it's time to
come back to the real world.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
