<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anderson: `It stinks to sit there and watch'
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Falcons running back Jamal Anderson, who
rushed for an NFC-best 1,846 yards in 1998, will miss the rest of
this season after tearing the anterior cruciate ligament in his
right knee in Monday night's 24-7 loss at Dallas. Anderson, who
signed a five-year, $32-million contract in August, will undergo
surgery in about two weeks. Anderson faces six or seven months of
rehabilitation and should be ready for next year's training camp.
Anderson spoke Wednesday with NFL writer Mark Schlabach.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's your mindset now?
</P>
<P>
   A: You know, it's upsetting, particularly with the way things
are going for us as a team. I felt like I needed to pick it up
myself, along with everybody around us, in light of what happened
to (quarterback Chris Chandler, who missed the Dallas game with a
strained right hamstring). It was terrible. I felt like I could pop
up and walk and run again, but the results proved differently. I'm
upset right now and frustrated a little bit.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about speculation that your two-week holdout from
training camp contributed to this injury?
</P>
<P>
   A: I've always had pride in myself for being a person of class
and certain stature. I just won't even address that. It was
disheartening to me and my family and the reaction _ positive or
negative _ is irrelevant. I never reported as light (236 pounds) as
I did. My hamstrings held up.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you glad you signed a new contract before getting hurt?
</P>
<P>
   A: Given the season we had last year and running the ball 410
times, obviously you're putting yourself at great risk any time you
get on the field. But running that many times, it was a
consideration to make sure that my future was secure. We took all
those things into consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you blame artificial turf for the injury?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's a tough call. I don't really like playing on turf. I
love grass games. I consider myself a football purist and I believe
football should be played on grass. I just like the way I look
after playing on grass; I like being dirty after the game. But we
play in the Georgia Dome, so it's just something I had to deal
with. People said you look quicker on turf. I think (the injury
happened) from watching too many Barry Sanders highlights.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When will you be back?
</P>
<P>
   A: If I wanted to play, I could assure you that I could probably
play at the end of the season. It's one of those things, how much
you want to push yourself?
</P>
<P>
   Q: How will you cope with not playing?
</P>
<P>
   A: It stinks, man. It's no fun. This is football season, and it
stinks to sit there and watch. It was painful to watch them on
Monday night. I will suffer hopefully 18 weeks like that with the
playoffs and everything.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
