u w BC-GOP-LIMITS-HNS &LR;      09-22 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-LIMITS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP UNDER PRESSURE AS PROJECTED SPENDING MAY EXCEED BUDGET CAPS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Amid accusations within their own party that they
have used accounting ``gimmicks,'' Republican leaders are under
pressure to raise federal spending caps to meet Year 2000 budget
requests.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office has warned that the projected
spending in next year's appropriations measures could drain at
least $16 billion from the Social Security Trust Fund, despite
Republican claims to the contrary, if anticipated surpluses fail to
materialize next year. The new fiscal year begins in eight days.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sens. Larry Craig of Idaho and Chuck Hagel of
Nebraska have issued a similar warning, telling their colleagues
that techniques such as declaring emergency spending or
``borrowing'' from future budgets in order to get around the 1997
spending caps is, at the least, a disingenuous way to run the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Hagel accused his colleagues of ``living a charade, which
demeans our country,'' and called on Republican leaders to
acknowledge that next year's budget will indeed break the caps
agreed to by Congress and President Clinton in 1997 _ a deal that
helped achieve a balanced budget last year for the first time in
nearly three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., has done just that, telling reporters
that the caps have already been exceeded because ``we've had
emergencies we've had to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   GOP and Democratic critics say those emergencies, such as
declaring funding for the 2000 census and for some routine defense
programs to be emergency-related expenditures, are not really
emergencies at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans have shown an inability to get the basic job
of Congress done, and that is writing and passing and getting
signed the spending bills in the budget. They can't make their
budget work or stand on its own without resorting to cheap budget
gimmicks,'' said House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for the Republicans to realize that the budget
they're operating under is faulty and that they need to go back to
the drawing board,'' Gephardt said, calling on Republicans to admit
they've abandoned their promise to stay within the spending caps
and away from Social Security money.
</P>
<P>
   Lott's admission underscored the problem Republicans are having
in keeping their promise not to break the budget limits set two
years ago and to protect Social Security. Pressures have been
building not only to maintain adequate funding for government next
year, but to come up with new spending for programs favored by
lawmakers on both sides of the aisle.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders say they need $20 billion to $30 billion in
extra funding next year just to meet the demands for new spending
from their own colleagues. That money, some lawmakers say, will be
impossible to come up with even if next year's projected non-Social
Security surplus is enough to cover it, given that the 1997
spending limits mandated funding cuts of $37 billion this year for
non-Pentagon programs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to declaring some program funding as emergency
spending (which takes it off budget and means that it cannot be
counted against the 1997 spending caps), GOP leaders are trying
other ways to avoid the appearance of having busted the balanced
budget agreement.
</P>
<P>
   One effort is centered around taking money earmarked for the
Department of Housing and Human Services. That could lead to
further cuts in some education programs and a number of housing and
social service programs, such as day care. Some consideration also
has been given to delaying several billion in tax credit payments
to low-income Americans.
</P>
<P>
   To cover the use of the HHS money for other programs, such as
favored defense projects, GOP leaders in the House want to replace
it by using a forward-funding accounting technique that would
borrow $15 billion in fiscal year 2001 money for education and Head
Start programs.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear, however, whether Lott and Senate Appropriations
Committee Chairman Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, will go along. Both have
urged caution in the handling of HHS cuts, and it seems likely that
Senate Republicans will end up looking elsewhere for additional
funding. The question is, where will it come from?
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt and Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., urged
Republicans Wednesday to reconsider their opposition to President
Clinton's proposed increase in the tobacco tax, which they insisted
would help meet additional spending priorities without having to
draw on Social Security receipts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either we use Social Security funding or the tobacco tax. I'll
settle for the tobacco tax any day,'' Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, last week
acknowledged the difficulty of finding new funding sources, telling
reporters that lawmakers have ``bumped into a wall'' in terms of
figuring out how to stay within the budget limits without giving in
to temptations to declare more emergencies and spend more of the
projected surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   With fiscal year 2000 beginning on Oct. 1, Congress has so far
approved and Clinton has signed into law only two of the 13 major
appropriations bills. Ten remain either tied up in conference
committees between the House and Senate or under consideration by
one chamber or the other. The largest bill, which covers
appropriations for HHS, has yet to be reported out of the House
Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Given the differences between the administration and Republicans
on spending priorities, it now seems increasingly likely that
Congress will pass a series of stop gap spending bills, known as
continuing resolutions, to keep the government operating past Sept.
30 and, quite possibly, through next year if a compromise on
remaining 2000 budget matters cannot be reached.
</P>
<P>
   The last thing Republicans say they want is a repeat of the
1995-96 partial government shutdowns, and a continuing resolution
would at least allow affected departments to continue operating
through 2000 at this year's funding levels.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart told reporters
Wednesday that he sees little chance of another ``train wreck''
like the one that occurred four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been discussion of a CR to move forward, so I don't
think there's ... any danger ... that somehow the government will
shut down,'' Lockhart said. ``We don`t see any reason to head into
October 1st, you know, with anticipation of a train wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
