u i BC-TIMOR-RDP-(TRIMS)-NYT     09-22 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-RDP-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AID TO TIMOR DELAYED BY DANGERS IN ITS TERRIFIED STREETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, East Timor _ Continuing concerns about security are
delaying the start of a huge aid program to help hundreds of
thousands of East Timorese refugees in urgent need of food, shelter
and medical care, several aid workers said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On the third day of an international peacekeeping mission to
subdue the terror here and provide security for aid distribution,
military officials said East Timor remained tense and
unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a difficult security situation,'' said Brig. Gen. Mark
Evans, commander of the Australian troops who are the bulk of the
international presence here. ``It's going to take a little time.
There are still some very dangerous people out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Jason Ross, another member of the peacekeeping force, said
secure areas had been prepared for refugees at the Roman Catholic
cathedral, the port and the stadium, but he said the military could
offer no food or water. ``It is still two or three more days before
the care agencies can come with supplies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Evans said the first 150 troops landed Wednesday in the eastern
city of Baucau, the first international deployment outside Dili. So
far, about 2,000 soldiers are working to secure the capital, the
general said. He said that even though his troops had met no open
resistance, the city Wednesday was noticeably more tense than in
the first two days of their deployment.
</P>
<P>
   Through a long and enervating afternoon, tough young men
wandered the streets, apparently both supporters and opponents of
independence for East Timor. There was an air of menace and
potential violence.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The commander of the international forces, Maj. Gen. Peter
Cosgrove, has said that his forces are not here to carry out an
aggressive campaign against the militias, and indeed a number of
his officers have noted that they are ``thin on the ground,'' with
a force that is expected to grow to no more than 8,000.
</P>
<P>
   On foot and in two vehicle convoys of armored personnel
carriers, the troops have been patrolling the capital, and stopping
and searching men they suspect to be carrying weapons. Any armed
men they find are handed over to the Indonesian police, who
themselves have been accused of cooperating with the militias.
</P>
<P>
   Another officer, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
military discovered a cache of 40 weapons Wednesday, bringing the
number of confiscated weapons to 600. He said caches of explosives,
mostly based on fertilizer or nitrate, had also been found.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when the body of a Dutch reporter was discovered in
eastern Dili, a British reporter said that a bullet had been fired
at her in the well-patrolled center of the city. In both cases,
militias backed by the Indonesian military or elements of the
military itself were suspected.
</P>
<P>
   After the people here chose independence in a referendum on Aug.
30, the militias, who oppose independence, opened a campaign of
terror that has left the city terrified and in ruins. Now, with
foreign troops patrolling in armored personnel carriers, some
pro-independence fighters have come down from the hills to look
around.
</P>
<P>
   Unconfirmed reports of atrocities by the militias began to
emerge Wednesday. Late Wednesday evening, two military officers
said a patrol would be sent in the morning to a house in the city
center to investigate a report that bodies had been found in a
well.
</P>
<P>
   One Indonesian reporter said the decapitated body of a woman had
been found in the well and that there were believed to be a number
of others. The reporter said instruments of torture had been found
on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   With parts of the burned-out shopping district still smoldering
Wednesday, hundreds of frightened refugees moved from place to
place, carrying their belongings on their heads, pulling them in
carts or trundling them along piled high on looted office chairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes at night we are sleeping and the soldiers shoot into
the air,'' said Marco Artur Nevis de Sousa, 20, as he and his
family headed toward the city's small stadium with a load of
mattresses, cooking pots, rubber tires, a red furry Santa Claus, a
guitar, a stack of plastic chairs and a large framed painting of
the Last Supper.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get drunk and they shoot their guns and they make the
children afraid, the ladies afraid and they cry,'' he said. ``Now
the Australians say, `Come to the stadium and we will protect
you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Philip Maher, who represents the aid agency World Vision, said
the distribution of aid to more 30,000 desperate people camped in
the hills above Dili would not begin for several more days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are starting at ground zero,'' he said. ``We have no
vehicles and no compound. We have food in warehouses in Jakarta.
People have the notion you can arrive and dump food off, but that
is very ineffectual. It only feeds the strong. We want to do this
properly; if you don't, you end up with mayhem.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Relief officials estimate that about 200,000 people have fled
their homes throughout this territory of 800,000 and that another
200,000 have fled or have been forcibly removed across the border
into West Timor. Many of these people, they said, are in urgent
need of food and other supplies. The refugees who are camped in the
hills above Dili say they are eating little more than cassava roots
and are sleeping on the ground and covering themselves with leaves
against the cold.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to these displaced people, many others who remain in
vandalized towns and villages around East Timor are also suffering,
aid officials said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Parachute drops of relief aid have not proceeded in the numbers
that had been planned. In the village of Dare, six miles south of
Dili, an official with the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees,
said a small amount of food aid had been delivered but was not
being distributed because so many people were in need that it was
impossible to apportion it fairly.
</P>
<P>
   Urs Boegli, a spokesman for the International Committee of the
Red Cross, said, ``I would not dare open a large distribution point
now because I am afraid people will come out of their relative
safety to get food. The rest of our problem is based on security.
The city is not a challenge. The challenge is beyond the city. You
can only venture there with a modicum of security.''
</P>
<P>
   A military officer, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said,
``Humanitarian agencies are here, but their work is particularly
difficult. There is the question of where they are going to set up
their bases, where they are going to find resources such as
transportation, but particularly the question of security.''
</P>
<P>
   Another senior military officer said, ``It'll take time. The
militias haven't faded away. This is a difficult country to cover,
and we have a limited number of men and you can't police every back
alley.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``There are more police in New York City than we have
soldiers here, and they still haven't managed to stop the
killings.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
