r a BC-FILM-MINUSMAN-TEX     09-22 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MINUSMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MINUS MAN' ADDS UP TO UNEXCEPTIONAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Don't bring a dumb date'' is a cocky (not to mention
condescending) tag line for a movie, and ``The Minus Man'' doesn't
entirely live up to the boast. It's an intriguing enough study of
an ingratiating young man who happens to be a serial killer, but
your smart date is just as likely to find it dry and empty as to
find it perceptive and thought-provoking.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Hampton Fancher, who wrote the screenplays for
1982's ``Blade Runner'' and 1989's ``The Mighty Quinn,'' isn't
interested in exploitation _ or even chills (this is probably the
least violent serial-killer movie you'll ever see). He's primarily
interested in getting inside the head of Vann (Dallas' Owen
Wilson), a sweet, attractive, low-key guy who has a nasty habit of
poisoning people (even this is seen as part of Vann's ``niceness,''
because he picks the most humane way he can think of to dispatch
his victims).
</P>
<P>
   The movie sees things through Vann's eyes, and because even he
doesn't know why he indulges in his fatal hobby, it's up to us to
try to figure out his motives.
</P>
<P>
   Vann drifts into an oceanside town, where he boards with Jane
and Doug (Mercedes Ruehl and Brian Cox), a couple who are also more
troubled than they appear on the surface. Doug gets Vann a job at
the post office, where Vann attracts the attentions of a shy
co-worker (a more-vulnerable-than-usual Janeane Garofalo). And he
continues to practice his pastime, getting more bold and sloppy as
he goes along.
</P>
<P>
   Another tag line for the movie is ``Conversation usually
follows,'' and that seems like a better boast, as the movie is
almost guaranteed to get you talking about what makes Vann and the
others tick (of course, the conversation might start with ``What
the $%&AMP;! was that all about?''). The movie's press notes
breathlessly brag about how it's a look behind the ``surface of
normality,'' as if that were an original concept. It wasn't even
original when Alfred Hitchcock, whom Fancher clearly admires,
addressed it decades ago in ``Suspicion'' and ``Shadow of a
Doubt.'' You can even catch variations on the theme in two other
movies this week, ``American Beauty'' and ``Mumford.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fancher does give ``The Minus Man'' a sustained moodiness,
marked by dark humor, and he gets good performances out of his
cast, especially Wilson and Cox. Singers Dwight Yoakam and Sheryl
Crow are impressive in a brief, booze-soaked prologue.
</P>
<P>
   It's tough to be comfortable with a movie about a sympathetic
serial killer when real-life mass violence has recently hit so
close to home. Comfort isn't the point here, though; the point is
to get you talking. ``The Minus Man'' succeeds at that, but despite
the movie's pride in itself, it's unlikely that the conversation
will last the entire post-movie meal or long drive home.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
