<SLUG> BC-FBC-INSIDE-FOOTBALL23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Floyd proves costly for East Carolina
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The flooding from Hurricane Floyd that is ravaging
eastern North Carolina has stranded the East Carolina team in
Columbia, S.C., this week _ the week of its big game against No. 9
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The school is in Greenville, N.C., about 75 miles east of
Raleigh. Because of damage from Floyd, the players and coaches
couldn't go home after winning at South Carolina on Saturday to go
3-0. The campus remains unfit for students, and an apartment
complex where two dozen players live has been condemned.
</P>
<P>
   So the team has stayed in Columbia and used South Carolina's
practice facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The flooding even forced relocation of Saturday's game from
Greenville to Raleigh and N.C. State's Carter-Finley Stadium. The
game had been touted as one of East Carolina's biggest at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to lose a good recruiting weekend,'' coach Steve
Logan said. ``There's a lot of stuff involved. But I'm still glad
we're playing the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL's Carolina Panthers, about 80 miles north in Charlotte,
N.C., have pitched in, donating practice jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest headache, Logan said, has been trying to come up
with something for the players to do when they are not practicing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a constant deal trying to come up with something to keep
everybody from going crazy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all of the $250,000 East Carolina earned for playing
South Carolina will be eaten up by expenses for the extended stay
away from home.
</P>
<P>
   NEBRASKA'S EVANS: ``WHERE'S THE LOVE?''
</P>
<P>
   This week's reality check goes to former Nebraska running back
DeAngelo Evans, who quit the team last week in a huff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel like I was being used in the offense the way I
should have been,'' said Evans, who told coach Frank Solich in a
private meeting that ``unless some major changes were made,'' he
was through. Solich immediately offered to release Evans from his
scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Evans had second thoughts about his immature act, however, and
asked Solich if he could return. In the meantime, Solich asked key
people on the team what they thought. Their response: ``The guy is
selfish and has never been a team player. We're glad he's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   So Monday, Solich told Evans he was through at Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Evans responded by saying publicly that the ``program is showing
me no love'' and that Solich was being ``stubborn and classless.''
</P>
<P>
   Gee, it's hard to understand why the Nebraska players didn't
want Evans back.
</P>
<P>
   JUST THINKING
</P>
<P>
   _ We should find out tonight if No. 8 Virginia Tech (2-0) is the
real deal when the Hokies host Clemson (1-1) on ESPN. Remember,
Virginia Tech coach Frank Beamer interviewed for the Clemson job
that went to Tommy Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   _ Speaking of Tommy Bowden, his name has been one of the first
to come up should Alabama fire Mike DuBose. Bowden's father, Bobby,
wanted the Alabama job when Ray Perkins left in 1986. The school
hired Bill Curry instead. The Bowden family has roots in
Birmingham. Suppose Tommy Bowden gets the job and hires brother
Terry, a former Auburn coach, as offensive coordinator. Wouldn't
that be fun?
</P>
<P>
   _ Virginia coach George Welsh obviously made somebody mad. He
opened the season with three consecutive ACC games, two on the
road, and Saturday he goes to BYU, a very tough place to play.
</P>
<P>
   WORTH NOTING
</P>
<P>
   _ After Texas Tech lost 21-14 to North Texas, which was
outscored 78-3 in its first two games, newspaper columnists began
calling for the resignation of Red Raider coach Spike Dykes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wisconsin coach Barry Alvarez probably will watch Saturday's
big game with Michigan from the press box. The 52-year-old Alvarez
is scheduled to have knee-replacement surgery.
</P>
<P>
   _ A sign that things really are changing at Oklahoma under new
coach Bobby Stoops: Before 1992, the Sooners had never averaged 20
passes a game for a season. In Saturday's 41-10 win over Baylor,
quarterback Josh Heupel completed 37 of 54 passes for 420 yards and
three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   _ Since missing a field goal in the opener against Louisiana
Tech, Florida State placekicker Sebastian Janikowski has hit nine
in a row, including all five tried last week against N.C. State.
Janikowski also had a tackle on a kickoff return that saved a
score.
</P>
<P>
   BY THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   185: Nebraska's total offense last week against Southern
Mississippi, the Cornhuskers' worst offensive performance in six
years.
</P>
<P>
   12: Number of TD passes thrown by Kentucky's Dusty Bonner, to
lead the nation.
</P>
<P>
   122: Victories at Air Force by coach Fisher DeBerry, pushing him
past Army's Red Blaik as the coach with the most wins at a service
academy.
</P>
<P>
   0-3: Notre Dame's record this season against the Big Ten, the
conference it shunned this summer after a membership offer was
extended.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
