<HEADLINE>
WACO DISPUTE BREWS AS DANFORTH LETTER COMES TO LIGHT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A territorial dispute is brewing between government
teams investigating the 1993 Waco standoff and whether federal
agencies tried to cover up details of the FBI's final assault on
the Branch Davidian compound.
</P>
<P>
   Special counsel John Danforth, who was appointed by Attorney
General Janet Reno to examine the Waco case, cautioned Senate
investigators against undermining his inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter disclosed Wednesday, Danforth complained that the
investigators had been dispatched to Texas ``without even troubling
to give me a call.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had agreed that we would work together so that I
can fulfill my mission as special counsel,'' Danforth wrote in a
letter to Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, who is urging creation of a special Senate task force to
examine the Waco case as part of a larger investigation into the
Justice Department, acknowledged that Senate staff members had
traveled to Texas but ``not with full committee authorization.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigators were dispatched by Sen. Arlen Specter, a
Pennsylvania Republican who is likely to oversee the special task
force if it is approved by Senate leaders from both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Without an agreement by Democratic leaders, Senate Republicans
are prepared for the full Judiciary Committee to re-examine the
FBI's tactics to end the Waco siege and whether the government
tried to cover up the use of potentially incendiary tear gar
canisters. The standoff ended with the Branch Davidian compound in
flames and more than 80 people killed.
</P>
<P>
   Senate leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, met Tuesday and
Wednesday about the scope of the investigation. Their talks bogged
down over Danforth's complaint and Specter's reported plan to hire
Charles LaBella to lead the task force inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   LaBella is a former federal prosecutor who oversaw a Justice
Department examination of 1996 campaign fund-raising abuses and
publicly disagreed with Reno's decision not to turn the
investigation over to an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Specter and his aides did not return telephone calls Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democratic Leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota said he was
not inclined to go along with Republicans on appointment of a
special task force.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to wonder whether there is anything left to
investigate, after all these years and all these investigations,''
Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they (Republicans) want to pursue yet another investigation
within the confines of the Judiciary Committee, that's their
prerogative. We can't stop them,'' Daschle said. ``If they would
come to the Senate asking for extra money to do so, we'd have a
problem with that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
