u a BC-MUSEUM-FUNDING-GIULIA     09-22 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUM-FUNDING-GIULIANI-2TAKES(TRIMS)-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR THREATENS TO CUT MUSEUM'S FUNDING OVER CONTROVERSIAL EXHIBIT
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By DAN BARRY and CAROL VOGEL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani threatened Wednesday to cut
off all city subsidies to the Brooklyn Museum of Art unless it
cancels next week's opening of a British art exhibition that
features, among other works, a shark suspended in a tank of
formaldehyde, a bust of a man made from his own frozen blood and a
portrait of the Virgin Mary stained with a clump of elephant dung.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, who has seen the show's catalog but not the
exhibition itself, derided the works of art generally as ``sick
stuff.'' But he singled out the portrait of the Virgin Mary as
particularly offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have a right to government subsidy for desecrating
somebody else's religion,'' he said. ``And therefore we will do
everything that we can to remove funding for the Brooklyn Museum
until the director comes to his senses and realizes that if you are
a government-subsidized enterprise, then you can't do things that
desecrate the most personal and deeply held views of people in
society. I mean, this is an outrageous thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   If the mayor follows through on his threat, it could severely
hamper the museum's operations. The city gives the museum nearly $7
million a year in operating expenses _ nearly one-third of its $23
million budget _ and has reserved another $20 million in the budget
for capital improvements. The museum is the second largest in New
York, after the Metropolitan, and has a permanent collection of
more than 1.5 million objects.
</P>
<P>
   But if Arnold L. Lehman, the museum's director, was intimidated
by Giuliani's expression of outrage, he did not let on Wednesday.
He said he hoped to meet with the mayor ``to encourage him not to
take such an action,'' and added ``it is part of a museum's job to
support the right of artists to express themselves freely.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's angry reaction _ ``I'm offended,'' he said _ is
typical of the visceral response that the show, called ``Sensation:
Young British Artists From That Saatchi Collection,'' has generated
both in the United States and in Europe, where it opened to raves
and criticism at the Royal Academy of Arts in London two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Featuring the work of young British artists whose works are
displayed in museums around the world, the show is intended to
disturb, perturb and provoke thought. It was mounted at a cost of
$1 million and is the largest ever held by the Brooklyn Museum. The
show is financed in part by the Christie's, the auction house.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics and viewers in London argued that the content of
the show was offensive and intended to shock for shock's sake. A
few wryly suggested that it was designed primarily to increase the
value of the works amassed by Charles Saatchi, the London
advertising executive.
</P>
<P>
   The most extreme reaction was to the artist Marcus Harvey's
depictions of Myra Hindley, who was convicted in the macabre
``moors murders'' of children in western England in the 1960s.
Protesters splattered ink and raw eggs on the painting, saying it
trivialized her victims' suffering and glorified her crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Others, though, felt that the exhibition captured an important
moment in the history of contemporary British art. Many dealers say
that they have waiting lists of collectors eager to buy the works
of those they believe to be the groundbreaking artists.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition attracted record crowds in London and at the
Hamburger Bahnof in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   The Brooklyn Museum sought to create the same kind of excitement
for the show's only North American engagement, which opens Oct. 2.
It announced that children under the age of 17 will have to be
accompanied by an adult. Even its promotions read like health
warnings on a cigarette pack: ``The contents of this exhibition may
cause shock, vomiting, confusion, panic, euphoria and anxiety. If
you suffer from high blood pressure, a nervous disorder or
palpitations, you should consult your doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was the show's catalog that sparked the charged emotions
that publicity-hungry museums crave.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Damien Hirst is perhaps the exhibition's best known artist; his
work depicting a pair of cows sliced and suspended in a tank of
formaldehyde caused a stir at a Soho gallery three years ago. And
his shark-in-a-tank piece immediately attracted the ire of People
for the Ethical Treatment of Animals.
</P>
<P>
   Ingrid Newkirk, the organization's president, dismissed Hirst as
a ``shock jock'' who ``is contributing to the slaughter of animals
for no other reason than his own aggrandizement.'' (Hirst denies
that he kills animals, saying they are already dead.)
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   William Donohue, president of the Catholic League for Religious
and Civil Rights, said that the catalog turned his stomach. ``I
think the whole city should picket the show,'' he said. ``This
exhibition is designed to shock, but instead it induces
revulsion.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was the reaction of Giuliani that signaled both a
publicity coup for the museum and a threat to its own finances.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody wants to do that privately and pay for that
privately, well that's what the First Amendment is all about,'' he
said. ``I mean, you can be offended by it and upset by it, and you
don't have to go see it, if somebody else is paying for it. But to
have the government subsidize something like that is outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He went on to add a quick critique of Hirst's work. ``I though
that's what they did in biology laboratories,'' he said, ``not in
museums of art.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Mayor Randy Levine later explained the mechanics of the
mayor's threat to cut off city funds. ``They get their checks on a
first-of-the-month basis,'' Levine said. ``Those checks will be
suspended unless this exhibit is canceled.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked what would happen if the museum did not cancel the
show, Levine said: ``Then they're not going to get any more city
funds.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Abrams, a New York attorney who specializes in First
Amendment law, suggested that the mayor understands the amendment
that protects free expression ``precisely backwards.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Punishing the Brooklyn Museum by seeking to remove its funding
because the mayor disapproves of what he perceives is the message
of its art is at war with the First Amendment,'' Abrams said. ``The
mayor has every right to denounce the exhibition. He should
understand, however, that the First Amendment limits what he can do
to retaliate against art of which he disapproves.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The struggle between artists trying to express themselves and
the government trying to define what it considers acceptably
artistic has intensified in recent years with disputes over several
exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the Corcoran Gallery in Washington backed down and
canceled an exhibition featuring the homoerotic art of Robert
Mapplethorpe and financed by the National Endowment for the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1998, the Supreme Court upheld a congressional decency
test for awarding federal arts grants, but only after a majority
interpreted a 1990 law as containing only ``advisory language''
that did not actually prohibit federal subsidies for indecent art.
In a majority opinion by Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, the court
suggested that if the law was invoked to impose ``a penalty on
disfavored viewpoints,'' it would violate the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came in a case brought against the NEA by the
performance artist Karen Finley and three other artists. Two NEA
grants in 1989, for a retrospective of sexually explicit
photographs by Mapplethorpe and to the artist Andres Serrano, who
photographed a crucifix immersed in his own urine, had ignited a
furor that has never completely died down.
</P>
<P>
   Some museum directors were taken aback by Giuliani's threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm appalled,'' Mimi Gaudieri, the director of the Association
of Art Museum Directors. ``We've been through this war before _ not
only with Mapplethorpe but with Serrano and others _ and we've won.
It just doesn't play in the political arena.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Ofili, a Roman Catholic whose portrait of the Virgin Mary
so offended the mayor and whose work often features clumps of
elephant dung, defended his work as being of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an altar boy I was confused by the idea of a holy Virgin
Mary giving birth to a young boy,'' he said. ``Now when I go to the
National Gallery and see paintings of the Virgin Mary, I see how
sexually charged they are. Mine is simply a hip-hop version.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
