<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY SHARES LIFT NASDAQ, BUT DOW FALLS 74 POINTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ High-technology stocks powered the Nasdaq market to a
sizable gain Wednesday, but other major indexes were down as
investors sorted through a confusing barrage of information and
rumor.
</P>
<P>
   Some expressed fears that the dollar would skid further against
the yen, while others focused on a reassuring economic survey by
the Federal Reserve or on a partial rebound by the Dow Jones
industrial average after it fell to about 10,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's concern about money leaving our markets and going
abroad,'' said Tim Woolston, a portfolio manager at Boston
Advisors, referring to the consequences of the dollar's fall on
foreign exchange markets.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow closed at 10,524.07, a loss of 74.40 points, or 0.7
percent, but that was better than its earlier loss of 104.47
points, to 10,494.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty of the 30 Dow components lost ground, with Union Carbide,
Procter &AMP; Gamble, United Technologies and IBM each down around 2
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just haven't gone down enough to turn the buyers on,'' said
Alfred Goldman of A.G. Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fared somewhat better,
eking out a gain of 2.93 points, slightly more than 0.2 percent, to
1,310.51. But much of its strength was in the high-technology
sector. The broader malaise was reflected by a decline by a
majority of index stocks, 255, while 225 rose and 20 were
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Over the longer term, there has been ``an extremely broad-based
pullback,'' said Timothy M. Stevenson, a senior portfolio manager
at First Capital Group. More than half the S&AMP;P 500 companies show
declines for 1999, he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to a tabulation by Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, more
than 3,700 New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq stocks have shown an
average decline, unweighted by capitalization, of 24 percent from
their 52-week highs, producing what some are calling a ``stealth''
bear market.
</P>
<P>
   The bright spot Wednesday was the Nasdaq, which climbed 37.06
points, or 1.31 percent, to 2,858.16.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A better-than-expected profit report by 3Com Corp., the most
active issue of the day, helped send its shares up 1 5/16, to 28|,
and set a good tone for the computer-related sector. Microsoft rose
1 7/16, to 96 1/16; Qualcomm 7 13/16, to 190[; Yahoo 9 15/16, to
179{; Ebay 8{, to 149[, and America Online, 6[, to 91.
</P>
<P>
   Turnover on the Big Board swelled to 822.2 million from 785.3
million Tuesday as new 52-week lows swamped highs by 262 to 23.
Declining issues outnumbered advancing ones, 1,711 to 1,248.
</P>
</TEXT>
