<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A war of worlds _ and nerves
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Even world-class professionals who play with
clubs and balls to pay mortgages know that there's pressure in
regular golf tournaments and then there's Ryder Cup pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Regular tournament pressure can turn knees to Jell-O. Ryder Cup
pressure is a fist to the sternum and the inability to breathe _ a
fear that you might die standing over a putt, and the fear that you
might not.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1993 Ryder Cup at The Belfry in England, rookie Davis
Love III was so scared at the thought of hitting the first ball
that he was squirming with foursomes partner Tom Kite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to try and get out of it so bad,'' Love said
Wednesday at The Country Club. ``On the walk up to the first tee, I
told Tom, `Don't you think you'd be better hitting off the odd
holes?' He said, `What are you trying to do, get out of it?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time Davis teed off, he was a blithering idiot,'' Kite
said.
</P>
<P>
   Love then proceeded to blast a drive, as Kite recalls, ``10
miles down the first fairway.''
</P>
<P>
   The 24 participants of the 33rd Ryder Cup would pay a lot for
such a guarantee when the event begins Friday morning. If there's
such a thing as a root canal to the nervous system, this is it.
Teammates and nations are watching. And the event has evolved into
golf's War of the Worlds.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Maria Olazabal, a two-time Masters champ, never forgets the
numbness that enters his body on the tee box. In 1987, he hit the
opening shot for the Europeans at Muirfield Village.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that stands still is the shaft of the club, and
that is before you take the club out of the bag,'' said Olazabal, a
six-time participant. ``The rest, everything shakes _ hands, legs,
absolutely everything. And that's how it is. There is nothing you
can do to avoid that.''
</P>
<P>
   Scotland's Colin Montgomerie, who opened at Oak Hill, said it
was ``the worst I've ever felt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to tee the whole thing off at Oak Hill in 1995, and
that's as nervous as I want to be, thank you very much,''
Montgomerie said. ``I don't want to feel that again, because of the
expectation, having to hit the fairway and lucky enough doing so.
But I don't want to feel that pressure again.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweden's Jesper Parnevik said the pressure is worse as a
captain's pick. He remembered a snap hook from his first tee shot
at Valderrama two years ago. He's thankful he got the ball off the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something you can't really prepare yourself for the first
time you play in a Ryder Cup, because it's so much beyond any
tournament you play anywhere in the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With seven rookies on their team, the Europeans could be more
susceptible to the pressures. But last time, they won with five.
And it's the Americans who are trying not to get three-peated.
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal has tried to calm 19-year-old Sergio Garcia by
reminding him, and the other rookies, that it gets easier with age
and experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to be nervous on the first tee, just like you,''
Olazabal said.
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik and American Jeff Maggert say the pressure makes it a
struggle to play a normal game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're playing a regular tournament, you're just playing
for yourself,'' Olazabal said. ``Here, you're representing a
country. In our case, you're representing a continent, too. That
changes the whole picture.''
</P>
<P>
   And if you arrive with a troubled golf game?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when pressure turns into bad pressure, fear and
panic,'' Olazabal said, ``and you don't want to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
