u i BC-TAIWAN-QUAKE-ART-NYT &LR;      09-22 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-QUAKE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN SURVIVORS ASK WHAT COMES NEXT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TAIWAN-SCENE) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(md) 
 By CALVIN SIMS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAICHUNG, Taiwan _ As she slept early Tuesday morning, Chien
Tsai-ping heard a loud explosion that knocked her out of bed.
Bleeding from her head and clutching a cross around her neck, she
dragged herself down a staircase and toward the moonlight that was
shining through large rips in the walls below.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced that it was God who saved me,'' Ms. Chien said.
``It was my beliefs that led me to the light.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least 79 other residents of her neighborhood, Dakun, died
as this city near the epicenter of the devastating earthquake on
Tuesday suffered some of the worst casualties and damages.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was my home and my business for 20 years, and suddenly in
a few seconds it was totally destroyed,'' Ms. Chien said, pointing
to a lopsided building that seemed on the verge of collapse. ``What
am I supposed to do now?''
</P>
<P>
   That is a question that many quake victims are beginning to ask
themselves and their government as they begin to face a long and
painful process of rebuilding their shattered lives.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday, the death toll had risen past 2,000, with an
additional 4,400 people injured and 2,600 believed still trapped in
the rubble, the government said.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of thousands are homeless, and although electric power
was restored to most of the capital, Taipei, many communities in
northern and central Taiwan remain blacked out.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chien is living in a military shelter down the street from
her house, which is uninhabitable. At the shelter, which provides
three meals a day, she sleeps on the floor in a large tent with 100
other people.
</P>
<P>
   Tsai Chin-wang, a street vendor and Ms. Chien's neighbor, said
although he was grateful that his wife and three children had
survived the quake's demolition of their house with them in it, he
wondered whether his family could survive the rigors of living in a
shelter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The food is good, but we are basically sleeping outdoors on
grounds, and we have no bathrooms and no privacy,'' Tsai said.
``This is no way to raise a family.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Liao, who moved his family into the shelter on Tuesday,
said, ``The government needs to do something to help us.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the army, Linda Fang, said that the military
shelters were meant to be temporary and that many residents were
depressed because their lives had been ``turned upside down'' and
they were uncertain what the future holds.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, thousands were left homeless by the quake and others
fearful of the strong aftershocks are living in tents in parks and
playgrounds across the island.
</P>
<P>
   After three strong aftershocks startled Taiwan Wednesday
morning, Khu Mu-hsiang found cracks in his apartment walls and
decided to move his family into a tent at Soowai Elementary School,
across the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very scary, and we are taking no chances,'' said Khu, who
arrived prepared with a portable radio, a flashlight and a small
cooking stove. ``My mother's house has already collapsed.''
</P>
<P>
   Many residents have nowhere to go. In Puli, in Nantau County,
also near the epicenter, the local government said 80,000 people
would spend the night in the streets because the earthquake had
destroyed their housing. Many inexpensive motels and government
shelters were filled to capacity.
</P>
<P>
   National and local officials said that they were aware of the
difficulties that survivors faced and that they were taking steps
to work on them. But the officials said their first priority was to
locate and rescue people who were pinned in the debris.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, an international group of earthquake specialists,
including some from the United States, Russia, Japan and Israel,
began assisting in the rescue operation. Two U.S. rescuers found a
man in a caved-in apartment building in Touliu.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was pretty glad to see us,'' said Capt. Michael Reilly, one
of the U.S. workers who took four sniffing dogs to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous countries have promised to provide food and other
assistance, including China. Wednesday, the government thanked
Beijing for its offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be a good beginning to improving ties,'' said Su
Chi, chairman of the Taiwan government Mainland Affairs Council,
which oversees relations with Beijing. ``I hope we can work on this
basis and make efforts together to build up stable and peaceful
relations.''
</P>
<P>
   Some local governments have acted on their own to ease the
victims' pain. In Taipei, the municipal government is paying for
more than 100 former residents of the collapsed Sungshan Hotel to
stay at other hotels in the area.
</P>
<P>
   But the growing number of bodies being recovered has overwhelmed
local governments, which are running out of body bags. Hospital
morgues have run out of room to store the bodies properly and are
placing them at roadsides taped in blue plastic sheets. Without
proper refrigeration in the September heat, the bodies are starting
to decompose, releasing foul odors.
</P>
<P>
   With widespread power shortages, even the bodies in morgues were
starting to decay. Many distressed relatives have been peering
through the plastic body bags to identify relatives, and some have
been delivering bags of ice to help preserve the bodies of their
loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the police in Taichung, Richard Wu, said most
bodies would eventually be cremated, in accordance with the
families' wishes. He said cremations had been delayed because the
local government was waiting for the prosecutor's office to examine
the bodies and ascertain that no foul play was involved in the
deaths.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
