<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gangs manage to get along in N.C. shelter
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TARBORO, N.C. _ Inside Tarboro High School, a hand-written
poster challenges the rumor that cases of tuberculosis have cropped
up among evacuees from Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteer Hattie Stocks quickly challenges another. ``There is
no rioting here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the week since dangerous flooding prompted officials to turn
this low-slung brick high school into one of eastern North
Carolina's biggest emergency shelters, officials have turned this
last-resort stop into liveable quarters for more than 2,500 people.
</P>
<P>
   It's been rough, shelter manager Dave Stone said, but it hasn't
been as bad as rumors around Tarboro have made it. There have been
no fights between gang members from Tarboro and neighboring
Princeville, no arrests, no altercations that shelter officials
couldn't handle, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a community here for people who have lost their
homes,'' Tarboro police officer Bruce Edwards said. ``Tempers are
going to flare.''
</P>
<P>
   It helps that two dozen law enforcement officers _ local police,
National Guardsmen, state Alcohol Law Enforcement agents _ are
patrolling the grounds and the hallways lined by purple lockers.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they're looking for signals of gang activity, such
as young men wearing bandanas around their heads or hanging from
pockets. Tuesday, Stone watched as two young men approached three
others in a hallway. After pausing and exchanging looks, they moved
along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shelters are a neutral site,'' Stone said. ``We have security
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, some people scuffled for clothing being
tossed from the back of a rental truck. ``That's about the closest
thing to violence we've seen,'' said Kip Aldridge, a North Carolina
Alcohol Law Enforcement agent.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, clothing and other supplies were pouring into the
school, and people lined up, waiting to pick through garments to
replace ones they had worn for several days.
</P>
<P>
   Among the many organizations providing help to storm victims is
Atlanta-based Heel Quik, which conducts annual drives to collect
and repair shoes for homeless people.
</P>
<P>
   All of Edgecombe County's water supply is considered unusable,
so shelter residents use portable toilets and showers, nippy with
dipping temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   People are sleeping on cots and mats in the gymnasium, or in
their vehicles parked in the jam-packed lots. On Wednesday, a stiff
breeze buffeted five gray tents identified as ``privacy shelters,''
tucked along a brick wall.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross has set up health services in Room 106 where,
during normal times, students learn Spanish. In the main office,
medical supplies line the counter.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we use the portable toilets, we know we will be going
home in three days,'' said Linda Hester, one of two dozen Southern
Baptist Convention volunteers from Georgia. ``How would you like to
know there is no time limit on how long you might stay?''
</P>
<P>
   Young boys picked up garbage on the grounds. One of them,
11-year-old Anthony Whitehead, said he's not yet comfortable after
spending a week at the shelter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sleeping around a lot of people I don't know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a makeshift stab at home cooking, the Georgia volunteers
cooked chicken and dumplings on gas burners under tents. People
started moving through the lines by 11 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   It was nourishment and, for some, a distraction after days away
from home _ and many more to come.
</P>
<P>
   Flooded from her Tarboro home, Helen Burton, 38, expects to
remain in the shelter until she arranges more permanent housing.
``I'm upset, but there is nothing I can do about it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
