<HEADER>
A2326 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CHINA-NUKE-640&AMP;ADD-NY     09-22 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-NUKE-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO AND FEEH ORDER FBI TO BROADEN INQUIRY INTO CHINESE ESPIONAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JAMES RISEN and DAVID JOHNSTON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno and FBI Director Louis
Freeh have ordered federal agents to broaden their investigation
into evidence of Chinese nuclear espionage, moving far beyond the
government's earlier scrutiny of a scientist fired from Los Alamos
National Laboratory, government officials said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The widened inquiry ordered by Reno and Freeh will include
reopening a fundamental debate of whether American nuclear secrets
were stolen and, if so, where and how the theft may have occurred,
law-enforcement officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Other federal officials said the new effort is a tacit
acknowledgment that the initial federal espionage investigation of
Los Alamos was mishandled. The debate over the inquiry has badly
frayed relations between law-enforcement and Energy Department
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities have been buffeted by complaints about the
conduct of the investigation. A presidential review board and
others have argued that the FBI and Energy Department focused
prematurely on Wen Ho Lee, a Taiwan-born scientist dismissed from
the New Mexico laboratory in March for alleged security violations.
</P>
<P>
   And Republicans in Congress have said that the bureau failed to
move aggressively enough to investigate Lee, and have also attacked
the Justice Department for rejecting the bureau's repeated requests
to wiretap and electronically monitor Lee early in its
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Now, officials said, the government will go back to ``ground
zero'' to conduct a broader probe of the evidence that China
obtained secret design information about America's most advanced
nuclear warhead, the W-88.
</P>
<P>
   Some U.S. intelligence officials now say that classified
information on the W-88 that was apparently obtained by the Chinese
was available at many other government installations and at defense
contractors in addition to the Los Alamos design laboratory where
it originated.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the FBI will conduct a more thorough investigation
of the evidence of espionage and search for alternative
explanations of what happened. The bureau was likely to investigate
military and contractor facilities to see if it can find another
possible source of the information besides Los Alamos, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet officials acknowledged that the FBI does not yet have any
new suspects who have become the targets of their espionage probe.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how the decision to re-open the bureau's espionage
investigation will affect the government's decision whether to
prosecute Lee on charges that he mishandled classified materials, a
lesser charge than espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials said that Reno and Freeh coordinated their
decision to broaden the inquiry with the U.S. attorney for New
Mexico, John Kelly. Officials say Kelly has aggressively advocated
prosecuting Lee in New Mexico over his allegedly unauthorized
transfers of computer codes containing nuclear secrets from the
lab's classified computer network into an unclassified system.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the Energy Department, the FBI, the Justice
Department and Kelly's office met two weeks ago to reach an
agreement on how much classified material would be available to
prosecutors from the Energy Department for use as evidence in a
possible trial of Lee. Officials say progress has been made among
the agencies on the issue, but Energy Secretary Bill Richardson has
not made a final decision. Reno must give her approval before any
prosecution can go forward.
</P>
<P>
   Lee has denied that he spied for China, and has said that he was
singled out by investigators because he is a Chinese-American. He
has acknowledged that he downloaded classified computer codes, but
said that he did so as a routine part of his job at Los Alamos to
protect the information from computer crashes. Lee has not been
charged with any crime.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The government's investigation of China's apparent theft of
nuclear secrets has been under fire ever since the case became
public in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence that China stole classified design information from the
W-88 led the Energy Department and the bureau to begin a
preliminary inquiry into the matter in 1995, and by June 1996, the
FBI had opened a full criminal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The initial inquiry looked at six Energy Department facilities,
including Los Alamos where the W-88 warhead were designed.
Archivists at Los Alamos told Energy Department officials that the
most important documents on the W-88 had not been distributed
beyond Los Alamos in the time when investigators believed the
espionage had occurred.
</P>
<P>
   One of the key pieces of evidence in the probe was a Chinese
government document, dated 1988, that included classified material
about the W-88 and which officials said they determined could not
have come from any public source.
</P>
<P>
   That convinced investigators that the espionage had occurred
between 1984, when the final design for the W-88 was approved, and
1988, when the Chinese document was dated.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators came up with a list of about a dozen suspects who
had access to the information, had traveled to China or had other
contacts with Chinese scientists, and for whom security concerns
had already been raised.
</P>
<P>
   But the FBI quickly focused on Lee, with whom they had
maintained a long and complicated relationship. Lee had previously
been both investigated by the bureau and had cooperated with it in
an investigation. He had also provided information, apparently
about Chinese scientists visiting Los Alamos, to the CIA.
</P>
<P>
   Lee was already being investigated by the bureau when the
nuclear weapons inquiry began. In November 1995, the bureau
suspended that previous investigation and instead began to look at
Lee as part of the weapons case, according to an August report
issued by the Republican chairman and ranking Democrat on the
Senate Governmental Affairs Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But the decision to focus so early in the investigation on Lee
has come under mounting criticism in recent months, from within the
government, from Lee's lawyer, Mark Holscher, in Los Angeles, and
from other outside critics. Now, officials say that they have
determined that the classified information included in the 1988
Chinese document had been distributed widely to other government
facilities and contractors by 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said on Wednesday that the classified material was
potentially available at hundreds of facilities by that time,
underscoring the belief that investigators focused too quickly on
Los Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   Lee first came to the FBI's attention as early as 1982, after
the government recorded a telephone call he made to a scientist who
had been dismissed from Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory in
connection with an earlier investigation of China's theft of U.S.
neutron bomb secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Lee came under suspicion again as a result of a 1994 incident
that occurred while he was meeting with visiting Chinese nuclear
weapons scientists at Los Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI was told that Lee was embraced by Dr. Side Hu, a leading
scientist in China's nuclear weapons program, who then made it
clear to others in the meeting that Lee had been helpful to China's
nuclear program. The bureau began a counter-intelligence probe as a
result of that incident, which was later merged into the W-88
investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 2056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0419 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2327 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SPRINT-MARKETPLACE-NY     09-22 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: SPRINT'S FOREIGN-ENTANGLEMENT LESSON 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What in the world, literally, is going on with Sprint Corp. and
its Global One venture with France Telecom and Deutsche Telekom of
Germany?
</P>
<P>
   As other big U.S. telecommunications companies, including AT&AMP;T
and Bell Atlantic have forged new alliances with foreign partners
in recent weeks, that old question once again hangs in the air.
</P>
<P>
   It has been obvious since the spring that Global One is on the
rocks, riven by competing priorities, an absence of coordination
and an unsurprising tension between German and French executives.
Just about everyone in the communications business, including many
executives involved in Global One, thought the troubled partnership
would be resolved or dissolved by now.
</P>
<P>
   Neither has happened. Propelled, perhaps, by frustration, no
less a Global One figure than Michel Bon, France Telecom's
chairman, has on separate occasions this month described the
situation as ``impossible'' and ``bedlam.'' Indeed, the three
companies have recently said they are discussing ways to end the
partnership.
</P>
<P>
   The reason the circus has run so long appears to be that Global
One's fate has depended in large part on whether Sprint, with its
market value of $47 billion, is acquired outright by Deutsche
Telekom, which already owns a 10 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   According to executives close to the talks, Sprint conducted
extensive discussions with Deutsche Telekom during the summer about
such an acquisition. But those same executives say that the talks
have cooled significantly in recent weeks and may have hit a
roadblock altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to the companies said that MCI Worldcom Inc.
has seriously considered a bid for Sprint. Such a deal would bring
MCI Worldcom, the No. 2 U.S. long-distance carrier, closer to AT&AMP;T
in the long-distance market; Sprint's national wireless operation
would also fill a hole in MCI Worldcom's portfolio. Sprint may have
backed away from Deutsche Telekom to assess MCI Worldcom's
interest, the executives said.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the breakdown of the Deutsche Telekom merger talks
appears to be an attempt to separate those discussions from the
Global One negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The two issues are linked because the German and French
companies each own 10 percent of Sprint, and each has a seat on
Sprint's board. Neither company may raise its stake in Sprint
without the consent of Sprint management.
</P>
<P>
   More important, even if Sprint were to invite Deutsche Telekom
to raise its stake, France Telecom would be entitled to increase
its own stake by an identical amount. The arrangement gives France
Telecom an effective, if not explicit, veto over any Deutsche
Telekom acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   That power has proved crucial in at least two ways, and may even
have fueled the discord within Global One, which had about $1.1
billion in revenue last year.
</P>
<P>
   According to executives close to Global One, Deutsche Telekom
was interested in acquiring Sprint last winter. France Telecom
vetoed it, perhaps even before Sprint knew of Deutsche Telekom's
interest.
</P>
<P>
   So, the executives said, when Ron Sommer, Deutsche Telekom's
chairman, decided to bid for Telecom Italia, Italy's dominant phone
company, this spring, he did not inform France Telecom. Sommer was
piqued, they said, and perhaps fearful that France Telecom would
try to block the Telecom Italia move as it had his earlier
ambitions for Sprint. The German and French companies have a
venture in Italy that competes against Telecom Italia.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom's bid for the Italian carrier, coupled with the
lack of advance notice, sent Bon into a rage, executives close to
the alliance said. France Telecom sued Deutsche Telekom, and the
collapse of Global One seemed all but certain.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint, Deutsche Telekom and France Telecom all declined to
comment Wednesday. But Klaus Czerwinski, a Global One spokesman,
said, ``It is very unlikely that Deutsche Telekom and France
Telecom will stay in one alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   The three partners are now haggling over Global One's
international network and customers. France Telecom wants those
assets for itself, and has been insisting on them as the price for
its approval of any acquisition of Sprint by Deutsche Telekom,
executives close to the alliance said.
</P>
<P>
   For Sprint, the executives said, the loss of the Global One
assets would significantly undermine the argument for merging with
Deutsche Telekom in the first place: to form an international
communications powerhouse with operations beyond Germany and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street speculation that such a deal is in the works has
raised Sprint shares from a low of $42.625 on Sept. 1 to to
$54.4375 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom appears less interested in the Global One
assets than either its French or U.S. partners are. In fact, it may
form an international operation on its own, according to executives
close to Global One, by acquiring either a big international
carrier like Global Crossing Ltd. of Bermuda or Equant NV of the
Netherlands, or a string of smaller carriers like RSL
Communications Ltd. of Bermuda and Global Telesystems Group.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, though, no partner wants to walk away from Global One
empty-handed. And as the companies circle each other, the real
losers may be Global One's sales staff.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the recent turmoil among the partners has not
made the Global One operation any more disjointed than it was
already. But some executives close to the alliance say that some of
the big multinational companies that are the venture's intended
clients have clearly become wary of signing up with an alliance
distinguished chiefly by infighting.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint seems especially cognizant of the problem, appearing
willing to put acquisition talk aside to deal with Global One
first. According to people close to the venture, William T. Esrey,
Sprint's chairman, has called a special board meeting for next week
at which he intends to read the riot act to Deutsche Telekom and
France Telecom, encouraging them to resolve their differences in
the interest of at least preserving Global One as a viable
commercial entity.
</P>
<P>
   The three companies say they intend to fix the Global One
problem by year's end. If they do not, some alliance executives
fear, there may not be much of a Global One to fix.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
