u i BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BELGRADE-N     09-22 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BELGRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STREET PROTESTS AGAINST MILOSEVIC DRAW FEWER SUPPORTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (md) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Street protests intended to oust Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic appeared to falter on their second
day, giving some comfort to a government that was deeply shaken by
the loss of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Some 7,000 people turned out in fine weather for the rally here
in the capital, compared to some 20,000 on Tuesday. In Nis, about
8,000 came, compared with 20,000 the day before; in Kragujevac,
5,000 came, half of Tuesday's total. In Novi Sad, 5,000 came,
compared with some 7,000.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Alliance for Change, a loose coalition of
opposition parties dominated by the Democratic Party of Zoran
Djindjic, insisted Wednesday night that the rallies and the
campaign to oust Milosevic would continue.
</P>
<P>
   The 88-day-long protests of the winter of 1996-97 also started
small, they said, and built slowly to large numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But the starting time for Thursday's rally was moved up two
hours, to 4 p.m., to catch people in town before they head home,
and some officials said there were already discussions of how to
play down the importance of the rallies, in order not to discredit
the Alliance for Change.
</P>
<P>
   Djindjic, speaking Wednesday at the Belgrade rally, said
somewhat plaintively: ``We are being asked whether the people have
any more energy'' for the protests after 10 years of hardship and
war under Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Loss of energy, he said, ``is natural. But if the people don't
find this energy we are doomed. This is the last battle, not just
for our generation, but for our children and grandchildren. We have
no other option but to be here every day, rain or sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Alliance for Change officials said later that they might move
more quickly to announce an alternative, transitional government,
to be headed by the respected former central bank governor,
Dragoslav Avramovic, 79, or move to more confrontational tactics,
like a general strike or road blockages, or an agreement by
opposition-controlled cities to stop recognizing the authority of
Milosevic's government.
</P>
<P>
   And they seemed, in comments Wednesday, to be moving closer to
the idea of using the rallies to press for early elections under
fair conditions, the route favored by the largest opposition party,
the Serbian Renewal Movement, which has dissociated itself from
these rallies in the hope that they will fail.
</P>
<P>
   The movement's leader, Vuk Draskovic, has said that if the
opposition parties could agree on conditions for a free and fair
ballot, he would join the protests in order to press Milosevic to
call elections. The Alliance for Change, however, has insisted that
Milosevic resign first.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, however, Djindjic said that Milosevic would
steal any election unless he were forced, by mass street
demonstrations, to organize a truly fair vote. And Avramovic, in
his speech, said that he will try to reach an agreement with other
opposition parties on demands for free and fair elections and the
country's democratization.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, Avramovic is clearly trying to unite the
opposition, understanding that without Draskovic, however disliked
he may be by the Alliance for Change, the effort is likely to fail.
</P>
<P>
   There is an ongoing round table discussion among opposition
parties to try to agree on conditions for a fair election _
Djindjic boycotted 1997 elections as unfair, acting then against
U.S. advice, while Draskovic took part, lending them legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   But there is little indication that the Milosevic government
feels any need just now to give anything to the opposition, which
remains divided.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Democratic Party official said despairingly Wednesday
night: ``Everybody knows they have empty refrigerators, empty
factories, empty pockets and an empty life. No one wants this
Milosevic government, but they're afraid to push it out. They want
someone else to do it _ they want me to do it. But I can't do it by
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Bratislav Grubacic, an independent analyst close to Djindjic,
noted Wednesday that the numbers of people swelled for a post-rally
march with whistles past state television, Parliament and the state
newspaper Politika. ``People want action, not these boring
speeches,'' he said. ``People seem to be waiting for someone to
throw the first stone.''
</P>
<P>
   While the police stayed in the background in Belgrade and major
cities, they banned rallies planned for Bor and Cacak, saying that
they lacked necessary documents.
</P>
<P>
   State television took a gloating tone as it described the
opposition's lack of support, though it also gave artificially low
turnout figures. It continued its attack on the Alliance for Change
for being American puppets, in the pay of Washington, who were
acting unpatriotically in order to finish what NATO started with
its bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   State television calls the Alliance for Change the ``Alliance
for NATO'' and the rallies for Milosevic's ouster ``a continuing of
the aggression by other means.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 2058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
