u i BC-RUSSIA-HEARINGS-NYT &LR;      09-22 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-HEARINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAIRMAN ADMITS BANK'S `LAPSE' IN JUDGMENT IN RUSSIAN LAUNDERING
CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Slugged earlier as RUSSIA-CONGRESS; With RUSSIA-BANK) 
(nk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The chairman of the Bank of New York said Wednesday
that suspicious activity in nine accounts at the core of the
Russian money laundering scandal was not stopped because the
accounts were held by the husband of a highly regarded bank
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas A. Renyi, the chairman and chief executive, told
lawmakers that allowing the accounts held by Peter Berlin, a
Russian-born businessman who is married to a bank vice president,
Lucy Edwards, to remain ``open and active without sufficient
questioning was a lapse on the part of the Bank.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, he said, the activity in the accounts was
``unremarkable.'' But when the flow of money through the accounts
jumped sharply, lower-level bank supervisors who monitored the
activity failed to notify their superiors, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Questions were not pursued with sufficient vigor or
follow-through, and the questioners relied too heavily on the fact
that Mr. Berlin was married to a well-regarded bank officer,''
Renyi said. ``They did not see the obvious conflict that we might
see in hindsight.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past three years, Renyi said $7.5 billion had flowed
through accounts Berlin opened in 1996, in the name of a company
called Benex. Investigators say that some of the money may be from
legitimate and legal transactions, but they also say they suspect
that billions of dollars may have come from organized crime,
corporate embezzlement and, possibly, diverted foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
   The bank has been cooperating in the investigation by the FBI
for a year. Neither it nor any of its employees has been formally
charged with any wrongdoing. However, the bank has fired two
employees, including Ms. Edwards, and suspended a third. Ms.
Edwards and her husband have denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Renyi's testimony capped a second day of hearings by the House
Banking Committee into allegations of Russian corruption and money
laundering. The Bank of New York has been the leading American bank
in Moscow specializing in international services for Russian banks
and businesses. It was widely used to handle payments between
Russian companies and foreign suppliers, and by people who wanted
to send money out of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Renyi said the bank conducts business with about 160 Russian
banks, and that $3.7 billion a day in transactions flowed through
accounts that Russian banks maintain at the Bank of New York, a
small fraction of the $600 billion a day from all of the bank's
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   In light of the recent disclosures, Renyi said the bank was
reviewing whether to continue its business with Russian banks.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony and in responses to questions, Renyi sought to
portray the bank, founded in 1784 by Alexander Hamilton, as a
victim of poor judgment by low-level employees and a global
payments system that puts priority on speed rather than knowing
whether the electronic money transfers are legal.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers sounded dubious. ``The fact an incident would occur at
such a respected bank is frightening to me,'' said Rep. Carolyn
Maloney, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   And while Renyi was careful not to accuse Ms. Edwards of any
wrongdoing, he seemed to be drawing a legal curtain between her and
the bank. Ms. Edwards, who worked in London, was dismissed shortly
after the federal inquiry became public last month, for ``gross
misconduct,'' according to a person with direct knowledge of her
dismissal, including falsification of bank records and for never
telling the bank that she was married to Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Renyi's remarks Wednesday marked the first time that a senior
bank official attributed the bank's lax response to the fact some
employees were comforted by the fact that Ms. Edwards was married
to Berlin, and had referred the accounts to the bank.
</P>
<P>
   But a person with knowledge of the dismissal said the bank was
offering two contrasting stories: Ms. Edwards had failed to
disclose her marriage on an official bank form she submitted
annually, but some bank employees were nonetheless aware that her
husband was Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning from Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, who is chairman
of the committee, Renyi also confirmed reports that a son-in-law of
Russia President Boris Yeltsin had assets in accounts at the bank's
branch in the Cayman Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators say they are examining the accounts in
their widening money-laundering inquiry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
