<HEADER>
A2332 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     09-22 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ER' PRODUCER DELIVERS A SPINOFF _ STAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After making ``ER'' a respected drama and a ratings winner,
producer John Wells has been trying to duplicate the creative magic
elsewhere, with little success. ``Trinity,'' a cop-based family
drama, did not win respect or ratings last season and was shown the
door. This year, Wells got a hand in NBC's ``The West Wing'' as an
executive producer (although it's considered Aaron Sorkin's baby),
and two more dramas are reportedly waiting on deck.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, he revisits his ``ER'' stomping grounds to introduce
yet another series, and in a Hollywood where you're only as good as
the gap between hits, it's not surprising that ``Third Watch'' is
as close to an ``ER'' spinoff as it can be, without Wells and NBC
actually calling it one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Third Watch,'' which will air Sundays, is like ``ER: Life on
the Street.'' It focuses on firefighters, paramedics and cops who
work the 3-to-11 p.m. shift. You've seen these folks before. These
are the no-name heroes who zip in and out of ``ER,'' barking orders
about vital signs. Now we get them front and center and see how
they patch up the injured before wheeling them through hospital
corridors.
</P>
<P>
   Wells has concocted another series that moves like a runaway
freight train, crunching everything in its way. Story lines are
soapy and layered, and there's a similar multiple-lead character
structure. Michael Beach, whom you'll remember as Jeanie Boulet's
HIV-positive ex-husband on ``ER,'' seems to be in the position to
serve as the show's center. That would be refreshing, particularly
this season, considering all the fuss over the lack of minority
leads.
</P>
<P>
   Beach plays a paramedic, a nurturer, the levelheaded team leader
called ``Doc.'' Bobby Cannavale and Kim Raver are the others, and
both are holdovers from Wells' ``Trinity.'' Everyone else is
relatively unknown and will have to fend for themselves in getting
good story lines.
</P>
<P>
   That shouldn't be a problem. As it was in the early days of
``ER,'' narrative is pared to the bare essentials. There are
veteran cops, green rookies, hotheads. A paramedic in love with
another paramedic whose ex-husband works with them. ``Why did we
break up anyhow?'' he wants to know.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of talk. Talk that's quick and terse and to the
point since, well, these people rarely have time.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran cop to rookie: ``What are we doing out here?''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie: ``Enforcing the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran: ``No. We're solving problems. We go from job to job,
solving problems as quickly as we can. Then we come up, go to
another problem.''
</P>
<P>
   In the opening episode alone, a woman drops her baby from a
burning high-rise apartment building, a paramedic is sprayed with
gunfire, a woman gives birth on a subway train, a paramedic rushes
to her ambulance shouting, ``I love this job.''
</P>
<P>
   Because so much of ``Third Watch'' is borrowed, there are no
stylistic breakthroughs, and the dialogue is straight from the
Heros' Handbook. It's entertaining, at least. Which is more than
half the battle in a season in which you'll be shocked as to what
is being passed off as such. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also new Thursday: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Stark Raving Mad''
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Neil Patrick Harris, Tony Shalhoub
</P>
<P>
   Eccentric bestselling horror writer Ian Stark (Shalhoub from
``Wings'') is driving his neurotic editor (''Doogie Howser M.D.'s''
Harris) crazy. How? Practical jokes, mostly. And touching him. Like
putting his hand on his shoulder. Harris' Henry McNeely is a
bookish little creep who can't handle germs or anything else.
</P>
<P>
   It's a run-of-the-mill buddy comedy that will have to get much
better than its pilot to survive three years, which is how long NBC
Thursday-night comedies seem to last these days. One year for NBC
to notice that it's a clunker, another year while it switches to
another night, and a third year for it to get pummeled in the
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stark Raving Mad'' could also refer to anyone who decides to
make this ``must see TV.'' Do yourself a favor and watch ``Action''
on Fox.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins covers television for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) .MDUL/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
