<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-THIRDWATCH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLID `THIRD WATCH' SUFFERS AN ABUNDANCE OF DEJA VU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Wells, one of the creative honchos behind the magic of
``ER,'' tried to duplicate it last season with ``Trinity,'' an
ensemble drama about an Irish-American family. ``Trinity'' sank
quickly in a puddle of Celtic melancholia, but Wells is obviously
undeterred. This season, his production company is back with two
more ensemble pieces for NBC: Aaron Sorkin's ``The West Wing,''
which premiered Wednesday night, and his own ``Third Watch,''
debuting Thursday at 10 in the coveted ``ER'' slot before moving to
Sunday nights at 8 this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   An ambitious combination of ``ER'' and ``Hill Street Blues,''
``Third Watch'' encompasses the lives of paramedics, firefighters
and police officers staffing the 3-to-11 p.m. shift in New York
City. The cast is solid, the writing OK, but the first two episodes
of ``Third Watch'' really don't take us anywhere we haven't been
before. I mean, who doesn't know that public-safety work in the big
city is dangerous? People get shot, spouses worry, partners sulk,
junkies squeal, etc.
</P>
<P>
   As ensemble dramas go, ``Third Watch'' isn't bad, but it's
nothing special. The crucial task for Wells and his collaborators
will be making us care about this large group of people _ the core
ensemble totals nine _ the way we've come to embrace the detectives
on ``NYPD Blue,'' the doctors and nurses on ``ER,'' the lawyers on
``The Practice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Third Watch'' attempts to do it by emphasizing the choices
people make every day _ decisions made unconsciously at times, but
often freighted with huge implications. It might be as simple as
entering a building, turning right to avoid crossing traffic, going
out for coffee. One second, things are normal; the next second, a
life is changed forever.
</P>
<P>
   Early favorites on the likability meter are Monte ``Doc'' Parker
(Michael Beach), John ``Sully'' Sullivan (Skipp Sudduth) and Faith
Yokas (Molly Price). Parker is a paramedic, Sullivan and Yokas are
police officers. Together, they form the moral compass of the
group, but while their needle may be pointing to right choices, the
possibility remains that viewers of America, trudging through a
forest of more than 40 new shows, will encounter ``Third Watch''
and say, ``Been there, done that.''
</P>
<P>
   For someone who's lost, that's a good thing. But for someone
seeking new and different, it's an easy choice.
</P>
<P>
   Third Watch. Hourlong ensemble drama about New York City police
officers, paramedics and firefighters working the 3-11 p.m. shift.
Starring Michael Beach, Coby Bell, Bobby Cannavale, Eddie Cibrian,
Molly Price, Kim Raver, Anthony Ruivivar, Skipp Sudduth and Jason
Wiles. Season premiere Thursday night on NBC; show moves to its
regular day Sunday. Parental guideline rating: TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
