<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKING-RUSSIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANK EXECUTIVE ADMITS TO `LAPSE' IN WAKE OF MONEY-LAUNDERING
ACCUSATIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANDREW BROMAN 
Houston Chronicle Washington Bureau 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Bank of New York's top executive acknowledged
Wednesday that ``a lapse'' by the bank enabled Russian businessmen
to funnel several billion dollars through several accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Russian businesses and individuals, some allegedly linked to
organized crime, are suspected of channeling as much as $10 billion
through the bank, and the FBI and Treasury departments are
investigating the case.
</P>
<P>
   Large volumes of money that moved through the bank over the past
three years drew ``red flags,'' bank president Thomas Renyi told
the House Banking Committee, which is holding hearings on the
allegations. ``But the questions (about the account) were not
pursued with sufficient vigor or follow-through,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Renyi mostly defended the bank, emphasizing it has not been
charged with any wrongdoing. ``No relevant authorities have
asserted that the Bank of New York has engaged in money laundering
or violated any other law,'' he said. ``Neither the bank nor any of
its customers have lost any money as a result of the activities in
question.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Attorney General James Robinson, who spoke before
Renyi did at the hearing, said he could not comment on the case.
``This has been and will continue to be a complex and painstaking
investigation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Allegations of corruption broke one month ago, after federal
authorities discovered about $4.2 billion was funneled through
several accounts last year. A top executive, Lucy Edwards, helped
set up the accounts for her husband, Peter Berlin, a Russian who
represented himself as a small-businessman working out of New York,
according to Renyi.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have contacted employees involved in the case,
Renyi acknowledged Wednesday, but no charges have been filed. So
far, the firm fired Edwards and suspended one other employee.
</P>
<P>
   Since the scandal broke, the Bank of New York and government
officials have fashioned new anti-money laundering measures, aimed
to keep better track of foreign businesses and individual bank
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns that money from the International Monetary Fund was
diverted to the Bank of New York has prompted calls for tighter
controls on the way banks do business with foreign correspondents.
Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said Tuesday no information has
surfaced that proves IMF funds were moved to the New York Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Summers also told the committee that the United States will urge
withholding international loans from Russia until its leaders
implement more reforms to curb money laundering.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on the general state of Russian crime, Robinson said
current law has fallen behind the pace and ability of crime
organizations to launder money. One problem is that ``only a very
limited number of foreign offenses are now qualified as specified
unlawful activities,'' he said. Current laws, for example, do not
cover public corruption against foreign governments, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration Thursday will introduce a bill, which
Robinson said would enable federal prosecutors to gain more access
to foreign business records and improve the government's ability to
prosecute banks that knowingly accept criminal money.
</P>
<P>
   Renyi cautioned the government not to overreact to this
particular case. The bank has developed internal programs to thwart
criminal-related transactions, he said. A new Anti-Money Laundering
Committee, for example, reviews unusual account activity and
reports directly to the bank's board of directors. The bank now
works with outside consultants to monitor the flow of funds through
the bank.
</P>
<P>
   If lawmakers craft too strict of laws, Renyi said foreign banks
may ``simply drive would-be wrongdoers to less stringent points of
entry into the system,'' he said. ``Any policy action that would
reduce the importance and attractiveness of the U.S. dollar as the
currency of choice for international trade ... would place the
United States at a competitive disadvantage.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
