<HEADER>
A2343 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-MD-HORMONE-NYT &LR;      09-22 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MD-HORMONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS TURN MARROW INTO MUSCLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In unexpected testimony to the versatility of the body's cells,
researchers have found they can make bone marrow cells turn into
muscle, causing mice with muscular dystrophy to produce correctly
working muscle cells. The experiment suggests that a form of bone
marrow transplant _ a well established surgical procedure _ could
in principle treat patients with a variety of diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate relevance of the new result is for muscular
dystrophy, a set of diseases said by the Muscular Dystrophy
Association to affect 250,000 Americans. Researchers have tried to
treat the disease with injections of normal muscle cells from a
relative, but the cells do not spread beyond the site of injection.
</P>
<P>
   In a report the Thursday issue of the journal Nature, biologists
from Children's Hospital in Boston say they gave bone marrow
transplants from normal mice to dystrophic mice, and that 12 weeks
later about 10 percent of the muscle fibers in the diseased animals
were making the correct form of dystrophin, the protein that is
genetically defective in Duchenne's muscular dystrophy.
</P>
<P>
   The treated mice did not appear stronger, said Dr. Louis M.
Kunkel, one of the authors of the research, because a 10 percent
replacement is not therapeutically useful. But Kunkel and his
colleague, Dr. Richard C. Mulligan, believe their work suggests
ways of developing possible treatments. That view is shared by
other experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The integration of these cells with the muscle cells is a
great finding because it really does open up the possibility of
therapy for these patients,'' said Dr. Mark F. Pittenger, a
biologist at Osiris Therapeutics in Baltimore who is working on
muscle replacement techniques.
</P>
<P>
   The new finding extends the fast growing body of knowledge about
stem cells, the long hidden source of the body's ability to renew
and repair its tissues. Unlike mature cells, which are permanently
committed to their fate, stem cells can both renew themselves as
well as create new cells of whatever tissue they belong to.
</P>
<P>
   Mulligan said that a colleague, Dr. Margaret A. Goodell, learned
through a lucky discovery five years ago how to isolate a special
sub-population of the bone marrow stem cells that form the blood
system. These cells may be ancestral to the ordinary bone marrow
stem cells and thus possess greater versatility, though this has
not been proved.
</P>
<P>
   It is these presumed ancestral bone marrow stem cells that were
used to treat the dystrophic mice, which are animals whose
dystrophin gene has been removed so as to mimic the human
condition.
</P>
<P>
   In a parallel experiment, the researchers also used Dr.
Goodell's technique to isolate ancestral-type stem cells from
muscle. The muscle-derived stem cells could also repopulate both
the bone marrow and muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Many details of this complex experiment have yet to be worked
out, such as the exact relationship between the ancestral cells
derived from bone marrow and from muscle, and their relationship to
mesenchymal stem cells, the known progenitor of muscle. Pittenger
said he believed the ancestral-type cells must first develop into
mesenchymal stem cells before forming muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Both Kunkel and Mulligan hope to develop treatments for muscular
dystrophy, though in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   Kunkel, who has been studying muscular dystrophy for 18 years,
succeeded in isolating the dystrophin gene in 1986. He believes the
ideal treatment suggested by the new approach would be to take a
sample of a patient's own muscle, isolate the ancestral muscle stem
cells and treat them outside the body with the correct version of
the dystrophin gene. The treated cells would then be returned to
the patient without danger of immune rejection.
</P>
<P>
   But Mulligan fears that the patient's own muscle cells may be
compromised in some way and that ``there's a far greater hope that
if you make use of the bone marrow compartment you might have a
ready source of cells.'' He envisages taking the patient's bone
marrow cells and trying to repair the defective gene.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
