u a BC-DAM-REMOVAL-SPI &LR;      09-22 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAM-REMOVAL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTILITY AGREES TO REMOVE DAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A giant electrical utility will remove a large dam
in Washington state rather than pay the millions of dollars it
would cost to make the dam less harmful to fish.
</P>
<P>
   The removal of the Condit Dam on the White Salmon River, which
flows from the glaciers of Mount Adams into the canyons of the
Columbia River, will mark the first removal of a large dam in
Washington state, and the 125-foot-high dam is thought to be the
tallest dam ever removed in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement announced Wednesday to remove the dam in seven
years, which must be approved by federal regulators, gives a boost
in credibility and momentum to a national dam-removal movement
still celebrating last month's breaching of the Edwards Dam in
Augusta, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Dam-removal advocates, including Interior Secretary Bruce
Babbitt, say that many of the nation's large dams do more
environmental harm than economic good. They are eying a number of
dams in Washington state and around the country for possible
removal, including, most controversially, four dams on the lower
Snake River.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is yet another example that river restoration is on the
national agenda,'' Babbitt said. ``Among the 75,000 (large) dams in
this country, there are a good number which have simply outlived
their purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   The Condit Dam was ultimately doomed by a combination of biology
and economics. The dam's owner, a publicly-traded Portland-based
utility called PacifiCorp, chose to pay the $17 million cost of
removing the dam rather than come up with the $30 million in
fish-friendly changes that would have been required for the company
to renew its federal license to operate the dam.
</P>
<P>
   The dam generates just 14 megawatts of power _ enough
electricity for about 13,000 homes, but relatively small change in
the world of electrical power. Overall, PacifiCorp generates 8600
megawatts of power, including 1100 from hydropower.
</P>
<P>
   But the 86-year-old dam has had a dramatic impact on the life of
the White Salmon River, a narrow, 45-mile long waterway that rushes
along the border between Kittitas and Skamania counties and empties
into the Columbia River about 60 miles east of Portland. The river
has become popular among white-water rafters and kayakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Condit is the only dam on the river, and blocks access for
migratory fish to about 13 miles of upstream spawning grounds (a
waterfall blocks salmon access farther upstream), as well as to
several White Salmon tributaries such as Spring Creek and
Rattlesnake Creek. Before construction of the dam, some coho,
chinook, steelhead, lamprey and cutthroat trout migrating up the
Columbia would spawn in the White Salmon and its tributaries; those
runs are now at or near extinction.
</P>
<P>
   Two early attempts to construct fish passage around the dam
failed, and the initial owner of the dam, Northwestern Electric,
was allowed to pay for a fish hatchery rather than come up with a
way for wild fish to pass the dam.
</P>
<P>
   The White Salmon now supports only fish spawned in a hatchery
downstream, and the reservoir above the dam is stocked with trout
by state officials and supports a native trout fishery that has
thrived in the absence of competition from larger fish.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists are optimistic that as many as 10,000 salmon
would return to the river once the dam is removed, and that
restoration of the fish runs would make the upstream river more
attractive to fish-eating bear, osprey and bald eagles. The
upstream White Salmon remains relatively pristine. The river, which
runs through forests and canyons, is partly federally designated as
a Wild and Scenic River and protected as part of the Columbia River
Gorge National Scenic Area.
</P>
<P>
   The Yakama Nation, which has treaty rights to sites along the
river, will help manage the fishery after dam removal.
</P>
<P>
   PacifiCorps reluctantly signed the agreement to remove the dam,
saying the alternative was costly litigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a company whose business it is to produce low-cost power,
removing a hydropower project isn't something you approach with a
lot of joy, but given the circumstances, we think it was the best
outcome,'' said company spokesman Tom Imeson.
</P>
<P>
   The company was essentially forced to the bargaining table by
federal regulators. In 1996 the Federal Energy Regulatory
Commission, which licenses dams, ordered the company to construct
costly fish ladders and screens as a condition of renewing its
operating license.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than fight the requirements in court, the company entered
settlement talks with federal and state agencies, the Yakama
Nation, and environmental groups. Under the deal, signed yesterday
in Portland, the company will be allowed to operate the dam for
seven years and to use the revenue from that operation to pay for
dam removal.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction from elected officials was supportive, although Rep.
Brian Baird, D-Wash., said he is concerned about the plight of the
people who own summer cabins on the reservoir behind the dam. Those
people are likely to lose their waterfront property when the dam is
removed because the reservoir, which is known as Northwestern Lake,
will narrow into a river.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Gov. Gary Locke praised the parties to the deal,
saying ``The agreement by PacifiCorp, the tribes and
environmentalists to remove the Condit Dam is the kind of
cooperative, results-oriented solution we will need as we work to
restore our wild salmon runs without destroying our economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt and Rebecca Wodder, the president of the environmental
group American Rivers, predicted that more dams will be removed as
the licenses of hydropower dams expire and federal regulators
require prohibitively costly environmental improvements as a
condition of license renewal.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt, an enthusiastic supporter of removal of the two dams on
the Elwha River on the Olympic Peninsula in Washington state, said
he is optimistic that Congress this year will grant the federal
government enough money to purchase them from their private owner,
and that the government can then move toward removal of one of
them.
</P>
<P>
   As for the much more controversial proposal by some
environmental groups to remove four dams on the lower Snake River,
Babbitt said the debate is just beginning, while Wodder said that
the agreement on the Condit shows that ``dam removal is a
reasonable option.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
