u p BC-MCCAIN-BUCHANAN-NYT &LR;      09-22 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-BUCHANAN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN URGES A PARTY SWITCH BY BUCHANAN 
 (rk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John McCain denounced Pat Buchanan's views of
World War II on Wednesday and called on the Republican Party to
``stand on principle'' and bid farewell to the conservative
commentator instead of struggling to keep him in the fold.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's comments set him apart from the other Republican
presidential candidates, who have either urged Buchanan not to seek
the Reform Party nomination and risk draining conservative votes
from the eventual Republican nominee or stepped gingerly around the
controversy. And they came at a time when Buchanan's third-party
flirtation is starting to cause a backlash among some of the
Republican Party's conservative intelligentsia.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a former prisoner of war who has been making a special
appeal to veterans, singled out Buchanan's views, expressed in a
new book, that Hitler had offered ``no physical threat to the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona senator said in a statement released by his
campaign: ``Defeating Hitler's Germany and Tojo's Japan was a very
noble cause, and I wouldn't want any Republican to ever think
otherwise _ or any American for that matter.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, McCain had said he welcomed a vigorous foreign
policy debate with Buchanan over issues like global trade and the
U.S. role in trouble spots like Kosovo. But in a telephone
interview Wednesday, McCain said he considered Buchanan's views of
World War II ``so far outside of the philosophy of what America is
all about that it's unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   In his new book, ``A Republic, Not an Empire'' (Regnery
Publishing), Buchanan questioned whether Hitler chose to wage war
with the West or was driven to it by Britain and France's promise
to declare war on Germany if the Nazis invaded Poland. Buchanan
argued that Hitler was interested in eastward expansion and would
have left the United States alone.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging the fears that Buchanan could carry conservatives
out of the Republican Party with him, McCain said, ``I am fully
aware of the political implications of a Buchanan third party
candidacy. But regardless of what the polls show, our party must
stand on principle.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan defended his views Wednesday on CNN, arguing that ``at
least the Western democracies and Western Europe could have been
saved'' if Britain and France had not declared war on Hitler. He
said the Western war guarantee to Poland ``didn't save anybody in
Poland, six million people died in Poland. How could it be worse
for Poland? How could it have been worse than what it was for
European Jews?''
</P>
<P>
   A backlash against Buchanan has begun among some of the
conservative intelligentsia. The editor of ``The Weekly Standard,''
William Kristol, reminded Republicans in the current issue that
Harry S. Truman had not urged Henry Wallace to stay in the
Democratic Party. ``Are Republicans capable of being as courageous
and astute as Harry Truman was half a century ago?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   In the upcoming issue of The National Review, another writer,
Ramesh Ponnuru, argues that Buchanan, because of his views on trade
and foreign policy, ``is in no important sense a conservative any
more.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's effort to push his party to cut Buchanan loose was
not embraced Wednesday by other Republican candidates. Aides to
both Dan Quayle and Steve Forbes, who are fighting for the support
of social conservatives, said the party would be worse off if
Buchanan and his followers leave.
</P>
<P>
   The campaigns of Elizabeth Dole and Gary Bauer declined any
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Scott McClelland, a spokesman for Gov. George W. Bush, said the
Texas Republican believed that in World War II ``our soldiers were
fighting for freedom.'' But he also reiterated that Bush had spoken
with Buchanan during the Iowa straw poll in August and asked him to
remain a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Collins, a spokesman for the Republican National Committee,
said the party chairman, Jim Nicholson, still planned to meet with
Buchanan soon to make the case for the Republican Party. ``Our
basic take is that Senator McCain has spoken for himself,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
