u s BC-GLF-RYDER-NYT &LR;      09-22 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDERDOGS, AND LOVING IT EVERY MINUTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ So far, Lee Westwood and Colin Montgomerie
are enjoying everything about Ryder Cup week. They are enjoying
their teammates, who seem relaxed and confident. They like The
Country Club, a golf course that will require both skill and
strategy. And most important, Westwood and Montgomerie like
Europe's chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice being the underdogs,'' said Westwood, who couldn't
resist taking a small poke at Jeff Maggert, who called the U.S.
team the world's 12 best players on Tuesday. ``There's less
pressure on us and more pressure on them. There's great expectation
for them to win. It's in their own country, so the pressure is
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can beat anybody. I think this format leads to
shocks. They must be under pressure, being the 12 best players in
the world, according to themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Europeans can one-putt as frequently as they think of
one-liners, then the United States could be in trouble when the
biennial competition begins on Friday. The Europeans seem to relish
their underdog role, and in the past, they have flourished in it,
winning the 1995 and 1997 Ryder Cups when the United States was
expected to win.
</P>
<P>
   But it is hard to imagine Europe's winning this year unless its
two best players, Montgomerie and Westwood, play a huge role. Seven
of Europe's 12 players are Ryder Cup rookies, and those
first-timers will undoubtedly be nervous, especially playing in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Both Montgomerie and Westwood played the maximum five times in
1997, and that will probably happen again this weekend. That has
been Europe's winning formula in past years: rely heavily on the
top players, with others filling in as needed.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie and Westwood have paced themselves during practice
rounds this week, knowing they will be worked hard once the
competition begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very tiring week mentally more than physically,'' said
Montgomerie, who will be playing in his fifth consecutive Ryder
Cup. ``You go out and practice, and there's got to be 30,000 to
40,000 people out there. I just hope if I do play five times, that
I can get as many points as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see how Montgomerie reacts, not only
to being counted on so heavily, but also to playing another
pressure-laden event in the United States. Montgomerie has been the
dominant player on the European Tour this decade, winning the last
six European money titles, and leading this year's money list
again.
</P>
<P>
   But he has never won a tournament in the United States in 57
attempts, and he has yet to win a major championship, something his
critics point to as a glaring hole in his resume. Montgomerie has
also been distracted at several events in the past by unruly fans
who have heckled him; he is a player who wears his emotions
outwardly.
</P>
<P>
   The last thing Europe needs is a moping Montgomerie. But fans
during practice rounds Tuesday and Wednesday were very cordial to
all the Europeans, and Montgomerie said he expected that trend to
continue.
</P>
<P>
   Told that he had had problems with American galleries in the
past, Montgomerie smiled and said, ``Have I?'' Then he added: ``I
don't foresee any problems this week. I wholeheartedly enjoy
playing golf in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Montgomerie and Westwood are accurate drivers, which is
crucial at The Country Club. Players who drive the ball well will
be able to attack the small greens and make birdies. Players who
spray the ball off the tee will scramble to make pars and lose
holes.
</P>
<P>
   More responsibility will fall on the shoulders of Montgomerie,
Westwood and Jose Maria Olazabal to lead the Europeans, because
their team has undergone a changing of the guard. Five players who
have been a huge part of Europe's recent teams did not qualify for
this year's event _ Nick Faldo, Bernhard Langer, Ian Woosnam, Seve
Ballesteros and Costantino Rocca.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be different, no doubt about that,'' Montgomerie
said. ``Those guys were at the top of the tree for a long time, but
that doesn't mean we can't do well without them. What's coming
through in Europe is very, very good. And I'm sure we'll prove that
this week.''
</P>
<P>
   It is expected that the European captain, Mark James, will pair
Montgomerie with Paul Lawrie in foursome and four-ball events,
while Westwood could be paired with Darren Clarke, his close
friend.
</P>
<P>
   But regardless of his playing partner, as Montgomerie goes, so
goes a large part of Europe's team. He played a major role in
Europe's victory in 1997, earning 3.5 points. And he would love to
contribute even more this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the players are looking toward Monty, because he's
been the European No. 1, for the past it seems about 35 years
now,'' James said. ``He's our biggest star at the moment. Why
wouldn't I play him five times? I think that's a strong
possibility. As you guys would say, right now, his game is not too
shabby.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
