<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2358 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-HNS &LR;      09-22 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ For several years now, their names have
become synonymous with big-time golf as it heads into the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   You know them as Tiger Woods and Justin Leonard. As Jim Furyk
and Phil Mickelson. As Jeff Maggert and David Duval.
</P>
<P>
   You might also know them as the oh-for-Ryder six-pack.
</P>
<P>
   Tack on 41-year-old Hal Sutton and 40-year-old Tom Lehman _
Sutton was part of two U.S. losses more than a decade ago when he
was a precursor to the current frat-pack of flashy phenoms, and
Lehman has proved that failure in the Ryder Cup is a taste late
bloomers can acquire _ and you have eight members of the 1999 U.S.
team who are hoping to take their first sip of success from the
Ryder Cup this week at The Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   That's two-thirds of the U.S. team that has never played for a
winning Ryder Cup team.
</P>
<P>
   For Duval, there's an excuse. He's playing in his first Ryder
Cup. He's innocent until proved guilty.
</P>
<P>
   But Woods, Leonard and Furyk were on the losing 1997 team in
Valderrama, Spain. And Maggert, Mickelson and Lehman were members
of the '95 and '97 teams that lost to the Europeans. As for Sutton,
he hasn't been to this party since 1987, but those teams he was on
in the mid-'80s were the first to lose the Cup since 1957.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, this is an American team that needs to break through
some barriers, even if it will be heavily favored when the
competition begins Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being on the team in '97, I know how important it was to
(captain) Tom Kite to try to win it back and then to know the
disappointment,'' says Leonard. ``I don't feel like we've taken on
any extra burden. But I think for guys like Jeff and I who haven't
been on a winning team, we want to make Ben's (captain Ben
Crenshaw's) hard work pay off. We want to be able to enjoy Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had that (losing) taste in our mouth before. And we'd
like to try something else.''
</P>
<P>
   To say the least, it's a blow to the Americans' confidence, not
to mention their ego, that the players who are supposed to be the
cornerstone of professional golf into the next era have been so
stunningly bad in Ryder competition.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 at Valderrama, where the Europeans built a huge early
lead and then coasted to the win, the threesome of Davis Love III,
Woods and Leonard posted a combined 1-9-3 match record. They were
the toothpick-strong backbone of the U.S. collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Love has been in four Ryder Cups and been involved with one
victorious team.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the need for the younger generation of U.S. golfing
stars to get off the goose egg that has put so much pressure on
them going into this year's Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, there's a very strong sense of urgency for this
team to win,'' Lehman says. ``I think we need to win. That's all
there is to it. And I fully expect us to play our best golf, and I
expect us to win, as I'm sure the Europeans expect to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I have full and complete confidence in the other 11 guys on
this team and myself. I think it's a must-win for us.''
</P>
<P>
   And not just to validate the youngsters on the PGA Tour. Lehman
and Maggert share a common thread with Crenshaw in that they know
how much preparation goes into the Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me being on the last two Ryder Cups and not winning, as a
player, it was easy for me to put that behind me,'' Maggert says.
``But the things that I remember is Lanny (Wadkins) and Tom Kite. I
really felt for those guys because they worked their tails off for
two years. And I felt bad for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to win this thing for myself. But I want to do it for
Ben and Julie (his wife) because I know how hard they worked the
past two years and it means a lot for them if we win. And it means
a lot to me, too. But from the last two Ryder Cups, I really felt
for the captains because I know how much they wanted to win the
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had great teams in '95 and '97, and we all know what the
results were then. I feel like we have a really strong team. But
golf is a funny game at times. And anything can happen. I think
everybody on the team is in a good frame of mind. But as far as
being overconfident, I don't think anyone's taking this thing for
granted, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on the result of recent years, one would expect not.
</P>
<P>
   But if getting pummeled two times in a row does anything to a
team, it tests its pride. The Americans know now what they may not
have wanted to admit in the past _ that Europe's players and team
concept, along with their mastery of the Ryder Cup formats, make
them a worthy foe every time this match is contested.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been on two losing teams while being expected to win
pretty handily, and it's been certainly disappointing to experience
that,'' says Mickelson, who has seen his wonderful 4-1-2 match
record wasted in the last two Cups. ``I think in the past we may
have felt like they were going to give it to us. And we saw through
the play of the European side and the putts they made and shots
they hit that they beat us pretty soundly.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if we're going to expect to win this year, we're going to
have to play extremely well.''
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw has tried to do his best to defuse talk that the
pressure is squarely on the Americans. But he admits that many
members of his team need to fill a void in their professional
careers, and there's only one way to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would certainly love to complete a career that way,''
Crenshaw says of being a member of a winning Ryder Cup team. ``Many
of the Ryder Cup participants on the American side are at the
veteran stage of their career. So I think they're very intent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the last couple of matches, we do have some
younger players that have not been successful in the Ryder Cup. And
I think that they dwell on that. But I certainly think that in an
overall view, both sides, if you've done a lot of wonderful things
in your career and you don't tack on a Ryder Cup victory, you feel
a little bit lacking, I would say.''
</P>
<P>
   And Crenshaw is quietly optimistic that his team recognizes what
must be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terribly important for us,'' he says. ``I think everyone
knows that for our side, not having had success in the last few
occasions. And the players have asked themselves over a long while
about what sort of effort they were going to put forth. It's
wonderful seeing that come together.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's nothing that says heartbreak isn't waiting
again for the Americans this week at The Country Club. The
Europeans exude a sort of confidence that belies the fact that they
have seven players who will be playing in the Ryder Cup for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   As captain Mark James says, searching for the reasons why Europe
has been better in the past two Ryder Cups is a matter of looking
at the situation honestly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very, very easy, if you lose a match once, to blame it on
not being hungry or having a bad captain or the players not being
team-oriented,'' James says. ``But you're looking for excuses, I
think. It comes down to how they play. I think sometimes the role
of the captain and team spirit can be overstated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you look for excuses, you're hiding the fact that
maybe one team played slightly better.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is what the Americans must do to get off the schneid this
week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 2123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
