<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0440 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2360 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-BANK-ART-1     09-22 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BANK-ART-1,120(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FULL SPEED AHEAD, IN FOG OF RUSSIAN BANKING, BANK OF NEW YORK HIT A
SHOAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON and NEELA BANERJEE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ When Vladimir Potanin, one of Russia's leading tycoons,
founded a bank last year out of the ruins of the nation's economy,
some Western banks decided to keep their distance. They did not
want the new bank as a client until Potanin settled with creditors
at his old insolvent one, Uneximbank.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bank of New York was one of a number of banks that did
pick up the account, displaying an aggressiveness that has made it
the leading American bank in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   In the eight years since the collapse of the Soviet Union, the
Bank of New York has emerged as the undisputed leader in providing
an essential behind-the-scenes payment service linking Russia's
economy with the West. It is a high-volume business in which
thousands of international transactions are handled in a sequence
of payments involving Russian and foreign banks.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the FBI examines the bank's records for possible money
laundering, specialists question whether the huge flow of money _
nearly $4 billion a day _ made the bank less vigilant than it
should have been about the background of its customers and the
sources of their money.
</P>
<P>
   ``They turned into a huge supermarket,'' said Andrei
Melnichenko, the director of MDM Bank, which was a Bank of New York
customer until he had a dispute with the bank. ``If you have many
clients and you want to have good relations, you don't have time
enough to control all of it and there is a risk of error.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in hearings in Washington on Wednesday, Thomas A. Renyi,
chairman of the bank, said it had failed to pursue questions about
the billions of dollars flowing through accounts that had been
opened by the husband of a bank officer.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation has brought allegations of surreptitious
capital flight and possible money laundering. But it has also
thrown a spotlight on the hazards and rewards of banking in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bank of New York went to places other foreign banks had
not been before and provided good service,'' said Richard
Hainsworth, the Moscow representative of Thomson Financial
Bankwatch, a rating agency. ``But the Bank of New York's
flexibility and aggressive marketing also later led it to work with
clients that other banks ostracized.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a risk that confronts any foreign institution determined
to do business in the twilight world of the Russian economy, where
companies often circumvent the rules, and corrupt officials are all
too common.
</P>
<P>
   No one has charged the bank with any wrongdoing. But since the
investigation surfaced last month, several Russian bankers say,
they have taken some business to other foreign banks simply to
avoid being linked to the Bank of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the Bank of New York has declined to comment. But on
Wednesday, Renyi said the bank was reviewing whether to continue
its business with Russian banks.
</P>
<P>
   The bank has performed an important function in the Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Russia's trade revolves around the dollar, and many
foreign companies want to be paid in dollars by their Russian
customers. To serve their clients, Russian banks need what is
called a dollar settlement account with a powerful Western bank
that can transfer dollars from one account to another quickly and
safely. But these accounts can also be used to spirit money to
offshore banking havens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half the banks were set up by a couple of guys who wanted to
get money out of the country,'' a former Western banker in Moscow
said about Russian banks. ``You'd go there and some 22-year-old who
spoke English and had just finished a degree in finance would be
the chairman. People tried to explain it by saying it was a new
economy _ but come on!''
</P>
<P>
   Figuring out which clients operate in the gray areas of the
economy is difficult. ``People felt that Russian banks were
responsible for checking their clients' pasts,'' the former Western
banker said.
</P>
<P>
   And since the fees for processing each transaction are small _
American banks generally charge $2 and $4 a transaction _ the goal
was to line up as many clients as possible. ``It is
volume-driven,'' said Margot K. Jacobs, an analyst for United
Financial Group.
</P>
<P>
   With millions of dollars in fees and relatively little risk, the
Bank of New York had plenty of competitors, including Republic
National, Citibank and Chase Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bank of New York led the business because it offered
some practical advantages. First, it had worldwide experience. It
also had a popular staff of Russian-speaking bankers: Vladimir
Galitzine, Natasha Gurfinkel Kagalovsky and her assistant, Lucy
Edwards. They understood the society and were on a first-name basis
with the players.
</P>
<P>
   They also had a reputation for expert service. Ms. Kagalovsky,
who eventually assumed responsibility for the bank's Eastern
European division, was widely consulted by Russian bankers.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was extremely friendly,'' said one former Western banker
in Russia. ``You'd go into a party and there would be eight Russian
bankers around her because to them she was the No. 1 banker for
Russia's interests in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no data available that establishes a clear link between
the success of the bank's settlement business in Moscow and the
money that flowed through bank accounts in London and New York that
are under investigation. What is clear is that the Bank of New York
led the field, with clients that included major Russian banks like
Inkombank, Menatep and Sberbank, which is owned by the government.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Dimitri V. Ponamarev, the head of the Russian Trading System,
which is used by brokerage houses to buy and sell stocks over the
counter, said his organization chose the Bank of New York for the
reasons many others did: It was the leader and it kept customers
happy. ``There were no complications,'' Ponamarev said. ``Everybody
used them.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia's financial collapse in August 1998 and the allegations
of money laundering swirling around the Bank of New York have had a
sobering effect on many banks here.
</P>
<P>
   Murad M. Megali, managing director of Chase Manhattan Bank
International, who oversees the bank's business in Russia and other
former Soviet republics, declined to comment specifically on the
Bank of New York. But he noted the problems in doing business here:
``Eighty percent of the battle is won or lost at the gate. If you
let in wrong clients, you set yourself up for a fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Chase Manhattan, he said, tried carefully to check the banks it
did business with and rejected a significant number, particularly
after the 1998 crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also bankers who say some critics of Bank of New
York were simply less successful at correspondent services and in
fact dealt with many of the same clients in other areas.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Still, the Bank of New York's decision to accept Potanin's new
bank as a customer illustrates how complex it is to build a
business in Russia: As Potanin established the new bank, Rosbank,
the creditors for his old bank, Uneximbank, were still demanding to
be paid.
</P>
<P>
   Critics complained that Rosbank had been set up with the
remaining assets of the bankrupt Uneximbank, an accusation that a
spokesman for Rosbank denied. Others questioned whether it was
ethical to do business with a new bank if it was controlled by
people whose old bank had just collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   American Express Bank decided against setting up a correspondent
account for Rosbank. Chase Manhattan also made it clear it was not
willing to set up such an account.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of New York and Republic National Bank, however, agreed
to set up accounts, as did Credit Suisse First Boston and other
European and Asian banks. A spokesman for Rosbank said the bank now
had correspondent accounts at 53 banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to do business in Russia and be lily white,'' said
Hainsworth, of the Thomson bank rating agency. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 2124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
