<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0442 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2363 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r b BC-FILM-JAKOBTHELIAR-TEX     09-22 0405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-JAKOBTHELIAR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUTH IS, `LIAR' TAKES THE COWARD'S WAY OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The tradition of short stories in which deception and pain
devastate the life of the protagonist can be found in the novel
``Jakob the Liar'' by Jurek Becker (Penguin, $11.95). But if you're
looking for similar complexity in the film adaptation starring
Robin Williams at his dampest and neediest, you'd be advised to
give the book another shot. Williams is Jakob, detained in a
Nazi-occupied ghetto with thousands of other Jews. While waiting
for humiliation at the hands of a Nazi, Jakob happens to overhear
on the Nazis' radio a piece of news that is so powerful even the
Nazi propaganda machine can't put too good a face on it: Russian
forces are threatening to overrun the Germans at the Polish border,
not too far from the ghetto.
</P>
<P>
   The news is too much for Jakob. He leaks it to a slow-witted but
well-meaning boxer friend (Liev Schreiber), who not only blabs
about the possibility of Soviet saviors but also says that Jakob
has a secret radio. This misinformation gives a cast including
Armin Mueller-Stahl, Alan Arkin and, most embarrassingly, Bob
Balaban a chance to compete for the most eye-moistening attention.
Coming after the stylized approach of ``Life Is Beautiful,'' which
dealt with the Holocaust in similar terms, ``Jakob'' has almost no
chance of gaining an audience. For the material to work, the movie
would have to be a lot more daring in its mix of bleak humor and
hopelessness, focusing on a narrator and central figure who is
essentially unreliable. (His unreliability is the point of the
story.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Jakob'' is too intent on winning us over to gamble on such a
stratagem. Its timidity, flinching from a great subject, results in
an ending determined to make audiences leave the theater feeling
uplifted. Maybe the Robin Williams who starred in ``The World
According to Garp'' would've been up for starring in a film about
finding slivers of hope only to have them dashed before your eyes,
or for playing a man who was untrustworthy instead of someone
ennobled by torment. Nowadays, he might have forced a happy ending
even on ``Garp.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jakob the Liar'' is rated PG-13 for adult subject matter,
violence and mild sexuality. .MDNM/ (Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 2124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0443 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2365 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TOBACCO-REACT-NYT &LR;      09-22 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. EMPLOYING 2 STRATEGIES IN LAWSUIT AGAINST CIGARETTE MAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., Fla., Texas, Calif., Ind.)  (With TOBACCO-SUIT) 
(lh) 
 By BARRY MEIER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The lawsuit filed against cigarette makers Wednesday by the
government has two legal strategies.
</P>
<P>
   In one thrust, the government will try to recover money it says
it spent on treating smoking-related illnesses of the elderly,
military personnel and federal employees by relying on federal
statutes that legal experts describe as obscure and rarely used.
</P>
<P>
   But in the second strategy, the Justice Department portrays
cigarette makers as racketeers who should be forced to disgorge
ill-gotten profits, saying they conspired for decades to mislead
the public about the health risks of smoking and the addictiveness
of nicotine.
</P>
<P>
   Several legal experts said the suit faced stiff legal challenges
from tobacco makers and could take years to reach trial. But in the
meantime, they said, it puts tobacco producers back into the
position they sought to avoid by agreeing to pay states $248
billion to settle their smoking-related suits _ that of renegades.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry wants the cultural understanding of smoking to be
one where it is OK for adults to smoke and not OK for children to
smoke,'' said Stephen Sugarman, a professor of law at the
University of California at Berkeley. ``They do not want it to be
one where the cigarette is considered evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Little, a lawyer for Philip Morris Cos., the nation's
largest cigarette maker, said that the federal lawsuit did not
contain any surprises and that he expected it to be dismissed
quickly in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has no basis in law,'' Little said. ``It has no basis in
fact.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the legal uncertainties surrounding the federal
lawsuit are like those that accompanied the states' suits, the
first of which was filed in 1994 by Mississippi. A state had never
previously sought to recover money from cigarette makers, so their
lawyers had to devise new theories or adopt old ones to a new
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   The states, which sued to recover money spent treating
low-income patients through the Medicaid program, used a variety of
approaches including claims under their state consumer protection
or fraud laws. For their part, government lawyers, who are seeking
to recoup Medicare and other outlays, are also relying on laws
never tested before against cigarette makers.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is the federal Medical Care Recovery Act, which was
passed in 1962 to enable the government to recover money spent
treating military personnel, American Indians and others injured by
products or in accidents. Robert Rabin, a law professor at Stanford
University, said the law was amended in 1996 to permit the
government to recover money spent treating Medicare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   However, Rabin said, typically only individual claims were
brought under the Act, so one major hurdle that the government
faces is whether a court will allow it to bring together millions
of individual claims in a single action against cigarette makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Feds can't aggregate claims, the statute is of no
benefit to them,'' Rabin said.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also marks the first time that federal officials have
used the Racketeering Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act
against an entire industry. The so-called RICO statute was
initially passed to fight organized crime, though it has been used
against businesses accused of conspiring together to cheat the
public or the government.
</P>
<P>
   Both Florida and Texas used Rico counts in their lawsuits
against cigarette makers. But G. Robert Blakey, a law professor at
Notre Dame University who worked with state officials in Florida
and Texas, said Justice Department officials were initially
skeptical when he proposed a similar strategy to them in January.
</P>
<P>
   The racketeering claim, however, could prove the government's
most powerful legal weapon against cigarette makers, some lawyers
believe. To prove such a claim, the government must show that
cigarette makers engaged in an pattern of activity intended to play
down the risks of smoking and the addictiveness of nicotine.
</P>
<P>
   If successful, producers would be forced to disgorge past
profits as ill- gotten gains and potentially pay treble damages.
</P>
<P>
   Little, the Philip Morris lawyer, said the government's
racketeering claim was legally unfounded. But Joseph DiGenova, a
lawyer in Washington, disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I am concerned, this is an unprecedented use of the
statute, and it may be a legitimate one,'' DiGenova said. ``It all
depends on what the evidence is.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether a judge or jury will ever hear that evidence is anyone's
question. All of the state lawsuits were settled prior to verdict,
and as a result there are not legal precedents for the government's
case. In addition, with huge financial stakes at issue, there is
always the potential for settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The government is eager to get federal regulation over the
cigarette industry, a concession that the states failed to achieve
in their settlements. But election politics could cloud settlement
prospects as the tobacco industry awaits the next president.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mary Aronson, a tobacco industry analyst in Washington,
said she believed the selection of a favorable judge in the federal
case could be a spur to settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might provide a certain type of leverage for settlement,''
Ms. Aronson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
