<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0446 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2370 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SAKS-OUTLOOK-2TAKES-A     09-22 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAKS-OUTLOOK-2TAKES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAKS TRIES TO BALANCE TRADITION AND RISK
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic and photo are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a fall windows at Saks Fifth Avenue's flagship
Manhattan store, a certain fashion dissonance was on display.
</P>
<P>
   The background suggested a genteel Tuscany picnic _ replete with
baskets of grapes, Chianti Ruffino in a straw bottle holder and
denuded tree branches. It was a setting that the store's most loyal
customer, a well-kept woman in her late 40s, might know well.
</P>
<P>
   But the clothes seemed cut for another silhouette completely _
maybe a 20-something actress attending a post-movie-premiere party
at the downtown nightclub Moomba. In one window, a mannequin posed
noncommittally in Dolce &AMP; Gabbana hot magenta floral hip huggers
and electric-orange leopard print pin-point heel pumps. In another,
the mannequin lounged in a vinyl camisole with a 3-D print secured
with Velcro straps.
</P>
<P>
   ``How'd that look on me, John,'' joked a well-dressed tourist to
her husband as the two ogled the display in early September. ``I
could wear it to the beach.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week Saks Fifth Avenue, the venerable clothier to the
ladies who lunch, turned 75, but a placid old age is not in the
cards. Even with America in the midst of a consumer spending boom,
Saks Fifth Avenue _ along with Neiman Marcus, the other luxury
department store chain _ is struggling to make the kind of profits
Wall Street demands of retailers these days.
</P>
<P>
   The secret to high-fashion success has always been finding the
right balance between nurturing cutting-edge design and stocking
enough money-making name brands to satisfy traditional customers.
But for Saks today, under new and very bottom-line-oriented
management, that balancing act has turned particularly precarious.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Saks Holdings Inc. _ the store's owner _ was bought
by Proffitt's, a fast-growing Southern retailer. And R. Brad
Martin, the chief executive of Proffitt's _ since renamed Saks Inc.
_ had lofty expectations for his catch. He had made his company an
investor darling by gobbling up regional department store chains
like McRae's, Younkers and Carson Pirie Scott, and then squeezing
out big savings by consolidating mundane back-office functions like
real estate and ordering office supplies.
</P>
<P>
   But with earnings slumping, Martin ``does not have unlimited
patience,'' said Robert F. Buchanan, a retail analyst with A.G.
Edwards, who met with him recently. ``He is not going to stand by
if the performance continues to lag _ he will make changes.''
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the year, Martin had predicted 6 percent
growth in sales and nearly 35 percent growth in earnings. To
investors worried that Saks Fifth Avenue, with its high
concentration of couture brands like Bill Blass and Yves Saint
Laurent, would not mesh well with the rest of his empire, Martin
scoffed. All fashion decisions at the chain would continue to be
made by its impeccably groomed longtime chairman and chief
executive, Philip B. Miller.
</P>
<P>
   But in mid-August, Saks Inc., which is based in Birmingham,
Ala., rocked Wall Street by lowering its earnings estimates for the
year to $1.80 a share from $2.10. During calls with analysts,
Martin admitted that roughly 8 cents, or nearly one-third of the
shortfall, could be traced to lower margins from Saks Fifth Avenue,
which now accounts for about 40 percent of Saks Inc.'s revenue.
Analysts and investors responded by pounding the stock, which in
February went as high as $39.50, sending it to a new low of $17,
where it has remained.
</P>
<P>
   Did performance really suffer, or did Martin expect too much?
Miller's blue eyes flashed with anger at the suggestion that Saks
Fifth Avenue had lost its way. Ensconced in his paisley
wall-papered office, Miller insisted that sales growth was above
that of the rest of Saks Inc., which will be about 4 percent for
the year, and that he beat out other luxury merchants, notably
Neiman Marcus, as well. ``We have taken real market share from the
competition,'' Miller said. ``We may not have met expectations, but
we certainly did not embarrass ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, designers who sell to the company, as well as analysts
who cover it _ many of whom have had heart-to-wallet conversations
with Martin recently _ see real trouble in the gap between Martin's
expectations and the chain's performance.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem seems to be that there was a general
softening in the luxury market over the summer. While plenty of the
highest-end merchants, like Gucci and Tiffany, have reported strong
sales recently, Neiman Marcus Group Inc., Saks Fifth Avenue's most
direct competitor, posted disastrous results last month. With
anemic sales growth of less than 1 percent forcing Neiman Marcus to
make steep markdowns, profits plunged 83 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Saks also faces the matter of getting the right merchandise
mix. Some of this might be easily remedied. For example, analysts
say Saks Fifth Avenue is still heavy on formal business clothing,
particularly expensive men's suits like Hugo Boss and Brioni, while
much of America has long since moved to casual workplace attire.
Also, Saks Fifth Avenue's private-label clothing _ which Martin is
counting on to lift profits in the future _ is still too expensive
for its quality. Fine-gauge white men's T-shirts that might be a
buy at $40 instead go for $78.
</P>
<P>
   Most serious is the assertion by Wall Street that Saks Fifth
Avenue cannot manage its high-end designer fashions. ``In an effort
to have a compelling assortment, things got away from them,'' and
they went too far with riskier designs that did not sell, said
Christine Kilton-Augustine, a retail and apparel analyst with ING
Baring.
</P>
<P>
   High-end designer apparel accounts for 15 percent of Saks Fifth
Avenue's revenue and probably only about 6 percent or 7 percent of
its profits, but it sets the tone for the entire store.
</P>
<P>
   Established couture and career lines from Chanel, Max Mara and
Prada have a devoted following at Saks. But while these big brands
bring in a steady flow of revenue, that money comes with a lot of
strings attached. Many of those brands have developed their own
stores, which compete for business. Some do not allow Saks Fifth
Avenue to display the entire collection, and many make demands
about merchandising.
</P>
<P>
   Edgy styles from emerging designers like Alexander McQueen and
Issey Miyake take up less space, but have the potential to play a
more important role, attracting younger, more adventurous women.
These customers may spend less on clothes but will purchase
cosmetics, like the $75 lipsticks offered by the Saks house brand
By Terry, or spend $150 for a faux diamond choker.
</P>
<P>
   By supporting such brands when they are still relatively
unknown, Saks also gambles on a richer payoff if they suddenly
become popular. They are hoping for the next Dolce &AMP; Gabbana _
``the next big hit before it gets too big,'' explains Ike Lagnado
of Tactical Retail Solutions Inc., a consulting firm in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that small designers take a lot of effort, and
money, to nurture, and they have unpredictable sales. Unlike the
big brands, lesser-known names offer stores nothing in the way of
support _ like advertising dollars or money back if sales fail to
materialize _ so a bad season for enough small designers can have a
serious impact on the bottom line. Analysts say that is exactly
what happened at Saks Fifth Avenue this past year _ and that the
new owners may not have the stomach for it.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It is hard for an outsider to discern to what extent emerging
designers are in trouble at Saks Fifth Avenue _ everyone from the
store to the designers, who have few other places to sell their
goods, has a stake in painting a rosy picture _ but some troubling
issues have emerged. Ellen Carey, who represents the Australian
designer Collette Dinnigan in the United States, has only praise
for Saks Fifth Avenue, which has put Ms. Dinnigan's designs in 12
stores. Miller has been tremendously supportive of the brand, she
said, but added that the chain cannot give designers the intensely
hands-on maintenance that a much smaller specialty store like
Barney's offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saks has sophisticated owners and sophisticated shoppers, but
the sales staff needs to be brought up to par,'' Ms. Carey said.
She said Ms. Dinnigan has managed to sell roughly 60 percent of her
collection at full price each season because she ships her entire
collection at once, so that it is obvious how to display it. Other
designers sometimes ship trousers one week and blouses another,
leaving it to the store staff to assemble outfits for customers.
</P>
<P>
   Several designer representatives, who insisted on anonymity,
were even more worried. They fault Saks Fifth Avenue not for lack
of trying, but for being part of a discouraging cycle in luxury.
For years mid-level, or ``bridge,'' designer wear has been
suffering because department stores, pressured to compete with
discount and specialty stores, have been marking down such goods
steeply. Now the same cycle is happening to luxury, which had
previously been immune.
</P>
<P>
   ``They mark down very early, and don't give the merchandise the
time to perform,'' one designer representative complained. ``Last
fall, our winter goods hit the floor in October, and by November
they were on sale.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, on an early September afternoon, the markdown racks
were overflowing. An Armani denim jacket had been slashed from
$1,245 to $372, and a Chloe basket-weave skirt in royal blue was
going for $600 off its list price of $1,050.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Martin insists that he has no intention of meddling in
Saks Fifth Avenue's designer business and that he has full
confidence in the chain's luxury strategy. ``I believe absolutely
that this economic model can be profitable,'' he said. ``Designer
is at the heart of who we are and a key element of our future
strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Martin has already made back-office changes at Saks
Inc. that could hurt the chain's ability to attract luxury
customers. For example, he has cut its renovation budget by 20
percent _ a Saks spokesperson said that the savings all came from
efficiency moves, not cuts in projects _ and forced the retailer to
reduce inventories.
</P>
<P>
   Designers lament that they have already felt the impact of the
merger and Saks Inc.'s overriding concern with profitability. Many
say they are being forced to reach sales goals for full-price
merchandise that would be difficult for one speciality store, let
alone for a 59-store chain.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin made no apologies for his determined approach. ``We
expect an extraordinary return on capital invested,'' he said,
``and Saks Fifth Avenue's portfolio will give us that return.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
