<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-UPDATE-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Sept. 26,
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE story &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-REPUBLIC-CELEBRATION (Shanghai, China) _ The 50th
anniversary of the People's Republic of China is being heralded
here with a celebration intended by the government to top all
celebrations. On Friday morning, half a million invited citizens
will gather in Tiananmen Square in Beijing for a speech by
President Jiang Zemin, followed by the biggest military parade in
the country's history, with 90 floats, 140,000 marchers, numerous
tanks and weapons, and 130 sorties by Chinese Air Force planes. At
dusk, 100,000 dancers and singers will perform. When darkness
finally falls, fireworks displays with names like ``Chanting the
Eulogy of the Motherland'' will burst forth simultaneously from 10
locations around the capital. By Sheila Melvin. &UR;  &LR; (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO-FILM-FEST (subslug) (Toronto) _ The ten-day Toronto
International Film Festival ended its 24th incarnation last Sunday
after hosting more than 300 films, dozens of major stars and
filmmakers and hundreds of journalists and industry types from all
over the world. Slightly bleary from a day's worth of questions
about ``Sunshine'' _ a Hungarian generational epic from director
Istvan Szabo in which Ralph Fiennes plays three roles _ the actor
was collecting his thoughts after the last of the journalists had
left and was preparing to make a 36-hour escape before he had to
return for yet another push, this time for ``Onegin,'' an
adaptation of Pushkin's narrative poem directed by Martha Fiennes,
his sister. By Rick Lyman. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   GAY-AIDS-FILMS (Undated) _ The Association of Lesbian and Gay
Pride Films, an activist group in France, has produced a series of
10 short films geared to the gay and lesbian population in the
context of AIDS. The films titled ``L'Amour Est a Reinventor''
(``Love Reinvented'') were released in France in 1998 and will open
in New York on Friday. By David Bahr. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GALLO-THEATER-DESIGNER (New York) _ What makes a David Gallo
design a David Gallo design? The scenic designer David Gallo will
only say, ``I tend to do things (italics)large.''(end italics)
That's a rather broad esthetic philosophy, but it sits well with
the husky, garrulous man whose latest larger-than-life set
surrounds the action of ``Epic Proportions,'' a new comedy opening
Thursday at the Helen Hayes Theater. By Steven Drukman. (Moved).
Photo.
</P>
<P>
   EVE-ENSLER-THEATER (New York) _ If you'd never seen Eve Ensler's
one-woman show ``The Vagina Monologues'' and if you knew she had
also written plays about Bosnian refugees, women in prison and
nuclear war, you might expect her to be humorless, single-minded,
even didactic. But to step into Ms. Ensler's apartment in Chelsea
is to confront a positively bubbly figure. Ms. Ensler, 46, good
humor masks a serious purpose and a troubled personal history that
gave rise to ``The Vagina Monologues,'' which began its second New
York run last Tuesday (in previews at the Westside Theater). The
monologues are part of Ms. Ensler's crusade to wipe out the shame
and embarrassment that many women still associate with their bodies
or their sexuality. By Dinitia Smith. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   UPSIDE-DOWN-DANCE (New York) _ To the propulsive beat of the
Nigerian composer Fela Anikulapo Kuti's music, the choreographer
Ronald K. Brown led his 12 sinuous dancers across the floor in
fast, rhythmic movements, each stride increasing the tension in the
studio. Just five minutes into ``Upside Down,'' Brown had already
reached a wrenchingly emotional place. It is a place he fruitfully
visits often. ``Upside Down,'' a section from a larger work, the
1998 ``Destiny,'' illustrates the enormous effort and energy it
takes to move toward inner peace in a chaotic world. When Brown's
aptly named company, Evidence, begins its one-week engagement at
the Joyce Theater on Tuesday, it will present ``Upside Down'' as
well as two other Brown works; Ebony Magazine'' and ``Water.'' By
Valerie Gladstone. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BROOKLYN-PHILHARMONIC (New York) _ For their season that opens
on Friday, Robert Spano and the Brooklyn Philharmonic have put
together a set of programs to survey the 20th century at its end.
This is a 20th-century season in two ways: not only does all the
music come from the last hundred years, but the planning has a very
20th-century feel. Spano and his orchestra are concerned less with
great composers than with great themes _ war, politics, pop
culture, the environment, faith _ and there is no attempt to make
sure that all the outstanding creative personalities will be
represented. By Paul Griffiths. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   VIENNA-PHILHARMONIC (Seewalchen Amattersee, Austria) _ Yes, 1999
is a Johann Strauss year, filled with commemorations of the
composer's death 100 years ago. And yes, it ends in the turning not
only of the century but also of the millennium. Yet when the Vienna
Philharmonic performs Strauss waltzes on New Year's Eve and New
Year's Day in the Musikvereinsaal in Vienna and on worldwide
television, it will be conducting business more or less as usual.
By James R. Oestreich. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHRIS-GAINES-ALBUM (Undated) _ Whether it is a testament to
cowardice, marketing or megalomania, ``Chris Gaines'' is a gutsy
undertaking, not only as an attempt by an outsider to fit into
another genre but also as a greatest hits album that tries to fit
into each phase of that genre's recent history. Gaines may be a
pseudonym _ complete with an elaborate invented background that
incorporates bits of Dylan, Beatles and Prince lore and parallels
elements of Garth Brooks's life (the solo careers of both begin in
1989, and both have the same number of letters in their first and
last names). But Chris Gaines is very much Garth Brooks, who has
described himself as a melting pot of the past. By Neil Strauss.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CONDE-NAST-ARCH (New York) _ I hope that the completion of the
new Conde Nast headquarters last month will make people think twice
before complaining about the Disneyfication of Times Square. Things
are better than that, and worse. Disney is but one in a group of
media giants that have chosen to settle here. Besides Conde Nast,
publishers of The New Yorker, Vogue, Vanity Fair and other
glamorous titles, the group includes Reuters, Bertelsmann,
Billboard Publications and MTV. By Herbert Muschamp. (Moved).
Photo.
</P>
<P>
   MONROE-PIANO-SALE (New York) _ As grand pianos go, the one going
on the block at Christie's this month is nothing special.
Paderewski did not play it. Neither did Liberace, though he would
have swooned over its fondant-white finish and maybe added some
stylistic flourishes of his own. And as far as Christie's knows, no
one but Marilyn Monroe, its last owner, ever tickled its ivories,
though it is possible that Frank Sinatra, a Monroe beau, might have
plunked out a tune or two. The baby grand piano is a centerpiece of
the sale of Ms. Monroe's personal effects at Christie's new
salerooms at Rockefeller Center on Oct. 27 and 28. By Mitchell
Owens. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   MARILYN-PERFUME (Los Angeles) _ Over the last couple of years,
the estate of Marilyn Monroe has not been kind to the goddess whose
memory it protects. In 1997, it sanctioned a line of Marilyn Monroe
lingerie. The 50s-style underwear was hawked at department stores.
Now comes an estate-approved perfume called Marilyn, from
International Flavors and Fragrances, the company that has
recreated the essence of Elizabeth Taylor, Victoria Principal and
Christie Brinkley. This takes the concept of celebrity perfume to a
new level: the notion of smelling like a famous dead person _ even
Marilyn Monroe _ is at best an odd one. By Deanne Stillman.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   BIBLE-ART (Hatfield, Mass.) _ Putting pictures to words is Barry
Moser's profession, but never has the challenge been greater than
in his latest project: a monumental, fully illustrated version of
the King James Bible. Not only is this the most central, most
revered and surely most contested text in our culture, but it is
one already firmly fixed in our collective minds by religious
inclination and by the countless artists who have already left
their mark. Moser, while keenly aware of those precedents and
preconceptions, has approached this daunting project by returning
to the words themselves to confront familiar stories as if for the
first time. By Miles Under. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-MOESHA (Undated) _ As everyone in television sounds off about
desires supposedly dear to their hearts _ to see more nonwhite
actors in prime time and to see more shows that the whole family
can enjoy _ the producers and cast of ``Moesha'' have their Oz-like
wish. ``Hey, folks,'' they wonder, ``why not look here in your own
backyard?'' ``Moesha'' (pronounced mo-EESH-a), which has just begun
its fifth season on UPN, is about a family. It has a mix of
characters and plot lines that can engage both adolescents and
adults. And the family, like almost all the supporting characters,
happens to be black. By Lawrie Mifflin. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (`t' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ITALY (Undated) _ Calabria by the sea. By Paul Hofmann.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-DISABLED (Undated) _ Airlines face scrutiny over
wheelchari policies. By Betsy Wade. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-JAPAN-FARMTOWN (Undated) _ Japan, without the urban
sprawl. By Nicholas D. Kristof. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Egalite at last on Paris trains;
Cartier Exhibition goes to Chicago; A new hotel near the Forbidden
City; French artists invade the West Coast; Where East meets West
in Berlin. (Moved). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Question and answers on travel. This
week: Paris bike tours; Taking Portuguese in Rio; Spain's Eresma
Valley sites. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ How safe are thrill rides? By
Betsy Wade. (Moved).
</P>
