<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-HAMAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLOT REPORT IN ISRAEL AND ARRESTS IN JORDAN RENEW FEAR OF HAMAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The political and security threat posed by the
militant Islamic movement Hamas got renewed attention Wednesday
when Israeli officials charged that two bombs that exploded
prematurely this month had been intended for passenger buses, and
when Jordan arrested three leaders of Hamas at the Amman airport.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli Ministry of Public Security said four Hamas
plotters, all Israeli Arabs, had planned to bomb two
Jerusalem-bound buses on Sept. 5 after being recruited and trained
in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The plot failed when the bombs exploded almost simultaneously in
two cars, one in Tiberias, killing the driver, and another in
Haifa, killing the driver and a passenger.
</P>
<P>
   The ministry would not comment on reports that the plot had been
directed by the Hamas office in Amman, where the Jordanian police
seized three longtime leaders of the group Wednesday as they
stepped off a plane from Tehran, Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Those arrested included Khaled Meshal, head of the Hamas
``politburo,'' who is best known as the target of a botched
poisoning attempt by Israeli agents in Amman in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   One month ago, in an unexpected display of displeasure by King
Abdullah, Jordanian authorities issued arrest warrants for the
three men, closed their offices in Amman, rounded up more than a
dozen subordinates and seized what they said were weapons caches.
</P>
<P>
   The warrants coincided with the Hamas leaders' trip to Iran, and
Jordanian officials clearly hoped the men would not return.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli security officials said Wednesday that most of the
evidence linking Hamas to the two bombs came from the surviving
member of the team, who the police said had confessed to a plan to
place the bombs in the baggage compartments of the buses and then
disembark at the first scheduled stop.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper reports said the Shin Bet security service had
identified Hamas operatives in the West Bank as the suppliers of
the detonating devices, and the Hamas office in Jordan as the
coordinator of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Indications that the plot may have been directed from Jordan
could help explain Abdullah's decision to clamp down now. Hamas has
been tolerated by authorities in Jordan because of the support it
enjoys among many Palestinians there.
</P>
<P>
   But the new king has also professed a desire to make Jordan a
supportive bystander rather than an intermediary in the
Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Another concern also appears to be Hamas' influence in Jordan's
politics as the new king takes his first tentative steps toward
democratic reform.
</P>
<P>
   Jordanian officials said Meshal and a deputy, Ibrahim Ghosheh,
both Jordanian citizens, would face trial on charges related to
illegal political activities and clandestine military training
exercises.
</P>
<P>
   The third Hamas activist detained, Musa Abu Marzook, who is said
to hold Yemeni citizenship and Egyptian travel documents, is to be
deported, though to where is uncertain. He was expelled from Jordan
in 1995 after political clashes there, only to be jailed upon his
arrival in the United States. He was re-admitted to Jordan in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
