<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2378 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-CANCER-CARE-NYT &LR;      09-22 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CANCER-CARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY FINDS SHORTCOMINGS IN CARE FOR CHRONICALLY ILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Health experts have long known that family members,
particularly women, shoulder a heavy burden in caring for the
dying. But a new study suggests the burden is greatest when the
death is due to chronic illnesses like heart and lung disease,
perhaps because society has paid disproportionate attention to
people who die of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The research, based on interviews with 988 terminally ill
patients and those caring for them, is the first to examine the
role of family members in detail, and the first to look at the
needs of people afflicted with a range of illnesses. Previous
studies focused solely on cancer and dementia.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that patients with chronic illness other than
cancer needed more assistance with nursing, personal and household
care and transportation than cancer patients, in part because
people with cancer are more likely to have hospice care, and were
more likely to have unmet needs. These chronically ill patients
also relied on paid assistance more often; the researchers
theorized that they had been sick for so long that by the time they
were close to death, their family members were exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are trying to improve health care in this country for
dying patients and you look at these data, you will say that cancer
care is not perfect but it is under control,'' said the study's
lead author, Dr. Ezekiel J. Emanuel, chairman of the Department of
Clinical Bioethics at the National Institutes of Health. ``For
people without cancer, we have a big problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The research, published in Thursday's issue of The New England
Journal of Medicine, found that 41 percent of chronically ill
noncancer patients reported having ``substantial'' need for help
with their daily needs, as opposed to 29 percent of cancer
patients. Twenty-three percent had problems left untended, as
opposed to 15 percent of cancer patients. And 20 percent relied on
paid caregivers, as opposed to 11 percent of cancer patients.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors who care for the dying said the findings confirmed what
they saw in their practices: Cancer patients are fairly
self-sufficient until the last six months of life, when they
deteriorate quickly and often turn to hospice care, a system that
was designed with them in mind. But there is no equivalent system
for other chronically ill patients, who follow more of a
roller-coaster pattern over a period of years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a narrative that goes with cancer; everyone
understands that there is a terminal illness, and that it is not
forever,'' said Dr. Diane E. Meier, an expert in end-of-life care
at Mount Sinai Medical Center in Manhattan. ``It is the family
caregivers of frail, older adults with chronic illness who are
often looking at five, 10 years or longer of being the primary
caregiver for a person who cannot take care of themselves. And that
puts a very different set of stresses on families.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts are just beginning to think about how to ease those
stresses, said Dr. Anne Wilkinson of the Center for Care of the
Dying at George Washington University here.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy percent of Americans die of chronic illness, Wilkinson
said. But, she added, ``we haven't yet identified clearly or
explicitly what kinds of needs they have.'' That is because many
doctors do not recognize these patients as dying, which accounts
for why previous studies have focused so heavily on cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that 96 percent of primary caregivers _ those
providing dying patients with the most assistance _ were family
members, and 72 percent were women. Yet when women became ill
themselves, they were forced to rely on paid help to a far greater
extent than men, a finding that held true even among women who were
married.
</P>
<P>
   The 988 patients in the study came from six places around the
country, and were referred by their doctors, who estimated that
they had less than six months to live. Nearly 60 percent were older
than 65. Roughly half had cancer; 18 percent had heart disease, and
11 percent had lung disease. Patients with dementia were excluded,
because they could not be interviewed, as were patients with HIV,
Dr. Emanuel said, because they account for only a small percentage
of deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the research is important because most of the
existing studies on family caregiving was conducted more than a
decade ago, before managed care revolutionized the American medical
system, forcing shorter hospital stays and placing much greater
responsibilities on relatives. At the same time, the baby boom
generation is aging, forcing policy makers to think about who will
care for greater numbers of dying patients.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
