<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2382 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-FALCONS23-COX     09-22 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hanspard has empathy with hurt Anderson
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Byron Hanspard has been down this road before, a
passenger on a bus nobody ever wants to ride, with Jamal Anderson
driving.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately after Hanspard tore up his left knee in the
final preseason game of 1998, Anderson, his fellow Falcon running
back, was at his side under the Georgia Dome, near tears.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was at the hospital that night until 4 a.m., trying to
get Hanspard to laugh.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy. Hanspard was out for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Anderson's out for the season with a torn right anterior
cruciate knee ligament.
</P>
<P>
   This time, it's up to Hanspard to carry the load for the
Falcons, who face quite a task in trying to bounce back from an 0-2
start.
</P>
<P>
   What irony. Hanspard's injury, after all, had a lot to do with
Anderson rushing an NFL-record 410 times last season for franchise
records of 1,846 yards and 14 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   That translated into a five-year, $32 million contract this
summer, when Anderson also got a $7.5 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Hanspard will again caddy for Anderson, this time with
encouragement and advice on bouncing back.
</P>
<P>
   It started moments after Anderson was hurt Monday making a cut
on the Texas Stadium turf. Hanspard was right there, leaning over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was concerned for him, and praying for him, that it wasn't
as bad as mine,'' said Hanspard, an ordained Pentecostal minister.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Hanspard almost finds it amusing so many people are
ready to bury the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   It's not like the 5-foot-10, 200-pounder is a bum.
</P>
<P>
   If the sight of him racing downfield as a rookie in '97 on a
77-yard run that remains the longest in franchise history wasn't
encouraging enough, look longer. He also had runs of 57 and 53
yards to go with a stellar 6.3-yard average per carry.
</P>
<P>
   As a bonus, the speedy native of Desoto, Texas, returned two
kickoffs for touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   But Hanspard hears the theories he's not durable enough to
handle the ball as much as Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' he said. ``Everybody is saying that because I'm
coming off knee surgery ... but the Lord has blessed me to go above
and beyond.''
</P>
<P>
   With Hanspard, there is no avoiding references to religion. He
is an ordained Pentecostal minister. His faith was a big help in
rehabilitating what team orthopedist Andrew Bishop once described
as a ``potentially devastating, career-ending injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only was the primary stabilizing ligament in Hanspard's left
knee torn, but the patella tendon was as well. Bishop cut
Hanspard's right knee and used parts of that patella tendon to mend
the damage.
</P>
<P>
   Hanspard, who rushed for 2,084 yards as a junior at Texas Tech
before going pro and being drafted by the Falcons in the second
round in 1997, has made an amazing recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``God has completely healed my knee,'' he said. ``Yes, I have
room for getting it stronger, but it's completely healed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is saying (his durability is an issue) because I'm
coming off knee surgery . . . but the Lord has blessed me to go
above and beyond.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Reeves isn't exactly sure what that means.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson averaged 25.6 carries per game last season. Can
Hanspard measure up to that?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea,'' Reeves said. ``If we are having success
running the ball, then hopefully, he will get it 20 or 25 times a
game. The only thing you worry about is ... swelling or any
soreness.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanspard will probably not carry the ball that often, at least
not most games, as second-year pro Ken Oxendine, who's 6-foot, 230
pounds, will get action, too.
</P>
<P>
   Hanspard is better suited to run wide, and on draws and screen
passes, when defenders are spread out, and he can dart and dash.
Oxendine's style fits the middle of the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I'm capable of running the ball just as well as Jamal
did,'' he said. ``There may be worries for other people, but not
me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have little choice but to have faith similar to
Hanspard's.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
