</P>
<P>
   (NYT43) NEW YORK -- Sept. 22, 1999 -- GOODALL-PROFILE, 09-22 --
Jane Goodall, the British primatologist, is raising money for seven
chimp sanctuaries in Africa. For the last 13 years, she has never
been in one place more than four weeks. (Librado Romero/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT42) NEW YORK -- Sept. 22, 1999 -- SAKS-OUTLOOK-2, 09-22 --
The stock of Saks Inc. has dropped sharply this year, but Philip
Miller, the president of the Saks Fifth Avenue unit, remains
upbeat. ``We have taken real market share from the competition,''
he says. (Frances Roberts/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT41) COLUMBUS JUNCTION, Iowa -- Sept. 22, 1999 --
CHRISTIAN-DIVERSITY, 09-22 -- The Rev. Bernard Weir, center,
preparing for a Quinceanera (aka 15th birthday celebration) at Our
Lady of Guadalupe Catholic Mission in Columbus Junction. The life
of organized religion in the United States has been growing more
diverse than it was two or three decades ago, and not just in
traditional immigrant gateways like New York and Los Angeles, but
in many small places in between.(Buzz Orr/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT40) JAMALPUR, India -- Sept. 22, 1999 -- INDIA-CASTES-VOTE,
09-22 --Binda Prasad, right, who is the village chief of Jamalpur,
with Lallu Prasad. As hundreds of millions of Indians vote in
national elections this month, it appears that people like the
Prasads, from the most despised castes, are voting in greater
numbers, gaining new influence and turning political calculations
upside down as they refine the very meaning of the centuries-old
caste system. (Celia W. Dugger/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT39) NEW YORK -- Sept. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 26 --
GALLO-THEATER-DESIGNER-1, 09-22 -- The scenic designer David Gallo
at the Helen Hayes Theater, on one of the sets he created for the
play ``Epic Proportions.'' What makes a David Gallo design a David
Gallo design? ``I tend to do things large,'' he says. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) NEW YORK -- Sept. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 26 --
GALLO-THEATER-DESIGNER-2, 09-22 -- Members of the cast of ``You're
a Good Man, Charlie Brown,'' one of several recent Broadway shows
with sets designed by David Gallo. ``I tend to do things large,''
says Gallo, who admits that he consumes anything and everything in
popular culture - vintage comic books, rock-and-roll, Cecil B.
DeMille movies - for visual ideas. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) NEW YORK -- Sept. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 26 --
CONDE-NAST-ARCH-2, 09-22 -- For the growing crowds in Times Square,
just crossing the street can mean waiting in line. Disney is but
one in a group of media giants that have chosen to settle here.
(Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) NEW YORK -- Sept. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 26 --
CONDE-NAST-ARCH-1, 09-22 -- The Conde Nast Building, at right, a
Fox &AMP; Fowle design, is part of a media cluster forming in Times
Square. Joining Conde Nast, publishers of The New Yorker, Vogue,
Vanity Fair, and other glamorous titles, the group includes
Reuters, Bertelesmann, Billboard Publications and MTV. (Chester
Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) NEW YORK -- Sept. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 26 --
BROOKLYN-PHILHARMONIC, 09-22 -- Robert Spano outside the Brooklyn
Academy. For their season that opens on Friday, Spano and the
Brooklyn Philharmonic have put together a set of programs to survey
the 20th century at its end. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) NEW YORK -- Sept. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 26 --
EVE-ENSLER-THEATER, 09-22 -- The playwright Eve Ensler, whose work
``The Vagina Monologues'' was first produced in SoHo in 1996. The
monologues are part of Ms. Ensler's crusade to wipe out the shame
and embarrassment that many women still associate with their bodies
or their sexuality. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) NEW YORK -- Sept. 22, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 26 --
UPSIDE-DOWN-DANCE, 09-22 -- The choreographer Ronald K. Brown and
the poet Cheryl Boyce Taylor during a rehearsal of ``Water'' by
Brown's company, Evidence, in Manhattan. When his company begins
its one-week engagement at the Joyce Theater on Tuesday, it will
present ``Upside Down,'' ``Ebony Magazine,'' and the New York
premiere of ``Water.'' (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) UNDATED -- Sept. 22, 1999 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 09-22
-- Wood in contact with the soil will eventually rot. Builders try
to prevent this by supporting framing members of a house, porch or
deck on masonry footings or a concrete foundation. Even with these
precautions it is possible for wood to rot if it gets wet enough
and if the temperature rises above the freezing mark. (Edward R.
Lipinski/New York Times Illustration) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) NEW YORK -- Sept. 22, 1999 -- RADIO-GIANT, 09-22 --
Listening to ``The Jewish Giant'' are Jenny Carchman, far left,
with her grandmother and father, Dorothy and Philip Carchman. The
powerful 25-minute audio documentary on the life of Eddie Carmel,
whose swollen dimensions were the result of acromegaly and were
caused by a tumor on the pituitary gland, will air on National
Public Radio on Oct. 6. (Frances Roberts/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- Sept. 22, 1999 -- HARLEM-DANCE, 09-22 --
Members of the Dance Theater of Harlem in ``Return'' at City
Center. The company's 30th birthday is happy cause for celebration,
and its gala opening of a two-week anniversary season at City
Center on Tuesday night naturally had a festive atmosphere. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- Sept. 22, 1999 -- LIVINGSTON-FILMS, 09-22 --
Jennie Livingston pitching her new project to Peter Broderick of
Next Wave Films as part of the Independent Feature Film Market. A
deal would be nice, but she's not expecting one. ``They could be
interested or they could just be tracking you,'' says Ms.
Livingston, director of the highly acclaimed documentary ``Paris Is
Burning.'' ``If something happens, something happens. If not, then
I've done what I can do.'' (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- Sept. 22, 1999 -- SAKS-OUTLOOK, 09-22 --
This group of women from Florida can't imagine actually wearing the
clothes by the designer Issey Miyake being displayed at Saks Fifth
Avenue's flagship Manhattan store. Last week Saks, the venerable
clothier to the ladies who lunch, turned 75, but a placid old age
is not in the cards. (Rebecca Cooney/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) UNDATED -- Sept. 22, 1999 -
SUB-MUSEUM-FUNDING-GIULIANI-2, 09-22 -- A portrait of the Virgin
Mary flecked with elephant dung titled ``The Holy Virgin Mary'', by
Chris Ofili. If the directors of the Brooklyn Museum of Art hoped
to provoke the public with such offerings in an exhibition of
cutting-edge British art that opens next week, they may have scored
a publicity coup at the expense of the museum's budget. A catalog
description of this and other pieces so provoked Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani of New York on Wednesday that he vowed to cut funding to
the private but city-subsidized museum until its director ``comes
to his senses.'' (From exhibit catalog ``Sensation'', Thames and
Hudson, 1997/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) TAIPEI, Taiwan -- Sept. 22, 1999 - TAIWAN-QUAKE-2, 09-22
-- Rescue workers use heavy equipment in their search for survivors
early Thursday in a building damaged in Tuesday's earthquake. The
death toll from the powerful quake climbed to over 2,000 people,
with more then 4,000 injured, officials said. Some 2,600 people
were believed to be trapped in rubble, but rescuers were finding
more bodies than survivors as they bored into collapsed houses and
high-rise apartment complexes across central Taiwan. (David L.
Ryan/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) SANTA ROSA, Calif. -- Sept. 22, 1999 -
LIGHTING-STRIKES-FLOATER, 09-22 - Lighting erupts over Santa Rosa
early Wednesday as leftover moisture from Hurricane Hillary was
funneled north bringing simultaneous lightning strikes and heavy
downpours. The photo was taken on the North End of Fountain Grove
on Skyfarm Drive viewing the Santa Rosa Plain to the west. (Kent
Porter/Santa Rosa Press-Democrat) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) UNDATED -- Sept. 22, 1999 -- MUSEUM-FUNDING-GIULIANI,
09-22 -- Damien Hirst's ``This Little Piggy Went To Market, This
Little Piggy Stayed At Home'', which features a halved pig in
formaldehyde solution. If the directors of the Brooklyn Museum of
Art hoped to provoke the public with offerings such as Hirst's
piece in an exhibition of cutting-edge British art that opens next
week, they may have scored a publicity coup at the expense of the
museum's budget. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York on Wednesday
said that he will cut funding to the private but city-subsidized
museum until its director ``comes to his senses'' about the works
on exhibit. (From exhibit catalog ``Sensation'', Thames and Hudson,
1997/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) GREENVILLE, N.C. -- Sept. 22, 1999 --
HURRICANE-CAROLINA-3-B&AMP;W, 09-22 -- An employee of the Greenville
Utilities Commission walks through a water treatment facility on
Tuesday. Flood waters, fouled by waste of all kinds, has rendered
local water supplies undrinkable.(Chris Cummins/Cox News Service
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) BOSTON -- Sept. 22, 1999 -- BBA-COMMENT-BOS, 09-22 --
Boston Red Sox pitcher Pedro Martinez on his way to his 22nd win of
the season, against the Toronto Blue Jays on Tuesday, during which
he also became the second pitcher to record 300 strikeouts in each
league. ``I didn't even know that I broke a record until I looked
at the scoreboard,'' he says. (Jonathan Wiggs/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 22, 1999 - GIFFORD-FLOATER, 09-22 --
Frank Gifford angrily walks away from a panel of the National Labor
Committee on Wednesday after saying the group unfairly attacked his
wife. Three years after his wife, Kathie Lee Gifford, co-host of a
daytime talk show, pledged to help end labor abuses in the apparel
industry, thousands of Salvadoran women still produce clothing for
her label under brutal conditions, the committee, a labor rights
organization, claimed on Tuesday. Mrs. Gifford released a statement
expressing concern over the allegations and pledged to remove her
clothing line from the factory alleged to have abused workers if
her own investigators find trouble.(Paul Hosefros/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 22, 1999 -- RUSSIA-BANK, 09-22 --
Thomas Renyi, chairman of Bank of New York, prepares to testify
before the House Banking and Financial Services Committee on
Wednesday. Renyi, the head of the U.S. bank at the center of
allegations of massive money laundering from Russia, said Wednesday
there had been a lapse in its internal controls but stressed it was
not accused of any wrongdoing. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Sept. 22, 1999 --
FOOD-CHILD-PEPIN-BOS, 09-22 -- Julia Child cooking with Jacques
Pepin in her kitchen in Cambridge. The duo will appear on a new
22-part TV series, ``Julia and Jacques Cooking at Home.'' This is a
new kind of cooking, announces the French-born Pepin. ``Cuisine
d'opportunity,'' he says, pronouncing the English word
``dop-pear-tune-ee-tay'' so it sounds convincingly French. (Suzanne
Kreiter/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Sept. 22, 1999 -- CIR-GAME-MEGAPLEXES-2,
09-22 -- At ESPN Zone, New York Marathon art is overhead. Just
don't call them arcades. In an industry long associated with
violent video games and delinquent teen-agers, these hubs of the
coin-operated game business are embracing a new style to reach a
larger market. (Michelle V. Agins/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Sept. 22, 1999 -- CIR-GAME-MEGAPLEXES-1,
09-22 -- New game centers want to avoid any hint of the seedy.
Broadway City's entrance is designed to be inviting, with an
embedded subway-token replica. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Sept. 22, 1999 -- CIR-OPERA-COMPUTERS, 09-22
-- Michael Hacker uses a computer console to control on-stage
lighting during a rehearsal at the Met. ``The variables are the
people on stage,'' says Hacker, who is comfortable with the
alliance of art and technology. ``They come in late, they don't
stand in the right spot. We have to add, override and adjust
continuously. The computers are the most reliable part.'' (Marilynn
K. Yee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. -- Sept. 22, 1999 --
CIR-GIRLS-SCHOOLS-2, 09-22 -- At Girls' Middle School in Mountain
View, Irene Groethe, left, and Gabrielle Bressack team up on a math
problem. Such independent girls' schools aspire not only to get
girls through adolescence with their self-esteem intact but also to
turn a stereotype on its head - the notion that women do not belong
in technical fields. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) OAKLAND, Calif. -- Sept. 22, 1999 --
CIR-GIRLS-SCHOOLS-1, 09-22 -- At the Julia Morgan School for Girls
in Oakland, Ann Clarke, director, and (from left) Kay Buckley,
Chelsea Maco and Mellissa Gray experiment with dry ice. The school,
which opened its doors for the first time earlier this month, is
one of two independent girls' schools to have started recently in
the San Francisco Bay Area. (Dan Krauss/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) SEDONA, Ariz. -- Sept. 22, 1999 -- ARIZ-SOLAR-HOUSE,
09-22 -- The Hundelt house, near Sedona, functions without the
power grid. Living off the grid, an option that was once available
only to the rich or the intrepid, is going mainstream, at least in
this sunniest corner of the country. (Arizona Public Service/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) BOSTON -- Sept. 22, 1999 -- BBA-COMMENT-BOS, 09-22 --
Boston Red Sox catcher Jason Varitek, left, congratulates pitcher
Pedro Martinez after his 22nd win of the season, a victory over the
Toronto Blue Jays on Tuesday night, during which he also became the
second pitcher to record 300 strikeouts in each league. ``I didn't
even know that I broke a record until I looked at the scoreboard,''
he says. (Jonathan Wiggs/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Sept. 22, 1999 --
GLF-RYDER-SHAUGHNESSY-BOS, 09-22 -- The United States Ryder Cup
golf team in Brookline on Tuesday. More than any international
competition - more than the Olympics, the World Cup or the Davis
Cup - this is the event that reinforces all the stereotypes that
the they, the ``Euros,'' have about us, the Americans. (Jim
Davis/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BOSTON -- Sept. 22, 1999 -- FASHION-COLUMN-BOS, 09-22 --
Julie Crenshaw models a Ryder Cup gown by Badgley Mischka in the
Public Garden in Boston. During this week's Ryder Cup golf
festivities, the players' wives and girlfriends are going to be
decked out Hollywood-style in head-to-toe Mischka, starting
Wednesday night at a Four Seasons gala ball where Celine Dion and
the Boston Pops are scheduled to perform. (Dominic Chavez/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) TAIPEI, Taiwan -- Sept. 22, 1999 - TAIWAN-QUAKE, 09-22 --
Rescue workers, lifted by a crane, use a flashlight to search for
survivors Wednesday night in a building damaged in Tuesday's
earthquake. The death toll from the powerful quake climbed to over
2,000 people, with more then 4,000 injured, officials said. Some
2,600 people were believed to be trapped in rubble, but rescuers
were finding more bodies than survivors as they bored into
collapsed houses and high-rise apartment complexes across central
Taiwan. (David L. Ryan/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MELROSE, Mass. -- Sept. 22, 1999 - DOLE-EDUC, 09-22 --
Mayor Patrick Guerriero, of Melrose, Mass., presents a t-shirt to
Elizabeth Dole during her visit to the high school outside Boston
on Wednesday. Looking on at right is Emily Bachman, Melrose H.S.
senior class president. Framing her education agenda around a
reminiscence of her own teaching days, Dole, the Republican
presidential candidate, called today for parent-approved locker and
backpack searches and drug testing of students.(Wendy Maeda/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Sept. 22, 1999 --
BLOCK-PROFILE-ERNST, 09-17 -- Mark A. Ernst's outside H&AMP;R Block,
where he is expected to become chief executive in a year or so.
Ernst, 41, spent two seasons preparing income tax returns in his
father's office, a job that made him realize that ``this is a very
personal-relationship business.'' (Don Ipock/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 22, 1999 -- TOBACCO-SUIT, 09-22 --
Assistant Attorney General David Ogden, left, and his boss,
Attorney General Janet Reno, take questions from reporters after
announcing the Justice Department's filing of a civil lawsuit
against the tobacco industry on Wednesday. The lawsuit filed in
U.S. District Court in Washington alleges the cigarette companies
conspired since the 1950s to defraud and mislead the American
public and to conceal information about the effects of smoking.
(Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) GREENVILLE, N.C. -- Sept. 22, 1999 --
HURRICANE-CAROLINA-2, 09-22 -- Volunteers load drinking water into
boats for transportation the Gum Swamp Church, one of several
shelters established north of the Tar River, on Wednesday.
Everything from caskets to bloated animal carcasses to household
goods floated in polluted waters flooding parts of an
18,000-square-mile area in the region rendering water supplies
undrinkable.(Jean-Heri White/Greenville Daily Reflector)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) PENDER COUNTY, N.C. -- Sept. 22, 1999 -
HURRICANE-CAROLINA-1, 09-22 -- A stranded dog is confined to a
porch area along the Northeast Cape Fear River on Tuesday. The dog,
along with three others, were left by their owners at the house
which is surrounded by flood waters following heavy rains last week
from Hurricane Floyd. Rescuers patrolling the area left large
supplies of food for the dogs.(Mark Courtney/Wilmington Star-News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Sept. 22, 1999 - GLF-RYDER-CUP-2-BOS,
09-22 -- European Ryder Cup Team members, from left, Jose Maria
Olazabal, Mark James and Colin Montgomerie, look over the Ryder Cup
during a team photo session at The Country Club on Wednesday. The
European team will defend its possession of the Ryder Cup against
the U.S. in competition which begins Friday.(Barry Chin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Sept. 22, 1999 - GLF-RYDER-CUP-BOS,
09-22 -- Fans try to get a better look at U.S. Ryder Cup team
member Tiger Woods during a practice session at The Country Club on
Wednesday. The U.S. will play against Europe in the 33rd Ryder Cup
competition which begins Friday.(Jim Davis/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) PUYI, Taiwan -- Sept. 22, 1999 -- TAIWAN-QUAKE-COX, 09-22
- Luo Jian Zhe, 33, and his wife, react after hearing that the body
of his sister had just been pulled from the rubble of their
destroyed home on Wednesday. Luo is holding a burning incense
stick, a Buddhist practice. Rescuers worked frantically into a
second, critical day Wednesday to uncover an estimated 3,000 people
who may still be buried alive in the ruins of a massive earthquake
that killed more than 1,770 people and smashed entire mountain
towns in central Taiwan.(Joseph P. Albright/Cox News Service Photo)
LITE
