<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUSTICE DEPARTMENT SUES MAJOR TOBACCO COMPANIES
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department filed a far-reaching civil lawsuit
against the big cigarette companies that accuses them of conspiring
since the 1950s to defraud and mislead the public about the health
effects of smoking.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks to recover billions of dollars the government
spent on smoking-related health care for elderly Medicare patients,
veterans and Federal employees.
</P>
<P>
   EARTHQUAKE'S INDUSTRIAL DISRUPTION
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's devastating earthquake could delay or reduce the
production of high-technology items ranging from cellular phones to
Furby dolls _ far broader than just the computer semiconductors
that Taiwan makes in large quantities. By some estimates, it will
take at least two weeks to restore power to industrial areas.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ AND S&AMP;P RISE; DOW FALLS
</P>
<P>
   High-technology stocks powered the Nasdaq market to a sizable
gain, but other major indexes were down. The Nasdaq composite index
was up 37.06 points, to 2,858.16. The Dow Jones industrial average
fell 74.40 points, to 10,524.07, and the broader Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index gained 2.93 points, to 1,310.51.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese yen strengthened, extending its gains against the
dollar amid signs that Japan and its allies would take no immediate
action to curb the currency's rise.
</P>
<P>
   MORGAN STANLEY'S PROFIT UP SHARPLY
</P>
<P>
   Earnings at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter rose 55 percent in the
third quarter, as stock underwriting and merger fees continued to
bolster its bottom line. The company earned $970 million, or $1.65
a share.
</P>
<P>
   STERN PLANS TO SELL THE VILLAGE VOICE
</P>
<P>
   The Village Voice and six alternative weeklies owned by Stern
Publishing are for sale.
</P>
<P>
   XEROX IS BUYING A PRINTER BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   Xerox is buying Tektronix's color printing business for $950
million in cash, moving solidly into second place among printer
makers behind Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC HOLDING LINE ON OIL OUTPUT
</P>
<P>
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries decided to
continue cutting production of crude oil, a move expected to raise
prices for crude oil, gasoline and heating oil this winter.
</P>
<P>
   MORE CUTS AT UNITED TECHNOLOGIES
</P>
<P>
   United Technologies plans to cut its worldwide work force by
14,500 jobs, or about 10 percent of its 142,500 employees.
</P>
<P>
   REALNETWORKS TO ANNOUNCE DEALS
</P>
<P>
   RealNetworks, which makes software for sending audio and video
over the Internet, is expected to announce a series of alliances
with companies that will sell products or provide information to
users of RealJukebox.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIMMUNE TO BUY U.S. BIOSCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   Medimmune Inc., a biotechnology company, said that it had agreed
to acquire U.S. Bioscience, which is developing drugs for cancer
and AIDS, in a stock swap valued at about $492 million. The deal is
the latest in a wave of consolidation in the biotechnology industry
as large and profitable concerns buy smaller companies to add new
drug candidates to their product pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   DATE SET TO LIST STOCKS IN DECIMALS
</P>
<P>
   The Securities Industry Association has chosen July 3, a Monday
when trading is likely to be slow, to start converting stock prices
to decimals from fractions.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN CONCERNS STAYING IN RUSSIA
</P>
<P>
   Foreign businesses trading and manufacturing in Russia are
staying put despite the turmoil, money laundering investigations
and terrorist bombings.
</P>
</TEXT>
