<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-LABTESTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTS FIND NO DRUGS IN ASHBROOK'S SYSTEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB MAHLBURG 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Larry Gene Ashbrook, the paranoid loner who
fatally shot seven people at a Fort Worth church last week before
killing himself, had no drugs in his system, laboratory tests show.
</P>
<P>
   Toxicology results showed no trace of illegal drugs, such as
cocaine and heroin, according to Dr. Angela Springfield, chief
toxicologist for the Tarrant County Medical Examiner's Office.
</P>
<P>
   The tests also found no Prozac, a drug commonly used to treat
depression, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no drugs in his system,'' said Linda Anderson of
the Medical Examiner's Office. ``His toxicology was negative.''
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth police said this week that Ashbrook had been taking
Prozac, but they later retracted the statement and said that they
had made a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   A relative described Ashbrook as a paranoid schizophrenic to the
Wise County Sheriff's Department in July. But state mental health
officials said they had no record of contact with Ashbrook.
</P>
<P>
   A trace amount of alcohol was found during the tests, but
medical officials said the amount was too small to be significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could have taken a teaspoon of cough syrup,'' Anderson
said. ``It would have no effect on anyone's actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashbrook seemed to plunge into bizarre and violent behavior
after his 85-year-old father died in July, acquaintances and police
have said.
</P>
<P>
   FBI officials had also speculated that Ashbrook may have taken
his elderly father's medication shortly before the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The writing changed in the last couple of weeks of the
diary,'' Marjorie Poche of the Dallas FBI office said last week.
``It's only speculation, but he, Larry Ashbrook, may have started
taking his father's medication.''
</P>
<P>
   The medical examiner's office routinely does toxicology tests
after accidental deaths, homicides or any death involving trauma.
Additional tests for substances such as Prozac were conducted on
Ashbrook, Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Ashbrook's family donated his remains to a Dallas medical school
Tuesday, saying they want to do anything they can to help in the
wake of the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
