<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0461 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2391 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-RUSSIA-INVEST-ART-NYT     09-22 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-INVEST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USED TO CHAOS, BUSINESS STAYS PUT IN RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By NEELA BANERJEE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In the last month, Russia has been through what people
in other countries would call mayhem. A low-level war broke out on
the southern border in Dagestan. Then came money-laundering
investigations in the United States and Europe that have implicated
high-ranking Kremlin officials. And in a two-week period, five
terrorist bombings in Moscow and two other cities have left
hundreds dead.
</P>
<P>
   But to foreign businesses, especially those that have been in
Russia for several years, upheaval seems to be part of the
landscape. Despite all these disturbances, foreigners trading and
manufacturing in Russia have decided to stay put. Portfolio
investors in the Russian stock market have been more skittish, but
few have sold their holdings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business people here have seen a lot worse in Russia,'' said
Charles Hecker, a specialist on the former Soviet Union with the
Control Risks Group, a British corporate-security firm. ``They've
seen tanks in the streets in 1993, and they've survived. The
foreigners who've been here a while are usually from pretty hardy
stock.''
</P>
<P>
   If they were not, the foreign executives would have left long
ago. In the last three years, the period when many corporations
began expanding here, Russia has weathered a politically fraught
presidential race, followed by similarly fraught presidential
quintuple-bypass heart surgery. The nation's currency collapsed.
Its government defaulted on $40 billion of debt, half of it held by
foreigners. Six Cabinets and four prime ministers have come and
gone, the latest one, Vladimir Putin, beginning his tenure only in
August.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Russia was ranked as one of the 10 worst places to do
business by Transparency International, a Berlin-based
anti-corruption organization.
</P>
<P>
   Most businesses in Russia had been in a holding pattern long
before recent events. The breakdown of the economy in August 1998
badly damaged investment, and as a rule, businesses are delaying
any new projects until after the presidential elections next year.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the stock market is more sensitive to individual
events than direct investors. The RTS Index, a stock benchmark,
stood at 80.14 at the end of trading Wednesday, down 45 percent
from the 52-week closing high of 147.37 on July 8.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Boone, research chief for the Brunswick Warburg brokerage
house here, attributed the decline to Western investors'
nervousness about emerging markets in general.
</P>
<P>
   But the market decline has deepened since the news of the
bombings. And while hedge-fund investors have not sold their Russia
holdings, few seem to be buying either.
</P>
<P>
   The bombings have frightened foreigners much more than the
financial scandals, even though the latter seem to have more to do
with business. The accusations of money-laundering and suggestions
of high-level corruption may be revelations to people outside
Russia, but foreigners here reconciled themselves long ago to the
murkiness of business and upper-echelon politics. ``For those of us
who are ground-level managers of businesses, this has made very
little difference,'' said Eivind Djupedal, head of Cargill
Enterprises in Russia. ``The operating environment has never been
easy here anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite assurances by law enforcement that the bombers will be
found and punished, few investors seem to believe that. ``There's
no confidence among people who know Russia well that the
presidential administration or the government can, or will, solve
these problems,'' Boone said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, executives worry that the Kremlin could use the
instability from the bombings and the money-laundering scandal to
impose a state of emergency and cancel the presidential elections.
It is widely believed that there are people in President Boris
Yeltsin's inner circle who fear facing prosecution when a new
president comes to power and therefore have an interest in trying
to persuade Yeltsin to halt the elections.
</P>
<P>
   But the government has been careful throughout the troubles to
stress that elections will go forward. Some businesses are willing
to believe the official line until they see otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are looking to elections and thinking, `Will they go
well or not?''' said Scott Blacklin, head of the American Chamber
of Commerce. ``That's what will determine what businesses will do
in Russia.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
