<HEADLINE>
BIG SKY TEAMS TOPSY-TURVY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For those who thought Cal State Northridge, after
a 71-14 loss at Kansas, was headed for a second-division finish in
the Big Sky Conference, take a look at what happened last week.
</P>
<P>
   Montana State, ranked No. 20 in the USA Today/ESPN Division I-AA
poll, was upset 40-37 on the road by unranked Cal Poly SLO.
Northern Arizona, ranked 16th, was blown out at New Mexico 45-14.
</P>
<P>
   Eastern Washington, CSUN's opponent Saturday, was picked to
finish third in the Big Sky by conference coaches but lost at
Portland State 48-39.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Arizona was second in the coaches' poll in July.
Montana State was fifth. If the trend continues, CSUN could luck
out; the Matadors were picked to finish eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what they base those (Big Sky) polls on,'' CSUN
interim head coach Jeff Kearin said. ``I couldn't sit here today
and tell you who the favorite is to win this conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people would say that's Montana, which is ranked No. 2 in
most Division I-AA polls. But the Grizzlies went two overtimes _ at
home _ in their 41-38 win over Sacramento State on Sept. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Eastern Washington head coach Mike Kramer, whose Eagles are 1-2,
said Montana State's soft schedule _ the Bobcats opened against
Chadron State and Western New Mexico _ made last week's loss not as
surprising. Kramer also wasn't shocked by Montana's struggle
against Sacramento State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything really is playing true to form,'' Kramer said.
``The conference is gifted and balanced.''
</P>
<P>
   Kearin said, ``I look at us with a Marcus Brady and wonder how
anyone can count us out.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Hansen hasn't. CSUN is ranked No. 21 in his weekly Division
I-AA Football Gazette Poll.
</P>
<P>
   __ Getting the call: Two weeks ago, Bryson Atkins was so deep on
the depth chart at strong safety, he was playing on the scout team.
Now, because of injuries, the freshman from Alemany High has a shot
at starting against Eastern Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The coaches) said they are giving me an opportunity to
play,'' Atkins said. ``I didn't mind redshirting (the season), but
I wanted to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Atkins is learning the game. He played football only two years
in high school, at San Fernando in 1997 and Alemany in '98, and was
second-team All-Mission League at receiver and defensive back last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Atkins is making the trip to Eastern Washington
because of fellow freshman Travis Campbell's back injury. Campbell
(Westlake) made the travel roster and played briefly at Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Campbell) is a freshma, and he was playing,'' Atkins said.
``I took that as motivation. It made me work harder.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Out sick: Starting tailback Jaumal Bradley missed practice
because of the flu. He is expected to play Saturday. &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
