<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-RUN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEN. KENNEDY SAYS HE'LL SEEK REELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senator Edward M. Kennedy, whose 37-year career in
the Senate is already one of the longest in US history, intends to
run for reelection not only next November but also in the year
2006, he said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Few would have blamed Kennedy for wanting to retire. At age 67,
he has weathered a succession of traumas since his last campaign,
from the death of his mother in 1995 to those of two nephews,
Michael Kennedy and John F. Kennedy Jr., in the past 21 months. He
has worked almost incessantly, colleagues say _ and has built up
such an impressive legislative resume that some privately say he is
at his peak.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of a term beginning in 2007, he would be 81 and would
have spent nearly two-thirds of his life on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   But the senator, who walks on a treadmill five mornings a week
and goes on a yearly low-fat diet, said he has ``every
expectation'' that he will run in the next two elections for his
Senate seat. And his friends, relatives and colleagues were equally
confident he will stay in office as long as he can.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to it,'' Kennedy said, as he entered the
Senate chamber to cast a vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see him enjoying a life of leisure,'' said his son,
Representative Patrick J. Kennedy, Democrat of Rhode Island. ``For
him, the most exciting thing is being in the midst of a legislative
battle. He's at home in the Senate. And because seniority is the
nature of the way this place runs, he's going to be at the top of
his game at the twilight of his career.''
</P>
<P>
   After the plane crash that killed John Kennedy Jr. in August,
Kennedy returned to work exhausted and affected by the loss,
colleagues said.
</P>
<P>
   The accident ``took a lot out of him,'' said Senator Orrin G.
Hatch, Republican of Utah, who considers Kennedy a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch added: ``He is going to be here until he's 115 years old.
He wants to beat Strom Thurmond.''
</P>
<P>
   Another longtime associate predicted in recent weeks that
Kennedy would do just the opposite, retiring in 2006 to avoid
spending his dotage in the public eye. That associate, however, did
not claim to have talked to Kennedy about the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Thurmond, now 96 years old, is the longest-serving senator in
the history of the United States. If he retires at the end of his
term in 2002 as planned, Thurmond, a Republican from South
Carolina, will have been a senator for 47 years.
</P>
<P>
   Other than Thurmond and Kennedy, Senator Robert C. Byrd, a
Democrat from West Virginia, is the only member still in office who
makes the list of the ten longest-serving senators. Byrd, 81, ranks
fourth, having been elected to the Senate in 1958 after serving six
years in the US House of Representatives, where he was inaugurated
in 1953, the year Dwight D. Eisenhower became President.
</P>
<P>
   But Kennedy _ now the ninth-longest serving senator of all time,
elected to office in 1962 _ could ultimately beat them both,
according to Senate Historian Richard A. Baker.
</P>
<P>
   If he campaigns and wins in 2006, Kennedy would have 51 years of
Senate service under his belt by the time that term ended in 2013.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assuming Thurmond and Byrd step down at some point, he could
certainly outlast them all,'' Baker said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 2148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0464 </DOCNO>
