<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Thursday, September 23, on the New York
Times wire. For questions, please call Catherine Laidlaw at
415-777-6057 or the business desk at 415-536-5172. For business
stories running in main news, call the news desk at 415-777-7074.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; FOR THE BUSINESS FRONT OF THE SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INFOMEDIARY _  &LR; The Internet is watching your every move. Web
sites pelt your browser with ``cookie'' files that store
information about you. You've told total strangers your name,
address, age, income bracket and marital status, all for free
e-mail accounts and contests. No less an authority than Scott
McNealy, chief executive of Sun Microsystems, said this year: ``You
have zero privacy anyway. Get over it.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to get over it. You can get around it. Several
software products, some free, let people disguise their identities
online so they can surf without giving up their personal data.
These products help consumers delete privacy-invading cookies and
serve up bogus identities to Web sites that are avid to know all
about them. BY DAN FOST.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INFOMEDSIDE1: &LR;  Tips for consumers to protect their privacy
online. BY DAN FOST.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INFOMEDSIDE2:  &LR; Web sites with more info re online privacy. BY
DAN FOST.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEDIABYTES _  &LR; Broadcasting real news into countries with heavy
censorship has never been easy. But Radio Free Asia, an entity
established by the U.S. Congress in 1996, can do more than just try
to beat the authorities' signal-scramblers. BY DAN FOST.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RADIO _  &LR; Two young entrepreneurs from San Francisco are
embroiled in a legal battle with MTV Networks, after MTV bought
their business, Imagine Radio, and then tried to shut it down and
keep them from working in the industry. BY DAN FOST.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITY-PACIFIC _  &LR; City National Corp., a Southern California bank
holding company, agreed to buy San Francisco-based Pacific Bank for
$153 million in cash and stock to enter Northern California
markets. Beverly Hills, California-based City National will pay $29
for each Pacific Bank share, half in cash and half in stock. That's
a 42 percent premium to Pacific Bank's closing price yesterday.
Pacific, with 292 employees, has $728 million in assets and 12
offices, including branches in Hong Kong and the Cayman Islands. BY
SAM ZUCKERMAN.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
