<HEADLINE>
SILICON VALLEY RESEARCH LAB IS CHANGING ITS DIRECTION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (rk) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A Silicon Valley research laboratory,
established seven years ago to leapfrog generations of computer
technologies, is taking a narrower direction that reflects the
changing interests of the Microsoft co-founder who financed it.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the change, David E. Liddle, a prominent
computer scientist who founded the laboratory, Interval Research
Corp., has stepped down as director. Liddle's relationship with
Paul Allen, the Microsoft Corp. co-founder who seeded Interval with
a $100 million investment over 10 years, grew strained in the past
year, several employees said, as Allen increasingly pushed Interval
to focus its research on his business strategy in the cable
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Interval's original vision was to emulate the pioneering
tradition of Xerox's legendary Palo Alto Research Center, known as
PARC, a hotbed of computer innovation in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Liddle will remain chairman of Interval, which like Xerox's PARC
laboratory, is in Palo Alto, Calif., but will no longer be involved
in the organization's day-to-day activities, according to the
employees. His former executive management duties will be shared by
Arati Prabhakar, who joined Interval as vice president for research
in December 1998, and Douglas Solomon, who as vice president of its
advanced development activities since October 1998 has been
responsible for the commercialization of research results.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have simply formalized something that has been under way
for some time,'' Liddle said Wednesday. He said he hoped to focus
on the opportunity presented by high-speed multimedia networks.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to comment Wednesday, Allen's office referred queries to
Liddle.
</P>
<P>
   When Interval was founded, Allen said he was making a 10-year
financing commitment to support as many as 100 computer scientists
and researchers. Wednesday, the laboratory employs about 70 people.
</P>
<P>
   Liddle was a research scientist at PARC in the 1970s, when the
center was developing many of the ideas and technologies that have
shaped today's computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   PARC pioneered a wide range of technologies, including the laser
printer, the Ethernet office network and the ``graphical user
interface,'' the combination of multiwindow computer screens and
point-and-click navigation on which Apple Computer's Macintosh and
Microsoft's Windows operating system were modeled.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, while other companies grew rich adapting PARC's
inventions, Xerox itself was never successful in personal
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Liddle said he wanted to copy much of the philosophical approach
of the PARC researchers, who treated computer power as plentiful,
memory chips as cheap and data networks as commonplace long before
those technologies were commercially available.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, he made it clear he was not interested in merely
repeating the PARC experience at Interval.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to go in a fundamentally different direction,'' he
said in 1992. ``That vision at PARC has been driving the industry
for a long time. We are not trying to build on that vision but to
construct a new one.''
</P>
<P>
   But shortly after it was founded, Interval began to shift its
strategy toward a more business-oriented and less open-ended
research focus. In 1996, the research firm announced the first of
four projects being spun off as venture-financed start-ups. To
date, none have been notably successful, and Purple Moon, a
software firm started by an Interval researcher, Brenda Laurel,
went bankrupt this year before being sold to Mattel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked in areas where we found that commercialization has
been very hard,'' Liddle said.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, employees said, Interval has shifted its efforts to
areas like market research for the cable industry and developing
technologies for delivering interactive multimedia products and
content over cable, both of which serve the immediate needs of
Allen's rapidly expanding cable empire.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a vision of a wired world, and Paul is at the center
of it,'' Liddle said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although Liddle and Allen had been close until recently _ the
two would fly around the country in Allen's jet and would play rock
music together on guitars _ their relationship has suffered in
recent years. Allen has become more involved in day-to-day
activities at Interval, and his mother and sister have also played
a role in some decisions, according to people close to the research
center's affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working for Paul is about working for a family business in the
final analysis,'' said a consultant with close ties to the cable
industry.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Moreover, in recent years the growing perception in Silicon
Valley has been that Interval is not able to make the kinds of big
breakthroughs that were the trademark of Xerox's PARC in the 1970s
and of SRI International in the previous decade.
</P>
<P>
   That view has been accented by Liddle's management style, which
has been to keep research at Interval under tight secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   Computer industry analysts have come to believe that Liddle's
challenge in trying to orchestrate breakthroughs was formidable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Creating a community of people making a revolution is not
something that can be forced or ordered,'' said James F. Moore,
president of Geopartners and a computer and telecommunications
industry consultant. ``Xerox PARC was a fortuitous event. There
have been lots of other research greenhouses that have never
created flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting more than a year ago, Allen began refocusing the
research at Interval toward the needs of his Charter Communications
cable company which has been aggressively consolidating smaller,
second-tier cable companies around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The more pragmatic focus has led to several defections by
researchers but nothing approaching an exodus. But in interviews
Wednesday, several Interval employees said they were unsure about
the long-term future of the laboratory and whether Allen would
continue to finance the center.
</P>
</TEXT>
