<HEADLINE>
PIRATES FLOODED OUT BY HURRICANE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're the only team in the nation being held hostage, without
a home, or for that matter, a campus.
</P>
<P>
   That's the predicament facing East Carolina, which is spending
the week in Columbia, S.C., where it played South Carolina last
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Flooding caused by Hurricane Floyd closed a number of roads and
highways in and around Greenville, N.C., where the school is
located.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates are forced to stay in Columbia as they prepare for
this week's ``home'' game against Miami. Part of Greenville is
without electricity, and the drinking water isn't safe. School is
closed for the week.
</P>
<P>
   About 25 players, roughly one-fourth of the team, lost their
belongings. They happened to live near the Tar River, which has
overrun its banks in record flooding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their apartments are gone and everything they own is gone,''
East Carolina coach Steve Logan said.
</P>
<P>
   The flooding has even caused Saturday's game to be moved from
East Carolina to North Carolina State, which is located about 70
miles west in Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates have practiced at the University of South Carolina
in the morning. The Gamecocks have the facilities in the afternoon.
Logan and his staff have used makeshift video and scouting
facilities and meeting rooms while trying to maintain a sense of
normalcy in practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we're practicing, that's the only time we're not worrying
about what's going on back home,'' Logan said.
</P>
<P>
   Logan has had to keep his team entertained. They went to the
movies Monday and Tuesday, and Wednesday they went bowling. It has
all made Logan uncertain about how his team will play against the
Hurricanes (no pun intended).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to play,'' Logan said. ``I just don't know how
WELL we'll play.''
</P>
<P>
   __ The feud continues: The sniping between Colorado and
Washington has not subsided as the teams prepare for Saturday's
encounter in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Former Colorado coach Rick Neuheisel, who is now at Washington,
picked at the scabs of the rivalry by saying that comments Colorado
coach Gary Barnett made in a CNN/SI interview last spring portrayed
Neuheisel as a liar.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were comments he made . . . that questioned my veracity,
whether I was telling the truth regarding recruiting (violations)
and so forth,'' Neuheisel said. ``And I don't know where where he
comes off questioning that.''
</P>
<P>
   After violating an NCAA ``quiet'' recruiting period last winter
(Washington assistants were in recruits' homes on the Sunday before
signing day), Neuheisel was penalized by the Pacific-10 Conference.
Neuheisel called it an ```honest mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   He explained later that his NCAA rule book had not been unpacked
after his move from Boulder to Seattle _ which Colorado's
compliance office is still laughing about.
</P>
<P>
   In the CNN/SI interview, Barnett said he answered, ``Only Rick
knows that,'' when asked if he believed if Neuheisel knew he was
violating NCAA rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``I meant just what I said: He's the only one that knows,''
Barnett said this week.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Barnett continues to use props to motivate his team.
He entered last Thursday night's team meeting dressed in fatigues,
boots and helmet perched above a blackened face as the Buffaloes
prepared to face Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   A clip of Gen. George S. Patton's impassioned pre-battle speech
from the movie ``Patton'' had been plugged in and was ready to roll
on a giant screen in the team auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   In Barnett's minidrama, a tape played behind him showing the
final minutes of the Buffaloes' 33-17 loss last fall at Kansas.
There were also blown-up newspaper accounts of one of Neuheisel's
14 defeats in Boulder.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado defeated Kansas 51-17.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hidden treasure: Indiana quarterback Antwaan Randle-El is not
nationally known, but he should be. He ran for 115 yards and three
touchdowns and passed for 201 yards and one score in a 44-35 loss
to Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Randle-El has rushed for over 1,000 career yards and passed for
more than 2,000 yards, and done both faster than any player in NCAA
history.
</P>
<P>
   He passed those standards in 13 games, five less than it took
Minnesota quarterback Ricky Foggie, six less than Major Harris
required at West Virginia and eight less than Michael Bishop of
Kansas State needed.
</P>
<P>
   __ Badge of courage: Give Central Florida some credit for its
schedule. The Knights are in the midst a brutal opening. The
Division I-A school from Orlando, which is playing its first season
without quarterback Daunte Culpepper, opened against Purdue before
playing at Florida and Georgia Tech, where the Knights lost 41-10
on Saturday. This week, they take a trip to Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   __ Poll problems: Before taking the top-25 polls too seriously,
keep this in mind: One voter has ranked Virginia Tech No. 1 since
the preseason, while another voter forgot to put No. 15 Kansas
State in his top 25 last weekend. &QL; 
SCOTT WOLF'S TOP 10 &QL; 
__ 1. Florida State (3-0) _ 'Noles became first team in '90s to win
100 games (100-13-1). &QL; 
__ 2. Florida (3-0) _ Gainesville declares Spurrier's visor a local
landmark. &QL; 
__ 3. Penn State (4-0) _ If Arrington stays away from punter, he'll
glide to Butkus Award. &QL; 
__ 4. Nebraska (3-0) _ Larry Smith would rather be playing Oregon
this week. &QL; 
