<HEADER>
A2399 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOODS-TOWN23-COX     09-22 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOODS-TOWN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Too much death for N.C. towns
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINETOPS, N.C. _ Not all the dead are resting after Hurricane
Floyd killed more than 40 people in North Carolina and unearthed
coffins along swollen rivers.
</P>
<P>
   In neighboring Wilson, sobbing relatives Wednesday buried three
of the storm's victims, killed when a boat capsized last week near
Pinetops. But widespread flooding has delayed other burials across
eastern North Carolina, devastated by the state's worst natural
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Coffins and vaults bobbing in floodwaters have become an
unsettling sight, and some survivors don't want to bury their loved
ones in muddy graves. In nearby towns such as Rocky Mount, high
water separates bodies stored in hospital morgues from out-of-town
kin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is horrible,'' said Brenda Wright, nursing supervisor at
Nash General Hospital in Rocky Mount. Its morgue has room for
eight, prompting officials to bring in a refrigerated
tractor-trailer for Floyd's victims.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday, three of the hospital's 10 storm dead had been
delivered to funeral homes.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining seven were in the trailer, partly to prevent the
odor of decomposing flesh from fouling the morgue, Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   At least three graves in Pinetops have been ripped apart by
flood waters.
</P>
<P>
   Still, state officials said floating corpses in caskets pose far
less of a health risk than widespread municipal and farm sewage
spills.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing the spread of disease, officials are scrambling to
dispose of more than 100,000 hogs, 2.4 million chickens and 500,000
turkeys that drowned.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no health risk involved with an embalmed body,'' said
Jeff Winstead, an official with the state's emergency response team
in Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   The state medical examiner's office has a procedure for
identifying and reinterring corpses, Winstead said. But considering
the sewage and livestock threats, he said, ``That is not one of the
emergency issues.''
</P>
<P>
   As waters recede, Dr. John Butts, the state's chief medical
examiner, said he expects the official death toll of 41 to rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we expecting the number to increase? Yes,'' Wright said.
``It may be three or four more. It may be 10 more. I do not know.''
</P>
<P>
   In Aynor, embalmer Don Brown prepared two bodies over the
weekend, but flooding prevented him from releasing them to funeral
homes in Williamston and Elizabeth City.
</P>
<P>
   Rest Haven Cemetery in Wilson had dried out enough for
Wednesday's burial of Ben and Vivian Mayo and their 23-year-old
daughter, Keisha Vines. Vines' 5-year-old daughter, Tekisha, also
apparently died, but her body was not found until Tuesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were fortunate,'' Josephine Edwards, director of Edwards
Funeral Home, said as she greeted some of the several hundred
people who attended the two-hour service at the L.N. Forbes
Original Free Will Baptist Tabernacle.
</P>
<P>
   The three Mayo family members from Pinetops were among six
people who drowned a week ago in flooding from Town Creek in
Edgecombe County. Remembered during the service as a hero who tried
to save neighbors, Ben Mayo, 50, had steered the boat that
overturned, killing half the 12 aboard in Hurricane Floyd's most
deadly accident.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a mile away, a 6- to 8-foot swell rushed across the
low ground along Town Creek and unearthed two vaults in an old
cemetery along Bynum Farm Road.
</P>
<P>
   A third hole is empty, but Pinetops Mayor Earl Coker said he's
not sure whether it had contained a casket.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a week since flooding uncovered the stone vaults.
</P>
<P>
   One was turned on its side, with one end pointing into the sky.
Another poked from the ground, its lid ajar. Etching on the cover
identified the deceased as ``James Cobb,'' who died May 21, 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Another who is buried there is Simpson Cobb. His widow's
brother, B.C. Pitt of Pinetops, said it could be days before the
small graveyard is tended.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the people who look after the cemetery have been flooded
out of their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is something that happened beyond our control,'' said Pitt,
who is staying at the emergency shelter in Carver Elementary School
in Pinetops.
</P>
<P>
   If residents are able to restore the graves, volunteer fire and
rescue Chief Steve Bynum said, ``the county will make sure they are
taken care of.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
