r s BC-OUT-PAULY-COLUMN-LADN     09-22 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-PAULY-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL ANGLING EVENT MIGHT BE ON WAY OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fall for outdoorsmen is ushered in by deer season, waterfowl
hunting, rockfishing . . . and, most important, the state's
biannual Free Fishing Day.
</P>
<P>
   That day is Saturday, when the usual requirement of possessing a
fishing license is waived in an attempt to draw more people into
the wonderful world of angling. So, yes, Virginia, there is such a
thing as a free lunch _ if you actually catch something.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allows for the opportunity to learn and enjoy the
experience of fishing . . . because it's free. To see how you like
the sport before investing more time and money,'' said Elaine
Fischer, a fish and wildlife interpreter in the Department of Fish
and Game's Long Beach office.
</P>
<P>
   And if the only day of the year you decide to fish is Saturday,
it represents a savings of $27.55 on an annual resident
sport-fishing license (or $10 for a two-day license).
</P>
<P>
   It's the DFG's version of a get-out-of-jail-free card, except,
I'll have you know, that all other fishing rules regarding such
things as angling hours, bait restrictions and size and possession
limits still apply to any waters where fishing is permitted. So
brush up on the DFG's ``Sport Fishing Regulations'' handbook if
you're at all in doubt. (Anglers 15 and younger get a year-round
reprieve, never needing to have a fishing license.)
</P>
<P>
   Free fishing is the great news. The bad news is that the brakes
are being applied to fall's national equivalent of Free Fishing
Day. Unfortunately, National Hunting and Fishing Day is being
phased out by its organizers. But more on that later; I'm
definitely the type of guy who likes the good news before the bad
news.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday is designed by the DFG as a way to ensure its future.
The notion is that by bringing in new blood, fishing will continue
to flourish. Sage wisdom. My applause.
</P>
<P>
   To court prospective anglers, a free catfishing derby is slated
Saturday from 8 to 11 a.m. at La Mirada Park Lake, 13701 S. Adelfa
Ave. in La Mirada.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can borrow a loaner rod and reel,'' Fischer said. ``Many
people get very interested that way in a sport they've never tried
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Trophies will be doled out to youngsters with the heaviest
catches. A complimentary pancake breakfast will kick the event off
at 7 a.m. Information: (626) 333-1369. (See Page 14 for a map and
listing of other fishing holes.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the second part of the annual equation for this
special fourth Saturday of September has traditionally been
National Hunting and Fishing Day. Designated in 1972 by
then-president Richard Nixon, it was set aside to encourage
participation, conservation and safety in outdoor activities.
</P>
<P>
   But the 28th annual festivity has lost its luster. Its sponsor,
the National Shooting Sports Foundation, is phasing out National
Hunting and Fishing Day in favor of another program called Step
Outside. Step Outside invites experienced recreationists to bring
uninitiated friends and family members on hunting, shooting and
fishing excursions.
</P>
<P>
   ``(National Hunting and Fishing Day) is one day of the year and
Step Outside is more encompassing,'' explained National Shooting
Sports Foundation spokeswoman Colleen Swain.
</P>
<P>
   That might be true, but methinks you can't underestimate that
unique day.
</P>
<P>
   In years past, details on such essential matters as what states
honor National Hunting and Fishing Day and where events are being
staged were provided. Apparently that's a thing of the past.
``We're cutting down, that's basically why,'' Swain said.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a shame, for example, that NHFD's national director,
C.D. ``Chris'' Chaffin, chose this particular week to be away from
the National Shooting Sports Foundation's Newtown, Conn.,
headquarters and unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Swain remains upbeat about NHFD. ``I don't think interest will
dwindle,'' she said. ``Those sportsmen's clubs and individuals who
promote these things will continue to do them.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, several states likely will carry the National Hunting
and Fishing Day flame, but when the coach loses interest in the
remainder of the season, it's hard to rally the team.
</P>
<P>
   Call the National Shooting Sports Foundation at (203) 426-1320
to get involved in next year's National Hunting and Fishing Day, if
it's still around then. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
