<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-INVEST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTMENTS OF STATE FUNDS BY COMPANY THAT DIDN'T MEET GUIDELINES
LOST VALUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By R.A. DYER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Public school funds invested by a Dallas firm
have shrunk by millions of dollars, failing to keep pace with other
school fund investments and industry averages, records indicate.
</P>
<P>
   Despite not meeting guidelines set by the State Board of
Education, Barrow, Hanley, Mewhinney &AMP; Strauss was among nine firms
awarded contracts by the board in 1997 to manage portions of the
$19 billion state Permanent School Fund.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the State Board said members were not told that
Barrow, Hanley did not meet the minimum guidelines, and has
expressed concern about how the contracts were awarded.
</P>
<P>
   According to records, the company in 1998 began managing
investments of $200 million from the fund _ a public endowment used
to pay for textbooks, and managed by the State Board of Education.
But by June 30 of this year, the market value of the investments
had fallen to about $179 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Barrow, Hanley investments underperformed those of the eight
other money managers hired by the State Board in 1997. The Barrow,
Hanley investments, however, outperformed others investing in
similar equities during the three-month period ending June 30.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it is the firm's policy not to discuss
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Firm partner Michael Mewhinney is a close friend and former
business associate of Gov. George W. Bush. In 1993, Mewhinney owned
3.7 percent of the Texas Rangers at the same time Bush served as
the team's general managing partner.
</P>
<P>
   Mewhinney announced his retirement from Barrow, Hanley on May
26, saying he planned to work on the governor's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Bush has said the governor played no role in
selecting money managers for the Permanent School Fund. Likewise,
the spokeswoman said Mewhinney had no formal position with the Bush
campaign, nor had any formal position been proposed for him.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Ballard, acting director of the Permanent School Fund, said
Barrow, Hanley uses an investment strategy that did not pay off
when the company first received the investment contract.
</P>
<P>
   He said, however, that the strategy appears to have been more
successful in recent months, when the Barrow, Hanley investments
outperformed other small/mid cap equity investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They buy deep, boring stocks _ those that are not very sexy _
like a barge company with a good cash flow,'' he said. ``It's the
kind of market that does well when the global economy starts to
pick up. But the style doesn't work all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   But former State Board member Jack Christie, who was chairman of
the panel when the contracts were awarded in 1997, said he would
rethink the contracts if he found that any of the fund managers had
lost money after one year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would red-flag my desire to continue,'' said Christie, a
Republican from Houston. ``As long as we've had outside money
managers, none of them were in a deficit for the year.''
</P>
<P>
   State Board Chairman Chase Untermeyer said this week that he
might ask the board to reconsider all the money management
contracts it has awarded since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Untermeyer said a newly hired financial consultant will review
the board's investment policy and submit recommendations to the
board at its next meeting in November.
</P>
<P>
   Untermeyer earlier wrote the office of Attorney General John
Cornyn asking for an investigation into whether unspecified money
managers misled the board or misdirected Permanent School Fund
investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to look at (Barrow, Hanley), as well as all the other
money managers,'' Untermeyer said Tuesday. ``Money managers should
be judged on the basis of performance _ that should be the board's
primary concern. But I have been told that you need to look at it
over a period of time. ... You can't do it on the basis of one
quarter or one year.''
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's office has said Cornyn is considering
Untermeyer's request.
</P>
<P>
   According to a review of Permanent School Fund investments
prepared for the board by a Dallas consulting firm, the investments
made by Barrow, Hanley lost 5 percent of their net value between
July 1, 1998, and June 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Over the same period, the consultants' report showed, the median
value of similar small/mid cap equity investments by other money
managers nationwide rose 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the last quarter for which information was available _ the
months of April, May and June _ Barrow, Hanley's Permanent School
Fund investments grew by 18.6 percent _ higher than the industry
median of 15.8 percent, the report shows.
</P>
<P>
   Barrow, Hanley was one of four firms hired specifically to make
investments in the stocks of small and mid-sized corporations.
</P>
<P>
   The report also shows that investments handled by one of the
three other firms _ Harbor Capital _ fell by 3.62 percent in the
one-year period.
</P>
<P>
   The value of those Permanent School Funds invested in
small/mid-cap equities increased overall from $800 million to
$806.5 million since the contracts were awarded.
</P>
<P>
   The State Board of Education has paid Barrow, Hanley more than
$1 million, despite their investments' loss of value.
</P>
<P>
   Barrow, Hanley received the Permanent School Fund investment
contract even though their proposal did not meet guidelines set
forth by the State Board, records show.
</P>
<P>
   In submitting their proposal, for example, the firm showed less
than two years' returns in placing small/mid cap equity investments
_ even though the initial screening document on the state board's
bid request called for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Barrow, Hanley stated in its proposal that it could claim a
five-year track record by counting previous investments made by a
manager while working at a different company.
</P>
<P>
   The initial screening questionnaire also called for ``at least
five investment professionals dedicated full time to the services
proposed.'' The company reported it had two such professionals,
although those two worked with a larger team handling other sorts
of investments.
</P>
<P>
   The State Board of Education received 55 applications for firms
to handle small/midcap equities investments, records show. Of
those, Barrow, Hanley were ranked 50th and 51st on two listings
prepared by financial consultant Fred C. Seponara, records show.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the 15 State Board members, who are elected by
districts, now say that Texas Education Agency officials _ as well
as Seponara _ did not provide sufficient information.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Neill, a Fort Worth Republican on the board, said that
the initial screening questionnaire set forth ``minimum eligibility
criteria'' and that Seponara did not inform the board of Barrow,
Hanley's lack of a track record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very concerned,'' he said. ``We were not provided any of
that information.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a ``manager search quality control'' document provided
by Seponara to the board after the contract awards indicated that
Barrow, Hanley answered yes to all the preliminary questions on the
initial screening questionnaire.
</P>
<P>
   Seponara's report also indicated that Barrow, Hanley is
``domiciled in Texas'' _ even though records show that the company
is owned by United Asset Management, a Boston firm.
</P>
<P>
   Seponara, reached at his Blue Bell, Pa., office, could provide
no explanation as to why his firm's quality control document
contained apparently erroneous information about the firm.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
