<SLUG> BC-FILM-JAKOBTHELIAR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUTH IS, `LIAR' TAKES THE COWARD'S WAY OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The tradition of short stories in which deception and pain
devastate the life of the protagonist can be found in the novel
``Jakob the Liar'' by Jurek Becker (Penguin, $11.95). But if you're
looking for similar complexity in the film adaptation starring
Robin Williams at his dampest and neediest, you'd be advised to
give the book another shot. Williams is Jakob, detained in a
Nazi-occupied ghetto with thousands of other Jews. While waiting
for humiliation at the hands of a Nazi, Jakob happens to overhear
on the Nazis' radio a piece of news that is so powerful even the
Nazi propaganda machine can't put too good a face on it: Russian
forces are threatening to overrun the Germans at the Polish border,
not too far from the ghetto.
</P>
<P>
   The news is too much for Jakob. He leaks it to a slow-witted but
well-meaning boxer friend (Liev Schreiber), who not only blabs
about the possibility of Soviet saviors but also says that Jakob
has a secret radio. This misinformation gives a cast including
Armin Mueller-Stahl, Alan Arkin and, most embarrassingly, Bob
Balaban a chance to compete for the most eye-moistening attention.
Coming after the stylized approach of ``Life Is Beautiful,'' which
dealt with the Holocaust in similar terms, ``Jakob'' has almost no
chance of gaining an audience. For the material to work, the movie
would have to be a lot more daring in its mix of bleak humor and
hopelessness, focusing on a narrator and central figure who is
essentially unreliable. (His unreliability is the point of the
story.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Jakob'' is too intent on winning us over to gamble on such a
stratagem. Its timidity, flinching from a great subject, results in
an ending determined to make audiences leave the theater feeling
uplifted. Maybe the Robin Williams who starred in ``The World
According to Garp'' would've been up for starring in a film about
finding slivers of hope only to have them dashed before your eyes,
or for playing a man who was untrustworthy instead of someone
ennobled by torment. Nowadays, he might have forced a happy ending
even on ``Garp.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jakob the Liar'' is rated PG-13 for adult subject matter,
violence and mild sexuality. .MDNM/ (Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 2154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
