<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DOUBLEJEOPARDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASHLEY JUDD PUTS HER MOVIE CAREER IN `JEOPARDY'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ashley Judd needs a new agent _ and quick.
</P>
<P>
   Stardom for the sister of Wynonna and daughter of Naomi has been
predicted for years, ever since her memorable portrayal of a young
woman trying to make her way in a hard world in ``Ruby in
Paradise.''
</P>
<P>
   Put Judd in a dress, and she's the most beautiful woman on
Earth; put her in jeans and a T-shirt, and she's the sweet young
lady next door. Either way, she has this no-nonsense-but-tender
presence; we sense that she won't settle for less than she
deserves, won't give up without a fight.
</P>
<P>
   And it's that mixture of toughness and sexiness that, along with
a strong turn as a woman who escapes a perverted serial kidnapper
in 1997's not-scary-enough ``Kiss the Girls,'' that has
anticipation so high for ``Double Jeopardy.'' She and Tommy Lee
Jones share above-the-title billing, but this is cleary Judd's shot
at stardom.
</P>
<P>
   I hope she gets another: ``Double'' is a film lousy with
telegraphed plot twists, moments borrowed from other movies, and
cliched characters _ and, oh yeah, yet another chance for Jones to
play Mr. Tough Guy. Like we haven't seen that a dozen times.
</P>
<P>
   Judd plays Libby Parsons, the wife of egomaniacal rich guy Nick
(a bland Bruce Greenwood); the two go sailing on a boat he's about
to buy her, and she wakes up covered with blood _ with bloody
footprints indicating that ol' Nick cut himself up and jumped into
the water.
</P>
<P>
   She's convicted of his murder and sent to prison, where she
learns that A) Nick is alive and living with her son, Matty, and
her supposed best friend, Angie (a wooden Annabeth Gish), and B)
the double jeopardy rule: A person can't be convicted twice for the
same crime, so she's free to off ol' Nick when she's sprung.
</P>
<P>
   What happens next is about as suspenseful as watching concrete
harden _ Libby follows Nick's trail from San Francisco to Colorado
to New Orleans, with Jones (clearly slumming here _ how bad does he
need money?) dogging her trail and losing her several times.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that the trailer basically gives away the
entire movie, beginning to end. But that aside, anybody older than,
say, 5 could guess what will happen next. And next. And next.
</P>
<P>
   Judd does the best she can, under these dire circumstances;
she's a presence, no doubt about it, and the big screen loves her.
She deftly maneuvers Libby's moments of bewilderment, determination
and terror _ the part is all about just not giving up, and she
finds a home in it.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, there are a few interesting twists: Much of the plot
revolves around a piece of artwork by European modernist Wassily
Kandinsky, and there's a nice reference to ``The Vanishing'' in the
film's last third.
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately, these touches do not a good, suspenseful film
make, and ``Jeopardy'' sinks into a paint-by-the-numbers female
revenge fantasy. Judd clearly deserves better _ and after this film
bombs (as it deserves to) one hopes that she might get better
material and better co-stars. Then we might really see something.
</P>
<P>
   ``Double Jeopardy'' is rated R for violence, brief partial
nudity, language and a particularly bloody crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
