<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INFOMEDSIDE1-PRIVACY-SIDEBAR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TURNING DOWN COOKIES, CREATING PHONY IDENTITIES
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DAN FOST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
People concerned about online privacy can take matters into their
own hands.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Davis, CEO of Lumeria, offered some tips for protecting
privacy online.
</P>
<P>
   You can go into your browser's preferences file and turn off
cookies, but you soon will discover just how many sites require
that you accept a cookie. Plus, privacy advocates note, there are
cookies that users want to accept, such as those that remember a
password and save users the trouble of retyping it each time they
visit a site.
</P>
<P>
   Davis recommends that you never give your true identity when
signing up for something online. &UR;  &LR; If you're an old man in Northern
California, perhaps you want to sign up as a young woman in
Seattle. (But be careful: I gave a bogus ZIP code when I signed up
for a free Internet fax service and wound up with a number in the
wrong area code. When I tried to sign up again, the service
wouldn't let me _ it had placed a cookie on my browser and knew I
was back for more.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Another way to mask your identity is to set up free e-mail
accounts, like those available at a portal site (such as Yahoo or
Excite) or at Hotmail, and use them in identifying yourself around
the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public is concerned, and yet they still go around the Net
and fill out the correct information on forms,'' Davis said,
shaking his head in disbelief. ``People are honest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 2159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0482 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2413 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-TIGER23-COX     09-22 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-TIGER23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woods seeking a Spain painkiller
 &HT;    By Craig Dolch
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ It remains the only blemish on his
professional resume.
</P>
<P>
   Since turning professional three years ago, Tiger Woods has won
two majors and 12 PGA Tour titles, made almost $9 million in
official earnings while helping purses double and _ breath, please
_ increased the number of minorities who play or watch the sport.
</P>
<P>
   But he's never won a Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Woods' only previous Ryder Cup experience was a disaster in
1997, as the world's No.1-ranked player went 1-3-1 for the losing
American team at Valderrama. It was no coincidence that Sports
Illustrated made him its cover boy with the inscription, ``The Pain
In Spain.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods gets a chance to ease that memory this week as he's
expected to lead the favored American team to victory in the 33rd
Ryder Cup matches at The Country Club. His critics will point out
he also was expected to do the same in 1997, but Woods knew better.
</P>
<P>
   It may have been just five months since his record-setting
victory at the Masters, but Woods was in the middle of changing his
swing and he knew he wasn't going to Valderrama with his so-called
``A-game.'' Despite possessing one of the best match-play records
as an amateur _ he was a combined 42-3 while winning a trio of U.S.
Amateurs and U.S. Junior Amateur championships _ Woods wasn't
surprised he struggled in Spain, even losing to Costantino Rocca in
singles 4-and-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '97, I wasn't playing very well from the Western (Open) on,
and unfortunately it carried over into the Ryder Cup,'' Woods said.
``But this year I'm coming into the tournament with more of a
positive attitude and rightfully so. I've played well this
summer.'' Woods has won five of his past eight tournaments,
including the PGA Championship and the NEC Invitational against
stellar fields. Throw out his 37th-place finish at the Sprint
International because it came one week after his exhausting victory
at Medinah, and Woods has finished in the top 10 in his past seven
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger at this moment is playing some of the best golf of his
young career,'' U.S. captain Ben Crenshaw said. ``He has a very
strong mind to play this game at the highest level. And he's a
very, very smooth engine right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw's counterpart, European captain Mark James, was more
praising. ``Tiger's obviously the dominant figure in the game at
the moment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The European team can take solace only by knowing that Woods, as
brilliant as he's been playing, cannot win the Ryder Cup by
himself. ``All one player can do is win five points,'' says
Europe's Colin Montgomerie, ``and it takes 14 1/2 to win.''
</P>
<P>
   True, but Woods' presence alone seems to give the Americans a
decided advantage. And not just with his length on a course, where
he can drive two of the par-4s. There's also the psychological edge
he can provide teammates with his dominant play.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he goes out there and plays the way he's capable, then
that's going to be a big advantage for us,'' Jim Furyk said. ``That
in itself could probably bring the rest of us up to a better
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Many believed Woods failed to own up to his leadership role at
Valderrama, but he insists he simply was acting his age.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were criticizing me for not being a vocal leader. Well,
I was 21 years old and playing in my first Ryder Cup,'' Woods said.
``It's like saying Sergio (Garcia) needs to be the leader of the
(European) team when he's got some players who have been around 20
years. That would be doing them an injustice and not giving them
the respect they deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Woods no longer calls the Ryder Cup an ``exhibition,''
he refuses to overstate the importance of what happens this
weekend. He says he's going to try his hardest to finally put his
hands on the gold chalice, but he won't let a defeat ruin his
record run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's going to make or break your career,'' he
said. ``If we lose the Ryder Cup, I don't think I'm going to look
back and say it's a bad year. I've won six times this year. It's
been a pretty good year.''
</P>
<P>
   And it will become even better if that blemish gets removed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
