r f BC-MEDIABYTES-COLUMN-SFC     09-22 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIABYTES-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 AIRING REAL NEWS IN ASIA A RISKY BUSINESS
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DAN FOST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
Broadcasting real news into countries with heavy censorship has
never been easy. But Radio Free Asia, an entity established by
Congress in 1996, can do more than just try to beat the
authorities' signal-scramblers.
</P>
<P>
   It puts its news on the Web, at www.rfa.org.
</P>
<P>
   The private, nonprofit corporation _ which still gets all of its
funding from Congress _ seeks to put objective news on the air and
on the Web, into places like China, Laos, Burma, Vietnam, Cambodia
and North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in addition to scrambling the radio signals,
governments in those countries try to stifle access to the Web
site, and to the Internet in general. But that's a trickier task
because Asian countries also want to use the Internet to boost
their own economies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attitude of the Chinese government toward the Internet has
been defensive,'' said Zhang Weiguo, a visiting scholar at the
Graduate School of Journalism at the University of California at
Berkeley and a contributor to Radio Free Asia. In an e-mail
interview conducted through an interpreter, he explained, ``They
hope to benefit from the Internet economically, but at the same
time, they don't want to lose control politically.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiguo said Internet use is growing fast in China; although
experts predicted there would be 1.2 million accounts this year
(with each account likely to have multiple users), actual tallies
show more than 4 million accounts, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet has made it possible for the Chinese people to
have one more way to communicate with the outside world,'' he said.
``With the Internet, they inform the rest of the world what's
really happening inside China, and they can also find out what's
happening outside China.''
</P>
<P>
   That's essentially the Radio Free Asia model in all the
countries it covers. Pat Lute, a spokeswoman for the Washington,
D.C., service, was in San Francisco last week touting RFA's network
of correspondents who risk their lives to break news.
</P>
<P>
   She described correspondents in Changmai, Thailand, who
interview Burmese refugees as soon as they cross the border,
bringing news of that closed society.
</P>
<P>
   Lute warned people not to confuse RFA with Voice of America,
which still pumps U.S. propaganda around the world in English.
Radio Free Asia uses only native speakers and tries to provide its
audience with objective journalism.
</P>
<P>
   When the U.S. bombed the Chinese embassy in Belgrade this
spring, RFA's Web site hosted a lively debate over whether the
action was deliberate or accidental. One person accused everyone at
RFA of being spies for the United States, but Lute said such
postings proved its independence. ``It was exactly what democracy
is about,'' she said, ``a free and open exchange of ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   IN FAVOR OF JUNKETS: Leave it to John C. Dvorak, the
curmudgeonly dean of trade-publication tech journalists, to spark a
debate on what looks like a no-brainer.
</P>
<P>
   Dvorak's contrarian take: Why not let reporters take junkets
from tech companies?
</P>
<P>
   The question seems as easy to answer as why not allow payola. If
a journalist lets a company pay the way for, say, an overseas trip,
won't that somehow color the news coverage? Won't it damage the
hard-earned credibility of news organizations if they let the
companies they cover take them on tours, and wine and dine them?
</P>
<P>
   ``If a guy can't go on a junket, he's at an immediate
disadvantage,'' Dvorak says. ``It's a false ethic to protect large
publishing companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Dvorak speaks as a free-lancer, albeit a very successful one. He
writes columns for PC Magazine, PC Computing and some smaller mags
and hosts ``Silicon Spin'' on ZDTV as well as a syndicated radio
show.
</P>
<P>
   He says the big companies can afford to send their reporters far
and wide, while smaller publications and writers like him can't
afford to travel as extensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a company is doing something in Korea and they want me to
see it, they should pay for it,'' he says. ``Why should I pay to go
see their dog and pony show?''
</P>
<P>
   But what if he thinks their products are terrible? Could he rip
them in print? ``I've done it,'' he says. ``It's fair to the
reader, as long as you let the reader know these guys paid for the
trip.''
</P>
<P>
   European journalists take junkets as a matter of course, he
said. Everyone there does it, and everyone knows, so there's no
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Dvorak's been on junkets to Asia, to Finland and, earlier this
year, to the Hannover Fair in Germany. ``That was a nice junket,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   A company named APC, which makes power supplies, took him to the
massive German trade show in April, and he found it ``very
educational to go on the coattails of a company that knows the
ropes.''
</P>
<P>
   By now, you can probably hear editors grinding their teeth at
Dvorak's heretical stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just astonished,'' says Tim Graham, president of the
Northern California chapter of the Society of Professional
Journalists, and the editor of TechWeek. ``It's very disturbing to
hear him think it's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   The SPJ policy, which is online at www.spj.org/ethics/code.htm,
is clear: No free trips or any other actions that compromise
journalistic integrity.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Graham says, many newsrooms took all sorts of
freebies, Christmas gifts and junkets. But after Watergate, ``most
newsrooms cleaned up their act, and established a we-pay-your-way
policy. It's become accepted practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Neil Chase, an assistant professor and director of technology at
the Medill School of Journalism at Northwestern University, helps
run the Computer Press Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I let a company fly me first class over to Asia and put me
up in a fancy hotel and show me a product, I'm going to be more
favorably inclined to it than if I saw it in a friend's basement,''
Chase says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Journalism is never cheap,'' he notes. ``If you want to do an
objective job, you have to spend a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Chase says reporters need to ask two questions: ``One is, are
you doing anything that is affecting your ability to report
objectively? And the second, and more important, are you doing
anything that would affect the perception that you're objective?''
</P>
<P>
   The perception of a conflict, as we've learned in politics, is
often just as important as a real conflict.
</P>
<P>
   John Markoff, a New York Times technology reporter based in San
Francisco, loves to hear about his friend Dvorak's trips but never
takes similar opportunities even though they crop up all the time.
``Last week, I was invited to Singapore,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking funding to go places or to travel to corporate events
crosses the line pretty clearly,'' he says. ``I would feel very
uncomfortable.'' This week, Markoff hit the road to Seattle for
Microsoft's ``MSN Strategy Day,'' but the Times is paying his way.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the junkets Dvorak describes ``might be fun, but they
have little to do with news gathering,'' Markoff says. ``They wine
you, they dine you and show you products in a controlled manner.
Those are the kind of events I try to avoid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
