O'MEARA, SANDELIN TALKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Mark O'Meara said he talked to Jarmo Sandelin
Tuesday night and things were cordial. Two years ago, Sandelin
called the American ``Mark O'Nearer'' after an infamous incident
late in the fourth round of the Lancome Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Sandelin was on record as saying O'Meara should have given back
the trophy he won (Sandelin was second) when a taped broadcast
showed that the American mis-marked his ball. ``I have no issue
with Jarmo Sandelin,'' said O'Meara.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aid from overseas
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Phil ``Wobbly'' Morsby is part of a group of European caddies
who came over to support their mates. Morsby caddies for Ian
Woosnam, an eight-time Ryder Cup participant . . . Lee Westwood,
who seems a lock to be paired with Darren Clarke, played the front
with Sergio Garcia in four-ball. On the back, he played foursomes
with Padraig Harrington, with Garcia paired with Jesper Parnevik.
The Garcia-Parnevik team is one European watchers expect to be a
sure thing . . . Scotsman Andrew Coltart, a captain's pick, has
been struggling with his game, as has Sweden's Jarmo Sandelin. Both
appear to be certain sit-downs for the first four matches Friday.
Harrington and Jean Van de Velde most likely will sit out, too,
though the Irishman has looked extremely sharp in his two practice
rounds, after coming off a good effort at last weekend's B.C. Open
. . . The difference in pressure for the US as compared to Europe
in Spain two years ago? ``I think the Europeans, people at home,
are all hoping that we're going to win, and not expecting us to
win,'' said Northern Ireland's Clarke. ``And that's a huge
difference.'' . . . Ooops Dept. In the players' guide put out by
the PGA of America, European captain Mark James is listed as 29
years old. Which he was _ in 1982 . . . Even in the rain, the
Europeans took their time during the practice rounds, putting two
and three times on each green as they acquainted themselves with
the course.
</P>
