<SLUG> BC-RADIO-ENTREPRENEURS-MTV-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 2 NET ENTREPRENEURS MAKING NOISE OVER MTV DEAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DAN FOST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
Two young Internet entrepreneurs from San Francisco, who are
embroiled in a legal battle with MTV Networks, say MTV bought their
business and then tried to shut it down.
</P>
<P>
   Rotem Perelmutter, 27, and Michael Briseno, 28, last year
founded Imagine Radio, which built customized radio stations on the
Internet. They sold it to MTV for $14.5 million in February. But
the deal started to sour almost immediately, and now the two are
fighting one of the largest media companies in the world, MTV's
parent, Viacom.
</P>
<P>
   The men's lawyers say the cable powerhouse subverted their
original business and now is banning them from working in Internet
radio for a year because MTV fears the impact of Internet radio on
its franchise business of showing music videos on television.
</P>
<P>
   MTV declined to comment on the case, but in court filings, it
accused Perelmutter _ who had already received more than $3 million
of his $6.6 million take in the deal _ of ``scheming to replicate
the business he had just sold to MTV (Networks) in the hope of
selling it again to others for an even higher amount.'' It said
Briseno was part of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The case sheds light on the way deals get done in the
high-stakes world of the Internet. An affidavit filed by
Perelmutter tells of being alternately ``threatened and cajoled''
and wined and dined by MTV executives eager to buy his small firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made every effort to `wow' me, and they succeeded,'' he
said in the affidavit. ``We attended dinner at Nobu, a very
fashionable sushi restaurant (in Manhattan). We were surrounded by
famous people, including Calvin Klein, Cindy Crawford and Donald
Trump. ... (then-President and Chief Operating Officer of MTV
Networks Mark Rosenthal) held out his hands and pointed his fingers
like guns, stating to me, `You the man' and `Rotem, it's all about
you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   According to affidavits, Perelmutter and Briseno were friends as
undergraduates at the University of California at Los Angeles, and
in 1997 founded an Internet radio company in Perelmutter's
apartment in San Francisco. Perelmutter, an Israeli native, was the
financial brains, and brought $50,000 of his life savings; Briseno
represented the technical side of the company.
</P>
<P>
   The fledgling firm, Silver Island, sought to help people build
customized radio stations on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Although the entrepreneurs began to run out of money in
mid-1998, they received funding from computer magazine publisher
Imagine Media of Brisbane, Calif., and changed the name to Imagine
Radio. Imagine Media and Perelmutter were the primary owners of the
new company.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the year, MTV began wooing the company, and the
deal closed in February. MTV planned to use Imagine Radio
technology for a project now known as Sonic Net, which would stream
radiolike content over the Internet so users could in effect create
their own station.
</P>
<P>
   But Briseno and Perelmutter were frustrated almost immediately,
and say they spoke to MTV about leaving. They planned to create a
new business that would serve MTV and other Internet radio
companies.
</P>
<P>
   MTV now denies knowledge of the new business and charges the men
with plotting to compete with Sonic Net.
</P>
<P>
   Although Perelmutter and Briseno acknowledge that they signed
contracts in which they agreed not to compete with MTV for certain
periods after they leave, they say they signed those without the
benefit of counsel and with MTV's assurance that it would not
enforce the claims. Briseno also says the prohibition is not
enforceable.
</P>
<P>
   MTV took the pair to New York state court this month, trying to
put a stop to their new business, but a judge refused to grant a
temporary restraining order. MTV is now trying to move the case to
federal court. It wants to keep Perelmutter and Briseno from
working in the Internet radio business until February 2000 and
February 2001, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Briseno's attorney, Dale Lysak of the Dzivi Law Firm in San
Francisco, says MTV is ``judge-shopping.''
</P>
<P>
   The state court judge has set a conference date for late
October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
