<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-CHIP-IMPACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN QUAKE TO BE COSTLY TO WORLD TECHNOLOGY MAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By WAYNE ARNOLD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ Industrial disruption from Taiwan's devastating
earthquake could delay or reduce the production of high-technology
items ranging from cellular phones to Furby dolls _ affecting far
more than just the computer semiconductors that Taiwan manufactures
in large quantities.
</P>
<P>
   As electronics and computer companies everywhere sought to
assess how badly the quake would affect them, it also became clear
Wednesday that power failures on Taiwan could worsen or prolong
operating problems there, even at installations that suffered
little or no structural damage. By some estimates, it will take at
least two weeks to restore power to industrial areas.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan is the world's fourth-largest maker of semiconductors and
the third largest of personal computers. Most of its products go
into big-name brands all over the world, including IBM, Motorola
and Toshiba.
</P>
<P>
   Industry executives and analysts said that it was premature to
assign a firm cost to the quake but that it was likely to be high.
Taiwan authorities are giving initial estimates of more than $3
billion in damages.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate and obvious impact on international business from
the earthquake that struck on Tuesday was on semiconductor makers,
which supply the chips that are the brains of personal computers.
The stock prices of producers that rely on Taiwan's chip foundries,
such as Motorola and National Semiconductor, have been dropping,
while those of rival manufacturers that obtain chips elsewhere,
like in South Korea, have been rising.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest blow in the history of the semiconductor
industry,'' said Hiroshi Yoshihara, a Salomon Smith Barney analyst
in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   But more than the supply of semiconductors has been affected.
High-technology manufacturers buy the main personal computer
circuits known as motherboards, as well as monitors, liquid-crystal
displays and even batteries and chargers, from companies in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Such companies make notebook computers for Fujitsu, NEC and
Apple Computer, among others. Compaq shops in Taiwan for hard-disk
drives. Dell Computer and Hewlett-Packard buy computer modems
there. Toy makers like Mattel and the Bandai Co. of Japan also buy
equipment from Taiwan. All in all, Taiwan exports at least $12
billion in high-technology goods to foreign manufacturers a year.
</P>
<P>
   The earthquake struck the center of the island, well away from
the main concentration of factories in the north, and most of those
appear to have avoided major damage. Taiwan Semiconductor, with the
world's biggest chip foundry, said its installation had withstood
the quake and that it would lose no more than 10 percent of its
production this month.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said Wednesday that the big problem facing
producers in Taiwan was not structural damage, but the absence of
electricity. ``The most serious impact is power,'' said C.M.
Chiang, managing director of International Data's Taiwan office.
</P>
<P>
   ``From initial reports so far, it seems that most of the
factories of our supplier are intact,'' said Cecilia Pang, a
spokeswoman for Hewlett-Packard in Singapore. ``The problem is the
power outage. They can have the factory running, but without power
they can't do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides power failures, analysts saw minor structural damage as
posing a problem. ``The biggest impact is on the semiconductor
industry, because of its complexity,'' said William Milton of Brown
Brothers Harriman in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The circuits in Wednesday's semiconductors are one-400th the
thickness of a strand of hair, so the equipment needed to make them
is extremely delicate. Even if such equipment was not damaged, it
would require extensive testing and recalibration before it could
be used again.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, chips take up to 60 days to produce, and Yoshihara
said any chips that were in production at the time of the quake
would probably have to be discarded. A one-day power loss late in
July cost the Taiwan chip industry millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, an effect of Tuesday's earthquake could be to
inflate further the prices of memory chips, which have been rising
because demand is outstripping supply. The price of the most
popular 64-megabit memory chip has more than tripled since July.
After news of the quake, the average price jumped nearly 12
percent, according to the American IC Exchange, an electronic
pricing service for chips in Aliso Viejo, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Production delays could also be bad news for companies that
depend on Taiwan for ``logic chips,'' the more complex
semiconductors used to run cellular phones and that give toys like
the Furby their talents. Also vulnerable, Milton said, are such
small concerns as Xilinx Inc., which designs chips and then
contracts with companies in Taiwan to produce them. Xilinx issued a
statement saying it did not expect to be hurt by the quake.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said it was possible that larger companies and the
electronics industry as a whole could be insulated against Taiwan's
problems. Even though many chips are made on the island, the output
still accounts for only about 15 percent of global memory-chip
production, compared with 34 percent by South Korea. And as with
other components, most big manufacturers buy parts from several
countries. NEC, for example, buys parts for its PC's from China and
the Philippines, as well as Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, executives said it would take time to shift purchases
to other suppliers or even to determine just how much their
supplies from Taiwan would be affected. As Motorola shipped in
radio equipment for rescuers, an executive said he was trying to
track down a shipment of batteries for the company's cellular
phones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
