<SLUG> BC-CITY-PACIFIC-BANK-SALE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 STRUGGLING PACIFIC BANK OKS SALE TO CITY NATIONAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By SAM ZUCKERMAN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
SAN FRANCISCO -- Pacific Bank, a once-high-flying San Francisco
commercial lender that fell from grace during California's real
estate crash at the beginning of the decade, agreed to sell itself
Wednesday to City National Corp. of Beverly Hills, Calif., for $153
million in cash and stock.
</P>
<P>
   The takeover, which must be approved by regulators and
shareholders, will give fast-growing City National its first
foothold in Northern California. With $6.7 billion in assets, City
National is the largest community bank headquartered in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific, with $728 million in assets, has four branches in San
Francisco and Burlingame, Calif.; five branches in the Los Angeles
area; and offices in Hong Kong and the Cayman Islands.
</P>
<P>
   The two banks have the same mix of businesses, including trust,
international finance, and banking services for wealthy individuals
and small to midsize businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our business profiles are very similar,'' said Michael Tun
Zan, Pacific's Burma-born president and chief executive. ``We will
be the springboard for their expansion in the north.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacific has been through rocky times in recent years after
nearly failing when its large portfolio of commercial real estate
loans produced big losses in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, its ties to Asia produced a multimillion-dollar loss
in the fourth quarter after several Hong Kong customers defaulted
on loans.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Pacific was hamstrung in finding a buyer because
a Singapore shareholder who owned a 37 percent stake in the bank
refused to take stock in exchange for her shares. Last year, she
sold her shares in a public offering, freeing Pacific to pursue a
sale of the bank.
</P>
<P>
   City National has long been one of the highest-profile
independent banks in the state. Known as ``the bank of the stars,''
it built a strong business with Hollywood insiders. CEO Russell
Goldsmith, son of City National's previous chief, headed Republic
Pictures Corp. before he moved to the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its glitzy reputation, much of City National's business
has been in the more gritty world of companies in such areas as
apparel and import-export. Since Russell Goldsmith took over as CEO
four years ago, City National has bought seven Southern California
banks and one trust company.
</P>
<P>
   After the purchase is complete, Tun Zan will stay on as City
National's senior officer in Northern California, Goldsmith said.
</P>
<P>
   The bank expects to shut several overlapping branches in the Los
Angeles area but doesn't expect to close offices in Northern
California, Goldsmith said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
