<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-EDUC-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLE EMPHASIZES STRICT DISCIPLINE IN SCHOOLS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELROSE, Mass. _ Weighing in on an issue where rivals for the
White House had staked out positions weeks ago, Elizabeth Dole
Wednesday proposed streamlining the federal government's role in
education by giving states and local districts the power to
determine how federal money should be spent and academic targets
met.
</P>
<P>
   At Melrose High School here, where the Republican presidential
hopeful was a student teacher more than 40 years ago, Dole spoke to
an audience of the school's brightest youngsters _ class officers
and honor students _ and proposed ``zero tolerance'' for classmates
who disrupt lessons and cause disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced by the class president, Emily Bachman, Dole quipped:
``Hmmm. Female president. That sounds pretty good to me.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, Dole's vision hearkened to an earlier age, stressing
discipline and putting ``teachers back in charge of their
classrooms.'' She proposed that school officials search the lockers
and backpacks of students and test them for drug use, subject to
their parents' approval. And disciplinary records of problem
students, she said, should travel ``with the young person from
school to school.''
</P>
<P>
   Although federal money plays a relatively minor role in
financing public education, voters have identified education as a
priority in public opinion surveys as the presidential primaries
approach. Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and Vice President Al Gore
both made policy speeches on the issue several weeks ago as summer
vacation drew to an end.
</P>
<P>
   For her policy speech, Dole chose as her backdrop a school whose
principal, Daniel R. Burke, has made a crusade of restoring
discipline, clearing the halls of students cutting classes or
milling about and outlawing hats in school. Behind Dole, aides had
stacked the 8-inch pile of papers of the elementary and secondary
education reauthorization bill, which she waved at throughout her
speech as if it were an unwieldy beast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the federal government has 788 different federal
education programs,'' she said. ``These provide only 7 percent of
the money that we spend on public schools, but they create 50
percent of the paperwork for teachers and administrators.''
</P>
<P>
   While not mentioning school vouchers, Dole proposed annual tax
credits of up to $1,000 a person for contributions to nonprofit
educational foundations associated with public or private schools.
The credits would presumably be granted in addition to deductions
already permitted for donations to charity.
</P>
<P>
   ``That gift,'' Dole said, ``could be used for books,
scholarships or other education purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying she favored ``a rich smorgasbord of education choices,''
Dole mentioned ``opportunity scholarships for students in failing
schools, or charter schools or home schooling'' as potential
solutions. But she did not offer details.
</P>
<P>
   Asked explicitly about her position on vouchers after her talk,
Dole sidestepped the question, essentially paraphrasing from her
speech her support for her version of the three R's: returning
control to states and local school districts, restoring discipline
and reinforcing parents' involvement in their children's education.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Driscoll, a 74-year-old retired secretary who showed up to
hear Dole, said that she was pleased to see a woman running for the
presidency but that she had doubts about Dole's proposal to scrap
federal regulations wholesale.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the federal regulations exist because parents have
abdicated their roles,'' Ms. Driscoll said. ``We can't just go back
in time.''
</P>
<P>
   The young people chosen to listen to the candidate said they
agreed with her emphasis and with their principal's stress on
discipline. ``He's getting us more ready for the real world,'' said
Joseph Matara, a 17-year-old senior.
</P>
<P>
   His friend, Joshua Goldstein, 16, said he did not mind the bag
or locker checks, particularly after the spate of killings at
schools like the one in Columbine, Colo. ``You're in school to
learn, not to worry about getting killed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one uninvited student managed to make her way
inside to film the speech, and her reaction was quite different.
Emily Taffe, 17, said she realized that schools needed ``to be
pulled out of the abyss,'' but Dole's message sounded heavy-handed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a prison,'' Miss Taffe said. ``We're here because
we have to be, but that doesn't mean it has to be so harsh.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
