<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCINTOSH FAMILY TREE 
HOME FOR THE WINTER
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DORA GALITZKI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Last year, I picked tart and crunchy ``native New England
Macouns'' at an orchard in Massachusetts, but at another place the
owner declared them ``a cross between McIntosh and a Cortland
type.'' Given the similarities in taste, coloring and name, one
might suspect a common lineage for Macs and Macouns. But what is
the relationship?
</P>
<P>
   A. Like a Kentucky Derby winner put out to stud, the McIntosh, a
venerable apple first found about 1800 on John McIntosh's farm in
Ontario, has been crossed with many other apples, often with
winning results.
</P>
<P>
   Your Macoun, introduced in 1923, is the result of a McIntosh
crossed with a Jersey Black.
</P>
<P>
   Cortland, introduced in 1915, is a Macoun half-sister: a
McIntosh crossed with an apple called Ben Davis. Other interesting
offspring of the prolific McIntosh include Empire (a 1966
introduction, whose other parent is unknown), Jonamac (1972,
Jonathan), Spartan (1936, Newtown), Summerred (1964, Golden
Delicious) and Tydeman Early (1945, Worcester Pearmain). One of my
favorite apples, Liberty, is a McIntosh grandchild, a cross between
a Macoun and a Purdue 54-12.
</P>
<P>
   This year's dry spring and summer has resulted in a bumper crop,
but not all the interesting ones will get to the supermarket. To
help you find more interesting apples and other produce at farms in
the New York region, the state's Agriculture and Markets Department
has published a new edition of ``The Guide to Farm Fresh
Products.'' A free copy is available by calling (800) 554-4501 or
from www.agmkt.state.ny.us, the department's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Home for the Winter
</P>
<P>
   Q. My houseplants have spent the summer on my porch. I will move
them back inside soon. But I've noticed earwigs in my spider
plants. Should I spray with a pesticide before bringing them in, or
should I wait until the temperature drops enough to harm the bugs
(but not, I hope, the plants)?
</P>
<P>
   A. Most houseplants are tropical or subtropical in origin while
the bugs are local, so I wouldn't want to bet on giving bugs the
cold shoulder before the plants begin to suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Earwigs and other insects in the soil can be forced to the
surface by soaking the pot up to its rim in a sink full of water.
What you do with the bugs as they surface is up to you.
</P>
<P>
   Plants like their changes gradual, to ease the shock of new
surroundings. Inside, light and humidity levels are much lower,
while temperatures are higher. Move them into shadier spots a week
or two before bringing them inside, but most have to be inside
before night temperatures are consistently below 50 degrees. A few,
including bay laurel, cactus, camellia, citrus, clivia, ivies,
Norfolk Island pine, scented geranium and oleander, can stay out
until nights regularly approach 40 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   A GREENER SPRING
</P>
<P>
   Q. I saved seeds for a fall crop of spinach but never planted
them. Will they be OK to plant next spring?  &QL; 
A. There's a certain sadness about fall cleanup and shutting down
the garden. But one of the things to lighten a gardener's heart is
to seed some cold-tolerant varieties of spinach in the fall and let
the young plants overwinter. By giving them a head start, you
insure that you will be eating fresh spinach salad next spring
while your friends are still waiting for their seeds to germinate.
And even better, during the long winter, you can occasionally think
about it quietly waiting there and let a faint smile play across
your lips.
</P>
<P>
   Fall Green, Vienna or Winter Bloomsdale are varieties
recommended for overwintering. Planting them up to the second week
of October gives them a chance to develop a few leaves and roots
before winter. They don't need to be mulched: the leaves will get
ratty through the winter, but the root system will be fine. When
spring arrives, new leaves will sprout from the established root
system.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have one of the varieties that overwinter, your
seeds should be all right. Spinach seeds remain viable for three
years if stored cool and dry.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 West
43rd St., New York 10036, or by e-mail to gardening(AT)nytimes.com.
Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished questions
cannot be answered individually. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 2213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0493 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2430 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-ONEMAN'SHERO-TEX     09-22 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ONEMAN'SHERO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILM SPOTLIGHTS MEXICAN WAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Mexican War of the 1840s wasn't fought solely by Mexicans
and Americans. The sons of Irish immigrants, fleeing the potato
famine, joined the U.S. Army with the promise of citizenship and
land for their families. The historical drama ``One Man's Hero'' is
about a group of those Irish soldiers who, after suffering
persecution for their Catholic beliefs, deserted and eventually
wound up fighting for the Mexican side _ and became Mexican heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Berenger plays Sgt. John Riley, the leader of the Irish
troops, who deserts his post with a group of young soldiers after
saving them from lashings by their martinet commander (Stephen
Tobolowsky, in a thankless, one-dimensional role); they were being
punished for crossing the border to attend Catholic Mass. Riley
takes the men to Mexico, where they're captured by
</P>
<P>
   guerrillas fighting the Mexican government. But it's the
government that ultimately offers Riley and his men a choice: fight
for Mexico and earn land to settle on, or die. Riley chooses to
fight, and his rag-tag band becomes known as St. Patrick's
Battalion _ or Los San Patricios.
</P>
<P>
   ``One Man's Hero'' is one of those frustrating movies that are
better than they could have been and not as good as they should
have been. That sounds oxymoronic, but both sides of the argument
are based in the movie's low budget (director Lance Hool struggled
for two decades to get the movie made, and even now it's getting a
haphazard, underpromoted release).
</P>
<P>
   With Berenger at the fore, struggling with an Irish accent,
``One Man's Hero'' resembles one of those historic dramas made for
TNT _ at least till the second half, when the battle scenes hit
high gear. Berenger is earnest, though, as is the movie; it's so
intent on educating you that it sometimes feels like an unusually
well-done high-school history-class film.
</P>
<P>
   But if the movie had had more financial backing, it really could
have been something. One wonders what someone like Steven Spielberg
could have done with this story, especially after Spielberg made
his fascination with history evident with ``Amistad'' and ``Saving
Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Mexican War has to be one of the most ignored
subjects of the past 30 or 40 years, almost to the point that
anything on the subject would be welcome. And the movie provides
good parts for multifaceted Mexican star Daniela Romo (as a nurse
who becomes Riley's love interest) and character actor Joaquim de
Almeida (''Clear and Present Danger''), who gives the film's best
performance as the conflicted rebel leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``One Man's Hero'' isn't interested in being objective, although
it is fair enough to mention that not all Americans were in favor
of the war. And in the movies, where fiction almost always corrupts
fact, history must be taken with a grain of salt. ``One Man's
Hero'' will have as much of an uphill battle at the box office as
its protoganists had in war, but it will probably send those who
see it scrambling to the Internet or the library to find out more
about its subject. And that, really, is all the filmmakers could
ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``One Man's Hero'' is rated R for violence.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
