<HEADER>
A2432 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-Y2K-REPORT-(TRIMS)-NY     09-22 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-REPORT-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL ON 2000 FINDS NEWS LARGELY GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BARNABY J. FEDER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although serious concerns remain, especially in health care,
small businesses, local government and education, the United States
is largely prepared for year 2000 computer problems, according to
the committee that has been the Senate's chief watchdog on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the committee said, it has become increasingly
worried that lagging preparations overseas could lead to economic
disruptions severe enough to hurt U.S. businesses and generate
pleas for international aid.
</P>
<P>
   The publication of the committee's report with just 100 days
left until Jan. 1 was one of many public and private sector year
2000 events this week, most with generally positive overviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is probably more complacency that will come out of this
than we would like,'' said Sen. Robert F. Bennett, the Utah
Republican who is chairman of the Senate Special Committee on the
Year 2000 Problem. ``We are in much better shape than I would have
anticipated a year and a half ago, but people who go through the
details of the report will find plenty of indication that there is
still much work to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   The year 2000 computer problem stems from representing the year
in electronic dates with just two digits, like 99 for 1999. Faulty
devices and programs can malfunction when they read 00 as 1900
instead of 2000 or simply fail to recognize it as a valid date.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Year 2000 flaws have been popping up for years in software _ a
separate report out Wednesday said that 82 percent of large
companies had already encountered them _ but the first weeks of
January are expected to bring the largest volume of malfunctions.
</P>
<P>
   The report on large companies, which is sponsored by CAP Gemini
America, an information technology consulting company in New York,
said that although nearly half did not expect to have all of their
critical computer systems fixed before the end of the year, only 12
percent expected such vulnerable systems to pose a ``significant
business risk.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey also reported that 44 percent of the year 2000
malfunctions to date occurred in systems the companies had
repaired. Computer experts say that it is common to introduce new
errors when debugging software, which is one reason contingency
planning for breakdowns is an essential part of year 2000
preparations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't say everything is fine and rosy,'' said James
Woodward, head of CAP Gemini America's information systems
management group.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Many recent reports and presentations are certainly emphasizing
optimistic expectations. Perhaps more strikingly, a National
Association of Manufacturers poll of vital concerns of small
manufacturers published Wednesday did not even bother to pose a
question about year 2000. Earlier this year, the manufacturing
group had seen the threat of year 2000 problems and lawsuits as so
important that it made legislation restricting litigation one of
its main policy objectives.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's Senate report, which is available on the Internet at
www.senate.gov/y2k/documents/100dayrpt, contained no major
surprises for computer experts and others involved in year 2000
activities.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's biggest areas of concern were generally in
sectors where information about preparations has been hard to
obtain. In the $1.5 trillion health care industry, the committee
praised year 2000 programs at drug companies, distributors and
major hospitals but expressed grave concerns about the readiness of
computer systems in the nation's 50,000 doctors' offices and 15,000
nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main reason is that we simply can't get information about
them,'' Bennett said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 2217EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
