<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0504 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2445 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-GOODALL-PROFILE-ART-N     09-22 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODALL-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PRIMATOLOGIST'S CONTINUING PILGRIMAGE ON BEHALF OF THE
CHIMPANZEES
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ OK, we're going to see what Dr. Jane Goodall has been
up to lately, and at first you may find it a little icky-poo.
</P>
<P>
   It has to do with this red canvas tote that Goodall, the British
primatologist, has been schlepping around on her speaking
engagements, a bag that includes not just one inspirational stuffed
animal, but two.
</P>
<P>
   The older, a stuffed monkey called Mr. H. _ Goodall, who made
her reputation observing chimpanzees in the wild, has always named
her animals _ was given to her a few years ago by a U.S. marine who
was blinded and went on to be a very fine magician. Goodall whips
Mr. H. out for grown-ups as well as children, insisting, in a
British accent that is lately more Mary Poppins than Diana Rigg,
that if they touch it, it will change their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The other toy is a black-and-white dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amber Mary,'' Goodall says. ``She was given to me by a little
girl who had saved her pocket money. Her little brother had died of
leukemia and she gave it to me so the orphan chimps wouldn't be
alone at night. I use it for my talks and when children say they
have no money, they couldn't possibly help, I tell them the story
and say, `Not even a few pennies?'''
</P>
<P>
   A little sigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see many hankies go up to eyes. It makes me weepy every time
I tell it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's got to be a promotional tour that brings Goodall to our
city, right?
</P>
<P>
   Yes and no.
</P>
<P>
   There is a PBS special, ``Jane Goodall: Reason for Hope,'' which
will be broadcast at the end of October, and a book of the same
name, but Goodall's travels are more of a campaign, almost
religious, a crusade on behalf of animals.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1986, when she saw a film on the brutal treatment of
laboratory chimps, Goodall has been traveling continuously to raise
money for seven chimp sanctuaries in Africa operated by the Jane
Goodall Institute. For the last 13 years, she has never been in one
place more than four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, on her way to Community Intermediate School 229 in
the Bronx, where she will talk to children about her Roots and
Shoots environmental program, she speaks of Ted Turner's chimp
channel, which she loathes, and a chimpanzee pictured on a cereal
box, which appears to be smiling, but is not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't a normal, happy smile,'' Goodall says. ``It's more a
grimace of terror, like this'' _ she does the grimace, showing
teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Ham when he came down from space. It was the most
tortured face I've ever seen. The space capsule overheated and
plunged into the ocean. After that, they put him in a cage, alone
in the National Zoo. Quite a way to treat a hero. I missed meeting
Ham by a year, which I very much regret. He died young of an
enlarged heart, undoubtedly brought on by stress.''
</P>
<P>
   If all this makes Goodall sound like an ecological missionary, a
sort of wildlife nun, she will tell you, with a start at the word
``nun,'' that she doesn't see herself that way at all.
</P>
<P>
   Ask her, back in her hotel suite, what she does for fun, and
she'll report that after a grueling book tour she's been known to
run up the down escalator, then go to her room, hit the chocolates
and Scotch and count the money from the collection boxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I quite enjoy that.''
</P>
<P>
   As for living among the animals, it was something she always
wanted. Her parents (father an engineer, mother a novelist)
divorced when Jane was 12. Goodall grew up in genteel frugality in
a manor house in Bournemouth, on the coast. She got the itch for
Africa when she first read ``Tarzan.''
</P>
<P>
   She worked as a waitress to earn the money to travel to Africa,
where, at 24, she landed a job as secretary to the paleontologist
Dr. Louis Leakey, an enthusiastic ladies man. He recruited Ms.
Goodall to observe chimpanzees, though she had no scientific
training. The doctorate from Cambridge came later. There were two
marriages: to a wildlife cinematographer who made Goodall a
National Geographic TV star and with whom she had a son, and to
Derek Bryceson, a member of the Tanzanian Parliament. He died in
1979.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been written of Goodall's scientific findings, so let
us focus here on jungle love.
</P>
<P>
   In your new book, Goodall, you spend but one paragraph on your
first serious love affair but pages on your first meaningful
relationship with a chimp, who accepts a palm nut fruit from your
hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked into his large and lustrous eyes,'' you wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Why so little on love and so much on the monkey?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a fairly private person, I didn't want to write about
loving my husbands. Love stories _ you can go to any cinema and
read any novel. It isn't like what happened that day. It was rather
as though an alien came down. So magical, utterly magical, to break
down that mistrust and be able to communicate without the need for
words with another creature. I can still feel it to this day. And
it hasn't happened like that since. It was unique. Falling in love
with a human male is absolutely not unique.''
</P>
<P>
   Noted. The allegedly amorous Leakey, anything happen?
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible? Almost a giggle?
</P>
<P>
   ``He would have loved that, he would have loved to have had an
affair, but no. Fortunately, I was able to turn him into a fairy
foster father. Just with gentle resistance. He had everything I
wanted, I couldn't be nasty to him and I wouldn't have wanted to
be, he was wonderful. He felt happy about women, he liked their
company and I like the company of men.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
