<SLUG> BC-MORGAN-EARNINGS-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORGAN STANLEY'S 3RD QUARTER PROFITS SLIGHTLY ABOVE WALL STREET
ESTIMATES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, the most profitable Wall
Street firm, posted an earnings rise of more than half in the third
quarter, as stock underwriting and merger fees continued to bolster
the firm's bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley's net income for the fiscal third quarter, which
ended Aug. 31, surged 55 percent, to $970 million, or $1.65 a
share, from $626 million, or $1.01 a share, in the same period of
1998. Profits were slightly higher than the $1.61 a share expected
by Wall Street analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   All areas of Morgan Stanley's businesses contributed to the
profit growth, which one analyst called plain vanilla _ a steady
but unspectacular increase in everything from new stock issues to
the firm's Discover credit card business.
</P>
<P>
   The year-to-year profit comparison was inflated because last
year at this time Morgan Stanley and other securities firms were
suffering through a stock and bond markets slump that began with
Russia's default on its debt in August, 1998. Earnings growth is
slowing, however, from earlier this year, when Morgan Stanley
soared past analysts' estimates and reported quarterly earnings
records. Its profit was $1.15 billion in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steady and strong is okay with me,'' said Robert F. Scott,
Morgan Stanley's chief financial officer. ``We also had balance. We
are paying attention to all lines of our business.''
</P>
<P>
   Securities and investment banking operations were the biggest
profit generator, with net income of $633 million, up 43 percent,
accounting for about two-thirds of the firm's total profit for the
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Trading on behalf of customers and advising companies on mergers
and acquisitions contributed to a hefty rise in investment banking
revenue and trading commissions, the company said. Investment
banking revenue rose to a record $1.21 billion for the quarter.
Trading revenue more than doubled to $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The company's money-management arm also rebounded with net
income of $135 million, up from break-even in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Net income from credit card services advanced 10 percent to $202
million. Scott said the company's effort to expand the Discover
Card franchise had begun to pay off after a period of seeking to
improve the quality of its credit card debt. He said the business
is on course to expand more rapidly now as it begins an
international push.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The results were not quite as strong as those at rival Goldman
Sachs, which reported its third-quarter profit Tuesday. Goldman
earned $638 million in the quarter, double profits in the
year-earlier period and about equal to what it earned in the spring
quarter. Goldman's third-quarter earnings were helped by a big gain
in merchant banking, which can be volatile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Morgan Stanley's earnings were a little higher quality than
Goldman's,'' said Amy Butte, brokerage industry analyst at Bear
Stearns. ``But both are premier franchises, and they are gaining
incremental share in the global business.''
</P>
<P>
   On a quarter-to-quarter comparison, Morgan Stanley's earnings
picture is less rosy. The firm is locked in a fierce battle for
market share in highly profitable areas of investment banking with
Goldman, Merrill Lynch and other firms, a battle that may have
contributed to some slippage in Morgan Stanley's ranking in the
worldwide equity business.
</P>
<P>
   The company's trading revenue also declined nearly 40 percent
from a record-setting second quarter. Interest rates rose and
prices of many types of bonds fell, hurting results. ``The trading
business definitely slowed from the stupendous levels in the first
and second quarters,'' said Richard Strauss, brokerage industry
analyst for Goldman. ``It's probably a good proxy of what we can
expect to see in the final quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   On a quarterly comparison, Morgan Stanley's asset management
business also had lackluster results. Assets under management
increased by $10 billion for the period, to $415 billion. That 2.5
percent quarterly growth rate reflects a rocky summer stock market
but also increasing competition for the money of individual
investors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
