<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2447 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MIAMI-BONDHOLDERS-480     09-22 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIAMI-BONDHOLDERS-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BONDHOLDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y., Ariz., Miss.)REGULATORS SAY MIAMI DEFRAUDED(js) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The City of Miami, already besieged by scandals involving
election-law violations and political corruption, was accused by
federal regulators Wednesday of defrauding its bondholders by
deliberately concealing a financial crisis that engulfed city
government in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The accusation, which the city denies, was contained in an
administrative complaint filed by the Securities and Exchange
Commission against the city and two former city officials.
</P>
<P>
   The regulators said the city's misleading actions affected the
sale of $116.5 million in tax-exempt bonds issued in 1995 to
finance pensions, sewer construction and a public building project.
The commission is arguing, in effect, that the bond market might
have demanded a higher price or greater protections if it had known
the true state of the city's finances.
</P>
<P>
   The risk to bondholders is unclear because the case may affect
Miami's overall credit rating, which can influence the prices at
which bonds trade in the market.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, while not seeking any monetary penalties, is
asking an administrative law judge to find the city at fault and
require accurate reports on its finances in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The case is the latest skirmish in a five-year campaign by the
commission to force cities, counties and other municipal bond
issuers to keep investors informed about significant changes in
their financial health, just as publicly traded corporations are
required to do, said John C. Mattimore, the assistant regional
director in the commission's office in Miami. Such cases have been
filed against Orange County, Calif., Maricopa County, Ariz.,
Syracuse, N.Y., and several small towns in Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami case is likely to be closely watched by local
officials across the country because, if it is successful, it will
expand the traditional limits of the federal regulators'
jurisdiction in the municipal bond market.
</P>
<P>
   Like the earlier cases, the Miami complaint accused the city of
issuing misleading bond documents in connection with the sale of
specific bond issues. But in this case, the city is also accused of
providing inaccurate financial statements to investors months after
the bonds were sold.
</P>
<P>
   Such subsequent reports have not been cited in earlier cases,
said William R. Baker, an associate director of the security
commission's enforcement division.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although such statements are not required by any SEC rule or
regulation, what we are saying in this case is that whatever you
decide to disclose must be truthful,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the commission has accused the city of failing to
disclose publicly that its cash flow had precipitously declined
after the close of its 1994 fiscal year, raising the possibility
that it would not be able to cover its operating expenses and pay
the interest on its outstanding bonds during the 1995 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Miami is fighting the charges.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Thomas Tew, a lawyer for the city, said Miami officials fully
discussed the 1995 budget problems to its auditors, Deloitte &AMP;
Touche, and followed Deloitte's advice in preparing its financial
reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not believe that we violated the securities laws,'' Tew
said. ``We relied upon our auditors.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Ringel, a spokeswoman for Deloitte, said the firm had
cooperated fully with the regulators. A ruling in favor of the
commission ``should put an end to the city's claim that it was
unaware of its true financial condition, and to its efforts to
shift responsibility to others,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   For Miami, the complaint is the latest in a long series of
corruption cases. In the past six years, state charges have been
filed against at least 270 public employees, as the city has
wrestled with hectic growth, ethnic divisions and drug-dominated
crime problems.
</P>
<P>
   The other defendants in the SEC case include the city's former
city manager and its former director of finance, who deny any
wrongdoing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
