<HEADER>
A2462 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-1STLD-     09-22 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSED DEAL WOULD DELAY COSTLY FIGHTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to update; total rewrite)  
 (ATTN: Calif., Alaska, Texas)  (lh) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Key members of Congress who met in secret Wednesday
night to weigh the fate of the Air Force's $70 billion F-22 fighter
jet program said they had sketched out a deal to delay production
of the plane by a year until it passes more flight tests.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting ended without a final agreement. But Rep. Jerry
Lewis, R-Calif., who persuaded the House to take the unusual step
of denying the Air Force $1.8 billion to buy the first six F-22s,
said the still-developing deal would prevent the purchase of those
planes next year.
</P>
<P>
   The outlines of a deal over the F-22 call for ``testing first,
and avoiding a rush to failure,'' Lewis said. The proposed
compromise would neither kill the program nor give it full life,
but would extend its incubation by a year.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, the chairman of the House Appropriations Committee's
military spending panel, said Sen. Ted Stevens of Alaska, the
Republican chairman of the Senate Appropriations Committee, offered
a deal in which some of the $1.8 billion would be shifted to more
research and development of the F-22. Little or no money would be
spent to start up full-scale production of the plane.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a key concession won almost single-handedly by
Lewis. Republican senators, backed by the White House, senior House
Republicans, the Air Force and the plane's prime contractor,
Lockheed Martin Corp., wanted all of the money restored to build
the planes as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Testing will be at the forefront,'' Lewis said. ``We will have
a pause in procurement.'' That means no F-22 would be produced in
2000. The Air Force has argued that a pause would kill the F-22
program.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiators were still far apart on how much money would be
spent on the aircraft next year. The Senate's bill called for a
total of $3 billion, with $1.8 billion for procurement, or buying
planes, and $1.2 billion for research and development, or testing
parts and prototypes.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force already has spent close to $25 billion developing
the F-22, but has completed only about 5 percent of the necessary
flight tests. Over the next decade, it plans to spend $40 billion
or more building 339 of the aircraft. That puts the price tag of
each F-22 at close to $200 million, making it the costliest fighter
jet ever conceived.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who argued that the plane is too expensive and too
untested to be built as planned, persuaded the House this summer to
support a one-year pause in production of the F-22, so that the Air
Force and the Pentagon could reconsider plans to build three new
fighter jets in the coming decade, at a total cost of $350 billion
_ a sum far greater than the annual Pentagon budget.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's negotiations came in the opening round of a
House-Senate conference on the Pentagon spending bill for fiscal
year 2000, which begins Oct. 1. The final bill could total as much
as $270 billion, half the money Congress will appropriate to run
every agency of the government.
</P>
<P>
   According to several senators and representatives who were
present for the negotiations, Lewis offered to support production
of two F-22s, and Stevens countered with an offer to put most of
the $3 billion into further research and development of the plane,
with a fraction set aside to begin actually building it.
</P>
<P>
   But the two sides were still not on the same wavelength for most
of the three-and-a-half hour meeting, participants said. Lewis was
talking about the number of aircraft to be built, while Stevens was
talking about the amount of money to be spent.
</P>
<P>
   The two will meet again Thursday morning to try to pin down a
deal. Some bargain on the F-22 must be reached before the
negotiators agree on a Pentagon spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted to back Lewis' plan to spend the $1.8 billion on
other, less expensive aircraft, and Speaker Dennis Hastert
initially supported that idea. But Air Force officials managed to
change Hastert's mind, and he ordered Lewis to find a way to
restore some of the money for the F-22, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   The F-22 has also been strongly supported by the House Majority
Leader, Rep. Dick Armey, and the Majority Whip, Rep. Tom DeLay.
Both are Texas Republicans; many billions for the F-22 program
would be spent at Lockheed Martin's plant in Fort Worth, Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
