<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEDESTRIAN-FRIENDLY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY GETS UNLIKELY RECOGNITION: TRAFFIC SAFETY AWARD
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Ill.)  (Eds: Neel cq in last graf before optional material.) 
(nk) 
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Now, under the heading of ``Who Would Have Thought?''
comes the American Automobile Association's 1999 award for traffic
safety, an honor bestowed on communities that cherish pedestrians,
abhor bad driving manners, help little old ladies cross the street.
</P>
<P>
   One is Mendota, Ill., population 7,100, self-declared ``World's
Greatest Little City,'' a town with one stoplight and no taxis, a
place where people ponder what kind of reflectors to put on farm
equipment, consider it impolite to honk and take safety seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The other is a great big city, New York, population 7.3 million,
a place of horrific traffic and throngs of pedestrians that are
almost always in close touch. The kind of town where people view
traffic safety as a contradiction in terms and think blocking the
box is standing in front of the television.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be kidding!'' said Joe Scagluso, a computer
executive who works in Times Square, when informed Wednesday about
the city's new stature as a model of pedestrian safety. ``You take
your life in your hands out here,'' he said with little
exaggeration, as a line of trucks and taxis thundered past at 42nd
Street and Seventh Avenue, within inches of his ear.
</P>
<P>
   Down at Broadway and Houston, a quiet backwater compared to
midtown, Wolfgang Herrmann offered his own assessment. ``There are
always more cars,'' said Herrmann, 68, a retired salesman and
seasoned pedestrian. ``In a few years the city will be totally
kaput.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, he'd find some major disagreement at AAA, the
nation's oldest and largest advocacy group for yes, drivers. It
will honor both New York and Mendota on Thursday with the group's
Distinguished Achievement Award _ not to be confused with its
Outstanding Achievement Award and Excellent Achievement Award.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York has more traffic and more pedestrians than most
places in the world, but this is not a measure of congestion,''
said Mark Kulewicz, director of traffic engineering and safety for
the Automobile Club of New York, the regional branch of the
American Automobile Association. ``It's about safety,'' he said,
``And it turns out New York is a pretty walkable place. The
improvement has been dramatic.''
</P>
<P>
   In sister city Mendota on Wednesday, news of the award came as
Mayor Steve Bowne was presiding over Farm Safety Week, an event he
described as typical in a broad effort to enhance traffic safety.
Farmers, he said, are being encouraged by the city to replace or
install bright reflectors on any equipment they drive into town.
</P>
<P>
   ``This award speaks to a real commitment to safety, and not just
by the police,'' he said, adding that other programs, involving the
schools and parents, have been aimed at requiring children to wear
bicycle helmets, and instructing people how to properly use car
seats for infants.
</P>
<P>
   Bowne, clearly delighted to share the spotlight with New York,
offered a dash of his own big-city sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm wondering if I can use this award to launch a campaign for
the Senate from New York,'' said Bowne, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, famous back home for cracking down on
jaywalking and erecting barricades in midtown to help out drivers,
received news of the award with his own big-city sense of humor.
``New York City is honored to receive this prestigious award, which
recognizes our national leadership in the area of traffic safety,''
he said in a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   But seriously, the AAA said it determined its winners by
evaluating such data as pedestrian fatalities, seat belt use,
biking accidents and drunken driving. It singled New York out for
its steep drop in pedestrian fatalities: Based on police reports,
it said 179 pedestrians were killed in the city in 1998, a 51
percent drop in the eight years since 1990, when there were 366
pedestrian deaths. (One rather big footnote: Pedestrians still make
up about half those killed in the city's traffic accidents.)
</P>
<P>
   The group said the city deserved kudos for attacking such safety
problems with educational programs and police work
</P>
<P>
   ``We are delighted to recognize the vital and life-saving work
that is being done by the city of New York and the other award
winners,'' said Donald T. Phillips, president of the Automobile
Club of New York, who is to announce the group's selection of New
York and Mendota at a banquet in Rye Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their dedication to traffic safety cannot be surpassed,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for pedestrian safety, suggesting that the American
Automobile Association's dedication to both sides of the story left
something to be desired, said the group had ignored serious safety
problems that remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city does deserve credit, but needs to widen its scope
from simply dealing with pedestrian education and drunken driving
to measures that reduce aggressive driving,'' said Neel Scott, the
campaign director for Transportation Alternatives, an advocacy
group for pedestrians and bicyclists.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the seeming chaos of city streets Wednesday, where
construction had converted many sidewalks into scaffold-covered
obstacle courses and pedestrians maneuvered clogged crosswalks,
many pedestrians reacted to the news of the award with
bewilderment.
</P>
<P>
   ``People just run you over,'' said Tone Christensen, a model on
her way to a haircut, who was interviewed at the corner of 42nd
Street and Seventh Avenue. Barely audible under the din of
construction and heavy trucks grinding over potholes, she stood out
in the crowd for her courage _ if not foolhardiness _ since she was
riding a bicycle through Times Square, and doing so without a
helmet.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have just to watch very closely,'' said Ms. Christensen, a
native of Norway. ``The people in cars are so aggressive _ they are
very selfish, I think.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
