<SLUG> BC-MULTICULTURAL-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING :  GENERAL MOTORS AIMING PITCHES TOWARD BLACK
CONSUMERS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   General Motors, the nation's largest advertiser, is
significantly increasing efforts to aim sales pitches at black
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   GM, which spent $2.1 billion on American advertising last year,
has signed an agreement with BET Holdings Inc. in Washington, owner
of media properties that include the Black Entertainment Television
cable network, Emerge and Heart &AMP; Soul magazines and BET Weekend, a
Sunday newspaper supplement.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, for one year with options to renew, deepens a
relationship between GM and BET that has included traditional
elements like commercials and print ads. GM will also become
involved with BET.com, a Web site being started by BET with
partners like the Microsoft Corp. They will also cooperate in
entertainment marketing promotions that could, for instance, lead
to product placement of GM cars and trucks in movies produced by
BET.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is emblematic of two important trends that are
reshaping the advertising and media industries. One is the
increasing interest among mainstream advertisers in so-called
multicultural marketing aimed at fast-growing demographic groups
like black, Hispanic and Asian-American consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The domestic automakers ``had the lion's share of the
African-American and Hispanic markets and lost that for various
reasons,'' Philip Guarascio, vice president for marketing and
advertising at the North American operations of GM in Detroit, said
in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``That business is available to get back,'' he added, ``and all
of us are very aggressive in trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis Carr, executive vice president for broadcast media at BET,
praised GM for ``a tremendous step toward showing its commitment to
and value for the African-American consumer market.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That issue is farther along in the last year than in the past
15,'' he added, referring to agitation by some to prod mainstream
marketers into spending more to reach minority consumers in
minority media.
</P>
<P>
   Such consumers ``have to be taken much more seriously, not as a
secondary target but as a primary target,'' Carr said, adding: ``In
places like New York, Chicago, Los Angeles, Detroit, Philly, if you
add up the African-American population, the Hispanic population and
the Asian population, they're not minorities anymore. They're
majorities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You either get it now,'' Carr said, ``or get it later, when
your competitors are in front of you.''
</P>
<P>
   The other trend the deal typifies is the rise in what are known
as cross-media advertising packages, which are meant to provide
``one-stop shopping'' in the various properties owned by media
conglomerates. A primary reason given by the top executives of
Viacom Inc. and the CBS Corp. for their merger is the ability of a
combined Viacom to offer advertisers consumers of all ages in media
as disparate as television, radio, films, billboards and the Web.
</P>
<P>
   GM has signed a big cross-media agreement with units of Time
Warner Inc., as has the Dodge division of DaimlerChrysler AG Ford
Motor Co.'s cross-media deals include one with Martha Stewart
Living Omnimedia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to use BET's resources as a platform to create what I
call naturally intrusive marketing that starts connecting with
potential customers,'' Guarascio said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cross-media in its purest form is just a dollar commitment,''
he added. ``This is more elaborate.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Guarascio said, rather than develop a TV program
simply because BET owns a cable network, ``we can come up with a
special on African-American Olympic hopefuls'' based on the GM
sponsorship of the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``If an idea is big enough, we can take it outside BET,'' he
added, ``like making it part of our Warner Brothers venture.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal calls for General Motors to increase its ad spending in
BET media by more than 50 percent. Guarascio and Carr declined to
provide details.
</P>
<P>
   According to Competitive Media Reporting, a unit of VNU NV, GM
has already been raising its budgets devoted to buying commercial
time on Black Entertainment Television. The company spent almost $4
million there in 1998, compared with $2.9 million in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
