<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF: PAKISTAN, SRI LANKA, BRITAIN, RUSSIA, TURKEY,
ITALY, SPAIN, CANADA, MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: COUP RUMORS DISMISSED
</P>
<P>
   Responding to rumors of an army coup, Information Minister
Mushahid Hussain said no such thing would happen because there was
``complete harmony'' between the civilian and military wings of the
government. Opposition groups have united against Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif since he called for a withdrawal of Pakistan-supported
forces from a conflict with India in Kashmir this summer.
</P>
<P>
   SRI LANKA: CALL FOR WAR
</P>
<P>
   In a demonstration in Colombo, hundreds of hard-line ethnic
Sinhalese nationalists, part of a group called the National
Movement Against Terrorism, urged the government to crush the Tamil
Tiger guerrillas militarily rather than seek a negotiated
settlement. Suspected Tiger militants killed more than 50 Sinhalese
villagers last weekend. The Tigers are seeking a separate ethnic
Tamil state.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: A DIANA MEMORIAL
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair announced that a fountain would be
built in a London royal park, not yet chosen, to honor Diana,
Princess of Wales. Plans by the government-led memorial committee
to erect a fountain in the gardens of Kensington where she lived
were dropped last year because of local objections.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: PLEDGE ON CHECHNYA
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops ``have no intention of entering Chechnya,'' the
deputy interior minister said, dismissing reports that the Kremlin
plans to repeat the disastrous civil war it waged against the
breakaway republic from 1994 to 1996. But Russian jets made 30
strikes on targets inside Chechnya on Wednesday, authorities said,
and thousands of troops are trying to cordon off the republic to
block further attacks on neighboring Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: QUAKE VICTIMS PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred protesters in the city of Adapazari, which was
devastated in the earthquake last month, marched on the local
governor's office. They demanded tents and more attention to their
plight. It was among the most vocal protests by survivors bitter
about the government's failure to provide effective relief.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: OCALAN'S SURRENDER CALL
</P>
<P>
   The imprisoned Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan said he
hoped that some of the fighters of his Kurdistan Workers Party,
known as the PKK, would surrender to the army. ``As there is no
longer an obstacle to democratic steps,'' he said, ``I call on one
PKK group to come to Turkey with their arms as an expression of
good will.'' Ocalan has been condemned to death, but there has been
no move to carry out the sentence, and he has pledged to work for
peace.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: SOS SAVES ILLEGALS
</P>
<P>
   A total of 150 illegal aliens were rescued from a sinking ship
off southern Italy after a Kurdish refugee on land received a
cellular phone call from a panicked Kurdish passenger. The coast
guard said the passengers, mostly Kurds and North Africans, left
Turkey six days ago.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: MOVE TO EASE PINOCHET DISPUTE
</P>
<P>
   The foreign ministers of Spain and Chile met at the United
Nations in New York to reduce tensions over the arrest of Gen.
Augusto Pinochet, the former Chilean dictator, who faces an
extradition hearing next week in London. Madrid prosecutors again
sought to overturn a Spanish judge's warrant for Pinochet on
charges of rights abuses, despite previous court rulings that Spain
has jurisdiction in the case.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: MANITOBAN OUSTED
</P>
<P>
   Canada's longest serving provincial premier, Gary Filmon of
Manitoba, was narrowly defeated by his longtime rival, Gary Doer.
In his fourth attempt against Filmon in 11 years, Doer, a local
leader of the New Democratic Party, won 45 percent of the vote,
compared with 42 percent for Filmon, a Progressive Conservative.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: OPPOSITION PLAN
</P>
<P>
   A council of 14 prominent citizens has suggested that a
nationwide primary be held for opposition parties to choose a
single candidate to represent a coalition among them in
presidential elections next year. The council, which gave the
parties until Monday to accept or reject the plan, said 12,000
voting stations could be set up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
