<SLUG> BC-VILLAGE-VOICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 14 YEARS OF STABILITY, VILLAGE VOICE IS UP FOR SALE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Village Voice, the grizzled dean of alternative
newspapers, was put up for sale Wednesday by Stern Publishing,
ending a 14-year period when the contentious weekly's ownership
became uncharacteristically stable, its circulation
uncharacteristically buoyant and its profile uncharacteristically
low.
</P>
<P>
   The move makes The Voice and six other alternative weeklies
owned by Stern the latest baubles in the media industry bazaar, a
bazaar whose buyers are increasingly likely to come from unlikely
places.
</P>
<P>
   Among those expected to receive the financial data from Veronis,
Suhler &AMP; Associates _ the firm handling the sale _ are newspaper
companies, Internet companies, Wall Street investment firms and
overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
   By far the greatest change during the Stern period was the
elimination of the cover price for The Voice in New York City. The
move proved to be a boon to circulation, which was 111,298 in April
of 1996, when the cover price was eliminated. At then end of 1998,
circulation was 250,961, including 23,232 paid copies bought or
mailed to areas outside the city.
</P>
<P>
   There was no indication that a sale would have any immediate
impact on the newsroom, where the editor, Donald H. Forst, presides
over a staff of 100 journalists. David Schneiderman, a former Voice
editor who is now the president of Stern Publishing and one of
those organizing the auction, said: ``Change is usual for me. I'm
not surprised by it.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Stern, the chief executive of Stern Publishing, whose
investments in real estate and stewardship of the Hartz Group have
made him hundreds of millions of dollars, decided to sell his
publishing interests earlier this summer, when it became clear to
him that none of his three children wanted to manage this part of
the family business, according to Schneiderman and two of Stern's
children.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Stern, at 33 the youngest of Stern's children and the
only one who has worked in various capacities in publishing for the
last three years, said in an interview that she cared about the
business, but not as a life's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've loved working at The Voice,'' said Ms. Stern, who is
currently creative marketing director at the paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Running the publishing business was never what I aspired to do
as my life's work,'' she added, ``even though it has been a
tremendous experience.''
</P>
<P>
   For senior Voice writers, like Nat Hentoff, changes in ownership
are nothing new, and they have seldom if ever been harbingers of
interference with the self-consciously iconoclastic enterprise,
which was founded in 1955 by a group including the novelist Norman
Mailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a place that responds well to rigidity,'' Hentoff
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
