<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CARIOCA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAHIA CARIOCA, 79, RENOWNED BELLY DANCER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tahia Carioca, the dancer often called the Marilyn Monroe of the
Arab world, died of a heart attack in a Cairo, Egypt, hospital on
Monday. She was 79.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Carioca's parents were mortified when as a teen-ager she
took her beauty and talent to a Cairo nightclub to dance for
strangers, but it was the beginning of a journey that would make
her one of the world's most renowned belly dancers.
</P>
<P>
   Though the hold of fundamentalist Islam on Egyptian society has
virtually wiped out public manifestations of her art, she was in
the end granted the official approval her parents withheld, as the
Egyptian culture minister, Farouk Hosni, led her funeral
procession.
</P>
<P>
   She married 14 different husbands and once slapped King Farouk
when he threw an ice cube down her dress. She had roles in more
than 300 movies and television shows.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond mere fame, she virtually defined the intricate,
pulsating art called raqs sharqi in Arabic nations but known in the
West as the belly dance since a promoter at the 1893 Chicago
World's Fair dreamed up the name.
</P>
<P>
   Belly dancers cover less territory than Western dancers,
concentrating instead on often minute movements, sometimes
emphasizing such tiny muscular articulations as a quivering lower
lip.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really liked watching her; she would draw you in,'' said
Morocco, the stage name of a New York dancer who was inspired by
Miss Carioca and herself became a leading international performer.
She recalled the intensity of Miss Carioca's musicality and her
grace.
</P>
<P>
   When another great Egyptian belly dancer, Samia Gamal, died in
1994, her funeral was officially ignored, Morocco said. Her style
of dancing was sometimes called coltish or kittenish, in contrast
to the strength and dignity of Miss Carioca's approach. Miss
Carioca used her many films to raise the status of Middle Eastern
dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``She got it recognized as part of the Egyptian fine arts
landscape through her portrayals of it in movies,'' said Julie
Elliot, a belly dancer who lives in the San Francisco Bay area.
``She was a pioneer of modern oriental dance as it is done today.''
</P>
<P>
   Miss Carioca, originally named Abla Mohammed Karim, was born in
1920. She studied dance at Ivanova Belly Dancing School in Cairo
before moving to Mohammed Ali Street, Cairo's 1930s and '40s
version of Broadway. She took her stage names from the Brazilian
sambas she liked to perform.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Carioca became one of the biggest stars at a Cairo
nightclub owned by Badia Massabni, a Lebanese woman. The club was
an elegant re-creation of a British music hall and was frequented
by both British colonial administrators and the local aristocracy.
Women as well as men were part of the audience. Dancers wore
elegant, bejeweled gowns, sometimes with bare midriffs and
sometimes not.
</P>
<P>
   But the nice surroundings did not make belly dancing, something
that up until that time had been performed mainly at private
weddings and celebrations, publicly respectable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many men would reject the trade and would never marry a female
performer,'' Karin van Nieuwkerk wrote in a 1995 book about
Egyptian dancers called ``A Trade Like Any Other'' and published by
the University of Texas Press.
</P>
<P>
   Morocco said, ``Women do not show themselves publicly outside
the family and, maybe, somebody they're going to marry.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Miss Carioca married many interesting men, among them
a U.S. army officer whom she met during World War II, an actor and
a prominent playwright.
</P>
<P>
   That none of thd matches lasted long may have owed something to
her sometimes assertive personality, Morocco said. ``She was sort
of a big mouth,'' she said, ``but very sweet.''
</P>
<P>
   Miss Carioca is survived by an adopted daughter, Atiyat Allah.
</P>
<P>
   Her first film was ``Doctor Farahat'' in 1935, directed by Togo
Mizrahi. One of her most popular movies was ``Youth of a Woman,''
in which she played a landlady who seduces a naive, young peasant
student. It was shown at the 1956 Cannes International Film
Festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was an important part of Egypt's movie history,'' said the
film director Gulal Sharqawi.
</P>
<P>
   She gave up dancing in 1963 but as late as the mid-1980s ran her
own theater in Cairo, helping to write and choose plays, as well as
directing and producing.
</P>
<P>
   She took to wearing the Islamic head scarf before retiring
completely from public view 13 years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
