<SLUG> BC-MEDIMMUNE-U.S.-BIOSCIENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIMMUNE TO ACQUIRE U.S. BIOSCIENCE FOR $492 MILLION
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Pa., Md., Calif.)  (nk) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Medimmune Inc., a biotechnology company, said Wednesday that it
had agreed to acquire U.S. Bioscience Inc. in a stock swap valued
at about $492 million.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Bioscience, based in West Conshohocken, Pa., is developing
drugs for cancer and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is the latest in a wave of consolidation sweeping the
biotechnology industry. Increasingly, large pharmaceutical
companies, as well as some of the few profitable biotechnology
concerns, are buying up smaller companies to add new drug
candidates to their product pipelines. For companies like
Medimmune, which has seen its share price more than quadruple this
year, such deals are less costly and less risky than developing new
drugs from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   The year began with Warner-Lambert's announcement on Jan. 26
that it would pay $2.1 billion for Agouron Pharmaceuticals, a San
Diego company with a single marketed AIDS drug and a cancer
research program. Since then, Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn has bought Sugen
Inc., Abbott Laboratories has bought Alza, which had itself
acquired Sequus, and Johnson &AMP; Johnson has acquired Centocor.
Analysts say there will be many more such deals because drug
companies are pressured to increase earnings faster than they can
develop new products.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Medimmune, which is based in Gaithersburg, Md., closed
Wednesday at $109.25, up $7.1875, on Nasdaq. Shares in U.S.
Bioscience, closed at $14.125, up $2.625, on the American Stock
Exchange. Under terms of the deal, Medimmune will exchange 0.15
share of its stock for each Bioscience share.
</P>
<P>
   ``This acquisition further solidifies Medimmune's commitment to
the field of oncology,'' Wayne T. Hockmeyer, Medimmune's chairman
and chief executive, said in a statement. ``It will provide us with
three marketed products in the fields of oncology and infectious
disease, as well as development capabilities and an oncology sales
and marketing infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1988, Medimmune has specialized in drugs for
infectious diseases and organ transplants. Earlier this year the
company expanded its strategic focus to include cancer products
with the acquisition of Vitaxin. A genetically-engineered antibody
designed to prevent tumors from growing by restricting their blood
supply, Vitaxin is now in the second of the three phases of
clinical trials typically required for new drugs by the Food and
Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Bioscience's product portfolio includes Ethyol, which is
approved for the reduction of cumulative kidney toxicity associated
with repeated chemotherapy in patients with advanced ovarian cancer
and non-small cell lung cancer. In June, the drug was also approved
by the FDA for use in the reduction of chronic dry mouth in
patients undergoing radiation treatment for head and neck cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Other products include NeuTrexin, which is used to treat
moderate-to-severe pneumocystis carinii pneumonia in patients with
compromised immune systems and is in clinical development for
metastatic colorectal cancer, and Hexalen, a chemotherapy used to
treat patients with persistent or recurrent ovarian cancer.
Lodenosine is in clinical trials with the potential to treat HIV
infection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
