A2597 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     09-22 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME HAS COME FOR NFL CURRICULUM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you watch college football on television, you're guaranteed
to see it. A guy will make a nice play, his mug will pop up on the
screen and below that his height, weight and class will appear
this: Major _ Undeclared.
</P>
<P>
   How's that for intentional grounding? You don't have to be a
Rhodes scholar to scoff at the illogic of it all. Next to ``We
follow the NCAA rules to the letter,'' it's the biggest lie in
college sports, the notion that any football player in a top-25
program enrolls in school without a clue what he wants to do with
his life.
</P>
<P>
   Show us a Division I starter who hasn't planned on playing
professional football since he was knee-high to a tackling dummy
and we'll show you a player who came late to the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Football players enroll in college to pursue a B.A. all right _
a bachelor of athletics. Art history, public policy, gender
studies; academic beards, all. It's silly, making these
student-athletes hide their true ambitions just for the sake of
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Damn the deceit. If athletes intend to matriculate to the NFL,
there is plenty they'll need to know. Goodness knows there are
enough classes to keep them eligible. So just give them their own
major, already. For those studying pre-NFL, we recommend the
following core curriculum:
</P>
<P>
   __ Practical chemistry _ The bulky syllabus includes voluminous
discussion of anabolic steroids, Androstenedione and human growth
hormone. Masking agents also are uncovered and explored.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Class is pass/fail. Final exam is an urinalysis; pass it
and pass the course.
</P>
<P>
   __ Real life 101 _ Not an MTV course. Every week, students
accompany different blue-collar workers to their jobs, to see what
life is like for those lacking 4.2 speed in the 40.
</P>
<P>
   Required course materials: Hard hat, hair net, bulletproof vest.
</P>
<P>
   __ Marketing No. 1 _ Noted expert Brian Bosworth teaches
students the tricks to attaining fame whether or not they've got
game.
</P>
<P>
   __ Modern literature _ Students write their autobiographies, as
told to their athletic department tutors.
</P>
<P>
   Required text: ``Give Me the Damn Ball'' by Keyshawn Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   __ Jurisprudence for jocks _ Students study the pros and cons of
various criminal defenses. Misdemeanors, felonies and paternity
suits are explained in full.
</P>
<P>
   Guest lecturers include Jim Brown and Dave Meggett.
</P>
<P>
   __ Broadcasting for puns and profit _ Students learn to recite
cliches, read from a teleprompter, use a telestrator and act like
pompous fools.
</P>
<P>
   __ Pre-draft math _ Plugging in different sets of statistics,
students calculate Ricky Williams' 1999 salary.
</P>
<P>
   __ Advanced surfing _ Students build their own Web sites to open
up new windows of communication and commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Course Fee: $70, cost per student to register names and
addresses.
</P>
<P>
   __ Humanitarianism for beginners _ An independent study course.
Students spend four hours a week caring about somebody other than
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Note: The final exam is an essay. Students are marked down for
every ``I'' they use.
</P>
<P>
   __ Theology 300 _ Students explore the question: Does God really
decide who wins between the 49ers and the Rams?
</P>
<P>
   __ Managing the media _ Students are schooled in how to answer
any question blandly, even if the reporter is wearing a funny hat
or feather boa.
</P>
<P>
   Note: The final is an extemporaneous oral exam. Each student is
asked an outrageous question in front of the class and is graded on
the civility and insipidity of his response.
</P>
<P>
   __ Anger management _ The point is beaten into the ground that
people are not punching bags. Students explore healthful outlets
for their rage and aggression.
</P>
<P>
   Guest lecturers include Dan Wilkinson and Lawrence Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Above course is best taken in conjunction with:
</P>
<P>
   __ Weight-training for the soul _ Heavy self-examination
facilitates students in lifting the chips off their shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   __ Introduction to sociology _ Self-proclaimed expert Reggie
White lectures on the melting pot that is the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   __ Going deep _ An analytical-reasoning class in which students
tackle issues such as, why does the NFL court beer distributors as
major sponsors and then act so shocked when players turn up with
drinking problems?
</P>
<P>
   Moderator: Kerry Collins.
</P>
<P>
   That about covers it. It's a heavy workload, to be sure. But
whether students have their eyes on the sheepskin or the pigskin,
they've got to stay on the ball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
