<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE PULLING OUT ALL THE STOPS, THE METS CAN'T WIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There would be no dramatics, no questions about why
the Mets chose to pitch to one of the Braves' main offensive
threats on Wednesday night. This loss was simpler to explain and
much harder to take, ending not with a bomb but with a whimper.
</P>
<P>
   In the Mets' 5-2 loss to the Braves _ their second defeat in a
row and the sixth in eight games against Atlanta this season _ the
unraveling was not done by a most valuable player candidate but by
the Mets' own failure to squeeze out even a single run after
loading the bases in an eighth inning laden with frantic
substitutions.
</P>
<P>
   The result was the same. The Braves have proved in the first two
games of this pivotal series that despite struggling through their
closest division race in seven years, they still possess the finely
honed capacity to choke the bubbling hope out of the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   With the lss, the Mets dropped three games behind the Braves in
the National League East and face the ignominious possibility of
being swept for the first time since the All-Star Game break when
Al Leiter faces Greg Maddux on Thursday afternoon. The Mets still
have the wild card to fall back on, and that seems like a much more
likely landing spot. The Mets still led the wild-card race by three
games over the Reds, who were playing a late game in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   After the Braves took a 3-2 lead in the seventh, when the bottom
of the order began slapping singles about the field, the Mets had
their best threat of the series. Mike Piazza and Robin Ventura
singled to start the eighth inning. After a Braves pitching change
to bring in Mike Remlinger, Melvin Mora _ the first of a series of
pinch-hitters _ came to the plate for Benny Agbayani. Mora bunted,
moving Piazza and Ventura over.
</P>
<P>
   Shawon Dunston was announced as the next pinch-hitter for Darryl
Hamilton, but after Russ Springer came on to pitch, Bobby Valentine
inserted Matt Franco instead. He was intentionally walked to load
the bases. That brought Bobby Bonilla, who had smashed a pinch hit
double Tuesday night, to the plate to hit for Rey Ordonez.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast. First, the Braves would bring in Terry Mulholland
to pitch to Bonilla and Valentine would send Jay Payton in to run
for Matt Franco. He took the first pitch for a ball, then fouled
off the next two to go down 1-2. He swung on the fourth pitch he
saw to strike out. Todd Pratt _ the fifth pinch hitter _ was next,
pinch hitting for pitcher Orel Hershiser. He grounded out weakly to
end the inning, the Mets using everyone except the equipment
manager in an astounding show of futility.
</P>
<P>
   They have tried to pitch Chipper Jones away and they have tried
to jam him inside. With each little move their pitchers make, the
Mets, like men trying to wriggle free of quicksand, sink just a
little bit more.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, the Mets went at Jones again, hoping that this
time the pitch would squeeze somewhere outside what seemed to be
Jones' enormous hitting zone, that an intentional walk was really
not necessary to neutralize the danger of the Braves' best player.
Jones had hit two home runs Tuesday night, and it was reasonable to
wonder why the Mets would even pitch to him.
</P>
<P>
   But they did, and they paid for it. Orel Hershiser sent a
fastball high and inside in the first inning, and Jones slammed
another home run to give the Braves a 2-0 lead and created perhaps
the best argument for the Mets to not let him get anywhere near the
batter's box again.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday night, the Braves would look just as foolish
facing a slugger. Piazza had eked out just one hit Tuesday night,
but he has bludgeoned Tom Glavine in the past. Piazza entered the
game batting .389 against Glavine (14 for 36) with three home runs.
Finally, it was time for the Braves to make a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza worked the count to 2-2 in the fourth, with John Olerud
on first. Glavine tried to work a pitch past Piazza, but the ball
stayed up and over the plate. Piazza belted it to left field for
his 37th home run of the year and a tie score, 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine, a former Cy Young award winner like Tuesday's starter
John Smoltz, is not the same pitcher this season. In his last
start, Glavine allowed four runs and eight hits in just five
innings. He is just 11-11 this season, with an unusually high
earned run average of 4.35.
</P>
<P>
   With Greg Maddux still to come, the Mets knew that this might be
their best opportunity to take a game from the Braves. Countering
with Orel Hershiser, the Mets could rely on getting at least six
strong innings.
</P>
<P>
   What they could not have anticipated was that, except for the
home runs, Hershiser would engage Glavine in the second quickly
paced pitchers' duel in as many nights. After giving up the home
run and then walking Ryan Klesko, Hershiser retired the next 11
batters on a variety of grounders and pop-ups.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves barely mounted a threat in the bottom of the fifth,
when Eddie Perez singled up the middle. But Walt Weiss struck out
and Piazza sent a one-hop throw to Rey Ordonez that got Perez at
least two feet from second base. Glavine struck out to end the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, Hershiser hit Gerald Williams in the back.
Williams was on first when Jones came up. Hershiser had got Jones
to ground out weakly in the third. His first two pitches were away.
His second was not. Jones made contact, but the fly ball settled
softly into Rickey Henderson's glove. Hershiser then made an
acrobatic spinning catch of Ryan Klesko's hopper to the mound to
end that inning, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
