<HEADER>
A2600 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-REDSKINS-JOHNSON-     09-22 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REDSKINS-JOHNSON-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.) 
QUIETLY, JOHNSON LIFTS UP THE REDSKINS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASHBURN, Va. _ Brad Johnson's world has been flat, round and
steep all in one, a kid who grew up in the mountains of North
Carolina, living to play basketball but winding up a quarterback,
at first a wounded one and then a star.
</P>
<P>
   He was unknown at Florida State, where he started six games and
was the 14th quarterback selected in the 1992 draft. He was
inactive for the Minnesota Vikings for two years, sped to the World
League, came back as a big-time Vikings starter, went back to being
a backup, then became a starter again and then a backup again, all
the time suffering injuries from neck to ankle to thumb to knee.
</P>
<P>
   Now a Washington Redskin, some of his teammates say of Johnson,
``It's Brad's World.''
</P>
<P>
   They say he seems to be in his own time zone, his own space,
with a mind that they have been unable to unlock. He does not rant
in the middle of the huddle or the locker room. He enters and
leaves in his pigeon-toed stroll with few knowing more about him.
He says especially little to the defensive players. He does talk
more one on one, though, picking his spots, finding his way and
creating his own nook since being acquired on Feb. 15.
</P>
<P>
   In that whirlwind trade, the Vikings received three draft picks:
a first-round choice (11th overall) and a third-round pick in
April's draft and a second-round pick in next year's draft.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived here for his news conference with the Redskins
showcasing their three Super Bowl trophies. Get the hint? The
Redskins have given up plenty for Johnson. Some said too much.
</P>
<P>
   But not Darrell Green, the 17-year cornerback who is one of the
Redskins' staples.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids we had here before, and I mean K-I-D-S,'' he said,
spelling for emphasis, ``they came at a time playing quarterback
for us when there was so much going on in the staff, management,
coaching, new players, at the beginning of a whole era. I'm talking
about Heath Schuler and Gus Frerotte and Trent Green. Great guys,
but not prepared for the scrutiny of the situation and not allowed
to grow. Brad Johnson magnifies that. This is a pro. A
professional. This guy can look at five receivers on every play. A
professional at his position who knows what it takes to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Through two weeks of pro football, across the league, it has
been Brad's World.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson ranks first in quarterback passer rating (129.5). He has
thrown five touchdown passes and no interceptions. He has passed
for 613 yards. He has completed 65.6 percent of his passes. Under
his direction, the Redskins have gained more first downs (53) and
scored more points (85) than any team.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday he helped Washington score 50 points against the
Giants. In this week's version of New York, New York, the Redskins
(1-1) return to Giants Stadium to play the Jets (0-2).
</P>
<P>
   In Brad's World the snaps are clean, the setups in the pocket
are quick, the pass protection is rigid, the scene develops quickly
for him, all receivers are open, passes are perfect, receivers
catch it, drives roll. And roll. And roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing ain't all me,'' Johnson said Wednesday afternoon at
the Redskins' practice facility. ``I've had some success and so has
the team, and we're all trying to build on it. The perception of
what a quarterback should be is not all yelling and standing up in
the middle of the room getting attention. A leader does his work
and does it right and then watches everyone get on board. This team
needed a new direction. You look up there on the walls and there's
Joe Theismann who played here, and I tell you, he's a different
person than me. But there are a lot of different ways to skin a
cat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brad's World? That's actually kind of accurate. I'm an
easygoing person. I'm quiet. But I'll do anything to win.''
</P>
<P>
   He is a survivor who flourished.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who turned 31 last week, toiled through more than half
a season in his second year at Minnesota in which he did not even
dress for games. ``I knew I wasn't a good football player,'' he
said, ``but I thought one day if things come together I could play
in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   He earned his way into uniform as a backup to Warren Moon and
then asked the Vikings in 1995 to send him to the World League.
Many quarterbacks run from the World League, but Johnson ran toward
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked to go because I knew I needed to play,'' he said. ``It
worked out. I learned how to become more assertive there. I had to
be creative, speak up for myself, for the team, take some chances
with the offense. I wouldn't say I went there immature, but I did
go there as an immature quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson got a break in 1996 when Moon was injured, and he played
beautifully (2,258 yards, 17 touchdowns in 12 games). The next
season he started 13 games _ 3,036 yards and 20 touchdowns _ before
injury hit. Last year he lost his job, for good, to Randall
Cunningham after more injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate the perception that I didn't play well or that I wasn't
able to compete in Minnesota,'' Johnson said. ``But I give the
coaches and the people there credit because they stayed with me in
the early years; they gave me a chance to learn, and they saw
something in me. They knew I was willing to work hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Safety Sam Shade said: ``We've got plenty of guys who talk a
lot. I think Brad is more like me. I just got here from Cincinnati,
him from Minnesota, so we want to get things done before you start
talking a lot and telling people how to get up to speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is 6 feet 5 inches, 224 pounds, and he is 16-9 as a
National Football League starter. He has thrown 49 career touchdown
passes, 29 interceptions. He has sparkled before, just not
consistently because of injury and circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   Norv Turner, the Redskins' head coach, said Johnson is sharp in
the film room and translates that onto the field. Turner said that
Johnson improvises during games and that ``our whole team is
feeding of him right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Westbrook, the big-play receiver, said that he and
Johnson talk all the time, even in the huddle, about how to run a
pass route and about what each other expects.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has a grip on the offense. He releases the ball quickly.
He scrambles looking for receivers. He knows what he is doing, his
teammates say.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, if he continues leading the Redskins to victories, Brad's
World will easily become their World.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had an opportunity and I've tried to be prepared for it
and hit it,'' Johnson said. ``My goal is not to have 53 friends on
the team, but my goal is to gain respect for them and for myself
and this organization. I used to pull for this organization as a
kid; they were my favorite team. It's been some down times here
lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I think about some of the bad times that happened for me,
during them, I kept busy looking to see what good would happen
next. A lot quarterbacks, a lot of players have been cut and traded
and bounced back. We've got a group here that can do something big.
I want to be a big part of that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
