<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TOBACCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TOBACCO BECOMES A FEDERAL CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, Sept. 23:
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department's lawsuit against the tobacco industry
may prove a critical moment in the fight against smoking if it
forces the industry to stop marketing cigarettes to children and
agree to greater federal regulation. Congress, unable to wean
itself from campaign contributions from the tobacco industry,
refused last year to curb the industry's devious marketing
practices or to give the Food and Drug Administration authority to
regulate tobacco and nicotine. That has left the Clinton
administration no choice but to seek change through the courts.
</P>
<P>
   The potential costs of this suit to the industry are crippling,
which may give the industry a powerful incentive to settle on the
government's terms. The lawsuit seeks monetary recovery for the
more than $20 billion a year that the federal government spends on
treating people with smoking-related diseases under federal health
programs. The government is also seeking any ill-gotten profits
made through fraud and misrepresentations. Equally important, it
asks for permanent injunctions against industry deceptions about
the hazards of smoking.
</P>
<P>
   The industry has long understood, through its own research, that
smoking can cause disease and death and that nicotine is addictive.
Yet it carried out a relentless national campaign of falsehoods
designed to cast doubt on those very questions. The conspiracy of
lies has been documented in thousands of incriminating documents
unearthed in litigation brought by the state attorneys general.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the industry agreed to pay 46 states $206 billion over
25 years. Four other states had earlier reached settlements
totaling $40 billion. The state settlements also included
restrictions on outdoor advertising and the use of promotional
products to lure children to the smoking habit. But much remains to
be done to curb teen-age smoking and to help millions of addicted
smokers quit.
</P>
<P>
   Congress should give the Justice Department the $20 million it
has requested in the fiscal year 2000 budget to pursue this case.
The industry will likely spend much more than that fighting the
suit. Billions of dollars ride on the outcome. But it is the
nonmonetary controls that could help reduce smoking's annual death
toll of 400,000 Americans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 2317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
