<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKS-DECIMALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL PICKS DAY TO BEGIN TEST OF PRICING STOCKS IN DECIMALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A securities industry trade group has chosen what is
certain to be one of Wall Street's slowest trading days of next
year to begin the process of converting stock prices to decimals
from fractions.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities Industry Association, whose members include Wall
Street investment banks, brokerage firms and mutual fund companies,
said yesterday that it would ask securities regulators to approve a
three-phase conversion process that would begin Monday, July 3,
with a one-month pilot test involving about 40 securities.
</P>
<P>
   Those 40 securities, which have yet to be chosen but which will
include stocks on all of the major equity markets, will have their
prices quoted in minimum increments of 5 cents. Currently, most
stock prices move in minimum increments of one-sixteenth of a
dollar, or 6.25 cents, and are quoted on trading terminals,
newspapers and other forums in fractions.
</P>
<P>
   For more than two years, regulators and Wall Street firms have
been discussing the looming conversion of stock and option prices
to decimals, a move that many overseas markets have already made.
But the move has been put off until after the beginning of next
year to allow securities firms to prepare their computer systems
for the Year 2000 issue.
</P>
<P>
   A major concern of securities firms is that the conversion will
increase the number of quotes and orders so much that it might
overload exchanges' computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   A study commissioned by the association predicted that
converting to a system where stock prices are quoted and move in
increments of one penny at a time would increase by 80 percent the
number of trades taking place each day. In addition, the number of
quotes processed through the computer systems of market
participants would jump by 139 percent each day, while overall
share volume would increase by only 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A move to a minimum price increment of 5 cents, however, would
cause an increase of only 3.5 percent in the number of trades and
quotes, the study predicted. Wall Street has already found that by
quoting stock prices in sixteenths rather than eighths of a dollar,
the average number of trades each day has increased faster than
expected.
</P>
<P>
   The trade group's Decimal Steering Committee chose July 3 as the
date to begin the conversion project because Tuesday, July 4, is a
national holiday. Although the financial markets will be open on
July 3, many Wall Street professionals are likely to turn the first
weekend in July into a four-day holiday, making trading volume
light as the switch to decimals gets under way.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed timetable for the decimal conversion must be
approved by the Securities and Exchange Commission. Annette
Nazareth, director of market regulation at the SEC, lauded the
industry's effort to move along the switch to decimal pricing. But
in a statement issued Wednesday, she added, ``Although the staff is
open-minded regarding possible implementation phase-in plans, we
would obviously view with a critical eye any plan that
substantially delayed the ultimate implementation of decimal
pricing.''
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 7, in the second phase of the proposed process, all
stocks and stock options would begin to be quoted in decimals and
traded in five-cent minimum increments. Eight weeks later, on Oct.
2, all securities could be quoted and traded in ``whatever
increments market forces determine,'' the group said.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in November, securities firms are expected to begin
internal testing of the ability of their computer systems to use
decimal pricing, followed by testing between firms in April and
May.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 2317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
