<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2610 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-ISLAND-LAB-NYT &LR;      09-22 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ISLAND-LAB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESIDENTS NEAR U.S. LAB TAKE GERMS STUDY MATTER-OF-FACTLY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORIENT POINT, N.Y. _ Plum Island doesn't look all that sinister
from here, a mile across open water.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the signs at the restricted ferry dock warn the curious to
keep their distance. And there have been plenty of rumors over the
years that the Agriculture Department's Animal Disease Center on
Plum Island is just a euphemistic front for black-budget research
into horrifyingly deadly substances like nerve gas, or anthrax, or
the hantavirus.
</P>
<P>
   But few people have lost any sleep worrying about outbreaks. In
fact, residents seem to have become so dulled to the rumors that
facts hardly get them going.
</P>
<P>
   Or so it appeared Wednesday, upon the news that the government
plans to upgrade its super-secret laboratory on the tiny island to
study germs that can kill humans as well as cows and swine. The
plan is part of an effort by the Clinton administration to deter
so-called bioterrorists, who might use germs to attack American
crops or livestock.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't do it here, where are they going to do it?''
said Pep Kalin, a retired water company official who was walking
along Route 25 in a stiff, cold wind. ``I've been living 49 years
here in Orient. Everybody talks about Plum Island, Plum Island,
Plum Island. But it hasn't bothered me yet. My father-in-law worked
there in maintenance, took 31 showers a day, every time he went
from one building to the next. Their operation doesn't bother me.
If you don't like it, get the hell out of town.''
</P>
<P>
   What was on people's minds Wednesday in Orient _ and in East
Marion, Greenport and the other hamlets along the North Fork where
many of Plum Island's 300 current workers live _ was money. The
Agriculture Department is asking for $75 million next year for the
project, and out-of-work mechanics, shopkeepers and local officials
all wondered aloud how soon those millions could begin trickling
into wallets, cash registers and tax coffers.
</P>
<P>
   At the 200-year-old Orient Country Store, Linton Duell, the
owner for the last 20 years, said he hoped that the more dangerous
pathogens being studied would mean more jobs for guards and cleanup
crews, the kinds of people who frequent his shop to pick up the
paper, take a load off at the lunch counter, nurse a cup of hot
coffee and catch up with their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to be done somewhere,'' Duell said of the sensitive
research on the island. ``I just hope they do it well. I hope the
security is up to standards. They'll probably be hiring for
security personnel. They were contracting it out to the lowest
bidder. But I'm not so sure that's the best policy when you're
talking about national security.''
</P>
<P>
   David Kapell, a real estate broker and the mayor of Greenport,
was practically ecstatic about the prospects for local development.
</P>
<P>
   ``What could be better for the area than to have a cutting-edge
technology developed right here?'' he said in the middle of lunch
with his wife, guessing that the project would create at least 50
new jobs right off the bat. ``This is exactly the kind of thing we
need.''
</P>
<P>
   He, too, might benefit. After all, he said, he had sold houses
to at least half a dozen Plum Island scientists over the years.
</P>
<P>
   A few dozen new jobs could provide quite a lift, Kapell said.
Plum Island remains one of the North Fork's largest employers, but
only because industry of any kind is scarce. The animal research
center, which opened in the early 1950s on the 840-acre island, was
dramatically cut back in the late '70s or early '80s. ``We saw the
virtual elimination of a whole class of residents,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kapell said he was not completely overlooking the danger of the
proposed changes at Plum Island. ``There's always concern, every
time you have a potentially deadly activity,'' he said. ``But it's
got to be considered in the light of 50 years of history of a safe
operation. I've known enough of the scientists over the years to
know that these are very legitimate, highbrow researchers. And,
personally, I have faith in the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Kapell drives a car with official plates. He is the
government.
</P>
<P>
   There are more skeptical types, like an older man who was
walking along the deserted central street of a subdivision of large
summer homes that have a clear view of Plum Island. ``Our secret
government,'' he said, reading a newspaper headline, then added,
``You never know what they're up to.''
</P>
<P>
   As a flock of starlings took flight before him, the man, who
refused to give his name, said he worried about birds flying over
to Plum Island and picking up deadly germs. ``I'd love to see that
place shut down,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
