<SLUG> BC-REAL-CHECKOUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REALNETWORKS, REALJUKEBOX AND FINALLY, IT SEEMS, REAL MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Wash.) (rk) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Realjukebox is starting to earn some real money
for its developer, Realnetworks Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Realnetworks, a Seattle company that makes software for sending
audio and video over the Internet, will announce a series of
alliances on Thursday with companies that will sell products or
provide information to users of Realjukebox, a software product
that allows people to copy, store and play music from compact disks
on their personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Checkout.com, the new Internet entertainment Web site co-founded
by Hollywood talent manager Michael Ovitz, will become the
exclusive online vendor of compact disks and provider of
entertainment information for users of Realjukebox. Another
company, 800.com, will be the exclusive seller of electronic
products, while MP3.com will provide music that users of
Realjukebox can download free.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deals are not being disclosed. But industry
executives said that Checkout.com would pay Realnetworks at least
$8 million; the two other deals are somewhat smaller. Together the
deals would represent a nice lift for Realnetworks, which had
revenues in its latest quarter of $28 million and a net loss of
$270,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realnetworks is getting to a new level of scale in terms of
the impact we have and our ability to derive economic benefit from
it,'' said Rob Glaser, the company's chairman and chief executive.
He said income from the agreements would be spread over several
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Realjukebox, which can be downloaded for free over the Internet,
has gained 10 million users since its introduction in May. The
software allows users to store music from compact disks on their
hard drives, to download music from the Web and to play back the
music on their personal computers or download it to new portable
digital music players.
</P>
<P>
   That large base of users is what made it attractive to
Checkout.com, a new entertainment service that hopes the deal will
drive users to its Web site as it fights to distinguish itself from
numerous other online music vendors. ``It's not like we're just
throwing some ad banners out there,'' said Richard Wolpert,
Checkout.com's acting chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Checkout.com, a privately held company based in Beverly Hills,
Calif., bills itself as an entertainment portal, providing
information on entertainment such as biographies and concert
reviews, in addition to selling compact disks. Its other big backer
is Ronald W. Burkle, a billionaire supermarket magnate. Ovitz and
Burkle have purchased several Internet companies to augment their
fledgling Internet empire.
</P>
<P>
   Realnetworks is also announcing a deal with Sony Music to allow
consumers who play a forthcoming album by Rage Against the Machine
on their computers using Realjukebox to download an unreleased
track of the band's live performance at Woodstock this summer.
Realjukebox users will also be able to preview three tracks from
the record about a month before its scheduled release in early
November.
</P>
<P>
   The announcements come as Realnetworks begins shipping the final
version of Realjukebox. The 10 million downloaded until now have
been beta versions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
