<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MCCAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORAL: BASHING JOHN MCCAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, Sept. 23:
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain is a conservative Republican who favors tax
cuts and opposes abortions and most gun controls. So why are
right-wing groups like Americans for Tax Reform, the National Rifle
Association, the American Conservative Union and the Christian
Coalition saying terrible things about him? The answer is that
McCain is pushing for a ban on unregulated ``soft money'' donations
to political parties. These groups would not be affected by
McCain's legislation, but the Republican Party is urging them to
line up against it and help keep wavering Republican senators in
line.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the House passed the Shays-Meehan reform bill,
clearing the way for a renewed drive in the Senate. The legislation
sponsored by McCain and Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis., is supported
by seven Republicans and all 45 Democrats, but it will take 60
votes to break the expected filibuster. Some Republicans who say
they want reform were not willing to break the filibuster because
of alleged concerns about the constitutionality of McCain-Feingold.
In the past, they cited the bill's proposal to regulate
advertisements in the last two months of a campaign by allegedly
independent groups.
</P>
<P>
   But last week McCain and Feingold dropped that part of the bill.
Even so, Americans for Tax Reform and allied independent groups
have been busy this week in New Hampshire and South Carolina
attacking McCain. They accuse him of being an enemy of free speech
and conservative politics.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for these absurd charges is clear. These groups are
not really independent. They are more like adjuncts of the
Republican Party and share the party leadership's desire to
preserve money-driven politics. For example, Americans for Tax
Reform, run by Grover Norquist, a pal of Newt Gingrich, actually
received $4.6 million from the GOP in 1996 and ran ads to help
Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans say they decry the influence of
special-interest money in American elections. Among them is Chuck
Hagel of Nebraska, who last year ran against Mitch McConnell for
the job as the Senate GOP's chief fund-raiser. He cited what he
said accurately was McConnell's abuse of power in raising soft
money. George Voinovich, newly elected senator from Ohio, has said
he would vote for a soft-money ban. But the pressure from the party
machine is so great that both men are waffling on the
McCain-Feingold soft-money ban.
</P>
<P>
   Now is the time for these senators to follow McCain's brave
example in rejecting money-driven politics. The attack on McCain
has nothing to do with conservative principles. It is an attempt to
cripple his presidential campaign because he has challenged the
grip of special-interest money across the political spectrum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
