<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-RETURN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEENS GATHER FOR PRAYERS AT SITE OF TRAGEDY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Many young people dodged bullets inside
Wedgwood Baptist Church a week ago. Last night, hundreds were back
in the church praying and writing messages on the concrete floors,
vowing that fear and evil will not prevail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Satan, you can't stop us,'' said a message near the altar.
</P>
<P>
   Another said, ``Our God is an Awesome God.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Al Meredith, Wedgwood pastor, said he is humbled by the
courage the youth have shown since the shooting rampage, in which
Larry Gene Ashbrook fired more than 100 bullets during a See You at
the Pole youth rally. Ashbrook, 47, killed seven people and injured
seven others before taking his own life.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred young people and adults met in three separate
groups last night, and those in the sanctuary were invited to write
messages on the concrete, which has been stripped of bloodstained
carpeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are praying that a spirit of fear doesn't overtake us,''
Meredith told about 200 people in the fellowship hall.
</P>
<P>
   Meredith said later that writing the messages is a way for young
people to purge their grief. He said he is especially proud that
some wrote messages of forgiveness to the gunman.
</P>
<P>
   Near the spot where Ashbrook committed suicide, one youth wrote:
``We don't hate you, Larry Ashbrook. We hate Satan.''
</P>
<P>
   The messages included many statements of love for the people
killed.
</P>
<P>
   At the spot where children's choir director Sydney Browning was
slain, there were dozens of messages.
</P>
<P>
   Browning had T-shirts made for choir members bearing the
initials, ``TBCINT,'' an acronym for ``The Best Children's Choir in
North Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   One youngster wrote on the floor, ``Sydney We love you. Sing a
song for me in the TBCIH, meaning `The Best Children's Choir in
Heaven.' ''
</P>
<P>
   At all the doorways were declarations challenging Satan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Satan I rebuke you from ever passing through these doors ever
again,'' one said. ``This is my Father's House. You have no place
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The messages will be covered when new carpeting is installed
this week. But one teen, who wrote a message to his slain best
friend, said that doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will know they are still under there,'' said Matt Henson,
17.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Fannin, the church youth director, said many young people
who survived the shooting had feared going into the church again.
But they have gradually overcome the fears, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still in a grieving and healing process, though,''
Fannin said.
</P>
<P>
   A church member who requested anonymity was inside yesterday,
filling in bullet holes and shrapnel marks from a pipe bomb and
painting the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Meredith said that one Metroplex church took an offering and
donated $42,000 to the Wedgwood church. The donor congregation
asked not to be named, Meredith said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he received a call from President Clinton this week
offering condolences and inviting Meredith to the White House for a
prayer breakfast. Meredith had to decline because of a previous
engagement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reached Meredith on his car phone as Meredith drove to
the Monday afternoon graveside service for Cassie Griffin, a
14-year-old shooting victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president was very sympathetic and talked about the recent
tragedies in different parts of the country which were caused by
troubled individuals,'' Meredith said.
</P>
<P>
   During the five-minute call, Meredith said, Clinton expressed
concern about increasing gun violence and said he hopes to discuss
with Meredith how churches can reach angry, frustrated loners who
might commit such crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Meredith said that at the end of the conversation, he prayed for
Clinton and his family after asking the president's permission.
</P>
<P>
   The pastor also told church members last night that proposals
for a memorial have been made by the architect who is supervising
an expansion at the church. Church members voted to appoint a
committee to study the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The architect, Bill Petrelli of Arlington, has designed a
memorial that would honor the shooting victims and include the
message that the forces of darkness will not prevail over the
light, Meredith said. The octagonal structure would include
waterfalls and a reflecting pool. Petrelli didn't charge for the
design, Meredith said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 2327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
