<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0525 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2626 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CLEMENCY-NYT     09-22 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLEMENCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE CLEMENCY CONTROVERSY
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, Sept. 23,
1999:
</P>
<P>
   In offering clemency to 16 jailed Puerto Rican nationalists, did
President Clinton endanger the safety of the American people? That
is the question posed by the release this week of a strongly worded
letter to Congress from the Federal Bureau of Investigation. The
letter states that the FBI opposed clemency because it would return
hardened terrorists to the clandestine movement for Puerto Rican
independence and would ``psychologically and operationally
enhance'' the criminal activities of terrorist groups. Clinton will
need to answer these contentions, as they form the core of law
enforcement objections to his act of mercy.
</P>
<P>
   The president took an important, if belated, step on Tuesday to
try to quell the swirling controversy. In a five-page letter to
Rep. Henry Waxman of California, the ranking Democrat on the House
committee investigating the decision, Clinton provided his first
detailed explanation of the evidence and arguments that persuaded
him to make this rare use of his clemency power.
</P>
<P>
   The nub of his case was that none of the prisoners at issue were
``convicted of crimes involving the killing or maiming of any
individuals,'' and that the sentences they received were unduly
severe _ as many as 90 years in some cases _ for what they had
done. These are compelling arguments that led religious and
humanitarian leaders to call for clemency and led this page to
conclude there was a basis for clemency in these cases.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton has not adequately explained how he concluded that
the release posed no danger to the public. He said he took
seriously the opposition voiced by law enforcement officials and
made clemency conditional on a prisoner obeying regular statutory
parole requirements and renouncing violence. But he must answer
criticisms that such vows can be broken and that the mere presence
of a released nationalist can stir other terrorists toward
violence. Even acknowledging that the FBI has seldom seen a
terrorist it is willing to release, the agency has raised issues
that need a public answer.
</P>
<P>
   As for the widely held suspicion that Clinton's clemency
decision was influenced by the senatorial ambitions of his wife,
Hillary Rodham Clinton, the president said the timing was due to
the imminent departure of his former counsel, Charles Ruff, and the
decision was not tailored to please an important New York voting
bloc.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming Clinton's version of all these matters is true, he
should be willing to release the pertinent White House files.
Although the president constantly abused executive privilege when
trying to shield embarrassing information about Whitewater and his
affair with Monica Lewinsky, he may be on strong legal ground in
asserting privilege this time to resist a House subpoena for the
pardon documents. Under the Constitution, the power to pardon or
grant clemency is solely the president's. But this is a situation
that calls for maximum candor. Clinton's letter of explanation,
welcome though it is, is no substitute for full disclosure. As
Professor Stephen Gillers of New York University School of Law
suggested in an Op-Ed article in the Times on Monday, it should be
possible to strike a deal in which Congress agrees to drop its
subpoena in exchange for Clinton's voluntarily providing the
relevant White House documents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 2330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0526 </DOCNO>
