<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAK FELLS POLI-DIXON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Bad news continued Wednesday for the beleaguered
UCLA Bruins, who announced junior split end Brian Poli-Dixon is
probably out for the season after breaking his right wrist against
Fresno State.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's bad luck or cosmic retribution for the
disabled-parking scam _ exploit the handicapped, and bad karma's
sure to follow _ the Bruins now have lost three players for the
season: Poli-Dixon, defensive end Travor Turner and offensive
tackle Josh Webb.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, reserve freshman linebacker Asi Faoa might be lost
for the year because of a back injury suffered Tuesday, starting
cornerback Jason Bell is out indefinitely with a bad heel, and
starting quarterback Cory Paus is out at least a week because of
bruised ribs.
</P>
<P>
   Combine Poli-Dixon's injury with receiver Danny Farmer's
lingering ankle sprain and receiver Freddie Mitchell's nagging knee
sprain, and the Bruins are suddenly vulnerable at what was
considered their strongest position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking to (defensive coordinator) Bob Field about it _
we're a beat-up team,'' Bruins coach Bob Toledo said. ``Our
receivers were supposed to be the best in the country and now we're
beat up.''
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore Jon Dubravac, who was expected to redshirt, will
replace Poli-Dixon as the No. 2 split end behind Brad Melsby.
</P>
<P>
   Poli-Dixon was one of UCLA's top playmakers. He caught 10 passes
for touchdowns last year despite a sprained left wrist, and he has
eight catches in three games this season.
</P>
<P>
   The injury occurred in the first quarter, when he braced himself
after flipping over on a tackle. He played the rest of the game,
dropped a pass and caught a touchdown pass, then practiced Monday
and Tuesday. He complained of pain, however, and X-rays Wednesday
revealed a break.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins will request a medical redshirt for Poli-Dixon unless
he returns late in the season. Players may receive medical
redshirts if they do not play in more than three games. Toledo said
he'll request a medical redshirt for Faoa, as well, if he cannot
return.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Farmer had his best practice of the season Tuesday.
His cuts were sharp and routes crisp. He felt just as good
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hanging in there,'' he said. ``I'm starting to get my
rhythm back. Tuesday was the first time in a while I've practiced
the whole time. I feel comfortable again being on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmer also felt good last week _ until he tweaked the ankle
making a cut. Because it's the most serious type of sprain (above
the ankle bone), the Bruins worry Farmer won't be at full strength
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks pretty good,'' Toledo said. ``But he could go down
any second.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 2331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0527 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2630 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-PIRATES-HN     09-22 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-PIRATES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
So many mistakes, so little room for error. That was pretty much
the story of the Astros' 3-2 loss to the Pittsburgh Pirates on
Wednesday at Three Rivers Stadium.
<TEXT>
<P>
   First of all, there is the matter of assigning blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the umpires made the right calls, we just got beat by a
good pitcher,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said. ``If they
didn't, we got beat by the umpires.''
</P>
<P>
   The men in blue made a couple of calls with which the Astros
weren't particularly happy. Perhaps the most crucial came in the
sixth inning when Jose Lima walked Abraham Nunez on an apparent
three-ball count. At least that's how the Astros saw it.
</P>
<P>
   The confusion centered on a 2-0 pitch that Lima and just about
everyone on the Astros' bench thought was called a strike by
home-plate umpire Alfonso Marquez. Marquez denied signaling a
strike, making the count 3-0 instead of 2-1, as Lima thought.
</P>
<P>
   Nunez eventually walked and scored what proved to be the winning
run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't make a comment on that, because if I do, they'll stick
it to me,'' Lima said of the umpires. ``But I know in my heart that
it was a 2-0 count and that I threw a strike. It's on our
(pitching) charts. It's better for me to keep my mouth shut.''
</P>
<P>
   Easier said than done.
</P>
<P>
   ``The umpire is the boss behind the plate,'' Lima (20-9)
continued. ``I'm not a crybaby; I don't make excuses. When you see
me arguing, you'd better believe it's because I'm competitive, not
because I'm a crybaby. The umpires have the power out there, and if
I argue I'll get a bad reputation and I may never get another call.
I don't have anything else to say about that.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was plenty left to say about why the Astros lost for
the fifth time in seven games following their club-record 12-game
winning streak. The biggest reason was Pirates righthander Todd
Ritchie, who pitched a six-hitter and struck out 10 batters.
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie (14-9) even got praise from Astros center fielder Carl
Everett, which is the baseball equivalent of a presidential
endorsement. Everett seldom tips his cap to opposing pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid pitched a great game,'' Everett said. ``That's the
third time he's beaten us, so you have to give him credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie, who started the season in the minor leagues, has won
three of his four starts against the Astros, and the Pirates won
the season series 7-5. The Astros are off today before opening a
three-game series in Milwaukee over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pirates have had our number,'' Astros second baseman Craig
Biggio said. ``At least we didn't lose all three of these games. We
just need to get out of here, enjoy the day off and come back with
a fresh outlook Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   It may take more than a day off to change the Astros' outlook
about the quality of the umpiring in Wednesday's game. Dierker also
was peeved by a call at second base in the seventh inning when Lima
bunted into a double play, forcing Ricky Gutierrez at second in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone on our bench thought he was safe,'' Dierker said.
``This was a tough one to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The umpires were not to blame for all of the Astros' wounds;
some were self-inflicted.
</P>
<P>
   Lima twice failed in bunt situations. And with the score tied at
2 in the sixth inning, Everett made the final out between home
plate and third base when he tried to score from second on a ground
ball to first.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was clearly a baserunning mistake,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   With the bases loaded and one out, Daryle Ward hit a grounder to
Pirates first baseman Kevin Young, who one-hopped his throw to the
plate to force Stan Javier. While Pirates catcher Joe Oliver was
trying to sell his catch to the umpires, Everett was racing toward
the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver realized what was happening quickly enough to foil
Everett's plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see where he (Young) was throwing the ball,'' Everett
said. ``If there's a double-play ball and I'm on second base, I
always continue to go home. It was a miscommunication between me
and the third-base coach (Mike Cubbage).''
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the all the subplots was a swifty pitching duel between
Lima and Ritchie. The 2-hour, 3-minute game was the Astros'
shortest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how the clock reads, losses always make for a long
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``A loss is a loss,'' said Lima, who tied a career high with 10
strikeouts in seven innings. ``Even though the score was only 3-2,
I failed once again. We've got Cincinnati on our tails, and we
can't afford to be making mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates took a 2-0 lead on Warren Morris' RBI double in the
second and Brant Brown's third-inning sacrifice fly. Young singled
home Nunez after the controversial sixth-inning walk.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros scored both of their runs in the fourth inning, one
on Jeff Bagwell's RBI single up the middle and the other on Ken
Caminiti's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Lima failed in his second attempt to tie Joe Niekro's
single-season franchise record of 21 victories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
