<SLUG> BC-NY-MARITIME-COLLEGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDDLE EASTERN CADETS RESIGN FROM MARITIME COLLEGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ More than 20 Muslim cadets from the Middle East
resigned from the State University of New York's Maritime College
in the Bronx on Tuesday, saying they had been subjected to
demeaning treatment and, in two cases, physical attack by other
cadets.
</P>
<P>
   The freshman cadets, who are from Persian Gulf states like
Kuwait and Qatar, are all employees of a Kuwait-based shipping
company that is paying for them to study engineering or marine
transportation at the school. They contended that in the last
month, as they began to interact with upperclassmen, they had been
subjected to insensitive remarks about their religion and their
poor command of English.
</P>
<P>
   ``They treat Arabic people like animals,'' Mohamed Al-Marri, 22,
who is from Qatar, said of the indoctrination duty officers, who
are in charge of the cadets. ``They had problems with Arabic
people. They don't like our religion.''
</P>
<P>
   School officials said they were taking the complaints seriously
and were investigating. But they said they did not believe the
cadets were the targets of ethnic or religious bias, but were
chafing at the school's military rigors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The freshman year is like a plebe year _ it's pretty
arduous,'' said Rear Adm. David C. Brown, the president of the
Maritime College. ``There are a lot of rules. Everyone is above
you. Everybody has to participate in the same level of
regimentation and restriction.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he also thought that several of the students were
using the charges of persecution as an excuse to absolve them of
their financial obligation to United Arab Shipping Co., which began
sponsoring the students about a year ago. If the sponsored cadets
drop out of the school, they must repay their employer for all of
their tuition and other expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The school said the allegations involved 22 students, although
the students put the number variously at 21 and 23.
</P>
<P>
   The charges were levied as the school is attempting to resolve
financial problems of its own. Brown said Maritime desperately
needed to double its enrollment of 680 to remain a financially
viable part of the state university system. The enrollment of
foreign students is an important source of income for the school.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the Middle Eastern cadets remained in their rooms,
rather than lining up in formation or attending classes, and said
they would do so until they received instructions from United Arab
Shipping.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Abdullah Al-Shammari, a 24-year-old resident of
Kuwait, said he was the victim of an assault early Monday. He said
he answered a knock at his door at 3 a.m. and saw a man wearing a
black mask and black gloves. The man tried to hit him with a sharp
object, he said, and tried to push his way into his room.
Al-Shammari said he was scratched on his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Another Kuwaiti student, Faisal Ahmad, 25, said he and his
roommate were attacked in similar fashion, by a group of five men,
the previous weekend and also sustained minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the accusations were being investigated by the
university police and the commandant of cadets. Any cadets found
guilty of the attacks, he added, would be dismissed from the school
and could face criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   But, Brown added, ``We don't believe it's based on ethnicity or
religion.'' Rather, he said, he had reason to believe the attacks
had been personally motivated, although he declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Brown added that the American cadets had never had a problem
with Middle Eastern students. The school has had a successful
relationship with the Saudi Navy, he said. In 1995, 30 Saudi
students came to the college and 24 graduated in August. ``For us
and our students to interact with Middle Eastern students and know
their cultural requirements is nothing new,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
