<SLUG> BC-EDIT-EARTHQUAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE QUAKE NEXT TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, Sept. 23:
</P>
<P>
   In October, world population will reach 6 billion, or just
slightly less than double the population in 1960. That population
increase has not been distributed evenly, of course. Humanity has
crowded the coasts and clustered along the seams between tectonic
plates. It has made itself uniquely susceptible to disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Much was done in Taiwan to mitigate the effects of Tuesday's
earthquake, thanks to good and apparently well-enforced building
codes. But the simple proliferation of human beings dictated that
thousands would die. In the United States we have been lucky, so
far, that an economic toll from earthquakes is unmatched by a toll
in human lives.
</P>
<P>
   But such luck is not likely to continue forever. Even where the
best technology is enforced by the most able bureaucracies, it
seems inevitable that one day the mass of humans will outweigh the
protective infrastructure. In the developed world, we have been
absolved, to a striking degree, from the natural consequences of
our numbers. But as the world population continues to grow, to push
into crowded cities erected atop fault zones, to settle in flood
plains and low-lying coastal areas, we will be forced to witness
our own immensity in the immense casualties that follow upon
disaster. We will have to recognize that some regions impose a
harsh, inflexible limit to further population growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 2334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
