<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2635 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-FISCAL-570&AMP;ADD-NYT     09-22 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FISCAL-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI'S BUDGET FAILS TO USE GOOD TIMES TO PREPARE FOR BAD, CRITICS
SAY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ As they approved the new state budget last month,
Gov. George Pataki and legislative leaders called it a model of
sound judgment, a plan that raised spending at a modest pace and
put last year's large surplus into a reserve fund rather than
spending it.
</P>
<P>
   But a range of fiscal analysts, from Wall Street to private
watchdog groups to the state comptroller, have come to a strikingly
different conclusion: that despite a continuing economic boom that
has left most states in their best financial shape in decades, New
York's new budget actually worsens the state's long-term outlook.
</P>
<P>
   They point to several factors they say will make it harder to
keep the budget balanced in years to come:
</P>
<P>
   _ Spending is expected to rise faster than income this year,
because enormous tax cuts enacted in past years are keeping state
revenues nearly flat.
</P>
<P>
   _ The budget increased the use of one-time revenue sources that
cannot be repeated in the future, reversing Pataki's record of
cutting back on them.
</P>
<P>
   _ New tax cuts were enacted this year that will lower state
revenues in the future.
</P>
<P>
   _ While other states are using surpluses to pay off debts, this
budget will increase New York's debt, already the highest in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   These experts say the steps taken by the state were not
egregious, but that many were the sort of questionable maneuvers
that states usually make to get through hard times, not when they
are swimming in cash. The experts share a fear that time may be
running out to take advantage of the nation's long-running
expansion to get New York's finances in order.
</P>
<P>
   The most detailed and stinging criticism of the budget came
Wednesday, in a 58-page report by State Comptroller Carl McCall.
McCall projected that the state's $37.4 billion general fund will
face a $2.8 billion deficit next year, a $4.6 billion deficit the
following year, and considerably larger gaps after that.
</P>
<P>
   The deficits might not materialize if the economy continues to
grow at the blistering pace of the last three years _ something
economists do not expect _ but otherwise, they can be closed only
by cutting spending or raising taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's most distressing about it is they had a unique
opportunity to do some things that would have a positive long-term
impact, and they did the reverse,'' said McCall, a Democrat, who
did not lay blame specifically on the governor or the Legislature.
``They made the long-term problems more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, a Republican, said: ``I haven't seen his report, but the
budget is an excellent budget. It's soundly balanced and preserves
the entire $1.8 billion surplus.'' In addition to major spending
increases on education and the environment, he said, ``it continues
us as leading the nation in cutting taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   And McCall is far from alone in his criticism.
</P>
<P>
   State lawmakers ``went into the process with a long-run problem
and came out with a somewhat bigger long-run problem,'' said Diana
Fortuna, president of the Citizens Budget Commission, a nonprofit
group that closely studies the budget. ``This budget was just
focused on getting through this year and next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank J. Mauro, director of the left-leaning Fiscal Policy
Institute, a nonprofit group in Albany, said: ``This budget is
incredibly short-sighted. It tries to take care of the next couple
of years _ though even those will be difficult _ and after that we
go over the precipice.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As home to legions of stock traders and wealthy investors, New
York has benefited heavily from the bull market, in the form of
rising income tax payments. Yet Wall Street rating agencies give it
the second-lowest bond rating of any state, ahead of only
Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   This year, over the objections of the Democrats who control the
Assembly, the governor succeeded in having the entire $1.8 billion
surplus that accumulated during the 1998-99 fiscal year set aside,
rather than spent, in 1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
   But that money is already spoken for, because the state plans to
use it over the next two years to pay for property tax cuts that
have been put into law, but are taking effect in stages. That
reserve is projected to run out in two years, and while McCall does
not project the state's finances beyond two years, he and other
analysts said that it is safe to assume the predicted deficits
would balloon beyond that point.
</P>
<P>
   In their defense, administration officials pointed to a brief
report issued last month by Standard &AMP; Poor's, one of Wall Street's
major bond rating firms, that said the state's finances were
generally better than they were three years ago, a point no one
would dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Moody's Investors Service, Standard &AMP; Poor's main competitor, is
preparing a more detailed report for publication next month that is
expected to take a dimmer view of the budget. Moody's declined any
comment for the record until then, but one official there noted
that both the governor's and comptroller's office are projecting
much larger deficits one year into the future than they were at
this time last year, adding, ``that kind of speaks for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The new budget totals $73.3 billion, a 3.8 percent increase over
last year, but much of that is money _ like federal welfare and
Medicaid payments, and tuition paid by State University of New York
students _ that has no direct effect on state finances. When those
elements are stripped out, what is left is the $37.4 billion
general fund, the portion of the budget generated by state taxes
and fees, and the part that analysts focus on.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has claimed that general fund growth, at 2.4 percent, is
within the rate of inflation _ a contention many economists would
dispute _ yet it is still higher than the projected 2 percent
increase in revenue. But even that 2.4 percent figure was arrived
at through accounting moves that simply declared some revenue and
spending to be outside the general fund. When those gimmicks are
accounted for, McCall said, general fund spending is actually up
3.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   McCall also criticized the use of one-time revenues, like
selling assets or taking surpluses from little-noticed accounts,
that, by his count, total more than $500 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
