<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0532 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2644 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HARLEM-DANCE-REVIEW-A     09-22 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARLEM-DANCE-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCE THEATER OF HARLEM: STREET SMARTS AND SOUTH AFRICAN VISIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Triple quotes for ```Return''' in 3rd graf cq.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dance Theater of Harlem's 30th birthday is happy
cause for celebration, and the company's gala opening of a two-week
anniversary season at City Center on Tuesday night naturally had a
festive atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   An enthusiastic black-tie audience, which included Nane Annan,
wife of U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, cheered Arthur Mitchell,
the troupe's artistic director and founder, and the first of the
season's new works.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Garland, Dance Theater of Harlem's resident
choreographer, presented his latest premiere, ```Return,''' a witty
fusion of ballet technique and street gait whose irony toward
rhythm-and-blues had the audience in stitches.
</P>
<P>
   Very different in its musical inspiration was the New York
premiere of ``South African Suite,'' distinguished for its score by
the Soweto String Quartet, played live onstage by the group's four
string players and two percussionists. The piece, commissioned by
the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts, was
choreographed by a collective consisting of Mitchell, Augustus Van
Heerden and Laveen Naidu and was now seen in an expanded version
produced in March.
</P>
<P>
   The program was completed by the company's celebrated version of
Stravinsky's ``Firebird,'' choreographed in 1982 by John Taras and
set in the dazzling tropical clime that Geoffrey Holder brings to
life with his resplendent decor and costumes.
</P>
<P>
   Taras, a longtime associate of George Balanchine whose
international reputation as a choreographer dates back to the
1940s, has a mastery of classical technique that the other
choreographers onstage did not. Neither ```Return''' nor ``South
African Suite'' is world shaking. Yet they display a search for
something new, a freshness that comes with self-discovery that is
fascinating in its own way.
</P>
<P>
   Garland's turn to pop singers like James Brown and Aretha
Franklin and the creation of ``South African Suite'' after the
company's visit to South Africa in 1992, is not surprising. Life
experience, witnessed or lived, is often the best source of
creativity.
 &UR;  &LR; In the Soweto String Quartet, Mitchell has found his soul mates:
artists who use classical training as a springboard. Reuben Khemese
(cello), Sandile Khemese (principal violin), Thami Khemese (second
violin) and Makhosini Mnguni (viola) play Western instruments. Like
Dave Grusin, whose ``Bossa Baroque'' is part of the suite, they wed
classical and Baroque forms with the rhythms and melodies of South
Africa's people.
</P>
<P>
   These are diverse, as emphasized by the choreography and the two
drummers, Samir Chatterjee and Donald Eaton. A stylized warriors'
dance for 10 men has little in common with a swift solo inspired by
Indian classical dance that Camille Parson performed with a darting
liveliness.
</P>
<P>
   Like some South African jazz, the music has a gentle melodic
sound, and in this respect the choreography has the right tone. It
is elegant and refined in its abstract images.
</P>
<P>
   The lighting by Kevin Connaughton and Brady Jarvis reveals a
two-tier set. The musicians perform on the top platform, and
Caroline Rocher, in silhouette, is on the bench below. She is the
``enduring spirit,'' as the program calls her: She rocks an
invisible baby in her arms, struts on toe and walks on all fours,
her limbs stretched. She is vibrant and has a voluptuous jete.
Pamela Allen-Cummings' costumes include black-and-white print
halters for both men and women. A highlight is the acrobatic and
neoclassical adagio for Kellye A. Saunders and James Washington,
full of stretches and zigzagging bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Long, Paunika Jones and Kevin Thomas dance a jazzy
wrist-rotating trio, and Duncan Cooper and Ramon Thielen lead the
symmetrical warriors' dance, invisible spears held overhead. Here
as elsewhere, one notices a new talent, the young Eric Underwood.
</P>
<P>
   The choreography, rituals full of spliced-in conventional double
turns in the air and pirouettes, could use more invention. But the
spirit is right, and one has to be numb not to feel its
authenticity in the three-tiered communal celebration at the end.
</P>
<P>
   Garland also uses a suite structure in ```Return.''' But the
effect suggests a series of sketches that fade out with each
recording. Ms. Long, remembered for her fine dancing in New York
City Ballet, is the wiggling pert siren in Ms. Allen-Cummings'
silvery costume who opens the work to Brown's recording of ``Mother
Popcorn.''
</P>
<P>
   Transitions between steps could be smoother, but Garland knows
how to marry street smarts with neoclassical style. Ms. Long leads
a strutting group of women on toe and men in jumpsuits. Ms.
Saunders and Donald Williams get the love duet amplified by other
couples as Ms. Franklin sings ``Baby, Baby, Baby.'' In the final
hilarious number, ``Call Me,'' she sings ``I Love You'' to her one
and only, but Lenore Pavlakos moves from man to man in a tilted
embrace.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``Firebird,'' it was graced by Ms. Long's performance in
the title role. Small rather than dominating and excellently
partnered by Cooper, she triumphs through the details of her
dancing. Joseph E. Fields conducted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
