<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JASPER STILL WAITING TO LEARN KILLER'S FATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
and RICHARD STEWART 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRYAN, Texas _ Jurors deciding the fate of capital murderer
Lawrence Russell Brewer Jr., a white supremacist convicted in last
year's dragging death of a disabled black man, deliberated more
than 11 hours Wednesday before going to a hotel for the night.
</P>
<P>
   The jury of 11 Anglos and one Hispanic will return to court at 9
a.m. CST Thursday to resume deliberations on whether Brewer, 32,
will be sentenced to life in prison or death by injection for
chaining James Byrd Jr., 49, to a pickup by his ankles and dragging
him to his death near Jasper on June 7, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Brewer became the second man convicted of capital
murder in Byrd's killing. A Jasper County jury earlier this year
sent John William ``Bill'' King, 24, to death row. A third
defendant, Shawn Allen Berry, also 24, will be tried next month in
Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   After a tense day of waiting at the Brazos County Courthouse,
where Brewer's trial was moved, Byrd's nephew, Darrell Verrett,
said, ``I didn't expect it to take this long. Nobody did. I think
they're just being careful about everything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our sense of humor is seeing us through,'' said Byrd's sister,
Clara Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's brother, John, said, ``The waiting just causes more
agony for the family. The longer it goes, the worse it is. Either
way it goes, we lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's aunt, Shirley Brown, said as sheriff's deputies
escorted the Brewer and Byrd families to their cars, ``This is left
in God's hands.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Brewer's parents and other relatives and friends
took the witness stand to plead for a life prison sentence, which
would require Brewer to serve at least 40 years before being
eligible for parole.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the 11 hours and 20 minutes of deliberation, the two
families sat in the hallway outside the courtroom or on the
courthouse grounds, occasionally mingling with each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main word is frustration,'' said Jasper County District
Attorney Guy James Gray as he left the courthouse, But he said he
was encouraged that the jurors wanted to work until 9:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have obviously turned this over a hundred different
ways,'' said Gray's assistant, Pat Hardy. ``Either way, justice
will be done. I'll certainly be disappointed if they don't go for
the death penalty, but I know they are working hard and they are
doing the best they can.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Brewer's defense attorneys, Doug Barlow, said, ``To try
to tell what a jury is doing by how long they are out is like
trying to read tea leaves.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewer, the former ``Exalted Cyclops'' of a racist prison gang
affiliated with the Ku Klux Klan, has spent most of his adult life
in prison for burglary, cocaine possession and parole violations.
</P>
<P>
   But Byrd's gruesome killing, which drew worldwide media
attention to East Texas and prompted armed black separatists and
the KKK to march on Jasper, was Brewer's first violent offense.
</P>
<P>
   That fact may be the source of the jurors' difficulties in
answering one of three questions they must answer: whether Brewer
would be a continuing threat of violence if they spare him from the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   After four hours, jurors sent out a note, asking for the legal
definition of the words ``society,'' ``violence'' and
``probability.'' State District Judge Monte Lawlis sent back a
message saying there is no legal definition and jurors should rely
on the words' common meanings.
</P>
<P>
   Several hours later, jurors asked for a dictionary. It was
denied.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, jurors asked to see Brewer's letters and jailhouse
notes, a portion of his testimony and a psychologist's report.
</P>
<P>
   In closing arguments Wednesday morning, another of Brewer's
attorneys, Layne Walker, quoted Bible verses and told jurors that
other than their own salvation, this would be the most important
decision of their lives. He said Brewer was caught in ``the classic
situation of being in the wrong place at the wrong time.''
</P>
<P>
   During his trial, Brewer blamed his co-defendants Berry and King
for the crime.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
