<HEADER>
A2668 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-TOBACCO-SUIT-ART-1STL     09-22 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-SUIT-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1150(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DEPT. FILES SUIT ACCUSING TOBACCO INDUSTRY OF DEFRAUDING
PUBLIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for additions; grafs 11, 12, 18, and the final graf are
new.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By MARC LACEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Justice Department closed the book Wednesday on
its criminal investigation of the tobacco industry and instead
filed a far-reaching civil lawsuit that accuses the largest
cigarette companies of conspiring since the 1950s to defraud and
mislead the public about the health effects of smoking.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks to recover billions of dollars the federal
government spent on smoking-related health care for elderly
Medicare patients, military veterans and federal employees,
expenses not covered by the $246 billion in settlements that the
industry reached last year with the states over smoking-related
Medicaid costs for the poor and disabled.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who first announced that the Justice
Department would pursue such a lawsuit in his State of the Union
Message last January, told reporters at the White House on
Wednesday that ``the tobacco companies should answer to the
taxpayers for their actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Relying heavily on documents unearthed in the state claims, the
lawsuit accuses the tobacco industry of promoting biased research,
wrongly asserting that nicotine was not addictive and falsely
denying that they were targeting their products to children.
</P>
<P>
   Along with monetary damages, which the suit says exceed $20
billion a year, the suit seeks to tap into what the suit calls the
tobacco industry's ``ill-gotten gains'' and force the industry to
finance education programs about the health effects of smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the past 45 years, the companies that manufacture and sell
tobacco have waged an intentional, coordinated campaign of fraud
and deceit,'' Attorney General Janet Reno said at a news
conference. ``As we allege in the complaint, it has been a campaign
designed to preserve their enormous profits whatever the cost in
human lives, human suffering and medical resources. The
consequences have been staggering.''
</P>
<P>
   The defendants include Philip Morris Cos., The Liggett Group,
American Tobacco Co., British-American Tobacco PLC,
British-American Tobacco (Investments) Ltd., R.J. Reynolds Tobacco
Co., Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp., and Lorillard Tobacco Co.
Along with these companies, which sell more than 98 percent of the
cigarettes in the United States, the suit also names two industry
groups, the Council for Tobacco Research U.S.A. and the Tobacco
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Condemning the suit as politically motivated, tobacco executives
vowed to seek its immediate dismissal. ``We will not succumb to
politically correct extortion,'' said Greg Little, associate
general counsel for Philip Morris. ``We will not settle this
lawsuit. We're right on the law. We're right on the facts. We will
prevail in this lawsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   Criticism also came from the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, which
accused the Clinton administration of pursuing the lawsuit because
Congress last year failed to act on tobacco legislation that would
have tightened the regulation of tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   ``No business can feel secure in the United States when the
enormous power of the Justice Department can be unleashed against
them for the purpose of raising revenue and scoring political
points,'' Bruce Josten, the chamber's executive vice president,
said in a statement. ``This is nothing more than taxation through
litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about statements from the companies calling the suit
politically motivated, Clinton said, ``We did our best to work with
them and with the Congress to resolve many of these matters
legislatively, and they declined.''
</P>
<P>
   This development has elements that are both good and bad for the
tobacco industry. It escapes a criminal investigation that has been
lingering for years but instead faces a potentially costly civil
lawsuit. The federal government, if it enters into settlement talks
with the industry would likely try to get the industry to agree to
increased regulation.
</P>
<P>
   But industry foes praised the Justice Department for keeping the
makers and marketers of cigarettes on their heels. ``When the
Justice Department wins, it will be a great victory by the American
taxpayers,'' said Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., who has fought for
tighter regulation of the tobacco industry. ``The tobacco companies
have perpetrated a fraud on the American people for decades. When
it comes to a matter of law, all their campaign contributions won't
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit heats up an issue that was already bubbling on the
campaign trail and on Capitol Hill. Congressional Republicans, who
receive the bulk of the industry's political donations, have
accused the White House of going too far to regulate what is a
legal product. The House and Senate have resisted an administration
effort to add $20 million to the appropriations bill that funds the
Justice Department to pay for the litigation.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, who is generally
considered the leading Republican presidential contender, said that
Bush ``hoped the era of big government will not be replaced by the
era of big lawsuits.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the government case is built upon much of the same
evidence as the state cases, the Justice Department is relying on
different statutes _ the Medical Care Recovery Act and the Medicare
Secondary Payer Act, both of which the government typically uses to
recover medical costs in individual cases.
</P>
<P>
   By amassing the cases of tens of thousands of smokers into one
suit, the government is seeking to sidestep the industry's
preference for trying smoking cases smoker by smoker. The industry
argues that smokers have long been warned of the health effects of
smoking, but the government's lawsuit says the industry engaged in
a vigorous campaign to create doubt among smokers.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with fierce political resistance, the federal government
decided not to pursue a plan to seek some of the money the states
received in settlements over Medicaid costs.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials refused to elaborate on the end of
the criminal investigation, which began about five years ago and
looked into whether tobacco executives lied to Congress and
regulatory agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The civil case cannot use evidence obtained during the Justice
Department's criminal investigation without a court order. But the
civil case can rely on documents that came to light during the
state suits and other suits filed by individuals.
</P>
<P>
   In one example, the suit cites a 1998 press release issued by a
trade group, the Tobacco Institute, saying claims that cigarette
smoking is addictive ``defy common sense and contradict the fact
that people quit smoking every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal lawsuit is the first the government has filed
against an entire industry using the RICO statute. The law was
drafted in the late 1960s to fight organized crime but has been
broadly applied by federal prosecutors against businesses and
others engaged in a pattern of illegal acts.
</P>
<P>
   A few states, including Florida and Texas, have used RICO counts
in their lawsuits against the cigarette makers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember an entire industry that was targeted as if it
was a racketeering enterprise'' by the federal government, said
Joseph DiGenova, a former federal prosecutor in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Justice Department's decision to formally end its
long-running criminal investigation, DiGenova said that he believed
the decision was practical and well founded. While the burden of
proof in a criminal case is guilt beyond a reasonable doubt, the
burden in the type of civil action filed on Wednesday is only a
preponderance of the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``They chose the easier route for them and very wisely because
criminal cases, by their very nature, are iffy,'' said DiGenova.
</P>
<P>
   The case, filed in the U.S. District Court in the District of
Columbia, has been assigned to Judge Gladys Kessler, who was
appointed to the federal bench by Clinton in 1994 and is known for
pushing to resolve disputes out of court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-22-99 2358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990922.0538 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2672 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOODS-TOWN23-1STLEDE     09-22 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOODS-TOWN23-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1ST LEDE
 &HT;    EDs: CORRECTS name of Ayden in 14th graf; adds clarification to
last graf.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Too much death for N.C. towns
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINETOPS, N.C. _ Not all the dead are resting after Hurricane
Floyd killed more than 40 people in North Carolina and unearthed
coffins along swollen rivers.
</P>
<P>
   In neighboring Wilson, sobbing relatives Wednesday buried three
of the storm's victims, killed when a boat capsized last week near
Pinetops. But widespread flooding has delayed other burials across
eastern North Carolina, devastated by the state's worst natural
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Coffins and vaults bobbing in floodwaters have become an
unsettling sight, and some survivors don't want to bury their loved
ones in muddy graves. In nearby towns such as Rocky Mount, high
water separates bodies stored in hospital morgues from out-of-town
kin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is horrible,'' said Brenda Wright, nursing supervisor at
Nash General Hospital in Rocky Mount. Its morgue has room for
eight, prompting officials to bring in a refrigerated
tractor-trailer for Floyd's victims.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday, three of the hospital's 10 storm dead had been
delivered to funeral homes.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining seven were in the trailer, partly to prevent the
odor of decomposing flesh from fouling the morgue, Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   At least three graves in Pinetops have been ripped apart by
floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
   Still, state officials said floating corpses in caskets pose far
less of a health risk than widespread municipal and farm sewage
spills.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing the spread of disease, officials are scrambling to
dispose of more than 100,000 hogs, 2.4 million chickens and 500,000
turkeys that drowned.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no health risk involved with an embalmed body,'' said
Jeff Winstead, an official with the state's emergency response team
in Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   The state medical examiner's office has a procedure for
identifying and reinterring corpses, Winstead said. But considering
the sewage and livestock threats, he said, ``That is not one of the
emergency issues.''
</P>
<P>
   As waters recede, Dr. John Butts, the state's chief medical
examiner, said, he expects the official death toll of 41 to rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we expecting the number to increase? Yes,'' Wright said.
``It may be three or four more. It may be 10 more. I do not know.''
</P>
<P>
   In Ayden, embalmer Don Brown prepared two bodies over the
weekend, but flooding prevented him from releasing them to funeral
homes in Williamston and Elizabeth City.
</P>
<P>
   Rest Haven Cemetery in Wilson had dried out enough for
Wednesday's burial of Ben and Vivian Mayo and their 23-year-old
daughter, Keisha Vines.
</P>
<P>
   Vines' 5-year-old daughter, Tekisha, also apparently died, but
her body was not found until Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were fortunate,'' Josephine Edwards, director of Edwards
Funeral Home, said as she greeted some of the several hundred
people who attended the two-hour service at the L.N. Forbes
Original Free Will Baptist Tabernacle.
</P>
<P>
   The three Mayo family members from Pinetops were among six
people who drowned a week ago in flooding from Town Creek in
Edgecombe County.
</P>
<P>
   Remembered during the funeral service as a hero who tried to
save his neighbors, Ben Mayo, 50, was steering a rescue boat that
overturned, killing half of the 12 people aboard in Hurricane
Floyd's deadliest accident.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a mile away, a 6- to 8-foot swell rushed across low
ground along Town Creek and unearthed two vaults in an old cemetery
on Bynum Farm Road.
</P>
<P>
   A third hole is empty, but Pinetops Mayor Earl Coker said he's
not sure whether it had contained a casket.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a week since flooding uncovered the stone vaults.
</P>
<P>
   One was turned on its side, with one end pointing to the sky.
Another poked from the ground, its lid ajar. Some of the people who
look after the cemetery have been flooded out of their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is something that happened beyond our control,'' said B.C.
Pitt, who is staying at the emergency shelter in Carver Elementary
School in Pinetops.
</P>
<P>
   If residents are not able to restore the graves, volunteer fire
and rescue Chief Steve Bynum said, ``the county will make sure they
are taken care of.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
